r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LAD     06-08 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCELLATIONS REVEAL SHORTCOMINGS OF MEDICAL SCREENINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A great deal about the ill-fated Evander
Holyfield-Henry Akinwande card is bothersome.
</P>
<P>
   A major event had to be canceled the day before it was scheduled
to take place. Two fighters (Akinwande and Ray Mercer) tested
positive for hepatitis B. Maria Nieves-Garcia couldn't fight
because she's 21 months pregnant. And Roberto Duran had his purse
garnished in a child-support case.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath, however, two questions stand out:
</P>
<P>
   One, why isn't medical testing done well in advance of major
fights to avoid last-minute cancellations? Didn't we learn anything
from the scheduled Tommy Morrison-Arthur Weathers fight in 1996,
which was canceled the day of the event when Morrison tested
positive for the virus that causes AIDS?
</P>
<P>
   And, two, why is testing for hepatitis B done only in a reported
four states?
</P>
<P>
   Consider the time and money lost as a result of the
cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield and Akinwande (who were to make $10 million and $2.5
million, respectively), the promoters, Showtime, cable distributors
and many more stand to lose a fortune because of an ill-advised
policy on testing. (And that doesn't take into account fans who
made travel plans and purchased tickets, for which they presumably
will get refunds.)
</P>
<P>
   New York, where the fight was scheduled to be held Saturday,
requires that test results be submitted a minimum of five days
before the fight. (California requires a test for hepatitis B 30
days before licensing but requires testing only once a year.)
</P>
<P>
   And that, according toe
New York State Athletic Commission, is ``only a request.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't enforce it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? To protect everyone involved, athletic commissions
across the nation should require that test results be submitted a
month before !ital!major!off! fights or no license. Simple as that.
If that means a foreign fighter must fly into the United States
solely to take the test, so be it. Again, it would serve everyone _
including that fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, this wouldn't work with many smaller cards, for which
last-minute replacements are the norm.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Holyfield-Akinwande fight was made months ago. Even
without appropriate policies, the fighters could've _ should've! _
had their tests in long ago. Holyfield's were submitted weeks ago,
Petrillo said, while Akinwande (who fights out of Orlando, Fla.)
was tested Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   To protect themselves, it boggles the mind that fighters
wouldn't make testing a high priority. That much is clear to
Holyfield, who said, ``I find it kind of strange that they wait
until the last minute for testing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're talking about title fights like this, there's no
reason you can't get it done well ahead of time,'' said Paul
Wallace, co-chair of the medical advisory board for the California
State Athletic Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree. It's absolutely absurd it wasn't done several months
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Petrillo said New York officials will ``sure have discussions
about this.''
</P>
<P>
   All states should. This really isn't that complicated.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of testing for hepatitis B itself isn't complicated,
either. It is vital, though.
</P>
<P>
   Hepatitis B is far more infectious than HIV, Wallace said, ``It
just doesn't have the notoriety.''
</P>
<P>
   In Akinwande's case, the disease was at the infectious stage,
according to a doctor who studied the fighter's blood sample.
Without testing, it seems, Holyfield would've been at risk. At the
same time, all those who have worked closely with Akinwande _
including sparring partners _ !ital!were!off! at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most states do not test for the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, Nevada, the world's boxing capital, is among them,
although Marc Ratner, executive director of the Nevada State
Athletic Commission, said his state is discussing its
implementation.
</P>
<P>
   The day the card was canceled, Jean-Christophe Courreges,
Akinwande's French manager, said, ``Anywhere else in the world, he
would be fighting. They don't test for this anywhere else (outside
the U.S.).''
</P>
<P>
   Well, if the powers that be are smart, they will after this. And
that includes California, which might want to test more frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public policy is not based necessarily on fact but on things
the media puts out,'' Wallace said. ``If a major star or public
figure ends up with hepatitis B, I would think we would see some
focus on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public health often suffers until there's some kind of
tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's avoid tragedy this time.
</P>
<P>
   Looking forward: Oscar De La Hoya, who defends his WBC
welterweight title against unknown Frenchman Patrick Charpentier on
Saturday in El Paso, Texas, reiterated his desire to fight Felix
Trinidad in what would be an attractive non-heavyweight bout.
</P>
<P>
   Arum, his promoter, said he met with Trinidad's handlers last
week. However, these are the early stages of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Arum said he made a ``crazily high offer'' to Trinidad, more
than $5 million, but Trinidad's people have not accepted. They said
they would consider it and get back to Arum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good meeting and they left on a good note,'' Arum
said. ``Oscar wants that fight. And we feel it's a very winnable
fight because of Trinidad's (aggressive) style. So we'd love to do
it, and I think we eventually will do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Arum said he might be willing to guarantee Trinidad more money
than De La Hoya, but De La Hoya would get a percentage of the
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I had this situation was with (Ray) Leonard when
he fought (Marvin) Hagler,'' Arum said. ``Leonard took a straight
buyout, Hagler fought on a percentage and Hagler made 1{ times what
Leonard made.''
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad claims he no longer is under contract to promoter Don
King, but Arum said that's not so clear, which complicates
negotiations but isn't necessarily an insurmountable obstacle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
