<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8494 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-TECHNOLOGY-HNS &LR;      06-08 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TECHNOLOGY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
USGA is ready to go to war
<TEXT>
<P>
   Governing body wants to bomb high-tech clubs back to Stone Age
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JAYNE CUSTRED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The United States Golf Association is about to declare war on
high-tech golf as we know it.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA, which along with the Royal &AMP; Ancient is the official
rules-making body for all of golf, has decided the new, space-age
equipment on the market today threatens the integrity of the game.
And the USGA is determined to do something about it, targeting such
products as titanium drivers and long putters.
</P>
<P>
   The first shots in the skirmish were fired three weeks ago. The
USGA found itself in the center of a heated controversy when its
newest president, F. Morgan ``Buzz'' Taylor, said in his inaugural
address that he was concerned that the new ``superb athletes'' in
the game, in conjunction with the latest in equipment, had the
potential to make many of golf's historic venues obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in an interview with Golf World Magazine, Taylor said it
in plainer terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our franchise is to preserve and protect the game's ancient
and honorable traditions,'' he said. ``I intend to do that, and
there's not one lawyer in the world who is going to get in our way
of doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting words, to be sure. But what do they mean? No official
proposal has been released, but the word is out that the USGA is
studying a number of changes in equipment rules, including a
crackdown on titanium drivers, setting a limit for lofts in irons,
banning long putters, limiting the lengths of shafts, and reducing
the maximum number of clubs allowed in a bag from 14 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   Most insiders think the focus will be on the ``trampoline
effect'' the USGA believes exists in some thin-walled titanium
drivers. The current Rules of Golf make it clear that the
``material and construction of the (club) face shall not have the
effect of a spring.'' The USGA contends this is what some of the
most popular drivers have.
</P>
<P>
   USGA officials also have hinted they will have a significant
announcement on the proposal as early as the U.S. Open, which will
be June 18-21 at the Olympic Club in San Francisco. No official
decision to change the Rules of Golf could be made until the USGA
and the R&AMP;A meet for the Quadrennial Rules Conference in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the major golf manufacturers have responded
swiftly and angrily. Callaway Golf, makers of the Great Big Bertha
and Greatest Big Bertha titanium drivers, which would be on the
USGA's extinction list if the rules were adopted, issued a 3{-page
news release announcing it would join with other companies in
opposing any such USGA rulings banning modern clubs. In addition,
Callaway bought full-page ads in the New York Times, USA Today and
Golf World to present its position.
</P>
<P>
   But while the USGA is threatening and the manufacturing world is
reeling, the one organization that would be most affected if all
the new changes were adopted is taking a wait-and-see attitude.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend hackers who dished out $500 a pop for a Big Bertha
driver might be disappointed if their weapon of choice is taboo.
But those golfers trying to make a living using the same driver on
the PGA Tour have considerably more to lose.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour is its own organization, separate from the USGA,
but it follows the rules as set down by the USGA. And PGA Tour
officials don't see that changing in the future, regardless of
which way the USGA rules on the equipment issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an equipment advisory committee, a standing committee,
that serves as our liaison with the USGA technical department,''
said Bob Combs, PGA Tour senior vice president of public relations
and communications. ``We're aware of the ongoing research being
done by the USGA, but there's been no release of data yet. So we're
just watching to see what the USGA's conclusions are and what the
data shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll all have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet regardless of the decision, the outcome is almost a foregone
conclusion. Tour officials stressed that ``we play under USGA
rules.'' There are guidelines that allow the PGA Tour to modify a
USGA rule, but those guidelines are rarely, if ever, evoked.
Modifying a rule set down by the USGA would only be done in what
one tour official termed an ``extreme'' situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most fundamental thing is that there are just one set of
rules for both pros and amateurs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, any sweeping changes in equipment rules made by
the USGA for their own competitions would also affect the events on
the PGA Tour as well. The pros could kiss their titanium drivers,
long putters and perimeter-weighted irons goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Some PGA Tour pros, such as The Woodlands Jeff Maggert, find it
a little hard to believe the USGA would go to such lengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't know if they would do it or not,'' Maggert said.
``The manufacturers would certainly go nuts. And there are
certainly a lot of guys out here using titanium drivers. Who knows
what they are thinking? But I think they must also realize that
golfers today are just better athletes, just like in other sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't so long ago that no one could run a 4-minute mile.
Now it's done all the time. The track is still the same distance.
So what now? Make them run in combat boots to slow them down?''
</P>
<P>
   Maggert agreed technology has come a long way in recent years.
But in his mind, the length of the putter and the type of the
driver make less of a difference than the size and condition of the
athlete using it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to go back to what it was like 30 years ago, then
don't forget the lousy fairways, lousy bunkers, lousy greens,''
Maggert said. ``They forget some of the things that made the game
so difficult back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite his disapproval of the USGA's proposals, Maggert
remained firm in his belief that if the USGA changes the rules, for
better or worse, the PGA Tour needs to follow them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the best interest for everyone to follow one set of
rules,'' he said. ``That's the whole point of golf. Everyone plays
by the same rules, plays the same game, whether a 35-handicapper or
a touring pro.''
</P>
<P>
   Now only time will tell under what rules the game will be
played.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
