</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING GOES RIGHT IN M'S FINALE WITH DODGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After suggesting Saturday night that some lineup
changes were in store, Mariner manager Lou Piniella stuck with
basically the same starters Sunday and got a similar result in the
series finale against the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners were stung with another loss, 7-4, before 41,514
fans at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield and Eric Karros slugged solo home runs and the
Dodgers blooped losing pitcher Jamie Moyer into submission during a
game-clinching five-run rally in the sixth inning as the Mariners
fell eight games below .500 (27-35) for the first time since ending
the 1994 season with a 49-63 record.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the potential lineup change, Piniella said, ``I
wasn't talking 12 hours. We (management) know the things that need
to be done here. It's just a question of people being available. I
don't know what we can do or can't do. Right now, we have to play
better than what we have. And I expect us to play better than we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   The M's went down with a ninth-inning fight, scoring three runs
and then loading the bases to bring the potential winning run to
the plate. Sore-footed pinch-hitter David Segui struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. hit his 24th homer in the ninth but otherwise
had an rare dismal game _ striking out three times and misplaying a
line drive into right-center field for his third error of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We battled back and that's a good sign,'' Piniella said. ``One
swing, and we win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Segui, the only lineup change _ and only because he has a sore
right foot _ took three swings against Antonio Osuna, missing all
three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to hit a line drive somewhere in the gap and
score (pinch-runner Charles Gipson) from first base,'' Segui said.
``There are times you try to hit a home run. But I wasn't trying to
hit one out in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Piniella, ``David is hurt but gave it his best effort.''
</P>
<P>
   As they returned to their clubhouse, the Mariners continued to
rub their collective eyes in disbelief. They left 13 more
baserunners on base. And popups fell in front of Griffey and right
fielder Rob Ducey to fuel the Dodgers' big fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are struggling, things like that happen,'' Piniella
said.
</P>
<P>
   The M's have now lost six of their past seven games in various
ways. Ineffective starting pitching. Poor relief pitching. Errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is frustrating for everybody,'' said catcher Dan Wilson,
who went 3-for-4. ``We're all trying to work ourselves out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   So what it is going to take?
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Piniella: ``Getting good pitching, timely hitting,
catching the ball and winning some games.''
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Wilson: ``We need to execute and get our confidence
back.''
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Moyer: ``We need seven or eight strong innings, maybe even
nine, from our starters at least two times through the rotation to
take some of the pressure off the offense and bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Segui: ``Two weeks ago I would have said we needed a
shake-up. But I think it's past that stage. I think everything we
need is here, but what do I know?
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Alex Rodriguez: ``It isn't a confidence issue. It's an
execution issue. This team has won in the past and knows it can win
again. It's not like it has had a facelift.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Moyer, ``I don't think anyone in this room is going to
give up. But we have to find a solution someway, somehow and real
quick.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, who won the final two games of the interleague
series, rode the solid pitching of starter Darren Dreifort for
eight innings. The right-hander, whom the Mariners reportedly
requested in recent trade talks involving Randy Johnson, spaced
nine hits and got a superb defensive play by second baseman Eric
Young, who deprived Edgar Martinez of a run-scoring single in the
third inning.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle was 0-for-7 with runners in scoring position until
Rodriguez singled home Cora from third base in the seventh inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
