<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-FINALS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS HOLD JAZZ TO RECORD LOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Utah Jazz coach Jerry Sloan stopped midway through his
postgame news conference when someone handed him the statistical
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was actually the score?'' a stunned Sloan asked. ``This
was the final? I thought it was 196. Seemed like (the Chicago
Bulls) scored 196.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite, Jerry. And a longer gape at the final score would
explain that the Bulls offense in Game 3 of the NBA Finals was
hardly the difference at United Center last night.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago 96. Utah 54.
</P>
<P>
   Old? Tired? Cracks in the armor?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Bulls beat ragged the old cliche of defense winning
championships. Yep, the Jazz are tired of hearing about how good
the Bulls are as they shoot for a sixth championship.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, after Sunday's _ fill in the discerning adjective
here _ the Jazz are broken and picking up the pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Riding a defensive effort better than police vests stopping
bullets, the Bulls completely flattened the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   It only seems as if Utah has been eliminated from the Finals.
The series is far from over. However, if ever was such a thing as a
commanding 2-1 lead, the Bulls have just that.
</P>
<P>
   The after shock is still resonating:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Utah's point total was the fewest ever by a team in an NBA
game since the advent of the 24-second shot clock in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The Jazz made just 21 field goals and scored only 23
points in the second half _ the fewest ever in an NBA Finals game.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Chicago's 42-point margin of victory was the largest in
Finals history.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Chicago has never lost a playoff series after
taking the lead. Not only have they stolen the homecourt advantage
in this series, Games 4 and 5 are at United Center. The Bulls are
8-1 at home in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   What _ that is positive _ do the Jazz have to look forward to?
``You watch endings of games like this and you better be ready to
play the next game,'' Jazz forward Karl Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Malone watched the waning moments of Game 3 from the bench. The
Bulls led by 18 points at halftime and owned a 27-point advantage
by the start of the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago snatched the game's momentum with one simple yet
hard-to-do adjustment. They controlled Malone and John Stockton,
and the rest of Utah's pieces fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good feel for them,'' said Bulls star Michael
Jordan, who told his teammates long before the third quarter ended
that he wanted to rest the final period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The screen and roll is very tough to play,'' Jordan said.
``But once we got a feel for it and saw something that worked we
kept at it. Now we're starting to affect them to some degree in
stopping the screen and roll. That's great defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen's ability to roam and disrupt Stockton was the
key. Pippen often defended whomever was an offensive liability on
the floor for Utah. As soon as Stockton crossed midcourt, Pippen
doubled off his man and ran toward Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy closed down the passing lanes and frustrated the
NBA's all-time assists leader. Stockton had seven assists and five
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I've ever seen a team play any better
defensively since I've been in the business,'' Sloan said. ``They
ate us alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah never got into its offensive sets. The Bulls forced Utah
into a playoff-high 26 turnovers and had 13 steals. Essentially,
the Bulls were more aggressive and mentally tough.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the third quarter, Utah had 13 field goals to
match 13 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten better (defensively) _ to be able to take them
out of their sets and rotate and get to their shooters,'' Pippen
said. ``Our defense is what's carrying us throughout this series.''
</P>
<P>
   The pick and roll Utah methodically destroys opponents with went
stale. Malone rebounded from poor performances in the first two
games and scored 22 points on 8-of-11 shooting. But the Jazz had
just 16 assists and shot 30 percent as a team.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls even checked Malone, who hit his first six shots.
Bulls coach Phil Jackson switched Dennis Rodman to guard Malone
instead of Luc Longley. Malone went just 2 of 4 in the second half
with Rodman badgering him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Luc played him real soft, and it looked like
(Malone) was going to hit that jump shot all day at the start,''
Jackson said. ``I put Dennis on him on the outside and they never
really got anything started with Karl in the post from there on
out. It shut down his touches.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone wasn't ready to give the Bulls too much credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They cut them down on everybody. They had a helluva defensive
game. It was an old-fashioned one (last night). We got exactly what
we deserved,'' Malone said. ``But our plays work. It's evident our
plays work when we run them.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, the small problem of when Chicago is running
its system to perfection. That is the simplest explanation for last
night _ a game in which the team with one of the game's best
offensive players won with offense being an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fine tuning a lot of things and we're starting to look
good,'' Jordan said. ``I like that. It's a good time to look
good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
