<HEADLINE>
SURFING THE TUBE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TODAY: You've got to give credit to Earvin Johnson _ a.k.a.
``Magic, a.k.a. ``Buck,'' a.k.a. ``The Grin That Stole Late Night''
_ for having the nerve to put his rep on the line and do a
late-night talk show when so many others have tried and fouled out.
How many people told him a 6-foot-9 point guard couldn't happen
either? To prep for this, the one-time Lakers coach says he had
regular sessions with a speech coach and an interview coach. Just
as long as Del Harris isn't his motivational coach. ``The Magic
Hour,'' Channel 11, 11 p.m. weeknights.
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY: What's the hook for Magic Johnson's talk show? The
billboards say it's his infectious smile. But when Lakers fans
think of Magic's most famous hook _ that baby one to win Game 4 in
the '87 Finals _ they're the ones still grinning ear to ear. As
part of ESPN Classic Sports' tribute to the NBA Finals, it
continues its own special that picks out the most memorable Games 1
through 7 through the years. Tonight, it's the Magic Hour in
Boston. ``Ultimate NBA Finals Series:'' Lakers at Boston, Game 4 of
the '87 Finals, ESPN Classic Sports, 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY: Call it futbol. Call it soccer. You know it's really
kickball _ or more specifically, it's Nation Ball. As long as
everyone plays fair and listens to the teachers on yard duty, we
expect everyone to learn something from this experience. First
rule: No spitting from the Eiffel Tower. World Cup '98 from France:
Brazil vs. Scotland, ESPN, 8 a.m. (repeated on ESPN2, 5 p.m.);
Morocco vs. Norway, ESPN, 11:30 a.m. (Also: ESPN begins soccer
coverage with an ``Outside the Lines'' special on the U.S. team,
Tuesday at 4:30 p.m.; ABC, ESPN and ESPN2 have World Cup coverage
every day through July 12).
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY: They've got this next season to figure out whether the
first season of ``We Got Next'' has a future. WNBA season opener:
New York at Cleveland, Lifetime, 5 p.m. (Also: The Sparks' season
opener in Utah isn't televised, but their game Sunday at Phoenix is
on KNBC/Channel 4 at 1 p.m. NBC also has New York at Houston,
Saturday at 1 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY: KTLA's latest advertisement slogan is that it has the
Dodgers on EVERY FRIDAY NIGHT THIS SUMMER. Know what? They're
right. Colorado at Dodgers, Channel 5, 7 p.m. (Also: Fox/Channel 11
has Saturday's game at 1:05 p.m.; Fox Sports West 2 has Sunday's
game at 1:05 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY: The Capitals' incentive to win the Stanley Cup: An
invite to the White House! NHL Stanley Cup Finals: Washington vs.
Detroit Game 3, ESPN, 5 p.m. (Also: Fox/Channel 11 has Game 1,
Tuesday at 5 p.m.; ESPN has Game 2, Thursday at 5 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY: Oh, there's gonna be a sixth game back in Utah, all
right. It's in NBC's contract with the NBA that Michael Jordan is
milked as much as possible. NBA Finals: Chicago vs. Utah Game 6,
Channel 4, 4:30 p.m. (Also: NBC/Channel 4 has Game 4, Wednedsay at
6 p.m. and Game 5, Friday at 6 p.m.)
</P>
