<HEADLINE>
STARS' ZUBOV ARRESTED ON SUSPICION OF FELONY ASSAULT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dallas Stars defenseman Sergei Zubov was arrested by Coppell
police early Sunday morning on suspicion of assaulting his wife
Irina and exhibiting a ``deadly weapon,'' police said.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov was released from custody Sunday and police issued a brief
statement. When asked if Zubov had been arraigned, a police
dispatcher said the department could not comment further than what
was contained in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   The statement said officers were called to the 1000 block of
Gibbs Crossing at 3:05 a.m. Sunday in reference to a 911 hangup.
</P>
<P>
   ``After an initial investigation, it was determined an assault
had occurred and, during the assault, a deadly weapon was
exhibited,'' the police statement read.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov was arrested on suspicion of aggravated assault-family
violence, a second-degree felony.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov, 27, completed his second season with the Stars _ his
sixth NHL season _ Friday when the Stars lost in Detroit,
eliminating them from the playoffs in the Western Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   Stars general manager Bob Gainey said the Stars have talked to
Sergei and Irina Zubov.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in touch with all the parties, and we realize the
seriousness of the situation,'' Gainey said. ``We've tried to
support all of the people in this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Zubov's agent, Jay Grossman, said he could not comment on the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the 1994 Stanley Cup champion New York Rangers,
Zubov is among the Stars' top performers and was tied for second in
the NHL this season in points by a defenseman with 57. He was the
Stars' second-leading scorer behind Mike Modano in the playoffs
with nine points in 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Moscow, Zubov came to the Stars in a 1996 trade with
Pittsburgh. He is under contract for two more seasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
