</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELMONT PICTURE ALMOST WORSE 
</HEADLINE>
 STAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ It was difficult to watch a Triple Crown triumph
slip away in the last few yards of a 1 1/2-mile race. Racing fans,
80,162 strong, came out to Belmont Park to see history made
Saturday, and they were denied that experience at the wire.
However, it could have been worse. Instead of losing his Triple
Crown bid on the track, Real Quiet could have lost it in the
stewards' stand, and that would have been truly ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet, who had won the Kentucky Derby and Preakness and was
attempting to become the 12th Triple Crown winner in the Belmont
Stakes, zipped past the eighth pole with a 4-length lead. But it
was not meant to be as Victory Gallop, second in the Derby and
Preakness, closed strongly on him, survived two bumps, the second
of which was more than sufficient to cause a disqualification, and
prevailed by a nose.
</P>
<P>
   Had the photo gone the other way, the stewards said they would
have had to take Real Quiet, the 4-5 favorite, down, depriving him
of the sport's greatest honor and depriving his connections of the
$5 million Triple Crown bonus. Had the three stewards acted,
politics would have intruded on the scene and conspiracy theorists
would have abounded. It was unfortunate for those who appreciate
the sweep of history that Real Quiet was defeated, but he is not
the greatest horse ever to stick his head through a bridle, and it
was better that he lost to Victory Gallop's charge than to the
stewards' votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we got beat,'' said Elliott Walden, trainer of
Victory Gallop, Sunday. ``I thought he was going to get by a little
easier. It did seem like the bumps stopped his momentum. It wasn't
about trying to beat Real Quiet or Bob Baffert (Real Quiet's
trainer). It would have been difficult to be second in all three
Triple Crown races, especially when you think you're due. Nothing's
going to change. I'll just keep taking care of business and play
with my kids. I'm blessed to have a horse like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Walden, who is an excellent Kentucky horseman, did an
outstanding job of getting Victory Gallop from the Preakness to the
Belmont in top shape. After the Preakness, Victory Gallop developed
a skin rash, caused by ringworm, and lost weight. But he was
dead-fit for the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week went very well for Victory Gallop,'' said Walden.
``The skin rash cleared up the way it was supposed to. After the
Preakness, it didn't look like we could move with Real Quiet and
get by him. But we tried to learn from that and we made our move
late this time. I'm so happy for the Prestons (brothers Art, Jack
and Jan of Prestonwood Farm) and everyone who gets up every day amd
works for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, who is media savvy, took the high road immediately
after the race and Sunday. ``When something like this happens,
there is nothing you can do but take your butt-kickin' and go
home,'' he said. ``It was a great day and a great race. Now, we
just have to regroup.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert trains Silver Charm, who lost the Belmont to Touch Gold
nearing the wire last year, which also cost Baffert the Triple
Crown and his share of the $5 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting closer,'' he said. ``We'll get it down one of
these times. It's disappointing, it's a letdown because you get
this far. But I still think I would have felt worse if this had
happened in the Kentucky Derby. The Belmont was about history and
the fans. It was there and we had it. But what can you do? You
can't re-run the race. I wouldn't do anything different.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent Desormeaux, who rode Real Quiet and was outfinished by Gary
Stevens on Victory Gallop, criticized himself for moving too soon
entering the far turn. Frankly, he also was a little wider than he
needed to be, but Baffert refused to rip Desormeaux's ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lot tougher on Kent,'' Baffert said. ``(Saturday
night), he was really taking it hard. Kent is a very emotional guy.
He rode great. I'm glad it turned out the way it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been worse if we had gotten our number taken
down. Gary is not the kind of guy to claim foul for no reason. He
told me that he put the race on hold (requested that the stewards
delay making it official) because the photo could have gone either
way and Real Quiet had come out on him. The inquiry took so much
time, I thought maybe Victory Gallop came in on us. I did not want
to win this on a disqualification and I wouldn't have wanted to
have lost it on a disqualification. And everyone who saw the race
would have hated to have been a steward and have to make a
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that both Real Quiet and Victory Gallop ran hard,
winning races. It's pretty gratifying for a trainer to know that
his horse didn't pack it in at the top of the lane like some of the
others' horses. The fans saw a horse race all the way to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next for Victory Gallop most likely will be the $1 million
Haskell Invitational, going 1 1/8 miles at Monmouth Aug. 9. Among
his opponents there could be Indian Charlie, another top 3-year-old
trained by Baffert, and Coronado's Quest, the talented colt trained
by Shug McGaughey who won the Riva Ridge Stakes on the Belmont
undercard. Real Quiet might go to the $750,000 Travers Stakes, at a
mile and one-quarter at Saratoga Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet became the 14th horse to lose the Triple Crown in the
Belmont and the sixth since the last successful bid by Affirmed in
1978. Since Affirmed beat Alydar in a classic stretch battle,
Spectacular Bid (1979), Pleasant Colony (1981), Alysheba (1987),
Sunday Silence (1989), Silver Charm (1997), and Real Quiet have
failed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
