<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMP HELPS MOLD CLAY, PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Willie Clay is grateful that only one of the
major defections from the Patriots this offseason came on defense,
cornerback Jimmy Hitchcock, who was dealt to the Minnesota Vikings
for a third-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   For if more had, Clay knows the defense would have felt the
impact, much like the offense knows it will now.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the guys we lost were quality leaders and veterans and
people who made our team better,'' said Clay. ``We lost a great
deal of leadership when we lost Dave Meggett, Keith Byars, Sam
Gash, and Curtis Martin. It's very difficult to compensate for the
loss of a Meggett, who was just a great team player and someone who
could go around the locker room and just get everybody going.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens in a situation like that is you feel it the most
in the huddle. With Dave or Sam or Keith, you'd have someone who
could step up and say something when something needed to be said.
Curtis wasn't a vocal guy, but he had the respect of everyone on
the team because of the way he went about preparing for a game and
the way he conducted himself on and off the field. Now, somebody
else is going to have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay, who Sunday took part in the final day of mandatory
minicamp before more than 22,000 season ticket-holders at Foxboro
Stadium, said he also will miss Hitchcock, a neighbor in the locker
room and on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy was a friend and someone I really enjoyed being
around,'' said Clay. ``He played very well for us last year. Now we
have to go about replacing that spot on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was surprised by the defections, Clay said,
``Nothing surprises me anymore. People come and go and trades and
free agency are part of the game. Sometimes they're not easy to
figure out, but all I know is that it's over now. It's happened and
there's nothing we can do about it. Now we have to think of how to
replace those people and go from there. There's no use in going
backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay, a safety, is concerned about the right cornerback
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get the job done at that position, whether it's
one guy or by committee,'' he said. ``If it's by committee, so be
it. Someone has to step up and hold up their end at that position,
because you're going to see 10 other positions where people are
going to do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Because first-round draft pick Tebucky Jones was injured early
in Friday's session (pulled left hamstring), Clay didn't have a
chance to form an early opinion as to whether Jones can handle the
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to tell,'' said Clay. ``We have a veteran like Steve
Israel ready to step in if he's healthy and Chris Canty has learned
a lot over the past year. It's up to Tebucky, I guess. He's going
to get the opportunity to show everyone he can play there. It's too
bad he got hurt because a young kid needs all the time he can when
he first comes into the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   If there were any ``stars'' of the earlier rookie camp and the
minicamp, they were the young cornerbacks. Penn State's Mark Tate,
who spent much of last year on the practice squad, Kato Serwanga, a
free agent from California, and Terry Billups, a free agent from
North Carolina, all were impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Canty, who had been buried on the left side behind Ty Law, had a
chance to play with the first defense at right corner during
minicamp and played well. He's trying to change the opinions of
those who believe the Patriots made a mistake by making him their
first-round pick last year.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling after the camp is that the defense is ahead of the
offense, something that may be heard often during training camp in
Smithfield, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of minicamp was mainly on the offense, particularly
rookie running back Robert Edwards. Eyes also were following Drew
Bledsoe, as always, wide receiver Terry Glenn, and the offensive
line, which must come to make holes for the new halfback.
</P>
<P>
   The defense, meanwhile, appears to be for real.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in three years, the Patriots are running the
same defense for the second straight year. The constant changing of
schemes had taken its toll on some players. Now, rather than having
to learn a new style, they can just concentrate on improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot to be said for coming back here and playing the
same defense and just getting better on what we did last year,''
said linebacker Chris Slade. ``I think we're all pretty excited
about our defense. I thought we really came together toward the end
of the season and we played really well in the playoffs. If we can
get some help from our offense, I think it's going to be a great
year for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Ted Johnson won't agree that the Patriots played well
against Pittsburgh in the playoffs, even though they lost, 7-6,
allowing only a first-quarter touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have held them scoreless,'' he said. ``You can always
be better. But over the past few years, having to learn a new
defense and a new philosophy all the time, that cuts into the real
genuine experience you can have when you're actually out there and
you know the routine. Now we know the routine. We know where
everybody is supposed to be. We can help each other out a lot
more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the right ingredients and the right staff to get the
job done,'' Clay said. ``If we make enough adjustments, everyone is
expecting us to win.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jones was held out for the remainder of the camp after being
hurt. He was limping, but it was too early to tell the severity of
the injury. He will remain in the area, as will other rookies and
free agents, until June 26, when the strength and conditioning
program comes to an end ... Bledsoe likely will leave the area
shortly and return to his Montana retreat, as well as go home to
Washington state, until the start of training camp July 19. ``I
think we've made a lot of progress on the offense,'' he said.
``We've started to get our timing down with the receivers. I think
we'll adapt to it pretty quickly once camp starts.'' ... Owner
Robert Kraft, offensive lineman Bruce Armstrong, and coach Pete
Carroll addressed the fans before practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
