<HEADER>
A8543 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-GLAVINE-BO     06-08 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-GLAVINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMMY GUNNING FOR WIN OVER HOMETOWN TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Billerica, Mass., now may be in Tom Glavine's rear-view
mirror, but it's never out of sight. And certainly not out of his
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Any link to home makes Glavine a little sentimental, which is
why pitching Monday night's opener of the Red Sox-Braves series at
Turner Field still is special for the former National League Cy
Young winner and Most Valuable Player of the 1995 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is I'm still a Boston sports fan,'' said
Glavine. ``I keep up with the Red Sox and the Bruins and the
Celtics and the Patriots. I read whatever I can about them and
follow them on TV whenever I get the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine is happy to see the Red Sox doing so well, and says,
``Because Jimy Williams is there makes it even more special for me,
because he was a big part of what we did here in Atlanta for so
many years. Don't get me wrong, I'm going to go out there and try
to beat them as hard as I can, but sometimes you dream a little and
wonder what it would have been like to be a Red Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine could have traded in his Braves jersey a couple of years
ago when he became a free agent, but he decided not to leave a good
situation. He was there for the bad years in the late 1980s, so why
not stick around for the good times?
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, the Braves have been perennial contenders, and
Glavine has been one constant. He, along with manager Bobby Cox,
pitching coach Leo Mazzone, and to a degree John Smoltz, are the
last links to the bad Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The high point of Glavine's career came in '95 when the Braves
won it all and Glavine won Game 6 of the World Series with a
sterling 1-0 masterpiece over the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the Braves have been good in the playoffs, but not
good enough, beaten in the NLCS by the expansion and wild-card
Florida Marlins last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are dominating the regular season again. Even with an
8-2 rec-ord and a 2.10 ERA, Glavine can't boast that he's the
team's best pitcher. There's Greg Maddux, 9-2, with a 1.69 ERA;
lefthander Denny Neagle, 7-3 with a 3.04 ERA; young Kevin Millwood,
8-2 with a 4.07 ERA; and, waiting in the wings, the injured Smoltz.
Filling in for Smoltz has been veteran Dennis Martinez, who has a
2-2 record and a 3.86 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have a chance for four 20-game winners, last
accomplished by the '71 Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been pretty amazing and pretty impressive,'' said
Glavine. ``In the past, we always had four good starters. But now
with Kevin coming along, we've got five. Every day we pitch, we
have a top pitcher going against you, and that's not something many
teams have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the biggest differences in this year's team is
that we have a lineup that can score runs. Having Andres Galarraga
in the middle of our lineup has greatly improved our ability to
score runs. He's just a great hitter. He hits for average and
power. In years past, teams knew that we didn't have that
righthanded thump and then could flood us with lefties late in the
game. With Andres in the middle, they can't do that now.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine says his own pitching hasn't changed a bit. He says in
any given year one pitch is working better than another. This year
he's rediscovered his breaking pitch to go with one of the best
changeups in the game and a fastball that seems a yard quicker when
he's getting his offspeed stuff over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think being able to mix in a slider has really helped me in
keeping hitters off balance,'' he said. ``Part of being a
successful pitcher is being able to change what you do from time to
time so hitters don't see a pattern. I'm constantly doing that. You
have to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is precisely what Steve Avery has had trouble doing since
he left the Braves two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, like many in baseball, is baffled by the struggles of
Avery. At one time Avery and Glavine were inseperable, part of
baseball's most incredible staff. Glavine's great stuff and Avery's
dominating heat complemented each other well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having watched him up close for many years, I can't tell you
how good this guy was,'' Glavine said. ``He was the best young
lefty I'd ever seen. He carried us at times in '91 and '92 and in
the playoffs pitching big, money games. He had it all. To watch him
struggle ... it's baffling. I don't know what's going on with him.
I spoke to Steve in spring training and I knew he had some things
he was working on, but I haven't seen him since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's said that he doesn't have injuries and that he
fully recovered from his oblique muscle injury toward the end of
his time here, but he was never the most forthcoming guy when it
came to stuff like that. I mean, when his son was sick in '95,
nobody knew anything about it until he had to leave the team for a
while. He keeps things to himself. So, who knows if he was hurt
more than he ever said?
</P>
<P>
   ``What I do know is that sometimes when you struggle like he has
you have everybody in the world trying to tell you what's wrong.
Everyone means well because they're trying to help. But your head
can be swimming in all sorts of information. I hope that's not the
case there. When he left Atlanta, I thought it might be good for
him to go someplace else and get a different point of view. I think
Joe Kerrigan is a great pitching coach, but I don't know more than
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great that Ave is back in the big leagues. That's
a positive start,'' said Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine is thrilled that Williams has become a successful
manager. Williams was the third base coach and infield instructor
under Cox, and he also was the coach who worked with the pitchers
on their hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that someday we would lose him because he's too good of
a baseball man not to have been managing somewhere,'' Glavine said.
``I know the situation in Toronto was tough on him, but I think the
years he got to work under Bobby really helped him figure things
out. I was hoping he'd get a job, and then when he got the Red Sox
job, I was excited, because if I had to hand-pick someone to manage
my hometown team, I would have picked Jimy.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine asks his fellow Sox fans to be patient with Mark Lemke.
``He was the first roommate I ever had in the minors and we've been
through a lot together, so I'll always love the guy,'' Glavine
said. ``When we won in '95 and we all stormed out of the dugout
when we got the last out, one of the first people I looked for was
Lemmer. If you're looking for great production from him every day,
you're not going to get it. But he'll give you steady and at times
great defense. He'll help your pitchers out tremendously, and
honestly, I can't think of a guy who had bigger hits for our team
at the most crucial times.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's struggling now (he is injured), don't get down on him.
He'll come around, and when he does, he'll be a big asset for the
Red Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, Glavine, who will face Derek Lowe Monday night, is
impressed with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro Martinez is one of the best pitchers in the game, and
with Bret Saberhagen looking like he's back, to go along with Nomar
and Mo, that's a pretty strong nucleus,'' he said. ``They're one of
the best teams in baseball this year, so it'll be a challenge for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   A hometown challenge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
