<HEADER>
A8548 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ETHNIC-FINANCE-SFCHRO     06-08 1451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHNIC-FINANCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL FIRMS TAPPING INTO ETHNIC MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURA CASTANEDA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Banco Popular recently mailed preapproved credit card offers to
scores of Latinos across the United States.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The offer from the San Juan, Puerto Rico-based bank featured Don
Francisco, the host of a popular Spanish-language variety show
called ``Sabado Gigante.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I already have my Banco Popular Visa card and there is one
reserved just for you!,'' a grinning Don Francisco is quoted in
English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's credit cards, insurance products or mutual funds,
financial companies like Banco Popular are starting to take aim at
the nation's growing ethnic markets.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for ethnic consumers _ and bad.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, ethnic consumers are getting more opportunities
than ever to join the financial mainstream. On the other hand,
objective noncommercial information about products and services is
still hard to find in many of these communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marketers always have an agenda. They don't paint a complete
picture,'' said Kathy Li, director of Consumer Action's National
Resource Center in San Francisco. ``Many immigrants don't know
that. All of a sudden, they're bombarded with mailers,
telemarketers and salesmen. They take it for granted that what
they're told is true.''
</P>
<P>
   The preapproved offer from Banco Popular, for example, included
a $750 credit line, a $30 annual fee, and a 21.9 percent interest
rate.
</P>
<P>
   Informed consumers would know that if they had shopped around,
they could have qualified for a no-fee credit card with a lower
interest rate.
</P>
<P>
   There's a big untapped market for financial goods and services
in ethnic markets, according to Claritas Inc., an Arlington,
Va.-based market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Of the almost 267 million people in the United States, 12.7
percent are African American, 10.7 percent are Hispanic and 5.6
percent are Asian American (Japanese, Chinese, Korean, Vietnamese,
and Asian and Pacific Islander), Claritas said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 53.66 percent of Hispanics, 44.17 percent of African
Americans, and 76.75 percent of Asian Americans had credit cards,
Claritas found.
</P>
<P>
   Just 5.41 percent of Hispanics, 5.01 percent of African
Americans and 14.38 percent of Asian Americans owned mutual funds
in 1997, Claritas said.
</P>
<P>
   And 47.22 percent of Hispanics, 61.42 percent of African
Americans and 52.70 percent of Asian Americans had life insurance
in 1996, the most recent figures available, Claritas said.
</P>
<P>
   Banco Popular certainly isn't alone in targeting ethnic
consumers._ Freedom Card Inc., based in Marina Del Rey (Los Angeles
County), plans a statewide rollout next month of the Freedom Card,
a credit card targeting African Americans who haven't established
credit histories.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. in Boston launched a
marketing effort last year targeting Chinese Americans. The company
changed its name for the Chinese market to ``Everlasting Health''
and started providing bilingual agents, materials and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   _ A few weeks ago, Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. in San Francisco became
the first U.S. brokerage to create an Internet trading site in a
foreign language _ Chinese _ at www.schwab.com/chinese.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, ethnic groups often were ignored by financial goods
and services companies because marketers focused on the general
market, said Kris Reed, vice president of Claritas' financial
services group.
</P>
<P>
   Little information also was available about the purchasing
behavior of immigrants or low-income consumers, which often comes
from credit reports, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more financial goods and services companies are trying to
find immigrants and low-income consumers who have managed to climb
the economic ladder. ``The search now is for the ethnic population
that's reached a true middle class by being here long enough and
assimilating,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   A few companies, like Banco Popular and Freedom Inc., are
targeting immigrant and low-income consumers at the other end of
the spectrum who haven't yet established credit histories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers evolve, and we want to be there at all stages,''
said Rick Parlade, Banco Popular's senior vice president of
marketing. ``Given enough time in the U.S., Latinos will form a
banking relationship. We want to be that bank.''
</P>
<P>
   There can be a downside to these efforts, however. Banco Popular
may be trying to help Latinos establish credit, but it's also
offering discounts on money transfers from Western Union and
prescriptions from Kmart.
</P>
<P>
   By offering such discounts, Banco Popular is tacitly sending a
message to Latino consumers that it's OK to pay for prescriptions
out-of-pocket instead of getting health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   It's also encouraging the continued use of agencies like Western
Union, which provide expensive check cashing services and money
transfers.
</P>
<P>
   Parlade disagreed. He said a large number of Hispanics are
``unbanked'' and uninsured. He said Banco Popular wants to reach
these customers, and offer them a credit card option and discounts
on prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some negatives associated with check cashing and the
services offered by check cashers,'' he said. ``But in general, a
reputable check casher provides a valuable service.''
</P>
<P>
   Most important, Banco Popular allows Latinos to do business in
Spanish by providing bilingual materials and customer service
representatives, Parlade said.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley Buford, chairman and founder of Freedom Card Inc., said
many African Americans either don't use banks and have no credit
history at all, or have a ``challenged'' credit record because of
past problems with late payments and the like.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Card is designed to make it easier for first-time
credit card applicants to get a card by considering ``alternative''
credit histories, such as records of regular and timely payment of
phone bills and electric bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone has had the same phone number for 20 years, that
certainly suggests they're a stable person. Just because they don't
have a traditional credit history doesn't mean they're not credit
worthy,'' Buford said.
</P>
<P>
   The secured Freedom Card carries an interest rate of 12.5
percent to 18.5 percent. The unsecured Freedom Card has a 90-day
introductory interest rate of zero, which rises to between 15.5
percent and 18.5 percent. Both charge a $35 annual fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's got to be an opportunity in our financial system for
people to start again,'' said Buford, adding that Freedom Card also
offers a consumer-credit-education and money-management program.
</P>
<P>
   Cecilia Liu, director of Asian markets for John Hancock, said
it's important for companies to speak directly to ethnic markets by
providing materials in their native language and being culturally
sensitive to their needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Asians are still more comfortable speaking in their
own language, although they have no problem in English,'' she said.
``They feel more comfortable with different concepts.''
</P>
<P>
   The only way consumers can protect themselves is to become
educated about financial goods and services and make the effort to
shop around for products before they make a purchase, said Li of
Consumer Action.
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream publications such as Consumer Reports or Money
magazine may not be popular in ethnic communities, but there are
some places where consumers can get objective noncommercial
information in their native languages.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Action offers a variety of free brochures about credit,
insurance, investing and other consumer issues in English, Spanish,
Chinese, Korean and Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Credit Counseling Service, which helps consumers
straighten out credit problems, provides counselors, seminars and
education materials in a variety of languages. In addition to her
duties at Consumer Action, Li hosts a Cantonese-language radio
call-in show called, ``Consumer Rights,'' on Fridays from 1 p.m. to
2 p.m. on KEST-AM (1450).
</P>
<P>
   Bank Rate Monitor later this week will introduce a
Spanish-language version of its Web site at www.bankrate.com, which
will provide news and free rate information about mortgages, home
equity loans, auto loans, credit cards, and savings and checking
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Whether shopping for a new credit card or an auto loan,
consumers should do their homework before spending their money. And
if English is their second language, they should demand disclosures
in their native language or ask someone they trust to translate the
materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't sign anything you don't understand,'' said Gail
Hillebrand, a senior attorney for the San Francisco office of
Consumers Union, which publishes Consumer Reports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
