<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-WASDIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'LL BE FAMILY NIGHT FOR WASDIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ John Wasdin said he had been looking forward to making
the trip to Atlanta for quite some time. After all, his family had
planned a reunion around the Red Sox' three-game set vs. the Braves
beginning Monday night. From Tallahassee to Jacksonville, Wasdins
all over Florida were ready to make the trek north to converge upon
Ted Turner Field to watch their favorite Boston pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate them, Wasdin purchased some 30 tickets for each
game.
</P>
<P>
   Plane reservations had been confirmed. Hotel rooms booked. And,
yes, there were even plans for a family trip to Six Flags. But then
something came up last Wednesday night that caused a major glitch
in Wasdin's plans for a happy family reunion.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox optioned him to Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had about 45 people going to Atlanta, at least 30 for each
game,'' said Wasdin as he dressed for Sunday night's game against
the New York Mets. ``I'm from Tallahassee, so I have my mother and
father and friends going from Tallahassee to Atlanta. I live in
Jacksonville, which is where my wife's family is all from, and she
had all her family going to Atlanta on their vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I called them on Wednesday night and said, `Hey, I don't
think I'll be making it,''' he said. ``But they were still going to
go, because they basically wanted to see my new baby, my new little
girl, Avery Denise. So they were like, `Well, we're going. We don't
care if you're going or not.' So the tickets were not going to go
to waste if I was going or not going.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin smiled and laughed. He could afford to do so, especially
since he got his ticket to ride to Atlanta when the Red Sox
recalled him some 24 hours after sending him down to the minors.
The roster spot became available when Dennis Eckersley was placed
on the 15-day disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an experience like no other, I guess you could
say,'' said Wasdin, asked to describe his wacky week. ``From the
day I got optioned to the day I got recalled, it seemed like
forever in between, but the time was just a few hours, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin said he was scheduled to start for Pawtucket Sunday. Upon
his arrival in Pawtucket, he telephoned pitching coach Joe Kerrigan
to get his throwing assignment, but was told to hold off and report
back to Fenway Park Thursday, because something might be up with
Eck's arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got recalled and got a chance to pitch (against the Orioles
Thursday), and got a chance to pitch the next night (in the series
opener against the Mets Friday),'' said Wasdin, who retired all
nine batters he faced in three innings of work in a 9-2 loss to the
Mets. ``It was a lot of pressure to come in and throw that first
night back, because, in my mind, I didn't want to get sent down,
but I didn't have the stats to back that up. I really didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say all you really want to say, but when you've got a
6.30 ERA and you've given up more hits than innings, that's not
getting the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was precisely the reason Wasdin wound up in Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to acknowledge it then, because no one wants to
get sent down,'' he said. ``But I was like, hey, this is a chance
for me to get back into the rotation, or to start again, or to get
my feet back under me. So I had the right frame of mind, then I got
recalled and I was like, `OK, let's show them I can pitch here and
that I can be consistent,' because that was the thing _ I was
inconsistent, I was flip-flopping. I'd have a two good innings then
I'd have a bad inning, or something like that. But to have two good
outings back to back really helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   Said manager Jimy Williams, ``He's got a good arm. He always
competes. He's resilient and can pitch a lot. Pitching those three
innings the other day really helped us. Even though we didn't win,
it helped save our bullpen a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   While it also helped lower Wasdin's ERA to 5.35, it did little
to improve his hits-to-innings-pitched ratio, which is 39 to 33
2/3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, being sent down really made me more focused. It kind
of rejuvenates you, so to speak,'' Wasdin said. ``Maybe I was in a
little bit of a lull or a dead period where I was going through the
motions, and being sent down might have fired me up a little bit.
It made me re-evaluate my situation here and realize you can't take
anything for granted and you've got to go out there and make each
inning and each pitch count. Basically, that's what I'm going to
try and do from here on out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
