<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENKINS-JENKINS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA TITLES START WITH STOPS 
BY BRUCE JENKINS
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-SFCHRON   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The highlights of Sunday night's game will be
condensed into a few choice plays, like Michael Jordan's one-armed
magic against Greg Ostertag or the full-court pass by Dennis
Rodman, and rightly so. NBA greatness is always defined by scoring.
With a few choice words _ Magic's hook, West's bomb, or merely
Garfield Heard _ you're right back in the moment.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a cult level to NBA lore, stories barely remembered
and seldom told. They are the unopened volumes, telling the real
story, and they center entirely around defense.
</P>
<P>
   In that ridiculous 42-point rout of Utah, the Chicago Bulls set
a team-wide offensive standard they won't be able to match. Not in
this series, maybe not ever if Jordan sails into the sunset. Nobody
could miss, not even Jud Buechler. Bill Wennington was a heck of an
option. Even Dickey Simpkins put one down. It was bawdy, comical
and completely unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee you,'' said Buechler, ``you won't see a score like
this again in the series.''
</P>
<P>
   But what's happening inside the Jazz players' heads? How does it
feel knowing that they can't execute their offense, that they can't
set the tough screens, that a 6-for-6 start by Karl Malone means
absolutely nothing?
</P>
<P>
   The malady has persevered through two full games now, and in a
short series like the NBA Finals, that's a trend. ``We aren't
putting up much of a fight,'' said Utah coach Jerry Sloan, ``and
that's really disappointing. I mean, we're out there and we can't
make a simple inbounds pass. I think it's embarrassing _ for the
entire NBA _ not to come out with any more fight than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan glanced at a copy of the final boxscore, a surrealistic
set of numbers showing seven turnovers by Malone, 30 percent
shooting by the Jazz, a combined two points by John Stockton and
Howard Eisley, and the 96-54 final.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is actually the score?'' said Sloan. ``I thought it was
196.''
</P>
<P>
   No team in the history of the 24-second shot clock had scored
fewer points. Not just in the Finals or the playoffs, but in  &LR; any
 &LR; game. The plodding beasts of the mid-50s did better than this. It
was also the most one-sided game ever witnessed in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Center Greg Foster was seething. Where he comes from, the hard
streets of Oakland high school ball, you don't lose a game this way
without losing some pride, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just real f_ embarrassing,'' he said. ``And I'll tell
you what, if we're not embarrassed by this, as a team, you can just
go ahead and give 'em the trophy right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewed from a historical sense, the Bulls are not unlike the
49ers during Joe Montana's run. Excitement flowed from the offense
_ like Jordan, Montana was one for the ages _ but the 49ers won
their Super Bowls with defense. Insiders remember Dan Bunz, Hacksaw
Reynolds and Eric Wright as much as they remember ``The Drive,''
Roger Craig or Jerry Rice.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls may not be remembered as one of the all-time defensive
teams, because the specter of Jordan will be all-consuming. But
they've earned the reputation. As Buechler said, ``Michael and
Scottie Pippen are two of the best defenders to ever play. Throw in
Dennis Rodman, and everybody else getting into it, and it just gets
crazy out there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In all my years in the business,'' said Sloan, ``I don't think
I've ever seen a team play better defensively than Chicago did
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockton looked positively helpless, shooting 1-for-4 and never
getting to the free-throw line. Malone broke from the gate like a
cooped-up thoroughbred, but he was a different man after Rodman
entered the game. At the time, he was on a 5-for-5 roll. For the
rest of the first half _ nearly 15 minutes' worth _ Malone took
only two shots.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman has his own unique way of explaining things. As he said
before the game, ``I'm doing a great job on Malone. He doesn't
intimidate me. Why would he? He went to school (Louisiana Tech)
with my sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   But you can't put it all on Malone. The man did score 22 points
in a clear revival of his shooting touch. ``It wasn't Karl's
fault,'' said Foster. ``No one else did a damn thing to help him.
All anyone wanted to do was shoot the ball, not make the extra
pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone insisted that ``Our plays work. But we have to run 'em.
They had a hell of a defensive game, and we didn't respond.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's the hidden legacy of the Bulls. Occasionally through
time, a defensive play will stand out, like the great Boston Garden
steals by John Havlicek and Larry Bird. More often, those moments
disappear. People remember Magic and Doctor J, and they forget
about Michael Cooper, K.C. Jones, Walt Frazier, Satch Sanders. They
forget how the Warriors shut down Elvin Hayes in '75 or why Bill
Russell kept beating Chamberlain and West.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is Rodman on Malone, Jordan on anybody, and the
octopus-like Pippen, whom coach Phil Jackson says has ``the ability
to be a one-man wrecking crew'' on defense. It's a fine part of
history, every bit as relevant as Jordan's astonishing repertoire.
Years from now, the Jazz can tell you all about it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
