<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-AVERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVERY ARMED WITH NEW DELIVERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ All he's ever wanted to do in Boston, really, is
contribute _ in any way possible. As a starter. A reliever out of
the bullpen. And, on those rare occasions, even as a pinch runner.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Avery has done it all.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday night before 30,630 at Fenway Park, Avery took
another step in cementing his spot in Boston's starting rotation _
which always had been his intended role _ by throwing seven innings
of shutout ball, allowing just three hits and one walk while
ringing up four strikeouts, to lead the Red Sox to a 5-0 victory
over the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time he felt this good after a game?
</P>
<P>
   ``Umm, it's been a while,'' said Avery, who struggled through a
minor league assignment in Pawtucket in April before he recently
found the groove by tinkering with the angle of his delivery. ``The
last time I really threw the ball like I felt I was capable of was
in Cleveland last year. It just helps your mentality to go out
there and to feel good with what you're doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm throwing the ball, and I'm struggling to throw
strikes and struggling for the ball to come out the way you want it
to, you're not going to be yourself mentally,'' he added. ``But
when you can relax and concentrate on the hitter and do what comes
naturally, it helps everything. I felt, mentally, I was a lot
better tonight, even better than the last time because the last
time I was a little bit nervous with what I was doing out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery's last start was last Tuesday in Toronto. He went five
innings and allowed three runs and three hits in a 5-3 victory,
only his second of the season and first since a 5-0 shutout over
Kansas City May 16. The reason he was nervous was that he was
experimenting with some new mechanics on the mound, a new release
point suggested by pitching coach Joe Kerrigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been used to throwing it over the top,'' said Avery, who
said he received a phone message from Atlanta pitcher John Smoltz
when he returned to the clubhouse. ``But by dropping my arm down, I
probably got rid of some of the other bad things I was doing. I was
striding too far, and leaning away from the plate. But I can't do
these things when I'm throwing from the angle I'm throwing at.
Balls come out a lot better and I'm a lot more consistent. Tonight,
I threw the ball wherever I wanted to most of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, with the exception of a lapse in the fourth, which
prompted a visit from Kerrigan. So why did it take so long to
detect Avery's delivery problem, and to correct it?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times when you're asking someone to make a change
like that, you've got to ask them to make it their idea,'' Kerrigan
said. ``Or, at least, half their idea, especially with someone
who's been very successful since he was 19 years old throwing from
the same arm slot.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan indicated ``we finally put it to him in a meeting in
New York in Yankee Stadium. Then I just asked him to play catch
with me in the outfield in Trenton and told him to throw it
sidearm, just to see what it looked like. Then we gradually did it
on the side.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery said it took some doing to get used to a delivery ``that
felt like I was throwing it sidearm,'' he said, but it takes some
time and some practice _ and a little patience, as well _ before it
becomes second nature to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I got a little bit tired tonight, I felt myself wanting to
go back to what I was used to,'' Avery said. ``But, really, I tell
everyone _ I tell Hattie (catcher Scott Hatteberg) and I tell Joe
to remind me to keep my arm down there. It's probably going to be
that way for a little bit, but you can't argue with the results.''
</P>
</TEXT>
