<SLUG> BC-CYCLING-USPRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEELS OF FORTUNE FOR HINCAPIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ George Hincapie was thinking he was in the
twilight zone. His mother Martha was crying tears of happiness. And
the bike race announcer was screaming, ``Oh, how sweet revenge
is!''
</P>
<P>
   All this as Hincapie _ a winner turned loser in this race a year
ago _ was shooting over the finish line first in Sunday's First
Union US Professional Racing Organization Championship, winning in
6 hours 6 minutes 35 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Hincapie hopped on the podium when he thought he was
the first American finisher, thus gaining the title of US
professional national champion. But he had it taken away minutes
later when judges disqualified him for illegally using a team car
to draft with in the race.
</P>
<P>
   So no wonder when he took to the winner's stand Sunday, he said,
``If anyone has something to say, say it now, or forever hold your
peace.'' The crowd roared. It kept roaring, and clapping, as
Hincapie was bestowed win after win and check after check.
</P>
<P>
   First, it was $30,000 for winning the race, which was 156 miles
long. Then it was a starred-and-striped jersey for being the first
American to win, and becoming the year's US pro national champion.
Finally, there was a silver cup and a check for $10,000 for winning
the Solidarity Cup, a series of races completed Sunday that took
place over the past two months in Poland and America.
</P>
<P>
   But Hincapie, 24, chose to be diplomatic later, accentuating the
positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's not revenge,'' he said. ``Last year was devastating
to me; I thought I was the strongest and I thought I won. But that
was last year. This is this year, and I won.''
</P>
<P>
   The race that covered 10 circuits around downtown Philadelphia
traveled along the Schuylkill River, up the steep road called the
Manayunk Wall, and back down to make a loop in front of the fans at
the start-finish line. And the fast, crescendoing synthesizer music
and the announcer's frantic voice were not in the least too intense
for the drama that unfolded during the last half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off the last climb at Manayunk, Lance Armstrong made a
strong attack to get out front, and most of his US Postal Service
teammates followed suit. (``They're trying to put a stamp on this
race!'' the announcer yelled.) But despite his attempt at humor, he
was right; the team was riding with conviction.
</P>
<P>
   As the riders made their way on the last three 3-mile circuits
of the race, the red, white, and blue Postal Service jerseys
dominated the lead pack of 30. The Polish, Spanish, and Italian
riders were trying to pedal up to the front and dominate, but
Hincapie said it was two Americans _ Frank McCormack, of Leicester,
Mass., and McCormack's brother Mark, of North Easton, Mass. _ who
were really causing him trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two riders are incredibly fast, so I really had to rely
on the distance,'' he said. ``I would say normally in any
50-kilometer race, those two guys would be faster than me. But I
was confident that after 160 miles, that it's a different sprint,
and I was confident in my ability to sprint. I had to just believe
in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   So with just 200 meters to go, as riders jostled for position
and rode far faster than the 25.43 m.p.h. they had been averaging,
Hincapie made for the line. That, he said, is when his mind zoned
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing,'' he said. ``A moment like that, it's kind of
just like you're in outer space. The last 50 meters, you don't feel
nothing, you don't hear nothing. All of a sudden you're just like
in the twilight zone. You wish that moment could last forever.''
</P>
<P>
   And as he was winning, his mother was crying, like last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was crying then, and I'm crying today,'' she said, holding a
bouquet of flowers her son had won.
</P>
<P>
   The women's race was ridden simultaneous to the men's race but
covered 57.6 miles and is on the World Cup circuit.
</P>
<P>
   As if to say, ``Been there, done that,'' Petra Rossner of
Germany raised her hands in victory even before she crossed the
finish line. Rossner, who won the race in 2 hours 22 minutes 18
seconds, was the winner here two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dede Demet, of Boulder, Colo., held onto her first-place World
Cup standing after finishing seventh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
