<HEADER>
A8603 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTITRUST-ANALYSIS-SF     06-08 1518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTITRUST-ANALYSIS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY U.S. IS CHANGING TACK ON ANTITRUST ENFORCEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From entrepreneurial darlings to evil monopolists,
from nerds in a garage to corporate titans, Intel and Microsoft
symbolize the technology industry, the fastest-growing segment of
the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission will meet today on whether to file
an antitrust suit against Intel, following on the heels of a
similar Justice Department action against Microsoft. Sources expect
the FTC to approve an action against the Santa Clara chip giant.
</P>
<P>
   With these two historic antitrust cases, the federal government
is targeting the two companies that more than any other symbolize
the phenomenal growth and success of the high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits mark a sea change in antitrust enforcement. After
nearly 16 years of relative quiet on the issue of big-firm
domination, the federal government has opened an aggressive attack
on the twin behemoths of America's most prominent industry.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high. Should the lawsuits succeed, they will
impose rules and limits on an industry that has prided itself on
its freewheeling independence.
</P>
<P>
   Reminiscent of decades-old antitrust cases against big oil and
big steel, these suits seek to rearrange the driveshaft of the U.S.
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who's right, but I'm sure that 10 or 15 years
from now, history will be very different depending on what this
court does,'' said Robert Litan, a former Clinton administration
antitrust lawyer who negotiated the original 1994 consent decree
with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Both actions spring from government investigations into whether
the firms used their monopolies _ Microsoft's operating system
software and Intel's computer chips _ to squash competition.
</P>
<P>
   However, neither case turns on classic antitrust issues, such as
predatory pricing. Instead, Intel and Microsoft appear to have
drawn the government's attention because smaller players had
complained about the two giants' dominance in their markets.
</P>
<P>
   But why high tech, and why now?
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1970s, antitrust action against dominant firms had
been in full retreat, led by University of Chicago economists who
argued that the goal of antitrust should be to protect consumers,
not competitors.
</P>
<P>
   More efficient and innovative companies serve consumers better,
they argued, even if it means the leader drives out weaker rivals.
This ``Chicago School'' thinking spread through mainstream academia
and took root in the federal judiciary, including the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   By 1982, the Reagan administration virtually eliminated
dominant-firm cases; antitrust efforts were refocused on
anti-competitive mergers, collusion and criminal activity such as
bid-rigging and price-fixing.
</P>
<P>
   A major exception was the 1984 breakup of AT&AMP;T; the
administration argued, however, that AT&AMP;T was more like a monopoly
created by government regulation than one derived by efficiency;
even as AT&AMP;T's divestiture was announced, the Justice Department
dropped its 13-year antitrust case against IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Bush administration actually initiated the
investigation against Microsoft, dominant-firm antitrust action
began its real resurgence under President Clinton, with cases
against the mergers of Office Depot and Staples, and Lockheed and
Northrop, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Differing ideology clearly played some role. ``The current
administration is far more skeptical of the strength, vibrancy,
dynamism and self-correction of the marketplace,'' said Rick Rule,
a former Reagan antitrust chief now consulting for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is far more blind to the limitations of government, the
costs of enforcement and the relative weakness of the government in
correcting the marketplace.'
</P>
<P>
   But politics are hardly all-explaining. Microsoft's critics and
defenders straddle the ideological map. Former judge Robert Bork,
whose 1978 book The Antitrust Paradox did much to lead the
antitrust retreat, is now heading the intellectual attack on
Microsoft. And Sen. Patty Murray, a liberal Democrat from
Microsoft's home state of Washington, is among the company's
staunchest defenders.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the revival of antitrust zeal, some say, is that
the cute little baby high tech firms of 1980s have grown into big
ugly giants. They and their founders dominate the Information Age
like the robber barons did the Industrial Revolution: Bill Gates
and Microsoft are today's version of John D. Rockefeller and
Standard Oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason the Reagan administration didn't have to confront
this is, of course, because Microsoft and Intel were not in the
dominant positions that they are today,'' said Litan.
</P>
<P>
   The world has changed too. ``It's no accident that the law was
much more conservative at a time when American companies were
running for their lives against formidable Japanese and European
competitors,'' said William Kovacic, an antitrust scholar at George
Mason University.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Defendants in antitrust cases were winning when ``America had
clearly lost its unchallenged supremacy on the world economic
scene,'' Kovacic said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies did a great job of saying, `We're not hideous
monopolists, we are national treasures, we are engines of
competitive success in the global marketplace,' '' he said.
``They'd look at judges and say, `Do you really want to take that
apart?' and in one courtroom after another, the federal judiciary
said, `No we don't.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Some say it is high tech's greatest asset _ innovation _ that
makes it an antitrust target. Fierce global competition in mature
industries offers no room for monopolies in things like chemicals,
steel, automobiles and machinery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no new ideas that are going to get you 60 or 70
percent of the cement business,'' said Robert Crandall, a Brookings
Institution analyst. ``Whereas with things changing rapidly in high
tech industries, you're more likely to hit upon something which
gets you a large share of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Theories have evolved too. Chicago School thinking has come
under attack from new theories of ``network effects'' and
``lock-ins.'' By this thinking, an inferior technology can gain
such a foothold that it blocks adoption of superior technologies.
Microsoft's Windows operating system is on so many computers, the
argument goes, that all new software applications have to run on
it; and the more applications that are written for Windows, the
less the chance that a better software platform can ever dislodge
it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many antitrust experts see an uphill battle for the
government. The courts, including the Supreme Court, remain hostile
to plaintiffs alleging predatory behavior.
</P>
<P>
   A taste of this came with a recent appellate court decision
favoring Microsoft in which the government alleged that the company
violated the 1994 consent decree by bundling its Internet browser
with Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   The court said judges should not be designing software.
</P>
<P>
   ``That language is very favorable to Microsoft,'' Litan said.
``It's a concern that many judges are going to have on their minds.
If Justice is going to win this case on the browser issue, they are
going to have to have a satisfactory answer to explain to the
courts why judges won't have to be involved in the minutiae (of
software development) or find a way to keep them from having to
arbitrate every new wrinkle that happens to come into (Microsoft's)
operating system.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton antitrust chief Joel Klein has taken a relatively
moderate approach, eschewing any breakup of Microsoft and instead
attacking exclusive marketing agreements and ``bundling'' of
Microsoft's Internet browser with Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the FTC's anticipated case against Intel appears to
be quite narrow. It is expected to focus on whether the
market-leading chip firm had a right to withhold design information
on upcoming chips from companies that sued it for patent
infringement.
</P>
<P>
   But even these narrowly drawn cases could enmesh the courts in
disputes over basic business strategies: how to market products,
how to write customer contracts, how to price products and how to
design them, and what obligations dominant companies have toward
their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Others say Microsoft's tactics are a simple case of a monopolist
forcing consumers to buy its other products. Xerox tried it with
copier paper; IBM tried it with punch cards; even a manufacturer of
a salt dispenser to make snow melt tried to get everyone to buy its
salt too.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been going on since 1890,'' said Irwin Stelzer, an
analyst at the American Enterprise Institute. ``I've been in this
antitrust racket for 40 years, and every business that gets
challenged begins by saying its industry is different. This is a
classic antitrust case with a very clever public relations overload
that is trying to say, `This is high tech. Dare not interfere with
us or the economy stops.' The fact is, innovation will stop if you
allow Microsoft to keep competitors out by tying new products to
their monopoly power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
