</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, June 14.)  
 (HLW)  
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; WOMEN WITH MEN: THREE STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Ford. Vintage Contemporaries, $12.
</P>
<P>
   The three male protagonists in these post-macho tales, whether
in Paris, Montana or Chicago, are always with women, even when
they're not. They also share a sense that things aren't working out
as they should, or perhaps once did. In praising this ``superb
volume'' last year in these pages, Michael Gorra said of the
author, ``Nobody now writing looks ... more like an American
classic.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BLOOD RITES: ORIGINS AND HISTORY OF THE PASSIONS OF WAR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Barbara Ehrenreich. Metropolitan/Holt, $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   The author, armed with a Ph.D. in biology and a sweeping range
of historical literature, argues that it isn't self-interest or
immutable aggressive instincts that drive humans to war, but the
primordial trauma of being hunted by animals who might be appeased
with bloody rituals. ``One of today's most original writers has
tackled one of humankind's most intractable subjects,'' Michael
Sherry wrote in the Book Review last year. ``Properly awed by her
subject, she seeks to nudge and provoke readers, not overpower
them.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MERCY SEAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Rilla Askew. Penguin, $13.95.
</P>
<P>
   This ambitious frontier novel, filled with echoes of the Old
Testament, is narrated by a tough 10-year-old girl who becomes the
prime mover in her extended family as it journeys from Kentucky to
the remote Indian Territory of Oklahoma. The author ``artfully lays
bare the sins and promises of a pioneer society,'' James Polk said
in these pages in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MANSION ON THE HILL: DYLAN, YOUNG, GEFFEN, SPRINGSTEEN, AND
THE HEAD-ON COLLISION OF ROCK AND COMMERCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Fred Goodman. Vintage, $14.
</P>
<P>
   A former editor at Rolling Stone profiles some of
rock-and-roll's most influential musicians and managers, and in the
process tracks the growth of an industry that once aspired to
change the world. The result is ``an excellent chronicle of rock's
sad metamorphosis from a quasi-moral force into an unstoppable
money machine,'' Charles Kaiser said here last year.  &UR; INVISIBLE
REPUBLIC: BOB DYLAN'S BASEMENT TAPES &LR; , by Greil Marcus (Owl/Holt,
$12.95), focuses on a legendary group of more than 100 cowboy
ballads, Appalachian tunes and other folk songs recorded by Dylan
and the Band in 1967. ``No previous writer has so transportingly or
authoritatively revealed ... Dylan against the receding vistas of
American music and culture,'' Robert Polito wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TALKING TO THE DEAD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Helen Dunmore. Back Bay/Little, Brown, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   A London photographer travels to rural Britain to care for her
older sister and her newborn son, a visit that stirs painful
memories of the sisters' infant brother and the increasingly
suspicious circumstances surrounding his death 25 years earlier.
This ``gripping and complex'' story ''metamorphoses from a simple
mystery into a moral whodunit,'' Carol Kino said in the Book Review
last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE KISS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Kathryn Harrison. Bard/Avon, $11.
</P>
<P>
   The author tells of her obsessive affair with her father, a
handsome middle-aged preacher who turned up after a long absence to
seduce her when she was a college student. This ``powerful,
disturbing'' memoir is about ``the soul of a young girl and the
terrible injury inflicted by the man who should have been its
protector,'' Susan Cheever wrote here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FUGITIVE PIECES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Anne Michaels. Vintage International, $12.
</P>
<P>
   This first novel by a Canadian poet takes shape in the journal
of a Polish Jew and orphaned Holocaust survivor, whose inner life
is filled with inquiries into the nature of memory, guilt, atrocity
and love. Last year, our reviewer, W.S. Di Piero, admired the
book's ``lyricism and sassy deftness.''  &UR; THE SHADOW CATCHER &LR; , by
Andrzej Szczypiorski, translated by Bill Johnston (Grove, $12),
features another protagonist scarred by Nazi-era Poland. In this
coming-of-age novel, a sensitive 15-year-old boy in Warsaw
gradually senses that his safe, privileged world is crumbling
around him. The author ``revels in smells and textures, bodies and
sounds,'' Piotr Michalowski said here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE INHERITANCE: HOW THREE FAMILIES AND THE AMERICAN POLITICAL
MAJORITY MOVED FROM LEFT TO RIGHT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Samuel G. Freedman. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $15.
</P>
<P>
   The author charts the rise and fall of the New Deal coalition by
following three blue-collar immigrant families -- one Irish, one
Polish, one Italian -- as they claw their way to respectability by
the third generation. In 1996 our reviewer, James M. McPherson,
called this a ``timely, incisive, and engrossing book.'' The same
publisher has issued another personal account of the nation's
rightward shift,  &UR; RADICAL SON: A GENERATIONAL ODYSSEY &LR; , by David
Horowitz ($15), in which a son of communist parents details his
journey from Marxist radical in the New Left of the '60s to
militant critic of his former associates. This is a ``warmly human
and abrasive'' autobiography, Richard Gid Powers wrote here last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE STORY OF JUNK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Linda Yablonsky. Back Bay/Little, Brown, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   The narrator, an aspiring writer who deals heroin to pay for her
habit, is surprisingly sharp and upbeat as she plies her trade in
the East Village drug and art scene in the 1980s. Last year in
these pages, Catherine Texier called this first novel ``a
fascinating account ... of life at the edge of one's soul.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
