<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The Longest Day can't get a minute
 &HT;    (For release Wednesday, June 10, 1998.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 54th anniversary of D-Day, the Sixth of June, passed
Saturday without mention in my local newspaper, or on any of the
local and national TV news shows I saw.
</P>
<P>
   One of those all-movies cable channels I am fond of watching
actually showed war films all evening and night. But they were of
the Korean and Vietnam Wars.
</P>
<P>
   Four years after much of the Western world commemorated the 50th
anniversary of the momentous 1944 Allied invasion of Nazi-held
Europe, the significance of it seems no longer worthy of a line of
observance, or a flash of film.
</P>
<P>
   With me, D-Day is a reverent occasion. As has been my long
custom, I pulled out my dramatic, albeit militaristic, soundtrack
of the 1962 classic war film ``The Longest Day'' and played it
loudly in my home.
</P>
<P>
   It's an empty nest now, been so for a while. Only my wife could
hear it, and she understands me.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, I insisted our four children listen to both it
and to me telling about why I believe D-Day was the most important
day in the history of our civilization _ an arguable opinion but
mine nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   Probably because I went through much of my impressionable
adolescence during World War II, the dates of seven critical events
during that war have stayed in my memory bank, although the total
number of Hank Aaron's home runs and the birthdates of several of
my nine grandchildren already have seeped out.
</P>
<P>
   They were Dec. 7, 1941 (Pearl Harbor); June 6, 1944 (D-Day);
April 12, 1945 (Roosevelt's death); May 7, 1945 (Germany's
surrender); Aug. 6, 1945 (Hiroshima); Aug. 14 (Japan's
capitulation); and Sept. 2, 1945 (Japan's formal surrender.)
</P>
<P>
   A friend who I asked said he thought one of the most memorable
dates in his life was the day we landed on the moon _ but he
couldn't tell me what the date was (July 20, 1969). And I confessed
to him that I could not remember the date of the end of the Korean
War although, on the very day it ended, I was on orders to ship
over there (July 27, 1953).
</P>
<P>
   Another friend once called me ``a collector of battlefields,''
inasmuch as I had twice visited the beaches of Normandy and the
American cemetery above it, and have twice been to Pearl Harbor, as
well as to Bastogne in Belgium, where the great Battle of the Bulge
was fought in 1944, and to Monte Cassino, site of a lengthy siege
during the Italian campaign, as well as to other battle sites in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he's right, but more likely I'm a keeper of memories
(and the dates of those memories) from a time when there was no
debate about whether a war had to be fought to save civilization.
My visits to those sites, particularly the cemetery in Normandy,
were more as a pilgrimage to give thanks to, and to honor, those
who died so that future generations may live.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, I took my grandson there. At age 13, it was
time he felt what I felt when I was 13.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds corny and sentimental to talk that way today, but
that's me. I'm going to keep playing the theme from ``The Longest
Day'' until the tape wears out, and I'm going to keep remembering
that day, and those other important wartime dates _ because someone
has to.
</P>
<P>
   And it would be gratifying if our newspapers, radio and TV
stations cut a little time out of their crime and sex reporting to
commemorate and keep alive the memories of those supremely critical
days that shaped our lives.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
