<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Short Takes: Goldwater's epitaph
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even liberals are elbowing each other out of the way to say nice
things about Barry Goldwater. Sen. Goldwater was the trusted
friend, straight-shooter, gallant warrior, true blue conservative _
the kind of conservative liberals want back. Yet, in one moment of
Goldwater's life he irrevocably splintered the terms of the
national debate.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1964 GOP convention, Goldwater, accepting his party's
presidential nomination, declared, ``Extremism in defense of
liberty is no vice. Moderation in pursuit of justice is no
virtue.'' It brought down the house the way Dwight Eisenhower's
petulant poke at ``sensation-seeking columnists'' _ pronounced
``col-yum-nists'' _ did in 1956. The cheering startled Ike more
than the Ardennes.
</P>
<P>
   If Goldwater meant what he said, one can only wonder what he
thought he meant. Containing Communism? The Bomb? The crowd knew,
or thought so. It was a stunning statement in a country whose
genius had been moderation, all of a sudden on its way to becoming
a semi-dirty word. The genie was out of the bottle, later to be
clothed in more respectable togs: Silent Majority, Southern
Strategy, Reagan Democrat, New Right. The incivility of your choice
could be noble pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater went on to other things, most notably talking Richard
Nixon out of office; Henry Kissinger and Alexander Haig also claim
credit. Goldwater never took what he said back. Someone repeated it
at his funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
