<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8754 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN10-COX     06-08 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Push to stifle unions still threatens
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Partisanship aside for a moment, anyone with even vestigial
twitches of fairness has to be relieved that California voters last
week put the kibosh to a referendum that would have forced unions
to get written permission from their members to spend dues money on
politics.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was pitched as defending the little guy from the
predations of powerful union bosses _ ``paycheck protection,''
so-called _ but it was no such thing.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum was part of a national effort by Republicans and
conservative action groups to misuse the law to defund a political
opponent. Similar referenda are afoot in three other states. A push
for comparable legislation is being made in at least two dozen
state legislatures, and a look-alike bill is pending in the U.S.
House.
</P>
<P>
   The California vote will slow the drive but won't end it.
Sponsors figure they are bound to win in some states, and in
others, as in California, the push will help to keep the AFL-CIO
out of electoral politics by draining its treasury. The unions and
their allies had to outspend the proponents massively _ to the tune
of some $20 million _ to turn the California initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The unions' vigorous self-defense overcame an initial 30-to-70
percent deficit in the polls to win an impressive 53-to-47 percent
victory. Significantly for a measure titularly in their protection,
64 percent of union voters opposed the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was their vote just cash-and-carry politics. Once the rank
and file tumbled to the real agenda, volunteers scrambled against
the proposition. The unions figure, as a side benefit, they have
enlivened some 24,000 previous dormant members for grass-roots
politicking in California's fall elections.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt to take organized labor out of political play is a
reaction to revived union activism. After years of hibernation, the
AFL-CIO bestirred itself some $35 million worth in the last
election cycle, either in overt support of Democrats or in supposed
nonpartisan ``issue'' advertising that covered its partisanship
only technically, about like a thong bikini covers a sunbather.
</P>
<P>
   Even that level of spending wasn't close to pre-emptive.
Union-backed candidates had only indifferent success, and the
Center for Responsive Politics calculates that even with
re-energized union political spending, corporations still outspend
the unions 11-to-1 in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Claims of union advantage are a falsehood of political
convenience for the GOP and for conservative interest groups,
lately so taken with what they believe should be their
inevitability that they have lost all patience with competitiveness
in politics.
</P>
<P>
   If fairness were more than just a hollow drum beaten on behalf
of neutralizing labor, the legislative push would be equally
demanding annual signatures from shareholders before corporations
could spend their mite for politics. Interest groups would be
required to get written permission from members for partisan
spending. It might be interesting to see how the National Rifle
Association membership would fall out.
</P>
<P>
   The folks trying to engineer at least a rough fairness into
politics are the ones pushing for broad campaign funding reform.
The groups trying to sideline the unions are notably absent from
that effort.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
