<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-METROS-FUSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE METROSTARS ARE HOT, BUT NOT REALLY BOTHERED 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ As the MetroStars played their third
game in a week, the temperature here on Sunday was a frying-pan-hot
97 degrees, with no clouds overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not move,'' Coach Alfonso Mondelo said. ``We could
not think. Our midfielders were totally dead in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   So Mondelo implored his players to seek ball control against the
Miami Fusion, to be patient and to focus on producing
high-percentage shots. And they did everything he asked in a 2-1
victory before 9,075 at Lockhart Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The victory lifted the MetroStars to 7-6 in Major League
Soccer's Eastern Conference and gave them 19 points in the
standing, 2 behind second-place Columbus. Miami (5-9) lost its
fifth straight game.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was far from easy. Tony Meola, who stopped 27 of the Fusion's
28 shots, said, ``I don't know how our guys lasted for 90
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars won the game near the end, when both teams were
heavy-legged from the heat and humidity. Eduardo Hurtado passed on
the left to Miles Joseph, who moved past a defender and beat an
on-rushing Scott Budnick, who was making his first start in goal
for the Fusion.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph, a substitute for Giovanni Savarese in the 62d minute,
bowed after his goal in the 88th minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a bad first touch and the crowd let me know about it,''
Joseph said, smiling. ``So I had to give them something back.''
</P>
<P>
   Savarese had yielded to Joseph because of the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``My legs were starting to tighten up,'' Savarese said. ``It was
unbelievable out there. I just felt somebody could give us more of
a lift at that point. I wanted to do the smart thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Savarese had given the MetroStars the lead in the game's 35th
minute. Budnick left the net to wrest the ball from midfielder Paul
Dougherty, but he could not control it and, in a strange sequence,
the ball rolled down his back and over to a looming Savarese.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the confusion,'' Savarese said. ``So I moved in to see
what else would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Savarese found himself with a clear eight-footer for his fifth
goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Fusion evened the game in the 63d minute. Defender Matt
Knowles's attempted clearing pass bounced off Fusion forward Dan
Stebbins and went to midfielder Diego Serna, who burst through a
suddenly flat-footed MetroStars defense and beat Meola with a
15-foot shot.
</P>
<P>
   Meola retrieved the ball from the net and angrily punted it
toward midfield.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Knowles, who recently returned to the MetroStars from
the Staten Island Vipers of the A-League and today was replacing
the American World Cup player Alexi Lalas, made the defensive play
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Serna had raced around a diving Meola about 5 yards from the
goal in the 31st minute, and had nothing but daylight between him
and the net. But he tapped his shot instead of blasting it.
</P>
<P>
   That left precious moments for Knowles, starting because Mark
Semioli was sidelined with a possible broken big toe on his right
foot, to swoop down and intercept the ball inches shy of a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Tony take him wide, so I just closed in behind him,''
Knowles said. ``I felt good today, but what a day to get thrown in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Meola, ``If we had given up a goal there, we could have
been in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Meola kept the MetroStars competitive. The 28 shots he
faced tied his personal high in M.L.S., matching a barrage he faced
against D.C. United earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a brilliant game,'' Mondelo said. ``He made four or
five really key saves.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather did not bother Meola all that much _ he remembers
playing three World Cup games in oppressive heat _ and he did not
think the Fusion got off very many challenging shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of 25- to 30-foot dribblers,'' he said.
``Really, the credit should go more to the character our guys
showed. We just kept fighting. And the fight paid off in the end.
We got ourselves a victory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
