<HEADLINE>
JERSEY GIRL WINS FIRST TRIPLE TIARA RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the day after the 3-year-old colts ended their
pursuit of the Triple Crown, 10 3-year-old fillies began the road
to the Triple Tiara on Sunday at Belmont Park, and Jersey Girl took
the first leg of the series by winning the Acorn Stakes by 2}
lengths for her fifth straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   Jersey Girl was second in the betting to Countess Diana, winner
of the Breeders' Cup Juvenile Fillies and the Eclipse Award as
2-year-old champion last year. But for the second time in a month,
Jersey Girl ran away from Countess Diana, who tired and faded to
fifth place.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's really grown up since last year, and that's the
difference,'' said Mike Smith, who rides Jersey Girl for Todd
Pletcher and the Ackerley Brothers Farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's bigger, stronger and faster this year, and she's got a
lot of her senses together. She's learning how to relax out there,
and that's the key.''
</P>
<P>
   Pletcher said he was looking to the Mother Goose Stakes in three
weeks for his filly's next start, and added: ``She likes to train.
She's a smart filly, and a pleasure to be around.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Mott, who trains Countess Diana, said she had no excuse,
and added: ``I thought she was up for a better race than that. I
thought she was as tight as she needed to be, but she backed up too
early.''
</P>
<P>
   Jersey Girl broke third before nudging up to second after a
quarter of a mile and then gaining the lead after a half mile.
Countess Diana took the early lead but tired after a half mile, and
lapsed back to fifth place as the field entered the homestretch.
</P>
<P>
   Jersey Girl ran the mile in 1:36 1/5, with Santaria second and
Brave Deed third.
</P>
<P>
   The winner paid $8.30 for a $2 bet to win as second choice to
the even-money Countess Diana, and went home with $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   The series continues June 27 with the Mother Goose at a mile and
an eighth and closes July 25 with the Coaching Club American Oaks
at a mile and a half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
