<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INJURIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURIES STILL PILING UP FOR YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the Yankees continue to win, their injury list
continues to grow. Jorge Posada, who has gradually become the
team's front-line catcher this season, sprained his right foot
during batting practice before Saturday's game. At the very least,
the Yankees will call up a catcher from Class AAA before starting
their next series in Montreal Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the possibility that Posada, 26, will be placed on
the 15-day disabled list. Posada, on crutches after Sunday's game,
had X-rays that revealed no fractures. On Monday he will undergo
further examinations, including, in all likelihood, a magnetic
resonance imaging scan to test for soft tissue damage.
</P>
<P>
   Posada is usually upbeat and gregarious, but his demeanor had
changed markedly by the time he returned from the X-rays. ``I have
nothing to say,'' he said. ``I don't want to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Posada has started 32 of the Yankees' 57 games, and has 125
at-bats, 34 more than Joe Girardi, the Yankees' No. 1 catcher the
last two seasons. Posada has 7 homers and 23 runs batted in and is
hitting .248.
</P>
<P>
   As he took batting practice Sunday, he fouled a ball off the
instep of his right foot and apparently rolled his ankle in
reacting to the jolt. Girardi started in the Yankees' 4-1 victory
over Florida; Posada, sitting on the bench, felt no pain until the
middle innings, when his ankle began to hurt and he started to
limp.
</P>
<P>
   After he warmed up David Cone before the sixth inning, Posada's
foot began to hurt badly, and he retreated to the trainer's room
for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, said he should know
the extent of Posada's injury today. But because Posada probably
will not be available to catch tomorrow night's game, at least,
Cashman expects to call up Mike Figga, the catcher for Class AAA
Columbus. ``We won't play with only one available catcher,''
Cashman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have been extremely conservative in their treatment
of injuries, a luxury their fast start has afforded them. Scott
Brosius sustained a couple of bruises and, against his wishes, was
given two days off. Derek Jeter strained an abdominal muscle and
was immediately placed on the disabled list. The Yankees want their
best players fully healthy for the end of the season, and if
Posada's injury is at all debilitating, the team is likely to sit
him down for as long as necessary for him to heal fully.
</P>
<P>
   David Wells was scheduled to start Sunday's game, but when he
had trouble throwing in the bullpen Friday, team officials decided
to replace him with David Cone. Tendinitis was diagnosed in the
back of Wells's left (pitching) shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   But Wells and the Yankees expect he will be back in the rotation
either Friday or Saturday, when the Yankees will be playing the
Cleveland Indians at Yankee Stadium. Wells intends to throw
tomorrow, and if he cannot throw without discomfort, he will
probably be skipped in the rotation again and possibly placed on
the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Wells is taking anti-inflammatory medication. ``At this point in
the season,'' he said, ``why risk making something that is very
minor and possibly turning it into something serious? It's best to
just miss a start and see how it feels.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams hit a three-run homer Saturday and a solo home
run Sunday, and after not hitting a home run in his first 119
at-bats this season, he has 9 in his last 26 games, along with 30
rbi's. ``When he gets hot like that, it doesn't matter if he's
hitting lefty or righty,'' Tino Martinez said. ``He's in one of
those grooves, and you hope he just keeps it going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
