<HEADER>
A8850 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      06-08 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN `TRUMAN' AND `BULLWORTH,' BIG MEDIA AS BIG BROTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is going to be difficult to escape ``The Truman Show.'' For
weeks, the film, starring Jim Carrey, has been featured on magazine
covers and brooded about in beard-pulling advance features. Now it
has finally opened, and escape is even less likely.
</P>
<P>
   But after seeing the movie, escape is what I yearn for. Like
Carrey's character, Truman, who has been, since birth, an unknowing
subject of a 24-hour-a-day television show, I seek fresh air, open
skies, new possibilities. Truman begins to suspect his seaside
village is not all it's made out to be; I am beginning to suspect
something similar about my cultural surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the problem: I am being told, again and again, that we
are a lot like Truman. He is living in a world constructed by the
media. He is dominated by their desires, sacrificed to their whims,
and he doesn't even know it. It has become almost axiomatic that we
are in the same boat. The boundaries between television and reality
have broken down. We sit for months watching the O.J. trial as soap
opera. Networks interrupt their programming to broadcast a live
California suicide. Jerry Springer stages talk-show fights. So,
isn't ``Truman'' true?
</P>
<P>
   This is what we are meant to think. And that is what I want to
escape: the numbing insistence that we are the victims of higher
media forces that have constructed a prefab stage set, who pull our
strings and force-feed us useless products. And we, unknowing, turn
from our empty lives to submit to the moguls' intoxicating
fantasies. We are insistently told that we are duped, manipulated,
controlled.
</P>
<P>
   But I am beginning to suspect that this insistence is the real
duping and manipulation; we are duped into believing we are being
duped. Don't believe me? Try escaping that message. It is also
being drilled in by another recent film, Warren Beatty's political
satire ``Bulworth.''
</P>
<P>
   There, too, television is so powerful it is sometimes difficult
to tell whether life is an image of the screen or the screen an
image of life. The television interviewer Larry King (who has
actually predicted that ``The Truman Show'' will ``revolutionize
the art form'') books the fictional Senator-candidate Bulworth, on
his talk show. And in that film, too, television can seem to
undermine perception of the real. In the midst of a mental
breakdown, the senator sits with a television remote in his hand,
channel surfing his way into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Bulworth, like Truman, tries to free himself from the media's
manipulating power. He opposes a television interviewer's attempt
to break away to a commercial. He challenges the independence of
the questioners on a televised debate, pointing out that they are
rich people working for other rich people who are running rich
media companies that have subsidized his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his villains are the same moguls and producers who put
on the televised ``Truman Show'' in Carrey's movie, enslaving
Truman to a life of staged broadcasts. In Beatty's fantasy, the
conspiracy is even more nefarious, because it extends so deeply
into the pockets of corporate America and keeps so many different
Trumans in penury.
</P>
<P>
   Who can argue with these films' vision, when our attention keeps
being drawn to similar notions even outside films? We blame
television for violence, advertising for smoking and the media for
political mediocrity. These ideas now form the familiar contours of
our culture's seaside village; they provide the foundations for our
prefab dystopia. And they offer a seamless web of ready-made
interpretation about our masters and oppressors, spiced, in these
films, with just enough humor and farce to make the message
palatable.
</P>
<P>
   But we, like Truman, can begin to notice certain oddities about
this message that is supposedly reiterated for our benefit and
insight. There are postures that seem out of place. It may be worth
questioning the authority of the voices making proclamations, and
perhaps even their noble intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Whose interests, after all, are being served by seeing the world
in this way? Beatty's film believes the Trumanesque victims are
inner-city blacks. And Bulworth rescues them by becoming what
Norman Mailer once called a ``White Negro.'' He takes off his suit
and tie and smashes the oppressive bourgeois mold. He dresses in
baggy shorts for a television interview, swigs liquor during a
television debate, raps insults to corporate donors and adopts a
vintage 1968 radical political line, promising to lead the poor,
particularly the black poor, to economic freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Truman doesn't carry the torch for anyone else, but his way of
undermining his handlers is similar: break the mold, act in
unexpected fashion, rebel against the constraints of family, job
and community (all of which, after all, are phony).
</P>
<P>
   The level of disdain and condescension in these visions is
astonishing. Beatty can envision Bulworth having an impact only
when he jettisons all manners, adopts crude political doctrines and
becomes a White Negro cartoon. He insults those he claims to
champion.
</P>
<P>
   And isn't that true of the makers of ``Truman'' as well? If we
are meant to root for Truman against the delusions peddled by the
media masters, why does the film portray ordinary citizens as so
horrific? The stage set created for Truman (which he believes to be
real) appears to be an ordinary suburban development. But Peter
Weir's direction treats the village with winking mockery. When
Truman weeds his garden, he wears bright red polyester shorts. His
wife, while plugging a brand of hot cocoa or an all-in-one kitchen
utensil, is an exaggerated 1950s housewife in a checked dress.
Truman's job as an insurance salesman fits the same vintage
cartoon. This is a town of Stepford Wives, Children of the Damned,
Body Snatchers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the town is meant to be cartoonish; the film, after
all, presents it as a set made by the mad media masters directing
Truman's life. But the filmmakers also want their condemnations to
resonate in the ``real world.'' The film even shows us the viewers
of the Truman drama, people who are our counterparts, who watch
television day and night. And they are even more grotesque than the
bourgeois villagers.
</P>
<P>
   Two old ladies pathetically hug a pillow decorated with Truman's
picture. Two half-witted parking attendants can't keep their eyes
off the television. A corpulent man soaks in a bathtub hypnotized
by Truman's escapades. The film's unremitting scorn leaves no one
but Truman untouched.
</P>
<P>
   So here is what this vision of moguls and manipulation gives us:
a world of flaccid, dull-witted oppressed and untrustworthy
citizens who can't see what is in front of their eyes except to
watch a screen. They are supposedly saved by visionaries whose
rebellion undermines the phony stage set of bourgeois life. But
this rebellion, it turns out, is itself full of scorn. Truman may
not show it, but his inventors, the filmmakers, do. And so does
Beatty in his condescension.
</P>
<P>
   There is hardly any room in these films for ordinary people with
their problems and struggles; either you are a grotesque victim of
the moguls or an unmitigated rebel, a Child of the Damned or a
White Negro. Nothing seems real.
</P>
<P>
   That is the vision I seek to escape. But the filmmakers and
their allies have things locked up tight. They insist that they
alone have a true vision. Only they dare to show the reality behind
the pap. In these films, behind cameras we never see, are the real
heroes who should be hailed for their provocative and courageous
films showing us as the dupes we are.
</P>
<P>
   But isn't it peculiar that this courage and provocation are
really founded on cultural cliches and papier-mache politics?
Meanwhile, the results are so familiar and comfortable, we don't
even try to escape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
