<HEADLINE>
NEWS AND NOTES ON ADVERTISING 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wolf Group to Acquire Partners &AMP; Shevack
</P>
<P>
   Wolf Group Integrated Communications Ltd. in Toronto has
acquired Partners &AMP; Shevack in New York in the second deal in two
days in which a foreign agency company bought a midsized American
shop.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition, which more than doubles the billings handled by
Wolf agencies, was announced on Friday, a day after Publicis S.A.
in Paris bought Evans Group in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   As the world's largest single advertising market, the United
States offers attractive expansion opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Partners &AMP; Shevack is the second big American deal for Wolf,
which acquired Meldrum &AMP; Fewsmith Communications in Cleveland in
April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf, which is privately held, is paying Mickelberry
Communications Inc., parent of Partners &AMP; Shevack, an undisclosed
price in cash and stock for the agency, which has 120 employees and
billings of more than $250 million from clients like Aamco
Transmissions Inc., the Haagen-Dazs desserts brand sold by Diageo
PLC, Renaissance Cosmetics Inc. and the Scotts Company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to find an engine that could fuel our growth,'' said
Brett Shevack, chief executive at Partners &AMP; Shevack. ``Now we're
part of a group of agencies that will grow dynamically.''
</P>
<P>
   Partners &AMP; Shevack, opened in 1988, will be an autonomous unit
of Wolf, which also operates an agency under the Wolf name handling
accounts with billings of more than $200 million at offices in
Buffalo; Charlotte, N.C.; Cleveland; Columbus, Ohio; Rochester and
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The Partners &AMP; Shevack name will remain, said Larry Wolf,
chairman and chief executive at Wolf, as will present management
there, which includes Shevack; Lynne Seid, president, and Steve
Frankfurt, vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Key Personnel Moves Made at Two Agencies
</P>
<P>
   Two agencies have made top personnel moves.
</P>
<P>
   The GCI Group of Grey Advertising Inc. in New York is expanding
into management consulting services with the hiring of Keith Burton
as executive vice president and managing director of a new unit,
GCI Consulting, to be based in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, 43, had been executive vice president at the Hill &AMP;
Knowlton unit of WPP Group PLC in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   And Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. in New York has named Etienne Boisrond,
chairman and chief executive of Y.&AMP; R. France in Paris, to the new
position of chairman for the Asia/Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
   Boisrond, 45, who will be based in Singapore and Tokyo, assumes
his new duties from Tim Pollak, 52, who is leaving Y&AMP;R after 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   Pollak, a vice chairman at Y&AMP;R, is departing to seek
opportunities with client companies. Among the posts he has held at
Y.&AMP; R. were president of Y&AMP;R New York and chief executive of HDM, a
joint venture with Havas Advertising and Dentsu Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
