 NEWS &AMP; FEATURES SUMMARY No 2453 - JUNE 8, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. HONG KONG'S YEAR ONE UNDER BEIJING'S THUMB For the former
British colony of Hong Kong, Year One since the handback to Chinese
control, which ends June 30, has been what Queen Elizabeth II might
call an 'annus horribilis.' The stock market plunged, unemployment
is at record levels, and a bird flu that led to the slaughter of
millions of chickens was followed by an algae invasion that killed
tons of fish. For the most part, mainland authorities have observed
their 'hands-off pledge,' but in subtle and insidious ways, the
Beijing overseers are changing the face of what was one of the
world's most dynamic capitalist economies. From Der Spiegel. 2,000
words. (English translation available.)
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
JODY WILLIAMS AND THE EMBATTLED LANDMINE CAMPAIGN Last year,
Vermont's Jody Williams received the Nobel Peace Prize for her
efforts to ban land mines. And that's when the politics inside the
land-mine campaign were revealed. Here's an update. By James
Bandler. From The Boston Globe Magazine. 2,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
RAZOR'S EDGE Until about 10 years ago, teenage girls seldom fought
each other - even with fists. They did not carry knives and razors
and box cutters. They did not form roaming packs and attack other
girls. They did not fight with sticks, bats, bricks. Today they do.
What is the nature of this dismal trend and what is being done to
stop it? By Royal Ford. From The Boston Globe Magazine. 2,000
words.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
FROM LAWN CUTTER TO MULTIMILLIONAIRE :
</P>
<P>
   THE BLUE-COLLAR MIRACLE If ever there was a metaphor for the
boom in the American economy it is Laro Service Systems. Its
founders are part of a new class of service-industry entrepreneurs,
the blue-collar rich. In 1982, there were 29,000 self-employed
Americans making more than $100,000 in industries such as cleaning,
landscaping, food preparation, warehousing; today there are 80,000.
Competition is fierce; it is capitalism at its rawest. By Michael
Winerip. From The New York Times Magazine. 2,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
WHAT'S DOING IN AMSTERDAM Events, sightseeing, hotels and
restaurants in Amsterdam. By Eric Weinberger. From The New York
Times Way To Go! 1,500 words + photos + B&AMP;W map.
______________________________________________________________ 6.
FREE AT LAST In NASA's high-flying ``vomit comet,'' students can
escape the grip of gravity and learn a few things about outer
space, astronauts and future life for humans in a state of
'zero-G.' Here's an account of what happened earlier this year,
when 19 students and two journalists boarded the same capsule Tom
Hanks was in for the harrowing scenes from the film ``Apollo 13.''
By David L. Chandler. From The Boston Globe Magazine. 2,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
TREATMENT FOUND TO RESTORE IMMUNE FUNCTION IN HIV PATIENTS New drug
combinations have revolutionized the treatment of HIV infection and
AIDS. Many patients on these new regimens have seen the amount of
virus in their bloodstream plummet and their white cell counts
rebound. But there is concern that the immune systems of these
patients may never fully recover from the damage caused by HIV
infection and that they remain vulnerable to life-threatening
infections. Researchers working in Paris now report that the immune
systems of at least some patients on new drug therapies can recover
important aspects of their immune defences even if their immune
systems had been severely damaged by the virus before starting the
new treatments. By Michael McCarthy. The Lancet News Service. 1,000
words.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
MIRACLE WEED The hemp plant is packed with essential fatty acids
and amino acids, making it an ideal ingredient for beauty products.
Using cannabis-based cosmetics may bring to mind substance abuse,
but in fact industrial hemp is altogether different from the
smokable kind. It's virtually drug-free. By Alev Aktar. Faichild
Publications. 1,500 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
TREATING ASTHMA - NATURALLY Drugs and medications are useful tools
in controlling asthma, the lung disease which afflicts millions of
people. But conventional treatments have their own drawbacks, which
is why many doctors recommend supplementing them with natural
treatments. Kathy Sena looks at various nutritional supplements,
exercise programs and breathing techniques that can help control
asthma symptoms. From Let's Live. 1,400 words. 10. LEARNING TO READ
FOOD LABELS Dietician Mindy Hermann offers practical advice on
interpreting food labels and finding the food you want for yourself
and your family. From Family Circle. 1,400 words.
</P>
