<P>
   LAREDO-PROBE (Laredo, Texas) _ Federal agents who raided the
Webb County district attorney's office appear to be searching for a
link between the way certain criminal cases were handled and the
personal finances of key people in that office. By DANE SCHILLER
and CARMINA DANINI.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-PRISONERS (Marion, Ill.) _ The closest thing the
United States has to political prisoners are members of the Puerto
Rican liberation movement, FALN. Even though they have been
convicted of no violent crimes, members of the organization have
been jailed for more than 20 years, longer than some rapists,
murderers and kidnappers. By TONY FREEMANTLE (Photos available on
the New York Times photo service)
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-TURKEY (Albany, N.Y.) _ Residents of one neighborhood may
soon have to invest in a sign that reads: Beware of Turkey. A
troublesome tom turkey has attacked postal trucks, pecking at their
tires and preventing carriers from delivering mail to nine homes in
recent months. By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HABITAT-HOUSTON (Houston) _ With a mix of worship, work and
wood, a former president and 6,000 volunteers hope to raise 100
homes in the Houston area in one week. It will be the largest
project ever attempted by Habitat for Humanity in the United
States. The project begins Monday, June 15. By ERIC BERGER
</P>
<P>
   HABITAT-PRISONERS (Houston) _ Twenty-five inmates, some of them
rapists and murderers, will build one of the 100 Habitat homes. The
prisoners received a second chance of sorts through a new
faith-based program pioneered in Brazil and Ecuador. By ERIC
BERGER. (Photo available on NYT photo service Monday afternoon.)
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-DISHES (Albany, N.Y.) _ It's the summer season and to
many that means eating al fresco around the swimming pool, on the
patio or deck. This is the perfect time to have fun with colorful
dishes and whimsical patterns. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   PINK-FLAMINGOS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Lawn ornaments aren't really
new. They date back to the ancient Romans, who would set up altars
to pagan gods. But come summer in America, it's time to get out the
pink flamingos, statues of large, tropical wading birds that,
historically, began appearing on lawns and in gardens as early as
the 1800s. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-CENTER (Houston) _ For years, Houston has been about the
only major U.S. city without a community center where gays and
lesbians can gather to discuss issues or hold a potluck dinner in a
safe and homey environment. But that's recently changed with the
opening of two new facilities. By CLIFFORD PUGH
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A grandmother would like to know what
kind of cutting garden she should plant for her 4-year-old
granddaughter. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
