<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8903 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRAWFISH09-COX     06-08 1388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAWFISH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    T a s t i n g t h e s o u t h: Born on the bayou
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BREAUX BRIDGE, La. _ Kenneth ``Half Pint'' Thibodeaux _ that's
how he's listed in the phone book _ sounded like a Cajun musician
playing washboard as he scraped a spoon across the bottom of a pot
burbling with rich brown gravy. He was making a kind of music, all
right; he was fixing crawfish etouffee in the hope of beating 17
competitors in a cook-off. But unlike his rivals, he didn't seem
particularly curious about what the Guidrys and the Heberts and the
others were up to at their stoves. ``I eat at their houses all the
time,'' he said, ``so I know what their etouffee tastes like.''
</P>
<P>
   And they know what his etouffee tastes like?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. ``What I'm making today is all crawdaddies,''
Thibodeaux said, pausing for a swig of beer. He pulled closer and
lowered his voice. ``When I cook for company, I put some cream of
mushroom soup in there to stretch it. Crawfish is expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when crawfish (or crayfish, as biologists and
Yankees call them) were as cheap as mud and about as respectable.
When outsiders first came to work in the Louisiana oil fields
decades ago, they cringed to think anyone would eat the grubby
critters they saw skittering through the drainage ditches. The
locals actually were eating a cleaner breed of crawfish from
freshwater bayous, but that didn't keep them from acting sheepish
about it. ``People ate them at home, but when they went out they
hid it,'' says Dickie Breaux, a restaurateur in Breaux Bridge, who
remembers how the old Cajun dining establishments had private rooms
with closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   No one is ashamed of crawfish nowadays. Not only do people peel
and suck them right out in the open, they celebrate them at events
like the crawfish festival they've held every May since 1960 in
Breaux Bridge, a town of 6,000 near Lafayette. The little
crustacean has become a big red banner of Cajun pride, a cultural
trademark as distinctive as a spicy French drawl or a jumping
accordion on Saturday night. Mr. Mudbug has gone to town.
</P>
<P>
   Cajuns love crawfish for their taste, of course; the chef Paul
Prudhomme likens the tender curl of tail meat to lobster dipped in
butter _ only you don't need the butter. But Cajuns love crawfish
for another reason as well: It reminds them of themselves. It's a
culinary underdog from the backwoods that had to scrap and claw its
way to acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say a crawfish is the bravest thing in the world. It'll
take its pincers to a train,'' says Elaine Hardy, a supervisor in a
crawfish processing plant near Breaux Bridge, her voice filled with
an admiration that's common in southern Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Crawfish have been part of life for all her 59 years. ``I grew
up down in Butte la Rose when there was no roads, no electricity,
no nothing,'' she says. ``Whenever we wanted to have a party, we'd
just go out in the swamp with some bait and dip our basket in a
hole and get all the crawfish we wanted. We'd boil them bright red
and lay out some newspapers and, oh, it was delicious. I don't
think crawfish taste that good anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hardy was a girl, Louisiana had no crawfish industry to
speak of. Today there are 98 plants processing crawfish from 3,600
farmers and fishermen. The fishermen bring in the bulk of the
catch, knifing into the bayous before dawn in pointed canoes called
pirogues. The rest comes from farmers who grow crawfish in ponds
created from flooded, off-season rice paddies.
</P>
<P>
   At midafternoon, the harvest starts arriving at plants like
Bayou Land Seafood, a gamey-smelling complex on a murky bayou
outside Breaux Bridge. The crawfish men pull into the loading bay,
their thigh boots still wet, and deliver bags full of live
crustaceans that beckon through the mesh with their tiny claws.
Most of them are flash-boiled and peeled for tail meat. Eighty
percent of it never leaves Louisiana. ``The main market for
crawfish is as far as a coonass can drive in a day,'' says Tom
Hymel, the local extension agent, using a slang term for Cajuns
that a non-Cajun would use only if he had good health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Like wine, the quality of crawfish varies from year to year.
Last season's mudbugs were sweet and large due to favorable weather
conditions. Not so this season's. As he examines the specimens
coming into Bayou Land, owner Roy Robin cannot hide his
disapppointment. ``Look at those peanuts,'' he says, poking at a
bag.
</P>
<P>
   Size and taste aren't the only worries in crawfish country. In
the early '90s, China started flooding the American market with
tail meat at less than half the domestic price. Soon the imports
were outselling Louisiana crawfish. Last year, under pressure from
the industry, the federal government enacted tariffs on Chinese
crawfish that have brought prices closer to parity and given the
domestic producers the break they say they needed to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those producers are concentrated around Breaux Bridge,
where the biggest landmark is a drawbridge over Bayou Teche with
the image of a crawfish across the superstructure. It was there,
along a street marked ``Rue Pont,'' that crawfish fans started
gathering on an overcast Saturday morning last month for the parade
that kicked off their shellfish Mardi Gras. One of the topics of
conversation, as always, was the delicate matter of sucking.
</P>
<P>
   There are two types of people when it comes to eating crawfish:
those who suck and those who decline to suck. Make of it what you
will, but those who decline to suck the peppery juices and buttery
fats from the head section of a boiled crawfish tend to be women.
The gung-ho suckers _ the party-hearties who wear T-shirts that
plead, ``Pinch me, peel me, suck me'' _ are usually men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never met a woman who sucks the head,'' declared Cherie
Bourque, the recently crowned Miss Etouffee, as she sat in a
convertible waiting for the parade to begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just nasty,'' chimed in Mrs. Etouffee, Dawn Taylor, as
she straightened her tiara.
</P>
<P>
   The etouffee twosome were part of a royal turnout that included
a cracklin' queen, a boudin queen, a tamale queen and a crawfish
queen, king and pre-k queen identified by her sash as ``Li'l Miss
Pincer.'' They were joined in the procession by, among others, a
group of bon vivants who called themselves the Krewe d'Ecrevisse
(that's French for crawfish). Their float featured a 20-foot mudbug
with claws that might give Godzilla pause. ``We're confident that
we have built the world's biggest crawfish,'' said Steve Hebert,
resplendent in his sunglasses, Tabasco shirt and tie crawling with
plastic crawfish.
</P>
<P>
   After the parade, the festival got down to the serious business
of mass consumption. While hundreds stood in line for plates of
boiled crawfish, eight men with more ambitious appetites took their
places at a table in front of TV crews and a raucous crowd of
spectators. It was time for the ultimate test, the crawfish-eating
contest. There were eight entries from Louisiana (introduced to
cheers) and one from New York (booooooo!). ``You don't have to suck
the heads,'' the emcee told them mercifully, ``but you do have to
eat all the tail meat. We will be checking the shells.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd counted down the seconds, and they were off like a
pack of thoroughbred pigs. For 45 minutes, they peeled and
swallowed and guzzled beer and sweated and turned as red in the
face as their prey. Whenever a contestant looked like he was about
to keel over, someone in the audience would prod him on by shouting
something like, ``Go, big daddy, go!'' Halfway through, New York
threw in the towel. A few minutes later, another man stumbled off
the stage looking stunned and as bloated as a summer sausage.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the biggest daddy of all turned out to be a jowly
paper mill worker named Dane Howell. He laid waste to 19 pounds of
crawfish _ far short of the record set by a bar owner everyone knew
as ``Big Nick'' _ but an awesome performance nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Howell had a novel explanation for his triumph. ``My wife left
me in December and I went from 260 to 180 pounds, so I've got
plenty of room for crawfish.''
</P>
<P>
   They always do in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
