<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 11:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8909 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTISTS-C0NVERT09-CO     06-08 1795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-C0NVERT09-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Southern Baptists push beliefs in Mormon territory
</P>
<P>
   By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Baptist blitz is on in the home of the Church of
Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptists from across the nation, meeting for their
national convention in Salt Lake City, are taking part in an effort
to persuade Mormons to change their beliefs, to reach the
unchurched with the gospel of Jesus and maybe to win back some
Southern Baptists who converted to Mormonism.
</P>
<P>
   The convention will run in the city that was founded almost 151
years ago by Mormon President Brigham Young, who led a group of
pioneers into the valley to escape religious persecution.
</P>
<P>
   The fundamentalist-controlled Southern Baptist Convention
usually makes headlines from controversial resolutions adopted on
the convention floor, such as last year's boycott of the Walt
Disney Co. Though people have come to expect the unexpected from
the more than 5,000 messengers, or delegates, who attend the annual
meetings, what is known about this year's convention business seems
mild in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Paige Patterson, a former Dallas resident and one of two Texans
who orchestrated the fundamentalist takeover of the convention from
moderates, is the shoo-in for president.
</P>
<P>
   Messengers a re also expected to adopt an addition to the
Baptist Faith and Message, a statement of core beliefs, o hat says,
in part, ``a wife is to submit graciously to the servant leadership
of her husband.'' The addition, the first to be added to the faith
and message statement in 35 years, is expected to pass with an
overwhelming majority.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy this year, much to the chagrin of the Mormon
Church, is Southern Baptists labeling the Mormon faith a cult and
non-Christian and undertaking their most extensive pre-convention
evangelism effort. The program includes 18 neighborhood block
parties, door-to-door canvassing and sports camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do our best,'' said Phil Roberts, who is
spearheading the Southern Baptist evangelism effort that began
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Evangelism in the cities where annual conventions are held is
nothing new, but the tension created between the 10 million-member
Mormon Church and the 15.9 million-member Southern Baptist
Convention rivals that of the NBA championship matchup between the
Utah Jazz and the Chicago Bulls being played out in the nearby
Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the last time the church's beliefs were thrown
negatively into the national spotlight came during last year's
championship game _ played by the same two teams during the same
period. The National Basketball Association fined Chicago Bulls
star Dennis Rodman $50,000 for disparaging remarks he made about
Mormons. In a statement designed to apologize for the profanities
Rodman leveled toward Mormons, Bulls coach Phil Jackson defended
his player, saying:
</P>
<P>
   ``To Dennis, a Mormon may just be a nickname for people from
Utah. He may not even know it's a religious cult or sect or
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just the kind of image the Mormon Church has worked hard
to shed. President Gordon B. Hinckley, who became the church's
prophet three years ago, is one of the key figures in the past 15
years who has worked tirelessly to gain public acceptance of
Mormons as mainstream Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptists' belief
</P>
<P>
   Though the Mormon Church has gained respect in mainline
Christian circles, the Southern Baptists are bringing national
attention to the belief among many conservative Christians that
Mormons are not Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a common misunderstanding that the Mormons are a
Christian denomination and vary in minor points,'' said Maurice
Smith of New Braunfels, who retired four years ago as the Southern
Baptist Convention's associate director for world religions.
</P>
<P>
   Mormons believe they have the one true church that was restored
by founder and prophet Joseph F. Smith, who was given the Book of
Mormon from the angel Moroni in the early 19th century. The Bible,
Book of Mormon, Doctrine and Covenants (revelations given to Smith
and subsequent presidents of the church) and the Pearl of Great
Price (selected revelations, translations and narrations by Smith)
are the Scriptures and laws of the church.
</P>
<P>
   Proclaiming themselves the only one, true church makes the
Mormon Church a cult, said Roberts, director of the interfaith
witness team for the Southern Baptist North American Mission Board.
</P>
<P>
   They cannot be Christians because ``they have changed radically
and revised major Christians beliefs,'' Roberts added.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he said, Mormons believe Jesus was the offspring
of heavenly parents and that God, Jesus and the Holy Ghost are
three separate physical beings.
</P>
<P>
   Mormons freely acknowledge that their faith differs from other
Christian religions, but they argue that it is unfair to brand them
non-Christian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it is unfortunate that many believe we are not
Christians,'' said Ron Nielson, an Austin Mormon. ``Whenever I have
a discussion with anyone and/or know they believe in Christ, how
dare I say back to them, 'You are not Christian'?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never say or think otherwise, even though we may have
a different view or understanding of the nature of God. We should
at least accept and acknowledge each other's belief and faith in
Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinckley has instructed ``the saints,'' as Mormons call
themselves, to treat Southern Baptists, ``our brethren and
sisters,'' with politeness and respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``They accuse us of not being Christian,'' he said. ``I hope our
people will try to show them, by the very manner in which they act,
that we are truly disciples of the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, during the church's annual General Conference,
Hinckley said Mormons should remain confident in their beliefs and
not become ``disagreeable as we talk of doctrinal differences.
There is no place for acrimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all Southern Baptists favor the evangelism effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such an arrogant thing to do,'' said the Rev. Becca
Gurney of Georgetown, who is a moderate Southern Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see that as a loving thing to do,'' added Gurney,
president of the national Baptist Women in Ministry and former
associate pastor at University Baptist Church in Austin. ``It does
nothing to generate good feelings for people of different faiths.''
</P>
<P>
   In November former President Jimmy Carter, a Southern Baptist,
told a Salt Lake City newspaper owned by the Mormon Church that he
is against the evangelism effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the worst thing that we can do, among the worst things
we can do, as believers in Christ, is to spend our time condemning
others who profess faith in Christ and (to) try to have a very
narrow definition of who is and who is not an acceptable believer
and a child of God,'' Carter said in the Deseret News. Roberts said
Carter was off the mark. ``Our leadership takes exception to
that,'' he said. ``When a group violates historical Christianity,
we believe we have a mandate to share the gospel with them.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Roberts acknowledged, some Mormons are former Southern
Baptists. ``They do get a number of converts from the Baptist
ranks.'' The Mormon Church does not keep statistics on the previous
faiths of its members.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 2.6 million Baptists in Texas and almost 200,000
Mormons. No one from Austin preregistered to take part in the
evangelism effort in Salt Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised by that,'' said the Rev. Harold O'Chester,
pastor of Great Hills Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``In years past, we would have been the one to send folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salt Lake city is an out-of-the-way place. It costs a lot of
money to go.'' 'A calm convention'
</P>
<P>
   O'Chester is attending the convention with his wife, Barbara. He
predicts ``a calm, calm convention.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Chester said he supports Patterson for president but worries
that his longtime friend may be stretching himself too thin.
Southern Baptist presidents retain their professions, and Patterson
is president of Southeastern Baptist Theological Seminary in Wake
Forest, N.C., where O'Chester's son-in-law is attending school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my son-in-law Paige really doesn't need to be president
of the convention,'' O'Chester said. ``He's up to ears. . . . This
is the fastest-growing seminary in the United States now.''
</P>
<P>
   The addition to the Southern Baptist statement of faith is
unlikely to draw fire from fundamentalists, but it doesn't sit well
with moderates likesuch Gurney, who is not attending the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we honor God when we seek to love and educate people
rather than dictate an unrealistic family model for all to
follow,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ralph Smith, pastor emeritus of Hyde Park Baptist
Church in Austin, said the new addition does not make women unequal
to men in the marriage partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we know anything about has to have somebody who is
a leader,'' he said. ``The country has a president, the company has
a CEO, the newspaper has an editor, and a church has a pastor.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a conservative who also is highly regarded by many
moderates, is expected to be unanimously elected by messengers to
deliver the official convention sermon next year when Southern
Baptists meet in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Kelly Boggs, pastor at First Baptist Church of Leander,
said the addition to the faith statement doesn't put women in a
subservient role but places the responsibility for the family on
the husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I define 'submit' there is to respect and respond to
the husband's leadership,'' he said. ``At the same time, it's not
being a doormat or anything of that nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Mormons also believe that the husband is the family's leader.
And, like the Southern Baptist Convention, they oppose gambling,
abortion, pornography, homosexuality and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Both denominations win converts through strong missionary
efforts at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``They now send missionaries into the world, including Austin,
telling all of us, 'You're going to hell,' '' O'Chester said.
</P>
<P>
   Evangelizing Mormons in Salt Lake City, he said, ``is just
getting a taste of what they have been doing to us for years and
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said part of the evangelism effort, which this year
included special educational materials explaining Mormon beliefs
and how to evangelize to them, is designed to instruct Southern
Baptists on how to ness to Mormon missionaries thatwho ma ock on
their door.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Mormons is we don't have to come to them;
they'll come to us,'' he said. ``We're saying don't sicksic th g on
them, don't turn the sprinklers on them, but invite them in and
share the gospel.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
