<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMENTARY: My life in the gobbledygook trade
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Lane
</P>
<P>
   c. Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   I used to be one of those anonymous people who mail
important-sounding letters nobody understands. The kind of people
Vice President Al Gore talked about recently when he called for
plain language in government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government's writing must be in plain language,''
he wrote plainly. ``By using clear language we send a clearer
message about what the government is doing, what it requires and
what services it offers.''
</P>
<P>
   My work dispensing gobbledygook was not, however, on behalf of
the U.S. government. I performed this vital service for the private
sector. After an unexplained gap in my resume, I had bought myself
a $25 polyester jacket and an unstained Goodwill tie and went to
work for an insurance conglomerate in a big building.
</P>
<P>
   My resume says I was a paralegal. Actually, I was barely a
semiparalegal. Maybe even a quasiparalegal or pseudoparalegal. I'm
sure there are guidelines that could tell me which.
</P>
<P>
   My job was to keep loan deals alive and moving. The system was
easy. You'd look at a checklist, and if anything was missing, you'd
write a letter asking for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Write'' is the wrong word. ``Select'' would be more accurate.
</P>
<P>
   I'd go to a big loose-leaf binder and find the right
form-letter, photocopy it, fill in the company-name-here line, and
give it to a secretary. The secretary would type it up on nice
stationery, then I'd sign it and mail it.
</P>
<P>
   One week later, like clockwork, I'd get a worried call from a
business, bank or lawyer asking what the letter was about and I'd
tell them. They were always relieved when I told them and happy to
talk to me. That's because some of these were scary-sounding
letters.
</P>
<P>
   And all of them were baffling. Every one a real puzzler. They
might as well have been written in Sumerian, Morse code or COBOL.
</P>
<P>
   The only way I could pick out one letter from another was by
reading a short title on top. ``Letter asking for site plan.''
``Letter requesting construction status-report.'' Things like that.
Very handy.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knew the model letters were unintelligible but
deviating from them was strictly forbidden. They had been approved
by lawyers, I was told. The words contained hidden meanings we
could not hope to understand. Only the lawyers knew. Change one
word and the whole spell might be broken. You can't be too careful.
</P>
<P>
   I was a poor semiparalegal but the experience was instructive.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it has left me immune to mailbox panic.
</P>
<P>
   There's a kind of writing that always sounds worse than it is.
The pronouncements of governments, insurance companies and bill
collectors often are vague, but when things go bad, these same
institutions always find a way to express themselves with great
forceful clarity. Gobbledygook tells you there is still time to fix
things. That's reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   My office experience also taught me to say ``I don't know what
this means.'' No small accomplishment. The average person's entire
classroom experience, by contrast, teaches one never to do this.
You'll look dumb.
</P>
<P>
   But saying you don't understand is OK. It's better than OK. It's
empowering. It confounds your opponents. It makes bureaucrats
squirm. It is a reporter's most useful interview tool.
</P>
<P>
   Because I never expected anyone to understand the letters I
mailed, I only half expect to understand anything under an official
letterhead. Somehow the practice did not end when I wandered off
the job.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, it has spread. With computerization, offices no
longer need big loose-leaf notebooks of form letters.
Unintelligible writing is only a mouse-click away. This is great
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to communications technology, we can efficiently produce
and instantaneously transmit letters nobody can understand. So I
fear the vice president's crusade already may be too late.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least insufficiently proactive to have a strong degree of
probable wide-level implementation within any near-term determinate
time-frame.
</P>
<P>
   It's good to know I haven't lost the old touch.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
