<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8932 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAYDAY-DISNEY09-COX     06-08 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYDAY-DISNEY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gay Day at Walt Disney World featured the predicted open
displays of affection: hand-holding, hugging, snuggling and
kissing. But on this day, as on other days, most of those displays
involved couples of opposite sex, and nearly everything turned out
as tame as an old-time Disney movie.
</P>
<P>
   Even tamer were the dissenters who had threatened such a ruckus
that county deputies were put on riot alert.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Rescue, known nationally for its confrontational
anti-abortion protest, made good on its vow to send members into
the park to preach to gays. But instead of a charging phalanx led
by the group's lightning-rod leader, it sent a Louisiana pastor
followed by a few teenagers reading Bible verses. Hardly anyone
except reporters and Disney security staff paid attention.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the park, thousands of gay men and lesbians stood out
from the crowd in their bright-red shirts but otherwise followed
familiar protocol: standing on the seemingly endless line for Space
Mountain, posing for pictures with Mickey Mouse and jostling for a
prime spot to watch the Main Street parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful,'' said Josue Santiago of New York. ``I'm
having the best time ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Kat Campani, one of Santiago's friends, said the ride from their
hotel was marred by an encounter with roadside demonstrators who
shouted that Jesus could make them heterosexual. A banner plane
that made several passes over the park carried a similar message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then some people in our car started to shout back that Jesus
made us gay, and that ruined everyone's day,'' said Campani, who
was much happier with the more relaxed atmosphere inside the park.
</P>
<P>
   It was, for the most part, a quiet crowd. Gay Day at Disney is
not so much party as it is prelude to more than 40 related events
held in the Orlando area throughout the weekend as a kickoff to Gay
Pride Month. Early in the day, red shirts appeared to account for a
quarter of the crowd but less later on.
</P>
<P>
   The privately organized day at Disney has been an annual feature
at the park since 1991, but the atmosphere leading up to this
year's gathering was more highly charged.
</P>
<P>
   Disney is under intense criticism and even boycotts nationally
by several political and religious groups that consider its
employment policies, movies and television shows too friendly to
gays, and Gay Day has become the focus of protests.
</P>
<P>
   Three Treasure Coast elementary schools canceled trips to Disney
and other theme parks after some parents said they wouldn't let
their children attend during the gay events. School officials said
the plans were changed to avoid scheduling conflicts, but parents
made it clear they were concerned about what children might see.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Christian groups were encouraging members last week
to call stores that sell Disney merchandise to remind them of the
boycott. Gay groups were asking members to counter that by
purchasing Disney merchandise with $2 bills so the source of the
money was clear.
</P>
<P>
   Tension was evident at demonstrations throughout the Orlando
area and during a city debate over plans to fly gay pride flags on
light poles. The flags won approval.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Rescue's national director, the Rev. Philip L.
``Flip'' Benham, led protests at Orlando book stores and abortion
clinics and against Disney. He was arrested on charges of violating
a court order outside one clinic.
</P>
<P>
   News that Benham planned to enter the park prompted Disney to
cancel agreements for television coverage inside the gates. ``We
were concerned that a big media horde following him around would
create a distraction that would keep guests from having a good
time,'' said Bill Warren, a Walt Disney World spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Benham's emissary, Bill Shanks, wound up in a heated-but-civil
debate with Robert Pitman of Austin, Texas, who suddenly stopped
and shook his head. ``Hey, I came here to go on the rides, not talk
to him,'' Pitman said, and walked off with companion David Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Disney, which does not allow any group to demonstrate or hand
out leaflets on Disney World property, doesn't sponsor, organize or
publicize Gay Day, its spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People encourage other people to buy tickets, which they have
a right to do,'' Warren said. ``Our park is open to everyone from
all walks of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Swallow, one of the original organizers of Gay Day at
Disney, said he was dismayed by the event's current political
overtones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was started as a purely social gathering,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After attracting a few thousand people the first year, Gay Day
grew to more than 60,000 last year, Swallow said. This year's crowd
was predicted to top 100,000. There is no one group behind the
event. Attendance is fueled by publicity, promotions for events at
nearby night clubs and word-of-mouth. Gays are asked to wear red
shirts, which makes the crowd easier to count.
</P>
<P>
   Disney doesn't reveal attendance figures, and Warren said the
parks always reach capacity by mid-morning at this time of year.
But there is no comparable, privately organized theme day. ``This
one's unique for its magnitude,'' Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   Disney does sponsor several special events, such as Grad Night
and Night of Joy, which features Christian music, but they are held
after normal closing hour.
</P>
<P>
   David E. Caton, president of the Florida Family Association,
said he asked Disney to shift Gay Day to later hours to avoid
conflicts with those who are upset by seeing gays kiss or hold
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Caton, who has fought gay-rights proposals around the state,
said he has attended several Gay Days at Disney and heard visitors
complain that weren't told what to expect. He and other members
planned to videotape this year's scene, but not protest.
</P>
<P>
   Two Gay Day parties were scheduled for after closing hour at
Disney World sites, but Disney says it has no control over the rest
of the day. Disney won't talk about visitor complaints, but Warren
said the company's policy is to make customers happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A complaint is conceivable any day,'' he said. ``If they're
dissatisfied about something beyond our control, we can offer them
the opportunity to come back another day.''
</P>
<P>
   The offer would suit the Gibson family of Pennsylvania
perfectly. Robert Gibson said he saw nothing that upset him, heard
nothing rude and thought everyone at Gay Day got along well.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wouldn't have come today if I'd known about it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why, he exchanged looks with his wife and paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just may have been a better day,'' he said. ``That's
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
