<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8933 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDSNEWS-HUNGER09-COX     06-08 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDSNEWS-HUNGER09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When there's not enough food
 &HT;    By Stell Simonton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Thirty or so years ago, Rick Bragg was a poor boy
growing up in northeast Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not know then, like I know now, that my mama never ate
until we were done,'' he writes in his book ``All Over But the
Shoutin'''.
</P>
<P>
   His mother ate what was left over. She was making sure her three
sons got their fill, because there wasn't quite enough food to go
around.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Bragg is now a writer for The New York Times and has plenty
of money for food. But some people _ even today in our rich country
_ don't.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of times, adults who don't have much money find it hard to
buy groceries, pay rent and buy all the other things their families
need. They may put enough food on the table, but it's a struggle _
and it's a bad feeling.
</P>
<P>
   About one out of every eight households in this country have
that kind of trouble, according to the U.S. Department of
Agriculture. The department _ along with the Census Bureau and
other government departments _ learned this by gathering
information from 45,000 people in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Those households reported that they had to do things such as cut
back on the amount of food the adults ate so the children would
have enough. Or they borrowed food or got groceries from a church
or food pantry that gives away free food. Or they bought cheaper
food that was not as healthy.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Agriculture calls this being ``food
insecure.''
</P>
<P>
   But things are worse than insecure for about one out of every 25
households. Adults in those households told the Census Bureau they
often go hungry.
</P>
<P>
   In the worst case _ in about one out of every 100 households _
even the children did not get enough to eat. The department calls
this ``severe hunger.''
</P>
<P>
   What this means is that if you are in a classroom of 25
students, probably three of those kids belong to families that have
trouble buying enough food.
</P>
<P>
   If your school is in a rich neighborhood, maybe no one has
trouble buying groceries. But if your school serves kids who live
in poor areas, more kids may be going hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Families are embarrassed and hurting when they can't buy food,
says Sandra Robertson of the Georgia Citizens Coalition on Hunger.
``Not many people are willing to share that kind of pain in
public,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   BREAKOUT - OPTIONAL
</P>
<P>
   Hungry for answers
</P>
<P>
   By Benita Dodd
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgians are starving,'' actress Jane Fonda said in a speech
in April. She was talking about how poor some people are in
Georgia. The very next day, she said she was wrong and apologized
for the remark. People are not actually dying of hunger in our
state. But her speech made many people want to know how big a
problem hunger really is.
</P>
<P>
   Around the world
</P>
<P>
   Poverty is the main cause of world hunger. About 20 percent of
the world's 4 billion people are underfed, according to Margaret
Missiaen, an agricultural economist formerly with the Department of
Agriculture. Of the people who don't get enough to eat, about half
live in or near India. About two-fifths live in African and Asian
countries.Hunger 101
</P>
<P>
   In a class called Hunger 101 taught by the Atlanta Community
Food Bank, instructors pass out raisins, with some kids getting a
few, some kids getting a handful, others getting none. It's a
lesson that helps show how things are not always fair and equal in
this world. The class also explains why people suffer from hunger
and how you can help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped me see through the eyes of those in need,'' said one
student who took the class. The free, one-day class is held for
groups of all ages _ kids through adults. For more information,
call 404-892-3333 or check the Web site at http://www.acfb.org/
</P>
<P>
   Note: The Web site also has a great explanation of how you can
organize a food drive.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency help
</P>
<P>
   A food bank is a place that gives free food to those who need
it. Many churches sponsor food banks, sometimes called a food
pantry. To find if there's one near you, call 211. To find out how
you can help volunteer at a food bank.
</P>
<P>
   What you can do to help
</P>
<P>
   Find out the nearest food bank or food pantry. Volunteer to help
out there. Maybe you could organize things on the shelves or help
clean up.
</P>
<P>
   Groups and organizations can hold a food drive: collect food
items for a food bank.
</P>
<P>
   Go with your family to a community kitchen to help serve food.
Go on a day that's not a holiday, because plenty of people usually
help on holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Atlanta Community Food Bank
</P>
<P>
   World Hunger Year site on the World Wide Web for ideas about how
to help: http://www.kids.maine.org cando.htm
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
