<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8935 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDSNEWS-VOLUNTEERING     06-08 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDSNEWS-VOLUNTEERING09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Volunteering: 10 ways you can help out
 &HT;    By Derrick Henry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Look around. It doesn't take Superman's X-ray vision
to see that not everyone is lucky enough to have a happy and
healthy family, plenty of food on the table and enough money to
make ends meet. In fact, many people in our society need help.
Fortunately, there are many good organizations that come to their
rescue. And those organizations depend on volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteering may not seem like a very good deal. After all, you
are giving something to someone else free of charge. But most
volunteers have found that what they give is paid back to them in
many ways. When you volunteer, you make new friends, expand your
horizons, develop leadership experience and learn new skills.
Sometimes, volunteering can even lead to a paying job. But most of
all, it gives you a good feeling inside _ just by knowing that you
helped someone who really needed help.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you are 6 or 16, there are many ways you can begin
volunteering this summer, whether you spend time with a needy
person or help out an arts organization. News for Kids rounds up
some of the best volunteer opportunities for youngsters:
</P>
<P>
   Help the hungry
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Community Food Bank is an amazing operation. It
distributes 1.5 million pounds of non-perishable food a month to
700 agencies that serve the hungry. They are looking for kids 8 or
older (anyone under 18 needs an adult chaperone) to help sort and
inspect the food, making sure it is safe to eat. You might look for
dents in cans or a hole in the potato chip bags, or _ yuck _ a
half-full jar of peanut butter that has an imprint of a spoon
someone has licked. Those get rejected. ``Kids have a blast, and
it's great for families or a summer camp project,'' says volunteer
program manager Kathleen Kelly. Call 404-892-3333, Ext. 229.
</P>
<P>
   Serve homeless kids
</P>
<P>
   Many kids must live in homeless shelters with their families.
The Atlanta Children's Shelter serves as a day care facility for
preschoolers (kids 5 and younger) while their parents work or look
for jobs. The shelter needs youngsters to play with the kids, read
stories, supervise arts and crafts, and serve snacks. You'll get a
good feeling when you enrich a youngster's life. Volunteer Tatianna
Troutman, a seventh-grader at Atlanta's Paideia School, says: ``I
like teaching the children new things, like their colors. At first
this little girl did not know the difference between green and
yellow, and now she does, because I taught her.'' Volunteers must
be 14 or older (younger if accompanied by a parent or other adult).
Call 404-892-3713.
</P>
<P>
   Be a buddy
</P>
<P>
   All kids need good role models such as a big brother or sister
they can look up to. The 22 service sites for Boys &AMP; Girls Clubs of
Metro Atlanta need young people 12 and up to serve as mentors to
kids 6-11. Activities range from coaching sports to working with
computers. Call 404-527-7100.
</P>
<P>
   Feed sick people
</P>
<P>
   It's pretty bad when you're so sick you can't cook _ or earn
enough money to buy food. That's where Project Open Hand steps in.
Every day, the organization prepares and delivers two freshly
cooked meals a day to 550 people with AIDS or HIV-related
disabilities. The organization needs volunteers 15 and up to pack
up meals, as well as volunteers 17 and up to work in the kitchen.
Delivery routes are available to those 16 and older with a car,
drivers license and insurance. Call 404-872-2707.
</P>
<P>
   For animal lovers
</P>
<P>
   While you must be 18 to work directly with the animals at the
Atlanta Humane Society shelter, the city's oldest charitable
organization welcomes all creative fund-raising from kids of all
ages. For instance, one family donated $38 that it earned from a
lemonade and bake sale. And all are welcome to make pet toys or
even homemade dog biscuits (there's a special recipe available from
the Humane Society) to be sold in the gift shop at the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Three 11-year-old Buckhead girls _ Ashley Jones, Tessa Morris
and Libby Spears _ raised $200 for the Humane Society from their
pet-sitting service.
</P>
<P>
   Explains Tessa, a student at the Westminster Schools: ``We
started the pet-sitting service because we really liked animals. We
wanted to buy a horse, but decided that was impossible, so we
decided to donate the money to the Humane Society to help
animals.'' It took the three girls a year and a half to raise the
money.
</P>
<P>
   Call 404-875-2600, Ext 234.
</P>
<P>
   Brighten up a senior citizen
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting young people together with senior citizens is an
incredible combination,'' says April Cooks, outreach coordinator
for the volunteer organization Hands On Atlanta. The elderly just
light up when kids are around, she says. Cooks has many projects
for youngsters _ from serving meals to just visiting. You must be
18 if unaccompanied by an adult, but kids as young as elementary
school level are welcome, if they have adult supervision. Call
404-872-2252, Ext. 33.
</P>
<P>
   Help the earth
</P>
<P>
   Litter is a serious problem in Georgia. It not only looks bad,
it also can be dangerous to health and safety. You can help create
a better environment by volunteering for DeKalb Clean and
Beautiful's monthly cleanups of streets, vacant lots and illegal
dumping spots all over the county. These beautification events are
held the third Saturday of every month. Volunteers also are needed
to plant flowers and trees and to mark storm drains to remind
people not to dump chemicals that pollute creeks and rivers. You
must be at least 12; adult supervision will be provided. Groups are
welcome. Call 404-371-2654. And there are plenty of similar
opportunities in other counties. To find the Keep America Beautiful
affiliate nearest you, call the information line of Keep Georgia
Beautiful: 1-888-657-1122
</P>
<P>
   Especially for bookworms
</P>
<P>
   One of the main ways Goodwill Industries raises money for its
job-training programs is through its annual used book sale, the
nation's largest. The enormous preparation for this sale goes on
year-round, and hundreds of volunteers are needed. Duties include
sorting thousands of donated books and magazines into categories,
and cleaning and pricing them. ``Kids love using the pricing
guns,'' says book department director Monique Huiet,``and enjoy
racing each other to see who can empty a bin of books and put them
in the right place the fastest.'' Goodwill can use unaccompanied
children 12 and up; under that age, adult supervision is required.
Families and groups (such as Scout troops) are welcome. Call
404-377-0441, Ext. 156.
</P>
<P>
   Stagestruck?
</P>
<P>
   There's much more to putting on a successful show than just
actors and scenery. The Academy Theatre gives high school students
a chance to participate behind the scenes. These volunteers help
with everything from tours to administrative tasks. Call
404-525-4111.
</P>
<P>
   Explore other cultures
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta International Museum introduces us to the cultures of
the world through art. Volunteers 15 and up are needed to serve as
tour guides, work in the gift shop and office, greet visitors, help
install exhibits and more. ``It's real fun and a great learning
experience,'' says volunteer coordinator Jane Arthur. Call
404-688-2467, Ext. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-08-98 0317E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
