<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE TUESDAY FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These stories for release Tuesday, June 9, 1998, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURFER _ With ``The X-Files'' movie gearing up (it opens June
19), David Duchovny says he often feels like he's had enough of his
character Fox Mulder. His contract is up in two years and _ after
that _ expect him to be outta here. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   MONSTERS _ As Godzilla tromps into town, parents need to make
sure they arm their kids with the best weapons against monsters:
common sense and sleep. Psychologist Stephen Garber, author of
``Monsters Under the Bed and Other Childhood Fears,'' says the
bottom line is this: Kids under 8 or 9 really are not clear on the
difference between reality and fantasy -- no matter how well they
articulate to the contrary. (Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (d food)
</P>
<P>
   CRAWFISH _ Cajuns love crawfish for their taste, of course; the
chef Paul Prudhomme likens the tender curl of tail meat to lobster
dipped in butter _ only you don't need the butter. But Cajuns love
crawfish for another reason as well: It reminds them of themselves.
It's a culinary underdog from the backwoods that had to scrap and
claw its way to acceptance. (Auchmutey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   LAST-MILKMAN _ He is one of a dying breed. Yet Rick Lee will not
go gentle into that good night. His job won't let him. When you're
one of the last milkmen in Atlanta, those days start early, around
2:30 a.m. For 27 years Rick Lee has been rising at that hour to
thank his luck, curse his luck, and deliver milk, eggs, butter,
cottage cheese and orange juice. (Scott, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-COLUMN _ That non-championship season: Why it can be a
good thing that your kid's Little League team gets bumped off.
(Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-MARKETING _ Marketing on the Web isn't easy. But Coca-Cola's
clever Web promotions make it one of the smartest Web marketers
around. Brand manager Tom Halloran says the ``Alanna'' promotion --
the latest in Coca-Cola's use of the Web to promote various brands
-- is designed to increase the appeal of Cherry Coke to teens and
young adults who are part of what he calls ``the emerging wired
generation.'' (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKWARS _ Independent booksellers face tough times. Those who
have lasted through changes in the business continue to quietly
look for ways to do better and more efficiently what they have a
reputation for doing: providing personal service. ``I did feel
everyone understands the importance of independent stores,'' Abel
Zimmerman, president of Book People, said. ``As an independent, I
felt well received (by publishers).'' (Morris, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KIDSNEWS-HUNGER _ Rick Bragg is a writer for The New York Times
and has plenty of money for food. But some people _ even today in
our rich country _ don't. A lot of times, adults who don't have
much money find it hard to buy groceries, pay rent and buy all the
other things their families need. They may put enough food on the
table, but it's a struggle _ and it's a bad feeling. (Simonton,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   VOLUNTEERING _ Whether you are 6 or 16, there are many ways you
can begin volunteering this summer, whether you spend time with a
needy person or help out an arts organization. News for Kids rounds
up some of the best volunteer opportunities for youngsters: (List
follows) (Henry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-CONVERT _ Southern Baptists from across the nation,
meeting for their national convention in Salt Lake City, are taking
part in an effort to persuade Mormons to change their beliefs, to
reach the unchurched with the gospel of Jesus and maybe to win back
some Southern Baptists who converted to Mormonism. (Perkes, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GAYDAY-DISNEY _ ay Day at Walt Disney World featured the
predicted open displays of affection: hand-holding, hugging,
snuggling and kissing. But on this day, as on other days, most of
those displays involved couples of opposite sex, and nearly
everything turned out as tame as an old-time Disney movie. Even
tamer were the dissenters who had threatened such a ruckus that
county deputies were put on riot alert. (Kalajian, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MILENNIUM _ Where will you be when the clock strikes
midnight on Dec. 31, 1999? As we fast approach the year 2000, big
celebrations and observances have already been planned around the
world. If you want to make the scene, there may be a travel book in
your future: ``The Millennium: A Rough Guide to the Year 2000''
(Rough Guides, $8.95). (Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
