<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ Even liberals are elbowing each other out
of the way to say nice things about Barry Goldwater. Sen. Goldwater
was the trusted friend, straight-shooter, gallant warrior, true
blue conservative _ the kind of conservative liberals want back.
Yet, in one moment of Goldwater's life he irrevocably splintered
the terms of the national debate. Brief insights from the
editor-in-chief of Cox Newspapers, Arnold Rosenfeld. (Rosenfeld,
Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Supreme Court Justice
Clarence Thomas is going to break bread with the National Bar
Association. On July 29, he will be the luncheon speaker at the
group's annual convention in Memphis. Typically, invited speakers
are admired and respected by the groups they address. Justice
Thomas does not meet that criteria with the majority of the NBA.
(Jefferson, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-COLUMN _ In the 1980s, one could scarcely read a national
news story about Atlanta without seeing a mocking reference to our
dogged ``boosterism.'' Now in the late 1990s, the optimists don't
have to talk it up any more. Turns out that metro Atlanta's growth
has outstripped even the rosiest predictions of the most gung-ho
Rotarians. Still, the North Georgia gold rush goes on. Business
column by Marilyn Geewax. (Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED. (k, f)
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ I used to be one of those anonymous people who
mail important-sounding letters nobody understands. The kind of
people Vice President Al Gore talked about recently when he called
for plain language in government. (Lane, Daytona News-Messenger)
MOVED. (k)
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ Early in our marriage,
when I was away from home a lot, I talked her into being our
bookkeeper and bill payer. That got me out of chores I didn't like
to do, but at considerable sacrifice of financial freedom. Over the
years I've found it's not in my best interest to record certain
purchases in black and white until I absolutely have to. Column by
a former editor of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. (Minter,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)(k) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Last Friday I asked my
8th-graders to close their books (Saroyan's, The Human Comedy) and
define the word dignity. For a long few seconds, nothing happened.
Then Johnny went for a dictionary. Elizabeth Schuett, a teacher and
writer in Gibsonburg, Ohio, is a regular contributor to the Cox
News Service. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED. (k)
