<HEADLINE>
THE FUN OF FUND RAISING FOR TEXAS POLITICS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Short of spotting an illegality, major
candidates for statewide office in Texas have little room to
complain about an opponent's fund-raising practices.
</P>
<P>
   Money is the fuel that drives the media campaigns that have
become so essential to success on Election Day. And although many
politicians like to howl about the excesses of campaign finance,
most, in truth, are alarmed only when opponents are able to raise
more money than they are.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic gubernatorial nominee Garry Mauro may feel like he
has good reason to complain, since he is about as far behind Gov.
George W. Bush in collecting dollars as polls indicate he is in
capturing the hearts and minds of voters.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro hasn't exactly been empty-handed. A spokesman said he has
raised about $2.2 million during the past 12 months. He has even
had enough money to go on television with advertising, much earlier
than most campaign-watchers would have thought.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush has raised about $15 million for his re-election effort
and will rake in another pile of cash with a fund-raiser scheduled
for June 18 in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   News of Bush's upcoming event renewed suspicions _ actively
cultivated by Democrats and shared by just about everybody _ that
the Republican governor is seeking re-election as a prelude to
running for president in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has carefully avoided confirming the speculation, but he,
nevertheless, likely views the Washington fund-raiser as a
``twofer.''
</P>
<P>
   First, it will be a major opportunity to increase his campaign
coffers and enhance his ability to buy large amounts of TV time
this fall as he seeks to bury his challenger.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington gathering, hosted by a number of lobbyists and
associates of former President George Bush, the governor's father,
also will give the governor more exposure to influential people on
the national scene _ the kind of exposure he pretends to hate but
is essential for someone contemplating a race for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro is trying to make an issue of Bush's perceived
presidential ambitions. He claims Bush is more interested in being
president than governor and thus may not be giving full attention
to the state's needs.
</P>
<P>
   But Mauro can't legitimately fault the governor for going to
Washington to raise money because the nation's capital also has
been a major source of funds for the Democratic candidate. And
Mauro's star hosts have been his longtime friends, the First
Couple.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton helped
Mauro raise funds in Washington a year ago. Mrs. Clinton came to
Austin and Dallas in February to raise more money for Mauro, and
the president has written a fund-raising letter for the Democratic
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro has still more events planned with the Clintons in
Washington on June 23. Contributors will have to pay $5,000 apiece
to have dinner with Mauro and Mrs. Clinton but can attend a Mauro
reception featuring the president for only $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   And, just two days later, Vice President Al Gore, another likely
presidential contender in 2000, will fly to El Paso to help Mauro
raise some more cash.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro attended fund-raisers with Clinton in Houston and Dallas
last week, but those events raised money for Democratic
congressional candidates and the national Democratic Party, not for
the gubernatorial nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The president's interest in the Texas governor's race has been
so obvious that Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes remarked last week
that it was ``beginning to appear as if the Clinton administration
is underwriting the campaign of Garry Mauro.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats deny _ but not very convincingly _ that Clinton is not
only trying to help an old friend but also would like to see Bush
bruised up a bit in his re-election race before the governor
officially launches a national bid.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Clinton's help, Mauro is not likely to come close to
matching Bush in fund raising. But there is no doubt that Clinton
owes Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro, the longtime state land commissioner, was Clinton's Texas
campaign chairman, both in 1992 and 1996, and one of the
president's biggest boosters in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton never carried Texas, but that certainly wasn't Mauro's
fault. Mauro worked tirelessly for Clinton, even to the point of
almost getting himself into deep trouble _ the legal, not the
political, kind.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro was investigated by Travis County District Attorney Ronnie
Earle over reports that state telephones and state employees at the
General Land Office were used to campaign for Clinton in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Earle let Mauro off the hook, but the land commissioner
apologized and reimbursed the state.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
