<HEADLINE>
PLANTING FOR THE YOUNG GARDENER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My granddaughter, who's 4, has a passion for picking flowers.
I would like to plant a cutting garden for her. It must be one,
however, that will withstand plucking, pulling and pruning, and
continue to produce a bloom. The flowers don't have to be
spectacular, just prolific. The area I have in mind is 6 feet by 3
feet and has an eastern exposure.
</P>
<P>
   A: This can be a fun project. Before you plant, make sure the
soil in the area is organically enriched and drains well. If you
have your doubts, work in some compost. You might add a stepping
stone or two to improve accessibility. And possibly a small
birdbath or a shallow dish with a small stone that will provide
water and a basking place for butterflies. Then plant thickly,
especially since prolific blooms, not a beautiful design, is your
goal.
</P>
<P>
   You can plant yellow melampodium, purple angelonia and white
Mexican zinnias for blooms into fall. The melampodium averages a
foot in height; the angelonia is 12-15 inches tall; the zinnias
make a 10-inch mound. The flowers are relatively easy to pick.
Another summer annual about the same height, the bachelor button or
gomphrena, comes in purple, a reddish-orange, lavender and white.
These flowers are small globes, and I would think enticing to a
child. They dry nicely. She'd also probably have fun with the
feathery blooms of celosia. Multicolored zinnias are fun, too.
</P>
<P>
   Wishbone flower (Torenia) is perfect for a small child. This
foot-tall annual produces small, cupped flowers with stamens that
form a wishbone. The cups may be white with blue or rose rims or
pale blue with dark blue rims. They appreciate afternoon shade, as
do impatiens, another easy-to-pick annual.
</P>
<P>
   Every child, in my opinion, should have the joy of growing
sunflowers. These are so easy from seed. She could sow the seed,
watch them come up and pick the flowers in a couple of months.
Heights vary considerably, so look for the shorter ones for easy
access, the tall ones for oohing and aahing. You all could harvest
some of the large flower heads and roast the seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Black-eyed Susans and purple coneflowers are prolific summer
bloomers, too. The stems on these perennials, however, are a little
tougher than those of the above annuals. Grandmother might need to
stand by with a pair of small scissors.
</P>
<P>
   `Batface' cuphea is a drought-tolerant, sun-loving plant with
tiny blooms that resemble a bat's face. The ``face'' is purple; the
``ears`` are red. It flowers continuously spring-frost. This tough
little plant survives less-than-tender touches.
</P>
<P>
   When it's cool this fall _ what a thought _ plant alyssum,
calendula, dianthus, Drummond phlox, petunias and snapdragons. If
you plant daffodil bulbs in November, she'll have fragrant yellow
or white blooms next spring. Sow larkspur and toadflax, which has
colorful, tiny, snapdragonlike blooms.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've grown tomatoes for years and have learned to pick them
just as they begin to turn pink to avoid birds pecking at them. The
birds have always left the green fruits alone. This year, the
squirrels are pulling the largest green tomatoes off the plants,
carrying them across the yard and eating about a third of the
fruit. How do I protect my tomatoes? I'm about to try bird netting
over the tomato patch, but have you heard of a tobacco (nicotine)
home brew that will work?
</P>
<P>
   A: Early one morning this week, I startled a squirrel that had
just picked a neighbor's green tomato and carried it across the
street. When I picked up the fruit, a big chunk was gone. I think
the animal was just after the water in the tomato.
</P>
<P>
   Continue to keep water in your bird bath, and put up the netting
or erect a barrier with chicken wire. I think this is the most
effective control. Products that contain nicotine can be really
strong, and I'm wary of using them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Problem: Little to no tomato production. We have five tomato
plants, planted in March, that have good green color, have been
slow to bloom and have few green tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; The key to good tomato production is planting in March,
which you did, in a sunny area where there is soil that drains well
and is highly enriched with organic matter. You want to encourage
good plant growth so that the tomatoes can set fruit on their
flowers when night temperatures are above 55 degrees but below 72
degrees while daytime temperatures don't climb above 85 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Nature is not always obliging. This year the window of
opportunity was shortened. I can't help but think that the lack of
rain have contributed to various tomato dilemmas. Several gardeners
have said their tomatoes seem to be ripening later.
</P>
<P>
   Other causes of poor production are too much nitrogen
fertilizer, poor pollination, irregular watering, inadequate
sunlight and/or planting a variety not suitable for our area.
Tomatoes produce best with a full day of sun.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P. O. Box 4260, Houston 77210. The bulk of mail prevents
individual replies to all unpublished letters. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
