<HEADLINE>
WOMEN OF THE WORK FORCE, UNITE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VERONICA FLORES  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ I've never understood why men's groups have bashed
the annual Take Our Daughters To Work Day. The program, created by
the Ms. Foundation for Women, sets aside a day for adults to focus
on girls by taking them into the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Girls ages 9-15 throughout the country had their day in April,
but many Texas schools postponed the event.
</P>
<P>
   What about boys? the men's advocates complain.
</P>
<P>
   Spare me. Is it not enough that women in corporate America hold
only 2 percent of executive positions, yet make up 46 percent of
the work force? Seems to me, boys _ ahem, men _ are getting along
just fine.
</P>
<P>
   It's true, however, that boys need positive guidance, too. How
else will they grow to recognize how wonderful we are?
</P>
<P>
   But guys, lighten up. Take Our Daughters to Work is only one
day. Those who care about the development of boys have 364 other
days to pick from.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say Take Our Daughters to Work can be ignored.
Doing so would be a grave oversight. Society's best interests will
be served when girls grow up to fulfill their potential in the
workplace.
</P>
<P>
   The Ms. Foundation reports that by the turn of the century eight
out of 10 women between the ages of 25 and 52 will work outside the
home because they want and, in most cases, need to work. And for
the first time, most new jobs will require education or training
beyond high school.
</P>
<P>
   Yet girls face stumbling blocks all along the way.
</P>
<P>
   They are bombarded daily by images that reinforce the ignorant
notion that looks matter more than brains. Then we are surprised
when gregarious girls grow to be insecure adolescents who shy from
competition in front of boys, or worse yet, dumb themselves down
because they don't want to appear smarter than a boy they like.
</P>
<P>
   And we shake our heads again when the fragile teen who believes
boys won't like her if she says no, winds up pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Educators often are inadvertent culprits, as several studies
over the years have noted. For example, they are more likely to
attribute boys' failure to lack of motivation, while girls' failure
is attributed to lack of ability, one study showed.
</P>
<P>
   Adults are guilty too, as the study indicates they often don't
believe girls are capable of doing things the girls themselves
believe they can do.
</P>
<P>
   But girls also get very strong cues, perhaps the strongest cues,
from the women around them. The Ms. Foundation often repeats the
refrain, ``A girl is watching; what is she learning?''
</P>
<P>
   They are watching when women manage households, and they see the
contributions that the men in the women's lives do or don't make.
And they are watching, too, when women and their partners interact.
Do they see women asserting themselves or giving in?
</P>
<P>
   As girls watch women in the workplace, what will they learn?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Veronica Flores is a columnist for the San Antonio
Express-News, P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
