u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HABITAT-HOUSTON-HNS &LR;      06-08 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HABITAT-HOUSTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER, HABITAT AIM TO BUILD 100 HOMES IN ONE WEEK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Project begins Monday, June 15) 
 
By ERIC BERGER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ With a mix of worship, work and wood, a former
president and 6,000 volunteers hope to raise 100 homes in the
Houston area in a single week.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning next Monday, the 1998 Jimmy Carter Work Project aims
to build houses in Houston's Fifth Ward, a historic
African-American hub that fell on hard times between 1970 and 1990,
and Magnolia Park, a neighborhood with a rich Hispanic tradition
that dates to about 1910.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the largest project ever attempted by Habitat for
Humanity in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stage is set for us to make history,'' said Millard
Fuller, founder of Habitat for Humanity. Internationally, his
ecumenical organization has built 65,000 homes for low-income
families.
</P>
<P>
   Between 7 a.m. next Monday and midafternoon Tuesday, walls,
roofs and plasterboard for 100 new homes will spring up,
transforming once vacant lots into neighborhoods overnight.
Painting, wiring, landscaping and other new-home trimmings will
follow during the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is under the watchful eye and hammer of former
President Carter, participating in his 15th such project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting, challenging and always unpredictable,'' Carter
said of his Habitat experiences. ``Rosalynn and I don't consider it
a sacrifice. Each year that we go, it's an adventure for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 4,500 local volunteers culled from businesses, churches and
other groups will be joined by 1,500 sojourners with hard hats.
</P>
<P>
   Many will stay at the University of Houston, Rice University and
Texas Southern University while working different shifts from early
morning to late at night. For some the weeklong event will be their
first bout with Houston's summer heat and sultry humidity.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller said he considered that when recruiting volunteers for
the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just explained that it would be a worthwhile spiritual
experience,'' Fuller said. Then, tongue in cheek, added, ``Because
if you build 100 homes in June in Houston, you'll never consider
going to hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the local Habitat affiliate dedicated its first home
slightly less than a decade ago, Houston attracted interest as a
Carter project site as far back as 1989. But organizers determined
it was not feasible at the time and the project was shifted to
Milwaukee at the last moment.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Houston Habitat turned to Michael Shirl, a chaplain and
six-year volunteer, to expand their organization and finally bring
the Carter project to Houston, the fourth-largest city in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Habitat had just built its 52nd home in Houston and
no one seriously contemplated a 100-home project.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1996, local organizers planned 25 homes, a typical
number for a Carter work project. After they were selected as the
host city from more than 20 other applicants, however, they
discovered Fuller had grander visions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked us what we could do to make the project unique,''
Shirl said. ``What was it going to take in Houston to get the
public's attention?''
</P>
<P>
   Out of the ambitious goal of 100 homes grew Project Houston,
Shirl's plan to hike the local organization to ``the next level.''
Including the Carter project, Shirl wanted Habitat to build 385
homes between 1997 and 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Project Houston also meant major bucks for the organization,
with a goal of raising $15 million. Of that, $10 million has
already been raised. Some money was used for new office space and a
warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing has grown beyond my wildest dreams,'' said Carl
Umland, Houston Habitat's first president.
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said for the 22-year-old Habitat For Humanity
International. On its 10th anniversary in 1986, the organization
had built only 1,000 homes. Not until after Carter began his work
projects in 1984 did the organization really bloom.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, Habitat had built 49,000 homes. The organization plans
to build its 100,000th home in New York City by September 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Habitat's mission, Fuller said, is not only providing
homes for those in need, but also raising public awareness of the
dearth of affordable housing in Houston and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just coming to Houston to put on a show,'' Fuller
said. ``We're going to spread the message that if you are a city
official, pastor or businessman and you know people in your city
living in poverty and are doing nothing about it _ that's a
disgraceful thing.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a Housing and Urban Development study released in
April, about 64,000 Houston-area households face unaffordable rents
and poor living conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Better living conditions, Habitat's credo goes, creates a better
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of making good citizens out of people,'' Carter
said. ``These folks have been dependent on society, they've
probably been on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't felt like they were part of the community,'' he
said. ``They were alien no matter where they existed. They get a
house, they become a taxpayer, they become constructive citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their work at various Carter project work sites,
the 100 Habitat families or individuals receiving new homes have
already worked 300 ``sweat equity'' hours for their new homes. To
qualify, the applicants had to be first-time homeowners and earn
between $11,000 and $23,000.
</P>
<P>
   The homes, ranging in size from 1,100 to 1,250 square feet, will
cost between $43,000 and $46,000 with a no-interest, 15- to 30-year
mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   Each house completion culminates with a dedication service,
often a teary moment for the participants. Prayers are said and the
home's keys are given to the family.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Browning, house construction leader for a Carter project
home sponsored by Southwestern Bell, has been through two such
ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't wipe the smiles off the families' faces with a
Brillo pad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its initial difficulties finding environmentally clean
land and a recent concrete shortage, Shirl said Habitat remains on
schedule with the upcoming Carter project:
</P>
<P>
   The foundations and sidewalks are laid.
</P>
<P>
   The materials are in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteers are lined up.
</P>
<P>
   But a looming question remains _ will the weather cooperate?
</P>
<P>
   Summer heat can be managed with preparation, Shirl said. He
estimates volunteers will consume 40,000 gallons of water to combat
the humidity. Ultimately, moisture of a form other than
perspiration or humidity presents the greatest threat to the
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get past Monday afternoon without any rain then we're
home free in terms of weather,'' Shirl said. By then the walls and
some of each home's roof will be in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if it does rain, then I suspect some of us will be working
a few late nights.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
