<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIGHTFUL READING FROM THE STREETS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``I will never forget the day I moved in. I was
so happy I was crying. I was thinking to myself, now I have a place
to call my own.'' _ S.R.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have trouble these days remembering that every one of
``the homeless'' is actually a human being? Do you ever pass one of
those animated bags of rags in a doorway and bother to try to find
its eyes?
</P>
<P>
   Have you convinced yourself the homeless all prefer begging on
the street to living a normal life? Do you care anymore how each
man or woman got so down and out?
</P>
<P>
   Read ``We Are Home Now.'' It is a compilation of 36 essays by
people who lived in Hell but who managed to find the skinny, uphill
path that leads out.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them are only part of the way out. Homeless for years,
they now live in the Canon Kip Community House in San Francisco.
They fill their days with classes and activities designed to keep
them from going backward.
</P>
<P>
   Drug and alcohol rehabilitation. Training in job and life
skills. Psychiatric appointments. Support groups. The dentist.
Literacy class. Basic math. A writing workshop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living in the streets not only demoralizes you, it actually
zaps the emotional as well as the spiritual strength from you. How
many times had I thought of simply swimming out into the bay until
I could swim no more?'' _ M.L.C.
</P>
<P>
   Although it should, ``We Are Home Now'' will never make the New
York Times bestseller list. You won't find it in Barnes and Noble.
Written by 27 students in the Episcopal Community Services writing
program, it was edited by Ireri Valenzuela, an Adult Basic
Education teacher. The ever-philanthropic Miller Freeman Inc.
published it pro bono.
</P>
<P>
   The content is tough going. It contains very little nonsense. Be
they a 50-year-old Vietnam veteran or a 25-year-old HIV-positive
mother, the essayists are honest about what they have in common:
Alcohol or drug addiction. Jail. Subhuman living conditions.
Chronic poor health. Mental disorders. Shattered families. Hitting
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a drug addict in denial and blamed my bad luck on
everything and everyone but myself. For six years I was living in
the gutters of Oakland. My mind was filled with trash and I was on
a head-on collision with death and/or jail.'' _ R.W.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had sunk to the lowest level, and the only thing that was in
me that drugs couldn't kill was my soul. And that alone made me
take notice of my poor existence, and it haunted me every day. I
would think, what kind of man or woman would stay in the hellhole
of no existence? I had made myself sick, and I was tired of being
everything I didn't want to be.'' _ L.M.
</P>
<P>
   Some were born into poverty and substance abuse. Too many fell
into the hole after Vietnam or when a factory or small business
closed and left them unemployed and unskilled for the job market.
Divorce pushed some of the women to the edge. Alcohol and drugs
shoved almost everyone over.
</P>
<P>
   They never dreamed they could sink as low as they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my car, my house and soon found myself on the streets.
I was in and out of ... hotels, where they won't let you stay for
more than a month. I have been raped and stabbed while sleeping
outdoors. Once, I almost committed suicide.'' _ C.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would lie face-to-face with some total stranger who has,
like me, walked all day from one soup line to the next on dirty,
smelly feet that stretch across the cold, overcrowded floor, just
short of going into someone's mouth for lack of sleeping space.'' _
A.W.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in each story is one man or woman who got through to
the homeless person: A not-yet burnt-out social worker. A volunteer
at Catholic Charities. A staffer at Swords to Plowshares or A
Woman's Place. A Veteran's Administration nurse. A hotel night
clerk. A bag of rags on the next cot in an emergency shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Someone mentioned ``supportive housing,'' and Canon Kip, and
that suggestion led the ``We Are Home Now'' writers to Episcopal
Community Services.
</P>
<P>
   Once accepted and given an apartment, no one's life miraculously
turned around. The struggle to change is slow, hard work. But it's
easier with a room of one's own and people around who know progress
when they see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up this morning and felt good to be alive. I know that
I can't go back onto the streets. I need help, and this is the
place where I can get it.'' _ C.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless the fact that I am able to acknowledge in my right
mind the life I have so much detested ... God bless the chance this
place is giving me to do what is right without diverting off
path.'' _ P.B.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. A copy of ``We Are Home
Now'' can be obtained by calling 415-835-2484.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
