<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO COURT RULINGS GIVE MEANING TO THE WORD `JUSTICE' 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ At first glance, neither appears a matter of much
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Who cares if some boxing trainer is stiffed by his top fighter?
And who cares if a bunch of cops out on the town raise a little
hell? Big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Both are fairly big deals, however. That's because what happened
in these two court cases demonstrates that our legal system,
despite all its inane complexities and black-robed aloofness, is
essentially designed to see that the right thing gets done.
</P>
<P>
   The system exists for a reason _ to keep those with money and
power from riding roughshod over everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   As the late U.S. Supreme Court Justice William J. Brennan Jr.
said, ``The law is not an end in itself, nor does it provide ends.
It is preeminently a means to serve what we think is right.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, anybody sensible would be hard pressed not to conclude
that the New York Court State of Appeals did the right thing the
other day. By a 4-1 ruling, this state's highest court ruled that
multimillionaire Mike Tyson, who promised that Kevin Rooney would
be his trainer for his whole career, has to keep his word _ or, at
least, cough up some money in compensation. The ruling was more
arcane than that, but that's what it boils down to.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals ruled that the intent of contract law in
New York is to ensure that a deal remains a deal, that a handshake
is worth as much as an agreement engraved in stone and that movie
producer Sam Goldwyn was simply wrong when he said that, ``An oral
contract isn't worth the paper it's written on.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is good news to Kevin Rooney to the tune of several
million bucks, even though his legal fight will go on for a while
in another court. That ruling is good news for the rest of us, too.
</P>
<P>
   It tells us, as the late U.S. Supreme Court Justice Hugo Black
once wrote, that the courts stand against any winds that blow as
havens of refuge for those who would otherwise suffer injustice
because they're not as rich or powerful as the people doing them
dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the same day, another state appeals court issued
another ruling that sends a related and equally important message.
The City of Schenectady and its police union had refused to release
the names of a squad of cops who'd behaved like goons at a bachelor
party, getting tanked up and throwing eggs and beer cans at
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   This was a private personnel matter, said the union _ and city
officials supposedly answerable to the public. Sure, these guys are
paid with tax dollars. Sure, these guys are paid to arrest people
who behave the way they behaved. But nobody has a right to know
precisely which Schenectady police officers were involved in this
incident.
</P>
<P>
   That's none of the public's business.
</P>
<P>
   Two newspapers, the Albany Times Union and the Daily Gazette of
Schenectady, sued them for the names and won in that appeals court
decision. Just as the Rooney-Tyson ruling illustrates that the rich
and the non-rich are equal under the law, the decision in the
Schenectady case also illustrates two other rather crucial points
in the relationship between the rulers and the ruled.
</P>
<P>
   One is that the law is more than merely the expression of the
will of those in positions of power at any given moment. And the
other is that nobody has a more sacred obligation to obey the law
than those who enforce it.
</P>
<P>
   Who protects the public when it's the police violating the law?
Who polices the police? The independent court system.
</P>
<P>
   And thank God it's there.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
