<HEADLINE>
BEAR FACTS ABOUT BIRTH CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED _ The more I learn about labor and delivery, the more
I'm convinced that the women who have given birth and the men who
have ``helped'' them belong to some secret society.
</P>
<P>
   They must make you take an oath of silence while you're still in
the delivery room, holding your brand-new bundle of joy, figuring
that at that point, after all you've been through, you'll agree to
anything.
</P>
<P>
   They MUST. If they didn't, it's all that anyone who has gone
through it would ever talk about.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I have completed our birthing classes and patiently
await the Big Event. It's sort of like being trained as a
firefighter and sitting around the station, waiting for the alarm
to ring. You know it's going to. You just don't know when.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us think we have a general idea of where babies come
from. As kids, we start out with the basics: stork, cabbage patch,
whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Then we move on to scandalous grade-school gossip for the more
anatomically correct version, which is greeted by shock, outrage
and strong denials, because there is no way any grown-ups _
especially your PARENTS _ could ever engage in something so . . .
so . . . WEIRD. &QL; 
THE TRUTH BEHIND SANTA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Walter Crigler was my school's source of information. He knew
everything first; in addition to the baby rumors, he had some
disturbing information about the legitimacy of Santa Claus as well.
Walter would have made a fine reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at least for people my age, we studied sex and birth in
school. The information was taught in such a clinical,
avoid-the-real-issues way that it made conception and delivery
sound about as enticing as changing the oil in your parents' car.
</P>
<P>
   Which was sort of the point, I think.
</P>
<P>
   This was the body of knowledge I was armed with when we began
the classes. Things started out great. Our excellent instructor
asked how much weight the expectant mothers had gained. Answers
varied.
</P>
<P>
   I asked how many partners had gained weight, partly as a joke
and partly as an explanation for my sympathetic belly.
</P>
<P>
   Every single partner raised a hand. One guy had gained 17
POUNDS. He also suffered from morning sickness. I don't want to be
around when he starts getting contractions.
</P>
<P>
   After more discussion and instruction, all of which was
informative and had everyone feeling good about things, we moved on
to . . . the movies. &QL; 
A FINGER ON THE PULSE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remember the car-wreck films shown during driver-education
class, designed to scare impressionable teens into not driving like
maniacs? Compared with birthing movies, those might as well be Bugs
Bunny cartoons. I'm surprised anyone who sees these ever has a
second kid.
</P>
<P>
   And what is the story with the couples in the movies who allow
themselves to be filmed? ALL of themselves, if you get my drift; I
thought I'd have to go to medical school to get such a thorough
look. I don't know if the filmmakers pay the couples, but they
should. A lot. And a little digital technology to change the
identities of the people involved might be nice, too.
</P>
<P>
   I took the instructions to heart despite the feeling that my
role in the actual process will be to stand around and say things
like, ``Breathe!'' every so often and then run for cover. My wife,
who isn't nearly as bewildered about all this as I am, despite
being the one who will have to do all the work, decided I might
feel like a bigger part of things if I volunteered to cut the
umbilical cord after the baby is born. OK, I said, and read up on
how this is done.
</P>
<P>
   Ugh. I wasn't thrilled to learn that the cord can be tough but
was relieved to know that neither the baby nor the mother feels any
pain, so I convinced myself this would be a good plan. Until I read
a passage suggesting you might want to wait to cut the cord _ after
it stops pulsing.
</P>
<P>
   Pulsing? PULSING? Who knew?
</P>
<P>
   The couples who have been through this before, that's who.
</P>
<P>
   But you'd never know it. They're not saying anything. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
