<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PACIFIC LOOK AT THE 20TH CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The century now in its concluding years certainly
was savage and bloody-minded, a time when tyrants or fools reigned
too long, and men and women and the nations in which they lived
suffered grievously.
</P>
<P>
   It is good to be reminded, then, that all was not lost during
these 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   That is what strikes me so much about the fine art exhibit now
on display at the New York State Museum in Albany. It is titled
``Still Life: The Object in American Art, 1915-1995,'' and its 66
paintings reveal the creative power of the artistic imagination
that flourished during the same years that all that savagery was
taking place.
</P>
<P>
   The paintings, the work of 59 artists, are representative of the
varieties of approaches to art that thrived in this century, which
is one of the striking attractions of this show. You can stand and
view the work of one artist, working in one style, and walk a few
feet further on, to see another artist's esthetic appreciation of a
still life from a much different viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit is drawn from the collection of The Metropolitan
Museum of Art, the greatest museum in this country and likely the
world, which attracts nearly 5 million visitors each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still Life'' is on display in the State Museum until July 26.
It is here as part of a special series of Great Art Exhibitions, in
which the Met has played the key part.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Still Life,'' you will find the work of Georgia O'Keefe,
Franz Kline, Stuart Davis, Marsden Hartley, James Rosenquist, Max
Weber and so many others, providing a rich menu of artistic
expressions. These are the painters who contribute heavily to
defining American art of this century.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, they have also made a statement, asserting the
quality of American painters, who, it seems to me, tend to be not
appreciated to the extent that they should be. This exhibit reveals
them in all their creative glory.
</P>
<P>
   One of the striking contrasts of the ``Still Life'' show is one
work by George Grosz, a German painter renowned for his bitter
caricatures of the post-World War I German state. With the rise of
Nazism, he emigrated to American and lived and worked here for 27
years. His contribution to the State Museum show is titled ``Still
Life with Walnuts,'' which vastly differs in outlook and execution
from the biting satire that had been the hallmark of his work in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Art Exhibitions not only will continue to host
exhibits from the Metropolitan Museum. Next year, two important
shows are already scheduled, one drawn from the Museum of Modern
Art and the other from the Whitney Museum of American Art.
</P>
<P>
   These exhibits are worth your time and effort to go to see them.
They will make you feel better about yourself and the times in
which you have lived.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
