<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BUYER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOOK SCOUT WHO BEATS THE SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DONALD G. SMITH  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MARIA, Calif. _ Rollie is a book scout. He buys old books
and sells them to dealers. Book scouts, as they say in the
business, buy from the dumb and sell to the smart.
</P>
<P>
   I met him at least 10 years ago. I have seen him no more than a
half-dozen times since then and really don't know him all that
well. Rollie has beaten The System. He has no office, no employees
and no forms to complete. He works his own hours.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't a business for everyone. A book scout starts with a
solid education in literature and then spends a long apprenticeship
learning the book business; reading catalogs and periodicals;
becoming familiar with obscure publishing houses, past and present;
becoming acquainted with dealers in various cities, and knowing
what they are looking for.
</P>
<P>
   The daily routine includes visits to used-book stores, thrift
shops, swap meets and garage sales, always on the lookout for that
jewel on the bottom of the pile.
</P>
<P>
   He deals entirely in cash. I have no idea of his arrangement
with the Internal Revenue Service _ and I don't want to know. Armed
only with superior knowledge, he starts usually around mid-morning
and works about a four-hour day.
</P>
<P>
   His base of operations is Los Angeles, but he travels to San
Francisco at least once a month and makes an annual ``New
York-Boston run.''
</P>
<P>
   Rollie has sometimes been compared with a professional gambler,
but this is a false impression of a book scout. Rollie never risks
anything. He buys only books that are going to bring a higher
price, often only a block or two away. The worst that can happen is
a day with little or no profit.
</P>
<P>
   He insists on total independence. He has no bank account and no
credit cards. Whenever he can't pay in cash, he uses a cashier's
check. He gets around by bus or cab. He doesn't own a car, which
means no driver's license, no vehicle registration and no
automobile insurance.
</P>
<P>
   He has no money invested _ where he stores his cache is a matter
for conjecture. I remember one occasion when a man said that it was
wise to have one's money invested and ``working for you.'' Rollie's
answer was that when financial transactions are recorded, the money
can only work against you.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when we had a lot of Rollies in this country.
There were independent farmers, itinerant peddlers, circuit-riding
preachers and traveling craftsmen who could fix anything that
broke.
</P>
<P>
   Those days are mostly gone. We are left with a nation of people
who exist only in the depths of a giant computer and whose lives
are controlled from the darkness of that well.
</P>
<P>
   This is why Rollie is such a rarity. He has beaten the system
because he isn't a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Donald L. Smith is retired from corporate communications.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
