<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9039 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PINK-FLAMINGOS-HNS &LR;      06-08 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINK-FLAMINGOS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINK FLAMINGOS FLY BACK INTO FASHION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Although they don't actually fly north for the
summer, pink flamingos have been somewhat popular lawn ornaments
since the 1920s and hold sway, along with elves, frogs, fawns,
toadstools and rabbits, among the various commercial lawn oddities
and decorations.
</P>
<P>
   Lawn ornaments aren't really new. They actually date back to the
ancient Romans, who would set up altars to pagan gods.
</P>
<P>
   But come summer in America, it's time to get out the pink
flamingos, statues of large, tropical wading birds that,
historically, began appearing on lawns and in gardens as early as
the 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   Early flamingos were made of bronze and were expensive, compared
to today's hollow pink plastic version that costs approximately $10
a pair (one with head up and one with head down) at Kmart.
</P>
<P>
   The English were fond of using stone statuary of animals in
their 19th-century gardens.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s and 1930s, lawn flamingos were made of concrete,
which can still be bought for about $58.99 per bird. Some of these
leggy versions also came in enamel-painted plywood cutouts, and
then foam, but dogs tended to chew the latter.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1940s, the pink statues were created from plastic and
began appearing on the front lawns of modest American homes,
especially those in areas that lacked natural fauna.
</P>
<P>
   As new housing developments and mobile home parks flourished
after World War II, so did the lawn ornament industry, producing
gnomes and other cutesy critters or folksy images.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1950s, Florida was becoming a major vacation and
retirement destination, and the hot pink plastic flamingo lawn
ornament a must-see souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   The three-dimensional hollow plastic version of the bird,
featuring long straight black legs to stick into the ground, was
designed in 1957 by Don Featherstone, who designed them for Union
Products in Leominster, Mass., a lawn-ornaments manufacturer. (The
company had already been producing two-dimensional plastic pink
flamingos.) More than 20 million of Featherstone's pink flamingos
have been sold since then.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1970s, plastic pink flamingos were persona non
grata, except among those who love kitsch.
</P>
<P>
   But they winged their way back toward mainstream America in the
late 1980s, when retro became hip. Plastic pink flamingos are
available at many garden and lawn centers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
