   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Tuesday, June 9, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Bob Schenet at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   PIXEL-MYSPACE (Seattle) _ If Microsoft Windows were a religion,
a core belief would be that the computer screen and the Windows
desktop are nearly the same thing: The desktop fills the screen and
displays everything the user needs to know. Time for some heresy,
Seattle software designer Tom O'Rourke says. O'Rourke's new
venture, The Pixel Co., uses the dark border at the edge of the
desktop for a new control bar called MySpace that is separate from
Microsoft Windows and can launch applications, find Internet
content and control devices such as CD and DVD players.
</P>
<P>
   By Warren Wilson. (story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BANKS-CROSS-SELLING (Undated) _ ``Cross-selling'' is the new
mantra of the financial services business. The gargantuan
combination of banker Citicorp and insurer Travelers is predicated
upon the idea that the way to survive and thrive is to offer every
type of money product under one roof. The NationsBank-BankAmerica
combination is similarly designed to provide a coast-to-coast
retailer of financial products.
</P>
<P>
   By Bill Virgin. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
