<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-DISHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SET YOUR TABLE WITH SUMMERTIME HUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It's the summer season and to many that means
eating alfresco around the swimming pool, on the patio or deck.
This is the perfect time to have fun with colorful dishes and
whimsical patterns.
</P>
<P>
   You can create a nautical theme to one with a woodsy flavor or
vibrant artistic one with custom hand-painted earthenware.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be afraid to experiment, but if you are the timid type,
don't fret. Tabletop designers have color coordinated most of
today's selections, so that you can't make a color faux pas.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our designs are exclusive to Pier I Imports, said
Kimberly Chaumont, company buyer for picnic and poolside products.
``Everything is based on being able to be mixed and matched, so
that you can play and have fun with shapes, patterns and colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaumont added that through their research, consumers want a
more upscale look in acrylics and pieces that can be used inside as
well as outside, as acrylics have become a year-round business.
</P>
<P>
   ``To meet this request, we have added aluminum stems and sleeve
to many of the acrylic tumblers, wine and martini glasses,''
Chaumont said. ``This is our third year to repeat our petal shaped
dishes. Don't worry about the hot bright colors you may be buying
this year, because those colors will continue through the spring of
1999. So you will still be able to add on and coordinate future
purchases with those that you may make this year.''
</P>
<P>
   By mixing and matching, you don't have to worry about buying a
whole set of dishes at once, you can add on from one season to the
next, as your budget allows. Most dishes are sold individually as
open stock, while pricer dishes are often sold as sets. Even still,
you can often buy serving platters, sugar and creamers, salt and
peppers and serving bowls separately. Mixing colors, patterns and
shapes makes for a most interesting table.
</P>
<P>
   There is a myriad of patterns and shapes from which to choose to
produce a fun and festive table setting.
</P>
<P>
   Besides solid or frosted colors in bright, jewel and pastel
hues, there are gingham, polka dot, stripe, floral, geometric,
fruit, vegetable and artistic hand-painted designs.
</P>
<P>
   Each store may put its own spin on a place setting, but with
careful shopping, you should be able to produce a variety of
colorful and patterned mixtures in various shapes, whether it be in
acrylic, stoneware, porcelain, melamine, ceramic, earthenware,
enameled tinware, glass or polypropylene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always read the directions for the type dishes you are
buying,'' Chaumont said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our acrylic pieces are dishwasher safe and should hold up for
about five years, before showing some wear and tear. In time,
injected acrylic colored plates may begin to crack and get cloudy.
Anything that is hand-painted should always be hand washed to
preserve its design. Polypropylene plates, knives, forks and spoons
are very durable and should exhibit no signs of color fading. You
should also be careful with picnic and poolside dishes, as many of
these are not suitable for the microwave.''
</P>
<P>
   Patio dishes feature a large dinner plate, salad/dessert plate,
cereal/soup bowl, mug and demitasse cup and saucer. By shopping
around you can also find decorative chargers (large service plate
under the dinner plate), in metalics or matching acrylic hues.
Frosted glass chargers can be found at Pier 1 for $20, although
they must be hand washed and $20 earthenware chargers in clay red,
royal blue and teal that are dishwasher safe.
</P>
<P>
   Pier 1's acrylic flower picnicware is $2.50 to $4 each for
8-inch and 12-inch plates and an 8-inch bowl, $3.50 to $4 each for
matching drinkware, which includes a Margarita, goblet, tumbler and
double old fashion.
</P>
<P>
   In addition there are festive acrylic martini shakers for $10
and corkscew stemware for $4 each. Lending a more formal touch are
aluminum stemmed martini and goblet drinkware with acrylic tops for
$6.50 each. In keeping with the formal look, there are 24 ounce
acrylic tumblers with removable aluminum sleeves for $8.
</P>
<P>
   Colored acrylic trays can be found at Bed Bath &AMP; Beyond for
$7.50 each and matching beverage pitcher for $12.99. The chain
store also carries a colorful selection of Melmanine, which is
suitable for the dishwasher but not the microwave. A 21-inch
platter is $6.99, 10-inch dinner plate $2.99, 7-inch salad and a
soup/cereal for $2.19 and serving bowl for $3.99. All of the dishes
can be paired up with a four-piece set of plastic flatware for 99
cents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whimsey and country elegance can be added to the table with
earthy stoneware plates.
</P>
<P>
   When considering price and dining out of doors, diversity can
also be found by purchasing one inexpensive set for breakfast, tea
or dessert and a different set for dinner and lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Or supplement a new fun set of dishes by using your good china
or antique plates for dessert. Better yet, serve each course with a
different pattern or color.
</P>
<P>
   Many of today's acrylic dishes can also be paired up with
coordinating paper plates, which are cost effective as well as
saving on clean-up.
</P>
<P>
   Before rushing out to buy new dishes, it's always best to take
an inventory of what you have and build upon it, just like you
would with your wardrobe.
</P>
</TEXT>
