<SLUG> BC-BANKS-CROSS-SELLING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROSS-SELLING THE NEW MANTRA OF FINANCIAL INSTITUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL VIRGIN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You have a checking account with one bank, a credit card with
another, a car loan from the credit union, a home loan from the
mortgage company, insurance from the local agent and mutual funds
from half a dozen investment firms.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't you really prefer to buy all your financial services
from one company, much like you buy all your food from a single
grocery store?
</P>
<P>
   What's that you say? You don't mind dealing with half a dozen
different companies for your savings, investments and credit
accounts?
</P>
<P>
   Gee, that's too bad. Those banks, brokerages and insurance
companies are really, really counting on talking you into one-stop
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cross-selling'' is the new mantra of the financial services
business. The gargantuan combination of banker Citicorp and insurer
Travelers is predicated upon the idea that the way to survive and
thrive is to offer every type of money product under one roof. The
NationsBank-BankAmerica combination is similarly designed to
provide a coast-to-coast retailer of financial products.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a lot of debate over how successful financial
services companies will be at cross-selling _ and whether consumers
will accept one-stop-shopping for mutual funds and car loans the
way they do for hamburger, lettuce and milk.
</P>
<P>
   Financial companies have some solid strategic reasons for hoping
consumers buy into cross-selling. It costs less to sell an
additional product to an existing customer than to recruit a new
one. Deanna Oppenheimer, executive vice president for consumer
banking at Seattle-based Washington Mutual Inc., said there's a 30
percent likelihood that a customer who buys one type of product or
service will still be with the bank two to three years later; that
jumps to 75 percent when the customer has three products or
services.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there's a big difference between knowing the importance
of cross-selling and doing a good job of it. In the past,
cross-selling meant dumping thousands of pieces of junk mail on
customers and hoping someone would be interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most banks don't have a clue'' how to cross-sell effectively,
said Todd Gurley, senior vice president with Aragon Consulting
Group in St. Louis. ``They haven't spent time over the last 10
years building databases or talking to customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Another failed attempt at cross-selling was the ``financial
supermarkets'' banks set up in the 1980s to offer not just banking
but discount brokerage services, insurance, even travel agencies,
often literally all under one roof. Customers seemed perfectly
content to shop around and, by the early 1990s, the concept had
evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   What's different this time, industry executives say, is that the
approach is much more tailored to customer interests.
</P>
<P>
   For banks like Washington Mutual, the strategy starts with a
checking account. While customers can and do hop among credit cards
and certificates of deposit, ``If you've ever tried to dislodge
yourself from a bank, it's a painful process,'' Gurley said.
``There are real barriers to changing. There are real opportunities
for banks, if they get their acts together, to market one-stop
shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   To make the most of those opportunities, banks want to get close
to their customers, building relationships off that first account.
That runs counter to the industry trend in which, because of
cost-cutting, customers are being pushed more and more to
impersonal contacts like automated teller machines and telephone
and computer banking.
</P>
<P>
   The way the banks hope to reverse the trend is to mine the
mountains of data about their customers sitting in their computer
files _ data collected on home loan, credit card and insurance
applications, for example.
</P>
<P>
   By knowing more about their customers, banks can tell who might
be demographically ready for a home loan, who is about to finish
paying off a loan and might be in the mood to divert that money to
an investment account. Said Gurley, ``It's not junk mail if you're
interested in it.''
</P>
<P>
   At Washington Mutual, the job of cross-selling starts when a
customer opens an account. ``We talk about other products and
services, and as we have special offers we have mailings, and the
branch folks will call to follow up,'' Oppenheimer said.
</P>
<P>
   KeyCorp has a database management system it says will analyze
its 8 million customer households and allow ``our sales force to
focus on the most profitable relationships and sales.'' The idea,
said Barrie Macdonald, senior vice president for retailing banking
at KeyCorp's Seattle-Bellevue district, is to move from being the
supplier of a single account to becoming ``the trusted adviser for
all of those (financial) products.''
</P>
<P>
   To make cross-selling work, banks will have to overcome several
obstacles. One is the reluctance on the part of customers to become
overly chummy with their banker or broker, particularly when it
comes to the details of their finances.
</P>
<P>
   Evan Hendricks, editor of The Privacy Times, a Washington, D.C.,
newsletter, said customers may not understand the amount of data
about them being shared by the various divisions of financial
conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's kind of an information arms race going on,'' he said.
That arms race can be expected to escalate as companies compile
files on customers not only from what they've already got but add
information from outside databases. Consumers _ and regulators _
are also likely to be unhappy about the sharing of sensitive health
information compiled by insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks said a national policy should require financial
companies to tell consumers why data are being collected and to
seek permission for those uses.
</P>
<P>
   Financial service companies say they are aware of the potential
objections. Oppenheimer said Washington Mutual's system is set up
so that if customers say they don't want solicitations, the account
can be flagged so it doesn't happen. The system also limits the
number of mailings a customer will get from the bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not overmail our customers,'' she said. ``We think
it's important from both the bank's and the customer's perspective
that you don't overuse that relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington Mutual also says it won't sell its customer lists.
``We're very protective of keeping customer confidentiality within
the bank,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The other potential stumbling block to cross-selling is the same
one that waylaid the financial supermarket _ customers may prefer
to shop on their own, particularly if they believe they can get
better deals by buying from more than one source.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal preference is to seek out each specific objective
from all available sources,'' Shorewood investor Patrick Haugen
said. He likens it to shopping for plants and gardening tools: The
local discount store may carry some along with the auto parts,
school supplies and clothing, but there's a far better selection at
the local nursery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same applies to all financial products,'' Haugen added.
``There is a `best' checking account, another `best' credit card,
another assortment of mutual funds that provide the mix I seek, and
another selection for stocks and a broker. It may be time-consuming
but that is how I would desire to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research has shown probably a quarter of customers are
disposed to buy all of their financial services from one source,''
said Bob Dickey, president of Safeco Corp., the Seattle-based
insurance and mutual fund company which says it isn't interested in
offering every type of financial product.
</P>
<P>
   But others in the financial services industry believe there are
plenty of customers who do like the convenience of one-stop
shopping, particularly if they trust the person they deal with
regularly or trust the brand name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people lead very busy lives juggling jobs and families.
It sure would be easier for them if they could depend on one source
to provide them with the financial services they would require,''
investor William Crotteau said.
</P>
<P>
   But Crotteau and other consumers are wary that ``insurance and
financial services are so very different that it would be difficult
for an organization to offer quality products and services under
one roof.'' Banking and investment services themselves are so
different, he added, that finding a company adept at both would
also be tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see one difficulty in having one-stop financial services
competing with those companies offering only one, and that is the
big guy gobbling up the small one,'' said investor Peggy Kramer of
Port Ludlow. ``I do believe in competition in the marketplace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
