<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-MORMONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAPTISTS MAKE FORAY INTO UTAH: MORMONS, VISITORS `AGREE TO
DISAGREE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ A much-ballyhooed Southern Baptist effort to
evangelize Mormons, which began over the weekend and is continuing
this week, has so far been a peaceful exchange of beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been some rough spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed to disagree, and we did it agreeably,'' said Rob
Lee, a Utah Baptist official who was one of more than 2,000
Southern Baptists who went door-to-door in this area, which is
believed to be more than 50 percent Mormon, during an evangelistic
blitz Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Baptists' Crossover Salt Lake City campaign
includes block parties, sports clinics and advertising through
billboards, radio and TV spots and newspaper ads. It will continue
on a smaller scale throughout the national Southern Baptist
Convention, which officially begins Tuesday and continues through
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 young people from the First Baptist Church of
Euless, Texas, participated in Crossover events or served as
greeters at the weekend Pastors Conference. The Rev. Claude Thomas,
First Baptist's pastor, is president of the Pastors Conference, one
of the Southern Baptists' pre-convention events.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Baptist videos and books about Mormons state that
the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints is a non-Christian
cult, the Mormons have generally have been amicable to the visiting
evangelists.
</P>
<P>
   Banners at the airport declared, ``Welcome Southern Baptist
Convention _ Exalting the Unchanging Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Mormons said they are perturbed that Baptists are
saying the Latter-day Saints are not Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are really Christian, you don't judge people,'' said
Tricia Larson, a longtime Mormon who was visited in her suburban
home below the snow-capped Wasatch Mountains by Baptists. ``Calling
us a cult and not Christian is not a Christian thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Larson's son, Scott, 16, said he was taken aback when one young
Baptist approached him while he was working at a downtown Salt Lake
City restaurant Saturday and gave him a comic book about Jesus
Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me that the comic book was the most important thing I
would ever read,'' Scott Larson said. ``He was a nice guy, but I'm
already a believer. So I thought he was kind of a nut case for
saying that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Chirban, 46, the Larsons' next-door neighbor, who is an
inactive member of the Greek Orthodox Church, said he was glad to
see the Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to see somebody come by besides Mormons,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another longtime Mormon, Don Uhlmer, 65, said he and the Baptist
evangelizers had a friendly dialogue. But he readily concedes that
the two faiths have a different view of Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jesus Christ we believe in is not the same one the
Baptists believe in,'' he said. ``And I guess we could say Baptists
aren't Christians because of that. But I don't think that's
productive.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who was one of the Baptists who visited the Larsons,
Chirbans and Ulmers, said Baptists don't want to be argumentative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just here to sell the love of Jesus Christ,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baptists reported scores of professions of faith during the
weekend blitz, including some by Mormons.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign by the nation's biggest Protestant denomination is
being carried out among some 1.6 million people who live in the
metropolitan area known as the Wasatch Front, extending along the
mountains from Ogden, Utah, on the north through Salt Lake City to
Provo. Surveys indicate that more than 50 percent of residents in
the area are Mormon.
</P>
<P>
   About 10,000 to 12,000 Baptists are expected to attend the
convention at the Salt Palace, just a few yards from the soaring
Mormon Temple, the symbolic center of 10 million Mormons.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Paige Patterson, who is expected to be elected
president of the Southern Baptists this week, said he had met with
two of the Mormon church's highest-ranking members, Neal A.
Maxwell, one of the 12 Mormon apostles, and James E. Faust, who
ranks just below Mormon president Gordon B. Hinkley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We differed on many things _ for instance, we don't believe we
can become gods as the Mormons do _ but our meeting was mostly
friendly. We talked about what we agree on, such as the need to
support families and fight pornography,'' said Patterson, who is
president of Southeastern Baptist Theological Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is releigion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
