A9062 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-JUDAISM-COX &UR;      06-08 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-JUDAISM-COX </SLUG>
    
 &HT;     LEADERS OF U.S. REFORM JEWS RETURN TO FIGHT ISRAELI PROPOSAL ON
CONVERSIONS
 &HT;     By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Standing behind police barricades at the holy site
of the Western Wall, American leaders in the less-traditional,
Reform branch of Judaism Monday opposed an Israeli proposal on
religious conversions that they say is an attempt to
``de-legitimize'' their faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a slap in the face to Diaspora Jewry,'' said Eric
Yoffie, president of the Union of American Hebrew Congregations
(UAHC).
</P>
<P>
   In an agreement with police, Yoffie's group held a short prayer
ceremony behind portable police railings far from the Western Wall,
one of Judaism's most holy places.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, men and women from the less traditional Reform and
Conservative branches of Judaism, even when far away on the plaza
facing the wall, have had things thrown at them by Orthodox Jews
who object to men and women praying together.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony went peacefully Monday, with only a few
disapproving Orthodox Jews even looking on at the Reform
worshipers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to be Jewish, you should be Jewish. Not 50-50,''
said Eliyakeem Gobay, a 23-year-old Orthodox Jew. ``Israel is
Jewish. It's not America.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoffie and more than 100 rabbis and members of Reform
congregations came to the Western Wall directly from the airport at
the start of a week-long attempt to dissuade Israeli leaders from
passing the so-called Conversion Law that is inflaming many
long-time Israel supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox advocates of the law seek to derail cases in Israel's
supreme court in which non-Jews, who converted to Reform and
Conservative Judaism, have sought to be recognized as Jewish by the
Israeli government's religious authorities.
</P>
<P>
   They have not been recognized by the country's religious affairs
ministry because of policies that only recognize conversions under
Orthodox Jewish rabbis, with much more strict adherence to Jewish
customs.
</P>
<P>
   Religious members in the coalition of Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu have threatened to bring down his government if
it does not elevate the current policies into national law _
roughly the current proposal.
</P>
<P>
   That would short-circuit the court cases and, according to many,
end efforts to loosen up the religious influence on the country's
laws governing conversions, weddings, funerals and just who is
considered Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox leaders have argued that the policies are needed to
make clear who is truly Jewish and to retain the Jewish nature of
Israel's culture and laws.
</P>
<P>
   Reform and Conservative leaders agreed to postpone the court
case in the winter in order to seek a compromise, but now the case
is resurfacing in the courts again. Most American Jews are either
Reform or Conservative and they have been outraged at what they
consider an Israeli snub.
</P>
<P>
   This group has meetings scheduled this week with Israeli
officials, including Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position will always be one for religious pluralism in
Israel,'' said Russell Silverman, of Coral Gables, Fla., who is
treasurer of the UAHC. ``There will be a groundswell of resentment
against the (Israeli) government if this passes.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Al Riesenburger, of Columbus, Ga., and member of the UAHC
board: ``They can't help but listen to us. We're here to let them
know we represent 900 congregations with more than a million
members.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
