<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VIEW FROM ABOVE CALLS FOR A PERFECT CALIFORNIA SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I took a daylong flight across Northern
California last week for a firsthand look at the land, lakes and
streams, a preview of the coming summer for camping, hiking,
boating and fishing.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing you notice is how there is still an overall look
of greenness to the foothills in the San Francisco Bay area, rare
for June. Then you can see how full the lakes are, all 75 of them
(including 25 that are off-limits to the public), with Lake
Berryessa east of Napa the most dramatic, huge and blue-green, with
silver trails from power boats streaking across the surface.
</P>
<P>
   We popped over the hills and toward the vast Central Valley, and
while the golden tint of summer is just now taking over here, there
are still countless pockets of water, ponds and flooded rice
fields, the latter green from fresh sprouts. I've never seen so
much wetland habitat in California, and I believe duck nesting
success will be among the best this spring and early summer in 50
years.
</P>
<P>
   I leveled the plane off at an altitude of 11,500 feet, set
cruise settings and trimmed for level flight, and charged toward
the Sierra at 185 mph. In the foothills near Grass Valley, looking
north, I could see 125 miles across the mountain ranges all the way
to Mount Shasta, and to the south, past the Sierra Buttes to the
peaks south of Lake Tahoe.
</P>
<P>
   I banked the plane, dropping the right wing, then slowly turned
to the east, scanning hundreds of miles of public recreation lands,
a piece of the 20 millions acres of national forest in the state.
Looking down across the mountain country, you can see why the
coming summer has the chance to be the best ever for outdoor
recreation in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   From Mount Whitney on past Tahoe all the way to Mount Shasta,
the snow line is roughly 7,000 to 7,200 feet on north-facing
slopes, 6,000 to 6,500 on south-facing slopes. Directly under snow
line, from 3,000 to 6,000 feet in the alpine zone, spring is just
arriving, with blooming dogwood and wildflowers, and ferns
unrolling like they're reaching for the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Week after week as summer advances and the snow line recedes
into higher country, it will unveil fresh, spring-like conditions,
perfect for camping, hiking, boating and fishing. This is a rare
treasure, the chance to experience spring over and over again as
the high country emerges from a colossal winter.
</P>
<P>
   By my calculations, for instance, you will have the chance to
see spring as late as August in the 10,000 to 12,500-foot country
north of Mount Whitney, in the John Muir and Golden Trout
wilderness areas.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in the Bay-area foothills, it is stunning to see how
full the lakes now are, one after another, everywhere you look ...
Union Valley, Englebright, Oroville, Bullards Bar, French Meadows
and beyond to the north of Bucks, Almanor, Eagle and Shasta. The
only lake that didn't appear full was Folsom Lake near Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   I checked later with Jeff McCracken at the Bureau of Reclamation
and he said space is being reserved for emergency storage, in case
of hot weather and a flood of snowmelt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at 96 percent capacity across Northern California right
now, and there's so much water entering the lakes that we could
fill everything to 100 percent overnight if we wanted to,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   California has 373 lakes you can drive to, 483 significant lakes
you can hike to, most all with campgrounds, and the forecast is for
all lakes to be full with water throughout summer. As water is
released from dams, it will be replaced at about the same rate by
water from melting snow.
</P>
<P>
   Looking down at Yosemite National Park, Half Dome dominates the
landscape. In the high country, Tuolumne Meadows at 8,000 feet has
about a foot of snow left, and it's going fast. But in shaded
canyons, such as Dana Meadow, there's still six feet.
</P>
<P>
   The air was lucky smooth, so I could cruise the plane up and
down canyons, often a source of lifting air and turbulence. From
the Sierra to the Central Valley, every stream in these canyons was
charging full, many pig-ugly brown from such high runoff, with the
Bear River the most off-color of all.
</P>
<P>
   California has 185 major streams, many with a dozen tributaries,
and almost everywhere you look, they are still running bank-to-bank
with high, cold water. While that has wiped out the trout season in
May, it means conditions will be great in July and even August
during the vacation season, a time when streams are typically
reduced to a warm trickle.
</P>
<P>
   In southern Plumas County, I turned a full 360-degree circle
over the Sierra Buttes, and looked down and saw that many of the
high-country wilderness lakes are still frozen, yet starting to
thin. Gold Lake near Graegle, for instance, had signs of thinning
ice near the outlet at the dam.
</P>
<P>
   I smiled as I looked down at nearby Mount Elwell, 7,812 feet
elevation, and the dozens of lakes at different stages of meltoff
in the surrounding Lakes Basin Recreation Area. Yeah, I thought, it
won't be long and it will be perfect here, and I dreamed of the
coming summer day when I'll be standing on that mountain top.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
