<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROOT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON: A FINE PLACE TO RAISE FUNDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ They love to beat up on Washington here in the
state capital. For that matter, they love to beat up on Washington
in Washington. But when it comes to raising money, there's no place
like the land of the gilded Beltway.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush and his Democratic challenger in the
gubernatorial race, Garry Mauro, both have Washington fund-raisers
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro's invitation touts a June 23 ``reception with President
Bill Clinton/Dinner with First Lady Hillary Clinton'' at the
Sheraton Carlton. The event also features players in the Clinton
White House's controversial fund-raising past.
</P>
<P>
   The consulting firm handling the invitation is Mercer and
Associates, a D.C. firm headed by David Mercer, former deputy
finance director at the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Mercer was once caught on an MSNBC hidden camera offering
big-time White House access for big-time bucks. A 1997 Los Angeles
Times piece said that ``the going price, according to Mercer, for a
seat next to then-White House aide George Stephanopoulos (was):
`100 to half a million.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And Erica Payne, the Mercer employee hired by the Mauro campaign
to handle the event, was identified in 1997 congressional testimony
as the aide who probably prepared a memo showing ``projected
revenue'' and money ``raised to date'' stemming from one of those
White House coffee gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   The coffee klatches led to accusations that Clinton used the
White House as a fund-raising tool.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro campaign manager Billy Rogers said that discussing Payne
and the White House fund-raising controversy in the same sentence
is below the belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erica has an excellent reputation. She's worked in Texas for
five years raising money for the Democratic Party,'' he said.
``These are good people.''
</P>
<P>
   Donors will shell out $5,000 for both the reception and dinner,
and $1,000 for the reception only.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bush is holding two fund-raisers June 18. Ticket
prices range from $500 a person for a reception at the Willard
Hotel to $10,000 a couple for dinner at the Four Seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The events rely heavily on deep connections to Bush's father.
Among those helping to organize the event are President George
Bush's White House counsel, C. Boyden Gray; his ex-spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater; and his erstwhile top campaign hand Fred Malek.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bush, who has a campaign war chest approaching $15
million from donors all over the country, said it's natural to
raise out-of-state money; he figures that non-Texas dough will end
up composing 15 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who live outside the state who
understand how important it is for the governor's office in Texas
to be held by a fellow like me,'' Bush said. They may also be
thinking that now is a good time to get in good with a potential
presidential contender.
</P>
<P>
   Bush added that it ``should not surprise you that mutual friends
of mine and my dad's are supporting me. The best kind of support to
have is from friends. They don't have unusual expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jay Root is chief of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram's Austin
bureau. Visit him at jroot(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
