<HEADER>
A9113 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAHLER-POPULARITY-HNS     06-08 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAHLER-POPULARITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECADES AFTER HIS DEATH, MAHLER RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALLAN ULRICH  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If Gustav Mahler had not come along to give
artistic utterance to our contemporary dilemmas, we might have been
forced to invent him.
</P>
<P>
   What other composer so mirrors the anxieties of a world he left
87 years ago? What other musician so eloquently reflects the doubt
and despair of a planet on the brink of the millennium?
</P>
<P>
   Since Mahler's death we've experienced two world wars, the
threat of nuclear annihilation, the advent of Freudian psychology
and other scientific theories that have nibbled away at our notion
of free will. In that time, the composer's popularity has soared.
His was music once deemed protracted, difficult, neurotic and not
quite healthy, in keeping with the expressionist fervor sweeping
the arts at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the last 35 years have witnessed among American orchestras
a frequency of performances of Mahler symphonies and song cycles
that makes the previous 50 years' treatment seem inconsequential.
Record companies now produce Mahler symphony cycles the way they
used to dash off Beethoven Fifths; the current Opus catalog lists
41 performances of Mahler's Symphony No. 2 alone, and that is not
an easy project to assemble.
</P>
<P>
   The Symphony No. 5 was once an event. In 1998, it is not
uncommon to find it programmed in the same community four or five
times a season, by different orchestras _ as much as, if not more
than, Beethoven's ``Eroica.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the San Francisco Symphony and its music director, Michael
Tilson Thomas, will not risk alienating the paying customers when
they launch their 17-day Mahler Celebration Thursday in Davies
Symphony Hall. One is hard-pressed to name another composer who
evokes a greater response in the conductor.
</P>
<P>
   Why audiences have fallen under the spell, despite Mahler's
often mammoth structures, his dense counterpoint and his allusions
to obscurities of Teutonic folklore, is simple. People love Mahler
because he is ``about something'' and his music ``goes somewhere.''
His symphonies trace an arc that always, even in the gentle Fourth
Symphony, flirts with Armageddon.
</P>
<P>
   Resolution means either cataclysmic breakdown (in the Sixth
Symphony) or fusion with a vast humanist organism (the Eighth) or
abnegation (the Ninth) or ironic, even hysterical triumph (the
Fifth and Seventh). The search for secular spirituality _ for
communion with an enigmatic universe _ is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, we love Mahler too much. Perhaps, we have made of him
an auditory mood ring. Perhaps, we have imposed the values of our
own age upon him to the extent of altering the shape of the music.
The contemporary emphasis on ``feelings'' _ ours, rather than the
composer's _ may have pushed us, listeners as well as interpreters,
to sentimentalize and inflate Mahler, sometimes to the point of
fulsomeness.
</P>
<P>
   It seems peculiar to discuss authentic performance practice in
connection with a composer who has been dead less than a century.
But Mahler's leading champions among conductors, Bruno Walter and
Willem Mengelberg, both left us ample evidence about how their
mentor wanted his music to go.
</P>
<P>
   Consider one movement (the most famous in Mahler, thanks, in
part, to countless bad ballets that have used the music) _ the
fourth movement, Adagietto, from the Symphony No. 5, which Tilson
Thomas conducts Friday and Saturday and repeats next season.
Mengelberg's 1929 recording, the music's disc debut, runs 7:04
minutes. Walter, in his 1947 recording of the entire symphony, does
it in 7:35 minutes. Since then, conductors have stretched the
Adagietto like warm taffy. Leonard Bernstein, in his 1987 reading
with the Vienna Philharmonic, jumps to an astonishing 11:13
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1973, Herbert von Karajan, in a remarkable act of
self-communing bravura, elongated the movement to 11:53 minutes,
proof of the Berlin Philharmonic's capacity for sustaining lengthy
phrases but a subversion of the symphony's architecture.
</P>
<P>
   It is Gilbert Kaplan, the renowned Mahler fan and auto-didact
conductor, who comes closest to that first generation of
Mahlerians, dispatching the Adagietto in 7:53 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Now we know that performances of most Romantic music have slowed
down in the past century; and while audiences would likely reject
such distentions in Beethoven, they seem not to object in Mahler.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Americans, I believe, can trace their permissive attitude to
Bernstein. For many, he remains the most ubiquitous and eloquent,
if not the most consistently persuasive, Mahlerian of the past 35
years. And he has contributed substantially to our perception of
the composer. Thus, in the context of a Mahler celebration, Tilson
Thomas' June 19 tribute to Bernstein, in his 80th anniversary year,
seems entirely appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   But this country boasted an active Mahler performance tradition
before Bernstein. It was Eugene Ormandy who made the first
electrical recording of the Symphony No. 2 with the Minneapolis
Symphony, in a live performance in 1935 (it's on a Biddulph compact
disc). The same orchestra premiered the Symphony No. 1 on record in
1940 under Dimitri Mitropoulos (Sony Masterworks recently reissued
the performance on CD in its Heritage series).
</P>
<P>
   Mitropoulos, who was Bernstein's predecessor at the New York
Philharmonic, included six of Mahler's completed symphonies on his
subscription programs; four (and two others) are collected in a
fascinating new set on Music &AMP; Arts, an outstanding addition to the
Mahler discography. Mitropoulos' febrile approach was not lost on
Bernstein. And Tilson Thomas extends that lineage.
</P>
<P>
   In the American Mahler tradition, it would seem, personality
sometimes prevails over discretion. We want this musician served up
without inhibition. That can be annoying and understandable, too.
Of all the major symphonists of the 20th century, Mahler is the one
about whom it is the most difficult to remain objective.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1432EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
