A9115 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-HNS &LR;      06-08 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE IS A LESSON IN INDIAN AND PAKISTANI NUCLEAR MOVES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The wild scenes of popular jubilation we all saw on our
TV screens after India and Pakistan exploded their first nuclear
devices were a strong reminder that the voice of the people can
sometimes be as ugly as that of their rulers.
</P>
<P>
   Being nuclear powers will certainly prove to be an economic
calamity for both countries and could turn into a human catastrophe
as well. The vast numbers of their poor will be the worst affected.
Already there are signs that the huge cost of developing nuclear
arsenals will make life materially harder for hundreds of millions
who even now exist at subsistence level.
</P>
<P>
   But these same impoverished Pakistanis and Indians cheered
loudest when the nuclear explosions were revealed. Both governments
counted on overwhelming domestic approval, and they were right. As
we know, for politicians it's domestic favor, not international
condemnation, that really matters.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and the American Congress can denounce the New
Delhi and Islamabad regimes as much as they wish and carry out
their threat to cancel much-needed economic assistance. Such
actions will make not a jot of difference.
</P>
<P>
   India is often referred to as the world's largest democracy, but
as Winston Churchill once noted, democracy is a poor political
system except, of course, for all the others.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan also has an elected government. In both cases, almost
no one uttered a word of dissent against the testing initially.
Opposition leaders rushed to endorse the decision.
</P>
<P>
   A political cliche of our era is that democracies don't
instigate wars. Former British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher has
said that the spread of democracy around the world fundamentally
enhanced the prospects for permanent peace. Thatcher is a wise
person, but she could be proved wrong on the Indian subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1950s and '60s, India's leaders posed as the world's
moral guides, laying down strictures especially to the United
States and the rest of the supposedly depraved and power-lusting
West. Some gullible American liberals fell for the Indian line.
What they overlooked was that India itself had already engaged in
naked aggression by seizing much of the rich state of Kashmir
before the subcontinent was finally partitioned between newly
independent India and Pakistan in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   In a free vote, Kashmir would have joined Pakistan, but the
self-righteous Indians wouldn't allow it. So for 50 years the two
countries have engaged in both hot and cold wars over the contested
territory. Analysts have pointed out that Kashmir is at the root of
both governments' decision to go nuclear.
</P>
<P>
   However, something more is involved. Becoming nuclear powers has
fed their sense of national pride and self-esteem. It's clear that
India's professed moral superiority to the West was good only as
long as New Delhi lacked the technology and resources to build the
bomb. After that, morality became irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't bode well for the future. Other Third World
countries also see a nuclear arsenal as the hallmark of national
greatness. They won't wait long to join India and Pakistan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
