<P>
   SCI-PLANT-INVASION (Undated) _ Invasive, non-native plants are
out of control in many on the nation's fields, forests, marshes,
stream sides and waterways. The ubiquitous invaders with roots,
leaves, shoots and seeds are running roughshod over native plants,
changing the quality of the soil, water and landscape and wiping
out countless creatures _ from microorganisms to mammals _ that
cannot withstand the onslaught. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SOLAR-NEUTRINOS (Undated) _ Just as the neutrino conference
in Japan seemed to clear up one mystery, it raised another: The
same team claiming the existence of neutrino mass may have also
cast doubt on the most elegant version of the changing-flavor
hypothesis, in favor of an alternative that many theorists find
ugly and contrived. The dispute is far from resolved. Gathering and
interpreting data about these particles is among the most delicate
and frustrating challenges of physics. For all the excitement over
last week's breakthrough, it may still be years before anyone knows
what's going on with the sun.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASIA-SCIENCE (Undated) _ Despite the contrast between the
carefully tended icons of the Japanese town of Hida (which bespeak
ancient religious mysticism) and the cutting-edge research on
neutrinos that was unveiled nearby during the past week, many Asian
scientists view the two worlds as complementary rather than
conflicting. ``We say that Buddhist tradition makes it easier for
us to grasp the dualities and transformations of particle
physics,'' said one of the Japanese scientists. An essay by Malcolm
Browne.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MISCONDUCT (Undated) _ Citing a string of recent cases, the
British Medical Journal says that scientific misconduct is a bigger
problem than scientists are willing to admit and that they have
often failed to adequately police their colleagues. By Lawrence K.
Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SEX-SMELL (Undated) _ When it comes to love, sex and
friendship, do birds of a feather flock together? Or is it more
important that opposites attract? The argument is so old that even
Aristotle mentioned evidence for both sides. Recently, a new
chapter has been opened by researchers who say that for at least
one type of gene people find difference sexy and sameness boring _
and that they use their noses to tell which is which.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEART-DRUG (Undated) _ The heart drug Posicor has been
withdrawn from the market because of dangerous interactions with
other drugs. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-IMMUNE-THEORY (Undated) _ Dr. Polly Matzinger, 50, a tenured
medical researcher at the National Institutes for Health, is
turning the world of immunology upside down with her radical theory
suggesting the human immune system is activated not by alien
substances in the body, but rather by dangerous ones _ her ``Danger
Theory'' of immunology. She explains her theories in Q&AMP;A.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
