<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9199 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      06-08 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD WE SELL OLD HOME OR RENT IT OUT?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 40 and my husband is 43 and we have three young
children. We hope to purchase a single-family home in the next
year. We own a condominium with a mortgage principal of $57,000 and
a market value of about $85,000. We intend to purchase a $200,000
house, and have saved $40,000 for a down payment. Here's our
dilemma: Should we sell the condominium and use the additional
money to reduce the size of the mortgage on our new house, or
should we keep it and rent it out?
</P>
<P>
   C.O., Bethlehem, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I can't give you an answer, but I can ask a lot of questions
back, and your answers should lead you to a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, how financially stable are you? Do you have a lot
of job security, and ample savings beyond the money set aside for
the new house to tide you over unexpected bumps?
</P>
<P>
   If there's doubt on either score, I'd favor selling the condo.
</P>
<P>
   Second, draw up a financial projection sheet showing best-case
and worst-worst case results of a rental.
</P>
<P>
   In the best case, you would begin with the expected income from
a full year's rental, and then subtract from that the cost of your
mortgage payments on the condo, the taxes on the condo, the cost of
your insurance for the property, and the fee levied by the condo's
management entity. To the resulting figure you can add the positive
effect that renting the condo would have on your tax liabilities
(remember, since it has become a rental property, you can now
depreciate its value). To the resulting figure add the increased
equity in the property you would achieve through the year's
mortgage payments. If that number isn't positive, abandon the
exercise right now _ and sell.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose the number is positive. Then consider the effects of
selling. Suppose you did achieve that $85,000 asking price (and
remember that most people tend to overestimate the value of their
homes). If you pay a 6 percent commission to a real estate agent,
that would reduce your net to $79,900, and after you paid off the
mortgage that would leave you $22,900 to add to your down payment
on the new home. If you got a 7 percent mortgage on your new home,
the addition of $22,900 to the down payment would reduce your
mortgage cost by $1,603 a year. How does that number compare to the
benefit you would realize by renting the condo? If the benefit is
equal to or less than $1,603, I suggest selling _ because you
should remember that the figures we worked out were a best-world
scenario.
</P>
<P>
   (An additional factor you might consider here is that if you
made a 31-percent-plus down payment on the mortgage on the new
house, you would probably get a better interest rate than if the
down payment was only 20 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   Now let's look at the downside. What would happen if there were
a significant increase in taxes, insurance costs, and/or condo
maintenance fees? What would happen if a major maintenance project
were dictated for the entire condo project, resulting in an
unexpected levy on you? What would happen if your particular condo
required significant maintenance expenses? And most important, what
would the numbers look like if the condo were vacant for a couple
of months a year (or if you had the poor luck to rent to deadbeat
tenants)? To work out a bad-case financial projection, you might
work the numbers with a projection of nine months rent rather than
twelve. To work out a still-worse-case projection, look at where
you'd be if you collected only six months' rent in the course of a
year. I'll bet these numbers are getting pretty ugly.
</P>
<P>
   It probably boils down to this: Do you feel the local rental
market is strong? Do you know the community well enough to feel
confident you can find a good tenant? Do you feel that the local
tax structure is likely to be stable? Do you think significant
increases in maintenance costs and/or condo management fees are
unlikely? Do you have sufficient financial reserves to deal with
unexpected problems? Finally, did the financial benefit of renting
very significantly exceeds the benefit of making a larger down
payment on your new home? If you came up with six yesses here, then
maybe renting is a good idea. My guess, though, is that for most
people the answer would be no.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 45-year-old single woman and I sold my condo this
spring, hoping to purchase a single-family home. I didn't find what
I was looking for in time, so I am now renting, with a lease ending
next May 1. The proceeds from the sale were $62,000, which I now
have in a savings account with a 4.76 percent annual rate. I need
to keep $10,000 in this account, which entitles me to avoid bank
service fees, but I would like to do better with the other money,
while still enjoying quick access in case I find the property I
want. I have considered a six-month CD, which would pay at a 5.75
percent annual rate. Do you have any other suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   M.G., Winchester
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, there are a couple of things you might do to get a
slightly better rate. You could shop around for a slightly better
CD rate; entering this week the nation's best rate for 6- month CDs
was 5.99 percent at First National Bank and Trust Co. of Minnesota.
Or you could scan the money market funds for those with the best
yields, and some of them currently are in excess of 5.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But you might also consider that over the next six months the
dollar difference between a money market fund that might yield 5.5
percent and a 5.75 percent CD would work out to $65, and that
tactic would involve moving the money twice, once to the CD and
then into a money market fund (or back to the bank) as the time for
your projected home purchase gets closer. I think if it were me,
I'd simply bung it into one of the better-yielding money market
funds right away and forget about it, diverting your energies
instead to the search for the perfect home. When you are dealing
with the short-term investment of a relatively small amount of
money, chasing a few extra basis points of return (a basis point is
one one-hundredths of a percentage point of yield) usually isn't
worth the trouble.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My 79 1/2-year-old mother has $425,000 in six different CDs
with maturity dates ranging from 9 months to 3 years. She receives
approximately $1,100 a month in Social Security. Her checking
account always has at least $2,000 in it, and she keeps $5,000 to
$8,000 in a money market account. She is in good health and travels
some, and feels comfortable with CDs because she understands them.
I set up her finances after my father passed away. Is this too
conservative? My brothers think I should be more aggressive with
her money. I think not. What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   R.K., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think that much more important than what you think and what
your brothers think is what your mother thinks. If she is
comfortable with CDs because she understands them, and would not be
comfortable with more aggressive investments either because she
doesn't understand them or _ more likely _ because she understands
enough to know that better returns mean a level of risk that would
upset her, you should honor her wishes. Suppose you directed the
lot into GNMA funds, which are a favorite of many retired people;
you might achieve a yield of 6.5 percent, or $27,625 a year. How
does that compare to the portfolio yield on the CDs? If the average
is 6 percent, the difference works out to $2,125 a year. Your
mother may well figure it's worth $2,125 a year not to have to
worry about the vagaries of the bond markets. Her opinion and
comfort should dictate the policy, from my point of view.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there are two things you might think about. If all of
the CDs are in a single institution, you should spread them out as
they mature so that no account exceeds the FDIC insurance limit for
the bank. I know, worries about banks have been almost nonexistent
for a number of years, but I still feel this conservative
precaution is worth taking. Second, if the ``money market account''
in which she maintains a $5,000 to $8,000 balance is a bank money
market account, you might urge her to move this to a mutual fund
money market account. Entering this week, the nation's average
yield for bank money market accounts was 2.52 percent; most money
market mutual funds have yield in excess of twice that. She would
be allowed the same quick access to her funds as with a bank,
(through check writing privileges) and the additional level of risk
between an insured bank money market account and an uninsured
mutual fund money market is, in my opinion, so small as to be
negligible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker will answer selected investors' questions in the
Sunday Mutual funds and Monday Money sections. Send letters,
including your name, address and telephone number, to: Kenneth
Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
