<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9217 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEMPLE-ESSAY-1500(2Ta     06-08 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEMPLE-ESSAY-1500(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HOUSE BY PENNY SEMPLE'S GARDEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETSY SEMPLE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My mother had news from her workplace in October, and she wanted
to share it with me. Her boss, she told me, will dedicate a Habitat
for Humanity house in her honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did you say?'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried, of course,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   When she relayed that story, I almost cried myself.
</P>
<P>
   And so on a brilliantly sunny March day _ the kind where the
gentle breeze had already swept the clouds from the sky _ I
couldn't help but shed tears when brand-new homeowner Sheryl
Holliday rounded up my family and unveiled a sign in her front yard
that said, ``The Garden of Penny Semple.''
</P>
<P>
   With all that Sheryl had felt had been given to her by the
Habitat for Humanity workers and volunteers, she wanted to give
something back.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   I've always wanted to do volunteer work for Habitat. I thought
its mission was noble, and I liked the fact that you could actually
see the results of your time and effort.
</P>
<P>
   Although volunteering for Habitat was always on my ``to-do''
list, work and home commitments always preceded it.
</P>
<P>
   When my mom told me her news about the Habitat dedication, I
knew I had to work on that house. It was a way for me to honor the
woman who had loved me and taken care of me for my entire life. I
had to be a part of any project with her name on it.
</P>
<P>
   My mom's involvement with the Consumer Action Center (CAC) and
with Habitat began with her admiration of Atlanta radio and
television personality Clark Howard. His radio show, TV segments
and books primarily cover consumer advocacy and protection issues.
Clark had also provided funding for two Habitat houses; two more
were to be built in February. My mom liked what Clark had to say;
it was an unusual conversation when my mom didn't have a tidbit of
information from one of his shows.
</P>
<P>
   As a person always ready to roll up her sleeves and help others
hash out their problems, it was a natural progression for my mom to
begin volunteering for the CAC through Howard's WSB-AM radio
station soon after my brother _ her youngest _ left home for
college. From there she was promoted to day supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   My mother's health was progressively getting worse during the
fall of last year, but that was something I noticed only in
hindsight. She had stopped working at the CAC and was eating less.
We all thought it was just a phase she was going through _ we just
needed to give her a pep talk and a jump start _ but she was
admitted into the hospital the Friday after Thanksgiving for
dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   For four days she was stable, but on the first Wednesday of
December, my father called me and asked me to come home. My mother
died after sunrise Saturday morning with those she loved and those
who loved her with her.
</P>
<P>
   After my mom battled for five years, a rare form of cancer took
her from us.
</P>
<P>
   Now the house would be dedicated to her memory. Working on this
house was a way to keep speaking her name, a way to bring our
family together from the Northeast, the Pacific Northwest, Texas
and the South, a way to again see her friends from the CAC.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   A Habitat house takes seven days to build. ``Our'' house took 6
1/2 days. When I arrived on Friday, March 13, the house was in fine
shape: roof shingled, windows and bathtub installed, porch and
stairways erected.
</P>
<P>
   I figured that any work I would do would only be details,
somewhat insignificant. I was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   On that first day _ a cold Georgia morning _ I had opted to help
create the front yard. Flowers, shrubs and tree landscaping were
important to my mother, and it was appropriate work for me to do.
</P>
<P>
   It felt good to do manual labor as a change of pace. I spend
most of my workdays navigating on a computer and thinking my way
through problems and challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Habitat volunteers walk in prepared to work and prepared to
sweat; there is no ego. As the volunteers working on the yard
formed a chain and passed fragrant rectangles of sod to one
another, I realized that I was working beside a former Georgia
gubernatorial candidate as well as Clark Howard himself.
</P>
<P>
   Later, while I was trimming sod with a carpet knife, I paused to
look up at the sky. I took a long breath as I scanned the expanse
from left to right. I returned my gaze to straight above me, smiled
and quietly said, ``Love you, Mom.'' I dropped my head and returned
to work.
</P>
<P>
   I later told a fellow volunteer _ one who knew my mom _ that she
was probably having a laugh at my doing all this yard work,
something she could rarely get me to do during my teen-age years.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   After laying sod, I spent the rest of my day working alongside
my sister; she had been dubbed the ``Caulk Queen'' by our Habitat
house leader, and I was recruited to help her seal the outside and
inside of the windows and along the interior baseboards of the
house.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was younger sister leading older sister as she
showed me how to properly perform the task, praising my work along
the way and sharing stories of Sheryl and her family, who would be
moving into this house.
</P>
<P>
   Before the day had ended, I was fatigued; I wasn't physically
prepared to volunteer for Habitat, but my mental and emotional
stamina was there.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's workday began at 8 a.m. My brother had arrived from
college in Alabama, and for every 20 minutes of work I did, I spent
five seeing what he was doing. In almost every part of the house,
inside and out, there was a Semple (or a Friend of a Semple)
present.
</P>
<P>
   We finished the house about 11:45 a.m. and rested on the newly
laid grass, waiting for the dedications to begin.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl's house sits next door to Evelyn's house. The two women
met at a Habitat function and struck up a friendship. Potential
Habitat homeowners must complete 150 hours of ``sweat equity''
building houses, both others' and their own. When the time came for
their houses to be built, Sheryl and Evelyn requested that they be
built side by side.
</P>
<P>
   On that final Saturday, Evelyn's house was dedicated first. A
local quilting group presented Evelyn with three quilts; a
queen-size quilt for the mom and full-size quilts for each of her
children. A reading advocacy group called Jack &AMP; Jill presented the
children with a bookshelf decorated by children and new books to
place on it.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn's minister spoke; a Habitat board member spoke and
presented her with a Bible; and Evelyn's house team leader, Larry,
stepped forward to present Evelyn with her house keys _ except he'd
misplaced them. Instead, he offered his car keys; we applauded.
</P>
<P>
   And then it was Sheryl's turn. As Sheryl, her daughter, mother
and fiance and Clark arranged themselves on the front porch, Clark
hollered: ``Will the Semple family gather on the porch?''
</P>
<P>
   My dad turned around and with a sweeping hand motion said,
``Let's go.''
</P>
<P>
   I kept my gaze toward the sod as I walked to the porch; I was
already fighting back tears and didn't want anyone to see me crying
so soon into the dedication.
</P>
<P>
   Clark spoke first, introducing my family and telling the crowd
how the house was dedicated in honor of the CAC volunteers and in
memory of my mother _ a woman, Clark said, who ``was someone very
important to me ... she had a courage I didn't possess.''
</P>
<P>
   I could hear my sister softly crying beside me. The dedication
continued, with Sheryl and her family receiving their quilts, Bible
and bookshelf. Then Clark called the CAC volunteers who were
present to come to the porch to receive a plaque.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who was one of my mom's closest friends at the CAC
handed my father a wrapped package. As he opened it, Beverly said,
``And there's Penny in the background.''
</P>
<P>
   I craned my neck to see what he was holding. It was a photograph
of him from the first Habitat weekend, standing on a ladder,
smiling and looking down at the camera. In the background is the
sky, moon and clouds _ and heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Sheryl was handed the keys to her house, she said,
``I need all the family to come with me.'' She led us to the
largest landscaped area in the front yard, just off the front
porch. Sheryl continued: ``I was so excited to know the dedication
of the memory of your wife, Penny Semple. There was something I
felt I needed to do out of love.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her fiance, Marty Thurman, gingerly stepped between the
flowers and shrubs, kneeled at the porch and pulled away trash bags
that concealed a sign. When they were done, they stepped away as
the group began to murmur. The sign read, ``The Garden of Penny
Semple.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl continued, ``As I build my garden, and as the flower bed
comes out, this is in remembrance of Penny.''
</P>
<P>
   My dad wasn't shy about his tears, nor were any of us, at that
point. He embraced Sheryl and then Marty. My grandmother clutched
Sheryl, and then it was my turn to hug her. I simply said,
``Sheryl, you're awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl and her family returned to the porch to receive their
keys from team leader Mark Butler. He had brought something extra
for them: a loaf of bread, ``so this family will never know
hunger''; salt, ``so they always know the spice of life''; and
sparkling grape juice, ``so this family knows joy and laughter of
life.'' With tears, he handed Sheryl her keys, and they embraced.
The house was finally hers.
</P>
<P>
   What followed was a conglomeration of sounds and sights: five
tables groaning under the weight of barbecue and all the trimmings,
children darting in and out of food lines, shrieks of ``One more
picture ... now look here ... where's my camera? I want a picture
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   I dutifully posed for photograph after photograph, still not
quite believing it was all over. As I took this scene in, I felt
detached. Here I was, the oldest daughter of this woman who'd had a
house dedicated to her memory, and I felt like an outsider.
</P>
<P>
   Although all these people around me knew where they were going,
I didn't have that luxury. Now that this house was built, what was
I to do?
</P>
<P>
   After lunch and dessert, people slowly made their way toward
restocking the trailers with work equipment. Volunteers and guests
exchanged hugs and goodbyes and milled toward their cars.
</P>
<P>
   I got my day's ``pay'' _ a Habitat T-shirt _ and went to say
goodbye to Sheryl. I told her I'd help her weed her garden the next
time I was in town.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
