<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9230 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-GAYS-BOS &LR;      06-08 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSY MAY FOLLOW THIS LOOK AT GAY HISTORY OF BOSTON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IMPROPER BOSTONIANS &QC; 
Lesbian and Gay History from the Puritans to Playland &QC; 
Compiled by the History Project &QC; 
Beacon Press, 212 pp., illustrated, $30 &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A richly illustrated history of lesbians and gay men, ``Improper
Bostonians'' may court as much controversy as the traveling exhibit
from which it evolved. When the History Project first mounted
``Public Faces/ &QC; 
Private Lives: Boston's Lesbian and Gay History'' at the Boston
Public Library in June 1996, detractors accused its members of
everything from outing notable personalities to historical
fabrication.
</P>
<P>
   Since few American cities revel in their history as much as
Boston does _ the city gave the early History Project its initial
funding in 1980 _ such denouncements seemed narrow-minded, even
homophobic. Perhaps in anticipation of critics, Representative
Barney Frank, who wrote its foreword, affirms the book's necessity
and scolds those who see it as yet another backbreaking bow to
political correctness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, it is reasonable to argue that the fact of
someone's homosexuality should be ignored by his or her biographers
only if one is prepared to argue that no other basic facts of the
private lives of prominent people should be recounted,'' Frank
writes. Further, he states, ``people who complain that they are
being told more than they want to know about the private lives of
lesbians, gay men, and bisexuals are, often without realizing it,
not only objecting to honesty but arguing in favor of outright
deception.''
</P>
<P>
   Those topics addressed, the History Project _ a Boston-based
group of archivists, writers, and activists dedicated to preserving
gay history _ presents an informative, engaging chronicle of
lesbians and gay men in and around the city, from ``Boston
marriages'' to butch balls, from Emily Dickinson to drag queen
Sylvia Sidney, the self-proclaimed ``Mess in a Dress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Improper Bostonians'' begins with the Puritan colonists. In
creating a new community, the Puritans turned to biblical teaching
to establish a social order. Homosexuality was implicitly outlawed
through laws forbidding sodomy, since it undermined the religious
notion that sexual relations were permissible solely for the
purpose of procreation. The earliest anti-sodomy laws made it a
crime punishable by death, though only two people were executed in
the New England Colonies.
</P>
<P>
   An early supporter of the sodomy statute was John Winthrop, the
first governor of the Massachusetts Bay Colony. After one
execution, Winthrop referred to the condemned as ``a monster in
human shape'' who indulged in ``unclean practices.'' Yet Winthrop
himself may have shared a passionate relationship with Sir William
Springe, a longtime friend. In 1646, Winthrop wrote to Springe, ``I
loved you truely (sic) before I could think that you took any
notice of me; but now I embrace you and rest in your love: and
delight to solace my first thoughts in these sweet affections of so
dear a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Winthrop was likely involved in a ``masculine friendship,''
which allowed two men to profess their mutual love so long as it
was not considered in defiance of anti-sodomy laws. It was somewhat
easier for women to develop close, passionate relationships without
inviting suspicion. By the 19th century, some women of independent
means lived as couples in ``Boston marriages,'' a term popularized
in Henry James's 1886 novel ``The Bostonians.'' James's sister,
Alice, had a long-term relationship with Katharine Peabody Loring
that was one model of the ``Boston marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't to say homosexuality was widely accepted. By the end
of the century, medical authorities were declaring same-sex
attractions ``deviant.'' Still, lesbians and gay men were
developing a vibrant, albeit underground, culture. By the 1920s, a
majority of Americans resided in cities, and gay people found
sanctuary in cafes, hotels, speak-easies, and bathhouses.
Especially popular were several bars, such as the Crawford House
and Half Dollar, dotting Scollay Square and the downtown Washington
Street area, then known as ``Gay Times Square.'' (Playland, a
gloriously tawdry dive open since 1938, still thrives as a remnant
from that era.) Of course, all the establishments were well-kept
community secrets, since the police and self-appointed authorities,
such as the New England Watch and Ward Society, kept constant vigil
for behavior considered criminal.
</P>
<P>
   In covering so extensive a period _ 300-plus years in 212 pages
_ some eras, especially the post-Stonewall years, are given short
shrift. Where, for instance, are the Hat Sisters, Buffy Dunker, or
the Reverend Peter J. Gomes? The book pretty much ends with the
election of openly gay Elaine Noble to the Massachusetts
Legislature in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   But that's a minor quibble; this is more coffee-table book than
encyclopedia, and far more enjoyable for it. The history presented
is well balanced between men and women, and people of color _
including sculptor Edmonia Lewis and writer Angelina Weld Grimke _
are also featured, a rarity in books on lesbian and gay history.
But, then, this is a rare book in many ways, both entertaining and
educational, as it uncovers a welcome slice of this city's
long-hidden, but no less worthwhile, history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
