<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-CENTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY FELLOWSHIP: NEW FACILITIES TO ACCOMMODATE MEETINGS IN HOUSTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLIFFORD PUGH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ For years, Houston has been about the only major U.S.
city without a community center where gays and lesbians can gather
to discuss issues or hold a potluck dinner in a safe and homey
environment.
</P>
<P>
   But that's recently changed with the opening of two new
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Lesbian and Gay Community Center opened recently in
an artsy section of the city known as the Montrose area. The
3,300-square foot house has meeting rooms, a large kitchen and
several bulletin boards that list upcoming events and roommate
searches.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Gay and Lesbian Political Caucus has moved into
offices upstairs and other community groups are expected to occupy
space in the building, said Carl Riedl, the center's president.
</P>
<P>
   There are also plans to add a library, a ``cyber room'' with
computers, and monthly exhibitions of artwork and exhibits, such as
a salute to Lesbian and Gay Pride Week later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want this to become a showcase of our history and what's
going on in the community,'' Riedl said.
</P>
<P>
   So what took so long?
</P>
<P>
   The oil bust, the AIDS crisis, and an atmosphere of fear and
distrust that existed after Houston voters rejected an ordinance to
protect gay and lesbian city workers from discrimination in 1984
are among the reasons cited for the lack of such a center before
now.
</P>
<P>
   The independent nature of Houstonians also worked against
previous efforts, some observers believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston is a more make-it-on-your-own kind of place,'' said
Alan Cranfill, executive director of the Hollyfield Foundation,
which also is opening new meeting spaces for gay and lesbian
community-based organizations. ``People don't seem to collaborate
as much. But in the last two years I've seen (it change). It's
finally coming around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hollyfield Conference Center, which opened Sunday in the
Montrose area, offers more than 3,000-square feet of meeting space
in an historic Italianate villa.
</P>
<P>
   The conference facilities will be available for rental to the
public at rates ranging from $80 to $500 and to gay and lesbian
community-based organizations at a reduced rate. There are also
three offices that will be rented to community groups.
</P>
<P>
   Houston real estate figure Jay Hollyfield, who died of
AIDS-related complications in 1994, endowed the Hollyfield
Foundation and requested his assets support equal rights for gays
and lesbians and those affected by AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation distributed $48,000 in grants last year to
organizations committed to such goals.
</P>
<P>
   Cranfill said the foundation surveyed community-based nonprofit
organizations and found the lack of meeting space a problem in
Houston. He envisions the center will be used for fund-raisers,
educational forums and board retreats.
</P>
<P>
   He sees the Hollyfield Conference Center as a complement to the
Houston Lesbian and Gay Community Center, not competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so few places for gays and lesbians to meet besides
people's homes. It's a positive thing that we're both available,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Riedl agrees that the centers can complement each other. He
points out that the Lesbian and Gay Community Center will function
as a clearinghouse for information and referral services.
</P>
<P>
   The Lesbian and Gay Community Center is open on Mondays and
Wednesdays from 6 p.m. to 9 p.m. and on Saturdays from noon to 4
p.m. It plans to extend its hours as soon as more volunteers are
found and trained.
</P>
<P>
   The center is privately financed by donations, grants and rents
from organizations using meeting rooms. Such fees are flexible
depending on a group's ability to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want this to be a seeding group for organizations to
develop,'' Riedl said.
</P>
<P>
   Such non-gay groups as the Houston chapter of the National
Organization for Women also plan to use the space for monthly
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Riedl is convinced the timing is right for the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gay and lesbian community is very much a reflection of the
community it's in,'' he said. ``We've seen Houston energized
lately. The economy is better, and we have progressive leadership.
We're really seeing that diversity is good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
