<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIE BETWEEN WEDDING COST, DIVORCE RATE NEEDS INVESTIGATION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Has anybody looked into the relationship between wedding
inflation and the divorce rate? The average wedding in the United
States costs $17,634, according to Modern Bride Research. That
figure probably factors in Las Vegas wedding-chapel weddings and
other cut-rate nuptials, which means that the average ``real''
wedding probably costs even more. And things are getting
increasingly elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, accepting a wedding invitation involved a one-day
commitment, maybe an overnight, if you had to travel any distance.
As a mere guest you were expected to show up for the ceremony and
the reception, after which you were free to drive home and talk
about what an awful time you'd had, speculate about how much it all
cost, and lay odds on how long the marriage would last.
</P>
<P>
   Now some couples want their wedding celebrations to go on for
three or four days. Everybody _ family, friends, the wedding party,
guests _ are invited for a land-locked equivalent of a cruise to
nowhere. I was agog the first time an invitation to one of these
affairs arrived, inviting my husband and me to a wedding in
California. It must have weighed almost a pound and looked more
like a Frommer's guide than an invitation. It was a booklet,
professionally printed. It included details about the wedding and
three days of related events, maps, lists of recommended hotels,
restaurants, beaches, running trails, golf courses (regulation and
miniature), and a lot of other local attractions.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, a similar invitation arrived asking us to
travel to Maui for a week of celebrations surrounding the marriage
of an old friend. It would have been nice to drop everything and
fly to the slopes of ``the mighty Haleakala volcano,'' as the
invitation described it, and join the happy couple and the
assembled throng for cycling, snorkeling, and whale-watching, among
other promised activities, but it just wasn't in the (credit)
cards.
</P>
<P>
   I thought about these weddings reading Cambridgian Dan Zevin's
``The Nearly-Wed Handbook: How to Survive the Happiest Day of Your
Life,'' which I found filed under ``reference'' in the bookstore,
instead of ``humor,'' where it belongs. Actually, it belongs on
both shelves. Anybody thinking even vaguely of getting married
should run to a bookstore and buy at least one copy. That way you
can't say you weren't warned.
</P>
<P>
   Zevin makes a distinction between getting married and getting
weddinged. For example, in getting married, ``you publicly declare
your love in front of the people who mean the most to you.''
However in getting weddinged, ``you desperately revise your guest
list according to which of the people are worth the seventy-five
bucks a head it's costing to feed them.''
</P>
<P>
   Reading Zevin's book made me wonder why more people don't elope.
Why not? There are so many reasons. Family expectations. Gifts. The
bride's dream of having her ``big day.'' Relentless pressure from
the wedding industry.
</P>
<P>
   Once the wedding juggernaut is on a roll, crushing everything in
its path, it's almost impossible for the bride or bridegroom to
escape. The bigger and more expensive the wedding, the harder it is
to back out. That's why I wonder if there's any correlation between
the high divorce rate and the escalating cost of weddings.
</P>
<P>
   How do you back out of a $50,000 wedding at the last minute? You
don't. ``I hate the sight of him,'' says the prospective bride, a
week before the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just nervous,'' says her mother.
</P>
<P>
   No, she really hates the sight of him. She knows she's making
the mistake of her life. But it's too late. The wedding is a major
investment. The marriage? Two years, tops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
