<HEADER>
A9269 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     06-08 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE BUGS, WILL DELIVER (HELP! HELP!) 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 (jt)  
 By STEPHEN MANES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Viewpoint Datalabs International Inc. has helped create many
computer-generated models for television and the movies, including
the latest version of ``Godzilla.'' Liveart98, its first product
for the general public, trades the monsters for bugs.
</P>
<P>
   The program costs about $90 and is designed to help users create
clip art by letting them modify three-dimensional models in a
variety of amusing ways. But it refused to work properly on one
computer until I spent hours diagnosing the problems, and on
another it refused to work at all.
</P>
<P>
   Given the list of problems that comes with it, I was unwilling
to give it a chance for a third strike, but apparently I can
consider myself lucky. ``You should have seen the bug list a month
ago,'' said Chris Lowery, the company's director of business
communication.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of exterminating the bugs before they crawled into the
box, Viewpoint chose to grace its Web site
(www.viewpoint.com/liveart/) with a list beginning: ``These are the
known bugs which we couldn't get out at shipping time. Updates will
be made available.'' Is there another industry where people get
away with this?
</P>
<P>
   The known problems include examples that range from ``Right and
Left mouse buttons sometimes gets confused'' to instructions about
what to do ``If you are using a hardware acceleration card and are
experiencing blue screen crashes after working for a while.'' Blue
screen crashes are an especially nasty breed in which the whole
system fails all at once, but I saw not blue but red when Liveart98
locked up my computer to the point where rebooting was required.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots and lots of problems with any new product,''
Lowery said. ``There are certainly a lot of rough edges in the 1.0
package.''
</P>
<P>
   He blamed some of the problems on Microsoft's shortcomings:
``We're intersecting with at least three component technologies
that are not well implemented and not well documented.''
</P>
<P>
   The technologies he referred to are three pieces of leaky
software plumbing known as OLE, DirectX and OpenGL, which Microsoft
includes in Windows 95 and applications. Developing software that
relies on all three is slightly less daring than hiring Moe, Larry
and Curly.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Jeff Prosise, an author and lecturer on Windows
programming, for a reality check. ``If you ask who's at fault,
there's plenty of blame to go around,'' he said. ``Developers are
often guilty of not testing their product adequately, but if
they're working with a technology that's complex and not well
documented, there's only so much they can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's OLE technology, he said, ``is poorly documented and
does not work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every programmer curses it,'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's implemented differently in every application,'' Prosise
said, ``and you can't say one way is correct, because the
documentation is so miserable. OLE is an ugly and ill-conceived
protocol that deserves to die a slow and agonizing death.'' But if
you want your program to appear as a more or less seamless part of
Microsoft Office 97 applications, as Liveart98 can when it works,
OLE is hard to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   DirectX has been a shaky technology since its outset. Designed
to make Windows multimedia applications run faster, it often causes
video problems that can be hard to diagnose and repair, even after
you download and install the latest video driver software to help
insure that the driver is not the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   One such download and some other tweaking finally got Liveart98
working on one of my computers, no thanks to Viewpoint's
documentation or the support technician I contacted. On the other
machine, the program remained intractable no matter what I tried.
Lowery said that only one person in 50 or 60 was having problems
and that the company was working on improvements.
</P>
<P>
   What does Liveart98 deliver if you manage to get it running?
Clip art that looks different from, but not necessarily better
than, the usual breed of graphics that lend church newsletters what
passes for visual spice. The program works on its own or from
within Microsoft Office 97 applications, but it will not rescue the
low repute of clip art or turn a visual incompetent into
Michelangelo.
</P>
<P>
   Your computer renders Live-art98's images from a library of
several thousand three-dimensional models on CD-ROM. A built-in
search engine lets you find possibilities from the broad
collection. When you type ``cat,'' the program cleverly proposes
everything from a feline skull to a Caterpillar tractor and a milk
carton, not to mention a pronghorn antelope and other unrelated
animals.
</P>
<P>
   Customization is the watchword. You can tilt and rotate the 3-D
models on the screen, so you can see a green tiger beetle from
above, from the side or from a worm's-eye view. Combinations of odd
angles and close-ups can make for arresting effects. For further
tweaking, you can render the models in various synthetic drawing
styles, create shadow effects by lighting them from nine different
points, and sometimes change their colors.
</P>
<P>
   In general, heavier stylization and inanimate objects give
better-looking results; more realistic modes give the
oversimplified surfaces of animate objects a disconcerting
artificiality reminiscent of the computer-generated humans in the
film ``Toy Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Rendering 3-D images takes plenty of computing power. If you
were wondering what kind of program might show off a high-powered
machine, this sort of thing is the answer. Viewpoint recommends a
166-megahertz Pentium processor and 48 megabytes of random access
memory, but even a machine of that caliber is likely to seem
lethargic. On the 400-megahertz computer that was able to run the
program, performance was fairly snappy, even though I had to turn
the video card 3-D acceleration off.
</P>
<P>
   Hardware and software makers see 3-D graphics, particularly for
games, as one way to help sell faster, more expensive computers.
But in their effort to improve computers' 3-D performance, they
have lost sight of the one great advantage of game machines and
their software: they just work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
