<SLUG> BC-NORMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE'S 86 AND AS FEISTY AS CAN BE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE NORMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I was ready for him to tell me I had cancer,'' she told me as
I drove her away from the doctor's office Tuesday. My aunt Goldie,
a frail 86-year-old, was not willing to take that news quietly. ``I
was going to tell him that I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few minutes earlier, we sat in front of the doctor's
desk, waiting for him to finish with another patient and come tell
us the results of a battery of high-tech tests.
</P>
<P>
   A wall full of medical textbooks and reference guides were on
his side. Goldie was at the mercy of medical reality, but _ even
though she is shortened in stature because of the effects that
aging has on bones _ she was ready to stand up and fight.
</P>
<P>
   A month earlier, a nurse who is Goldie's Sunday School teacher
and dear friend took her in the middle of the night from her west
Fort Worth home to the hospital emergency room. Severe stomach
pains had plagued her the entire day, and she began vomiting during
the night. She called her friend for help; the measure of the
friendship is that the help came immediately.
</P>
<P>
   She spent a full week in the hospital, with new tests every day
aimed at diagnosing the problem. Her thin arm was stuck repeatedly
for blood tests, intravenous feeding and medication. The doctors
were about to give up when they discovered something wrong with her
pancreas, a ``poorly defined area of soft tissue'' about the size
of a hen's egg.
</P>
<P>
   It could be cancer. They couldn't tell.
</P>
<P>
   At Goldie's age and delicate state of health, there was not even
the suggestion of cutting her open to take a closer look at the
problem. And if it turned out to be cancer, the typical treatments
_ radiation and strenuous chemotherapy _ also could be too much for
her.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors decided to give Goldie antibiotics in case they were
dealing with some kind of infection. They would wait a month and
run the tests again _ the change in results, one way or the other,
would literally tell this silver-haired, cheerful woman whether she
had been struck by a disease that would kill her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived a long time,'' she said. ``If I'm going to die now,
that's nothing that God and I can't handle. But I'd rather live a
few more years.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldie has lived in Fort Worth since 1943. Born in 1911, she and
the rest of my mother's siblings grew up in the tiny community of
Bangs, near Brownwood in Central Texas. It was World War II that
took her away. Rather, it took her husband away to the Army, and
she followed him while he was stationed stateside. When he _ and
one of his friends, later my dad _ shipped out to Europe, Goldie
took a girlfriend's advice and moved to Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   It was Rosie-the-Riveter time at the city's big bomber plant,
when thousands of American women pitched in to help make the
airplanes and other arms that their servicemen brothers and
husbands used to fight the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out there and asked for a job,'' Goldie said. ``They
said, `keypunch operator.' I said, `What's that?'''
</P>
<P>
   It was a job in the plant's payroll department. In the early
dawn of the computer era, it taught her a skill. After the war, she
took that skill to a Fort Worth insurance company and transformed
it into a career.
</P>
<P>
   Goldie didn't have children of her own. Now, with her husband,
my parents and the rest of her family gone, my brother and cousins
and I try to keep tabs on her. She's fairly independent, has a
close circle of friends from her church and makes friends easily.
</P>
<P>
   What she seems to hate most about getting older is giving up her
car. She taught herself to drive in 1933 by taking a car out into a
Brownwood pasture, getting behind the wheel and making it go until
she knew what she was doing.
</P>
<P>
   She hates the way older people are sometimes treated. Her
favorite television show, ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman,'' recently
was canceled. ``They said the only ones who were watching it were
old people, so they canceled it. That just makes me so mad.''
</P>
<P>
   So we sat there in the doctor's office, waiting for word on her
fate. She talked about how she had already fought off cancer once,
with surgery a little more than a year ago that left her weak but
still going. And her defiant streak showed: ``I just don't believe
I have it again.''
</P>
<P>
   The office door opened. The doctor came in, and he was smiling
broadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the good part about being a doctor,'' he said.
``Sometimes you get good news.''
</P>
<P>
   He never knew Goldie was ready to fight him if he had told her
she has cancer. She doesn't. She was happy.
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Norman is a columnist and an editorial page director for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
mnorman(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
