<HEADER>
A9279 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLEGE-GREENER-COX &UR; 4 HIGHMOBILIT   06-08 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-GREENER-COX </SLUG>
   440&AMP;ADD  SURVEY SHOWS REGRETS, HIGH
MOBILITY AMONG COLLEGE GRADS
 &HT;     By BOB DART 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The grass often seems greener on the other side of
the computer screen, a national career survey of college graduates
showed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half (43 percent) of the college-educated workers said
they would choose a different major if they could start over _ with
many favoring science or technology for the second time around.
</P>
<P>
   However, about 40 percent of the respondents now working in the
high-tech information industry would also pick a different course
of study _ with liberal arts or education being the most popular
choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that non-technical people want to know more about
technology, while technology people are finding there's more to
life than bits and bytes,'' said Alan G. Merten, president of
George Mason University, the Virginia college that co-sponsored the
survey.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone survey of 400 college-educated workers aged 30 to
55 was conducted by Market Research Institute. The respondents were
all employed and had been out of college for at least 10 years. The
nationwide survey had a margin of error of plus or minus 5
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The study showed a mobile work force, with 51 percent of the
workers saying they had already switched careers at least once
since graduating from college. Within careers, respondents had held
an average of four different jobs since entering the work force.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that information technology workers are
considerably more restless than the average employee. A third of
the high-tech workers expect to make a future career change,
compared to one in five of all college graduates.
</P>
<P>
   The workers realized that education is a lifelong process, the
survey indicated. More than half the respondents (57 percent) have
taken college-level courses since graduation, mostly to advance
their careers. Nearly half (46 percent) said they would need to
take more computer-related courses in the future.
</P>
<P>
   While he would ``have assumed more satisfaction'' with their
college majors, the findings were not shocking ``when you think of
the pace of change in the workplace,'' said David Potter, provost
at George Mason University, which has about 24,000 students and is
located in the Washington, D.C., suburb of Fairfax, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The desire of technical workers for a broader education and of
other grads for more technical training indicates that colleges
need to increase interaction between fields of study, Potter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no longer a dichotomy with two kinds of education,''
he explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't narrowly educate'' engineers, programmers and other
technical workers, he said, and a working knowledge of technology
is required in every field from law to agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   About four in every 10 respondents both inside and outside the
information industry would pursue a different major if they could
start over. Over all, 44 percent of these respondents cited
personal enjoyment as the reason they would choose a different
course of study, compared to 40 percent who cited career
advancement.
</P>
<P>
   Among high-tech workers who would change majors, however, 70
percent cited personal enjoyment, compared to only 26 percent who
said their careers would be enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of their majors, most of the respondents expressed
confidence in their ability to keep up in the Internet age. Only 7
percent feared that change would pass them by, and 60 percent said
they were comfortable with the technology in their homes and on the
job. About a third said they can handle the technology now but were
a little concerned about what comes next.
</P>
<P>
   Along with George Mason University, the survey was co-sponsored
by The Potomac KnowledgeWay, a business that works with information
technology industries, educational institutions and state and local
government officials in the Washington, D.C., area.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
