<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., June 14)  
 (JT)  
 By JOSEPH SIANO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Romanov Funeral
</P>
<P>
   Q. What can you tell me about funeral arrangements for Czar
Nicholas II and his family in St. Petersburg this summer? _ Gene
Horton, Blue Point, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. The Romanovs will finally receive a royal sendoff on July 17,
80 years to the day after Nicholas II, his wife, Aleksandra, and
their children were killed by the Bolsheviks. Several years ago,
DNA tests proved that bones found near the Ural Mountains city of
Yekaterinburg were those of the royal couple and three of their
five children (the remains of Aleksei and either Anastasia or Marie
have not been found).
</P>
<P>
   The Peter and Paul Fortress in St. Petersburg, with the family
crypt for 300 years of Romanovs, is where the remains will be
buried and where the ceremony will be conducted. But because the
cathedral in the fortress can hold only 150 people, attendance will
be limited to relatives and church and government officials.
</P>
<P>
   Others will watch the ceremony on a public square outside the
fortress, where television screens will be set up with
translations. The ceremony is scheduled to begin at about 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Tudor Tour
</P>
<P>
   Q. A high school graduate I know will be in England this autumn.
She has a fanatical interest in Tudor history, and wants to visit
relevant sites. Chances are, the friends she travels with won't be
as interested in the subject. Are there Tudor clubs she could
contact in England to meet like-minded people? _ John Charles,
Edmonton, Alberta, Canada.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is at least one, and your young Tudor fan will get a
much friendlier greeting than the one Henry Tudor gave to King
Richard III at the battle of Bosworth Field in 1485, when Henry's
forces defeated those of Richard, who was slain in the process.
Henry began the Tudor dynasty as King Henry VII, and was followed
by Henry VIII, who in turn was followed by his three children:
Edward VI, Mary I and Elizabeth I. But all three of the third
generation of Tudor monarchs were childless, and so in 1603, the
dynasty faded.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, the Tudor banner is upheld by the Tudor Group, 16
Lower St., Quainton, Bucks HP22 4BJ, telephone (44-1296) 655309,
run by Mark and Ruth Goodman. They do a variety of events
throughout the year to recreate Tudor history. The group has
members throughout the country, according to Ruth Goodman, and she
can put you in touch with local members.
</P>
<P>
   A Tudorite will feel at home at Kentwell Hall, Long Melford,
Suffolk CO10 9BA; (44-1787) 310207. The main part of this private
home dates from 1520. The domestic history of the period will come
to life here on Sept. 19 and 20 with up to 250 people in costume
showing what it was like to be anything from a peasant to a lord.
It's an hour by train from Liverpool Station in London to Sudbury.
Open Sundays in September and October from noon to 5 p.m., 11 a.m.
to 6 p.m. on Sept. 19 and 20.
</P>
<P>
   English Heritage helps organize living-history events and has a
calendar listing them. Tudor events in the autumn include ``Murder
and Mis-Marriage: the Two King Henrys,'' Sept. 19 and 20 at St.
Augustine's Abbey, Kent. Henry II and Henry VIII are featured, as
well as Anne of Cleves. For the strong of stomach, ``A Tudor
Surgeon'' at Deal Castle, Kent, on Oct. 17 and 18, is a look at
16th-century medicine. Contact English Heritage, Customer Services,
Post Office Box 9019, London W1A 0JA; (44-171) 973-3434.
</P>
<P>
   A Papal Visit
</P>
<P>
   Q. I understand that Pope John Paul II plans to visit the United
States again. If so, where will he go and how can I find out about
attending any Mass that he might celebrate? _ Jim Hunt, Greenwich,
Conn.
</P>
<P>
   A. If all goes as planned, the pope will be in St. Louis in
January to celebrate a Mass there and see the head of the St. Louis
archdiocese, Archbishop Justin Rigali. But details are sketchy at
the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop and pope knew each other for many years while
they worked together in the Vatican and became close friends,
according to Maureen Bergin of the archdiocese offices; in 1994,
the pope appointed Rigali to his current post.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bergin said that tentative plans called for the pope to fly
from Mexico to St. Louis on Jan. 26 and celebrate a Mass the
following day in the Trans World Dome, the 66,000-seat domed
football stadium near the Mississippi a few blocks north of the
Gateway Arch.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bergin said that there were no ticket-distribution plans,
and no additional details are likely to be announced until after
the papal planning team's visit around Labor Day. She suggests that
you call her at (314) 533-1887 sometime after.
</P>
<P>
   Live From the Falls
</P>
<P>
   Q. A while ago, I saw a telecast of ``Live! With Regis and Kathy
Lee'' from the Canadian side of Niagara Falls. They stayed in a
large hotel with great views of the falls. Which hotel was it, and
how can I get there by bus or train from New York City? How long
will it take by car? _ Mary Li, Dobbs Ferry, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. Usually, you wouldn't want to stay in a hotel where the water
runs all night. But not in this case. As for which hotel you saw,
the Niagara Falls Canada Visitor and Convention Bureau says it
could have been either of two featured on the program.
</P>
<P>
   The Sheraton Fallsview, (800) 267-8439, charges $184 (at $1.41
Canadian to the United States dollar), with breakfast, for a double
room with a falls view, $138 without, in summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Skyline Foxhead, (800) 263-7135, charges $170 to $205 in
summer for a falls view, $127 to $162 without; no meals included.
</P>
<P>
   Two bus companies serve Niagara Falls, Ontario, from the Port
Authority Bus Terminal at 42d Street and Eighth Avenue in
Manhattan. Trailways, (800) 858-8555, and Greyhound, (800)
231-2222, have numerous departures daily to Buffalo, where you
transfer to a Canadian line. Round-trip fare is about $110; 10 to
12 hours depending on number of stops.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak service from New York to Niagara Falls, Ontario, takes
about 9 to 10 hours each way, with round-trip fares of about $120.
Call (800) 872-7245 for exact schedules and fares.
</P>
<P>
   By car, it is about 400 miles; allow 9{ to 10 hours. Ask your
insurer for a nonresident liability-insurance card for Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Native-born Americans should take a birth certificate and a
photo I.D.; naturalized citizens should carry their naturalization
certificate. Passports suffice for both.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
