<HEADLINE>
FAITH DIRECTS THESE PILGRIMS' LONG WALK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA SMITH 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Zen Buddhists and agnostics, Catholics and holyrolling Baptists,
Bahai and Unitarians and Pentecostals, whites, blacks, sinners, and
candidates for sainthood lined up at 7 a.m. yesterday for ham
quiche, apples, cantaloupe, poppyseed bagels, thick slabs of raisin
bread, honey, cream cheese, jam, coffee, and tea. It was spiritual
sustenance, necessary fuel for an eclectic assemblage of pilgrims
who would later lace up battered Reeboks and Nikes, swig warm water
from rippled plastic bottles, and take yet another step toward
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The meal at Cambridge's First Baptist Church _ a site that once
was a station on the Underground Railroad _ was a brief respite for
members of the Interfaith Pilgrimage of the Middle Passage, a
journey that began at the Nipponzan Myohoji Buddhist Peace Pagoda
in Leverett last week. A determined core group of approximately 60
walkers set out on a year-long trek retracing the route of the
slave trade through the United States, the Caribbean, Brazil, West
Africa, and South Africa. Others will participate in segments of
the trip.
</P>
<P>
   In this physical reversal of the horrific passage in which
millions lost their lives, the pioneers hope to redefine the word
``freedom.'' They can't erase the bitter reality of slavery, but
they can teach new ways to live with its legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a journey of group consciousness,'' said Kansas City
native Clyde Love, 38, who intends to walk all the way. ``My
personal reason for doing this is not important. I will say this,
though _ I will not teach my child one thing about racism.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Anderson, a 23-year-old native of Northampton, will
rejoin the trek in New Orleans, where the pilgrims set sail for the
Caribbean. After that, he's in for the duration. ``The whole
journey is a walking, living prayer,'' he said. ``I feel at home
with the spirituality of it all. This is not, I repeat, not a
political event.''
</P>
<P>
   A huge banner above the table of food was a welcome to the
walkers from the children of the Cambridgeport Children's Center,
who, at 7 a.m., were probably all asleep, dreaming of less weighty
matters, unaware of the impact their message had on the gathering.
To join symbolically in the march, they had dipped their bare feet
in paint and walked the width of the banner. Some of the tiny
footprints were brown, some rust, others peach, some white. ``We'll
ride on their shoulders,'' said Erika Koslow, a 20-year-old
divinity student who'll officially join the march in Philadelphia
on June 25. ``Those strong little feet will carry us whenever we
get tired.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've reclaimed my life for this,'' said co-organizer Ingrid
Askew. ``This is about unearthing the truth and keeping it above
ground for the world to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Marching several blocks through sleepy Cambridge streets to St.
Paul AME Church, the drum-beating, flag-waving group loud-whispered
a Buddhist prayer before roaring out a chant of its own making. To
the strains of ``Sunshine in My Soul'' by the church choir, the
doors opened and the interfaith travelers filed into pews reserved
for them. It was a thrilling sight _ Asians with dreadlocked hair
and unwieldy backpacks, a wispy redhead with four rings in her
right nostril, aging hippies, businessmen in pinpoint Oxfords, the
gleaming bald heads of Buddhists, cameras clunking, gym shoes
squeaking, tie-dye and spandex alongside the crisp white uniforms
and erect bearing of brown-skinned ushers, stiff Sunday-suited
greeters, and the impeccably dressed matrons of the AME church.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation's prayers were driven, fervent, thanking God
for the journey. And meant to grant the workers Godspeed: ``We
know, God, even in the midst of all our struggles that You are the
one who brought us out, resurrected us, stood us on our feet,
enabled us to call Your name.'' The singing was urgent,
celebratory, and infectious, with much stomping of tired, calloused
feet. In a shaking, barely audible voice, Earline Robertson, a
43-year-old grandmother from Amherst, presented the Rev. LeRoy
Attles with a keychain _ one of 2,000 she has handmade to
distribute to friends along the passage.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson is marching even though she just had a cervical disc
removed. ``I know my pain will stop once I bring my ancestors
home,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   We'd do well not to lose sight of these pilgrims. They are part
of a journey fueled by song and great gushes of spirit, by the
insistent heat of history and maybe most of all by the sight of a
young white kid in chunky sneakers and beige corduroy pants
streaked with grime. Removed from slavery's shame by time and
privilege, he hunched over in the pew of Saint Paul, weeping into
his cupped hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
