<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HABITAT-PRISONERS-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS PRISONERS BUILD ON FAITH TO HELP ON HABITAT PROJECT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Art available on NYT photo service) 
 
By ERIC BERGER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Thugs, rapists and even murderers _ it will take them
all to ensure that Jimmy Carter Work Project volunteers achieve
their goal of building 100 homes next week.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the weeklong project, 25 Texas inmates from Jester
Unit II in nearby Huntsville will build one of the homes. Many of
the prisoners have already assisted with pre-building activities at
the Habitat for Humanity's warehouse for months.
</P>
<P>
   The inmates' involvement stems from their participation in a new
faith-based program in Texas prisons called the Innerchange Freedom
Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been blessed,'' said 37-year-old Gilbert Garcia who has
been in prison since 1989 for using crack cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-month-old initiative, started in the Texas Department of
Criminal Justice's Jester Unit II , builds upon a program pioneered
in Brazil and Ecuador more than two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Participation in the program does not shorten an inmate's
sentence, said Frederick Becker, senior warden of Jester Units I,
II and III in Huntsville, about an hour north of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The ecumenical and ethical underpinning of Habitat's efforts
fits neatly within Innerchange's goal of fostering a sense of faith
and community service in the inmates, who can only join the program
during the last 18 months of their sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Since its founding in 1976, Habitat for Humanity has built
65,000 homes for low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   The inmates say they have found God during their incarceration
and that participating in Habitat helps them do their part for a
society they have plundered.
</P>
<P>
   Take John Goree, a 38-year-old inmate serving a five-year
sentence. A week ago, he helped dedicate a house for a new family.
Goree said he's happy to be bringing people together, not tearing
them apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great because I could feel a sense of accomplishment, a
feeling of self worth because I was part of something,'' Goree said
of the dedication. ``I was real happy that we could share in
building that home and really blessing someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Regular volunteers who built the Houston-area home in Missouri
City _ the prisoners' first _ said what the inmates have done in
the past does not matter at a Habitat site.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very hard workers,'' said Sharon D. Heldt, president
of the Fort Bend Habitat for Humanity. ``All our volunteers
understood the program, and it wasn't like these guys were coming
here to get out of the jailhouse for a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in the program, the inmates rise at 5:30 a.m. for prayers.
Shortly thereafter they work at various community service
activities, including the Habitat warehouse. Later, after more
prayers, the participants have night classes before a 10:30 p.m.
bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, Goree and prisoner Walter Kasper have all been with
Innerchange since its inception in early 1997. At first, they said,
there were some difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the program's beginning a lot of people laughed at
us,'' Kasper said. ``Guys would say `I wouldn't be in that for
anything,' but now they're breaking down the doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasper, a clean-shaven 44-year-old with a chiseled face topped
by a buzz-cut, says he was a ``lowly'' robber and crook before he
ended up in jail 54 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me this has been a godsend,'' said Kasper, referring to
his participation in Innerchange. ``I turned 40 in prison and came
to the realization that I wasn't a nice man. This is an outlet to
assuage your own guilt to some point, to give back to the community
that we had taken from.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent hot June day, 13 inmates were at the Habitat
warehouse in north Houston and were busily piling wall sections and
loading lumber onto trucks. Nearby, some temporary help Habitat had
hired was taking a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look over there, at those guys, and they're loafing,''
said Sgt. Kevin Cooksey, one of two guards assigned to the inmates.
``But not over here. These guys are working hard and enjoying it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
