<HEADLINE>
RECKLESS DRIVING CARRIES LESS RISK IN SIBERIA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TYUKHTET, Russia _ Slava Cherkasov gunned the engine of his
Toyota and blindly shot out into the oncoming lane, blissfully
oblivious to the fact that he could not see what was coming.
</P>
<P>
   For this was Siberia, a land of huge expanses, harsh climate,
and stoic people, a place where amazing events seem commonplace,
but a seemingly normal task can become a big deal in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   No one here blinks an eye at a snap May blizzard or the grizzly
bears that occasionally wander across the two-lane highway that
links Tyukhtet with the rest of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   And no one seems to mind that half the cars have their steering
wheels on the right-hand side rather than the left, even though in
Russia, as in the United States, cars drive on the right-hand side
of the road.
</P>
<P>
   But a normal task like passing a truck on a highway becomes a
death-defying trick when you try to do it from the wrong side of
the car in a blizzard, with extra Siberian degrees of difficulty
posed by the risk of ramming some unseen bear in the oncoming lane.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Siberians can be unflappable, and Slava Cherkasov is
no exception. Consider what Cherkasov had to go through just to get
his car to Tyukhtet so that he could risk his (and my) life in it.
</P>
<P>
   There is no Honest Ivan Motors in Tyukhtet, a Siberian hamlet
with one grocery store and one gas station, a small collection of
weathered wooden huts inhabited by a few thousand weathered folks.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the industrial city of Krasnoyarsk, 130 miles to the
west, it's hard to get a good deal on a car. So Cherkasov, who has
been making his living as a private taxi driver ever since
Tyukhtet's moribund lumber factory laid him off, went auto-shopping
in Nakhodka, some 2,000 miles away on Russia's Pacific coast.
</P>
<P>
   There, he got a great deal on a 1980 Corolla: $2,000, just off
the boat from Japan, where, as in England, steering wheels are on
the right-hand side. After taking a couple of days to get used to
driving from the wrong side of the car, Cherkasov faced the problem
of getting his car back to Tyukhtet. For Siberia's vast taiga is
not connected to the Pacific Far East by any paved road.
</P>
<P>
   Here, it helps to know a Russian word, ``zimniki.'' These are
unpaved, uncharted roads that are passable only in winter, when the
swamps and rivers freeze and the mud turns to permafrost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zimniki'' are the unsung heroes of transportation in a country
whose paved roads have been rapped by everyone from Gogol to
Gorbachev. ``Zimniki'' bailed out the Red Army in Stalingrad.
``Zimniki'' remain the best way to get around Siberia today. And it
was a network of ``zimniki,'' plus a good set of radials, that got
Cherkasov and his Toyota out of the Far East and back to Tyukhtet.
</P>
<P>
   Tyukhtet got its paved highway only eight years ago, and all the
villages to the north along the Chulym River are reachable only by
water and ``zimniki.'' This semi-isolation has magnified the
hardships of rural Russian life _ high prices, rising unemployment,
rampant alcoholism, and chronically late paychecks for those who do
work.
</P>
<P>
   Cherkasov, who lives with his wife and 8-year-old daughter,
pumps water from a well and keeps a wood stove burning to heat his
two-room hut. The low standard of living in Tyukhtet is one of the
few amazing things that locals have not stopped noticing. The bleak
steppe that stretches from Krasnoyarsk to Tyukhtet is dotted with
the smoke billowing from aluminum smelters. They must be making
money. Where does all that money go?
</P>
<P>
   Cherkasov doesn't have an answer to that one. But as he blindly
gunned his right-hand-wheel Toyota into the oncoming lane, he had
the answer to the only question that mattered at that moment: This
being Siberia, chances are you and that truck up ahead are the only
ones on the road.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Filipov is the Globe's Moscow bureau chief.
</P>
</TEXT>
