<HEADLINE>
TEXAS PROSECUTOR CHALLENGES CONFISCATION OF FILES BY FEDERAL
AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER and CARMINA DANINI  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ Federal agents who raided the Webb County
district attorney's office appear to be searching for a link
between the way certain criminal cases were handled and the
personal finances of key people in that office.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-page search warrant that FBI agents used to cart away
thousands of case files and documents beginning the evening of May
29 hints broadly that such a link is at the heart of the
investigation that has caused an uproar in this south Texas border
city.
</P>
<P>
   That warrant, a copy of which was obtained Friday by the San
Antonio Express-News, authorized FBI agents to seize not only
thousands of criminal case files, but computer disks, phone
records, and foreign and domestic bank account information for
District Attorney Joe Rubio, members of his staff and his father.
</P>
<P>
   The warrant says agents were hunting for documentation showing
not only how criminal cases were tried, but decisions in which
charges were dropped and where defendants entered into a plea
bargain or were placed on pretrial diversion by Rubio's office.
</P>
<P>
   The warrant, signed by U.S. District Judge John Rainey, further
authorized FBI agents to seize memorandums and ethics policies
regarding interaction between the district attorney's office and
bail bond companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turned all that stuff over,'' Rubio said. ``Certainly
pretrial agreements are a matter of public record.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubio declined to comment specifically on what federal agents
were investigating. No charges have been filed in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The way Rubio's office handled 128 cases referred to it for
prosecution is at the center of the federal investigation, which
has brought many FBI and Internal Revenue Service agents to this
border city.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, agents have gone after the personal financial
records of 14 people including Rubio, his father, eight workers in
the district attorney's office, a former state district judge, a
bail bondsman, a justice of the peace and a former Webb County
jailer.
</P>
<P>
   The search of Rubio's office, other offices and homes triggered
several legal motions after federal officials refused to make
public the search warrants or return the seized files.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio Express-News filed a motion Thursday with
Rainey's court in Victoria, Texas, asking him to unseal the search
warrants and all supporting documents.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Donato Ramos, an attorney hired to represent the
district attorney's office, filed an emergency motion here Friday
to get the federal judge to order the return of as many as 5,000
criminal case files which were seized from Rubio's office.
</P>
<P>
   Hearings on those motions are scheduled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rubio said that although some files have been returned, his
office is paralyzed without the remaining documents.
</P>
<P>
   He also seemed to indicate the district attorney's office is
through cooperating with the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're shifting gears in the sense that we need the return of
these files,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to asking that the records and files be returned,
Ramos asked that the affidavit supporting the request for the
search warrants be unsealed.
</P>
<P>
   And the motion challenged the validity of the search warrant on
technical grounds, since it authorized the FBI to seize records in
Rubio's office on the east side of the fourth floor of the county
courthouse. Rubio's office is on the west side, the motion said.
</P>
<P>
   Because nearly 5,000 files and other documents were seized from
the district attorney's office, the government will be hard-pressed
to explain why it needs all those records, said attorneys familiar
with federal procedure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ramos' motion was accompanied by a three-page affidavit signed
by Webb County First Assistant District Attorney Monica Zapata
Notzon.
</P>
<P>
   Notzon, who has been with Rubio's office nearly eight years,
said FBI agents seized information unrelated to any of the 128
names whose cases were listed on the search warrant.
</P>
<P>
   The agents, Notzon said in her affidavit, took more than 4,000
closed files and 1,374 active files or pending investigations,
including nearly 300 domestic violence protective orders, during
the three-day raid.
</P>
<P>
   Had the agents restricted the search to the 128 names on the
search warrant, they would have seized no more than 300 files, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Documents taken included files for drug cases, at least one
attempted murder, misdemeanor theft and bond forfeitures.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor said she questioned why agents were taking a
domestic violence manual from a prosecutor not named in the
warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Agents agreed to leave the manual but still took other items
from his office, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
