<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9325 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-PLANT-INVASION-2T     06-08 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PLANT-INVASION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW METHODS EMPLOYED TO FIGHT INVASIVE PLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN.: Fla., Texas, Ore., Calif., Mont. ) 
(ja) 
 By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They could easily make tabloid headlines:
</P>
<P>
   ``Killer Smothers Hawaiian Host''
</P>
<P>
   ``Eurasian Beauty Stalks Wetlands''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stream-Side Slayer Strikes Again!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Aussie Strangler Sweeps Through Florida''
</P>
<P>
   ``Horse Poisoning Horror!''
</P>
<P>
   Committing these acts of violence are a rogues' gallery growing
out of control in fields, forests, marshes, stream sides and
waterways throughout the country: invasive plants.
</P>
<P>
   Even backyard gardens are likely to harbor one or more of the
rascals waiting for an opportunity to mount a horticultural coup
d'etat.
</P>
<P>
   The ubiquitous invaders with roots, leaves, shoots and seeds are
running roughshod over native plants, changing the quality of the
soil, water and landscape and wiping out countless creatures _ from
microorganisms to mammals _ that cannot withstand the onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Randall, an invasive plant specialist with the Nature
Conservancy and the University of California at Davis, said,
``Invasive plants are the second most serious threat, after habitat
loss, to native species of plants and animals and to maintaining
biologically diverse ecosystems.''
</P>
<P>
   Not counting those in Hawaii, with nearly as many imported
invaders as native plants, at least 300 species of invasive plants
threaten native ecosystems in the United States and the Canadian
provinces, said Janet Marinelli, director of publishing at the
Brooklyn Botanic Garden and co-editor with Randall of its
publication, ``Invasive Plants: Weeds of the Global Garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marinelli noted that half the invaders were brought to the
United States and Canada to beautify streets and gardens, among
them purple loosestrife, foxglove, Japanese barberry, Norway maple
and Scotch broom. But many of the imports arrived without their
natural enemies _ the insects, microorganisms and competing plants
that keep them in check back home.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the imports spread uncontrolled and drove out
native species of plants and animals, killed off cattle and
irrevocably altered environments. But now, scientists are launching
biological counterattacks that show promise of holding at least
some of the invasive plants in check. Their weapons include an
injectable contraceptive, imported insects that dine exclusively on
the invaders and old-fashioned weed-pulling by hordes of human
volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   To date, they can claim few victories. But among most successful
has been the conquest of the dreaded alligator weed, large mats of
which had been choking the Everglades waterways. By introducing a
flea beetle and moth that dine on it, biologists reduced the plant,
originally from South America, to scattered strands.
</P>
<P>
   In their search for effective control measures that cause no
harm to desirable species or to the general environment, scientists
scour a plant's native turf searching for insects and pathogens
that attack them and only them. Before such pests can be released
in test plots, however, they must pass stringent laboratory tests
to be sure the control agents will not become pests themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dennis Isaacson, an entomologist who is special projects
coordinator at the Oregon Department of Agriculture in Salem, said
one was an ``eat it or die'' test in which the insect is given
nothing but the target plant to eat. The second is a choice test
that allows the insect to choose between the target plant and a
related one. Isaacson explained that most plant pests are very
fussy about what they feed on, generally restricting themselves to
a single plant or group of closely related plants.
</P>
<P>
   But even with effective biological control measures in hand, the
effort can be stymied by unexpected complications, like finding
that an endangered species of bird is nesting preferentially in the
very tree designated to die.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the most offensive of the invaders:
</P>
<P>
   Purple Loosestrife. This Eurasian native of uncommon beauty with
tall showy spikes of purple flowers that bloom profusely in
midsummer has colonized countless wetlands nationwide, replacing
native vegetation in marshes, meadows, riverbanks and lake shores.
In the process, it has threatened the survival of rare plants and
reduced food and shelter for wildlife. Having failed to control it
by flooding, burning, mowing and dousing it with herbicides,
scientists at Cornell University are now making progress using
insects that attack the plant in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bernd Blossey of the New York State College of Agriculture
and Life Sciences at Cornell said that a root-feeding weevil, two
leaf-feeding beetles and a weevil that attacks the flowers had been
put to work in more than 1,000 wetland sites in 32 states. Although
so-called infertile cultivars of purple loosestrife are now sold in
nurseries, Blossey said they could produce viable seeds and should
not be used.
</P>
<P>
   Melaleuca. This tree may be as serious a threat to the survival
of the Florida Everglades as humans who drain its water supply. A
native of northern Australia and New Guinea with bottle-brush
spikes of white flowers, the melaleuca was imported in 1900 as an
ornamental that needed little or no care. Randall said it was also
used to dry up the Everglades when people thought the marsh was
bad. It now infests more than 1.5 million acres of Florida's
natural land and is spreading rapidly, with each mature tree
producing 60 million seeds a year.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ted Center, research entomologist with the Agricultural
Research Service in Fort Lauderdale, said that a half-inch-long
gray weevil that helped to keep the melaleuca under control in its
native Australia was the first hope for slowing the Florida
invasion. This weevil has a healthy appetite for the growing tips
where the flower clusters form and seeds are produced. The first
groups of weevils released last year at 10 sites seem to be
thriving, Center said, adding that it was too soon to see any
effect on the tree itself.
</P>
<P>
   Eight or 10 other insects that can launch different attacks on
melaleuca are also being studied, Center said. The current plan, he
added, calls for integrating various biological controls with more
traditional methods, like injecting them with herbicides and
cutting them down.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tamarisk. Also known as salt cedar, this native of Asia was
introduced in 1837 as an ornamental and later to stabilize stream
sides in the West. But the population exploded some 60 years ago,
leading to its current dubious distinction as ``the No. 1 weed pest
in the West,'' said Dr. C. Jack DeLoach, a research entomologist
for the Agricultural Research Service in Temple, Texas. He listed
its detractions: ``It has no value to native animals, it lowers the
ground-water table so that other plants can't reach it, it deposits
layers of salt on the soil so that other plants can't grow there,
it's extremely flammable and, after a fire, nothing but salt cedar
can come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Field tests of two biological control agents _ an Asian beetle
that eats the foliage and an Israeli mealy bug that sucks sap from
the twigs and kills them _ are being held up by a need to assess
the effects of salt cedar control on an endangered bird, the
southwestern willow flycatcher, which has taken to nesting in the
tree in some parts of Arizona, DeLoach said. He and others believe
that the salt cedar's downfall will allow a return of the willows
that were this bird's original home.
</P>
<P>
   Leafy Spurge. About 5 million acres in 26 states, including New
York, have been invaded by leafy spurge, an herbaceous plant from
Eurasia with milky sap that gives mouth sores to cattle and
displaces grasses and other cattle food, rendering range land
worthless. Ranchers tried putting sheep on spurge-infested range.
Although they eat the plant, they do not kill it and there is not
enough of a market for sheep wool and meat. So about 13 insects
have been imported to help control it. Dr. Neal Spencer, an
entomologist at a Department of Agriculture research laboratory in
Sidney, Mont., said flea beetles had so far been most effective.
The adult beetles feed on the leaves and their larvae mine the
roots, damaging them and opening them to attack by pathogenic
fungi.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow Star Thistle. This lovely looking weed from the
Mediterranean basin is strong enough to kill a horse outright, said
Dr. Juozaf Balciunas, a federal entomologist in Albany, Calif. In
most of the 20 million acres it now invades, it is the No. 1 range
plant pest, he said. It also invades vineyards. Control efforts are
so costly that farmers often just abandon the land to the prolific
plant. Five insects that attack it by dining on the flowers and
fruits have become ``pretty well established'' and are beginning to
make a dent on the number of plants in test areas, Balciunas said.
But the plant fights back; when there are fewer of them, each one
grows bigger, he lamented.
</P>
<P>
   Norway Maple. The majestic look of this popular Eurasian import
(it is the most planted street tree in the country) belies its
aggressiveness. Its seeds spread readily into open lots and forest
preserves, and a single tree can produce ``thousands of babies each
year,'' said Dr. Edward Toth, director of landscape management for
Prospect Park in Brooklyn. It is highly tolerant of shade, expert
at extracting nutrients and water from the soil and little, if
anything, can grow under its dense canopy. Native trees like the
sugar maple and beeches do not stand much of a chance around it.
</P>
<P>
   Toth is awaiting a permit to practice Norway maple birth
control, using a product called Florel, which is already sold as a
spray for trees to keep them from setting fruit. Since spraying a
60-foot tree is neither practical nor safe, Toth expects to inject
it directly into the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Scotch Broom. This highly prolific leguminous shrub with a
profusion of yellow pea-like flowers spreads through its long-lived
seeds and roots. Native to Europe and North Africa, it can thrive
on nitrogen-poor soil, since it makes its own fertilizer. It is
highly flammable, capable of carrying fire into the canopy of
neighboring trees. Isaacson in Salem, Ore., said a seed weevil
intentionally introduced in the West has reduced seed production by
75 percent over half the plant's range so far. However, for better
control, a 95 percent reduction in seed production is needed, which
may be provided by an accidentally imported beetle. Use of the
beetle is pending government approval.
</P>
<P>
   The list of nonnative plants that are able to escape natural
controls and invade areas where they are not wanted includes many
species that are still being purposely planted in gardens. They
include foxglove, vinca, periwinkle, myrtle, jasmine and bachelor
buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marinelli of the Brooklyn Botanic Garden said that before
planting an import, home gardeners should check on the conditions
under which it has become invasive and avoid planting it in a
similar environment. ``If, for example, a plant from Italy became
invasive in Australia, you wouldn't want to plant it in Southern
California,'' Ms. Marinelli said. But, she added, no source of
information on the invasiveness potential of various plants is
widely available. Ms. Marinelli believes it should become a common
category in gardening guides, similar to the listing of planting
zones.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities caution that not all non-native species are harmful.
Those that assimilate well and coexist peacefully with the native
stock are of little concern. And, every invasive import is not
necessarily a problem everywhere in its range. A species may be
highly invasive in one area but lack takeover muscle elsewhere.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1639EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
