<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9329 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-08 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEN STARR MAY BE DEMOCRATS' TOP ASSET IN NOVEMBER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT F. JORDAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there is one person who can persuade the nation's voters to
return control of the US House to the Democrats, it's independent
counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Although Starr, a Republican, personally would prefer a
GOP-controlled House, his relentless pursuit of President Clinton
is making voters tire not only of him, but of the Republicans and
their efforts to exploit, in Starr's words, this ``serious criminal
investigation'' into Clinton's sex life for their own partisan
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Now even the US Supreme Court has said, in essence, that he went
too far when he asked the nation's highest court for a quick ruling
over whether Secret Service agents and a senior White House aide
can be forced to testify before a grand jury. The court in just two
paragraphs told Starr Thursday that his bid for a quick ruling was
rejected and that Clinton's appeal will have to go through the
traditional appellate process, which could take months.
</P>
<P>
   Although Starr had won a string of legal victories in lower
courts, it is clear that the latest ruling has trumped, in terms of
public opinion in this high-stakes duel, Starr's earlier court
wins.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the decision gives Clinton and his White House
support team the advantage of appearing to have the court side with
him against Starr. And this view is not only helping Clinton, it is
helping the Democrats in their quest to regain control of the House
in the November election. Despite GOP claims that Clinton's appeal
is simply another strategic effort to stall Starr's investigation,
the court's ruling does far more damage to Starr than it does to
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While the ruling pushes back the clock as to when Starr will
submit his case to Congress, it is possible that most Republicans
in the GOP-controlled Congress are breathing a sigh of relief over
the court's rejection of Starr's bid to expedite the investigation.
They will not have to act on an investigation being conducted by an
unpopular independent counsel against a popular president.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats know they have at least a chance this year to
recapture the House _ thanks to Starr, Clinton's popularity, a
generally do-nothing GOP-dominated Congress, and the attempts of
the GOP right to push through its agenda.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton taking much of the credit for the good things
happening in this country, including a still-vibrant economy, the
Democrats are increasingly optimistic that they can topple the
11-seat margin that the GOP has over the number of Democrats in the
House. The GOP is aware that while it has the most seats and the
most money, the Democrats have a growing number of voters
gravitating toward them.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are going to get a lot of help from organized
labor, which won a major victory in California last week when
voters rejected a referendum that would have severely hampered
unions from raising funds to support political efforts such as
helping Democrats regain the House.
</P>
<P>
   After an intensive education campaign by the AFL-CIO and other
unions, voters realized that the so-called ``paycheck protection
act'' was not written to protect union workers' paychecks, since
such protections are already in place, but rather was a disguised
GOP effort to cripple organized labor's fiscal ability to help
Democrats defeat Republican opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, despite the problems swirling around his presidency, is
also helping other Democrats by remaining high in opinion polls,
which suggests that voters are more interested in what Clinton is
doing for them than what Starr is doing against Clinton. Clinton
and the Democrats hope that Starr and his investigation continue to
wear thin on voters and that no new scandal erupts that could
breathe life back into Starr's quest, and the GOP's haste, to get
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democrats' best weapon as nemesis these days, as House
Speaker Newt Gingrich was two years ago, is Starr. Without him, the
public might be less sympathetic toward Clinton if the
investigation had been about more than whether he tried to cover up
alleged sex with a White House intern. Without Starr, the Supreme
Court would not have delivered the victory for Clinton and the
defeat for the independent counsel. And without Starr, the
Democrats might not have had a remote possibility of recapturing
the House.
</P>
<P>
   The November election, of course is still five months away, and
anything can happen in that length of time. However, if the economy
continues to perform well, and Starr continues to perform poorly,
the Democrats may pull an upset in the House. And a Democratic
House, of course, would be much more to Clinton's liking during the
last two years of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   If this happens, Clinton and the Democrats might consider a
toast to the one Republican who helped to make it possible: Starr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
