u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIDENHOUR-IRONY-BOS &LR;      06-08 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIDENHOUR-IRONY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RON RIDENHOUR WAS A HERO AND A BRAVE JOURNALIST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Ron Ridenhour would have appreciated the irony of
his death.
</P>
<P>
   After serving as a helicopter gunner in Vietnam, he reported of
an evil that existed in the ranks, ``something rather dark and
bloody'' that took place at My Lai when Charlie Company massacred
the villagers. A year later, he returned to Vietnam as a
journalist, exposing himself to the possibility of friendly fire
from GIs resentful of his revelations that helped turn American
sentiment against the war.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of his career as a muckraking writer, Ridenhour
made other powerful enemies, inside corporate boardrooms and within
a corrupt New Orleans police force. Yet when he had a fatal heart
attack here last month at age 52, he was playing handball with a
friend.
</P>
<P>
   Tributes have flowed since then, and a national convention of
Investigative Reporters and Editors paused here Friday to
memorialize Ridenhour for his work as a dogged, independent
journalist who never made much money but made a profound difference
in American history.
</P>
<P>
   He once won a coveted George Polk Award in connection with his
articles in CityBusiness, a local tabloid, describing scandal in
the New Orleans Finance Department. He butted heads with the
nuclear industry for Gambit, another New Orleans weekly. He
received numerous awards and was published in Time, The New York
Times Magazine, and Playboy.
</P>
<P>
   But he is best remembered for his role as a good soldier.
</P>
<P>
   As he was winding up his tour of duty in 1968, he heard from
buddies of a US Army operation that wiped out ``Pinkville,'' the
name military mapmakers gave to My Lai. ``A lot of people went
pretty crazy that day,'' one member of Charlie Company told
Ridenhour.
</P>
<P>
   Horrified, Ridenhour began to gather information from other
sources. He learned that several hundred Vietnamese civilians _
men, women and children _ were systematically executed by the Army
raiding party.
</P>
<P>
   He returned home to write a detailed three-page letter in 1969
that he sent to President Nixon, Defense Department officials, and
many members of Congress. It was an agonized account of an American
atrocity. ``Somehow I just couldn't believe that not only had so
many young American men participated in such an act of barbarism,
but that their officers had ordered it,'' Ridenhour wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Only one person responded, Representative Morris K. Udall of
Arizona. Udall pressured the House Armed Services Committee, on
which he served, to begin an investigation that led to formal
charges against several members of Charlie Company. More
importantly, news of the massacre eventually burst on the American
consciousness, creating national revulsion against the war.
</P>
<P>
   Ridenhour was always laconic in describing his brush with My
Lai, but it was an obsession that followed him all his life. He
felt My Lai was a reflection of twisted military policy, ``an
operation,'' he contended, ``rather than an aberration.'' Ridenhour
minimized his role in exposing the affair, but he eagerly accepted
invitations to talk with students on the folly of Vietnam and what
he called ``the tenuous nature of military heroism.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. John F. Smith, chaplain at the Groton School, once a
staging area for ``the best and the brightest'' who managed the
war, recalled that ``Ron had barely spoken a sentence to his
audience of Groton School students, the oldest of whom was born
five years after the war ended, before there was complete,
enthralled silence in the room.''
</P>
<P>
   Author and former Vietnam reporter David Halberstam said
Ridenhour belonged in his ``small pantheon of heroes'' as ``an
American original, an absolutely authenic man in an age which is
increasingly inauthenic.''
</P>
<P>
   Others whose lives were changed forever in Vietnam remember
Ridenhour affectionately. ``Ron was courageous, it seemed to me, in
an old-fashioned, even ancient sort of way, brave of body and mind
and spirit,'' said Tim O'Brien, the novelist. Kevin Buckley, now an
editor at Playboy, said Ridenhour ``wanted people to know _ without
any doubt _ some of the most important truths of the war.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days after his death, dozens of Ridenhour's friends
crowded into a Lower Garden District cafe to laugh and cry and to
tell stories about his lovable gruffness and his erratic work
habits.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ridenhour produced an impressive number of magazine
articles, he never wrote a book. He was working on one when he
died. Characteristically, he was trying to document reports of
violence committed, within the US armed forces, against a unit of
black soldiers during World War II. David Corn, a writer for The
Nation, called it ``one of the best book ideas I had heard of in
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Thompson, the Louisiana chopper pilot finally decorated
this year with a Soldier's Medal for his attempt 30 years ago to
stop the My Lai massacre, came to the cafe wake. Though Ridenhour
was awarded no medals, Thompson and others hailed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ron would have been embarrassed to hear himself called a
hero,'' said Mary Howell, his companion for many years. ``But he
would have loved that his friends were sitting in the air
conditioning and drinking beer and talking about him for an hour
longer than was scheduled.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufauthor &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Wilkie is a member of the Globe staff, based in New
Orleans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
