<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9351 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     06-08 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDWATER KNEW HOW TO SALUTE THE UNIFORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barry Goldwater understood partisanship, and its limits. He also
knew the meaning of patriotism. Nobody had to tell him where one
left off and the other took over. An outspoken political
conservative and a Cold War hawk, Goldwater could have taught
useful lessons to the current breed of Democrats and Republicans
who are so full of themselves and so committed to the triumph of
their own causes that they scorn both moderation and manners.
</P>
<P>
   The first of those lessons is an old military dictum about
saluting the uniform. It goes like this: If you don't respect your
commanding officer enough to salute him sincerely, then salute the
uniform he's wearing. Extend to him the courtesy and consideration
that is owed to the office he holds. This goes for presidents,
obviously _ our commanders in chief _ and for certain other people
in life. How the current breed of congressmen, most without
military service of any sort, need to master that simple rule!
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater, like most members of Congress in that earlier
generation, was a veteran of World War II. We had shared, as
citizen soldiers, a common mortal endeavor on which our national
survival depended. We wished our leaders' plans well. Our lives
depended upon their success. We could grouse about those leaders,
but deliberately sabotaging them was never an option. The habit
grooves of that experience remain, carved deeply into our psyches.
</P>
<P>
   In the years after that titanic experience that altered the
course of so many lives, many legislators of both parties kept
their commissions in the reserve forces against the possibility of
being needed again for military service. We would go on active duty
three weeks each year.
</P>
<P>
   Every Wednesday morning on Capitol Hill, members of the 9999th
Air Force reserve squadron met for briefings on the world situation
and military readiness. The commander of our unit was Brig. Gen.
Barry Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats among us saw nothing amiss in this relationship. We
knew the metes and bounds of our respective military and civilian
duties. Defense Secretary Robert McNamara thought otherwise,
however, and in 1961 he disbanded the reserve military units
involving members of the legislative branch of our government.
Goldwater, along with the rest of us, accepted that verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona conservative was, in some ways, like Harry Truman.
Plain-spoken to a fault, he never hesitated to disagree with
presidents of either party when he thought one of them wrong on
public policy. He publicly faulted Richard Nixon over Watergate and
Ronald Reagan over Iran-contra, for example.
</P>
<P>
   But in spite of domestic political disagreements, he rallied to
Lyndon B. Johnson's side in August 1964 when North Vietnamese PT
boats fired repeatedly on the USS Maddox in the Tonkin Gulf and the
president ordered them and their supply base destroyed. Goldwater,
Johnson's opponent in that year's presidential election, was the
first person Johnson called, and the old soldier rallied to the
embattled president's side. Whatever their differences, he wanted
no partisan sniping to distract an American president from his
duties at a moment of international crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, although trailing Johnson in the polls and
desperately needing a political break, Goldwater steadfastly
refused to pounce on the personal tragedy of one of Johnson's aides
caught in a highly publicized homosexual liaison. The GOP candidate
harshly chastized one adviser who was goading him to take partisan
advantage of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   And years later, with Jerry Falwell tastelessly trying to equate
right-wing political policy with the Christian religion, Goldwater
said that Falwell deserved a ``kick in the ass.'' In the senator's
old-fashioned scale of interpersonal values, now ignored by so
many, some things were simply off-base. One was perverting religion
to political advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Another was attacking an opponent's patriotism or personal
character. Among the worst, we might infer, would be to let
partisan considerations interfere with the loyalty that each of us
owes the institutions of our government and the sometimes flawed
human beings charged with protecting those institutions.
</P>
<P>
   When it became belatedly clear in April 1984 that the CIA had
illegally invaded international waters, mined Nicaraguan harbors
and covered the deed with a fabric of lies, Goldwater was incensed.
He made no secret of his anger. Governments, ours included, had to
play by the rules. The administration, then headed by a member of
Goldwater's party, was derelict in tolerating so flagrant an abuse
of international law, he said forcefully to those responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when the Iran-contra scheme emerged, revealing a blatant
disregard for at least six laws and setting up ``impeachment''
whispers and a clamor for Reagan's scalp, calm heads prevailed. The
last thing America needed, I felt, was a frontal assault on the
president's personal character.
</P>
<P>
   By January 1987, I had been installed as speaker of the House.
Reagan had begun the last two years of his presidency. I knew his
dislike of detail, his occasional forgetfulness, his habit of
delegating broad responsibilities to others. I deliberately chose
to believe Reagan's vow that he hadn't condoned the flouting of
laws and couldn't remember ever being told of the elaborate scheme.
</P>
<P>
   A Democrat, I disagreed with Reagan on many issues. But I took
him at his word. He was president. I never wanted him personally
embarrassed. Then the country would be embarrassed, focus and
energy drained from great national goals. Reagan needed all his
credibility to negotiate effectively with the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Some don't understand that. Maybe they've never saluted a
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth, a Democrat, is a former speaker of
the U.S. House of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box
1413, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
