<HEADLINE>
MANY MALE CENTRAL AMERICAN IMMIGRANTS LEAD LONELY LIVES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHELSEA, Mass. _ The tangy aroma of beef stew wafted out a
window of a faded brick apartment building, where a flag of
Honduras rustled in the breeze. Two men sauntered in and rapped on
a door. It swung open, and a middle-aged lady wearing a
floral-print apron exclaimed, ``Ay, mis hijos, vengan.'' (Oh, my
sons, come inside.)
</P>
<P>
   Ramon and Julio stepped into a familiar world, an apartment
crowded with Central American men looking for a taste of home. In
the living room, four men at a card table leaned over bowls of
carne de res, a stew of beef, corn, cabbage, and potatoes. A
Spanish sports program blared from a TV in the background.
</P>
<P>
   In the kitchen, the lady placed plates full of stew, tortillas,
and white rice in front of Ramon and his friend. Ramon squeezed a
wedge of lime into the stew, stared at it, and saw the faces of his
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere I look, I see them,'' said Ramon, who left his five
children and wife in Honduras three years ago. ``I'm so lonely
without them. Here, at least I know I'm not alone.''
</P>
<P>
   On the weekends, this apartment of a Honduran grandmother _ like
a second mom to these men _ is one of dozens of places in Chelsea
where streams of lonely Central Americans congregate, to talk about
their homeland, their children, their wives, and the lives they
wish they could return to.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, they say they can't.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, where the unemployment rate ranges from 25 to 40
percent, their wives and children depend on the money they wire
weekly via Western Union, after a week of washing dishes,
assembling mattresses, loading trucks. The minimum-wage jobs make
their muscles sore and offer no benefits, but pay enough to help
their families survive. Most of them say they plan to return _
someday.
</P>
<P>
   Married men from Honduras, El Salvador, and Guatemala, almost
always illegal immigrants, are changing the face of northeastern
American cities like Chelsea, where they blend into predominantly
poor, but established, Latino communities. They live six or seven
to an apartment, scrimping to send every extra dollar home.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three weeks ago, a fire swept through four apartment
buildings on Essex Street in Chelsea, killing Roberto Lopez, an
illegal immigrant from El Salvador who shared an apartment with
seven other Central American men. He died trying to find money he
stashed under a mattress, as a roommate leaped from a third-story
window.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad,'' said Oscar Chacon, executive director of Centro
Presente, a Cambridge-based agency whose mission is to help Central
Americans living in Massachusetts. ``They come here and live with
seven, eight, even 10 people in tiny apartments. They endure that
hardship for their families back home.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 85,000 illegal immigrants lived in Massachusetts in
1996, according to the most recent estimate by the US Immigration
and Naturalization Service. INS doesn't keep more specific
information on undocumented workers, but Chacon's agency estimates
there are about 20,000 undocumented Central Americans in the state.
They arrive in a steady flow each year.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, INS has expelled illegal immigrants at record
pace. Men like Ramon say they break the law because they have few
alternatives. Their only work opportunity at home is often in sweat
shops of American companies, they say; the jobs pay less than their
own countries' minimum wage, or about $140 a month.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; gfdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,s1,s2,s3,s4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,38,14,14,15 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A neighborhood of men
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el5 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,v1,v2,v3,v4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,0,0,0,0 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufdrop,3,160 &LR; Lining the streets of south Chelsea are
dilapidated double- and triple-deckers, homes worn from generations
of immigrants who have lived here. Along Broadway, the main
business corridor, signs in Spanish outnumber English ones.
</P>
<P>
   The melodic sounds of rancheros, Cumbias, and boleros favored in
Central America compete with the pulsating rhythms of Puerto Rican
salsas and Dominican merengues. Music is a constant, blaring from
cars and through patios, where men sit and read Spanish-language
newspapers on a hot -evening.
</P>
<P>
   It's a neighborhood largely of men.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturdays, men fill two neighborhood laundromats, washing
clothes that, back home, their wives would scrub by hand. Nearby
fields and playgrounds are filled with men playing their beloved
soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought of coming here to live,'' Ramon said. ``I
don't want to be here. Every day, I think about going home, but if
I do, what will my children eat? They wouldn't be able to continue
in school.'' &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ramon, 50, is tall and thin. He wears a silver Levi's belt
buckle with his jeans and boots, and always wears long-sleeved
shirts, even on the hottest days _ a tradition of a genteel culture
he brought with him.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes when he wakes, he forgets where he is. His feet
planted on the low-grade carpet in his room, his dark brown eyes
focus, and he sees the sum of his American existence: a rickety
twin-sized bed, a dresser missing a drawer, five changes of clothes
hanging in the closet, a jug of Mazola corn oil, a roll of toilet
paper.
</P>
<P>
   He shares that room with Julio, a 39-year-old man from El
Salvador who sneaked into the United States 17 years ago and now
has a green card that allows him to legally live and work in the
United States. Nonetheless, Julio wants to keep his identity
hidden, so INS won't be able to track Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   They each pay $100 in rent to the main renters, a Guatemalan
couple who are also here illegally. Another man from El Salvador
rents another room. The five met in Chelsea and moved in together,
cutting down on expenses so they would have more money to send back
home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; gfdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,s1,s2,s3,s4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,38,14,14,15 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A billion-dollar export
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el5 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,v1,v2,v3,v4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,0,0,0,0 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufdrop,3,160 &LR; A
</P>
<P>
   s the sun rises above Chelsea, Ramon walks down the street,
where a van offers him and a dozen other men a ride to a factory in
a nearby suburb.
</P>
<P>
   There, he stands for hours at a time, dipping into batter
codfish that will be frozen and sold at supermarkets. He makes
$5.75 an hour, about $240 a week before taxes. He sends more than
half of it back home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  On the weekends, his wife and five children, &UR;  &LR; ages 6 to 13,
take a two-hour bus ride to Ramon's brother's home in Honduras,
because he has a phone. Ramon anxiously calls, and the conversation
is always the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tell me to come back home. I want to ...,'' he said, his
voice wavering. He takes a breath, as tears fill his eyes. ``It's
lonely. But I don't know what else to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon said most of the men from his village don't live at home;
most live in cities across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole generation of Central Americans here in
America,'' said Julio, Ramon's roommate and best friend. ``Our
children are being raised without fathers. It's so sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Several forces created the climate that caused this influx:
political unrest, human-rights abuses, poverty. In the 1980s, when
El Salvador, Nicaragua, Honduras, and Guatemala were facing
rebellions, young men fled because government and rebel forces were
putting high-powered guns in their hands, forcing them to a
showdown they wanted no part of.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the case of El Salvador and Nicaragua, the US
government poured millions of dollars in military aid to squash
rebellion, and the civil wars raged on.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration patterns have changed since peace returned to those
countries. Now, many are driven by poverty, following relatives who
discovered they can make a living wage in the United States. A new
wave of immigrants _ older, married fathers _ have taken the place
of single young men.
</P>
<P>
   ``The population of Central Americans in the US has become a
beacon of hope for the ones left behind,'' Chacon said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Salvadorans in the United States sent $1.2 billion
back home, according to the Salvadoran Central Reserve Bank, which
tallies figures from banking institutions. That's a lot considering
the country, which is about the same size as Massachusetts, sells
just under $2 billion a year in coffee exports, its largest cash
crop.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; gfdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,s1,s2,s3,s4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,38,14,14,15 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A dream in the distance
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el5 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; dm0,v1,v2,v3,v4 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; sv1,0,0,0,0 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufdrop,3,160 &LR; On the street where Ramon lives, it seems every
Central American has a plan: how much they need to save to buy land
back home, or to start a business. Most of them say it'll be just
another year or two before they return. Ramon said the same thing
when he arrived three years ago. But the money vanishes.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to save $3,000, buy two buses, and start a
transportation business. But almost every extra dollar is wired to
his family, making his dream distant and unsure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside, I feel like my heart is broken in half,'' Ramon said,
sitting on his twin bed. ``The other half is back home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
