<HEADLINE>
MY PERSONAL YOSSARIAN'S LIVER? THE CROSSWORD PUZZLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL K. HARRAL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a scene in Joseph Heller's classic book, ``Catch-22,''
where Yossarian is in the hospital and the doctors are trying to
figure out what's wrong with him.
</P>
<P>
   (Want to challenge whether ``Catch-22'' is a classic? A spot
check of our electronic database shows 345 hits on that phrase,
used, interestingly enough, mostly in sports and political copy.
That's a fair number, even after you exclude the references to
catching passes of 22 yards and fish of 22 pounds.)
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the doctor finally reaches a diagnosis: It's Yossarian's
liver.
</P>
<P>
   How, Yossarian wants to know, did he decide that?
</P>
<P>
   Because, says the doctor, he only missed one day in medical
school and it was the day they talked about livers and Yossarian
doesn't have anything he recognizes, so it must be the liver.
</P>
<P>
   There are days in this job when I feel like Yossarian and
there's a Catch-22 in everything the newspaper tries to do. A
Catch-22, by the way, is the hidden qualification that makes it
impossible to win. In the book, airmen don't have to fly combat
missions if they are crazy. But not wanting to fly combat is proof
that you are sane.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly I feel like Yossarian's doctor.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point: I didn't miss many days in journalism school,
but I must have been absent the day they talked about crossword
puzzles.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Fort Worth Star-Telegram managed to print the
wrong comics page, which is where we run The New York Times'
crossword.
</P>
<P>
   There's a way you can tell whether it is the right page: For one
thing, the crossword puzzle is numbered sequentially. For another,
there's generally a date somewhere in the cartoon panels.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, we used to assemble the comics pages by hand.
Now we job that out, and the page arrives as an electronic package
well in advance of the publication date. It is captured and
eventually placed on the page electronically as a unit.
</P>
<P>
   We work far in advance on some sections, so there are a lot of
comics pages floating around in the computer system. And when you
combine humans and computers, occasionally mistakes happen. In this
instance, the computer file was misnamed when it was downloaded.
</P>
<P>
   So even though we ought to be able to figure out what comics
page prints when, sometimes we don't figure it out. And when that
happens, it's the crossword puzzle fans who are the first to
notice, and they notice not so much because of the current puzzle
but because we print yesterday's answers as well.
</P>
<P>
   I don't work crossword puzzles. But judging from the reaction,
having the wrong answers in the paper is very disappointing. Having
the answers to a future puzzle is a little _ or maybe a lot _ like
rummaging through a closet and finding all your Christmas presents.
It sort of spoils the main event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I folded the answers under so I wouldn't see them,'' one
caller told me.
</P>
<P>
   There are some things you'd rather not be experienced in, and
messing up the crossword puzzle is one of them. But since we do
have some experience here, we did the only logical thing we could
do: We just reprinted the page.
</P>
<P>
   We shuddered at the expense, and we hated to give up valuable
news space to do it, but we did it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   And even though I remember talking about freedom of information
and the First Amendment and ethics and the laws of libel and
headline writing and story structure and all of that in college, I
can't remember a single lecture about the importance of the comics
pages and the crossword puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   That's a shame.
</P>
<P>
   You think I'm going to make fun of crossword puzzle fanatics
here, but I'm not. I'm going to make another point: A newspaper is
a collection of many things, each of them supremely important to
someone and not very important to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   The day may come when we are able to print newspapers designed
specifically for one person, containing only the subject matter he
or she is interested in and delivered to the doorstep as though it
were a mass-produced product.
</P>
<P>
   You sort of already have that available through online services
such as star-telegram.com, but you have to do some of the searching
and selecting yourself rather than have a bunch of people do it for
you and assemble it into precisely the package you want.
</P>
<P>
   And even if we ever are able to completely customize a
newspaper, I'm not so sure that's a good thing. I learn a great
deal about subjects I didn't know I was interested in by stumbling
across stories about them in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, there may have been two lectures that did
deal with crossword puzzles obliquely. Both were delivered by David
McHam, who will soon begin teaching journalism at the University of
Texas at Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   In one, McHam said that a newspaper is like a lumberyard. A
lumberyard that sells only two-by-fours isn't going to be in
business long, because sometimes people want doors and sometimes
they want panes of glass and sometimes they want sheets of plywood,
and you'd better have them in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Some newspaper readers want ads and some want sports and some
want international news and some want comics and some want
crossword puzzles.
</P>
<P>
   In the other lecture, McHam asked us who the final judges were
on whether a newspaper was doing its job. The question prompted
much discussion, which ended when McHam waved toward the windows.
</P>
<P>
   The experts, he said, are out there. They are the people who buy
and read the newspaper. They are the only ones who really know.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul K. Harral is ombudsman for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
His e-mail address is harral(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
