<HEADLINE>
TURKEY KEEPS THE POSTAL SERVICE AT BAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Along Loughlin Street, residents may soon have to
invest in a sign that reads: Beware of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Several times over the last six months, a troublesome tom has
attacked postal trucks, pecking at their tires and preventing
carriers from delivering mail to nine homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't interfere every day,'' said Mary Madonna, a
spokeswoman for the U.S. Postal Service in Albany. ``But when it
does, the carriers can't get through without damaging the truck or
the turkey.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents said the turkey and several hens have been living
peacefully in the woods surrounding the dead-end street in New
York's state capital for several years. For some reason, the bird
began attacking mail trucks over the winter, said Lloyd Hebert, 68,
a resident.
</P>
<P>
   The turkey seems to have a vendetta against mail trucks, said
Hebert, who scatters cracked corn and sunflower seeds in his yard
for the bird. No one has ever seen it attack a person or a vehicle
other than the mail truck.
</P>
<P>
   James Palmer, 76, theorized that the bird might have been
offended when a mail carrier leaned out the truck window and
gobbled at it a few months back. Hebert wondered whether the turkey
considers the eagle emblazoned on the mail truck a rival.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting Loughlin Street Friday, Karl Parker, a senior
wildlife biologist with the state Department of Environmental
Conservation, concurred with Hebert's suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not inconceivable that the turkey might be in breeding
mode and perceive the eagle on the truck to be another male,''
Parker said. ``Nobody ever said turkeys had a whole lot of brain.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker estimated that the turkey is between 2 and 3 years old
and weighs about 17 pounds. He said the conservation department has
not yet decided whether trapping and removing the bird would be
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But Parker did suggest Hebert install a conventional bird feeder
that turkeys can't reach to discourage them from sticking around.
</P>
<P>
   But Hebert said he would rather go a few days without mail than
lose the bird, which has become the unofficial neighborhood mascot.
Neighbors pick up their mail at the post office when the truck
can't get through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd miss it,'' he explained. ``We really like seeing that
turkey. In fact, we watch for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
