<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANELS OF SPECIALISTS OFFER PRESCRIPTIONS FOR A LONG, HEALTHY LIFE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With nearly 10,000 Americans turning 50 every day, prescriptions
for long life are tumbling forth in bewildering array. Take your
vitamins. Don't bother, just eat your vegetables. Swallow a daily
dose of DHEA. No, it's dangerous. Limit your fat calories. It's the
type of fat that matters, not the amount. Work up a serious sweat.
No, brisk walks are enough. Had your selenium today? Trivalent
chromium?
</P>
<P>
   Amid the cacophany, whom should you believe?
</P>
<P>
   Two credible new prescriptions come from expert panels that
sifted through the data to glean the best up-to-date evidence on
what aging adults can do to increase their chances of a long and
healthy life.
</P>
<P>
   One collection of 14 leading gerontologists, nutritionists, and
exercise researchers, convened by a private foundation called the
International Longevity Center, last week released a report called
``Prescription for Longevity: Fads and Reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The Center's starting point was the fountain-of-youth claims
made for such things as DHEA (dihydropepiandosterone), a
testosterone precursor that many experts fear could spur the growth
of incipient cancer. ``We saw the need for more rational discussion
of what we really know.'' says Dr. Robert N. Butler, a New York
geriatrician who heads the Longevity Center and formerly led the
National Institute on Aging.
</P>
<P>
   The other blue-ribbon group, which met in Boston in late May,
represents the World Health Organization's first attempt to define
optimal aging guidelines for the whole planet. Its report will not
be issued for some months, but participants discussed their
findings in interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guidelines represent a landmark. They will be very, very
important because the WHO is so respected,'' says Patrick R. Kenya,
chief of epidemiology and preventive medicine at Kenya's Moi
University, who adds that developing nations have barely begun to
address issues of aging.
</P>
<P>
   The WHO's goal is nothing less than to boost the quality of
elders' lives in rich and poor nations everywhere so their
burgeoning numbers will be more of a boon than a bane.
</P>
<P>
   Every month, the number of elders worldwide (defined as
individuals over age 55) jumps by 1.2 million people, notes Dr.
Vijay Chandra, director of India's Centre for Aging Research and a
member of the WHO panel. Four out of five are in developing
nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in human history'' prepares societies for the
longevity revolution, says Jeffrey B. Blumberg of Tufts
University's Jean Mayer/US Department of Agriculture Center on
Human Nutrition and Aging, which organized the WHO panel. ``Better
nutrition can help us avert a guaranteed catastrophe if we start
now. It's doable, and the impact would be enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sets of advice, summarized in the accompanying article,
overlap but not completely. Much is standard dogma, although there
is value in having two groups of experts put their stamps on what
they consider the best current thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these recommendations will not come as a surprise'' to
someone who ``exercises regularly, eats a balanced diet, watches
his or her weight, and keeps abreast of current developments in
health research,'' the Longevity Center report admits. ``Sadly,
however, this is not a description of the average American.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 20 percent of Americans eat the recommended five servings
of vegetables and fruits daily, the panel notes, and only 10
percent exercise religiously.
</P>
<P>
   On some points, the prescriptions are provocative _ such as the
WHO panel's conclusion that people over age 65 or 70 don't have to
worry as much about their weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do say you can safely gain some weight at older ages,''
said Irwin H. Rosenberg, director of the Jean Mayer/USDA Center,
who chaired the WHO panel.
</P>
<P>
   The debate centers on National Institute on Aging data showing
that mortality rates actually go up among older people who maintain
a body mass index (BMI) of 25 or less _ the lean profile advocated
by US health officials for all adults.
</P>
<P>
   Other researchers argue that this reflects the effect of older
cigarette smokers, who tend to be leaner but die more often of
smoking-related diseases. But the WHO panel disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our consensus was that among people over age 70, heavier
people tend to be more functional and thinner people tend to be
frail,'' said Dr. Ronenn Roubenoff of Tufts. ``The median BMI among
Framingham Heart Study participants is 28 for people with an
average age of 78. These are healthy, sucessfully aging people,
although many do have age-associated diseases. How do you argue
with success?''
</P>
<P>
   The other standout advice is the rigorous exercise standard set
by the Longevity Center. Few people (even among the 14 panel
members, one suspects) walk or run four miles a day, five days a
week. Even fewer lift weights, advice that should pay off in fewer
falls, better functioning, and healthier metabolism.
</P>
<P>
   Butler acknowledges not everyone will reach the goal. But if the
question is ``What does the best evidence suggest?'' that was the
panel's answer. ``We thought we'd be courageous enough to try it
out,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Longevity Center officials say they don't have copies of
``Prescription for Longevity'' available for the general public.
They plan to make it available at some point on a website.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
