<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9399 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-BLACKS-COX     06-08 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-BLACKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tiger woods' success and a growing black middle class draw
african-americans to the sport like never before.
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Memorial Day, the three men met at Atlanta International Golf
&AMP; Country Club in Decatur. Despite a midmorning tee time, they sat
in their carts for nearly an hour as group upon group of varying
abilities turned the No. 1 tee into golf gridlock. Unlike the
morning itself, however, the threesome wasn't steaming. One of them
fairly rejoiced, gazing around and thinking, ``This is
unbelievable. This is wonderful. This would've never happened 20
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   This was vivid evidence of golf's enormously increased
popularity among African-Americans in the Atlanta area, especially
among the burgeoning black middle class. Like most of the golfers
at Atlanta International that morning, the three men are black and
hooked on golf.
</P>
<P>
   So is Gregory Adams, 39, the chief presiding judge of the DeKalb
County Juvenile Court, who took up golf three years ago. ``And I
haven't stopped since. I love it. I look at the game as a form of
stress reduction.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Jatika Telfair of Clarkston, who founded Sisters Who Golf,
an organization that encourages African-American women and their
families to learn the mysteries of the flop wedge shot, or at least
how to grip the club properly.
</P>
<P>
   So is Patrick Desamours, 32, an investment broker who lives at
Hidden Hills Country Club in Stone Mountain and who, until 14
months ago, had considered golf ``a nonathletic sport that wasn't
worth the time.'' But since moving from his native New York to
Atlanta's warmer weather and taking up golf last year, Desamours
not only appreciates the game's complexities and recuperative
qualities but also the chance to do a little business outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest things that's attracting people now is this
whole thing of balancing business with pleasure,'' Desamours said.
``Every financial broker you've ever talked to said that's the way
to do business.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also the dramatic impact of Tiger Woods, whose historic
1997 Masters triumph, transcontinental drives and exuberance have
attracted millions _ particularly black women and junior golfers of
all races _ to the sport. Dave Ayers, the head pro at Mystery
Valley in Lithonia, estimates that minorities now constitute 25
percent of his business. ``Whereas three, four years ago, it was
negligible,'' he said. ``I'm sure it's because of Tiger's impact on
the game. I put him on my Christmas card list this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Batey understands. ``It's the Tiger thing,'' said Batey,
an assistant pro at Sugar Creek in DeKalb County. ``A lot of women,
their husbands played, but the Tiger thing has tweaked their
interest. My wife played because of me. But now her friends come to
me for lessons because of Tiger. They want to know what is it this
young brother is doing that mesmerizes people.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a matter of accessibility. While most of Atlanta's
exclusive private clubs are still overwhelmingly white, blacks have
access to some private country clubs and all public courses. That
wasn't so for Thomas Smith, who grew up in the shadow of the city's
nine-hole Candler Park course, was prohibited from playing there
before Atlanta's public golf courses were integrated and was cursed
at _ and sometimes pelted with rocks _ when he'd try to sneak on
and play, or even walk through the course on his way to caddie at
Druid Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Smith later helped integrate the city's public courses, was one
of Atlanta's first black club pros at Adams Park (now Tup Holmes)
and Candler Park, and staged Georgia's first integrated golf
tournament in the early '70s. He now runs a golf shop on Cleveland
Avenue, just down the road from Browns Mill Golf Course, which has
a rich tradition of supporting minority golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Blacks today) don't have any of the problems we had,'' Smith
said. ``All they have to do now to play is pay the money.''
</P>
<P>
   And they do. People like Tamika Hrobowski, 29, of Austell, a
lawyer with the Social Security Administration who had worked in
the Arkansas state prosecutor's office in Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Friday afternoons, everybody finished with court and the
guys would get together and go play golf,'' Hrobowski said. ``And
I'd be left behind to cover: `Sure, I'll cover for you.' I thought,
`One day, I'll play golf, too.' Just to go out with them and not
have to stay in the office and take complaints would be good.''
</P>
<P>
   As a kid growing up in Chicago, Hrobowski had played several
sports. Golf was never a consideration. She'd change TV channels,
see golf and watch a little before moving on. ``All you ever saw,''
she said, ``were older guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Older white guys, with plaid pants and big bank accounts. But in
Little Rock, Hrobowski was intrigued when her colleagues left early
on Friday to play golf. ``Something was drawing them out there,''
she said, ``and I wanted to know what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   She found out last year after moving to Atlanta. In October,
Hrobowski heard about Sisters Who Golf and picked up a golf club
for the first time. ``It's so encouraging to see somebody out there
who looks like you,'' she said. ``It was like, `OK, it's open to
us.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
