<HEADER>
A9400 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-FAMILY-COX     06-08 1464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-FAMILY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Cox writer Michelle Hiskey and her family, golf has been the
tie that binds.
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When my grandfather died, our family gathered in the small Idaho
town where he spent most of his 85 years. We grieved, greeted old
friends and laid Pete Hiskey to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Then we played golf.
</P>
<P>
   On the tee that day, only a few hours after the funeral, stood
my uncle, Babe, a regular on the Senior Tour who won two PGA
tournaments during a 25-year career. Next to him was my father,
Jim, who played the tour for five years and whose Christian
ministry serves golfers. Those two and another brother, Sonny,
played on nine NCAA championship teams.
</P>
<P>
   My brother Paul, soon to play the international pro circuit, was
there, along with our cousin Don, a club pro. Six of us attended
college on golf scholarships. Those of us who weren't playing for a
living were, for the most part, selling golf equipment.
</P>
<P>
   We had played some of the toughest courses in the world, but on
the day we buried Gramps, all of us teed off on a humble 18 holes
nestled in the western foothills of the Rocky Mountains. Riverside
Golf Course is pretty flat, and for $15 anyone can play all day
long.
</P>
<P>
   But it was sacred because it was the last of 18 golf courses our
grandfather built. A game so often viewed as a rich man's sport,
one that would shape all of our lives and frame moments of great
joy and heartbreak, for him started as a way to feed a hungry
family.
</P>
<P>
   Carving out courses
</P>
<P>
   My grandfather's grandfather came west on a Mormon ox-train in
1862, a harrowing journey to a promised land of bitter winters and
scorching summers. Soon the railroads simplified that crossing, and
his son _ my great-grandfather _ signed on as a railroad foreman.
His family lived in a boxcar set by the tracks in a remote corner
of southeast Utah. The youngest of his 10 kids was born in 1902 and
named Peter Marion.
</P>
<P>
   In the cemeteries of his hometown of Torrey, tiny tombstones
recall the children who could not survive the harsh conditions.
Those who made it learned to work at a young age and, when one job
ended, to find another. Gramps quit school in the eighth grade to
work on his brother's sheep ranch. As a shepherd, he spent weeks on
the range tending the herds, sleeping under the stars and, he would
later tell us, dodging rattlesnakes. He wore a big Stetson hat over
a face that seemed like all nose and ears.
</P>
<P>
   He once rode 100 miles to court the young woman he would marry,
and even after they settled down, he would leave home for weeks at
a time to find work. For a while, he labored in the mines and
routinely saw men die in dynamite accidents.
</P>
<P>
   When the Depression hit, the family had settled in Burley, a
small town in southern Idaho. Gramps' previous two jobs were as a
short-order cook and a nurseryman, but he was out of work. The
family relied on friends to bring them food.
</P>
<P>
   Gramps heard that the Works Progress Administration put men to
work building the city's first golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `There's no use kidding you guys,''' he related
to me years later. ``I don't know the first damn thing about
building a golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   He had never played the game, either. But the WPA, eager to give
work to the unemployed, put him on the crew. Gramps soon found
himself in charge.
</P>
<P>
   They used wheelbarrows to move the rocks and planted cottonwood
trees in the dusty soil. The first greens weren't even green _ they
were made out of sand. When the course was done, he played. That's
how he learned the game. The town asked him to stay on as the
course's caretaker, and when the economy improved, other towns
hired him to build courses and maintain them.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1930s, the family had grown to four kids and moved
to Twin Falls, a place later made famous by motorcyclist Evel
Knievel's attempt to soar across the Snake River Canyon. In that
steep gorge lies Blue Lakes Golf Club, where Gramps carved one of
the state's most beautiful courses out of boulders and brush.
</P>
<P>
   Learning the game
</P>
<P>
   The Hiskeys lived in a stone house on the city's municipal
course. The putting green was 10 feet from their back door; the tee
box 30 feet from their front steps. It might sound like they were
living in the clubhouse, but there wasn't one. The only other
structure around was the outhouse.
</P>
<P>
   My father played three holes each morning on his way to school,
and entered tournaments with money earned selling golf balls found
in ditches. It was the heyday of Byron Nelson and Ben Hogan, but
his big hero was his older brother, Sonny.
</P>
<P>
   Tall, gentle and handsome, Sonny mastered the game first and
showed his little brothers how to swing. ``He hit it so far that I
thought it'd never come down,'' my dad recalled. ``I just couldn't
believe he could hit the ball so far and so straight. ... He was
like a god to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Sonny did, the younger boys copied. After he won the
Idaho state amateur in the 1940s, the family defended the title
seven times in a row. Sonny won tournaments all over the Western
states, and caught the attention of college coaches. He went to
North Texas State on scholarship, and his team, which included Don
January, won the NCAA title 1949-52. The Korean War was going on,
so he postponed his plans to try the PGA Tour and served as a
reserve officer in the Air Force. The University of Houston,
meanwhile, recruited my father and his brother, Babe.
</P>
<P>
   Dad was on the ninth hole of a college tournament when his coach
approached. A terrible west Texas storm had come up. Sonny's plane
had gone down.
</P>
<P>
   Dad finished the round in a daze, shooting a 69 he barely
remembers. He finished the next day because Sonny would have wanted
it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Even though his team won the NCAA title that year, my dad was
filled with rage. One night he shook his fist at the sky and
screamed, ``Why did you take my brother and leave me? Why couldn't
you take me?''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, a buddy invited him to hear some noted athletes
talk about their Christian faith. That night, Dad found peace. He
began to see his athletic skills and Sonny's death as part of God's
plan.
</P>
<P>
   He played the PGA circuit for five years when the leaderboards
carried names like Snead, Palmer and a kid named Nicklaus. The
thrills of the tour, though, were eclipsed by a spiritual fervor.
With his brother Babe, he helped start the tour's weekly Bible
study, and later, his golf ministry based in Washington, D.C., took
him around the world for various tournaments and speaking
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``A stronger force was pulling me away from golf,'' Dad said.
But without golf, he might never have discovered his calling.
</P>
<P>
   Legacy lives on
</P>
<P>
   My first memory, at age 3, is of snow-capped peaks in a summer
when my father played the Canadian tour. My two brothers and I
watched the first man walk on the moon in an Ohio hotel room while
Dad played the Akron Open. Many of our trips ended in Idaho, and
Dad compared that trek to a blood cell winding through many
arteries before it reaches the heart.
</P>
<P>
   At home in suburban Washington, we dug up our back yard for
greens and sand traps that we hit to with chopped-down clubs. We
played with a dog found at one tournament who later died at
another.
</P>
<P>
   These Hiskeys ``all know how to play golf. And play it well,'' a
local sportswriter wrote in the Washington Star. ``It has been
planned that way. Ever since the crib.''
</P>
<P>
   Like my dad's generation, my brothers and I won a bunch of
junior tournaments and played golf in college. I knew from watching
my dad and uncle play that the pro life was not for me. I loved to
write. As I looked for a job, a byline in The Atlanta Constitution
caught my eye: Thomas Stinson, the former Washington Star reporter
who had written about my family and now covers the Atlanta Braves.
He helped me land an internship.
</P>
<P>
   I don't play that much anymore, except for last year, even
though _ or maybe because _ I was expecting my first child. On a
cold December afternoon, five days before Johanna was born, I
played two holes. We went par-bogey.
</P>
<P>
   She met the rest of the family when they gathered for the PGA
Merchandise Show in Florida. Since then, she's attended two pro
golf tournaments, and we often stroll around our neighborhood
course, occasionally picking up a stray Titleist.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes I feel sad, knowing that she will never meet her
great-grandfather and great-uncle. I realize how badly I want to
pass down the game to her, for it to mean as much to her as it does
to me. But as I wrote this story, I realized that golf had already
touched her life, long before she was born.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
