<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9402 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-FITNESS-QNA-COX     06-08 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-FITNESS-QNA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golfers must take care to be physically up to par
 &HT;    By Amanda Husted
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because recreational golfers aren't always the fittest of
athletes, many people assume that the sport isn't hard on the body.
But physicians who treat sports injuries see a fair number of
people injured on the golf course. Dr. Joanne B. ``Anne'' Allen, a
physi-atrist who specializes in sports and spine injuries and
occupational medicine with Peachtree Orthopedic Clinic in Atlanta,
talked about common problems for golfers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What kinds of injuries afflict golfers?
</P>
<P>
   A: The most common injuries for golfers are in the upper
extremities and the spine _ shoulder, elbow, wrist and lower-back
injuries. One reason is the biomechanical strain put on muscles by
the unnatural movement of swinging a club. Proper technique and
mechanics can help prevent strains and other injuries. And
performing specific exercises to strengthen the upper extremities
and the spine, and even basic stretches before you play, can be
beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are golfers at risk for heat exhaustion?
</P>
<P>
   A: Golf is not as athletic as track and field, for instance, but
golfers are outside in the same heat, and they often aren't in as
good physical condition. It's very important for golfers to remain
hydrated and avoid excess sun. They should drink at least eight
fluid ounces of water every 15 to 30 minutes on a hot, sunny day. A
golfer who drinks any alcohol during a round will be at higher risk
for dehydration and that may contribute to development of heat
exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the symptoms of heat exhaustion?
</P>
<P>
   A: A feeling of light-headedness, sweating and fatigue,
accompanied by changes in skin color and blood pressure, may be
indicators of heat exhaustion. If you experience any of these
symptoms, sit or lie in the shade and drink fluids immediately,
then get to a cool environment.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about skin cancer?
</P>
<P>
   A: Obviously, the risks increase for anyone who spends a lot of
time in the sun, whether it's playing golf or tennis or some other
activity. Sunscreen is essential, and wearing a hat is important;
choosing loose-fitting clothing will help avoid heat exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the difference in walking vs. riding a cart, as far as
exercise?
</P>
<P>
   A: There is a significant difference in the amount of calories
burned in walking and riding in a cart, so walking is much better
for the average golfer from that standpoint. But it also depends on
how good a golfer you are _ if you're hitting the ball all over the
course, you may do a lot of walking. If you're walking and not
riding, you'll also keep your back muscles limber and warmed up,
which may lower your risk of injury. But anyone who already has
back pain or injuries may be better off riding to avoid aggravating
them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you get injured, should you stop playing for a while?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's specific to the individual case, and depends on how
severe the injury is. If there is concern about continuing to play,
check with your doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Fax questions for our fitness experts to 404-526-5977; or send
e-mail to mwilson(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
