<SLUG> BC-GOLF-FITNESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Improving strength, flexibility and endurance can improve your
golf game.
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike tossing the caber or performing the clean and jerk, golf
does not involve displays of physical prowess.
</P>
<P>
   The incorrect corollary that often follows is that golf does not
require physical prowess. It does. To play golf, and to play it
well, a person needs strength, flexibility and endurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can work muscles that actually help the golf swing,'' said
Gary King, a teaching professional at RiverPines Golf Club in
Alpharetta, Ga.. ``You can increase your own stamina and
flexibility when you just thought you were going to have to use
graphite clubs for the rest of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   King, 42, does strength training and cardiovascular exercise
twice a week, in addition to his daily stretching exercises. He
developed his workout program with trainer Kelly Blackburn of
Alpharetta-based Elite Personal Fitness Trainers.
</P>
<P>
   In the several months since King started working with Blackburn,
his clubhead speed has increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds strange, but being able to relax your muscles
through the swing helps you hit the ball farther,'' King said. ``My
muscles are stronger and can relax better, which helps the speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Calf raises have strengthened a previously torn Achilles' tendon
that used to give him trouble, and the general aches and pains that
plagued him after a day of countless golf swings have eased. He
said he doesn't need Advil as much anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Blackburn, who works with the PGA Tour and often travels to
tournaments to help players, emphasizes that golfers can benefit
from overall physical conditioning as much as athletes in other
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, flexibility is key in golf,'' Blackburn said.
``A golfer has got to have the flexibility in the trunk for a full
shoulder turn.''
</P>
<P>
   On the PGA Web site (at http://www.pga.com), Blackburn
demonstrates various exercises that contribute to better
flexibility, strength and endurance. For midsection flexibility,
she recommends a trunk-rotation stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've also got to have overall strength, a strong base for
stability and power generated out of the hips,'' Blackburn said.
``That's what generates power behind the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Biceps curls, triceps kickbacks and lateral raises using hand
weights will improve arm and shoulder strength and help prevent
injury. Using hand weights also can increase forearm and wrist
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Marietta's Larry Nelson, another of Blackburn's loyal clients,
has greatly increased his strength and driving ability, she said.
Using the same clubs and balls, Nelson added 20 yards to his
driving distance after starting an exercise program.
</P>
<P>
   ``His results caught the eye of the PGA,'' Blackburn said.
</P>
<P>
   The most common injury among golfers is back strain. Strong
abdominal muscles are vital to improving posture and strengthening
the back. Blackburn suggests abdominal crunches and neck stretches.
Flexible, limber muscles are less likely to tear or be strained.
</P>
<P>
   The third prong of Blackburn's fitness program for golfers is
cardiovascular exercise, to boost endurance.
</P>
<P>
   Many golfers consider 18 holes a relaxing way to spend a
Saturday afternoon, but finishing the course is a chore for some.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come to me and say, `I start losing steam at about hole
13,' '' Blackburn said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and other health experts recommend at least 20 minutes
of aerobic exercise per day, three times a week, for overall
health. Aerobic exercise is anything that elevates the heart rate,
such as brisk walking, running, bicycling or aerobics.
</P>
<P>
   To learn more about specific exercises that can benefit golfers,
look up the PGA Tour Web site. Elite Personal Fitness Trainers also
has a site (http://www.elite-fitness.com).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
