<SLUG> BC-GOLF-HUMMER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: A visit to the swing doctor
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If men would analyze themselves as much as they did their golf
swings, imagine how the world might be bettered. Think of the
marriages strengthened, the children uplifted, the careers
expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, yeah. Yadda, yadda. Listen, one must keep these things in
perspective. What's the point of a happy home if it can't help you
break 100?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we would delve more into the intimate aspects of our lives
if they were anywhere near as fascinating as the search for the
perfect tee shot. If you could tape the marriage and break it down
to geometric components, then counselors would make as much as golf
pros.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the Norcross laboratory of George Kelnhofer, and be
prepared to be dazzled by the many facets and complexities of golf.
From his Georgia Golf Center headquarters, Kelnhofer would face one
of his greatest challenges: Dissecting the cadaver that is my
swing.
</P>
<P>
   Is there really anything that can be done to correct a
self-taught hacker who has spent a lifetime unmatching his set of
clubs and ingraining every fault until it has become habit?
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't take any longer to fix a 20-year player than it does a
20-minute one,'' Kelnhofer said with confidence. At $60 per
half-hour, here's hoping for a quick cure.
</P>
<P>
   But how much can just a few lessons really help the seemingly
hopeless player? If such a mope had a handicap, it easily could be
cut in half, Kelnhofer said. ``Most golfers' short games are very
bad; that's one area where you can make some rapid improvement,''
he promised.
</P>
<P>
   This lesson, however, was to center on the tee shot. Of my many
crimes I commit on a golf course, none is more heinous than those
done with driver in hand. I'm a big guy who hits a small ball.
While the rest of the world is gripping it and ripping it, I'm
chopping it and flopping it.
</P>
<P>
   On the tee is where Kelnhofer brings the full force of
technology to bear. Using a series of cameras and, of course, a
computer, he can break any swing all the way down to the smell.
Clearly, the science involved in launching golf ball and smart bomb
are almost equal.
</P>
<P>
   We proceed to his practice area, where even the process of
teeing up the ball is automated. Here, I take a couple of my usual
hacks for analysis back on the computer screen. Just let loose the
swing that says to the world, ``Lizzie Borden was my swing
doctor.'' It's one thing to have to witness the result of a bad
swing, and then go chasing it in the gorse. It's even worse to
actually step outside yourself and watch the swing in progress. You
see this horrible accident in progress and are helpless to do
anything about it. You knew it was that bad; you just didn't know
it was that obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Kelnhofer accentuates the flaws by splitting the screen and
calling up any number of smooth-swinging professionals as points of
comparison. Standing me up next to David Duval is as abhorrent as
displaying Dogs Playing Poker and the Mona Lisa on the same museum
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Three different cameras detail the atrocities. Rear view, side
view and even a shot from on high to remind this player he could
use some Rogaine as well as a little more shoulder turn.
</P>
<P>
   Then superimposed over Mr. Slice are nine different lines that
make up the blueprint of the proper swing.
</P>
<P>
   My set-up, I'm happy and proud to announce, was right in line.
The stance was pretty good. Nobody can stand better. But when
things start moving, it all falls apart like a Russian car.
</P>
<P>
   My pivot was stiff and awkward, Tin Man-like. And on the
downswing, the club was so far above the proper line that it
appeared I was trying to drive a tent stake instead of a golf ball.
At the point of contact, trying to make up for all the wrong that
went before, I was all up on my toes and out of balance. Those are
the swings that buy chiropractors beach homes.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to take a moment here to praise Kelnhofer's upstanding
professionalism. At no time did he fall to the floor in laughter or
run away in defeat. He stayed hard at it for the full hour, earning
total trust. By the end, I was ready to confess all my sins to him.
</P>
<P>
   He just went to work showing little tips and gimmicks to help
bring the swing more in line. More tilt, more shoulder turn,
tighten up on the hip movement. Sure enough, by the end, I was
coloring more inside those computer lines. The ball still wasn't
going anywhere, but that wasn't important at the moment. ``The golf
ball lies to you,'' Kelnhofer said. Over the last two decades, it
has been telling me some particularly vicious ones.
</P>
<P>
   With a tape of my lesson in hand, I could go boldly forth and
try to practice the techniques he crammed into the hour. He
attempts to keep it remedial, but there still seems an awful lot of
thought to take to the practice range. ``It's no different than
dance lessons. You've got to know where your feet go before you can
do it,'' he said. Well, I've tried dance lessons, and those didn't
take, either.
</P>
<P>
   What one golf lesson showed was the possibilities, and just how
much more I must invest in the game if I ever want to do it
competently. I know now I can improve, as long as I don't allow my
personal life to get in the way.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
