<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-INTERNET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web's awash in golf sites of every stripe
 &HT;    By David Davidson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Golf, an outdoor sport, and the Internet, an indoor medium,
might seem like polar opposites, but they do have something in
common: One is just as unlikely to keep you in shape as the other.
</P>
<P>
   However, golfers who address a keyboard and monitor before they
address a Titleist on the first tee might discover great benefit.
Even those who aren't into wearing pastel and would rather watch
golf on TV than actually play the game will find the Internet most
helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Golf sites are among the most prolific on the Web. There are
literally thousands to choose from _ from the very general to the
exquisitely specific, from those international in scope to sites
dedicated to the course just down the street.
</P>
<P>
   The four major tournaments hold a special fascination for
golfers, beginning with the Masters, played annually the first full
week of April. Next up is the U.S. Open, June 18-21, at the Olympic
Club near San Francisco, followed by the British Open, July 16-19,
at Southport, England, and finally the PGA Aug., 13-16, at Redmond,
Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Golf Association and the PGA Tour both have excellent
sites. Even the Royal and Ancient Golf Club of St. Andrews, which
has produced ``the Open'' championship since 1860, has waded into
cyberspace. If surfing all those sites involves too much mouse-age,
there's one site that gives in-depth scrutiny to all four major
tournaments: Golf Majors.
</P>
<P>
   http://www. masters.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www. usga.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.randa.org/
</P>
<P>
   http://www. pgatour.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.golfmajors.com
</P>
<P>
   The LPGA also has a thorough site for those interested in the
women's pro tour.
</P>
<P>
   http://www. lpga.com
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of mega-sites of interest to both players and
observers of golf, which provide everything from PGA, Seniors and
LPGA stats to worldwide guides to courses to travel packages to
weather. Infobeat will even e-mail news and information on golf _
free _ to subscribers. Golfonline, an electronic product of Golf
Magazine, is a superb site.
</P>
<P>
   http://www. golfweb.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www. iGOLF.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www. golf.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www. infobeat.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www. golfonline.com
</P>
<P>
   Most of the best players have their own Web sites. Jack
Nicklaus' site not only details his playing career but his
corporate side _ particularly course architecture _ as well. It's
no surprise that Tiger Woods has a site, but he's so popular
there's an unofficial site that allows surfers to jump to a variety
of other sites devoted to Woods. Chi Chi Rodriguez, one of the most
colorful players ever to play the game, uses his Web site to
forward his Youth Foundation, which seeks to help at-risk kids.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.nicklaus.com
</P>
<P>
   http://tigerwoods.com
</P>
<P>
   http://websites2000.com/
</P>
<P>
   golf/twoods/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.chichi.org
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of a trend toward boorish gallery behavior over the
last several years, etiquette among the players is still
sacrosanct. Now there's an Internet site addressing that part of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   http://www. mrgolf.com
</P>
<P>
   One dilemma golfers always face is which ball to play. There are
dozens of brands, compressions, etc., on the market. The Golf Ball
Place might help. Golfers can purchase online high-spin balls,
distance balls, a blend of those two traits, specialty balls.
There's even a history of the evolution of the golf ball, beginning
in 1550, when balls were solid wood.
</P>
<P>
   http://www. thegolfballplace.com
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia State Golf Association has a useful site that
provides players with rules, course ratings, handicaps, a junior
golf program and a hall of history.
</P>
<P>
   http://www. gsga.org
</P>
<P>
   Two other solid sources of in-state information are Georgia Golf
News and Atlanta Golfer. Both have information on everything from
public and private courses to driving ranges to playing tips, to
lessons to real estate to classifieds _ all aimed at the local
golfer.
</P>
<P>
   http://www. golfbits.com/
</P>
<P>
   http://www. golfatlanta.com
</P>
<P>
   There's also a site that shows, in graphic form, scorecards of
various courses around the state.
</P>
<P>
   http://golf.traveller.com/golf/
</P>
<P>
   scorecards/Georgia/
</P>
<P>
   Even local clubs are going into cyberspace. Stone Mountain and
Atlanta National are two of many examples.
</P>
<P>
   http://www. evergreenresort.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www. angc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
