</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-KIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Making golf fun for kids is part of teaching them to love the
game for life and to get on the right course.
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So your child saw Tiger Woods on television and wants to swing
into action. Before you buy an expensive set of clubs, spikes and
collared shirts, experts advise giving children the lay of the
land.
</P>
<P>
   With school out, many area golf courses, public and private, are
offering clinics or beginner programs for youngsters. Club pros
teach rules and etiquette, along with the correct grip, stance and
swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing for children to learn is swing and
control,'' said Craig Forney, head golf professional at RiverPines
in Alpharetta, Georgia. ``Most of the kids are into trying to hit
it onto the back of the range, like Happy Gilmore. They all want to
hit for power.''
</P>
<P>
   Forney stresses balance and a smooth swing to Wood-be players.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to learn the fundamentals first before you can be
Tiger Woods,'' Forney said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts believe children should be introduced to the game when
they show interest and enthusiasm. Of course, some parents bring
their 3- or 4-year-old to a pro for lessons, despite the child's
two-minute attention span. A more common starting age is 7 or 8,
although the bulk are in the 10-12 age group. Teenagers also are
choosing to pick up the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about a child is they are so willing to
learn,'' said Sam Puryear, executive director of the East Lake
Junior Golf Academy.
</P>
<P>
   To keep their interest, Puryear said he believes in instilling
fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids don't want to do something that's monotonous,'' he said.
``Don't spend all the time worrying about 'Do they have the proper
grip? Are they taking it back straight?' After a couple of years
ensuring the kids have a great time and letting them whack at it a
little bit, they develop a proficiency and then can fine-tune
certain skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Because children can outgrow their interest or their equipment,
experts suggest a modest investment in clubs, sometimes as little
as $40 for a set. Adult clubs can be cut down, but they are not
properly balanced and weighted for youth players. Some companies
make child-sized clubs, including Duluth-based U.S. Kids Golf,
which sells a driver, 7-iron, wedge and putter.
</P>
<P>
   Beginner programs allow tennis shoes and shorts and some don't
require collared shirts. However, Forney has had kids go the whole
nine yards and play in knickers.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the larger programs are offered by the Georgia State Golf
Foundation and the Atlanta Junior Golf Association.
</P>
<P>
   The GSGF will sponsor the Hook A Kid on Golf Tee Level Clinics
this summer at four Atlanta courses and one in Macon. The clinics
are for children 8-14 who never have played golf, do not own a set
of clubs and whose parents do not belong to a private golf club.
The kids receive donated clubs, a shirt and balls. For information,
contact Kim Doge, manager of foundation services, at 770-612-1788.
</P>
<P>
   The AJGA will expand its clinic program to five courses next
year and is taking names for the 1999 mailing list (call
770-850-9040 or check out the Internet at http://www.atljrga.org).
</P>
<P>
   The $115 program, with some scholarships available, includes a
get-acquainted event, six golf lessons and five play dates on a par
3 course. There are no cart fees because juniors carry their clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The AJGA prefers kids who know a bit about the game, ``whose
grandparent or parent has taken them to a driving range,'' said Pam
Shankland, director of the beginner program.
</P>
<P>
   The par 3 courses build self-confidence and self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they make a 10 on a hole, it's not fun to play,'' said
Shankland. ``They need to see some encouragement.''
</P>
<P>
   If kids join adults on a par 72 course, they should play from
where the older player has hit the ball to avoid a six-hour ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Puryear will let his 9-year-old son Antonio run in front of him,
``put his ball down and whack it. He knows when I catch up with him
to pick his ball up, it's time to go to the next hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
