<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9413 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-MARSHAL-COX     06-08 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-MARSHAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Erv Cherry defends against the worst enemy known to a busy
public golf course _ slow play.
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--Erv Cherry chases drunk drivers, unravels traffic jams
and tries to keep the peace. He's got his walkie-talkie, a special
vehicle and a regular beat to patrol _ everything but the
doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   But don't call him a cop. He's a marshal, a member of the thin
green line at North Fulton Golf Course. He wears a teal polo shirt
like his 21 fellow ``ambassadors,'' identifying them as defenders
against golf's most common enemy: slow play.
</P>
<P>
   Every Thursday, he cruises the course in his electric cart,
looking for trouble. At 69, a retired salesman with a Johnny Carson
twinkle in his eye, Cherry can persuade a beginner to pick up after
seven shots, cajole an executive to put away the cell phone and
shoo a big, barking stray dog.
</P>
<P>
   A widower who lives in Roswell, Cherry's life philosophy carries
over to his golf duties. ``Take the bitter with the sweet,'' he
says, ``and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   On the 15th hole, Jeff Scott of Memphis and his three sons are
poking around a creek, looking for the ball of one of the boys.
Scott reminisced about growing up nearby and playing in this same
stream.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry interrupts the history lesson. ``Copperheads down
there,'' he tells them.
</P>
<P>
   The family scrambles out of the gully, abandoning the ball.
Never mind that Cherry's never seen snakes down there. The
suggestion of danger works _ most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Cherry evacuated the course during a storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried,'' one golfer told him. ``I've never been
struck by lightning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think you had,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   For four years, Cherry's been in a line of fire that sometimes
defies geometry. Once, he parked under an old oak tree to watch a
hacker hit over a creek, and the ball spurted off at a right angle,
striking Cherry in the neck. That's one reason he always drives the
holes from green to tee, so he can see who's hitting. ``Keeps you
from getting killed out here,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He thought he had seen everything until the legendary Hooters
tournament a few years ago when some of the women from the
restaurant decided to play topless. No marshal intervened that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't do anything destructive,'' Cherry said, ``but they
sure screwed up traffic on Powers Ferry Road,'' which borders the
final two holes.
</P>
<P>
   And golfers hate gridlock. On a busy day, a foursome tees off
every 10 minutes at North Fulton, where 70,000 rounds are played
each year. Like driving in rush hour, it takes only one wreck _ a
lost ball, for instance _ to slow everyone else down.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry keeps the pack moving, from the beginners who whiff to
the sharks betting $50 a hole. The golfers who cop an attitude
usually have enjoyed a few too many cold beverages, and that's when
Cherry uses his walkie-talkie to call for backup from the pro shop.
The hassles are worth the payoff. In return for volunteering,
Cherry gets to play free golf. He tries to whittle down his 12
handicap by playing three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   During a round a couple of years ago, a ball flew onto a green
as he putted _ the equivalent of speeding in front of an off-duty
cop. The offender: David Justice, the former Braves outfielder.
``Do it again,'' Erv growled, ``and I'll kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a threat, just a bit of marshal humor. Guys like
Cherry seek to preserve the integrity of the sport because they
love it so much.
</P>
<P>
   He paused on the par-3 14th hole to remember Don Hipp, a fellow
marshal whose cremated ashes were scattered over this hole. ``The
next day it rained, but he's still there,'' Erv said, puffing on a
cigarette. ``I wouldn't mind that myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9421 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-WOMEN-COX     06-08 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-WOMEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The grass ceiling: Women feel uncomfortable in a game that is
dominated by men.
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A guy is playing golf with his wife and slices his tee shot into
the rough behind the barn. His wife says, ``Why don't I open the
door and you hit the ball through the barn toward the green?''
</P>
<P>
   The guy tries it, but the ball hits something inside the barn,
caroms off and hits his wife in the head, killing her.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the same guy is playing with a friend, and he
slices the ball behind the same barn. His friend says, ``Why don't
I open the door and you hit the ball through the barn toward the
green?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' the guy says. ``Last time I tried that here I made a
seven.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Grizzard got plenty of laughs from jokes about female
golfers who, he believed, got in the way of the good ol' boys.
</P>
<P>
   Stereotypes are only one of many barriers to women feeling
comfortable on the golf course. They often encounter discrimination
in club membership and tee times and a no-girls-allowed atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such obstacles, women are picking up the game in record
numbers, with the tenacity that they have shown in breaking into
the corporate world. They've banded together to find other female
players and tee up at courses that want them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf has been a male sport for so long ... and that trickles
down to the way we feel on the course,'' said Cindy Bettis, vice
president of the Amateur Golfers Association Tour of Atlanta. ``It
takes a while for us to realize that we can get out and be
competitive and feel comfortable. As long as women know the rules,
etiquette and pace of play, there's no reason they shouldn't be out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5.7 million women playing golf in this country represent
about 20 percent of all players but about 40 percent of all
beginners. Among the new golfers is Lois Thomas of Decatur, who
used to sum up golf with one word: dull. But after her husband and
co-workers got more involved in it, she started feeling left out.
As a computer analyst at BellSouth, she'd miss out on networking at
many corporate outings because she didn't know how to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``In golf, you're meeting a lot of people, and if you are an
executive or manager, it does make a difference,'' said Thomas, who
took her first lesson at a recent Golf for Women Day at Browns Mill
Golf Course. At home later, she practiced her swing with a broom.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family looked at me like I was crazy,'' she said, ``but I'm
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that women spend $3 billion on golf equipment and
greens fees each year, public golf courses are seeking their
business. Last month, Golf for Women Day drew 12,000 women to
courses operated nationwide by American Golf Corp. for free lessons
and rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Many private clubs, though, are not as welcoming. Georgia's best
female amateur players hold their championship during the week
because the best private courses usually reserve their prime
weekend tee times for members. As spouses of members, women have
lesser privileges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more elite the club, typically, the more discriminatory
against the women it is,'' said Lee Burton of Newnan, the two-time
Georgia Player of the Year. One of the best players at Atlanta
Athletic Club and a Furman University golf recruit, Leigh Turner
says she ``would like to go out before 12 (noon) on the weekends,
but I can't. On Saturday mornings, only members can play, and there
are only a few women members.''
</P>
<P>
   While law prohibits public courses from discriminating against
anyone who wants to play, the men can create a sometimes hostile
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's intimidating to be on the tee, know I'm not hitting well
and, oh, no, I've got three guys looking at me, and I've got to hit
this tee shot,'' said Anita Denney of Marietta. ``You just pray you
do.''
</P>
<P>
   To meet others like herself, Denney joined the Atlanta chapter
of the Executive Women's Golf Association. Its 360 women compete in
leagues almost daily. The group helps nurture beginners struggling
to master not only the intricacies of the swing but also the myriad
rules and etiquette points that can intimidate a player, regardless
of gender.
</P>
<P>
   Even if her skills need improvement, a woman will feel more
welcome on the course if she understands how the game is played and
is courteous to others, said Betsy Clark, director of education for
the Ladies Professional Golf Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women entering golf mirrors what society allows them to do,''
Clark said. ``Many people are recognizing that women can play this
game, and the myths are tumbling down.''
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   -- 5.7 million women play golf, representing 22 percent of all
golfers. Women make up 39 percent of the 3 million beginning
golfers.
</P>
<P>
   -- Since 1986, the number of women playing golf has increased 26
percent.
</P>
<P>
   -- The average age of women golfers is 43; for men, it's 39.
</P>
<P>
   -- The average household income for women golfers is $61,000;
it's $59,000 for men.
</P>
<P>
   -- Women golfers spend an average of $649 per year on golf; men
spend an average of $718.
</P>
<P>
   -- Women play, on average, 16 rounds per year; men play about 20
times.
</P>
<P>
   Source: National Golf Foundation
</P>
<P>
   QUICK TIPS
</P>
<P>
   Tips for women who want to start or improve at golf, and feel
comfortable on the course:
</P>
<P>
   -- Find other women golfers. Try the Executive Women's Golf
Association (770-984-7617) or Sisters Who Golf, a group for
African-American women (404-794-7000). Women with handicaps below
the mid-20s can compete in the Amateur Golfers Association Tour of
Atlanta (770-343-9969). Some public courses offer women's leagues.
</P>
<P>
   -- Look for women-friendly instructors and courses. Chateau Elan
in Braselton and Eagle's Landing Country Club were the only two
Georgia courses listed in Golf for Women magazine's top 175 courses
for women. They are judged on factors such as unrestricted tee
times, special women's programs, multiple women's tee markers,
child care, on-course restrooms, women's pro shop merchandise,
adequate locker rooms, practice areas and ``women-friendly'' male
staff and players.
</P>
<P>
   -- Take lessons _ but not from your husband or significant
other. ``The best piece of advice I give men is: Don't teach your
wife,'' said Bob Fritsche, regional manager for American Golf Corp.
``The game is too hard to understand, and the last thing a woman
wants is her husband yelling at her.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Relax. ``Women don't have to prove themselves; they're just a
regular person out there,'' said Cindy Bettis of the Amateur
Golfers Association Tour of Atlanta. ``If they don't make a big
deal of it, the guys won't, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
