<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL MILITARY FORCE FOR KOSOVO URGED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ British Prime Minister Tony Blair has called on
President Clinton and Russian President Boris N. Yeltsin to join in
preventing an all-out war in Kosovo, as the use of international
troops appeared imminent.
</P>
<P>
   In a 20-minute phone conversation Sunday, Blair and Clinton
discussed the possibility of using force to halt Serbian attacks on
ethnic Albanians. Blair, trying to forge a united response from
several nations, called Yeltsin and urged him not to oppose efforts
to resolve the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   In his strongest language of recent days, Blair told Yeltsin
that the international community, including Russia, must stop the
``barbarism'' in Serbia's southern province of Kosovo. During the
half-hour conversation, Blair asked Yeltsin to summon ``whatever
influence he has'' to persuade Slobodan Milosevic, president of the
Yugoslav Federation, to stop the killings. Serbia and Montenegro
are the two remaining republics of the Yugoslav Federation.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Blair, Clinton, and other Western leaders are
expected to authorize the use of troops to stop the bloodshed. At
the United Nations, the United States and Britain reportedly have
decided to seek an agreement authorizing ``all necessary measures''
against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   That is strong diplomatic language that would give NATO the
legal grounds to enter the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton decides to use force, he may initially have support
from Capitol Hill. Senate majority leader Trent Lott suggested that
he would support dispatching troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot allow this slaughter to occur,'' the Mississippi
Republican said on CNN's ``Late Edition.'' ``Once again the
Serbians are out of control. ... I'm not saying we should not
consider troops if it continues the way it is going.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurst Hannum, a professor of international relations at the
Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University, cautioned
that American and European leaders still have not agreed on clear
goals.
</P>
<P>
   The West has not endorsed independence for Kosovo, he said, yet
it is close to sending troops to the Kosovo-Serbian border _ a
maneuver that would seem to signal support for independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes sense to have troops poised, but I still wonder what
their purpose will be once they get in there,'' Hannum said.
</P>
<P>
   The flare-ups of violence in Kosovo and the flight of thousands
of refugees have rekindled old arguments about the obligations of
the United States and Western Europe in the ethnic and political
battles that rage in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Richard Holbrooke, the Clinton
administration's peace negotiator for Bosnia, said the West needs
to talk tough and back up its threats with troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're engaged in is classic preventative diplomacy,''
said Holbrooke, who brokered the Dayton peace accord of 1995 and
has been predicting violence in Kosovo for several months. ``There
is a mutual European-American mistake, and that is not realizing
the core lesson from Bosnia: The end of the Cold War did not mean
the end of America's obligations around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke and Robert Gelbard, US envoy to the area, have warned
that violence in Kosovo could spread to nearby areas with ethnic
tensions, including Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim Albanians are the overwhelming majority in Kosovo, where
several hundred people have been killed since fighting broke out in
February. Last week, thousands of Albanian refugees poured out of
villages destroyed by Serbian police fighting the rebels of the
Kosovo Liberation Army, or KLA. The rebels, who are becoming more
aggressive, on Sunday called on their ethnic brethren in Albania to
take up arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The KLA calls on all men from 18 to 55 years to join in the
struggle for the liberation of the country,'' the guerrillas said
in a statement published in an Albanian newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Serb forces reportedly continued shelling suspected
militant positions in western Kosovo. Albanian television reported
that rebels had blown up the police headquarters in Ratkoc.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo's provincial capital, Pristina, a crowd of 1,000
ethnic Albanians demonstrating for independence was dispersed by
club-wielding Serbian police, who beat and injured at least six of
the protesters.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton's top foreign affairs advisers will
discuss Kosovo today, a spokesman said. At least three
international forums will deal with Kosovo this week: the UN, NATO,
and the so-called Contact Group, where the West and Russia
coordinate Balkan mediation.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials spent eight hours Sunday in Albania interviewing
Kosovar refugees and aid workers, according to an official of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, the
peacekeeping body.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic will allow diplomatic observers to enter Kosovo, The
New York Times reported today. The first observer missions could
take place as early as today, the newspaper said, quoting senior
Clinton administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters saw some 50 Kosovo Liberation Army guerrillas slipping
across the border from Albania into Kosovo with 10 mules loaded
with ammunition. The guerrillas wore camouflaged fatigues and
carried Kalashnikov assault rifles.
</P>
<P>
   , British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said Sunday that
Milosevic had ``crossed the threshold'' in the last week. ``The use
of tanks, of artillery, of the might of the military army against
civilian centers of population is wholly unacceptable within the
modern Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair, attempting to raise London's diplomatic profile, has held
the rotating presidency of the European Union since January. He has
tried to coordinate US discussions with Russia, which tends to side
with its fellow Slavs in Serbia. Several diplomats said they expect
Russia to use its veto power in the UN Security Council to prevent
international troops from getting involved.
</P>
<P>
   Even US officials who want to take a more active role in Kosovo
are aware that the presence of troops could irritate Serbian
nationalists, who might try to orchestrate an attack in order to
humiliate the Pentagon and force a retreat.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly address, Pope John Paul II said the international
community ``could not stay inert before the violence, repression,
and fleeing of the population.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9466 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SEX-SMELL-2NDTAKE     06-08 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SEX-SMELL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: difference appealing.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a different research track, Dr. Ober and her Chicago
colleagues studied 411 married couples in 31 Hutterite colonies in
South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   A tight-knit religious group who marry among their own and
believe in large families, the Hutterites in her sample are
unusually closely related to one another because they are all
descended from only 64 people who emigrated from the sect's
original home in Europe in the 1870s. That means couples do not
have the astronomical odds against sharing MHC genes that they do
in secular American society.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ober's team sampled the DNA of all 411 couples, identifying
haplotypes on the MHC region of Chromosome Six. She then entered
the known genealogy of the Hutterites into a computer simulation,
which predicted significantly more haplotype-matched couples than
actually exist. That suggests, Dr. Ober said, that Hutterites
somehow avoid marriage to partners with whom they share too many
MHC genes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steven Gangestad, a psychologist, and Dr. Randy Thornhill, a
biologist, both at the University of New Mexico, have proposed that
symmetry between right side and left, which in many animals is a
sign of health, fertility and longevity, is also important in human
mating.
</P>
<P>
   Gangestad and Thornhill measured their male volunteers for ear
length, ear width, elbow width, wrist width, foot breadth, and
lengths of fingers and thumbs. In a paper to be published this year
in the Proceedings of the Royal Society of London, they wrote that
female volunteers who were not taking oral contraceptives, given
T-shirts that had been worn by the male volunteers, showed a
preference for the smell of the most symmetrical men only if the
women were at that stage of their monthly cycle in which they were
more likely to become pregnant. In fact, the doctors wrote, the
preference was stronger as the likelihood of pregnancy increased.
</P>
<P>
   Many other biologists are not convinced by these studies. ``I'm
basically skeptical until I see some really strong evidence,'' said
Philip W. Hedrick, a biologist at Arizona State University, and a
critic of the idea that smell affects human sex and marriage. ``I
think mate choice is probably a lot more complicated, particularly
in humans.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in the issue of the American Journal of Human
Genetics that published Dr. Ober's paper on Hutterite mate choice,
Hedrick and Francis L. Black of Yale reported that their analysis
of couples in 11 Amazon tribes had not found the same effect. The
paper looked at two MHC genes, while Dr. Ober used haplotypes, so
the studies are not strictly comparable.
</P>
<P>
   Hedrick has also clashed with Wedekind. The Swiss team
``basically trained his subjects to make odor significant,'' with
their nasal sprays and novels, Hedrick said.
</P>
<P>
   The scientific debate will continue as biologists plan further
studies and the technology for precisely measuring odor improves,
Wedekind said. In the meantime, he and fellow believers must also
contend with part of the lay public that is uncomfortable with
research that suggests that profound decisions about sex, marriage
and parenthood could be affected by body odor.
</P>
<P>
   ``One politician called and told us she would be doing
everything she could to see I was expelled from the university,''
Wedekind said. ``Some people really fight this kind of research.''
</P>
<P>
   Wedekind said he was unsympathetic to those fears. The
``keywords'' used to describe the research for reference, he said,
are ``words like humans, mate choice,' `genes.' That makes some
people want to fight it, and I understand their concerns. Some
people may be remembering what happened 60 years ago in Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
