<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9497 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTISTS-MORMONS-550(     06-08 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-MORMONS-550(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAPTISTS AND MORMONS DISPUTE WHO HAS THE TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos and graphics have been posted at Wieck.) 
(lh) 
 By CARY McMULLEN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Call it a confrontation between the confident
and the convinced.
</P>
<P>
   For the past week, Southern Baptists have been gathering here in
the capital of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints,
observing, listening to seminars on Mormon beliefs, and
evangelizing a people who say they are already Christian.
</P>
<P>
   The annual Southern Baptist Convention gets under way Tuesday at
the Salt Palace, far from the familiar flatlands and Appalachian
hills of the steamy South. As many as 9,000 representatives of
local churches will be present. Their willingness to come so far is
a perfect example, say their leaders, of renewed Southern Baptist
desire to carry the gospel into every corner of the globe.
</P>
<P>
   The Baptists have more than Mormons on their minds. They likely
will elect as their new president Paige Patterson, one of the
architects of the conservative movement that now dominates the
convention and its agencies. They will add an article to their
statement of belief that enshrines what they say is a biblical _
but others say anachronistic _ view of the family. And they will
give rapt attention to one of the most powerful evangelical, and
political, figures around, Dr. James Dobson.
</P>
<P>
   But in the days that led up to the convention, the dispute
between Baptists and Mormons was carried out in homes and on the
streets, as a series of events carefully planned by the
convention's Interfaith Witness Team brought the two sides face to
face. Up to 3,000 pastors, seminarians and lay people participated
Saturday in Crossover, a blitz of door-to-door visits, block
parties and sports-related rallies.
</P>
<P>
   This is the 10th year that Crossover has been conducted in
conjunction with the Southern Baptist's annual meeting. This year's
effort in Salt Lake City, however, has attracted more attention
than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, it is a dispute as old as Christianity itself,
over questions of authority and freedom, of scripture and
revelation, of heresy and orthodoxy. And the Mormon church has done
this before, facing Christians who are critical and even hostile to
their beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time, as a mob of Baptists come storming their gates,
it is not to beat them or throw them in prison, as was done by
distrustful citizens in the Midwest more than 150 years ago. It is
to make the case that it is their version of Christianity, not the
Latter-day Saints', that is the true one.
</P>
<P>
   And this time, Mormons are not running away, but welcoming their
accosters with what they say will be Christian charity. That may be
because the dispute is taking place in their own stronghold. But in
any case, the descendants of Mormons who walked 1,500 miles across
some of the most forbidding terrain in the world, pulling their
possessions in handcarts, are not likely to be intimidated by a few
well-dressed Baptists who want to hand them a brochure.
</P>
<P>
   At least one Mormon teacher says it is the Baptists who may come
away with a different point of view. ``The local church authorities
are anxious for the evangelicals to come and see what Mormons are
like in their own environment,'' said Stephen Robinson, professor
of ancient scriptures at Brigham Young University. ``I think it
will do more good for dispelling false information on both sides.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Southern Baptist leaders have not been shy about using the word
``cult'' when speaking of the Latter-day Saints. Phil Roberts,
director of Interfaith Witness for the convention's North American
Mission Board, said it's a term people understand. ``It means
they're not a Christian movement. From a sociological perspective,
they're very much mainstream. But theologically, we would say they
are a cult because they do claim exclusive truth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson says he finds the word ``cult'' unfair. ``Any statement
about Christ in the Bible, I believe,'' he said. ``My own
understanding is that salvation comes only through Christ and
repentance of sins. We are saved by grace through faith.''
</P>
<P>
   The conflict turns on what an authentic revelation from God is _
and who makes that judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptists, along with most Christians, Catholic and
Protestant, hold that the Bible is the complete revelation of God's
truth and that no other is needed or permitted. Mormons say that
there's nothing in the Bible that forbids further revelations.
``Latter-day Saints are saying, not only do we believe the Bible,
but the pattern of communication revealed there continues,''
Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   The belief in ongoing revelation goes back to the origins of the
Latter-day Saints in 1830, when 24-year-old Joseph Smith convinced
six others that he had translated a book of lost scripture given to
him on golden plates by the angel Moroni. The Book of Mormon has
been regarded by Smith's followers ever since as an authentic
revelation from God, a book of scripture equal to the Bible. Smith
assumed the mantle of a prophet, like Moses, and each of his
successors, including current President Gordon B. Hinckley, is said
to be a prophet also, capable of giving authoritative guidance to
the faithful on behalf of God.
</P>
<P>
   From the first, Mormon doctrines have come under fire:
</P>
<P>
   _ God the Father was once a man who became immortal and still
has a physical nature. ``As man now is, God once was. As God now
is, man may be,'' said an early president, Lorenzo Snow.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Godhead consists of Father, Son and Holy Ghost, but they
are distinct persons, thus rejecting the traditional doctrine of
the Trinity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Good works are required to maintain (though not to earn)
salvation. ``The LDS would say works are necessary to stay in the
covenant. We have an obligation to do what the savior asks us to
do. If we repudiate it, we can fall from grace,'' said Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some illegal or unsavory practices have been abandoned. By
prophetic declaration, polygamy was given up in 1890 and in 1978
black men were allowed into the priesthood, which was previously
reserved for whites and still is given to all males over age 11 who
demonstrate worthiness.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was denounced as a lunatic in his day, but it is more
difficult to apply the term to 10 million followers today who
uphold the virtues of God, country and family. In judging whether
the Latter-day Saints' claim of ongoing revelation is valid,
scholars and denominational leaders point to the church's origins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in objective analysis of their truth claims,''
Roberts said. ``Is there any evidence these things existed? Joseph
Smith said he was given gold plates. Where are they? He said
ancient American civilizations were Hebrew. Historians say they
were animistic and polytheistic. It seems to be a fabricated
document.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Roberts also says Smith is an unreliable figure who made
conflicting claims and was frequently wrong in his prophetic
declarations.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Blomberg, a professor of New Testament at Denver Seminary,
a Conservative Baptist school, says one of the ways Jews and
Christians judged scripture as authentic is by its widespread use
by communities of faith over a period of time. Even if a lost
letter of St. Paul were unearthed today, Blomberg contends, it
wouldn't be added to the Bible because it wouldn't have been widely
used by Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``By that definition, anything not available to 19 centuries of
church use is not valid. If God wanted us to have had it all along,
he would have made sure we did,'' Blomberg said.
</P>
<P>
   In rejoinder, Robinson appeals to personal conviction. ``The
best way to get any religious information is to ask God,'' he said.
``If he lets you know the information given is true, it is. We feel
the spirit has confirmed to us what Joseph Smith said is true.
Other Christians feel it has not.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson also protests that some doctrines held by Southern
Baptists are not found in the Bible, like the Trinity. ``That's a
product of the fourth and fifth centuries. That's the very thing
Southern Baptists get upset with Latter-day Saints for _ adding
things to the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   So convinced are Latter-day Saints of the truth of Smith's
teachings, they view all other religions as less than perfect. ``We
like to think of religions as different light bulbs. It's better to
be a 40-watt than a 20-watt,'' Robinson said. Asked if Mormons are
a 100-watt bulb, Robinson said, laughing, ``I guess that's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Mormons claim to be neither Protestant nor Catholic but a
restoration of the true church, lost since the days of Jesus.
Blomberg, who collaborated with Robinson on a book, ``How Wide the
Divide? A Mormon and Evangelical in Conversation,'' said Mormonism
should be seen as part of a restorationist movement in 19th-century
American religion that produced such mainstream Protestant churches
as the Disciples of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a religious phenomenon that had the idea the Protestant
Reformation didn't go far enough. They wanted to go back to the
apostolic era and restore the Christianity of the New Testament,''
he said. ``Mormonism went a step further and said, `Not only are we
restoring it, it hasn't been there since the first century.'''
</P>
<P>
   In effect, Smith and his followers dismissed 19 centuries of
Christian teaching.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, it is not only Southern Baptists who consider
Mormons non-Christian. Catholics and moderate Protestants have made
similar judgments. A recent article in the United Methodist Review,
reporting on a meeting between Methodist and Mormon leaders at
First United Methodist Church in Salt Lake City, said, ``Latter-day
Saints hold beliefs about God and Scripture that are so radically
different from traditional Christianity that some Protestants
question whether it is the same God who is being worshiped or in
whose name the baptism occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if Mormons are considered heretics by the rest of the
Christian world, why not leave them to their beliefs and let God be
the final judge? Why do Southern Baptists feel compelled to try to
convert them?
</P>
<P>
   The answer lies in the conviction of conservative leaders of the
denomination that everyone in the world _ including Baptists
themselves and their children _ must hear the gospel. This week's
effort in the Salt Lake valley is only part of a concerted
worldwide evangelistic program. Patterson has said if he is elected
president, he will set a goal of 500,000 baptisms worldwide in the
year 2000 alone.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptists have drawn fire for their recent
evangelization of Jews, but less widely known is that Roman
Catholics are targets of the Interfaith Witness Team as well. ``We
do not believe salvation is brokered and Roman Catholicism
traditionally says it is,'' Roberts said. ``Our basic assignment is
to reach all non-evangelical denominations and movements.''
</P>
<P>
   Both churches emphasize missionary work, but thanks in part to
their tradition of volunteer missionaries, Mormons have been
growing at a much faster rate than Baptists in recent years,
especially in countries outside the United States. By some
estimates, the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints is
growing by 40,000 members a year. It is already the seventh-largest
church in the United States and at current rates, it would come
close to the Southern Baptists' No. 2 ranking sometime in the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson says that growth may lie behind Southern Baptists'
labeling of Mormons as a cult. ``Basically, conservative
evangelicals have been interested in demonizing Latter-day Saints
to pre-empt the possibility that people will listen to what we have
to say,'' he said. ``It's an attempt to forestall conversions. The
wilder they can make us, the less likely people are to listen.''
</P>
<P>
   (Cary McMullen writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla. This
story was distributed by The N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
