<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV14-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN FLYING ISN'T AN OPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., June 14)  
 (JT)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A friend who was recently transferred to New York asked how she
can bring her parents from Louisville, Ky., to the city for a visit
when they will not fly and she does not want them to drive. To
paraphrase an old saw: Can they get here from there?
</P>
<P>
   The short answer is yes, but not easily. Louisville, like many
cities in the United States, including a number of university
towns, now has no train service, and while it has long-distance bus
service, the schedules sometimes involve weird arrival or departure
hours: no one wants to arrive in a bus station in a strange city at
3 a.m. Since the creation of Amtrak and the demise of independent
rail passenger service, an increasing number of places have found
themselves linked to the outside world only by rubber tires, mainly
private automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   To get a glimpse of the travel choices available to nondriving,
nonflying travelers, I examined the options for travel to New York
from Louisville; Iowa City, home of the University of Iowa, and
Phoenix, a major retirement center.
</P>
<P>
   Louisville, population 269,000, had rail service until 1979 when
Amtrak dropped the stop under congressional budget pressure;
Phoenix, population 983,000, had service until June 1, 1996. Iowa
City, population 60,000, lost its Rock Island service in 1970,
before Amtrak came into existence in 1971. These cities are all on
now-aging Interstate highways.
</P>
<P>
   The map in the Amtrak national timetable does not show Iowa
City, which is in the apparent void of eastern Iowa. Louisville and
Phoenix are linked to the Amtrak system by purple lines; these
represent ``Amtrak thruway services,'' which is to say a bus
connection. Marc Magliari, a spokesman for Amtrak, says that the
purple line indicates that Amtrak can sell a ticket for the
combined bus and rail trip, will transfer baggage and guarantee
that the passenger makes the connection. By ``guarantee,'' the line
means that if the bus misses the train, Amtrak will put passengers
up in a local hotel until the next train. This may sometimes be two
days off.
</P>
<P>
   Louisville to N.Y.: 3 Ways
</P>
<P>
   The trip from Louisville represents a hard choice. The bus-train
combination is slow, 30 hours and 45 minutes, and expensive if
sleeper accommodations are purchased, and they are an important
argument for the train. On June 2, the round-trip sleeper fare was
quoted at $940 for two senior citizens traveling together on July
14 and Aug. 1. Two train meals would be included each way. And
trains do permit a little walking around at will. The Greyhound bus
is faster and cheaper, but requires sitting up all night and an
early morning change of buses.
</P>
<P>
   Using Amtrak and its bus link, on a schedule chosen to reduce
the layover, a ``thruway'' bus leaves the Greyhound Station in
Louisville at 9 a.m. Eastern time and is due at Union Station in
Chicago at 3:25 p.m. Central time, a journey of 306 miles in seven
and a half hours. Then the Lake Shore Limited leaves Chicago at
8:15 p.m., which means a layover of almost five hours. (The Lake
Shore dining car does not serve dinner on leaving Chicago.) The
Lake Shore is due in New York's Penn Station at 3:41 p.m., a
journey of 959 miles in 18{ hours, although the clock shows 19{
because of the shift to Eastern time. The total number of miles for
this route is 1,265.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a price range for sleepers is impossible because Amtrak
uses the airline-created yield-management system, raising prices in
periods of demand and setting aside only a small number of tickets
at the lowest rates. Joyce Cosek, a long-time reservationist at
Amtrak, using the computer system, said that the minimum one-way
coach fare for Louisville-New York, with the bus leg included, was
$114, and the highest $181. If you break down the quoted sleeper
fare of $940 round trip for travel by two seniors July 14 and Aug.
1, this represents $470 each way, or $235 for each person. This is
a little higher than a rule of thumb Magliari quoted: an overnight
trip in a standard bedroom on Amtrak should be in the $150 to $200
range for one of two people.
</P>
<P>
   Another alternative is to take the whole trip by Greyhound,
across Ohio and Pennsylvania rather than through Chicago. Jim
Austin, who is responsible for the computer system that serves the
bus line's reservationists, said the bus company had six buses a
day from Louisville to New York, none of them ``direct,'' meaning a
transfer is required. The fastest time is 17 hours 15 minutes for a
trip of 805 miles. For this example, a bus leaves Louisville at
11:10 p.m. and arrives in Cleveland at 6:40 a.m., where a change is
required. The departure is at 7 a.m., with arrival at the New York
Port Authority Bus Terminal set for 4:25 p.m. The fare for a
passenger who walks up at the last minute is $108 one way, $175
round trip; tickets purchased 30 days in advance cost $118 round
trip. Greyhound has blackout dates around holidays when
advance-purchase prices are not available.
</P>
<P>
   The buses have toilets aboard, Austin said, but some people do
not like to use them, so there are rest stops every two to three
hours. Snacks may be available along the way, but the night is
spent sitting up, as it is on many long plane flights.
</P>
<P>
   A railroad buff in my family looked up Louisville in the
Official Railway Guide for 1940, when dozens of trains came into
the city every day. The Cincinnati Limited left Louisville at 12:53
p.m. and arrived in Penn Station at 8:15 the next morning, a total
of a little over 19 hours with no changes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
