<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9505 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2N     06-08 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2NDTAKE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: no changes.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another possible option today, if a costly one: Use a livery
service. P. Paul Powell Jr., executive vice president of Louisville
Transportation, a taxi and livery company, said a driver could be
found to make the trip straight through, which he estimated at 14
hours for the 800 miles, for $1,200. The price includes the
driver's trip back with no passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said that his company gets regular requests for service
to Orlando, and occasionally Las Vegas. Why Las Vegas? ``Well,
frankly, they get drunk,'' he said, ``and they have more money than
sense, so they go to Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   From Iowa City: 2 Ways
</P>
<P>
   The Iowa City-New York train trip covers a greater distance than
the Louisville-New York bus-train combination, but it is almost all
train travel, in a straighter line, and thus takes about the same
time, with a similar layover before catching the sleeper into New
York. The bus trip _ 23 hours _ takes longer than Louisville-New
York, but it is less demanding because it requires no change en
route. It would not require a lot of thought except that the fare
differential is greater.
</P>
<P>
   The Iowa City Amtrak trip involves getting a lift or a cab to
cover 56 miles to Mount Pleasant, Iowa, a stop on the California
Zephyr's route between Emeryville, Calif., and Chicago. There is no
Amtrak bus service here. The eastbound Zephyr goes through daily at
11:20 a.m. Central time and covers the 233 miles to Chicago in five
hours, arriving at 4:10 p.m. This too connects with the Lake Shore
Limited, departing at 8:15 p.m. and arriving in New York at 3:41
p.m. the next day. Factoring in the change of time, the trip of
1,248 miles will consume 29{ hours, including the layover and just
an hour for the drive to Mount Pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   The cheapest one-way Mount Pleasant-New York coach ticket is
$112, and the most expensive, $205. For a round trip for two
seniors using the sleeper on the Chicago-New York leg, leaving July
14 and returning Aug. 1, the fare was quoted on June 2 at $1,020.
</P>
<P>
   There are five Greyhound buses a day from Iowa City to New York,
a trip of 1,110 miles. The fastest trip takes 23 hours, according
to Austin, with the best schedule a departure at 11:05 a.m. Central
time, arriving at 11 a.m. Eastern time. The walkup fare is $119 one
way, $238 round trip; again, the advance purchase round-trip is
$118.
</P>
<P>
   From Phoenix: 2 Options
</P>
<P>
   The land trip from Phoenix to New York is 60 or 70 hours long,
no matter how you do it. The bus requires two changes, and you
would certainly be stiff after all that sitting. The train would
provide three nights in a sleeper and most meals, at a cost about
five times higher.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak provides a bus link north into Flagstaff, to pick up the
daily Southwest Chief, or south into Tucson, to pick up the Sunset
Limited on a Monday, Wednesday or Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   To take the southern route, a bus leaves the former railroad
station in Phoenix at 5 a.m., covering the 119 miles to Tucson by
7:05 a.m. Using Monday as an example, the train bound east to
Florida arrives at 7:40 a.m. and is due in Jacksonville 49 hours
later, at 11:45 a.m. on Wednesday. This leg is 2,101 miles. From
there, one of several choices into New York is the Silver Meteor,
leaving at 4:26 p.m. daily and arriving more than 17 hours later,
at 9:45 a.m. the next day, which would be Thursday. This leg is 978
miles.
</P>
<P>
   The least expensive coach ticket for Amtrak's 3,198-mile
Phoenix-Tucson-Jacksonville-New York trip would be $157; the most
expensive, $285. The sleeper trip was priced on June 2 at $2,005
for a round trip by two senior citizens traveling on July 15 and
returning Aug. 1. The per-night per-person cost for this fare works
out to $167, right in Magliari's ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   With Greyhound, there are several ways to get to New York, with
the fastest route for the 2,750 miles taking virtually 59 hours and
requiring two changes. The bus leaves Phoenix at 9:30 p.m. and
arrives in New York at 11:20 a.m. two days later. The walkup fare
for this is $122 one way, $215 round trip. The advance fare again
is $118 round trip.
</P>
<P>
   Where Trains and Buses Are
</P>
<P>
   The differences in bus or bus-train service from these three
locations are considerable; but some areas are even worse off.
Amtrak's skeletal structure does not touch four states at all:
Maine, Oklahoma, South Dakota and Wyoming, and almost skips
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Austin said that Greyhound service, although his map shows every
state is touched, was poorest where the population was most sparse:
South Dakota and the mountains of West Virginia. Compared with the
elaborate bus and train systems in Europe, these two maps look
skimpy in the extreme.
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents sell Amtrak tickets; a national timetable, with
the map, is available at railroad stations. Other information, or
reservations, is available at (800) 872-7245.
</P>
<P>
   Greyhound sells a national route map for $1.50 at its agencies,
but not a national timetable. For this, the traveler needs an
old-time wish book, the fat monthly bus guide for all lines, of
which Greyhound, with its subsidiaries, is by far the biggest. For
the current month's guide, send a check (no credit cards) for $15,
requesting the Official National Motor Coach Guide: Russell's
Guides, 834 Third Avenue S.E., Cedar Rapids, Iowa 52403; (319)
364-6138. The priceless advantage of this guide is the index in the
back: if a place name is there, there is a bus.
</P>
<P>
   The monthly bus guide solved a longtime mystery for me. When I
tried once to get to Bangor, Maine, Greyhound told me on the phone
it had no service north of Boston. Then a friend swore he had taken
Greyhound to Bangor and back. Russell's Guide shows Vermont Transit
connecting Boston and Bangor five times daily. Vermont Transit,
Austin explained, is owned by Greyhound, which makes connections
with its routes in Boston and sells its tickets. Confusingly, as it
happens with code-sharing by the airlines, sometimes a bus labeled
Greyhound runs to Boston and on through to Maine. Austin said that
the Vermont Transit name was retained because people in New England
liked it. But this does not explain why a caller was told that
Maine is not served by Greyhound.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
