<HEADER>
A9524 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-08 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAD OR ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court, as is often its wont, seemed
inclined toward a middle course as it listened Monday to oral
arguments over Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's demand to see
notes taken by a lawyer giving confidential advice to White House
aide Vincent Foster shortly before Foster committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The justices hinted they intend to balance the competing legal
interests involved rather than establish a sweeping new precedent.
</P>
<P>
   If that is indeed what they do, they will have justified their
keep this year, putting the brakes on an excessive overreach of
Starr's runaway probe without preventing legitimate inquiries. The
Supremes also refused recently to grant Starr an expedited hearing
on whether a top White House lawyer and three Secret Service agents
could be forced to testify about former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, Monday's line of questioning indicated that a
majority of the high bench may not be prepared to let Starr invent
a new legal excuse in order to get his hands on the lawyer's notes.
The prosecutor argued that the lawyer-client privilege expires with
the death of the client, creating a new exception to that basic
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the justices seemed wary of setting a broad
precedent that could prohibit future prosecutors in criminal cases
from interrogating lawyers about conversations with clients who had
died. Murder, for instance, might create a more compelling reason
for an exception than Starr produced.
</P>
<P>
   Both Starr's associate, Brett Kavanaugh, and Foster's lawyer,
James Hamilton, asked the court to establish a new legal doctrine.
Starr wanted the right not only to read the three pages of notes
but to compel testimony under oath from the lawyer himself about
the confidential exchange. Hamilton wanted the court to create an
absolute protection for lawyers and their clients that extended to
the grave no matter the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers at the oral argument came away believing the court
would divide, perhaps 5-4, seeing no compelling reason to give
Starr a brand-new legal weapon but leaving open the possibility
that other circumstances might justify overcoming the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   The 1993 White House firings of seven travel office employees,
the specific subject of Foster's conversation, were barely
mentioned. That particular controversy, in fact, is a marginal
issue in Starr's probe. The White House handled the situation
crudely but had the authority to fire the staffers. Starr's
interest seems to be mostly in whether First Lady Hillary Clinton
ordered the firings and then ducked responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The justices mostly suggested hypothetical situations that might
be affected by ruling one way or the other. Both Kavanaugh and
Hamilton were peppered with penetrating and sometimes unfriendly
questions.
</P>
<P>
   The potential consequences of a broad ruling in favor of Starr
have horrified the legal profession. The American Bar Association
sided with Hamilton, arguing that clients may not be candid if they
know their secrets can be spilled after they die.
</P>
<P>
   And what is recorded in Hamilton's notes would not be the end of
the matter. Hamilton may have jotted down ``Hillary did it'' or
written illegibly or simply observed that the depressed Foster
didn't know what to do. But if Starr wins, Hamilton could be hauled
into court to disclose everything Foster said, whether in the notes
or not.
</P>
<P>
   If that precedent were set, the next lawyer in the witness box
might well be Sam Heuer, who defended President Clinton's former
business partner James McDougal in the Arkansas trial in which
McDougal was convicted of fraud. Now that McDougal is dead, Heuer
might have very interesting things to say about his client's
honesty and knowledge of Clinton's involvement in the Whitewater
land deal.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy pondered: What if five defendants are
accused of some criminal offense and one dies in mid-trial? Would
it be legitimate to force the lawyer of the dead dependent to spill
everything his client said in confidence about his compatriots?
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers everywhere would have to pray that their clients
stay healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Starr contended that people are not concerned about their
reputations after they die and the only ones who would mind are
those who plan to commit perjury or have something to hide.
</P>
<P>
   But people do care about their historical legacy, and so do
their families and friends. And the candor essential to good legal
representation may involve only embarrassment if made public, not
criminal activity.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is way off base here, and the Supreme Court ought to
recognize it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
