<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: FREEBIE NIGHT FOR CULTURE VULTURES; SPLASHY
EXHIBITION; CHANGE AT THE SANTA FE; HANKS TO BE HONORED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Five dancing 12-foot puppets representing each of New
York's boroughs and celebrating the 100th anniversary of the city's
consolidation will lead the way down Fifth Avenue Tuesday night
from the Museum of the City of New York in the 20th annual Museum
Mile Festival. During the event, from 6 to 9 p.m., nine cultural
institutions will be open free to the public along a 22-block
stretch from 104th Street to 82nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   There will be music and other entertainment too. Participating
are El Museo del Barrio; the Museum of the City of New York; the
International Center of Photography; the Jewish Museum; the
Cooper-Hewitt, National Design Museum, Smithsonian Institution; the
National Academy Museum and School of Fine Arts; the Solomon
Guggenheim Museum; the Goethe-Institut New York German Cultural
Center, and the Metropolitan Museum of Art. This year for the first
time the Frick Collection at 70th Street and Fifth Avenue will also
be open free.
</P>
<P>
   Heights of Cool
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Moving toward the grand reopening of its entire
public complex on June 21 after a three-year, $20 million
renovation in conjunction with its centennial, the Cooper-Hewitt,
National Design Museum, Smithsonian Institution, opens a new
exhibition Monday called ``Fountains: Splash and Spectacle.'' More
than 250 works, including drawings, photographs and videos, focus
on the design, architecture, function and meaning of fountains from
the 1400s to the present, including the designs of the fountains of
Louis XIV in Versailles and Bernini in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Transition
</P>
<P>
   Richard Gaddes has been chosen by the board of directors of the
Santa Fe Opera to succeed John Crosby as general director effective
Sept. 30, 2000. Gaddes, who served as the company's artistic
administrator for a decade beginning in 1969 and was a founder of
the Opera Theater of St. Louis in 1976, has been associate general
director of the Santa Fe Opera since 1995. Crosby founded the Santa
Fe Opera in 1957 and will turn 72 this year. He will continue to
conduct for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Honor Bound
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tom Hanks will be the recipient of the 14th annual
American Museum of the Moving Image Salute on March 11, 1999, at
the Waldorf-Astoria. Announcing Hanks' acceptance, Rochelle Slovin,
museum director, said, ``Tom Hanks is an exceptional talent who
moves easily between films and television, acting, directing and
producing.'' Previous recipients include Sidney Lumet, James
Stewart, Sidney Poitier, Mike Nichols, Robert De Niro, Al Pacino,
Steven Spielberg, Robin Williams, Martin Scorsese and Dustin
Hoffman. Proceeds of the event are to benefit the museum's
education programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
