<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9537 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-COX &UR;  &UR; ANTITRUSTW     06-08 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-COX </SLUG>
     ANTITRUST WARS HEAT UP AS FTC SUES INTEL
 &HT;     Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;     By ANDREW J. GLASS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Intel Corp., the world's largest maker of computer
chips, became the latest target of government trust-busters Monday
when the Federal Trade Commission voted to charge the company with
illegally failing to share key data with its customers.
</P>
<P>
   William Baer, the FTC chief's litigator, accused Intel of
selectively using its paramount position in the chip market as a
``club'' against three computer makers after relations with the
firms had soured in separate licensing, patent and royalty
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   These quarrels caused Intel to unfairly deny these customers
access to its coveted ``how-to manual,'' the FTC said. In doing so,
Intel has ``cut off customers and competitors in order to impede
innovation and stifle competition,'' Baer said at a news conference
after the commissioners voted 3-1 to act.
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Clara, Calif., the $25 billion microprocessor firm said
the FTC action is based upon a mistaken interpretation of the law
and the facts. It vowed to fight the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``For more than 10 years, Intel has taken unprecedented steps to
ensure that all of our activities and policies are in full
compliance with existing law,'' Intel said in a statement. ``The
commission's decision today signals that they want to change the
very laws upon which we've based our policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Several legal experts noted that if the government prevails in
the Intel case, a dominant firm would be forced for the first time
to share its intellectual property with its customers _ even after
a falling-out.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC move follows a landmark Justice Department antitrust
suit against Microsoft Corp., which holds a virtual monopoly on the
Windows software that drives Intel chips.
</P>
<P>
   That means that the world's twin leaders in chips and software
for personal computer _ known as ``Wintel'' _ now face parallel
assaults from the government in Washington courtrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The scope of the two cases and their future legal tracks differ,
however. While the anti-competitive charges against Microsoft are
due to be tried before a federal judge in early September, Intel
must respond to the regulatory agency's complaint before an FTC
administrative law judge.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, by freezing out Digital Equipment Corp., Intergraph Corp.
and Compaq Computer Corp. from advance information, ``repeatedly
used its monopoly power as a club'' against them, according to the
11-page complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The case was spawned after the chip giant denied Intergraph
samples of new microprocessors in advance of their general
availability. It did so in retaliation for a patent infringement
lawsuit that Intergraph _ the developer of a rival chip to Intel's
Pentium, called the Clipper _ had brought against Intel.
</P>
<P>
   The suit sought an injunction to halt Intel's microprocessor
sales, which control 90 percent of the market. In April, a federal
judge in Alabama ruled in Intergraph's favor in the patent case,
without issuing the injunction.
</P>
<P>
   Given the high stakes involved, the issue is likely to be
finally resolved by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The basic issue in the suit is whether Intel is within its
rights to refuse to provide Intergraph and other firms with advance
inside information. As the FTC sees it, those denials violate the
antitrust laws because, as an monopolist, Intel has an
``affirmative duty'' not to ``harm competition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(This) is not an attack on Intel's success, which we applaud,
but only on unjustifiable conduct by Intel that keeps other firms
from being able to compete with it in the future,'' Baer said.
</P>
<P>
   If, he added, ``Intel can use its monopoly position in the
market for microprocessors to prevent other firms from enforcing
their own patents, other firms will have little incentive to invent
new features to challenge Intel's dominance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's illegal under the antitrust laws for a monopolist to
wield its monopoly power to lock others out of the market, and by
doing so preventing future competition, and cementing the
monopolists' dominance in its market. Over the long run that means
less competition, higher prices, reduced choice for consumers,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
