<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9539 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TONYS-ART-NYT &LR;      06-08 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONYS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TONY LOSERS TAKE STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-1243 or 1927.)  
(ja) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The producers of ``Honour,'' a four-character drama
about infidelity in the pundit class that marked Jane Alexander's
return to Broadway after four years as chairman of the National
Endowment for the Arts, announced Monday that it would close after
its Sunday matinee, becoming the first casualty of the Tony Awards
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The play had 57 regular performances and 28 previews. Producers
for several other shows that had hoped in vain for a Tony award on
Sunday to bolster sagging ticket sales met Monday to crunch numbers
and decide whether to close as well.
</P>
<P>
   Shows tend to close on a Sunday, squeezing in one last weekend
before going dark, and labor rules require producers to post a
closing notice by Tuesday evening if they intend to close on the
following Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The story was more upbeat for shows that did well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lion King,'' which has been selling tickets as fast they
are printed, won six prizes, including one for best new musical of
the season. A new block of tickets to the show, covering dates
until Oct. 31, 1999, went on sale on Friday and business was strong
Monday, a spokesman for the show said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ragtime,'' which had been the chief competition for the
best-musical award, drew Tonys for its score, book, orchestrations
and Audra McDonald's featured performance. Garth Drabinsky, the
creative director of Livent, the corporation that produced the
musical, said that ticket sales for the show, which had already
been strong, had more than doubled over the last week and were
being offered for performances through May 2, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art,'' the three-character comedy about longtime friends
bickering over a Minimalist painting, was a surprise winner for
best new play. Producers for ``Art'' said they expected to sell
nearly $100,000 in tickets Monday, nearly three times the average
daily figure.
</P>
<P>
   And the Roundabout Theater Company, which won awards for best
play revival (``A View From the Bridge'') and best musical revival
(``Cabaret''), said it sold three times as many tickets for ``A
View From the Bridge'' Monday as it had been selling before the
Tony Awards.
</P>
<P>
   The show that many had expected to win best play, ``The Beauty
Queen of Leenane,'' did win awards for its director, Garry Hynes,
and for three cast members. A spokesman for the show said that
tickets were selling Monday at about triple the rate of previous
Mondays and predicted that the dark comedy, which opened on
Broadway in April after a successful Off Broadway run, would recoup
its investment this week.
</P>
<P>
   One striking element about the 52nd annual Tony ceremony was how
much the awards for excellence on Broadway, which for decades had
been dominated by New York writers and artists, have taken on a
less New York-centric flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lion King'' was based on an animated film from Hollywood, and
``Ragtime'' originated in Canada. ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane''
is by a South London playwright and was first produced in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The award for best actress in a play went to an Irishwoman,
Marie Mullen, of ``Beauty Queen.'' The award for best actor went to
Anthony LaPaglia, an Australian, for ``A View From the Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Best actor in a musical went to a Scot, Alan Cumming of
``Cabaret,'' and best actress went to that show's Natasha
Richardson, who is English. The author of ``Art'' is Yasmina Reza,
a French citizen of Iranian descent.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's ceremony was the second for which that Rosie O'Donnell,
the talk show host, served as emcee from Radio City Music Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in her maiden voyage, she spurred a 35 percent jump
in television viewership, with an 11.2 rating and a 17 share. (Each
rating point represents 980,000 homes.) Despite a brisk season and
strong contests in numerous categories, this year's ratings were a
bit lower, a 10.3 rating and a 16 share for CBS. A network
spokesman said one reason for the drop was an NBA championship game
between the Chicago Bulls and the Utah Jazz on NBC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
