<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAMSUNG-CHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMSUNG ELECTRONICS TO STOP CHIP PRODUCTION FOR 1 WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Samsung Electronics Co. of South Korea, one of the
largest semiconductor manufacturers, said Monday that it would
suspend all production of memory chips and much of the production
of nonmemory chips for a week to reduce inventory and strengthen
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lee, a spokeswoman for Samsung Electronics, said the
company would all but shutter its operations at Kiheung in South
Korea, though its other manufacturing sites, which produce home
appliances and telecommunications components, would continue
running.
</P>
<P>
   Samsung is following Hyundai Electronics, another large South
Korean semiconductor manufacturer, which announced last week that
it would stop production of dynamic random access memory chips, or
D-RAMs, for a week.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts could hurt South Korea because semiconductors are one
of the country's largest exports and one of the biggest sources of
badly needed hard currency.
</P>
<P>
   LG Semicon, a third South Korean manufacturer, is expected to
follow its competitors. Together, the three companies produce 30
percent of the world's basic semiconductor chips.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts expressed skepticism about the impact of the cuts.
Twice before, the South Korean manufacturers have announced similar
cutbacks only to continue production, stockpiling their output
until prices rose on news of reduced production.
</P>
<P>
   SBC Warburg Dillon Read estimates that this year semiconductor
manufacturers will have 18 percent more inventory than needed to
meet demand; prices have fallen almost 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for semiconductor chips is slow partly because of
slower-than-expected sales of personal computers. Analysts do not
expect demand to rise markedly for another couple of years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
