<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9550 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV14-NY     06-08 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT THERE IN RADIOLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 14)  
 (Eds: Items in boldface should be set in italics.)  
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What were the most memorable lines spoken on old-time radio?
</P>
<P>
   I can hear it now: Edward R. Murrow, not just saying, ``This ...
is London,'' but describing what he saw in a sortie over Berlin
with the RAF: ``The small incendiaries were going down like a
fistful of rice thrown on a piece of black velvet. The `cookies,'
the 4,000-pound high explosives, were bursting below like great
sunflowers gone mad.''
</P>
<P>
   And two years later, the equally familiar voice of his CBS
colleague Bob Trout, announcing on V-J day in 1945: ``This, ladies
and gentlemen, is the end of the Second World War.''
</P>
<P>
   Listen now to the opening line of the NBC science-fiction story
``Knock'' on the 1950 series ``Dimension X'': ``The last man on
Earth sat alone in a room. There was a knock on the door.''
</P>
<P>
   A modern editor would have to make changes in all those lines.
By ``the last man on Earth,'' the writer meant ``the last person'';
now, because the male no longer embraces the female, he would have
to write ``the last person on Earth'' because the listener would
immediately assume that the source of the knocking was a woman, and
not some subhuman or superhuman species.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a newly spawned Trout would be less likely to say
``ladies and gentlemen,'' nomenclature so dated as to seem quaint,
and not even used on the doors of lavatories anymore. And the
dramatic  &UR; this &LR; , which used to be in fashion on radio to begin a
sentence, has fallen into an innocuous desuetude.
</P>
<P>
   Malapropisms, however, need no updating. ``I don't object to
President Roosevelt using the radio to inform the country on the
state of the nation,'' said a man in the audience on the Blue
Network's ``Town Meeting of the Air,'' ``but I do object to his
using it to propagate.'' And a character eagerly awaiting the
arrival of the Lone Ranger shouts, ``I hear a white horse on the
way!''
</P>
<P>
   These and other great moments in the broadcast word are taken
from John Dunning's ``On the Air: The Encyclopedia of Old-Time
Radio'' (Oxford University Press, $55).
</P>
<P>
   Comedy was based on carefully established character traits, a
technique that carried over into television sitcoms. Jack Benny was
the tightwad who, when held up by a thief demanding ``Your money or
your life!'' answered with a long silence, interrupting the
laughter only with ``I'm thinking.'' The bandleader Phil Harris
played his role with swaggering stupidity: ``Phil is spelled with a
 &UR; P &LR; ?''
</P>
<P>
   The classic word-picture was Fred Allen's trope about NBC
censors: ``They are a bit of executive fungus that grows on a desk
that's been exposed to conference.'' Groucho Marx's standard
question for politicians who appeared as contestants on his quiz
show _ ``How many times have you been indicted?'' _ would not be so
funny today, but his regular query to baseball umpires _ ``Do you
have any little thieves at home?'' _ is still apt.
</P>
<P>
   But the humor most missed today is the flash of wit. When a
young woman told Groucho, ``I go to a college for girls,'' he
riposted, ``That's the reason I'd want to go, too.'' And when the
Shakespearean expert and sportswriter John Kieran was stumped on
``Information, Please'' by a question that was sent in by his son,
he said, ``How sharper than a thankless tooth it is to have a
serpent child.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people today think ``Information, Please'' is the name of
an almanac. It was once a literate radio program, moderated by
Clifton Fadiman, that was broadcast from 1938 to 1951. The title
was based on what telephone users would say to smilingly live
operators when an unknown listing was desired. Of time and the
river of language: Now we pay for the information from a robot that
dials it for us for an additional 35 cents, and nobody has to say
``please.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW OID WOID
</P>
<P>
   A  &UR; syllogism &LR; , from the Greek for ``summing up,'' means ``the
drawing of a logical conclusion from two premises.'' In current
use, the deduction may be deceptive: ``All politicians and pundits
are venal; Safire is a political pundit; therefore, Safire is
doubly venal.'' The reasoning is seemingly logical but may be
false.
</P>
<P>
   In a footnote to his recent dissent from the Supreme Court
decision on Steel &AMP; Pickling Co. vs. Citizens for a Better
Environment, Justice John Paul Stevens used a syllogistic
construction: ``If A ... can be decided before B, and if B ... can
be decided before C ... then logic dictates that A ... can be
decided before C.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia, pickling Stevens for the majority,
observed that his brother justice's argument was ``replete with
extensive case discussions, case citations, rationalizations and
 &UR; syllogoids &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard of  &UR; factoid &LR; ,'' writes Stephen L. Wasby, professor
of political science at the State University of New York at Albany,
``but where did  &UR; syllogoid &LR;  come from?''
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; -oid &LR;  suffix, rooted in the Greek for ``shape,'' creates a
noun or adjective meaning ``similar but not the same; having the
characteristics of.'' A  &UR; factoid &LR; , coined in 1973 by Norman Mailer,
is an imagined or simulated fact.
</P>
<P>
   The noun  &UR; syllogoid &LR; , therefore, means ``an argument having the
form but not the logical force of a  &UR; syllogism &LR; .'' To Wasby's
point: Whence  &UR; syllogoid &LR; ?
</P>
<P>
   An exhaustive search of databases and legal tomes reveals that
we have here what the Greeks called a  &UR; hapax legomenon &LR;  _ a word of
which only one use is recorded in all literature. (Happens a few
times in the Book of Job, making that text so hard to translate.)
In other words: (A, major premise) the word didn't exist; (B, minor
premise) Scalia used it; (C, logical conclusion) Scalia must have
coined it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only three possible responses to your note,'' Scalia
responds to my written query, ``none of which is satisfactory. The
first displays illiteracy (`You mean  &UR; syllogoid &LR;  is not a word?'),
the second confesses incompetence (since a coinage that has to be
explained is a failure) and the third risks giving offense. I pick
the last, and shall not respond at all, which I hereby do. Best
regards.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1751EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9551 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAST-MILKMAN-COX     06-08 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAST-MILKMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Milkman: last of a generation
 &HT;    Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--He is is a dying breed. Yet Rick Lee will not go gentle
into that good night. His job won't let him. Nor, for that matter,
will his truck.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, three hours before sunup, somewhere deep in the
sprawl of Cobb County, Lee's milk truck has started to sputter. And
so has Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to that,'' he says, cocking an ear at the dashboard of
his 11-year-old Chevy C-130 with 252,000 miles on the odometer. The
engine sounds like it's coughing on a tough piece of steak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looks like I'm going to have to get her some new sparkers and
maybe a new rotary button for the distributor.''
</P>
<P>
   Some days it seems that the world's set against you. When you're
one of the last milkmen in metro Atlanta, those days start around
2:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   For the last 27 years, Lee has been rising at that hour to thank
his luck, curse his luck and deliver milk, eggs, butter, cottage
cheese and orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   From childhood it's a job he felt fated to do. He grew up in
DeKalb County,Ga., near Mathis Dairy. ``I learned to swim in the
pond there,'' he says. ``Splashing around next to all them cows.''
</P>
<P>
   He went to work for the dairy in 1971, a veteran home from
Vietnam, newly married and expecting a child.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, milkman was a job with a future. There were eight
Atlanta dairies with home delivery. On his first route in East
Point and College Park, Lee had 230 customers.
</P>
<P>
   He soon found that, with customers defecting to grocery stores
for cheaper milk, competition for the delivery business was
cutthroat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys from other dairies would do things like break your
bottles after you'd delivered them and leave a big mess on the
porch,'' Lee says. ``Or they would inject lemon juice through the
cap and spoil the milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then they'd call the customer the next day and ask: `Are you
happy with your service?'''
</P>
<P>
   One by one, home-delivery operations folded until only Mathis
survived.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 _ its fleet having shrunk in two decades from 80 trucks
to 25 _ Mathis, too, quit delivering milk and farmed out its
remaining routes to drivers with their own trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Lee is one of only eight milkmen still working in
Atlanta. Seven deliver Mathis products, one Parmalat. All of them
depend on long-time customers. ``I'm probably a last-generation
milkman,'' Lee says.
</P>
<P>
   He can't beat grocery prices _ he delivers a half-gallon of 2
percent for $2 _ although his milk probably beats grocery
freshness. Still, he says, his survival depends on selling
something without an expiration date.
</P>
<P>
   ``My customers don't buy milk,'' he says. ``They're buying me.''
</P>
<P>
   Slender, with shoulder-length brown hair streaked gray, Lee
looks his 50 years. His voice is nasal and high-pitched. He strikes
you as an odd, twangy, small-town character. A guy who stood still
so long the city sprouted around him.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking over his Cobb County route in 1980, that's pretty
much what's happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``That used to be a farm,'' he says, driving up Johnson Ferry
Road hours before daybreak, pointing out retail tracts north of the
infamous Riverside Drive intersection where, last year, somebody _
probably an irate commuter _ shot the stoplight with a gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't believe how much this place has grown up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee has 200 regular customers. Friday is his shortest route of
the week. This morning he'll drive 50 miles to deliver 78 gallons
of milk, a dozen eggs, a pint of cottage cheese and 4 gallons of
orange juice to 38 homes.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't wear a watch. He keeps track of time listening to the
radio (``When Randy and Spiff come on Fox 97, I know it's 6
o'clock''). He runs stop signs and occasionally red lights (``I
just don't see the point when there ain't anybody out here but me
and some jackrabbits'').
</P>
<P>
   Most mornings, he says, the testiest part of the job is dodging
``health nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got people out here jogging and walking their dogs on
800-foot leashes, and I come over the top of a hill and they're in
the middle of the road.''
</P>
<P>
   One morning he almost ran over a guy who was barefoot, wearing
nothing but a pair of green underwear and trotting down the center
line. ``He was into some serious squirrel,'' Lee says.
</P>
<P>
   Another time he happened upon the daughter of one of his
customers in a compromising position with her boyfriend on the hood
of the family sedan parked in the carport.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me, `If you tell my parents, I'll get them to cancel
their milk delivery,''' says Lee. ``I said I wouldn't. I mean,
whatever floats your boat.''
</P>
<P>
   He switches off his headlights at most stops to avoid waking
customers, bounds out of the truck and grabs the plastic jugs of
milk from the cooler. (Mathis quit bottling in glass four years
ago.) He half-jogs, half-skitters to the door and back.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally he leaves the milk, chilled to 35 degrees, in one
of the metal milk coolers some of his customers still have from the
old days. Most of the time he leaves it by the front door or
garage.
</P>
<P>
   A stop takes about 45 seconds. Then it's sometimes two miles to
the next customer.
</P>
<P>
   He knows each by name and has a bit of biographical information
on every one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stan Sikorski does something with computers,'' he says. ``His
wife, Karen, bears a striking resemblance to Brooke Shields. Her
hobby is music. She plays piano. They don't have children. They
have cats.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sikorskis have been customers for 12 years. They could buy
milk maybe 40 cents a half-gallon cheaper at the grocery. But it
wouldn't be the same, Stan says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just die-hard lovers of home delivery,'' he says. ``And,
beyond that, we feel we have a relationship with Rick.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a relationship Lee goes out of his way to cultivate. Apart
from his twice-a-week deliveries, he's become, over the past three
years, an everyman poet and philosopher.
</P>
<P>
   Yearly, he writes a Christmas story for his customers. And every
month he appends a story or bit of homespun wisdom at the bottom of
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Aphorisms _ ``If you don't stand for something you'll fall for
anything'' _ spice his conversation. Most of them concern the
importance of the family.
</P>
<P>
   Lee himself is divorced with two children. But the sting of the
split, 16 years ago, still hurts.
</P>
<P>
   ``My ex-wife is a good woman,'' he says. ``But as it turned out,
she didn't love me. And she just didn't like me being a milkman _
and neither did her mother.''
</P>
<P>
   He writes the stories and proverbs in his head, thinking about
them while he drives his route. Then it's a matter of condensing
them into a cohesive paragraph or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``This month, since it's Father's Day, the story I have is
called `A Light at the Top of the Stairs,' '' says Lee. ``Some of
the best conversations I ever had with my dad were late at night
when he was waiting up for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about how Dad is always there, waiting for you, to give
you guidance in your darkest hour.''
</P>
<P>
   It's near sunup and the streets are crawling alive with what
soon will be a headlong crush of commuters. Lee makes his last stop
and heads south on Johnson Ferry trying to beat gridlock before it
beats him.
</P>
<P>
   He picked up a new customer this morning. But he's fretting
about his old truck. Two days ago he dropped $175 on a new water
pump. The cooler leaks Freon. He piles ice on the milk to keep it
cold.
</P>
<P>
   Although he sells $8,000 worth of milk a month, after expenses
he takes home $1,600 to $2,400.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he thinks about another career. Then he looks around
and figures there's something to be said for being an anachronism
on wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little scary being in business for yourself,'' he says.
``But the good thing about is, you know exactly what you're doing,
exactly where you're going and exactly what you're delivering _ and
there ain't a whole lot of paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many people you know can say that about their jobs?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
