</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Learning right way to lose just as important as homers
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For us, the baseball season at Morgan Falls Park ended last week
in 90-degree heat, throat-parching dust and a thrashing at the
hands of the White Sox. The playoffs are double elimination, and
the Yankees are out of it.
</P>
<P>
   No one on our side of the field felt especially good afterward.
It was only a few weeks ago that we played the season opener,
winning, and the pennants flapping in the breeze on that spring day
seemed to augur a long run in the playoffs. Now we were packing up
the gear, leaving the field not as losers but as a bunch that had
lost. There's a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys,'' Coach Rob Windsor told his team of mostly
10-year-olds, ``we had a good year. I'm proud of all of you, and
you can be proud of how we played together as a team.'' Everyone
enjoys winning, he said, but sometimes you learn more by losing.
</P>
<P>
   I was thinking of this as I read letters responding to
free-lance writer Stan Moris' recent op-ed article in the Atlanta
Constitution. I don't know Moris, but I admired the honesty of his
piece.
</P>
<P>
   Moris and his 7-year-old son had had the experience of many
parents and kids who participate in organized baseball: Winning and
fun don't always mix, and you soon learn which of the two the
coaches _ and many parents _ care about more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is neighborhood baseball kid-driven or adult-driven?'' he
asked. ``I wonder. Too many parents and coaches have ... lost
perspective about what this is about. Sure, we all like to win. But
when winning is all that matters _ and 7-year-olds become the pawns
in the game _ something is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Three letters responding to Moris' article were all from men,
and none of them quite got the point. One letter writer, Jay Levy,
came close. Another, from Atlanta, cobbled together a few ex-jock
cliches and delivered a patronizing homily on hard work.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the letter writer from Sharpsburg, Ga. who made me
smile. This was the American male at his chest-thumping, clubhouse
best. ``The person who has had little success in winning and tries
to soothe his wounded ego by declaring winning to be unimportant,''
he wrote, ``is fooling himself and taking away any incentive he
might otherwise have had to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but ``there is no closer bond than that shared by
friends who fight the same fight together.''
</P>
<P>
   You would have thought it was the Battle of the Bulge, not a
baseball game played by boys who don't even shave.
</P>
<P>
   Americans like winners, not losers. Winning is ingrained in our
national mythology. We won the West, we won two World Wars and for
a long time we cleaned up in every Olympics. We measure our worth
in the won-lost column and take losing very personally.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is that all of us, sooner or later, lose. Forget
the baseball game, which is of no consequence anyway. We lose loved
ones, whether by death or divorce. Some of us lose a career and our
identity with it. Many of us will lose our health, if we only live
long enough, and others will lose hope.
</P>
<P>
   It seems reasonable to think the competitive spirit would work
to preserve the last, but it's hard to find any correlation. If the
sports pages are any index, the number of athletes with emotional
and psychological problems is disproportionate to the general
population. Many have been winners all their lives _ on the field,
at least. Somehow they never learned to win off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Men cling to the notion of sports as a metaphor for life. But
when the going gets tough, the tough don't always come through.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just athletes. Many studies have shown a higher
incidence of alcoholism and other problems among certain
high-achieving professional classes _ physicians, specifically _
than among the population at large. You don't get into medical
school _ or through it _ without discipline and an incentive to
excel. But they are not always assurances of much beyond the
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the letter writer from Sharspburg was very young, without
much experience in life. Or maybe he just knew more about sports
than he did life. It's easy to confuse the two.
</P>
<P>
   In five years at Morgan Falls, we've been lucky. We always seem
to get the best coaches, even if we haven't always had the best
teams. This year, Rob Windsor, an orthopedic surgeon, and D.K.
White, a contractor, let the kids play aggressively, take chances
and have a good time whatever the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   And they let the kids take their lumps, too. They're small
lumps, after all. But when a kid struck out or fumbled a grounder,
the coaches weren't full of frowns and recrimination (as a couple
of the parents were). They gave him a supportive pat on the rear
and told him he'd do better next time.
</P>
<P>
   They were coaches interested in developing young people, not
just players. As it turned out, the team won some and lost some,
like all of us. The kids enjoyed the winning _ that came naturally.
It was the losing that was hard to accept. No one wanted to, but
that's life.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
