</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duchovny marking his time with `X-Files'
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beverly Hills, Calif. _ David Duchovny is pretty much Foxed out.
``There are days when I'm sick of Mulder,'' he says. ``I'd love to
leave it behind. Sometimes it seems like all I do is play Mulder or
prepare to play Mulder or talk about playing Mulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is, of course, what he's being forced to do over and over
these days as the publicity machine cranks up for the June 19
opening of ``The X-Files: Fight the Future,'' the big-screen film
in which Duchovny stars as Fox Mulder, paranoid investigator of the
paranormal.
</P>
<P>
   Considering he'd rather be about anywhere besides cooped up in a
hotel room talking about ``The X-Files'' with a string of
journalists, he's pretty cool. He kicks off his shoes and leans
back on a couch, more relaxed than TV viewers have ever seen
Mulder.
</P>
<P>
   Duchovny says he has two more years on his contract with Fox's
TV series and then that's it: It will be over. Other players have
three-year contracts (such as co-star and Emmy winner Gillian
Anderson, who plays Scully) but it seems unlikely that Duchovny
will extend his contract, and the show would almost certainly close
up if he left.
</P>
<P>
   Almost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Files'' is the highest-rated show on the Fox network,
and if its ratings remain high, the corporate controllers would do
virtually anything to keep it on the air.
</P>
<P>
   But even Chris Carter, the show's producer and guiding light,
seems resigned to Duchovny's two-year deadline. He says he supports
Duchovny's honesty about being tired of playing Mulder.
</P>
<P>
   When the movie debuts, fans of the TV show are likely to be
buzzing more about what's not in the film than what's there.
Carter's reasoning for how many questions the film doesn't answer:
``You'd be more irritated if I made it simplistic than if I made it
complex.''
</P>
<P>
   While the film does reveal some of the show's out-there truth,
it doesn't tell all. Among the gleanings:
</P>
<P>
   -- The alien factor: Some key elements of the TV show come to
light with explanations of how aliens are trying to colonize the
Earth and how a mysterious powerful group known as the Syndicate is
collaborating with them.
</P>
<P>
   -- The sister and daddy factor: An explanation for the abduction
of Mulder's sister, Samantha, was filmed, but cut because it was
considered too confusing for nonfans. And if you want to learn more
about Mulder's true father, forget it. It's not even mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   -- The buzz factor: In what may become the most talked-about
scene in the film, millions of bumblebees swarm Mulder and Scully.
</P>
<P>
   -- The love factor: What's been a slow evolution on TV toward
more emotional closeness between Mulder and Scully picks up steam
in the film. But they're not yet to the mutual back rub stage.
</P>
<P>
   -- The end factor: Another thing that wound up on the
cutting-room floor was a shot of Duchovny's naked behind, peeking
through a hospital gown. Duchovny jokingly says he liked it because
``it was completely gratuitous, and the only way to do nudity in a
movie is to be gratuitous.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
