<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Across the river and into the pool
hall
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ACROSS THE RIVER _ For you who don't know, that's a local
euphemism for the next county over where influential beverages are
legally sold.
</P>
<P>
   But there comes a time when a man has to consider his conduct,
as judged by community mores.
</P>
<P>
   So it is for me, now that I have a young grandson.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I'm across the river, shooting pool with my Cousin
Bubba. I want to be ready and able to teach my grandson what a
man's gotta know to be a man.
</P>
<P>
   Yessir, I can just see the little tyke there by his
grandfather's side as I rack up the balls.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that I'm still in the learning stage.
</P>
<P>
   Drat it that I never learned to shoot pool. All those years I
frittered away working hard and trying to get ahead _ I could
instead have been devoting myself to the pool halls.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than a pool stick I chose to be a stick in the mud.
</P>
<P>
   Now I'm trying to right all of that in all of the wrong places.
</P>
<P>
   The particular place we stopped is sort of a backwoods version
of Cheers, where everybody knows your alias.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever says, ``Here's looking at you.'' East Texas
honky-tonks being what they are, best that you don't make eye
contact.
</P>
<P>
   Cousin Bubba knows his way around such local joints. And the
locals know him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bubba!'' the lady bartender called out as we walked through
the doors. ``Where you been so long?''
</P>
<P>
   You'd almost think they'd been keeping his stool warm for him.
</P>
<P>
   That's the good thing about being a good ol' boy. Everybody's
glad to see you coming.
</P>
<P>
   As for me, I'm more of a doog 'ld yob, or whatever the opposite
is. Nobody's glad to see me. It's as if they don't even see me.
</P>
<P>
   If they ever look my way it's out of the corner of their eye.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the way I shoot pool. If the stick were a six-gun,
I'd shoot myself in the foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put a little English on it,'' Cousin Bubba instructed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right-o,'' I responded, stiff upper lip and all that.
</P>
<P>
   The game is called 8-ball. The idea is to sink your balls,
either solids or stripes, before your opponent sinks his, all the
while saving the 8-ball until last.
</P>
<P>
   Bubba let me go first. I did my best with the break. The ol'
boys at the bar did their best not to break out laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot,'' I muttered.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what Bubba did.
</P>
<P>
   He won the first game.
</P>
<P>
   He won the second game.
</P>
<P>
   He won the third game.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, he was apologizing for being so rusty.
</P>
<P>
   About the time he was getting warmed up, I was giving up.
</P>
<P>
   I guess I waited too late in life. Man's gotta be what a man's
gotta be. And I'll never be in the pool hall Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   More's the pity for my grandson. I've nothing to pass on to him.
</P>
<P>
   Then again ...
</P>
<P>
   There's always the domino hall.
</P>
<P>
   Yessir, I can just see the little tyke there by his
grandfather's side as I shuffle those bones.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that I can see that Bubba's there, too, leaning over
my shoulder and trying to explain the game to me.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily
</P>
<P>
   News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is
P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin, Texas 75915; e-mail is
awew18a(at)prodigy.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
