<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, June 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The widespread chill east of the Rockies will continue to
moderate as high pressure moves off the Atlantic Seaboard. A broad
air flow from the South will draw very warm and more humid air into
the southern Plains and lower Mississippi Valley. Cool air across
the northern tier states will be stubborn in its retreat and the
result will be abundant clouds and showers from the Middle Atlantic
Coast to the upper Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Dry and seasonably cool air will dominate the Northeast, though
sunshine will be hidden by clouds at times. An area of high
pressure over the northern Great Lakes will hold firm, and this
will stymie the advance of sultry weather into New England. Winds
at 5,000 feet will blow from the Southwest toward the Ohio and
Tennessee Valleys. This surge of summery weather will trigger
clusters of showers and thunderstorms, particularly near the
western and central Appalachians. Some of the rain will progress
into the Carolinas and Virginia where onshore breezes will direct
ocean-cooled air inland.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Gulf Coast will see some sun, and it will be sultry
with isolated afternoon thunderstorms. More storms will develop
farther inland over the South as a warm front pushes slowly
northeastward. A few locally severe storms are possible in the
eastern Plains and Middle Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A disturbance over the Rockies should sponsor afternoon
thundershowers from the Wyoming mountains to the southern Sierra.
Considerable clouds will keep temperatures below season levels in
all but the interior Northwest. The deserts of the Southwest will
turn bright and a bit warmer.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny skies are expected in sections of the Florida panhandle
and the northern parts of Michigan due to nearby high-pressure
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Sunny Night
</P>
<P>
   Mostly sunny was the forecast issued Sunday evening by the
National Weather Service at Barrow, Alaska. Around this time of
year, the sun never sets at Barrow, a town located near latitude 71
degrees. Earlier, temperatures had soared to 51 degrees, one degree
shy of the record high for the date. Given that prevailing winds
from the northeast blow off icy waters of the Arctic Ocean and
import cold air into Barrow, the average high on June 7 is 35
degrees. But winds blew from the southeast on Sunday, allowing
temperatures to rise to levels more harmonious with 24 hours of
sunshine.
</P>
</TEXT>
