<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-JUDIASM _ JERUSALEM _ Standing behind police barricades
at the holy site of the Western Wall, American leaders in the
less-traditional, Reform, branch of Judaism Monday said Israel is
trying to de-legitimize them. Eric Yoffie, president of the Union
of American Hebrew Congregations and about 100 rabbis and members
of Reform congregations are attempting to dissuade Israeli leaders
from passing the so-called Conversion Law. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service). EDs: To move by 2 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DROUGHT _ AUSTIN, Texas (developing) Wildfire experts who
have been assessing dry conditions in Central Texas will identify
some of the most serious problems Monday, while Texas Gov. George
W. Bush is expected to address the drought in a press conference.
He may be asking for federal assistance to fight wildfires.
(Banta/Herman, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   INTEL _ WASHINGTON _ The Federal Trade Commission is expected to
file an antitrust suit against chip-making giant Intel. (Glass, Cox
News Service) Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-BUDGETS _ ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech won't have its lights
turned off, but the school may have to delay some projects next
year thanks to an upcoming operating budget shortfall. (Suggs,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-CONVERT _ Southern Baptists from across the nation,
meeting for their national convention in Salt Lake City, are taking
part in an effort to persuade Mormons to change their beliefs, to
reach the unchurched with the gospel of Jesus and maybe to win back
some Southern Baptists who converted to Mormonism. (Perkes, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
