<P>
   NIGERIA-ABACHA (Lagos) _ From wires: Gen. Sani Abacha, the
Nigerian dictator who crushed dissent, defied world condemnation,
and repeatedly put off handing power over to a civilian government,
died on Monday of a heart attack, leaving leadership of Africa's
most-populous nation in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-FTC (Washington) _ From wires: the Federal Trade
Commission on Monday filed a narrowly focused complaint against
Intel Corp., charging it illegally abused its monopoly over
computer microprocessors to restrain competition. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-ENVIRON (Trenton) _ In New Jersey, Gov. Christie Whitman is
putting her tax-cutting record at risk with a proposal to raise the
gasoline tax to help preserve half of the state's 2 million
remaining acres of undeveloped land over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-POLLUTE (Washington) _ Honda and Ford used devices on
hundreds of thousands of vehicles that made them run dirtier, and
perform worse, but also made them seem more reliable to owners.
Automakers will pay a record 24 million in fines and spend more
than $250 million to repair vehicles now on the road. By Matthew L.
Wald. 800 words &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (In the Shkelzen Mountains, Serbia) _ The
guerrilla force here, despite the hundreds of volunteers and
impressive arms supplies, remains poorly organized, led by
commanders with little experience. Recruits receive desultory
training that rarely goes beyond showing them how to clean,
assemble, and fire AK-47 assault rifles. The rebels also appear to
have embraced a disastrous military strategy, holding ground
against superior Serb forces for days until retreating with heavy
losses. By Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-HARASS (Toledo, Ohio) _ Students and other Chinese living
in the United States who have visited their homeland in recent
weeks report an unusual number of incidents in which they have been
taken into custody, interrogated and threatened by the police. By
Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-LAWYERS (Undated) _ Lawyers who fought the tobacco
industry have found a new focus for their energies: fighting for
their share of the spoils from lawsuits against the industry. The
issue of the lawyers' fees has become intensely controversial in
states that have settled lawsuits against cigarette makers as well
as in Congress, which is considering federal tobacco legislation.
At stake is the richest pot of fees in the legal history. By Barry
Meier and Jill Abramson.
</P>
