<HEADER>
A9606 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALVADOR-DALTON-700(2     06-08 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALVADOR-DALTON-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUERRILLA POET LIONIZED AT LAST BUT STILL ELUSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador _ It would surely have amused Roque
Dalton, inveterate bohemian and revolutionary that he was, to know
that the right-wing government in power here recently added his
poetry to the school curriculum. A fierce critic of organized
religion, he no doubt would also have chuckled at the notion that a
Jesuit-run university was sponsoring a project to publish his
complete works.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a quarter-century after he was killed by leftist
guerrillas who thought his vagabond ways a threat to their
clandestine struggle, Roque Dalton has finally become respectable.
Persecuted and scorned in his Central American homeland throughout
his turbulent life, Dalton has become both a symbol and a
beneficiary of the new, more liberal intellectual climate that has
emerged since a long and bloody civil war ended six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roque was one of the most important writers of his time, but
he died young, and because the war went on for so long, his works
were always prohibited and it was forbidden to talk of him,'' said
Aida de Dalton, the writer's widow and the caretaker of his estate.
``Now we are living in a time in which there is space to do all of
that, and a new generation is at last able to investigate his life
and work.''
</P>
<P>
   What Salvadoran readers are finding in collections like ``The
Offended Party's Turn'' and ``A Slightly Repellent Book'' is a
plain-spoken and mordantly humorous writer whose work seems as
timely as ever. Dalton grappled eloquently not only with the
universal themes of love and death and beauty, but also with such
specifically Central American concerns as what it means to be the
citizen of ``a Tom Thumb country'' on the margins of history and
burdened with huge social injustices.
</P>
<P>
   ``To many, Roque Dalton is the best Salvadoran poet who ever
lived,'' said the Rev. Rodolfo Cardenal, a Jesuit priest and vice
rector of the University of Central America who is overseeing the
publication project. ``He understood the reality of this country
and its struggle, and knew how to express the most genuine
aspirations of our people, which makes him an obligatory reference
point in defining Salvadoran nationality.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In ``Small Hours of the Night,'' now the title poem of an
English-language anthology of his verse (Curbstone Press: 1996),
Dalton wrote:
</P>
<P>
   When you know I'm dead, don't say my name
</P>
<P>
   Because then death and peace would have to wait
</P>
<P>
   Your voice, the bell of your five senses, would form
</P>
<P>
   The thin beam of light my mist would be looking for
</P>
<P>
   When you know I'm dead, say other words
</P>
<P>
   Say flower, bee, teardrop, bread, storm
</P>
<P>
   Don't let your lips find my eleven letters
</P>
<P>
   I'm sleepy, I've loved, I've earned silence
</P>
<P>
   Don't say my name when you know I'm dead
</P>
<P>
   I would come out of the dark ground for your voice
</P>
<P>
   Blessed with a fecund imagination and a prolific pen, Dalton
wrote not only hundreds of poems, but also several novels, a play,
a history of El Salvador, the biography of a Communist Party
leader, countless letters and numerous essays on literature and
politics, like ``Poetry and Militancy in Latin America.'' The
University of Central America aims to make it all available in the
Spanish-speaking world eventually, and perhaps even to publish a
biography of the writer.
</P>
<P>
   Neither task, however, promises to be easy, in large part
because Dalton, who was executed on May 10, 1975, just a few days
before his 40th birthday, apparently wanted it that way. At various
times, he lived in Chile, Mexico, Cuba, Czechoslovakia and Vietnam,
moving in and out of romantic relationships, constantly revising
his poems and leaving behind correspondence and unfinished
manuscripts each time he went underground or had to go to prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roque was not a very organized person,'' said Rafael Lara
Martinez, who teaches Latin-American literature at the New Mexico
Institute of Mining and Technology and is preparing an anthology of
Dalton's poems for use in public schools here. ``He wrote poetry
almost like Mozart wrote music. If he walked into a bar, he'd write
a poem on a napkin while he was having a drink, and as you can
imagine, that does not make it easy to compile a definitive
edition.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dalton's own origins are even more difficult to pin down. Dr.
Lara Martinez described him as ``a surrealist figure who was his
own invention.'' Friends and fellow writers remember him claiming
that his father was one of the notorious Dalton Brothers gang of
bank robbers, an American who, after eluding the police in Kansas,
fled here around the turn of the century with ill-gotten gains that
became the basis of the family fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Other members of the Dalton family recall hearing that they are
descended from an American arms dealer who bolted to El Salvador
after defrauding Pancho Villa during the Mexican Revolution.
Whatever the truth, Roque Dalton himself grew up as the alienated,
illegitimate son of a prominent landowner, imbued with a hatred of
the elite from whom he was excluded and the military governments it
controlled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complex facts of Roque Dalton's life have been overlaid _
or in many cases clarified and defined _ by myth,'' Salvadoran
writer Claribel Alegria writes in her introduction to ``Small Hours
of the Night.'' ``Even among his closest friends it is nearly
impossible to talk about Roque without falling into verbal
chiaroscuro effects: superlative and anecdotal exaggerations.''
</P>
<P>
   As an adult, Dalton soon got into political trouble, was twice
jailed by right-wing military governments and, according to his own
writings, was sentenced to death. He was saved first in 1960 when a
coup d'etat occurred a day before he was scheduled to be executed
by a firing squad, and on a second occasion a few years later when,
at least according to legend, he managed to escape after a
devastating earthquake destroyed the prison in which he was being
held.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, it was his own colleagues in the guerrilla
band he had joined who killed him, after a show trial in which he
was charged with being both an American and a Cuban spy. For years
his fate was a dirty little secret that admirers in the
Latin-American left did their best to conceal. But as the civil war
was ending, the faction responsible, the Revolutionary People's
Army, acknowledged its ``tremendous error'' in ordering the murder.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear in retrospect that Dalton's crime, aside from his
lack of discipline, was to have advocated reaching out to form
alliances with student, labor and peasant organizations rather than
looking to a nucleus of determined fighters to spark a revolution.
That very strategy, of course, would eventually be adopted by
Dalton's guerrilla colleagues during the 12-year civil war, in
which more than 75,000 people died before it ended in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may seem ridiculous now, but in those days, anyone could be
accused of anything,'' Ana Guadalupe Martinez, a leader of the
group, which has evolved into the Democratic Party, said in an
interview here. ``Within the confined environment of a small group,
we were so fearful of being infiltrated that everyone suspected
everyone else. We would have been afraid of our shadows.''
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, Salvadoran lawmakers unanimously approved a
resolution declaring Dalton the country's only ``poet of great
merit'' of the modern era, adding him to the pantheon of national
heroes. Responding to that change in climate, his family has begun
an effort to organize a museum in his honor here and to hunt down
those original manuscripts that are still missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our task now to create the conditions in which people
can study him and really get to know him and value him in all of
his magnitude,'' said Juan Jose Dalton, the writer's son and a
well-known journalist here. ``We recognize that he is part of the
national patrimony now, as strange as that may sound.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
