<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9608 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-TOBACCO-REVIEW-NYT     06-08 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TOBACCO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TOBACCO BLUES': A VISIT WITH FOUR TOBACCO FARMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Tobacco Blues'' is a fresh, humanizing approach to a subject
that has been thoroughly demonized in recent years. In answer to
the question, ``Can good people grow tobacco?,'' the producers,
Christine Fugate and Eren McGinnis, visit with four Kentucky
families who bear no resemblance to the cigarette executives who
have come to personify the ills of smoking: it's innocence by
dissociation.
</P>
<P>
   In case you were really wondering, yes, of course good people
grow tobacco. These hands-on farmers represent family values,
parents and offspring working hard to make a living from their
state's main cash crop. They differ over the virtuousness of
growing tobacco (most seem to find smoking distasteful), and any of
them could stand in as wholesome images of down-home Americana.
</P>
<P>
   What comes through in these friendly and revealing interviews is
the farmers' sense of being a beleaguered culture. None have gotten
rich on tobacco, but all have raised their children on its
proceeds, only to find their legacy threatened by conditions far
beyond their control.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good life, a hard life,'' says a woman whose family
scratches its living out of 3{ acres. Her husband says, ``In a good
year, you break even.'' That includes food, shelter and health
insurance and doesn't take into account the satisfactions of being
part of a community, with family and friends laboring together to
deliver what they proudly call ``a hand-made crop.'' Even the
annual auction, entertainingly pictured here, has a communal
feeling.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of tobacco-inspired folk songs and soft-focus
atmospherics, this ``P.O.V.'' offering presents an attractive way
of life. These Kentuckians _ their slogan, ``Keep the FDA off the
Farms!'' _ make up a struggling little army. They foresee U.S.
growers being beaten down by the government and losing out to
overseas producers.
</P>
<P>
   The program ends with a plug for organic farming, to which one
farmer, who grants that cigarettes are ``a pretty toxic product,''
has converted with some success. But few of these folks are going
organic. A man, seen on his tractor with a cigarette between his
lips, says simply that in Kentucky you can't raise anything that
brings in as much money as tobacco. Another takes refuge behind
slogans: ``If someone has a reason to smoke it, then I have a
reason to grow it.''
</P>
<P>
   Economics and conscience, a community's values and a nation's
crusade are in conflict here. The program leaves the viewer with
one of the more prosperous farmers (and one of the few heavy
smokers encountered) wondering how to distinguish the cigarette
from the grower (at least the small-scale family grower) in the
public mind. ``Tobacco Blues,'' sympathetic without being sappy,
should help.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `P.O.V.'
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco Blues
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. ET Tuesday on PBS
</P>
<P>
   Christine Fugate and Eren McGinnis, producers; directed by Ms.
Fugate; Sandra Chandler, director of photography; Kate Amend,
editor; Doug Hamblin, original music; Michele Wernick, music
supervisor; Harry Dean Stanton, narrator. A production of Cafe
Sisters Productions. Produced in association with the Independent
Television Service. P.O.V. is produced by American Documentary
Inc.; Ellen Schneider, executive director; Ward Chamberlin, chief
executive officer.
</P>
</TEXT>
