   All items fit to fax to 212-556-3535 (24 hours), via uniformed
government courier, or, now by e-mail (nylite(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It's been 38 years since I moved from Greenwich Village to
Washington, but I still return regularly to Manhattan for, among
other pleasures, an eavesdropping fix. Here's what I overheard on
the fourth floor of Barney's recently:
</P>
<P>
   One salesperson to another: ``Every morning when I wake up I
thank God that I know how to accessorize.''
</P>
<P>
   _JUDITH VIORST
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes before the start of a recent Broadway performance,
a theatergoer suddenly realized that his tiny cell phone had
somehow slipped out of his pocket and was lost somewhere beneath
the seats in his row.
</P>
<P>
   His neighbors were frantically helping him search the dimly
lighted theater when, several rows back, a smartly dressed Wall
Street type waved his own cell phone in the air and shouted:
``Quick, what's your number? I'll call you from mine.'' Within 30
seconds, a steady and distinct ring led the owner to the precise
spot where his phone had fallen, just as the curtain was rising on
the first act.
</P>
<P>
   Libby Jane Thall still gets a laugh when she thinks about the
conversation she overheard on Marathon Sunday on the Upper East
Side. She stopped and asked a woman in a silver aluminum apres-race
cape how she had done. The woman replied that her time had been
great and, as Ms. Thall was congratulating her, a father with a
daughter about 5 years old walked by.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy, why is that lady dressed as a baked potato?'' the girl
asked.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent flight from Columbus, Ohio, to La Guardia Airport,
my wife and I were seated behind a woman with a girl of about 4 or
5. It was obviously the girl's first flight because the woman was
narrating every detail, about the plane, the clouds, etc.
</P>
<P>
   We approached New York from the south and were treated to a
spectacular view of the skyline, beginning with the Statue of
Liberty and proceeding along Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, there's New York City,'' the woman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So where's the big apple?'' the little girl replied.
</P>
<P>
   _RICHARD GELTZER
</P>
<P>
   The classic children's song ``The Wheels on the Bus Go Round and
Round'' is keeping up with the times in some milieus. True, the
wheels are still going round and round, the wipers are swishing and
the doors are opening and closing. But forget those coins going
clink, clink, clink.
</P>
<P>
   Bethany Kandel was at the Children's Museum with her two sons
recently when the sing-along leader led mothers and children in
updating the verse. Pretending to slide their cards, they sang,
``The Metrocard on the bus goes `transfer OK, transfer OK, transfer
OK,' all over town.''
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for the red light to change on Madison Avenue in the
50s, I looked down and saw a poignant message scratched in a small
repaved area off the curb. In block letters the message said:
``MILLY PLEASE COME HOME I LOVE YOU.''
</P>
<P>
   That opened a stream of questions. I assume that Milly is a
female and the writer a male. Who is Milly: a wife, friend, sister,
child, dog? Why did Milly leave? Where did she go? Did she love
him? Has she returned? If she has returned, are they happy
together?
</P>
<P>
   Did he know that Milly often frequented that corner so that she
would one day read the pleading message?
</P>
<P>
   REVA FOX wants to know.
</P>
<P>
   A friend writes that the movers were still going in and out of
his new apartment when a woman walked through the open door into
the living room and announced that she lived in one of the
prestigious buildings on the block. Her daughter was returning from
London, she said, and she wanted her to live in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   She had looked at the kitchen on her way in and the apartment
was perfect, she continued. As for the view, her daughter would
love it.
</P>
<P>
   The somewhat stupefied new tenant informed her that the
apartment wasn't available _ he had taken it. She ignored him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll look around and see if my daughter will be comfortable,''
she said blithely as she took off to look at the bedrooms. She
emerged from her inspection to query: ``Where are the other
bedrooms?'' She was told there was only the one.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will never do,'' the woman proclaimed and stalked off.
</P>
<P>
   And if there had been two or three bedrooms, what then?
</P>
<P>
   Strolling along Second Avenue in the 60s, Charles Potter passed
a rather frazzled young woman wearing a T-shirt that advised: MAKE
LOVE NOT LAW REVIEW.
</P>
<P>
   Scene: A red light on the Bowery.
</P>
<P>
   Players: Martin Zelkind and a panhandler.
</P>
<P>
   Action: The panhandler approaches Zelkind who, trying to
forestall the inevitable request, says: ``Please don't annoy me; I
have a headache.''
</P>
<P>
   Instantaneous response from the panhandler: ``Take two aspirins
and call me in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Did the panhandler accomplish his mission and get a handout? Of
course.
</P>
<P>
   Alison Schiff was walking through Central Park when she
encountered a small dog, barking wildly, tugging at his leash and
jumping in the air. The object of his excitement was a much larger
dog, also on a leash.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the small dog shook her head and addressed the
other owner. ``He just has no common sense,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Ring reports that merger mania apparently isn't confined
to the financial industry. She spotted this handwritten sign in the
window of a recently closed Chinese restaurant on the Upper East
Side. ``China Inn had merger with Ming Garden,'' it said, and
listed the new location.
</P>
<P>
   My son, Graham, a high school senior, and I often commute
together. We had just squeezed onto a crowded D train when I
glanced down and saw that my shoelace was untied. There were no
seats, nor even a place to lean against. I knew that bending down
to tie it meant, at best, getting my long coat and briefcase dirty
and, at worst, losing my balance when the train inevitably lurched.
</P>
<P>
   I was mumbling that I'd wait until I got off when Graham dropped
to a crouch and tied it for me. My beaming at him stopped abruptly
when he pulled himself up to full height, looked down at me and
announced, very loudly, ``You know, you're going to have to learn
how to do this yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   _DIANE M. GOETZ
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star), &LR;
</P>
