<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9630 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRATEFUL-DEAD-375&AMP;ADD     06-08 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRATEFUL-DEAD-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LIVING ARE GRATEFUL FOR THE DEAD'S LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a band that's defunct, the Grateful Dead have been mighty
busy lately. In San Francisco on Thursday night, the surviving core
of the Dead introduced their new band, the Other Ones, reclaiming
three decades' worth of Dead songs including, pointedly, songs by
Jerry Garcia, whose death in 1995 put an end to the band. On Friday
night, members of the Dead's sound crew were on the QVC
cable-television shopping channel, hawking live recordings of the
Dead and taking in a quick $70,000. And on Saturday night, the San
Jose Stage Company in California gave the premiere of ``Cumberland
Blues,'' a musical built around early-1970s songs by Garcia and
Robert Hunter, the band's best lyricist.
</P>
<P>
   It's rock as repertory: a recognition that songs are now assets
as well as anthems. They can outlast their original moment by years
and decades. As musicians grow long in the tooth, their best songs
stay vivid and mobile, still ready to reach far-flung audiences.
The tricky part, for musicians who care about the songs as well as
the profits, is to keep an eye on the context.
</P>
<P>
   The Dead have been careful. None of the material they recorded
has been made available for commercials. Of course, they're not
hurting for cash; Grateful Dead Merchandising, selling everything
from concert recordings to logo-embroidered denim shirts, took in
$14 million last year. And the group has accepted its status as an
institution: A $50 million Grateful Dead museum, to be called
Terrapin Station, will probably settle on a site this fall.
</P>
<P>
   In an institution, history can outweigh the present. While
nearly every touring band keeps favorite songs in the set list,
some bands have turned into repertory groups playing not just
oldies but full-length albums. The Who has toured with a concert
version of its 1973 album ``Quadrophenia''; Cheap Trick, harking
back to its 1970s heyday, performed all the songs from its 1979
album ``Live at Budokan'' last month and plans to return Oct. 29
through 31 with three shows at Tramps devoted to its first three
albums.
</P>
<P>
   The message is that longtime fans are connoisseurs whose
appreciation extends beyond mere hits. It's also a grudging
recognition that for most rock songwriters, experience and
craftsmanship pale next to the inspirations of youth.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Then there's the theater option; as rock fans age, they don't
mind sitting down for decorous entertainment. Rock songwriters are
no strangers to theater productions, from revues like the Lieber
and Stoller anthology ``Smokey Joe's Cafe'' to full-scale rock
operas like ``Tommy.'' ``Cumberland Blues'' was authorized but not
initiated by the Dead (unlike ``Tommy,'' which had Pete Townshend's
full involvement). In the early 1970s, the Dead put psychedelia on
hold and returned to songs steeped in country, bluegrass and blues;
the San Jose company got the idea that the tales of backwoods and
frontier life that Hunter's lyrics conjured could be turned into a
coherent story.
</P>
<P>
   Playwright Michael Norman Mann listened hard to the songs, and
like someone working out a narrative crossword puzzle, he connected
characters' names and recurring images of hard work, gambling,
drinking, death and redemption. He came up with a backwoods family
story: a gambler, a miner, a preacher (for the redemption angle)
and good and bad women. It's ingenious and good-natured but thick
with cliches: ``You just want what you can't have, and you always
did.'' Yet the tunes are sure-fire. There are in-jokes for Dead
Heads, and the staging of songs like ``Deal'' and ``Bertha'' brings
out their theatricality. If Cole Porter songs can be strung
together for the stage, so can Garcia-Hunter songs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Dead's members aren't all ready to sit back and savor
the royalties. Although Bill Kreutzmann, the original drummer, has
retired, Bob Weir, Phil Lesh and Mickey Hart are heading back on
the road as the Other Ones, headlining this summer's Furthur
Festival with two guitarists and a saxophonist in Garcia's place,
as well as Bruce Hornsby on keyboards and a new drummer.
</P>
<P>
   The Dead became an institution by touring constantly,
reinventing (and sometimes mangling) the repertory every night.
Durable as the songs are, they need to be played and played with.
The Other Ones may be looking back at a proud legacy, and the
guitarists in particular are working in a style that has been
handed down to them. But their job is to keep the songs alive and
wayward in the present, and their first show promised that they
won't spend too much time looking back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
