<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES ARE LITTLE CHANGED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices of Treasury securities ended little changed
Monday, as some investors took profits after Friday's gains. Few
investors were willing to make large bets ahead of Wednesday's
scheduled congressional testimony by Alan Greenspan, the chairman
of the Federal Reserve Board.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 2/32, to
104 29/32, leaving its yield unchanged at 5.78 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pugliese, senior vice president and director of the
fixed-income department at J.W. Charles Securities Inc. in Boca
Raton, Fla., said that Treasury securities were trading in a range
that was defined on Friday after the market rebounded from a strong
employment report.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 5.75 percent yield on the long bond is going to be a tough
psychological barrier to break below, and support seems to be good
in the 5.80 percent to 5.85 percent yield range,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Carver, chief technical analyst with Technical Data in
Boston, noted: ``The lack of movement following an
unemployment-data release is quite common, and actually friendly.
Bonds demonstrated that their higher close on Friday was not a
fluke, having accepted those gains on Monday and never moving
appreciably lower.''
</P>
<P>
   While few market participants expect Greenspan to signal any
change in monetary policy on Wednesday, many investors remained on
the sidelines Monday, knowing that his remarks have the potential
to prompt big swings in prices. Some analysts say the market will
be closely watching whether Greenspan focuses on domestic economic
strength or on Asian weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's regular weekly auction of new three-month and six-month
Treasury bills was uneventful, analysts said. The three-month issue
was sold at an average rate of 4.995 percent, up from 4.945 percent
last week, while the six-month issue was sold at an average rate of
5.155 percent, up from 5.110 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
