<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the business news stories the Los Angeles Daily News
plans to move for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of Tuesday, June 9 and thereafter. The stories will carry the ``f''
financial news category code unless otherwise noted. For questions
about stories, contact Stewart Slavin at the Daily News, (818)
713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   WELLS-FUTURE (Los Angeles) _ The banking supermarket is coming,
and not over by the bakery section of your grocery store, either.
Banks are scrambling to broaden the range of financial products
they offer, led by such fast-moving players as Norwest Corp., which
agreed Monday to merge with Wells Fargo in a $31 billion deal. By
Dave McNary. (Will also move in the ``n'' national and ``a''
national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   WELLS-MERGER (Los Angeles) _ What kind of services can area
customers expect from a combined Wells-Norwest? In California, at
least, Wells Fargo has a strong network of retail operations,
albeit mostly ATMs, while Norwest is one of the area's largest
mortgage lenders. Will this be a marriage in which two companies
are strengthened because of their complimentary services? Or is it
ridiculous to think that Wells Fargo can manage a smooth merger
with Norwest after all the problems it had swallowing First
Interstate. By Deborah Adamson.
</P>
<P>
   WOODY-BACK (Los Angeles) _ The beak is back, Universal has
proclaimed. That is, Woody Woodpecker is being dusted off the
nostaglia shelf and thrust onto the big and small screens. By Dave
McNary.
</P>
<P>
   LLOYD-COLUMN (Los Angeles) _ Let the hire beware. Daily News
columnist Ken Lloyd, Ph.D., a specialist in organizational
behavior, answers readers' questions on workplace ethics and
relationships.
</P>
</TEXT>
