<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9655 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTORNEY-CLIENT-HNS &LR;      06-08 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTORNEY-CLIENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT WEIGHS BOND OF SECRECY BETWEEN LAWYER AND CLIENT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court grappled Monday with the question
of whether the long-established attorney-client privilege survives
the client's death, asking whether any erosion of the privilege
would affect the way people talk to their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that the court should preserve the tradition, James
Hamilton, lawyer for the late White House Deputy Counsel Vincent
Foster Jr., urged the justices to rule that the notes of his
conversation with Foster shortly before the aide's suicide should
remain secret.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1993, Foster had become embroiled in a controversy
involving the firings of seven career employees of the White House
Travel Office and their replacement with political appointees, one
of whom was a distant cousin of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, worried that administration officials, particularly
Hillary Rodham Clinton, would face a congressional inquiry and
possibly a criminal probe of the firings, sought Hamilton's advice
on what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Vincent came to talk to me on July 11, (1993), he asked
me if our conversation was confidential, and I told him that it
was,'' Hamilton said. Foster killed himself nine days later.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said a decision by the court to erode the
attorney-client privilege, the idea that a lawyer cannot be
compelled to divulge anything a client says, ``would have a strong,
chilling effect on client candor.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``People do care about their reputations and family
and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brett Kavanaugh, representing Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr, contended that Hamilton's notes could prove vital to the
investigation into whether Mrs. Clinton or any presidential aides
lied about the first lady's role in the firings.
</P>
<P>
   Kavanaugh said that letting the privilege continue after the
death of a client would ``wall off critical evidence'' from
prosecutors seeking the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would mean that innocent people would be wrongly convicted
and guilty people would be wrongly exonerated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The D.C. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last August that after a
client's death, the attorney-client privilege is no longer
automatic in criminal cases. The panel said that in some cases,
such as Starr's, a prosecutor's search for truth outweighed a dead
client's interest in confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   But Kavanaugh urged the justices to go further than the appeals
court and rule that the attorney-client privilege should not extend
beyond the grave in all criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg asked Kavanaugh, a prosecutor in
Starr's office, whether investigators' interests could extend
beyond the notes to actually questioning Hamilton about what he
learned from his client. Kavanaugh replied, ``Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the outcome of this bitter legal dispute could affect
how thousands of Americans consult with lawyers, especially in
their final years, the justices intensely quizzed Hamilton and
Kavanaugh on their positions.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor asked Hamilton if he
would waive the privilege to provide information that would prevent
an innocent person from being convicted of a crime.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would.
</P>
<P>
   Then Justice Antonin Scalia asked if he would waive the
privilege to provide information that would give prosecutors the
information needed to convict a person who was guilty. Hamilton
said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you would provide evidence to exonerate someone but not to
prove someone guilty,'' Scalia said. ``That seems
disproportionate.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalia continued to hammer away at Hamilton's argument later,
questioning him on how prosecutors can get at the truth when a key
witness dies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In your opinion, there is nobody, no matter how important the
issue is to the public, who can say enough is enough and let out
the information,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton repeated his view that the privilege should remain
intact.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg asked Kavanaugh why he should be given information _
Hamilton's notes of his conversation with Foster _ that he would
not be entitled to if Foster were still alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he (Foster) was still alive, we could compel him to
testify,'' Kavanaugh replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we see examples every day of people refusing to answer
questions from prosecutors,'' Ginsburg shot back.
</P>
<P>
   During Kavanaugh's argument, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist
asked about an aging father seeking advice from his lawyer on how
he could help his drug-addicted son. Then, a few years later, after
the father's death, the son is on trial for a crime. Could that
lawyer be forced to testify against the son, Rehnquist asked.
</P>
<P>
   Kavanaugh said that the lawyer would have to testify and, in
essence, use a father's own words against his son.
</P>
<P>
   But Rehnquist said that a client ``must feel free to tell a
lawyer the truth and the whole truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy asked what would happen in a case
that involved more than one defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Would the death of one of them mean that his or her lawyer would
be compelled to testify on what the dead man said about the crime
and the guilt or innocence of the other defendants, Kennedy asked.
</P>
<P>
   Kavanaugh said the lawyer would have to testify.
</P>
<P>
   The court is expected to rule on the case by early July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
