<HEADER>
A9657 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUSTRALIA-FASHION-700     06-08 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRALIA-FASHION-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIA SHOWS OFF ITS DESIGNERS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER STEINHAUER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For decades, it has been the rule in Paris and Milan: if you
build it, on a shoulder pad or on the bias, they will come.
</P>
<P>
   But the Australian fashion industry has never enjoyed such
assurances. Although dozens of designers have been creating fashion
there for several years, they have toiled in relative obscurity,
far from the watchful and promotional eyes of magazine editors and
U.S. and European retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Now appears to be Australia's moment, with lowered trade
barriers, the lower cost of clothing from Down Under, and an
international retail industry starving for fresh talent.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps nothing has done more for the Australian fashion
industry than its members themselves, who in the last three years
have worked _ and spent _ with diligence to elevate their
visibility among buyers and editors around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what is happening in Australia is a very big deal,''
said April Hughes, the fashion editor of Elle magazine, who
attended this year's shows in Sydney. ``A lot of people are ready
for fresh talent, and we found it there.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Australian Fashion Innovators, the country's fashion
trade group, held its third and by far most sophisticated fashion
week, which showcased 45 designers on the runway, up from 25 three
years ago, to promote the country's $8 billion industry. The
organization, which is run by Simon Lock, Australia's own Howard
Rubensteinesque promoter, has aggressively courted the media and
retailers since its inception, and this year got significant
response.
</P>
<P>
   With deep pockets filled by the show's main sponsor, Mercedes,
as well as by others like Moet &AMP; Chandon and Diet Coke, the
organization underwrote the trip for editors and retailers and
provided them with drivers and guides to shuttle them to shows,
stores and fine restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   And if all this courting were not enough, all the shows were
held in one location, and started on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other designers attract media and retailers from the U.S. and
Europe,'' said Lock, the founder and managing director of
Australian Fashion Innovators. ``We have had no such luck. So, we
have had to aggressively market this event. The strategy is to
support people with tight budgets for the first few years, with the
idea that they will eventually foot their own bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the horde were Bonnie Pressman, the fashion director of
Barneys New York, and buyers from Henri Bendel, Fred Segal and
Browns of London, as well as several American and European fashion
writers.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the perks, fashion hunters were also impressed with the
depth and variety of Australian fashion. Many Australian designers
are clearly influenced by the deep blues and bright colors of the
surrounding sea and rain forest, and the fabrics and patterns of
neighboring Asia, refreshing rejoinders to most of fashion's dark
palette. And Australia's runways are hosts to talent from New
Zealand and Southeast Asia as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The population of Australia is so culturally mixed, it is
difficult to say we are influenced by any one thing,'' said Pamela
Easton, a partner in Easton Pearson, a Brisbane-based company that
makes ethereal dresses with fabrics found in India. ``It is a huge
melting pot.''
</P>
<P>
   The cultural devotion to leisure and the warm climate have a
strong impact as well, evident in airy fabrics and
close-to-the-body cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of designers are also taking dribs and drabs from the
American and European designers who set the fashion agenda, one
that Australians approach with ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, they want to make clear that they are
technically savvy, have their own Vogue magazine and furiously
consume fashion news, making them as hip to the scene as their
contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the designers also like to use their distance
from the rest of the world as a badge of honor, representing
immunity from derivation. ``When you live this far away, you live
with blinkers on,'' said Marion Hume, a highly regarded English
fashion journalist who is now the editor in chief of Australian
Vogue. ``They have no interest in what the rest of the world is
doing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Either way, there are certainly designers with unique imprints.
The most famous Australian designer these days _ save Richard
Tyler, who has all but lost his passport _ is doubtless Collette
Dinnigan.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dinnigan traces her roots a decade back to a silk and
chiffon lingerie collection that was picked up by Saks Fifth
Avenue. Lace, silks, rose prints and other feminine accents were
later turned into a clothing line anchored by evening looks.
</P>
<P>
   Saks and Barneys have both carried the collection for a few
years. ``She started at a time with all this femininity, and sheer
was very important,'' said Nicole Fischelis, the fashion director
of Saks. ``She has established name recognition.'' Indeed, Ms.
Dinnigan was invited last spring to show in Paris by the Chambre
Syndicale.
</P>
<P>
   A newer but no less exciting face is Akira Isogawa, who moved to
Australia from Kyoto, Japan, in 1987 and has been creating fashion
in his new home since the early 1990s. His signature look is a
combination of antique kimono fabrics mixed with modern fabrics in
extremely sophisticated shapes. Among his designs were a natural
cotton dress padded with red cotton and embroidered with silver,
white silk Jacquard skirts with wrap tops, and simple silk dresses
with antique Japanese fabrics sewn in asymmetrical swaths.
</P>
<P>
   The normally subdued Ms. Pressman of Barneys becomes almost
animated when discussing Isogawa. ``He is amazing,'' she said. ``He
didn't remind me of anyone at all. It is Asian inspired, but at the
same time very modern and directional.'' The store has an exclusive
arrangement with him for New York, Beverly Hills and Chicago, where
he will be featured alongside labels like Comme des Garcons.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pressman, who has been at the forefront of finding young,
less expensive designers and nurturing them, also picked up several
lines for the store's lower-priced Co-op floor. Among her finds
were Wayne Cooper, who specializes in fun, sexy separates like
cowl-neck tank tops in stretch fabrics and silk capri pants;
stretch gauze pieces from a company called Pigs in Space, and
stretch nylon tops and skirts from Metalicus, whose pieces will
sell for about $50. Most of the young designers Ms. Pressman picked
up barely hit the $300 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Getting international exposure makes important business sense
for the Australians. For years, they were protected by heavy
tariffs. But in recent years those tariffs have come down, and the
local talent is now fighting for space with the Calvins and Guccis
of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Further, while the weak Australian dollar (roughly 63 cents to
the U.S. dollar) does not help sales at home, it does mean that
U.S. retailers can get more bang for their buck. And as the Asian
financial crisis drags on, the country's closest neighbors are not
its best customers.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Australian fashion is simply the next esthetic
product to make its way onto the map, along with the country's
films and wines. ``Australia used to be a place for backpackers in
their 20s or retired people on holiday,'' Ms. Hume said. ``But now
when you read Wallpaper and count how many mentions there are of
fashion or furniture designers, suddenly it has become groovy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
