<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-FOSTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES HEAR WHETHER ATTORNEY-CLIENT PRIVILEGE DIES WITH CLIENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An attorney told a skeptical Supreme Court on
Monday that notes of a conversation he had with former White House
counsel Vincent Foster Jr. must remain confidential despite
Foster's death and independent counsel Kenneth Starr's efforts to
gain access to them.
</P>
<P>
   However, the justices were also critical of Starr's contention
that the confidentiality of attorney-client discussions dies with
the client when the conversations pertain to a criminal probe.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, as part of his wide-ranging investigation of President
Clinton, is examining whether presidential aides, and perhaps first
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, lied under oath about firings at the
White House travel office in May 1993. As part of his
investigation, Starr subpoenaed three pages of notes Foster
attorney James Hamilton took during his two-hour conversation with
Foster July 11, 1993. Foster, deputy White House counsel and former
law partner of Hillary Clinton's in Little Rock, Ark., shot himself
to death nine days later.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton refused to surrender the notes, saying the
attorney-client privilege of confidentiality survives the client's
death. A U.S. district court agreed with Hamilton, but the U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Washington ruled the importance of the
notes to Starr's criminal investigation trumped the assertion of
confidentiality. Hamilton then appealed to the high court.
</P>
<P>
   During the hourlong Supreme Court argument, the justices fired
questions at Hamilton that indicated their belief the
attorney-client privilege might not be absolute after death. The
high court also grilled Starr aide Brett Kavanaugh, revealing the
court's potential disagreement with Starr's contention that the
privilege died with Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton argued the clients' right to have their attorneys keep
conversations private is ``transcendent,'' surviving even the
clients' death. Permitting prosecutors to compel an attorney to
violate this confidentiality would have a ``significant chilling
effect on candor'' between lawyers and clients who never want
illicit details made public, Hamilton said. ``People do care about
their reputations ... after death,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia, noting ``conspiracy theorists'' continue
to believe Foster was murdered, asked whether an attorney could be
compelled to disclose a client's statements that would prove the
innocence of a person on trial for murder. ``Courts like to get to
the truth,'' Scalia said.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton responded that ``the court might find an exception'' to
the privilege if it meant preventing a gross injustice. But Starr,
in seeking the lawyer's notes, is not trying to exonerate anybody
but ``to see if prosecution is a possibility,'' Hamilton argued.
</P>
<P>
   If the court rules against him, Hamilton said, lawyers will have
to give their clients a warning: ``Don't tell me what's really bad
because if you do I may have to disclose it to a prosecutor.''
</P>
<P>
   Countering Hamilton, Kavanaugh told an apparently unsympathetic
Supreme Court that ``pernicious consequences'' would result if
attorneys could refuse to divulge their clients' statements.
Innocent people will be wrongly convicted, and guilty people will
be erroneously acquitted, Kavanaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   Kavanaugh conceded that Foster, if he were alive, could be
questioned on the topics he may have discussed with Hamilton. But
now the only way to find out what Foster said is to gain access to
the lawyer's notes, Kavanaugh said, noting ``the witness in
question is no longer available.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Kennedy said lawyers themselves could be placed in
``grave danger'' if they are compelled to disclose conversations in
which their clients admitted to being in a crime syndicate.
Surviving members of the organization may try to kill the lawyer to
prevent their names and activities from being made public, the
justice added.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy also said the legal profession ``may be poorer'' if
clients no longer believed their private conversations would remain
secret. Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist added, ``The client must
be free to tell the lawyer the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The travel office controversy flared when Republican critics of
the president alleged that the first lady fired seven workers and
replaced them with family friends. The controversy grew with the
discovery of a memo from White House administration director David
Watkins to then-Chief of Staff Thomas McLarty that the travel staff
had been fired under ``pressure for action from the First Lady.''
</P>
<P>
   The justices, who had originally planned to hear arguments this
October at the earliest, took the unusual step of accepting in
April Starr's request that they hear the case on an accelerated
schedule to prevent delays in his ongoing investigation. The high
court is expected to render its decision in Hamilton vs. United
States this summer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
