<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
June 9. If you have any questions, please call Joe Klopus on the
Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4751.
</P>
<P>
   YORKTOWN-MEMORIES (Overland Park, Kan.) _ A survivor of the USS
Yorktown's sinking recounts his memories of that day. By TOM
PERRIN. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1855EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9684 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YORKTOWN-MEMORIES-KAN     06-08 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YORKTOWN-MEMORIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USS YORKTOWN PHOTOGRAPHS BRING BACK WARTIME MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM PERRIN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ The last time Jerry Lemberger of Overland
Park laid eyes on the USS Yorktown, he was fighting to stay alive
without a life jacket in the cold, oil-slickened Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   It was June 4, 1942, and torpedoes from Japanese airplanes had
badly damaged the aircraft carrier. The crew had been ordered to
abandon ship in the midst of the World War II Battle of Midway.
Three days later, after another hit by the Japanese, the Yorktown
finally sank to the ocean floor.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors didn't see the ship again until Thursday, when
photographs of the Yorktown were shown by undersea explorer Robert
Ballard at a Washington news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Memories began flowing the next day for Lemberger, who learned
about it in The Kansas City Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little heartbreaking. You think about the old guys
and the ones you knew who were killed,'' said Lemberger, 77, who
worked on the carrier as an electrician. ``It's nice that somebody
is remembering the war in the Pacific. We were always overshadowed,
in my opinion, by the war in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   All but 50 of the Yorktown's 2,450 crewmen were saved; no bodies
were left on the ship.
</P>
<P>
   The Yorktown is the deepest shipwreck ever discovered, lying
more than three miles below the ocean surface between Hawaii and
Japan. It is a mile deeper than the Titanic's resting place in the
North Atlantic, also photographed in a Ballard expedition.
</P>
<P>
   The ship will be left where it is, protected as a historic site.
The photographs are scheduled to be shown in a television
documentary in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Lemberger, who grew up in Milwaukee and raised a family in
California, first moved to Overland Park in 1974, when he worked in
sales for Excellon Manufacturing, a company that made equipment for
drilling and routing printed circuit boards.
</P>
<P>
   He was transferred to Georgia in 1981, then back to California
in 1982 before returning to the Kansas City area for good in 1987.
He retired in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Lemberger is in good health and lives in an apartment with his
wife, Mary, a Bucyrus, Kan., native. They enjoy traveling and
Lemberger is a twice-weekly golfer.
</P>
<P>
   When the ship was hit, Lemberger was on the fifth deck down in
the fire control switchboard room. A torpedo hit one compartment
behind, and all electrical power was lost. As a result, those
working in Lemberger's compartment didn't know orders had been
given to abandon ship.
</P>
<P>
   Lemberger and the others had been given up for dead by the time
they re-established communication 15 minutes after the abandon-ship
orders. When they got on deck before getting off the ship, he said,
only about 10 men remained on board, including the ship's captain
and other top officers.
</P>
<P>
   All of the ship's life jackets were taken by the time Lemberger
jumped into the ocean. Lifeboats were over capacity, so his only
option was to tie himself to a lifeboat's tow rope and try to stay
afloat.
</P>
<P>
   The ocean was coated with the ship's leaking oil, which made it
impossible for Lemberger to recognize anyone. The ocean was chilly,
and swallowing the oily saltwater made him ill. Overhead, an air
battle raged.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you're doing is looking up there and seeing our planes
engaging the Japanese,'' he said. ``You're hoping no Japanese drops
a bomb or strafes you. You never know what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   About two hours later, near dusk, Lemberger was rescued by a
destroyer. He was so weak when he boarded the ship that he needed
help walking.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me if I was worried about sharks or anything, but I
didn't,'' Lemberger said. ``You didn't think about anything, just
keeping your head above water.''
</P>
<P>
   The first night, still coated in oil, he slept near a smokestack
on the destroyer to keep warm. He said eight of his friends from
the Yorktown were killed during the battle.
</P>
<P>
   Lemberger and his wife of 55 years, Mary, courted through the
mail for about three years, beginning in 1941. One of his shipmates
from Bucyrus who knew Mary helped their relationship begin.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Mary in November 1942, Lemberger asked if she
would wear a ring from him, but didn't make it clear he had a
wedding in mind. She received an engagement ring in January that
Lemberger had financed with his winnings from card games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I'd be eliminated (killed) the next trip out, so I'd
better get married,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They were pen pals for three years before their first
face-to-face meeting on May 13, 1943, at Kansas City's Union
Station. A week later, Mary graduated from high school. On May 24
they were married in the home of a minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said it would never last,'' Mary said, laughing at the
irony.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Yorktown, Lemberger was stationed on the USS West
Virginia, a battleship, for the majority of his time in the Navy
leading up to his 1946 discharge.
</P>
<P>
   Later in life, Lemberger had several opportunities to do
business with Japanese companies. He still had bitterness toward
the Japanese before his first trip to Japan in 1969, but his
feelings quickly softened.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find out later _ and this is why all wars are crazy _ that
everybody is just like you and I,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
