<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9685 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBA-NOTEBOOK-COX0609     06-08 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-NOTEBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0609 &HT;    NBA notebook: Rodman thinks NBA's 'nothing without Bulls'
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chicago _ The momentum is on the side of the Bulls. Their Game 3
performance was unprecedented, and many wonder if the Utah Jazz can
recover from a 42-point whipping. By the looks of things, Friday
night could mark the celebration of the city's sixth NBA
championship in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   That thinking floated all around Chicago, if not the nation, on
Monday. It floated everywhere but in the world where Dennis Rodman
lives. In keeping with his different views of most situations,
Rodman talked briefly about the prospects of being the first home
team in league history to win the middle three games of the 2-3-2
format.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it'll definitely be a Game 6 (in Utah),'' Rodman said.
``It's what the NBA and NBC wants. Watch.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to say that the league and network, for financial
reasons, wanted an extended series. And they wanted the Bulls to
linger as long as possible ``because the NBA is nothing without the
Chicago Bulls,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ability to forget
</P>
<P>
   For those who think the Jazz will not be able to rebound from
the 96-54 humiliation the Bulls inflicted on Sunday, consider that
Utah was pounded by 21 points in Game 3 of the Western Conference
semifinals by the San Antonio Spurs. In Game 4, the Jazz played as
strong a game as it had in the postseason and won.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true, we did,'' guard Jeff Hornacek said. ``We're a
veteran team, a team that's not going to just quit. So, we'll show
up Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd better,'' Karl Malone said. ``If that kind of
butt-kicking doesn't make you want to come out and compete, you
shouldn't even be out there. Will we be ready? We'd better be.''
</P>
<P>
   Short on big men
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls have gotten by so far with a bench that is short on
productivity up front. Last year, Chicago played with Brian
Williams and Jason Caffey, two tough big men.
</P>
<P>
   Williams signed for big bucks with the Detroit Pistons, and
Caffey was inexplicably traded in February to the Warriors for
David Vaughn, who has been cut. The Bulls signed Dickey Simpkins,
who had been released by Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   Simpkins and backup center Bill Wennington seldom are used, so
Chicago is thin up front. All of that is incredible to Caffey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea (why I was traded),'' Caffey said. ``It doesn't
make sense to me still. And I don't think it ever will.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman misses practice
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Bulls forward Dennis Rodman was a no-show at today's
practice, drawing an undisclosed fine from the team, but not the
ire of his coach.
</P>
<P>
   The hair-dyed Rodman, who's known for his off-court antics,
didn't give the team a reason for his absence, Bulls coach Phil
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a difficult year for Dennis,'' Jackson said.
``With him, it's like squeezing a circle in a square.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
