<HEADER>
A9686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NHL-STANLEYCUP-COX     06-08 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NHL-STANLEYCUP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Underdog Capitals to doubters: Don't count us out
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One recent morning, Washington Capitals coach Ron
Wilson told his players they were on the verge of an achievement as
momentous as when Apollo 11 landed on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   If the Capitals reaching the Stanley Cup finals didn't go down
as a red-letter date in history on the same scale as Neil Armstrong
walking on the moon, it's at least fair to say that some Washington
hockey fans consider the feat to be as improbable. Long one of the
NHL's most pathetic franchises, the Capitals, who failed to make
the playoffs their first eight seasons, open play tonight in
Detroit as a heavy underdog to the defending champion Red Wings in
the best-of-seven finals. ``Boston, Ottawa and Buffalo were
supposed to beat us in five or six games,'' Wilson said, referring
to the Captials' playoff victims. ``I guess Detroit is favored to
beat us in four or five. I don't think many people are expecting us
to win the Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington failed to make the playoffs last year, finished third
in its division this year and had advanced as far as the conference
finals only once. The biggest reason it has made it this far is the
goaltending of Olag Kolzig. About Wilson's Apollo comparison, the
Caps' leader said, ``We hope to land in Washington. Four more
(wins) and mission accompished.'' But he is the furthest thing from
Neil Armstrong _ a native of Johannesburg, South Africa, who was
born to German parents and raised in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Kolzig was a backup last season, but this year he won a starting
job. He has been the hottest goalie in the playoffs, winning 12 of
Washington's 17 playoff games, with four shutouts, a 1.69
goals-against average and a saves percentage of .946. He even
outplayed Buffalo's Dominik Hasek in the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He covers a lot of the net and he's consistent,'' Detroit
coach Scotty Bowman said. ``And he's got to have a lot of
confidence after beating a guy like Hasek.''
</P>
<P>
   None of which has cast Washington into the role of favorites.
Detroit is solid, although not as spectacular, in goal with Chris
Osgood, but is far deeper offensively and has more playoff
experience. The Red Wings have been boosted in the postseason by
Sergei Federov, whose contract holdout wiped out the first 59 games
of the season and who didn't break a sweat in a game until the
Winter Olympics with team Russia. Federov has nine goals and 17
points in 18 playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit, which eliminated regular-season points champion Dallas
in the Western Conference finals, also rebounded this year from the
emotional loss of defenseman Vladimir Konstantinov, who suffered
career-ending injuries in an auto wreck after last year's Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a lot of people who counted us out early
because of the circumstances of losing a couple of players,''
defenseman Bob Rouse said. ``That just made the other guys that
much more hungry to prove them wrong. Obviously, we're a better
team with (Konstantinov). But I think it gave our guys the
incentive to pick up their play and contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   STANLEY CUP FINALS: DETROIT VS. WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   Tonight: 8 p.m., at Detroit on FOX.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday: 8 p.m., at Detroit on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday: 8 p.m. at Washington on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   June 16: 8 p.m., at Washinton on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   June 18: 8 p.m., at Detroit on FOX.
</P>
<P>
   June 20: 8 p.m., at Washinton on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   June 23: 8 p.m., at Detroit onFOX.
</P>
<P>
   If necessary
</P>
