<HEADER>
A9701 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GILLIAN-ANDERSON-IN-T     06-08 1486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILLIAN-ANDERSON-IN-THE-X-FILES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILLIAN ANDERSON, CONSPIRACY THEORISTS' PIN-UP GIRL 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Gillian Anderson with David Duchovny in a
scene from ``The X-Files.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Gillian Anderson is a goddess, television's finest actress, the
sexiest lady on the planet and bright as hell, too.
 &HT;    Or at least so believe most of the 4,000 awestruck fans
attending Expo, a gathering of ``X-Files'' aficionados in New York.
Anderson spends an hour answering questions and signing autographs
_ not to mention responding to bouquets, gifts and compliments _
with a steady stream of ``Thank you'' and ``That's so sweet.''
 &HT;    Two weeks later, speaking by telephone from the California set
of her new movie, ``Dancing About Architecture,'' the actress still
seems bemused by her Expo adulation.
 &HT;    ``You've got to be able to take in the information and put it
where it belongs in your brain,'' she says. ``Depending on who you
are and what kind of mood you're in on a certain day, you can
either believe it all or know it's not true. Either way, you say
`Thank you' and move on.''
 &HT;    Anderson pauses, then laughs, her smooth professionalism
slipping just a bit.
 &HT;    ``Come on, it's wonderful,'' she admits. ``It's amazing to hear
such compliments, and I think everyone in the world should have an
Expo every once in a while.
 &HT;    ``Wouldn't you love to have people spend an hour telling you how
wonderful you are _ just saying good things about you?'' she says.
``It's like a roast with no insults.''
 &HT;    It's been a long, strange journey to stardom for Anderson, a
29-year-old with pouty lips, soulful blue eyes and fiery red hair.
She was born in Chicago and reared in London, Puerto Rico and Grand
Rapids, Mich. She survived a punk phase _ replete with a Mohawk
legendary among X-philes _ and studied theater at DePaul
University's Goodman Theater School in Chicago.
 &HT;    Only five years ago, she was a struggling nobody with a couple
of one-shot television roles to her credit. Then came ``The
X-Files,'' a bizarro blend of sci-fi, horror, humor and the
paranormal.
 &HT;    ``I certainly didn't think `X-Files' would be a seemingly
lifelong job,'' she says, still seeming surprised. ``I didn't
realize that signing my contract would lead to all of this.
 &HT;    ``It's been a little bigger, let's say, than I ever expected.''
 &HT;    The series casts Anderson as FBI Special Agent Dana Scully,
partner of Fox Mulder (David Duchovny) in an ongoing investigation
into everything from murders and UFO sightings to monsters and
otherworldly black ooze. Their beat is the weird and the
inexplicable, with Scully as the severe, skeptical scientist and
Mulder as the acerbic would-be believer, haunted by the long-ago
abduction of his sister, possibly by aliens.
 &HT;    The series is a conspiracy theorist's dream, with webs of
governmental, quasigovernmental and nongovernmental organizations
all keeping secrets from each other and the public, earning
Anderson stardom among what is probably television's strangest
audience.
 &HT;    Just how large that audience is will be determined this summer,
as Scully and Mulder hit the big screen with ``The X-Files,'' a $60
million feature opening nationwide on June 19, written by series
creator Chris Carter and directed by Rob Bowman, who's helmed
numerous episodes. If it succeeds, look for more ``X-Files'' movies
to follow.
 &HT;    Anderson swears that the film will make sense to newcomers while
still rewarding longtime fans.
 &HT;    ``That was a huge concern,'' Anderson says. ``That was Chris
Carter's primary interest in writing the script and Rob Bowman's
interpretation of it.
 &HT;    ``We had to strike that balance, especially on this first
film,'' she says. ``If this works, the balance element might not be
so important later on, or as important.
 &HT;    ``I think we pulled it off. At least I hope we did.''
 &HT;    Anderson is typically cagy about what happens in the movie.
 &HT;    ``It's a lot of action, special effects and big, exciting
shots,'' she says cryptically. ``There's a lot of running. The
relationship between Mulder and Scully moves into new territory in
many different ways. It's very, very exciting.''
 &HT;    Eventually, Anderson offers a few more tidbits: She shares
scenes with guest star Blythe Danner, but not with Martin Landau
nor Armin Mueller-Stahl. She spends one sequence stuck in a vat of
goo. And the film answers a few old questions, and poses fresh ones
designed to set up the show's sixth season.
 &HT;    ``One thing I can tell you is that this is very much a movie,''
she says. ``For television, what we do is very ambitious. Doing
`X-Files' as a movie is just a natural progression, the next step.
Again, I think we've pulled it off.''
 &HT;    The film can only heighten public interest in Anderson, who has
already been the subject of magazine covers, action figures, prying
tabloid stories, CD-ROM games and those fan conventions. During her
``X-Files'' stint the actress has married, had a child _ Piper, now
2 _ divorced, won an Emmy and shot several soon-to-be-released
films.
 &HT;    ``I don't think anybody can be as prepared as they need to be to
deal with all of this,'' Anderson says. ``Sometimes I feel more
ready than other times. Sometimes I feel it's too much, that I've
got too much on my plate. Then I move past that point and start to
feel more stable again.
 &HT;    ``But I don't think anybody can prepare themselves for any kind
of public success,'' she adds. ``You can read about it and see what
happens to other people, but when it happens to you it's nothing
like you imagined.''
 &HT;    Intent on forging a post-``X-Files'' future, Anderson crams her
down time with film roles. She recently shot a cameo in an
independent drama entitled ``Chicago Cab,'' which currently has no
distributor, and played a supporting role in the family drama ``The
Mighty.''
 &HT;    ``It's a beautiful story about two outcast kids (Kieran Culkin
and Elden Henson) and their friendship,'' Anderson says of the
film, which co-stars Sharon Stone, Gena Rowlands and Meat Loaf.
``The film is getting wonderful advance reviews, and it deserves
them.''
 &HT;    The currently filming ``Dancing About Architecture'' features
Anderson, Rowlands, Sean Connery, Jon Stewart, Dennis Quaid and
Anthony Edwards, among others.
 &HT;    ``It's about relationships and having the courage to change,''
Anderson says. ``It's little vignettes that flip back and forth
between different pairs of people _ mothers and sons, lovers,
partners of sorts.
 &HT;    ``When I get to spend a couple of weeks doing projects like
`Dancing' or `The Mighty,' that I care about so much,'' the actress
says, ``it feels like I'm showing what I can do, feels like I'm
keeping my feet in the water until I have more time to do bigger
roles, different roles and different kinds of films.''
 &HT;    After she wraps ``Dancing'' and completes her ``X-Files''
publicity chores, it'll be back to the ``X-Files'' set in Los
Angeles, recently relocated from British Columbia. She's reportedly
committed to the show for two more years.
 &HT;    But it isn't just the show. At times, Anderson says, it seems as
if her entire life revolves around ``The X-Files.''
 &HT;    ``I shot the movie almost a year ago, right after we did a whole
season of the series and just before we did another season,'' she
says. ``We did an `X-Files' CD-ROM somewhere in there, and now I've
got to promote the movie.
 &HT;    ```Dancing About Architecture' is something completely
different. That's a good thing for me,'' she says. ``But there's
not a day when `The X-Files' doesn't come up. I don't think there
will ever be a day when it doesn't.''
 &HT;    Is she OK with that?
 &HT;    There's a long pause. Clearly, it's something the actress has
thought a lot about.
 &HT;    ``I don't know,'' Anderson says finally. ``I don't know.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
