<HEADER>
A9702 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JENNIFER-LOVE-HEWITT-     06-08 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENNIFER-LOVE-HEWITT-IN-CANT-HARDLY-WAIT-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JENNIFER LOVE HEWITT, PARTY OF ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Jennifer Love Hewitt in a scene from
``Can't Hardly Wait.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Even niceness has its problems.
 &HT;    Just ask Jennifer Love Hewitt, who ran into one while filming a
scene for ``Can't Hardly Wait,'' her new film, opening June 12. The
scene called for her to scream at another actor.
 &HT;    ``An extra didn't realize I was acting and came up and said, `I
thought you were that nice girl from ``Party of Five.'' I can't
believe you would treat your fellow actors the way you did,''' she
recalls. ``My jaw just dropped. I wanted to say, `I'm so sorry. I'm
not mean in real life!'''
 &HT;    That's life when you're a 19-year-old who's already a star,
courtesy of her popular television series and last year's feature
film, ``I Know What You Did Last Summer.'' She was a teen idol
before she was out of high school _ which involved problems of its
own.
 &HT;    ``I would be in the middle of kissing Scott Wolf on `Party of
Five' _ and suddenly we would have to break apart because I would
be required to go home,'' she says. ``My 10-and-a-half hours of
work were over.''
 &HT;    Hewitt may be hitting the big time, but she's kept a level
enough head to joke about her own success in the $100
million-grossing ``I Know What You Did,'' a routine teen-scream
flick which relied heavily on the anatomical appeal of Hewitt and
co-star Sarah Michelle Gellar.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes I call that movie, `I Know What My Breasts Did Last
Summer,''' she says jokingly. ``I've come to realize that boobs can
be a great accessory.''
 &HT;    Hewitt's lungs also proved an asset on that film. Asked to
demonstrate her trademark ``I Know What You Did'' bloodcurdling
scream _ after all, she starts filming the sequel, ``I Still
Know,'' next week _ she looks around the elegant suite at Los
Angeles' Four Seasons Hotel dubiously.
 &HT;    ``You really want me to do it?'' she asks. ``OK, here it is.''
She winds up, taking a deep gulp of air.
 &HT;    ``Aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaahhhhh!'' she yells, and the windows shake.
Two publicists come running, expecting the worst, only to find
their young charge taking a bow. ``Thank you, thank you very
much,'' she says.
 &HT;    Hewitt is more than heaving breasts and a resonant scream,
however. Besides her award-winning stint on ``Party of Five,'' she
recently sold her first screenplay, ``Cupid's Love,'' to New Line
Pictures for a reported $500,000.
 &HT;    ``I had a dream and woke up in the middle of the night, and I
was like, `Wow, I have a cute idea for a story,''' she recalls.
 &HT;    So she wrote an outline of the story _ about a wedding planner
who falls in love with a young hunk while planning his wedding _
and the rest is future film history.
 &HT;    First, however, Hewitt is spending the summer filming ``I Still
Know What You Did Last Summer,'' which co-stars that other teen
sensation, Brandy.
 &HT;    And, of course, there's ``Can't Hardly Wait,'' in which Hewitt
plays Amanda, a prom queen who must deal with the end of her
high-school era at a rocking graduation party.
 &HT;    ``The character for me was something I've never done before,''
Hewitt says. ``I always tend to play the very natural
girl-next-door who never gets the guy. In this film, I'm the
end-all, be-all dream girl and the center of this guy's
affection.''
 &HT;    The subject matter might seem familiar, Hewitt says, but it
wasn't.
 &HT;    ``I've never actually been to a real high-school party,'' she
admits. ``I was never interested. I had other things to do.''
 &HT;    Nevertheless, Hewitt has no regrets about the sacrifices she's
made for her career.
 &HT;    ``No, because if I had gone to real high school, what guarantee
do I have that I would have had the perfect high-school
existence?'' she says. ``Now with these movies, I can honestly say,
`I was the prom queen. I was the cheerleader. I did date Dexter,
the big football player.' And I'm not really lying.''
 &HT;    She's not the only reigning teen sensation, of course. Already
there have been rumors of competitiveness with her ``Party''
co-star Neve Campbell, who starred in that other teen hit,
``Scream'' (1996).
 &HT;    ``The only thing that Neve and I ever talk about as far as
career stuff goes is that she's the horror queen and I'm the horror
princess,'' Hewitt jokes. ``There is no competition.''
 &HT;    Hewitt saves her battles for the things that matter to her. For
example, she's sworn off on-screen nudity.
 &HT;    ``It's not for me,'' she says. ``Let's say I'm doing a horror
film. There is nothing about a girl running and having to show a
full boob shot that has anything to do with being murdered by a
psycho.
 &HT;    ``Plus I very rarely think that sex scenes or nude scenes in
movies are really needed to get the point across,'' she says.
``Very rarely. Two people making love does not mean they're in
love. You can show it in other ways.''
 &HT;    Hewitt was born in Killeen, Texas, where her parents divorced
when she was a baby. She made her professional debut at age 10,
singing at a March of Dimes fund-raiser. From that point on, she
was a girl possessed, with her mother, a speech pathologist, right
behind her.
 &HT;    ``My mom basically put her life on hold and pushed stop in the
middle of her career and her life and said, `OK, sure.''' she
recalls. ``And we moved to L.A., away from all of her friends, so
that I could live my dream.''
 &HT;    That dream began with a 1989 stint on the Disney variety show
``Kids Incorporated.'' A Barbie workout video followed, and then in
1995 she was cast on ``Party of Five'' as the object of Wolf's
affection.
 &HT;    ``I love the show,'' she says. ``It's probably the best job I've
ever had. I'm there for at least two more years, with a third one
being optional. I would definitely go the third year. I don't want
`PO5' to end.''
 &HT;    ``I Still Know'' is being shot in Mexico, to Hewitt's dismay.
 &HT;    ``We're way out from civilization,'' she grouses. ``There's
absolutely nothing to do. They've even given us snake kits. So
basically that sucks _ we're really roughing it.''
 &HT;    Making horror films has its drawbacks, Hewitt admits.
 &HT;    ``It's weird,'' she says. ``The entire time you're doing the
running-and-screaming scenes, you start to think, `What if that
hook actually made contact with my flesh? What would that feel
like? Run faster!' You start to book.
 &HT;    ``In fact, in the original movie, I was running a little too
fast. They said, `Love, you're not really running from somebody.
Slow down.'''
 &HT;    However, Hewitt's days as a teen scream are numbered. Next
February, she will hit the two-decade mark.
 &HT;    ``It will be kind of cool when nobody will be able to call me a
teen-ager anymore,'' she says. ``That will be kind of neat. But my
life probably won't be any different.''
 &HT;    That life has its perks, of course. Hewitt is still enough of a
teen-ager to have movie-star crushes of her own, but, unlike most
teens, she actually gets to meet her idols _ or almost.
 &HT;    Last year, her all-time favorite, Johnny Depp, actually visited
her on the ``Party'' set. Caught in sweatclothes and sans makeup,
Hewitt did what any teen-ager would do: She locked herself in her
trailer and died of embarrassment.
 &HT;    ``I was mortified,'' she recalls.
 &HT;    But the story has a happy ending: Depp was amused, and later
sent flowers when Hewitt graduated from high school.
 &HT;    ``That was the coolest,'' she says, beaming.
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
