<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REGIS-AND-KATHIE-LEE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGIS AND KATHIE LEE, MAKING MORNINGS MERRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a 300-word sidebar and a color slide of Regis Philbin and
Kathie Lee Gifford in a scene from ``Live With Regis and Kathie
Lee.'' 
 By CHRISTOPHER LOUDON  
 c.1998 Canadian TV Guide  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few people catch more flak for less cause than Regis Philbin and
Kathie Lee Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   Critics are quick to dismiss their daily chatfest as empty
gushing and self-promotional grandstanding. Cynics gripe about the
constant on-air references to her kids. Tabloid headlines scream
about his health, her marriage and more.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite the naysayers, Philbin and Gifford ride a
decade-old wave of popularity that shows no sign of cresting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I waited three months for these tickets and drove 15 hours to
get here,'' gushed one audience member outside their Manhattan
studio on a recent morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oprah's great and I like Rosie O'Donnell, but nobody can
compare to these two,'' another chimed in.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the best, I mean, they're just the best,'' enthused a
third.
</P>
<P>
   And for each of the 200 or so audience members who whoop and
holler for their midmorning heroes on a given day, there are 50,000
more like them watching at home.
</P>
<P>
   Why, after 10 years, are they still so mad about Philbin and
Gifford? Here are 10 reasons:
</P>
<P>
   1. The best chemistry on daytime television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Gawd, the dreaded `C word,''' Philbin says. ``Every
interview we do, that word comes up, and I don't even know what it
means.''
</P>
<P>
   Gifford nods in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must be a certain something that we have together,'' she
says, ``but I've never really been able to describe it. Can you?''
</P>
<P>
   Sure. It's their shared ability to play his jaded gruffness
against her wide-eyed enthusiasm, but it's also their knack for a
common touch that speaks directly to the heartland.
</P>
<P>
   2. They take the high road.
</P>
<P>
   Long before it became fashionable _ and ratings-favorable _ for
hosts such as Oprah, Rosie and even Geraldo to take a kinder,
gentler approach, Philbin and Gifford were there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why in the world should we want to say something unkind about
someone else?'' Gifford says. ``I can't imagine why anyone in our
position would ever feel the need to make a guest feel
uncomfortable or unwelcome.''
</P>
<P>
   3. They make it look easy.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't ``The MacNeil-Lehrer Report.'' Still, you have to
have a fair amount on the ball to fill upward of 250 hours a year
with conversation lively enough to hold the attention of 10 million
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Philbin and Gifford know who their viewers are and what they
expect from the show, and they make sure they get it.
</P>
<P>
   4. They keep it fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spontaneity is the key to the show's success,'' Philbin says.
``People think we spend all kinds of time together, but we're both
so busy with other things that it's only rarely that we see each
other outside the studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why the first 20 minutes of the show are so fresh,'' he
says. ``If we spent every evening socializing together, then we
would've discussed everything we had to discuss the night before.''
</P>
<P>
   5. They appreciate their fans.
</P>
<P>
   Both Philbin and Gifford show tremendous respect to their studio
audience. While other hosts spend commercial breaks chatting with
celebrity guests or hurrying backstage, Philbin and Gifford wander
out into the audience to answer questions, sign autographs and pose
for photos.
</P>
<P>
   They respect the viewers, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of our viewers takes an hour out of their day to
spend it with us,'' Gifford says. ``It's our job to honor that
commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   6. They've got guts.
</P>
<P>
   Many stars, faced with the negative press Gifford has received,
would duck for cover. Instead, she's had the strength to face the
criticism head-on.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Philbin bounced back from a serious heart scare
and, instead of waxing sanctimonious about his survival, seized the
opportunity to gently educate viewers about the importance of diet
and exercise. As a result, he's emerged as an aging America's
poster boy for healthy living.
</P>
<P>
   7. Nothing fazes them.
</P>
<P>
   The two hosts will go to just about any lengths to please their
audience. They've wrestled wild animals, weathered tropical storms,
been spritzed with cold coffee on ``Seinfeld'' and dressed up in
everything from grass skirts to giant sumo-wrestler fat suits.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare it isn't, but it's artful foolishness all the same.
</P>
<P>
   8. They've got heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kathie Lee is without question one of the most generous
individuals I have ever met,'' Philbin says. ``People don't really
appreciate how deep her commitment is. I swear this woman will go
out of her way to help anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Gifford, on the other hand, notes that the superficially gruff
Philbin has a remarkably tender side.
</P>
<P>
   ``With everything I've gone through over the past couple of
years, he's never wavered in his support,'' she says. ``And it's
not just me. Though he doesn't like to admit it, he cares so much
about all of the people around him. You couldn't ask for a better
or more understanding friend.''
</P>
<P>
   9. They make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to scoff at events such as the annual ``Queen For a
Day''-style Mother's Day show, but just try to stay dry-eyed when
they provide a cancer-stricken, single mother with a brand-new home
or give an ailing bridegroom and his wife-to-be the wedding of
their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's sentimental. But their unflagging altruism has helped
dozens of deserving individuals and causes, ranging from pediatric
AIDS to Special Olympics and multiple sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   10. They won't be around forever.
</P>
<P>
   They've had a tremendous decade-long run and are still going
strong.
</P>
<P>
   But ask them if ``Live with Regis and Kathie Lee'' is likely to
celebrate its 20th anniversary and, without a moment's hesitation,
these two very different people respond in unison:
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not!''
 &UR; SIDEBAR: A DECADE OF MEMORIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Of the more than 5,000 guests you've had on the show, who was
your favorite?
</P>
<P>
   PHILBIN: We've had so many memorable guests, but two of the
consistently most interesting have been Diane Sawyer and Barbara
Walters.
</P>
<P>
   GIFFORD: I'd have to say Audrey Hepburn. She truly was the
personification of grace and elegance.
</P>
<P>
   When she came on the show, she already knew that she was
suffering from colon cancer, but she made an extra effort to be
here so that she could spread the word about the wonderful work she
was doing with UNICEF on behalf of children all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the single biggest surprise?
</P>
<P>
   GIFFORD: For Regis, I think it had to be the time we caught him
completely off guard with a special visit from Perry Como.
</P>
<P>
   PHILBIN: We've had lots of crazy moments, but the one that
surprised me most was the kiss that Kathie Lee greeted Tom Selleck
with. She was locked onto him so tight, I thought she'd never let
go!
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was your biggest gaffe?
</P>
<P>
   PHILBIN: The biggest gaffe? You mean, like, mistake? That's easy
_ I haven't made it yet.
</P>
<P>
   GIFFORD: I think the biggest mistake I've made was letting my
emotions get the best of me the day that I had to defend myself
against the accusations (regarding child labor) about my clothing
line. I was so hurt and angry, but I probably shouldn't have gotten
so emotional.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has been the one most memorable moment?
</P>
<P>
   PHILBIN: Probably the time that we had the sumo wrestlers on the
show. That was really wild, and I think it was the longest laugh
we've ever gotten from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   GIFFORD: I think it would have to be the Halloween shows. There
was the time we dressed as Sonny and Cher.
</P>
<P>
   Even better was the year that we did the entire show with me
dressed as Regis and him dressed as me _ it would be pretty hard to
top that.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Christopher Loudon is the editor of Canadian TV Guide, based
in North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
