<HEADER>
A9709 &Cx1f; tab-z
w l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THE-ART-OF-MOVING-LIF     06-08 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-ART-OF-MOVING-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVING WITH CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 Includes two sidebars totaling 250 words 
 By LEAH INGRAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three of the biggest stresses in a person's life include giving
birth, taking a new job and moving. I know, because last summer,
six weeks after giving birth to my second child, I moved 600 miles
from Michigan to New Jersey for my husband's new job.
</P>
<P>
   We weren't alone. According to the U.S. Census Bureau, nearly
1.8 million Americans moved for job reasons in 1993, the last year
for which statistics are available.
</P>
<P>
   Moving is stressful for everyone, but it's especially hard on
toddlers and preschoolers. One of the best ways to help children
adjust is to get them involved in the move.
</P>
<P>
   Before they began their move from Ann Arbor, Mich., to Madison,
Wisc., last fall, Stacey and Stuart Udell let their 2-year-old
daughter Jillian draw on the boxes that would contain her clothes
and toys.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way,'' Stacey Udell says, ``when we got to the new house,
she'd know which boxes had her stuff in them.''
 &UR; MAKING A LIST, CHECKING IT TWICE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Besides planning for the actual moving day, you should create
``to do'' lists of things you need to handle before you leave. This
includes finding day care, if you need it, and new doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Your realtor, if you're working with one, may be able to help.
Sylvia Buchwald of William Raveis Real Estate in Trumbull, Conn.,
maintains a list of day-care resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just recently a couple moved from Maryland, and they needed
day care for their two little ones,'' says Buchwald, who referred
the couple to a licensed preschool on their new street. ``That's
where she ended up sending her kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Another great way to find a place to send your child is by
calling Child Care Aware at (800) 424-2246. It is a referral
service to local organizations that provide names, phone numbers,
fees and hours of operation of various child-care services in your
new community.
</P>
<P>
   Before we moved from Michigan, I called Child Care Aware and
received the name of a local child-care-referral agency in my new
town. They put me in touch with 10 different schools, one of which
Jane, my 2-year-old, now attends.
</P>
<P>
   Your current pediatrician, primary-care physician and
obstetrician/gynecologist are all great resources for new doctors.
But if they don't know whom to send you to in your new location,
there are other ways to find a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call the chair of pediatrics or obstetrics at the nearest
major medical school, and ask them to recommend three physicians,''
suggests Elise Babcock, author of ``When Life Becomes Precious''
(Bantam, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   Babcock adds that organizations such as the American Academy of
Pediatrics, the American Board of Medical Specialists and the
American Board of Family Practice also provide referrals.
 &UR; THE BIG DAY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whether you've hired movers or are moving yourselves, make sure
any items you'll want immediately upon arrival _ some toys for the
children, perhaps _ go into the truck last.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last things on the truck are the first to come off,'' says
Doreen Hankins, director of sales and marketing at Stevens
Worldwide Van Lines in Saginaw, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Plan to have someone available at the new house to watch your
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inevitably, parents will be distracted, and any time there's
less parental supervision, kids can be exposed to risk,'' says Ken
Giles, a spokesperson for the U.S. Consumer Products Safety
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   It's always best to keep important items with you during the
move, whether it's your child's favorite blanket, his birth
certificate or your own medical records.
</P>
<P>
   Before you start the car or hop on a plane to your new
destination, make sure you've packed plenty of snacks and toys to
keep everyone happy.
</P>
<P>
   A few days before the two-day drive from Michigan to New Jersey
last summer, I took Jane to shop for new toys to take in the car
with us. She chose a variety of items, including books and musical
instruments, which we put away until the big day. That way
everything was fresh and new to her, and she wouldn't become quite
as bored as she might with an older toy.
 &UR; HOME SAFE HOME &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things you'll want to do when you arrive at
your new home is a quick safety check of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Cover electrical outlets, check that banister posts aren't far
enough apart for a kid to get his head stuck in them and install
gates where necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know of one family that had moved from California to
Massachusetts, and had never lived in a house with a basement
before,'' says Terry Moerler, a broker with Re-Max in Thousand
Oaks, Calif. ``Their little boy opened a door and thought he was
walking into a room _ but it was the basement, and he fell down the
stairs.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to be cleaning up the new place, ``keep all
household cleaners in their original containers, and lock them away
from children,'' Giles says.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone is going to be unfamiliar with their new surroundings,
so it's a good idea to install night lights throughout the house.
This will help prevent you from going bump in the night, as well as
keeping your kids from being scared.
</P>
<P>
   In their new house in Madison, the Udells leave a light on for
Jillian ``so she doesn't wake up and be completely disoriented in
the dark,'' Stacey Udell says.
 &UR; MAKING THE NEW HOUSE A HOME &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the best ways to make your new house feel like home to
your children is to unpack their things first. Because my husband
Bill drove the truck with our possessions in them and arrived a day
before we did, he unpacked all of Jane's toys and set them up in
the playroom for her.
</P>
<P>
   When we arrived at our new home, Jane was at first shy and
reserved _ until she walked into the playroom. She looked around,
broke out in a smile and started shouting, ``Look, mommy, my toys,
all of my toys are here!''
</P>
<P>
   I knew right then that we were all going to be very happy in our
new home.
 &UR; SIDEBAR 1: ARE WE THERE YET? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While packing can be a bear, keeping your kids occupied during
the move can be a great big grizzly.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Gesse, a child-life specialist at Children's Hospital of
Michigan in Detroit, offers some suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   + Say it with music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Find sing-along tapes with shorter songs on them, because
toddlers and preschoolers have short attention spans,'' Gesse says.
``If you're traveling with a baby, you might want to find classical
or baroque music, which babies tend to like.''
</P>
<P>
   + Bring along interactive toys.
</P>
<P>
   The new talking Barney might make the perfect back-seat
companion. If your kid would enjoy pretending to drive, check out
the VTech Little Smart Tiny Tot Driver. It has its own steering
wheel and realistic car sounds, such as an engine starting and a
horn beeping.
</P>
<P>
   + Inspire the artist in your child.
</P>
<P>
   Coloring books and crayons are great for toddlers. Preschoolers
with more finely tuned motored skills might enjoy ``drawing'' with
a Magnadoodle or an Etch-a-Sketch.
 &UR; SIDEBAR 2: FINDING FRIENDS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Making friends for yourselves and your kids in a new location
can be challenging. Here are five tips to try:
</P>
<P>
   + Ask your realtor to introduce you to your neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   + Visit the neighborhood playground regularly.
</P>
<P>
   + Invite your neighbors over for a ``getting to know you''
brunch.
</P>
<P>
   + Get involved in your neighborhood association.
</P>
<P>
   + Join a local house of worship.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Leah Ingram is an Ewing, N.J.-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
