<HEADER>
A9710 &Cx1f; tab-z
w l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATURAL-PET-CARE-LIFE     06-08 1564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATURAL-PET-CARE-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PET OWNERSHIP GOES GREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 Includes a 100-word sidebar 
 By TRACEY C. REMBERT  
 c.1998 E: The Environmental Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans share their homes with more than 112 million cats and
dogs, not to mention an assortment of reptiles, birds, horses and
exotic animals.
</P>
<P>
   As pet owners become more health- and environment-conscious,
they're starting to bring that consciousness to the way they
provide for their companion animals. In 1996, U.S. pet owners
supported the natural-pet-food and -supplement industry to the tune
of $65 million, and sales keep climbing.
</P>
<P>
   But what is natural pet care? Holistic veterinarians say it all
begins with a nonprocessed, whole-foods diet.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Animal Protection Institute, commercial pet
foods, from Friskies to Kal-Kan, contain mostly grain wastes and
meat byproducts, which can include everything from euthanized
shelter animals to cancer-ridden livestock, roadkill, downer
animals, moldy grains and rancid restaurant grease.
</P>
<P>
   P.F. McGargle, a federal meat inspector who is also a
veterinarian, notes that feeding these low-in-nutrition packaged
``scraps'' to pets increases their chances of cancer and other
degenerative diseases.
</P>
<P>
   An API investigative report found that in slaughterhouses, after
choice cuts have been removed for human food, ``whatever remains of
the carcass _ bones, blood, pus, intestines, bowels, ligaments,
fat, hooves, horns and beaks'' _ are what find their way into the
pet-food stream.
</P>
<P>
   Why is this unhealthy practice so popular? In a word, profits.
Many pet-food companies are branches of human-food conglomerates
that want to turn waste products into sales. Ralston-Purina, for
example, gets the scraps from Heinz, Nestle and Mars to produce its
pet foods.
</P>
<P>
   So what options do pet owners have?
</P>
<P>
   ``Dogs and cats were designed to handle raw, uncooked foods,''
says holistic veterinarian Dr. Will Winter, who recommends mixing
fresh cuts of meat _ not ground meat _ with whole grains and
vegetables for a balanced diet.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies, such as Minnesota-based Sojourner Farms, sell
pet-food mixes containing nuts, herbs and grains, which can be
added to meat for complete nutrition. Fish can also join the
feeding dish, but should always be cooked to eliminate parasites.
</P>
<P>
   For already-prepared dry and wet foods for cats and dogs, both
Wysong and Lang's Natural have impeccable ingredients lists,
including organic and whole grains, and whole cuts of meat, while
avoiding unhealthy additives such as meat byproducts, meat meals
and grain flours to bulk up their foods.
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to wholesome treats for Fido, Dandy Doggie and
Wow-Bow offer a huge assortment of organic, vegetarian dog
biscuits, gourmet grain pastries and cookies, and fresh-baked
kibble.
 &UR; WHEN NATURE CALLS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bedding and litter are other prime areas where pet caregivers
can look to go greener and healthier.
</P>
<P>
   For litter-box-trained animals, holistic vets recommend avoiding
conventional clay litters, which are laden with silica dust, a
known carcinogen. Many ``scoopable'' clay litters have also been
found to cause intestinal blockages in cats and kittens when
inadvertently consumed while grooming.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies make wheat-based litters which are scoopable,
biodegradable and flushable, including Swheat Scoop and Heartland
Wheat Litter.
</P>
<P>
   Other dust-free, biodegradable alternatives include Feline
Pine's odor-absorbing pellets, made from 100-percent-recycled
pine-lumber waste from mill yards, or ECOfresh and Yesterday's
News, both made from 100-percent-recycled newspaper. CareFRESH,
produced from recycled wood pulp, can be used for exotic pets and
birds.
 &UR; FLEA PATROL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indoors or out, furry companions seem to be magnets for fleas.
But have you ever read the warning labels on conventional flea and
tick products? From shampoos and dips to foggers and collars,
conventional flea controls caution consumers to use gloves and keep
product away from skin and mucous membranes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they're being applied all over your pet, where the toxic
emissions from a flea collar or spray, for instance, are being
constantly inhaled or licked by the wearer. The Cancer Prevention
Coalition has warned against the use of several brand-name flea
collars, including Sergeant's, Hartz, Zodiac and Longlife.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional foggers, bombs, powders and sprays are just as
problematic, and should not be used around pregnant women or
children, as they pose a risk of neurological problems and
leukemia. They may also include the nerve poisons dichlorvos,
propoxur or diazinon, as well as many ``inert'' ingredients such as
methyl bromide, benzene, asbestos and DDT.
</P>
<P>
   For safer removal of fleas, a flea comb works wonders. Sold in
any pet-supply store for $3 to $7, this metal comb collects fleas
between its narrowly spaced tines.
</P>
<P>
   Herbal shampoos, collars, sachets and sprays using citronella,
eucalyptus, pennyroyal, tea-tree oil and other aromatic oils to
repel fleas and ticks are other less-toxic options, and are
available from natural-pet-care companies such as BioChemics, which
makes Bug Out spray, and One Earth, producer of herbal collars and
Citrus Shampoo Plus.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Goodpet's nontoxic, microscopic ``beneficial nematodes'' eat
flea larvae when sprayed outdoors, and are a good way to keep
infestations at bay _ a $25 container covers 4,800 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic and brewer's yeast are also recommended to supplement pet
diets, as they produce body odors that repel fleas _ One Earth
offers brewer's-yeast-and-garlic tablets and biscuits.
 &UR; ANIMAL ACCESSORIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With natural-pet-care companies abounding, anything your
companion may need can be bought through eco-friendly channels.
</P>
<P>
   World Wise has taken more than 25 billion soda-bottle caps, for
example, and turned them into sturdy food bowls, priced at $5.99.
It also produces an inexpensive cat scratcher from
100-percent-recycled cardboard, organic catnip and a heavy-duty
recycled-cardboard pet carrier.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for all-natural pet bedding, Creeping Jenny is
the place to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Organic bedding for dogs and cats is important,'' president
Jennifer Chamberlain says. ``Skin problems are the No. 1 reason
caregivers take their pets to the vet, and cedar and foam beds are
too harsh for many animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Creeping Jenny also offers hemp collars and leashes, hemp-rope
bones, organic catnip and hemp toys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hemp is digestible and breaks down easily if an animal
swallows it,'' Chamberlain says _ unlike the nylon threading found
in many products, which can cause intestinal blockages in pets.
</P>
<P>
   And for pet owners frustrated with doctors who prescribe
antibiotics at every vet visit, many are looking into homeopathic
remedies _ treating animals with a little of what ails them.
</P>
<P>
   HomeoPet, Dr. Goodpet, Animals' Apawthecary and Noah's Ark have
created a wide selection of homeopathic products, including
treatments for arthritis, urinary incontinence, eczema, flea bites,
anxiety, diarrhea and ear infections.
</P>
<P>
   With luck, taking a holistic approach to pet care will have Fido
wagging his tail and Fifi purring with good health _ and you
feeling good about having helped the environment.
 &UR; SIDEBAR: SOURCES AND RESOURCES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The following companies offer a variety of natural pet-care
products.
</P>
<P>
   + Absorption Corporation, makers of CareFRESH and ECOfresh _
(800) 242-2287.
</P>
<P>
   + American Holistic Veterinary Medical Association, 2214 Old
Emmorton Rd., Bel Air, MD 21015 _ (410) 569-0795.
</P>
<P>
   + Animals' Apawthecary _ (406) 821-4090.
</P>
<P>
   + Animal Protection Institute, P.O. Box 22505, Sacramento, CA
95822 _ (800) 348-7387.
</P>
<P>
   + BioChemics _ (800) 738-7669.
</P>
<P>
   + Creeping Jenny _ (818) 755-9531.
</P>
<P>
   + Dandy Doggie _ (888) 236-4568.
</P>
<P>
   + Dr. Goodpet _ (800) 222-9932.
</P>
<P>
   + Heartland Products _ (800) 437-4780.
</P>
<P>
   + M.D.E. Laboratories, producers of One Earth products _ (800)
