<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beanie heist busted at Florida McDonald's
 &HT;    By Shannon Colavecchio
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ When the van arrived at the McDonald's at
4132 Blue Heron Blvd., word spread quickly among employees that it
carried two boxes of Zip the Cat Teenie Beanie Babies _ 600 in all.
</P>
<P>
   But when managers opened up the van, they discovered the plush
collectibles were gone, Detective Pat Galligan said.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, an 18-year-old McDonald's employee lost her job
and landed in jail, charged with stealing the Happy Meal prizes _
street value $6,000 _ and selling 300 of the toys to a coworker.
</P>
<P>
   According to police, Latasha Chappell went to the van about
10:30 a.m. Thursday, June 4, took the two boxes of stuffed animals
and that afternoon sold one box for $50 to McDonald's employee Earl
Wynds, 29, of West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   But Wynds, who said he felt guilty and feared losing his job,
returned the stolen stuffed goods to his managers, Galligan said.
</P>
<P>
   No charges were filed against Wynds, but Chappell, of 5865
Haverhill Road, was brought into the police station for questioning
and ``finally broke down and said she had the other box at her
boyfriend's house,'' Galligan said.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the 300 Beanies in that box _ returned to the Blue Heron
Boulevard McDonald's the next day _ are still missing.
</P>
<P>
   Chappell, who had worked at the restaurant since March, was
booked into the county jail on petty and grand theft charges,
police said. Grand theft is a third-degree felony. Chappell was
released Friday afternoon on $3,000 bond.
</P>
<P>
   She had no prior criminal record, police said, but has now lost
her job and may face jail time.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things will make people crazy,'' Galligan said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
