<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMUNICATING-WITH-CHILDREN-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FINE ART OF LISTENING TO CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By JULIA MARTIN  
 c.1998 Child magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I refused my 2-and-a-half-year-old daughter's 12th
consecutive plea for candy, she began to scream and sob.
</P>
<P>
   Snapping and threatening a time-out weren't working, so I
decided to try a different tack.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are so sad that you can't have candy, aren't you, honey?''
I said, and gave her a hug.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, her crying softened and she began nodding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want one jelly bean,'' she whimpered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' I said. ``You really love to eat candy. You'd like
to eat it all day long, wouldn't you?''
</P>
<P>
   To my amazement, she calmed down and actually gave up on the
candy crusade, at least for the moment. My willingness simply to
listen and empathize helped her get over her troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lives have become so fast-paced we often don't slow down
enough to tune in to what our kids are saying,'' says Florence
Wolff, professor emeritus of communication at the University of
Dayton in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Yet experts say this skill is one of the most important you can
have as a parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the bedrock of communication, of your whole approach to
parenting,'' says Elaine Mazlish, co-author of ``How to Talk So
Kids Will Listen &AMP; Listen So Kids Will Talk'' (Avon Books, 1982).
``When your child feels you truly understand what he is saying and
feeling, it enhances the bond of closeness and trust between you
and gives him a tremendous feeling of self-satisfaction and
self-esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, good listening skills are easy to learn. Here are a
few key strategies to pursue.
 &UR; ATTENTION, PLEASE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can't really listen if you are preoccupied with other
things. If your child wants to talk _ especially if he's upset or
worried _ it's important that you stop whatever you're doing and
give him your full attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are opening mail or thinking about a meeting while your
child is talking, you'll tune out much of what he's telling you,''
Wolff says.
</P>
<P>
   You will also send the message that his concerns aren't a top
priority.
</P>
<P>
   It's also important to show him that you are listening and care
about what she has to say. Lean forward to let her know you are
interested. Holding hands or putting your arm around your child
also shows her how important she is to you, and will encourage her
to open up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physical contact is a way children feel connected to you,''
Mazlish says. ``It makes them feel cared about.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are times when you can't drop what you're
doing. But you can still let your child know you want to listen.
</P>
<P>
   If he approaches you at a bad moment, Mazlish says, say
something like ``I want to listen and give you my full attention,
sweetie. But right now I have to finish up this project. As soon as
I'm done we'll sit down and talk.''
</P>
<P>
   The crucial message is that you value what your child has to
say.
 &UR; LOOK FOR NONVERBAL CLUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Another key to effective listening is to take in the whole
message your child is sending, which includes facial expressions
and body language.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty percent of the speaker's message comes from nonverbal
signals,'' Wolff says.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially true of babies, of course, and small children
who have difficulty expressing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if your 9-year-old comes into the kitchen with a
problem and you keep chopping onions with your back to her, you'll
miss important clues. She may not sound very upset, but one look at
her would tell you otherwise: Her eyebrows are knitted, her body is
rigid and her fists are clenched.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't look at your child while she is speaking,'' Wolff
says, ``you miss most of what she is trying to get across.''
 &UR; EMPATHIZE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next, perhaps most challenging step is to identify and
affirm your child's feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, parents often do the opposite, denying the
feelings _ ``There's no reason to be so upset'' _ or offering a
philosophical response _ ``That's life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these reactions show the child she's wrong to feel the
way she does,'' Mazlish says. ``Denying a child's feelings in this
way tells her she can't trust herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Even supplying a solution isn't necessarily helpful _ it robs
the child of the opportunity to problem-solve on her own, and yours
may be the wrong solution for her.
</P>
<P>
   Kids are also more likely to turn up the volume when you don't
empathize, as I learned with my candy-crazy toddler. Frustrated
because they don't feel understood, they protest more loudly.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, focus on validating your child's feelings. Your
affirmation can be a simple but attentive ``Ummm, I see,'' or a
summary or reflection of the feelings behind her words.
</P>
<P>
   This approach accomplishes several things. It shows your child
that she and her concerns are important to you, it validates her
feelings and it helps her relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can stop trying to explain,'' Mazlish says, ``and be
consoled by the fact that you understand.''
</P>
<P>
   With that knowledge, the child is now free to let the emotion
go, or to think of a solution on her own.
</P>
<P>
   Bear in mind that acknowledging your child's feelings doesn't
mean allowing his heated emotions free rein. You can validate his
feelings while still setting limits.
</P>
<P>
   If your son is preparing to haul off and whack his brother, for
example, say ``You are so mad at your brother you'd like to hit
him. But now use words, not actions.''
</P>
<P>
   This approach won't always calm a distraught child. Sometimes,
he will actually become more willful.
</P>
<P>
   ``In such a case, you'll have to get firmer and deal with any
unacceptable behavior,'' says Dr. Emanuel Elfenbein, a
child-and-adolescent psychiatrist in Caldwell, N.J.. ``But an
empathetic response is a good first step.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the hardest moments are when your child tells you
something that makes you angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you come down hard on the child, she might withdraw,''
Mazlish says. ``She may be hesitant to come to you in the future
when she has a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're too angry to respond without criticizing or being
judgmental, take a break and cool off. At a later time, follow up
and express your concerns.
 &UR; MAKE TIME TO LISTEN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It helps to have a regular time and place set aside for family
members to express their feelings. For instance, you can encourage
conversation at mealtime or before bed.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Monica Goble, a pediatric cardiologist in East Lansing,
Mich., gathers her two boys for a quick 10 minutes on the couch
when she gets home from work.
</P>
<P>
   ``My inclination is to walk in and put something in the
microwave for dinner first thing,'' she says. ``But it works better
to give the boys my attention right off the bat so they can tell me
anything that's on their minds. They seem calmer after that, and
the whole evening goes better.''
</P>
<P>
   Many kids find it easiest to open up in informal settings,
rather than face-to-face talks. Walking the dog or reading together
offers a relaxed intimacy that breeds conversation.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a good idea, when you have several children, to create
one-on-one time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can be especially helpful with a child who is hard to
draw out, since he'll know it is his special time to be heard,''
Mazlish says.
</P>
<P>
   Some days, of course, your best intentions may backfire, and you
won't be able to resist judging or offering a well-meant but
ill-conceived bit of advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK,'' Mazlish says. ``Aim for good listening 70 percent
of the time, keeping in mind that, on some days, 10 percent will be
all you can manage.''
</P>
<P>
   The important thing is that you continue to make an effort to
tune in to your child. That will pave the way for a lifetime of
better communication between you.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Julia Martin is a Verona, N.J.-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
