<HEADER>
A9722 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMERWATCH09-COX     06-08 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERWATCH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Watch: Don't get taken for a ride by `dream vacation'
scams
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Most of us know there's ``no such thing as a free
lunch'' _ but many people don't understand that usually there's
``no such thing as a free vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   Travel-related fraud costs consumers about $12 billion annually,
according to the Federal Trade Commission, which reports that
complaints about such fraud rank among the top five highest it
receives annually.
</P>
<P>
   The travel tricksters prey on unwary consumers year-round, but
summer is their prime time for operation -- and the FTC recently
issued a new warning about misleading offers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, to underline its warning, the FTC last week alleged
that two Pennsylvania-based firms -- Commonwealth Marketing Group
and Great Escape Vacations &AMP; Tours -- were running a telemarketing
travel scam with victims throughout the nation. A federal court has
frozen the assets of the two firms and ceased their operations
pending trial or settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The so-called dream vacations (promised by the two firms) were
a nightmare,'' said Jodie Bernstein, director of the FTC's bureau
of consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands of consumers who thought they had qualified for a
discount vacation paid hundreds of dollars to collect, but they
didn't get what they paid for,'' she said. ``What were advertised
as `luxury cruises' were actually ferry boat rides, and the
`world-class hotels' were not. Instead of sailing into the sunset,
consumers were taken for a ride.''
</P>
<P>
   The FTC alleged that the firms targeted consumers who had been
enticed at local fairs and other public events to ``register'' for
a vacation to Florida and the Bahamas. Most people who registered
thought they were entering a drawing to win a luxury vacation.
</P>
<P>
   But they had not. Instead, they were contacted by telemarketers
-- and sometimes by mail -- and told there would be a fee, usually
$598, to register for the vacation, which supposedly was worth much
more. They were told the vacation was a limited-time offer and were
urged to pay quickly, the FTC alleges.
</P>
<P>
   Those who paid were sent a package of information, when they
learned they would have to pay several more hundred dollars in
``port reservation processing fees'' -- and the ``luxury cruise''
was only a five-to-six-hour ferry boat ride to the Bahamas and
back.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC also alleges that consumers who sought refunds were
usually denied.
</P>
<P>
   Travel fraud is on old problem, and one day you likely will be
targeted as a potential victim. But to protect yourself takes only
caution and common sense:
</P>
<P>
   -- Buy vacations from a business you know. Deal with members of
a professional association such as the American Society of Travel
Agents, the National Tour Association and the U.S. Tour Operators
Association.
</P>
<P>
   -- If contacted by phone or mail, be wary if the names of the
seller and travel provider differ. You may be dealing with a
marketer who has no further responsibility to you after the sale.
</P>
<P>
   -- Learn the language. ``You have been specially selected to
receive our spectacular luxury vacation offer'' doesn't mean you
have won a free vacation. It means you will be offered an
opportunity to pay for a vacation that probably won't fit your
definition of luxury.
</P>
<P>
   -- Get the details of your vacation in writing and a copy of the
cancellation and refund policies before paying. Determine exactly
what the price covers and what it doesn't. Don't accept such vague
terms as ``major hotels'' or ``luxury cruises.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Don't be pressured into buying. Scam operators often say they
need your commitment today, but a good offer by a legitimate
company today usually will be a good offer tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   -- Don't give your credit card number or bank information over
the phone unless you know the company. Sometimes fraudulent
telemarketers say they need the number for verification purposes,
but don't believe them.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, you have determined the offer is legitimate, it's
usually better to pay by credit card. That way, if you later
encounter problems, you may dispute the charges by writing to your
credit card issuer. You have up to 60 days after the bill's
statement date to dispute the charge.
</P>
<P>
   But look out for travel promoters who say you have to wait at
least 60 days after paying by credit card to make reservations.
They are scheming to get you past the time you may legally
challenge the charge.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
