A9724 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK09-COX     06-08 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Money Talk: Start young and retire comfy
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Can you ever afford to retire?
</P>
<P>
   More and more people are worrying about just that question. One
out of three working people think the answer is no. Their edginess
came to mind last week, as President Clinton, House Speaker Newt
Gingrich (R-Ga.) and more than 200 other top-drawer politicians and
money managers came together in Washington to encourage Americans
to save more for their retirements.
</P>
<P>
   They grabbed headlines grappling with familiar demons: America's
low savings rate, 3.9 percent last year, and Social Security
worries, among them. All in all, the talk probably left a lot of
people feeling even more uncertain about their chances of enjoying
a comfortable retirement.
</P>
<P>
   But, it is important to remember a couple of things:
</P>
<P>
   -- Most people can work out an estimate of how much they'll need
to save toward retirement.
</P>
<P>
   -- Most people can, without overwhelming strain, build a nest
egg for themselves. It helps if you start young, and it helps to
keep saving something from every paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   This is not rocket science. Think of it as assembling a model
airplane -- exacting, perhaps tedious. But at least the process
gives you an idea of what the picture really looks like.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring what you need
</P>
<P>
   There is no universal rule for how much to save. The old saw
about saving 10 percent of your take-home pay might be a comfort,
but it might be wrong for you. ``That's why people really should
invest a little time, doing their calculations themselves,'' said
Paul Yakoboski, a senior research associate for the Employee
Benefit Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   We have an advantage these days -- the Internet. You can find
plenty of interactive worksheets from various financial advisers.
Some of them are terribly misleading, however. I recommend the one
supplied by Vanguard (http://www
</P>
<P>
   .vanguard.com).
</P>
<P>
   Any good worksheet will walk you through a fairly detailed set
of questions, including your age, planned retirement date, income,
expected Social Security income, any pension you anticipate and
savings, both current and future.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that and other data will come from your records. Some of
it will be no more than estimates. For a projection of Social
Security income, call 800-772-1213. If you expect a pension, go to
the office that handles pensions and ask for an estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Saving the bucks
</P>
<P>
   Most people can build a significant nest egg, judging by data in
the Retirement Confidence Survey, which was released last week by
Yakoboski's institute and other agencies. Among other findings, the
study showed 56 percent of Americans believe they can put aside $20
a week for retirement savings.
</P>
<P>
   If you start young, invest that amount for 30 years and earn an
8 percent return, you would have more than $127,000. If you got a
bit more ambitious -- assuming you get regular pay raises and
increase your savings by $5 a week each year -- your 30-year
savings plan would grow to more than $419,000.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you didn't put the money into a tax-deferred account,
such as an IRA, you could still make a respectable amount. Not
$419,000 but about $282,000.
</P>
<P>
   If you took out only 5 percent of that to boost your retirement
income, you would have an extra $14,000. The rest would remain
invested, and still grow for you.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean that paying for retirement is a snap? No. Are the
steps mentioned here a sure thing? No. But are they better than
giving in to frustration or despair? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
