<HEADER>
A9712 &Cx1f; tab-z
w l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARLIC-AND-YOUR-HEALT     06-08 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARLIC-AND-YOUR-HEALTH-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GLORIES OF GARLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By CHARLES DICKSON  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chowing down on a clove of garlic may not be the best thing in
the world for your romantic life, but it may just be the best thing
you can do for your body.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic, that pungent little bulb with the shriveled-onion look,
is in the process of taking a giant leap from its status as a mere
cooking ingredient to newfound glory as a top seller on health-food
shelves.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't even smell anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic's higher profile has come about as a result of a
multitude of recent scientific studies, all of which seem to
indicate that garlic may be one of the healthiest substances you
can put into your body. The research into garlic's chemistry and
specific disease-preventive actions has already made it a niche
cure-all, and is rapidly driving it into the health mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, garlic is no herb-come-lately. It has a long history
of medicinal use, dating back to the Babylonians and Egyptians, the
latter of whom sealed it in their tombs. Greek athletes at the
original Olympic games chewed it for stamina, and its curative
effects were recommended by no less an authority than Hippocrates,
the Father of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the great French scientist Louis Pasteur
recognized its anti-bacterial properties, and in the First World
War ointments made from garlic were used to treat infection in
wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Garlic belongs to a family of sulfur-containing plants that also
includes onions. Now studies at leading medical institutions
worldwide are increasingly suggesting its effectiveness against
human maladies ranging from heart disease to cancer, from
infections to toxic stress.
</P>
<P>
   The first scientific clue to garlic's beneficial effects came
from a study of the vegetarian diet of the Jain sect in India.
Members of that community, who consume liberal amounts of onions
and garlic, were shown to have cholesterol levels 25 percent lower
than the general population.
</P>
<P>
   In another controlled study, reported in the American Journal of
Clinical Nutrition, a group of 41 men with moderately elevated
cholesterol showed a 6-percent drop in total cholesterol levels,
including a 4.6-percent drop in LDL or ``bad'' cholesterol, when
they ate garlic regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Additional studies suggest that several compounds in garlic _
allicin, ajoene and diallyl disulfide _ inhibit the chemical
pathways by which the body manufactures its own cholesterol, the
main source of the artery-clogging plaque that brings on heart
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian research team discovered the effectiveness of a
garlic extract in lowering fibrinogen in the blood, which is the
substance that causes clotting. This blood-thinning quality was
also observed by another group of researchers in Hamburg, Germany,
suggesting that garlic may be at least as effective as aspirin for
keeping heart attacks at bay, without causing the stomach distress
often associated with aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-cancer properties of this odiferous herb were first
documented by a research team in China, which studied the
populations of two neighboring counties, in one of which garlic was
a staple while in the other it was rarely used, and discovered a
dramatically lower incidence of cancer in the former.
</P>
<P>
   This led investigators at the M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in
Texas to inject cancer cells into rats in two groups, one of which
had been given cells previously incubated with various garlic
compounds.
</P>
<P>
   They discovered that the cells incubated with garlic failed to
produce tumors, while the untreated ones soon killed the animals.
These findings have been duplicated in subsequent studies at Penn
State University.
</P>
<P>
   A major part of garlic's high standing in folk medicine rests on
its reputation as a natural antibiotic, able to overcome an array
of infections.
</P>
<P>
   This apparently works in two ways: In some situations the garlic
kills the microbes directly, while in others it enhances the body's
natural defenses to boost the ability of immune cells to engulf and
destroy the germ cells.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Benjamin Lau of Loma Linda University in California has
demonstrated its effectiveness against microbes causing vaginal
yeast infections.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, studies done at the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research
Center in Seattle have revealed that when garlic extract is placed
in a culture dish of H. pylori, the bacteria responsible for
stomach ulcers, it severely inhibits the bacteria's growth.
</P>
<P>
   These results have led scientists to conclude that consuming
garlic might be an easy, inexpensive way to reduce the incidence of
stomach cancer, especially in the light of the growing problem of
antibiotic resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another beneficial aspect of this long-used but
often-overlooked herb is its enhancement of liver function.
</P>
<P>
   Our bodies are bombarded daily by a welter of environmental
hazards, from pollutants to pesticides. Not the least of garlic's
contribution may be its ability to shore up our detoxifying
defenses, especially in the liver. Evidence shows that garlic not
only boosts overall liver function but also enhances the production
of key detoxifying agents in the body.
</P>
<P>
   And so the litany of praise for this unpretentious herb
continues, as research teams almost daily explore new possibilities
for human benefit. Whether it's heart disease, cancer, infections
or toxic stress, chewing some garlic each day may be part of the
answer.
</P>
<P>
   A clove or two a day should do it _ but to avoid any romantic
complications, you may want to try a couple of 300-to-400-milligram
tablets or capsules, which are generally odor-free.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Charles Dickson is a Hickory, N.C.-based free-lance writer.
His ``Medicinal Chemistry'' will be published in October 1998 by
CRC Press.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
