<SLUG> BC-DROUGHT-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH WARNS DROUGHT PUTTING TEXAS IN RISK OF FIRES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With Texas suffering through one of its driest
springs ever, much of the state is in ``imminent risk'' of fires,
Gov. George W. Bush warned Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush asked President Clinton for an emergency declaration to
transfer U.S. Forest Service firefighters and equipment into Texas
as a precaution against the tinderbox conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and other state officials also asked Texans to
conserve water and urged local officials to consider outdoor
burning bans and restrictions on water use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is already dry, and we face a long hot summer,'' Bush
said. ``Already in early June we are seeing August-like conditions
with the bulk of the summer still ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Millwee, the state's emergency management coordinator, said
the spring drought was ``unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   ``During the month of May, it was virtually a record in terms of
dryness around the state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said 80 percent of the state is in drought and
``severe'' fire danger. Agricultural producers may suffer millions
of dollars in drought-related losses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's emergency proclamation for federal fire-fighting
assistance included 207 of the state's 254 counties, every area of
the state except north central and northeast Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The federal help, he said, would ``put equipment in place to
help save lives and property.''
</P>
<P>
   Two major wildfires already have erupted in West Texas this
spring, consuming thousands of acres in Presidio and Edwards
counties before they were extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Texas officials are keeping an eye on a forest fire in
Tamaulipas, a Mexican state on the Texas border. Except for smoke
that may drift north, that fire doesn't pose an imminent threat to
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Texas already has suffered on and off for several weeks
from smoke from fires in drought-plagued southern Mexico and
Central America. That smoke has prompted state officials to issue
health alerts, especially for people with respiratory problems.
</P>
<P>
   Many Texas counties report rain shortfalls of 78 percent or more
this spring, according to the governor's office. Bush said San
Antonio saw its driest April on record.
</P>
<P>
   The Lower Rio Grande Valley received only 17 percent of its
normal rainfall for March, April and May, potentially costing an
estimated $97 million in losses to cotton, corn and sorghum crops.
Several irrigation districts in the Valley face the possibility of
extreme water shortages in the next several months, state officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said water supplies in most parts of the state are at
normal levels now and are in much better shape than they were
during the 1996 drought. But, he cautioned, the lack of rainfall
means reservoirs are not being replenished, with the hottest and
traditionally driest part of the summer still to come.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 counties already have banned outdoor fires, and
Bush urged local officials to be cautious in allowing fireworks
displays for the July 4 holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Texans were urged to take shorter showers, turn off water while
brushing teeth and install low-flow plumbing hardware. They also
were advised to water lawns in the early morning and use drip
irrigation for shrubs and flower beds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
