<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKY-HIGHTECH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKY DAYTON PUSHES THE RIGHT BUTTONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sky Dayton bounds up to meet you with the
friendly, open face of a puppy dog. He wears a cable-knit pullover
and chinos draped over a lean frame, and a beard that just isn't
filling in the way beards are supposed to.
</P>
<P>
   He's also got a big smile on his face. He should.
</P>
<P>
   _ The company he founded three years ago, EarthLink Network Inc.
in Pasadena, recently signed up its 500,000th customer, making it
the fourth-largest Internet service provider, behind America
Online, the Microsoft Network and AT&AMP;T. That's fast company.
</P>
<P>
   _ On Friday, Dayton's company took over Sprint Corp.'s 130,000
Internet customers. The $15 billion long-distance giant gets 30
percent of EarthLink, but also gives EarthLink $24 million in cash,
a $100 million credit line and marketing muscle most young Internet
companies dream about.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dayton's company reported record 1997 revenues of about $80
million, more than double 1996. And wonder of Internet wonders,
analysts say his company should end this year in the black.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and one other thing. Dayton is 26 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the New Economy.
</P>
<P>
   To get an idea how fast his company has grown, consider this:
</P>
<P>
   Dayton's personal office in its two-building headquarters takes
up more room than his entire company did when it started three
years in a Los Feliz medical building.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Dayton had to scrape together every spare dime for a
party celebrating the company's 600th customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big goal for us back then,'' Dayton said. ``Now we
sign up 600 people in four hours.''
</P>
<P>
   He shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been amazing. It's a great feeling,'' Dayton said.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton was raised mostly in Los Angeles, though he lived for a
time in Northern California with his grandfather, a tech whiz who
served a prestigious stint as an IBM Fellow.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in part to his grandfather's Big Blue influence, Dayton
got into computers early, tinkering with a Timex Sinclair, one of
the earliest home PCs, at age 9. By his early 20s, Dayton decided
to try the Internet. But getting wired proved excruciating, even
for a wirehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was utter hell,'' Dayton said. ``I got no sleep, I didn't
go to work.''
</P>
<P>
   After spending 80 hair-pulling hours trying to hook up, Dayton
decided to start his own Internet company, focused on helping
people become Netheads without Netheadaches.
</P>
<P>
   His company emphasized customer service at a time when most
competitors didn't. That emphasis continues, with more than half
the company's 1,000 employees working in tech support and customer
service.
</P>
<P>
   The company put together a software package called Total Access
that installs Netscape Navigator and other programs, then walks a
new customer through the connection process.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers can create a customized ``start page'' on their Web
browser that includes news headlines in areas of interest, local
weather forecasts, stock quotes and more.
</P>
<P>
   The company even has a ``guardian angel'' program watching for
the ``connected but confused,'' calling to see if they need help.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these programs they do are really unique,'' said David
Goodtree, director of telecom strategies at Forrester Research in
Cambridge, Mass. ``When's the last time the phone company called
you up and asked if everything was going all right?''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what Sprint thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we linked up is we saw EarthLink being an
outstanding Internet service provider,'' said Sprint assistant vice
president Bill White. ``We saw we could grow much more rapidly by
partnering with them. They know the service well, have more scale
than we did, and there were a lot of opportunities for
cross-promotion and cross-marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal should help both sides, said Goodtree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprint spent a lot of money trying to launch an Internet
service and what they realized was they still didn't get it,'' said
Goodtree. ``EarthLink is known for great technical support and
customer service.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's top executive was equally admiring of Dayton, White
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chairman (and CEO) Bill Esrey is very impressed with him,''
White said. ``He's an entrepreneurial, energetic guy who knows what
he wants to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   From Dayton's point of view, the Sprint deal is only the biggest
of dozens of partnerships _ ranging from movie companies to
publishers to discount stores to credit cards _ that have stretched
EarthLink's resources by piggybacking on others' money and
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dayton vocabulary, partnering is a very big word,
encapsulated by his Dayton Theory of Internet Market Evolution.
Basically, Dayton says, smart companies focus on their business
niche, then find partners to do everything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``By creating that model, I was able to figure out who the
partners and the competitors are,'' Dayton said. ``Then it was a
matter of convincing the right partners to do the right deals.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees Hollywood as a particularly fertile place for
partnering, going back to marketing deals with movies such as ``The
Net'' and ``Contact,'' part of Dayton's ``evangelizing'' of the
entertainment business the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   As Dayton looks toward the future, he believes his company, and
the Internet in general, are well positioned to become a
mass-market phenomenon, moving beyond the technically proficient to
a basic part of most American households.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, the Internet wasn't a consumer product,'' Dayton said.
``Now, it's a baseline communications tool.''
</P>
<P>
   The implications are particularly interesting for the
entertainment business, Dayton said, because increasingly, the
Internet will be the way its products _ video, music, publishing _
arrive in the American home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entertainment business thrives on communication,'' Dayton
said. ``The Internet represents the best way to put more of their
product out there. We are the channel of distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayton has no plans to follow AOL and MSN into the content
creation business, however, saying EarthLink will continue do what
it does well and find more partners to do the entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons we're so successful is that I'm so focused
and the company is so focused,'' Dayton said.
</P>
<P>
   For Dayton, that means his company must be able to grow as the
Internet grows. That means being able to delegate.
</P>
<P>
   As the company boomed, Dayton did something many entrepreneurs
don't. He brought in help, led by CEO Garry Betty, a veteran
telecommunications executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure I'm surrounded by good people,'' Dayton
said. ``I think we have the most talented CEO in the business. We
work great together.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty said Dayton was ``smart enough to say, `I need help.' He
said, `You're running the company,' and he never looked back.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayton's company still faces many challenges, including such
threats as cable companies that would provide Internet service with
cable modems, said Goodtree. But, ``there's plenty of room for
EarthLink. They're squarely focused and pretty much the cream of
the crop,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton, who lives in Toluca Lake with his wife, Arwen, said he
feels confident about the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a good position in the first leg of a long race,''
Dayton said. ``I think this can be a major, major communications
company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
