<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9726 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-COLUMN09-COX     06-08 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marilyn Geewax's Business Commentary: Too few visionaries
planned for growth
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Metro Atlanta's business leaders have long been
stereotyped as blue-blazered boosters, relentlessly bragging about
the area's growth during their Kiwanis Club meetings. In the 1980s,
one could scarcely read a national news story about Atlanta without
seeing a mocking reference to our dogged ``boosterism.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in the late 1990s, the optimists don't have to talk it up
any more. Turns out that metro Atlanta's growth has outstripped
even the rosiest predictions of the most gung-ho Rotarians. A few
years ago, business leaders here were willing to concede that after
the 1996 Olympics, the area's economy would slow a bit in 1997 and
1998. But instead of taking a breather, the economy has roared
toward hyperventilation.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic on I-285 has gone from terrible to nightmarish to
suicidal. Georgia Power is struggling to churn out enough power to
keep air conditioners humming. The air is getting filthy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the North Georgia gold rush goes on. This is no
exaggeration: Metro Atlanta has the hottest housing market in the
region, which happens to be the fastest-growing region in the
country, which happens to have the strongest economy in the world.
In terms of growth, it really doesn't get any better than this.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like booster bullfeathers, take another look at
the statistics. Last week the Commerce Department reported that the
nation's sales of new homes surged to a record in April, climbing
5.2 percent to an unprecedented annual rate of 888,000, seasonally
adjusted. But that growth was extremely uneven: Sales declined in
every region except the South.
</P>
<P>
   And what an exception. The South's new-home sales shot up 18.1
percent. Within the region, metro Atlanta is even hotter. According
to statistics compiled by Property Data Systems for Northside
Realty Associates, housing starts rose 23 percent in the metro
area's northern arc during the first three months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   For many older Atlantans, this economic explosion brings a sense
of pride. After years of being labeled as bumpkins and boosters,
they are getting rich and having the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   But the daily hassles behind the growth statistics are getting
harder to handle. Everywhere in metro Atlanta, trees are being
turned into mulch as the bulldozers and chainsaws create room for
subdivisions and shopping centers. Red clay runs into streams and
brown haze hangs low.
</P>
<P>
   Last week brought more evidence of how good these times are in
terms of making money, and how bad they are in terms of protecting
air quality or reducing commute times. In Hall County, the planning
commission endorsed the construction of the Lake Lanier Country
Club, a 589-home gated community on the lake's far north side. The
homes will be priced from the mid-$200,000 to $2 million-plus.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago, the area north of Lake Lanier would have
regarded the opening of a live-bait shop as a step toward economic
development.
</P>
<P>
   The plans for Lake Lanier Country Club reflect the growing
wealth of metro Atlantans. You can't help but be happy to have
prosperous families moving into beautiful homes.
</P>
<P>
   But you also can't help but be horrified at the prospect of
another huge subdivision being created long before more sewers and
transportation systems are added to handle such rapid population
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the 1980s, it was a lot easier to be a civic booster
than a thoughtful planner. Metro Atlanta was blessed with lots of
people willing to promote business. Unfortunately, it had too few
visionaries willing to plan the commuter rails, park systems, sewer
pipes and water lines that would have made the resulting growth
more enjoyable for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
