<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARCUS-RESTRICTIONS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Town council claims ad restrictions hinder traffic
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH _ The mid-town public beach has no toilets; there's
no fishing after dark along the Intracoastal Waterway; and a
council member once suggested putting cameras on the bridges.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the town council has said its newest store, Neiman Marcus,
can't advertise off-island for a year after it opens.
</P>
<P>
   It's not snobbery, council members say, it's the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``That day and age died long ago,'' said Councilman Allen Wyett.
``No one has any reason to say anyone on this council is a snob.''
</P>
<P>
   The advertising ban is apparently unique. First Amendment and
land use lawyers can't recall a similar condition elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   To get approval to build on Worth Avenue, the Dallas retailer
agreed not to advertise on television, radio, in The Palm Beach
Post or the Sun-Sentinel, or by mass mailing outside the Palm Beach
zip code for a year.
</P>
<P>
   The council and Neiman will consider a written agreement
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those classic `only in Palm Beach' concepts,''
said Boca Raton attorney Robert Rivas, who handles First Amendment
issues. He said it would likely be unconstitutional if the town
were to try to impose such a condition on other stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are worrying about the traffic and this will help
reassure them,'' Councilman Sam McLendon said. ``The store will be
a novelty the first year and we will probably get more traffic, but
then it will quiet down.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Leslie Shaw proposed the restriction, saying he
wanted to ensure that the exclusive retailer was genuinely aiming
for the Palm Beach market. He suggested the council consider a
similar policy for stores coming to the island.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers may not like it but ``they could live with it,''
Chamber of Commerce President Jesse Newman said. ``For most stores
on (Worth) avenue, I don't think 5 percent advertise across the
county.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said stores should be able to advertise in the
off-season, between April and October, when traffic is lighter.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1980, the town has required stores and restaurants larger
than 2,000 square feet to prove that more than half their customers
are town residents, work in the town or are staying in island
hotels or homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's purely a concern about too much traffic,'' Wyett said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
