<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9737 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STODA-COLUMN09-COX     06-08 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STODA-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Can fraternal piety overcome team politics?
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You have to wonder how today's conversation between big brother
Bryan Murray and little brother Terry Murray is going to go, don't
you?
</P>
<P>
   Bryan is the Florida Panthers' general manager and one of the
people in charge of hiring a new head coach. Terry is a candidate
for the job, and he's in Ratville _ hey, Detroit already has
Hockeytown _ for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The former head coach? That would be Bryan, who last season
fired Doug MacLean and replaced him with his own self. When that
happened, Terry called Bryan with a question: ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's Bryan who will have a few of his own questions for
Terry. Foremost among them is sure to be an inquiry about what
Terry thinks he'll be able to do to begin resurrection of a
moribund team only a couple of seasons removed from an appearance
in the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say there's more than a little pressure on Bryan to
get the right man behind the Panthers' bench in the wake of the
franchise's precipitous fall from excellence. And let's just say
it's not automatic that Terry will _ or will not _ be that man.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan, of course, knows better than to give his brother the
position on the strength of their shared surname. He'd never do
such a thing. But he also knows it would be unfair to remove his
brother from consideration just because of that shared surname.
</P>
<P>
   So, Bryan, would it be easier to hire Terry or not hire him?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I can answer that,'' Bryan said. ``We
understand the situation. I'm not sure our families do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan's wife, Geri, and Terry'snd of ``Alanna'' collecting
objects and solving riddles to get past gateways, boulders and
rivers. (The answers to the first puzzle are on the site now, for
example.)
</P>
<P>
   Marketing on the Web isn't easy. But Coca-Cola's clever Web
promotions make it one of the smartest Web marketers arounustomers
a reason to come back.
</P>
<P>
   No one understands this as well as Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Halloran says the bulk of his consumers are young and spend a
lot of time on the Net and playing computer games. ``We thought,
`How can we tie in the fact that a lot of teens are playing
computer games and drinking Coke?'''
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Coke promotions especially unusual is that they
are not designed to be Web staples. They are used on an ``as
needed'' basis for seasonal promotions tied into its traditional ad
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola says the Cherry Coke promotion and the ``Alanna'' game
will run at least through November, with new clues and information.
</P>
<P>
   All this interactivity is designed to leave game players and
their friends with the impression Cherry Coke is a hip, cutting
edge product.
</P>
<P>
   Because Coca-Cola is mindful of its young target audience,
``Alanna'' is not a bloody shoot-'em-up game but a lush, quiet
``Myst''-like game with an educational component designed to help
players win the game.
</P>
<P>
   To add a touch of realism, the company also enlisted the help of
an Emory University professor who created the fictional Standlake
University of Cultural Anthropology Web site. Once there, you must
read through each page of that site to find out about topics such
as cuneiform symbols and ancient Babylonia _ just a way to add an
educational component to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely put an educational slant to the game,'' Halloran
says. ``We want to educate our teen customers. A lot of the clues
on the game site are based on ancient cultures. It's kind of a
study of archaeology.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no official list of hints or clues to help users solve
the puzzle. Folks intent on winning must keep visiting the site or
checking out different bottles of Cherry Coke. They can also check
out Coke and gaming Usenet newsgroups to swap clues and information
with other game players.
</P>
<P>
   A recent check of newsgroups shows several postings to
``comp.sys.ibm.pc.games'' and ``alt.food.cocacola'' talking about
the game and swapping tips and hints. Halloran calls this
world-of-mouth buzz ``viral marketing'' since he hopes it'll spread
that way. ``We're hoping there will be online chat and posts,'' he
says. ``We're hoping people will interact with the brand and each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   The promotion appears to be an expensive proposition, but
Coca-Cola won't say just how expensive it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we really didn't want to go down the route of a
traditional soft drink promotion,'' Halloran said. ``We think the
bang for the buck using the Internet and gaming is going to be
substantial for this particular brand.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no print ads, nor are there CD-ROMs available at any
Coke point of sale. The company is relying on word of mouth and the
Web to spread the word about Cherry Coke.
</P>
<P>
   ``This promotion is very different,'' Halloran said. ``It will
require consumers to think and act differently. It's a way to show
off the new version of Cherry Coke and get them engaged with the
product by playing the game. We want to be seen as something very
different from Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
