<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9738 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-CORRUPT-SOYIN     06-08 1430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-CORRUPT-SOYINKA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I CRY FOR NIGERIA' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By ZIA JAFFREY  
 FROM: The Progressive  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Wole Soyinka, the first African to win the Nobel Prize for
Literature, has been critical of Nigeria's home-grown dictators for
decades.
 &HT;    Arrested in 1965, Soyinka spent more than two years in prison,
largely in solitary confinement. He had tried to broker a
cease-fire deal between Nigeria's federal government and Biafran
rebels who wanted to secede from the country. His vitriolic memoir,
``The Man Died,'' was written between the lines of books smuggled
to him in prison.
 &HT;    Released in 1969, he entered a period of voluntary exile. He
lectured at universities, wrote, directed and produced plays in
Europe and West Africa, and founded the leading culture and
criticism magazine, Transition, in Ghana.
 &HT;    Soyinka returned to Nigeria in 1975, but left again temporarily,
in 1983, when he learned there was a price on his head.
 &HT;    Incarnations of his Guerrilla Theatre Unit, a production company
founded in 1978, have been performing for years to mass audiences
in Nigeria. Many skits have sharply rebuked Nigeria's military
regimes and policies and have been performed not only in
auditoriums but, provocatively, in front of government buildings or
in public squares and marketplaces where authorities have cracked
down.
 &HT;    In 1986 Soyinka won the Nobel Prize for Literature. The Swedish
Academy cited his ``prolific store of words ... in witty dialogue,
in satire and grotesquery, in quiet poetry and in essays of
sparkling vitality.''
 &HT;    Soyinka has implored African writers to become the conscience of
their nation or be forced to withdraw ``to the position of
chronicler and postmortem surgeon.''
 &HT;    In 1996 Soyinka published ``The Open Sore of a Continent,''
which accuses the Nigerian military regime of having robbed the
people of their nationhood by annulling the presidential election
of June 12, 1993. On that day 14 million Nigerians had crossed
regional, class, religious and ethnic lines to freely elect as
president a civilian Muslim, Moshood K.O. Abiola. A year later,
Abiola was imprisoned on charges of treason after he declared
himself the rightful president of Nigeria.
 &HT;    The military dictator Gen. Sani Abacha seized power and would
become Nigeria's nemesis. Among Abacha's human-rights abuses, cited
by international watchdog groups, the most infamous was the hanging
of writer and political activist Ken Saro-Wiwa in 1995, along with
eight other pro-democracy activists.
 &HT;    Other perversions of justice have included political detention,
extrajudicial executions, restrictions of freedom of expression and
association, meddling in the judicial process and torture.
 &HT;    Soyinka himself was charged with treason by the military regime
_ a capital offense. In exile since 1994, Soyinka has been
lecturing and writing in America and Europe _ most recently in
Rhode Island, New York, Massachusetts, Washington, D.C., Atlanta
and Champaign, Ill.
 &HT;    
 -0- 
 &HT;    ZIA JAFFREY: Where were you when you received the news that the
Abacha regime had charged you with treason?
 &HT;    WOLE SOYINKA: I was lecturing in the United States. Somebody
tracked me down and asked about my recent ``promotion'' from being
a mere ``terrorist'' to being a ``treasonable felon.'' We knew it
was coming; we knew it was building up. They aim to eliminate the
opposition. This is just one more step in that direction. So it
didn't make any impact on me. It simply meant that I had to turn up
my security one notch.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: I read in a London newspaper that you said there was an
Abacha death squad?
 &HT;    A: Yes. The death squad does exist. We know where they're
trained. We know where they're located, exactly in Abuja; we know
their modus operandi. So we're even able to know when some of them
are dispatched out of the country.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Because you've infiltrated?
 &HT;    A: Let's just say that the opposition has a reasonable network _
obviously, it's not comprehensive _ but we have efficient
intelligence.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: And the intelligence tells you that you're on the hit list?
 &HT;    A: Absolutely.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: In ``The Open Sore of a Continent,'' you suggested that the
next move for Nigeria's people would be civil disobedience.
 &HT;    A: Yes. Even while I was in Nigeria I was organizing a peaceful
march on Aso Rock (the seat of government) from every corner of the
country. ... I gave a press conference detailing the plans and
applying for torches, rations, blankets, halls, and schools along
the way where people would rest.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: For when was this planned?
 &HT;    A: Just about three months before I left. But I was summoned by
the SSS (State Security Services).
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What did they say?
 &HT;    A: Well, it was very polite, very courteous. The officer
apologized for not coming to my house to have the chat. He asked
how on earth did I think I could mount such an (opposition). ... I
said, ``... the people working with me are disciplined, and they
understand what's at stake. ...''
 &HT;    I think this frightened the regime very much. At the end, after
we'd gone through the whole thing he said, ``OK, thank you,
professor. Now I have a responsibility to tell you the decision of
the regime ... it considers itself bound to stop (your dissent) by
every means.'' ... Then arrests began. People were pulled in for
interrogation. Finally I had to accept the decision of the group
that I must leave.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Leave the group, or the country?
 &HT;    A: Leave the country.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Do you still have family in Nigeria?
 &HT;    A: I had to go back and get them out. As hostage-taking became a
cardinal policy of the government, the assassinations of relations
and colleagues of dissidents who are out of reach began to become
the norm. I had to get three adult members of my family out. The
surveillance had become crippling, really suffocating.
 &HT;    This regime just does not believe in innocence. ... In prison
(they incarcerate) children. ... The ages of the children-hostages
vary from four to 12 in Nigeria. They are kept in police cells.
It's something we have never experienced before. Never. Never.
They've always left civilians alone.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Tell me about the attack in which the government fired on
secondary-school students.
 &HT;    A: Many people don't know ... Not many people believe that
Abacha would fire on students. But we know this.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What were they protesting?
 &HT;    A: A 500 percent hike in school fees.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: In which city?
 &HT;    A: Benin. In Edo. I think on the first day of action close to 20
were killed, and others died later. We were monitoring the death
toll. It just kept increasing. The last figure I received was 37.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Ken Saro-Wiwa was a friend of yours?
 &HT;    A: We weren't close or anything of the sort. His orbit was quite
different from mine, but I absolutely supported his cause.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Why has Shell oil, even now, not cleared out of Nigeria?
 &HT;    A: Because they're confident of the protection of Nigeria's
regime. They signed a multibillion-dollar contract for a
liquefied-gas project. It was done secretly, but it came out, and
that is when I knew the company had cast its lot, irrevocably, on
the side of power. Everybody was calling for sanctions on Nigeria
and withdrawing business from the country and so on _ for Shell to
have signed that contract, nevertheless, shows that its commercial
interests preceded its humanism.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Where is home for you, at this point?
 &HT;    A: In my head, that's where home is _ in my head.
 &HT;     c.1998 Zia Jaffrey  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Zia Jaffrey is the author of ``The Invisibles: A Tale of the
Eunuchs of India,'' published by Pantheon. She has written for The
New York Times, The Nation, The Village Voice and other
publications. A longer version of this interview appeared in The
Progressive.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
