<P>
   NEWT-SCHOOLBOOKS _ ATLANTA _ Speaking at Supercomm, House
Speaker Newt Gingrich wants to get rid of school textbooks and says
children should use computers instead. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   CONRAIL _ Government is expected to approve Norfolk Southern and
CSX plan to divided Conrail. (Holsensdolph, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-COLUMN _ In the 1980s, one could scarcely read a national
news story about Atlanta without seeing a mocking reference to our
dogged ``boosterism.'' Now in the late 1990s, the optimists don't
have to talk it up any more. Turns out that metro Atlanta's growth
has outstripped even the rosiest predictions of the most gung-ho
Rotarians. Still, the North Georgia gold rush goes on. Business
column by Marilyn Geewax. (Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED. (k, f)
</P>
<P>
   BEANIE-HEIST _ RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ When the van arrived at the
McDonald's at 4132 Blue Heron Blvd., word spread quickly among
employees that it carried two boxes of Zip the Cat Teenie Beanie
Babies _ 600 in all. But when managers opened up the van, they
discovered the plush collectibles were gone, Detective Pat Galligan
said. Consequently, an 18-year-old McDonald's employee lost her job
and landed in jail, charged with stealing the Happy Meal prizes _
street value $6,000 _ and selling 300 of the toys to a coworker.
(Colavecchio, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ The McBealers are the most Web-savvy of any age
group. But what Web sites do they have bookmarked? Here are some
likely candidates: Every McBealer worth his or her salt has surely
checked out the online e-zine Swoon (http://www.swoon.com). The
online home of such Conde Nast magazines as Details, Glamour and
Mademoiselle, the site bills itself as the magazine of ``dating,
mating and relating.'' (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMERWATCH _ ATLANTA _ Most of us know there's ``no such
thing as a free lunch'' _ but many people don't understand that
usually there's ``no such thing as a free vacation.''
Travel-related fraud costs consumers about $12 billion annually,
according to the Federal Trade Commission, which reports that
complaints about such fraud rank among the top five highest it
receives annually. (Tharpe, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENGINEERS-MONEY _ ATLANTA _ Wonder why those new college
graduates with engineering degrees are smiling? Because they are
being offered big bucks by employers. Jobtrak Corp., which operates
an online job-listing site that links employers, universities and
students, said a May survey of selected schools nationwide found
that engineering graduates were being offered an average starting
salary of $58,513, the highest of 24 careers measured by the
survey. (Tharpe, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ ATLANTA _ Can you ever afford to retire?
</P>
<P>
   More and more people are worrying about just that question. One
out of three working people think the answer is no. But, it is
important to remember a couple of things . . . (list follows).
(Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MARCUS-RESTRICTIONS _ PALM BEACH _ The mid-town public beach has
no toilets; there's no fishing after dark along the Intracoastal
Waterway; and a council member once suggested putting cameras on
the bridges. Now, the town council has said its newest store,
Neiman Marcus, can't advertise off-island for a year after it
opens. It's not snobbery, council members say, it's the traffic.
(O'Meilia, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKWARS _ Independent booksellers face tough times. Those who
have lasted through changes in the business continue to quietly
look for ways to do better and more efficiently what they have a
reputation for doing: providing personal service. ``I did feel
everyone understands the importance of independent stores,'' Abel
Zimmerman, president of Book People, said. ``As an independent, I
felt well received (by publishers).'' (Morris, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-MARKETING _ Marketing on the Web isn't easy. But Coca-Cola's
clever Web promotions make it one of the smartest Web marketers
around. Brand manager Tom Halloran says the ``Alanna'' promotion --
the latest in Coca-Cola's use of the Web to promote various brands
-- is designed to increase the appeal of Cherry Coke to teens and
young adults who are part of what he calls ``the emerging wired
generation.'' (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
