<HEADER>
A9751 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-FOSTER-NYT &LR;      06-08 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-FOSTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER FOR FOSTER, FORMER WHITE HOUSE AIDE, URGES NOTES REMAIN
PRIVILEGED  
 (JT )
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN LABATON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The lawyer for Vincent W. Foster Jr., the late
White House aide, urged the Supreme Court Monday to allow him to
keep secret his notes of a final meeting the two men had in order
to preserve the sanctity of the lawyer-client privilege and, more
generally, to encourage clients to be candid with their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   But a prosecutor from the Whitewater independent counsel's
office who has sought the lawyer's notes for more than two years
replied that public policy favors a rule that the privilege dies
with the client.
</P>
<P>
   Although the high court put the case on an unusually fast track,
the justices appeared through their questions and comments to have
reached no easy consensus about what to do about an issue of
profound importance to the nation's lawyers: whether the
confidentiality of any conversation they have with a client
evaporates with the client's death.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the justices' comments conveyed a reluctance to carve
out any new exception to the privilege that could chill relations
between lawyers and their clients. But some of the justices also
greeted with skepticism the notion of a sacrosanct and eternal
privilege, one in which the dead would have a final say over the
living and which could rob investigators of evidence that they
would otherwise be able to obtain were a client alive and able to
testify.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia, for instance, told Foster's lawyer,
James Hamilton, that the exceptions to the lawyer-client privilege
already ``swallow up the rule,'' and that therefore there was not
much left for his client.
</P>
<P>
   ``Courts like to get at the truth,'' Scalia later added, echoing
a line from the independent counsel's brief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Courts like to get to the truth,'' Hamilton replied. ``But
privileges serve a transcendent purpose. If we have a rule that
says a privilege will be broken any time a grand jury needs to
prove who may have committed a crime, the privilege will be of very
little value.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's adversary, Brett Kavanaugh, had no easier a time.
When Kavanaugh told the justices that they could presume that most
people would not object to their conversations with lawyers being
made public after death because of a civic obligation to be
truthful with grand juries, Justice David Souter did not buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a great many people who may not want to fulfill''
those obligations, Souter said. ``We're being realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster was the deputy White House counsel and a close friend of
both President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton when he committed
suicide on July 20, 1993. Nine days earlier, he had met for two
hours with Hamilton at his home for a legal consultation. At the
time, Foster was deeply concerned about the way the White House had
handled the dismissal of the staff of the travel office.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton took three pages of notes during the session. Nearly
two and a half years later, a federal grand jury issued a subpoena
for them. The independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, has been
investigating both the travel office incident and the death of
Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, a divided federal appeals panel here ruled that in
criminal investigations involving a dead witness, the witness'
discussions with his lawyer are no longer absolutely protected. The
court said that the need for confidentiality must be balanced
against the needs of investigators and the general availability of
the information in other places.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, a qualified privilege that struck a middle ground
between the absolute positions of Hamilton and the independent
counsel, was the first time that a federal court had carved out an
exception to the attorney-client privilege in criminal cases after
a client's death. Although most courts around the nation have found
an exception to the privilege in cases where an estate is being
contested, there is virtually no case law on the issue before the
court in the Foster matter.
</P>
<P>
   While the American Bar Association, the National Association of
Criminal Defense Lawyers and the American College of Trial lawyers,
among other lawyer groups, have lined up in arguing for a
continuation of the privilege after death, the majority of those
legal scholars who have addressed the issue support either no
privilege after death or a qualified one that prosecutors may
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton Monday made a strategic concession that could earn him
the crucial vote he might need. Before Monday, his argument for an
airtight privilege was most vulnerable in those instances where a
client, before dying, had confessed to a lawyer about a crime for
which another person was then accused.
</P>
<P>
   But in response to a question by Justice Sandra Day O'Connor,
Hamilton Monday all but abandoned a privilege in such instances.
</P>
<P>
   Justice O'Connor, who formerly served as a lawyer, lawmaker and
state judge in Arizona, had raised the issue in connection with an
Arizona case in which William Macumber had faced a trial for a
double murder to which a deceased client had confessed to his
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   A trial judge held that the client's conversations were
privileged and could not be introduced in trial. A deeply divided
Arizona Supreme Court upheld that ruling, but reversed the
conviction on other grounds. Macumber was convicted on retrial at
which the alleged confession was also not admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In extreme positions where a defendant's rights are infringed
upon, a court might consider an exception,'' Hamilton said. ``That
is not this case. Here we have a prosecutor and a grand jury
seeking not specific information to exonerate anyone but seeking
all relevant information to consider prosecutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Kavanaugh sought to capitalize on the concession, observing that
by yielding in that instance, Hamilton was implicitly conceding
that the actual chilling effect posed by any exception would be
slight.
</P>
<P>
   But Chief Justice William Rehnquist acknowledged that for all
the arguments about chilling effects, the court was ill-equipped to
conclude what impact a ruling might have on relations between
lawyers and their clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is woeful dirth of any empirical research'' showing what
impact an exception might have, Rehnquist lamented.
</P>
<P>
   A decision in the case, Swidler &AMP; Berlin and James Hamilton vs.
United States, is expected before the court completes its term in
the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
