<SLUG> BC-DALTON-RESIGNATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVY SECRETARY JOHN DALTON RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Navy Secretary John Dalton, who cleaned up the
aftermath of the Tailhook sex scandal and integrated women sailers
into combat roles, announced Monday that he will resign at the end
of year.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton, 56, held the post of the Navy Department's top civilian
for five years, an unusually long tenure in the job. He didn't
spell out his plans for the future but said he would return to
private life.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton issued a statement accepting the resignation
and praising Dalton.
</P>
<P>
   ``His business acumen has helped to streamline and strengthen
operations, and he has worked ceaselessly to extend opportunity to
every sailor and Marine, helping draw strength from our rich
diversity,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen lauded Dalton for helping women
and minorities in the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``You expanded opportunities for women in the Navy by opening
combat aircraft and other jobs to them,'' Cohen said. ``You also
have worked hard and successfully to recruit more minorities into
the officer ranks of both the Navy and Marine Corps.''
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of the U.S. Naval Academy and officer aboard nuclear
submarines, Dalton said he plans to devote his remaining months in
office to sailor recruiting issues, the creation of a Navy ethics
center and ratification of the law-of-the-sea treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has been in search of a replacement since late
last year, officials said, noting that the other military service
secretaries who were appointed in Clinton's first term have since
departed.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., the chairman of the Senate Armed
Services Committee, said Dalton ``will not be an easy man to
replace and the Clinton administration has lost a true asset.''
</P>
<P>
   One candidate often mentioned as a successor was Rep. Paul
McHale, D-Pa., a retiring third-term representative and a former
Marine officer.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's staff had contacted McHale about the position in
December and by January had indicated that the lawmaker was the
first choice to succeed Dalton. McHale's name subsequently went to
the White House for final consideration, according to an official
who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   However, McHale took himself out of the running in April after
Dalton signaled he wouldn't be leaving anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   If McHale was reconsidering, he didn't let on Monday. He said in
a statement that Dalton ``has navigated the Navy through some very
rough seas.''
</P>
<P>
   As Navy secretary, Dalton presided over the service during a
time of tumult and tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his first major acts as the Navy civilian chief, he
fired Adm. Frank Kelso, the chief of naval operations at the time
of the Tailhook scandal, the 1991 aviator convention in Las Vegas
in which Navy and Marine fliers sexually assaulted several women.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton was later overruled by then-Defense Secretary Les Aspin
and Kelso was allowed to finish out his term.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton also inherited fallout from a 1992 cheating scandal at
the U.S. Naval Academy, after which lawmakers and pundits began to
question whether the Navy was rife with problems.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most tragic period of his tenure occurred when
Adm. Jeremy Boorda, Kelso's successor, committed suicide in 1996
after a reporter raised questions about whether Boorda deserved
several military medals.
</P>
<P>
   Although he didn't specifically mention the Tailhook scandal,
Dalton made several allusions to that incident in a resignation
statement he read at the Pentagon briefing room.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton said he had worked to achieve two major goals as Navy
secretary: To raise the Navy's standards of conduct and to improve
the Navy's operational readiness as a time when it was undergoing
budget cuts in the post-Cold War era.
</P>
<P>
   He said his administration has worked ``to restore the dignity
and respect with which our people treat one another.'' He said he
made it clear ``that we had no room in the Navy Department for
anyone who treated their shipmates with anything less than dignity
and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the Navy and Marines have become a team, a result
of moving the top Marine Corps officers into the Pentagon from
separate headquarters a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton said he planned to leave the job at yearend but was
making his resignation announcement now so that the Senate could
confirm his successor before he departs.
</P>
<P>
   In his resignation letter to Clinton, Dalton praised his boss
and declared that ``no president since Franklin Delano Roosevelt, a
former assistant secretary of the Navy, has been aboard more Navy
ships'' than Clinton has.
</P>
<P>
   On a personal note, Dalton praised his wife, Margaret, as the
``best `First Lady' of the Navy Department'' and noted that their
two sons served as officers in the Navy and the Marine Corps during
his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to assuming the post on July 22, 1993, he ran the San
Antonio office of Stephens Inc., a Little Rock, Ark.-based
investment company. In the 1980s, he ran a Texas S&AMP;L that collapsed
during the banking crisis. He was a top Democratic fundraiser in
Texas during the 1992 presidential campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
