<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-MIR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE LEAVES MIR AFTER FINAL VISIT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ U.S. shuttle astronauts and Russian Mir cosmonauts
parted company for the final time Monday amid embraces and promises
to rejoin one another aboard a new international space station.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle Discovery pushed away from Mir's docking port at
11:01 a.m., CDT, as the two spacecraft soared high over southern
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's departure brought to a close a three-year program of
nine shuttle docking missions to the Russian space station,
initiated to prepare for the assembly of a new global station.
</P>
<P>
   Construction is scheduled to begin later this year. The Russians
have pledged to scuttle the nearly 13-year-old Mir once crews
establish residency on the new station, probably before the end of
1999.
</P>
<P>
   As the shuttle prepared to push away, the nine astronauts and
cosmonauts gathered at the hatches of the two spacecraft for an
emotional farewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way can we stop the cooperation that started with this
program,'' said Discovery commander Charles Precourt. ``We've got
to keep going together in the future. We're really happy to be
leaping off in that direction with the international space
station.''
</P>
<P>
   As a parting gift, Mir commander Talgat Musabayev presented the
shuttle crew with the massive wrench that he and cosmonaut Nikolai
Budarin employed during a series of April spacewalks to install a
new steering thruster on their orbital outpost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie, take this wrench,'' said Musabayev. ``This wrench is
planned to be flown to the international space station. It's sort
of a relay (baton) from an old lady, station Mir, to the
international space station. Let's hope this wrench will be
successfully used in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle crew also gathered an acoustic guitar from Mir, a
gift presented by a U.S. team of astronauts in November 1995.
Musabayev strummed Beatles tunes on the instrument.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the final U.S. shuttle voyage allowed the
Discovery crew to pick up Andy Thomas, the seventh and final
American resident of Mir.
</P>
<P>
   During the program's course, shuttle and Mir crews exchanged
nearly 30 tons of food, clothing, fresh water and other supplies
that permitted Russia to maintain the aging outpost despite a
faltering economy. Dozens of scientists attempted experiments in
disciplines ranging from medicine and biotechnology to Earth
observation.
</P>
<P>
   The program was rocked last year, first by a flash fire aboard
Mir and then by a collision with an out-of-control Russian Progress
cargo capsule. NASA elected to complete its mission plans, though
some lawmakers and critics of the policy argued the program had
become too risky.
</P>
<P>
   An assortment of U.S. equipment remained aboard Mir but out of
reach in the station's Spektr science module, which was punctured
by the June 25, 1997, collision.
</P>
<P>
   The module was hastily sealed off as it decompressed. Stowed
inside are a large freezer, a small centrifuge and other equipment
for the collection, analysis and preservation of medical specimens;
an exercise bicycle; and the personal effects of U.S. astronaut
Mike Foale, who was using the module as his living quarters at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Also remaining behind is the docking module attached to Mir by a
shuttle crew in November 1995 to serve as a permanent berth for
U.S. spacecraft as well as an assortment of books, video and music
tapes ferried up by astronauts for their recreation.
</P>
<P>
   As the two spacecraft separated Monday, the astronauts and
cosmonauts joined in a final carefully choreographed experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery pilot Dominic Gorie eased the shuttle to a point 240
feet in front of Mir while the cosmonauts flooded the damaged
Spektr with a greenish tracer gas. The idea was to find the
puncture by watching for the gas.
</P>
<P>
   Precourt told mission control there was nothing visible but that
a light intensifying camera operated by astronaut Franklin
Chang-Diaz may have recorded something.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to review that film,'' Precourt informed
controllers.
</P>
<P>
   The first shuttle docking mission was launched in June 1995.
Discovery is scheduled to land Friday at the Kennedy Space Center
in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
