<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-UNREST-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSIONS RISE AS SETTLERS MOVE INTO ARAB NEIGHBORHOOD  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL GREENBERG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Expanding their foothold in East Jerusalem, Jewish
settlers moved into four homes in an Arab neighborhood early Monday
morning, setting off a violent confrontation and heightening
tension in an area claimed by Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Acting under cover of darkness, members of the settlement group
Elad entered homes that they said they had acquired in Silwan, a
village outside Jerusalem's walled Old City. They removed
furniture, spread coils of barbed wire and raised Israeli flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our aim is to Judaize East Jerusalem,'' declared Yigal
Kaufman, a spokesman for Elad, which has bought properties and
moved Jews into Silwan in recent years, sometimes displacing Arab
tenants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The City of David is the most ancient core of Jerusalem, and
we want it to become a Jewish neighborhood,'' Kaufman added, using
the biblical name for the Silwan area, which was the site of the
Israelite city of Jerusalem ruled by King David.
</P>
<P>
   A clash broke out at one house when a group of Palestinians
arrived with Israeli peace advocates and removed barbed wire.
Witnesses said that settlers had lashed out with sticks and that
the Palestinians had thrown stones. Two settlers were assaulted,
and Faisal Husseini, a Palestinian cabinet member responsible for
Jerusalem affairs, was slightly hurt. Israeli protesters from the
Peace Now movement were forcibly evicted by police officers.
</P>
<P>
   The settlers had moved into the homes with the advance knowledge
and protection of the Israeli police, raising charges that they
were tacitly backed by the Israeli authorities. ``The entry was
legal,'' a police spokesman said. ``The houses belong to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians and Israeli peace advocates accused Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Mayor Ehud Olmert of Jerusalem of complicity
in what they described as a calculated political provocation. But
aides to Netanyahu and Olmert denied any prior knowledge of the
settlers' action, saying the Jews had simply moved into homes that
were legally theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu and Olmert are staunch supporters of Jewish settlement
in East Jerusalem, and assert that the area, captured from Jordan
in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war, will forever remain part of Israel's
undivided capital. The Palestinians claim East Jerusalem as the
capital of their hoped-for state and view any Jewish settlement
there as an obstacle to a future peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prime minister's office was not party to the organization
and planning of the entry to those houses,'' Danny Naveh, the
Israeli Cabinet secretary, told the Israeli army radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all legal requirements regarding acquisition of the houses
have indeed been met,'' Naveh added, ``I see no reason, from the
point of view of the government and the prime minister, why those
people cannot be in the City of David.''
</P>
<P>
   A statement from Olmert's office asserted that the entry of the
settlers was ``a private matter'' that did not require the city's
intervention, because the Jews were exercising their legal
ownership. Olmert had no idea of the settlers' intentions and
learned of their action over the radio, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians remained unconvinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Netanyahu's office and the municipality are involved, and they
encourage these people to do these things,'' said Ziyad Abu Zayyad,
a Palestinian lawmaker from East Jerusalem. ``This is a political
entry. These people are not coming to live quietly. They want to
create political facts.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While three of the homes appeared to have been sold indirectly
to the settlers, a fourth building was officially transferred to
them after its Palestinian owner was declared an ``absentee'' who
had forfeited his property rights. The owner, Muhammad Karaeen, was
not in East Jerusalem during an Israeli census there after the 1967
war, and lost an appeal to the Israeli Supreme Court last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a cynical use of an unfair law,'' said Jawad Boulous,
a lawyer for Karaeen. ``The first priority should have been the
real owner of the house and his daughter, who has been living there
for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Elad says it has moved 17 Jewish families into seven housing
compounds in Silwan in recent years, and has already acquired
additional properties there.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad Shaaban, a Palestinian lawyer who lives near one of the
houses taken over Monday, said he feared that his own home might be
next.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a strategy, and they are implementing it in
stages,'' he said. ``They always say they are doing it by the law,
but what law? Law that discriminates and protects power and
violence is not a law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
