<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9786 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-HARASS-2TAKES-N     06-08 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-HARASS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S.-BASED CHINESE HARASSED BY POLICE ON VISITS HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ark., Calif.)  (mk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOLEDO, Ohio _ Ciping Huang was always known among her neighbors
in the Chinese city of Hefei as a dutiful daughter. And in the 13
years since she arrived in the United States, initially to study
science at the University of Toledo, she returned home as often as
she could. There had never been a problem with the police during
her five earlier trips to China.
</P>
<P>
   But during a long-planned vacation home this April, Ms. Huang
was allowed almost no time with her parents. Instead, the
36-year-old engineer found herself locked in a police interrogation
room for days, with plainclothed officers threatening to jail her _
and even hinting that she could face execution _ unless she
detailed her ties to dissidents in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said I had done things damaging to Chinese national
security and had broken the security laws, which can carry the
death penalty,'' Ms. Huang said. ``They said they could arrest
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Police deported her from China on April 19, allowing her 20
minutes to say a final goodbye to her aged parents. Now, safely
back in Ohio, where she lives with her American husband, Ms. Huang
said she is certain why she is being threatened by her government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a lot to do with Clinton,'' said Ms. Huang, vice
chairman of the Independent Federation of Chinese Students and
Scholars, which represents thousands of Chinese living in the
United States. ``They want to have a good image during Clinton's
trip to China. They want to give the world a good impression of
China. So they don't want any protests anywhere, in China or
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups and organizations representing students and
other Chinese citizens living in the United States say they have
received reports of at least a dozen incidents in recent weeks in
which Chinese visiting their homeland have been taken into custody,
interrogated or threatened by police.
</P>
<P>
   The harassment, they say, is clearly related to President
Clinton's trip to China this month. They say the Beijing government
is trying to send a message to Chinese living in the United States
that they must not organize protests here of Clinton's visit, the
first by an American president since the 1989 crackdown on
democracy demonstrators in Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   ''This may be a way of intimidating activists both in the U.S.
and in China who might try to speak out about the president's visit
_ and a way of closing down channels of communications in the
democracy movement,'' said Mike Jendrzejczyk, Washington director
of Human Rights Watch Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups say they have no way of determining the
exact number of these incidents in China; most of the victims, they
say, are afraid to report what happened to them after their return
to the United States, for fear that publicity could bring
retalation against their families.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know this has happened to several people, but they don't
want to talk about it openly because of their families,'' said
Jinghong Li, a software engineer in Los Angeles who is chairman of
the Independent Federation, a Washington-based group that was
founded as a result of the 1989 crackdown and organizes public
protests in the United States against the Chinese government.
''They can leave China, but their families stay behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with eight Chinese students and scholars who returned
to the United States from China over the last several months offers
evidence of a pattern: The visiting Chinese are detained, sometimes
for days, and questioned intensely about their involvement _ real
or imagined _ in the dissident movement in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Chinese do have close ties to the dissident
community here, while others do not. All insisted that their recent
visits to China were routine trips to see their families and
friends and were not intended to goad the Chinese government ahead
of Clinton's trip. Four of those interviewed agreed to be
identified by name, even though they said they feared their actions
would have repercussions to their families.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups say there was a similar pattern just before
President Jiang Zemin's state visit to the United States last
October.
</P>
<P>
   Xiang Qian Chang, an assistant professor of mathematics at the
Massachusetts College of Pharmacy in Boston, said he was called in
for an interrogation by police during a trip home to Beijing last
August, two months before Zemin's visit, and warned against
organizing protests in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said that President Jiang Zemin was going to the United
States and they said, Don't you go out and demonstrate,''' he said.
``I think they were very worried about the success of President
Jiang Zemin's trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Bangzheng Chen, a molecular biologist who has been in the United
States since 1985 and now works for the Food and Drug
Administration at a research center in Arkansas, said that he
visited China this March to see his 85-year-old mother and to
''visit with some old friends _ that was the only purpose of my
trip.''
</P>
<P>
   But a week after arriving in China, he received a phone call
''from some national security agents who said they knew I was back
in China,'' said Chen, who had last visited his homeland in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ''They said they wanted to see me,'' he said. ``I was surprised.
I felt a little bit nervous, because that was the first time in my
entire life that I had been called by a secret policeman.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They came by and picked me up immediately,'' he recalled. ''I
think there were three guys _ plainclothed, early 30s maybe, very
serious. They show me their identification. It says 'national
security bureau.'''
</P>
<P>
   Chen said that he was placed in an unmarked black car and driven
across town to a luxury hotel, the Jin Jiang, where the security
police had taken a room on the 32nd floor. For the next seven
hours, he said, he was interrogated about his ties to organizations
of Chinese students and scholars in the United States, most
importantly the Independent Federation, which has long been an
irritant to the Beijing government.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ''They know a lot about almost every member in the group,'' he
said. ''They knew the names. They knew more names than I did. They
asked me what role these people played in the organizations. All
the details. You name it. I told them I wasn't so involved. I said
I didn't have a lot to offer them.''
</P>
<P>
   But police were not satisfied with his answers, he said, and so
he was picked up again several days later and interrogated for
another three hours to four hours.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't want to go, but I had to go,'' he said. ''They told
me that they didn't want me to do stupid things in the United
States. It was clear to me that they didn't want anything to happen
to interrupt any honeymoon between Jiang Zemin and Clinton. They
are worried that we will do something outside of China that will
embarrass them.''
</P>
<P>
   Xiaorong Li, who holds a doctorate in philosophy from Stanford
University and has been in the United States for 10 years, went
home to China to see her parents in early April _ and was allowed
to remain in the country for less than a day.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Li, who became an American citizen two years ago and is
active in human-rights organizations in the United States, said
that she was picked up by police only 40 minutes after arriving at
her parent's home in the central province of Sichuan. She had
traveled to China on a tourist visa.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a knock at the door and my brother opened it,'' she
said. ''There were three men. One was older, maybe 50ish, and two
younger persons. And they said, 'We need to take you over to the
public security station.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Li was put into a police car and driven more than five hours
to an interrogation center in Chengdu, the provincial capial. ''You
shouldn't be doing this,'' she recalled telling the policemen in
the car. ''I need to say goodbye to my parents. I have to call the
U.S. consolate in Chengdu, and they basically ignored me and kept
driving.''
</P>
<P>
   When she arrived in Chengdu shortly before dawn, she said, she
was met by 10 police officers dressed in Western-style business
suits ''and one guy started videotaping me from the moment I
stepped out of the car _ they were very vicious, as if they had
caught a big criminal, and began ordering me around and shouting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept asking me questions like who I came into China with,
what was our plan, what did I want to do,'' she said. ''They asked
me what activities did I engage in in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Li pointed out that she was an American citizen and had
the right under international law to consult with American
diplomats, ''they said that it did not matter about my nationality
because anyone who breaks the law in China will be punished under
Chinese law.''
</P>
<P>
   The questioning lasted for about an hour, and her luggage was
searched as she watched on, helpless to stop them. She said she was
then hurriedly driven to the Chengdu airport, where she was put on
a plane bound for Hong Kong, the former British colony that, while
now part of China, maintains separate borders. Ms. Li said she was
told never to return to her homeland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
