<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CONRAL-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      CONRAIL DEAL APPROVED
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 8 -- Conrail's fate was effectively sealed
Monday when the U.S. Surface Transportation Board voted to approve
the $10.2 billion takeover of the Philadelphia rail cargo company
by two Virginia-based competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The vote assures the end of Conrail's 21-year run as the sole
rail shipper in the Northeast, replacing it with measured
competition between CSX Inc. of Richmond and Norfolk Southern of
Norfolk, Va. The deal is also expected to eliminate 1,900 jobs in
Philadelphia, mostly administrative tasks that were either made
redundant by the merger or transferred to other CSX and Norfolk
Southern offices.
</P>
<P>
   Winning approval from the Surf Board, as the agency is called,
was the last federal hurdle for CSX and Norfolk Southern. The board
will issue a formal written opinion July 23, and one month later
the take-over will be official -- although both rail companies must
still negotiate labor agreements with Conrail employee unions.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the board members were swayed by the idea of
injecting competition into the rail cargo industry. ``Shippers
throughout the East will have more options than they have had in
decades,'' said Linda Morgan, chairwoman of the Surf Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do hear in the long run will achieve the greatest good
while minimizing the harm,'' said Gus Owen, vice chairman of the
board.
</P>
<P>
   Owen and Morgan, who are the only members of the board while
they await the appointment of a presidential nominee, did, however,
vote to impose some conditions to the deal and promised to keep a
watchful eye out to ensure its progress.
</P>
<P>
   At the recommendation of the board's staff, they imposed a
five-year review period of the merger and called for detailed
weekly reports, in part a response to the disastrous gridlock out
West from the last big rail merger, between Union Pacific Corp
purchased Southern Pacific Rail Corp. two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although CSX and Norfolk Southern did not approve of the
conditions set by the board, neither company said they would be
deal breakers. ``The STB has applied unprecedented conditions,''
said John W. Snow, CEO of CSX. ``Had they gone any further, we
would have been forced to question going forward with the
transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to wait and be able to study (the conditions),'' said
Frank Brown, spokesman for Norfolk Southern.
</P>
<P>
   The deal had its share of critics, including Sen. Arlen Specter,
R-Pa., a member of the committee that funds the Surf Board. In
prepared testimony for last week's hearings on the deal, Specter
joined a chorus of doubters who questioned whether the $10.2
billion price for Conrail would cause CSX and Norfolk Southern to
increase rates to cover their costs.
</P>
<P>
   A bidding war erupted between CSX and Norfolk Southern last year
when Norfolk Southern tried to scuttle a friendly merger between
Conrail and CSX, driving up the cost of Conrail's stock to $115 per
share once the joint take-over was announced. Specter has favored
the friendly take-over, which would have led to fewer job losses in
Conrail's Center City headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   And the AFL-CIO has attacked board member Owen, individually,
for alleged ethical conflicts of interest with his private business
dealings in California, and the board, as a whole, for not taking
action against rail companies who break labor contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But most other state and federal lawmakers eventually lent their
support to the CSX and Norfolk Southern take-over, including Gov.
Tom Ridge, Philadelphia Mayor Ed Rendell and U.S. Rep. Bud Shuster,
R-Pa., chairman of the House Transportation Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Surf Board and its staff rejected the idea that costs would
soar because of the $10.2 billion price tag, instead asserting that
rates would most likely drop because of the competition between CSX
and Norfolk Southern. ``Overall, shippers will be better off than
before the merger,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   And management contends that out of 73,00 jobs currently held by
the three rail companies, the net loss of jobs will be just 1,900
when the deal is completed -- about the same rate as attrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Conrail employees will not know anything different other
than the logo on their paycheck,'' Brown, of Norfolk Southern,
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
