<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS KEEP THEIR EYES ON THE PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like mountain climbers afraid of heights, the Yankees
don't want to look down. They don't want to look around, to check
out the view from their lofty perch in the standings. Joe Torre,
the manager, walks out of the room if others start comparing and
contrasting his team's incredible record with other standards in
history.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte once glanced at daily notes dispensed by the team,
then quickly pushed them away when he saw a comparison of the
Yankees of 1998 and the Yankees of 1928. Tim Raines is curious, but
he would rather wait until October to discuss how good this team
really is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to have some accomplishments during the
season,'' Raines said, ``but it doesn't mean anything until you get
to the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, 44-13 and already 12 games ahead of second-place
Boston in the loss column, would rather keep their blinders on and
focus on their very next step. The cliche is in effect: One day at
a time, and right now that means playing the Montreal Expos in the
first game of a three-game series at Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about it, it really is easier to play that
way,'' Torre said. ``You start thinking about the numbers and then
you begin applying expectations and you start trying to do too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   They just do what they need to do, each day. Torre says he has
never been around a group of players who better understand why they
are successful, and are determined to keep doing the things that
make them win. For Pettitte, that means 20 minutes of
cardiovascular work and heavy weight training the day after he
pitches. For Chuck Knoblauch, the second baseman, that means
maintaining a strict diet and workout regimen and drinking lots of
water. Mariano Rivera does not use weights, but he runs regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is amazing, when you look around here,'' catcher Joe
Girardi said. ``It's the healthiest team I've ever been around.''
</P>
<P>
   Girardi's example would be as good as any. About three and a
half hours before a night game, Girardi stretches, then goes to the
Yankees' indoor batting cage to hit balls off a tee. He stretches
again a half-hour later, before the team batting practice. After
hitting, he retreats to the bullpen to work on blocking balls in
the dirt, framing pitches and taking short-hopped throws at the
plate. He might catch a pitcher's bullpen session, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   He stretches again before the Yankees take infield practice
about an hour before the game. More stretching, then he goes to the
batting cage with the batting coach Chris Chambliss to hit balls
tossed softly to him. At 7:10 for a 7:35 game, he goes to the
outfield for five sprints of 40 yards, then plays catch, and, on
the days he plays, he begins catching the starting pitcher in the
bullpen at exactly 7:23. Routine.
</P>
<P>
   Three or four times a week after games, Girardi will head to the
weight room and lift for about 30 minutes to strengthen his chest,
shoulders, legs, back and arms. If he is tired, he may break up his
workout and finish it the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi is hardly unusual. After most every game, a platoon of
Yankees will head to the weight room, Knoblauch, Chad Curtis,
Darryl Strawberry and Paul O'Neill among them. Raines never lifts _
he is thickly built, and feels additional muscles would only reduce
his flexibility _ but is devoted to stretching, before games, after
games, during games. Just keep warm and stretch.
</P>
<P>
   They win, they work out. They lose, they work out. Routine. Just
look ahead. Never look down.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are finishing a stretch of 10 games against four
struggling teams: the Chicago White Sox, the Tampa Bay Devil Rays,
the Florida Marlins and the Montreal Expos. The Yankees have won
the first seven, without lapses in concentration. They have won 43
of their last 52 games.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte said Saturday: ``We've got a lot of guys who take pride
in doing their jobs. That's what was so frustrating for me for a
while, because I felt like I wasn't doing my job. That's what we're
concentrating on, just doing our jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams is doing his job, driving in 30 runs in his last
26 games. Graeme Lloyd is doing his job, retiring 27 of 29 batters
over a period of 12 appearances. David Cone and David Wells, both
8-1, have not lost since the first week of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Chili Davis got hurt, and in his place, Strawberry has a
team-high nine homers and Raines is batting .297. Tino Martinez got
hurt, and the Yankees went 9-1. They are 4-0 since Derek Jeter went
on the disabled list. Cone was bitten on the finger by his mother's
dog, and Orlando Hernandez pitched in his place and won. Wells'
shoulder felt sore, and Cone pitched and won in his place. Rivera
was on the disabled list, and Mike Stanton saved five games.
</P>
<P>
   The team is on a pace to win 125 games, which would be a record
in this century.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we can't worry about that right now,'' Pettitte said.
``We've been very good, but when you start talking about greatest
teams in history, that's getting a little carried away, 50 to 60
games into the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The schedule will harden, beginning Friday. Three games against
Cleveland, which leads the American League Central. Then three in
Baltimore, four in Cleveland, then four games in four days against
Atlanta _ two in Yankee Stadium June 22-23, two down south, June
24-25. And three games against the revitalized Mets, June 26-28.
</P>
<P>
   They will not look far ahead, Pettitte said. They will not look
behind. They will just focus on what is in front of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1931EDT &QL; 
