<SLUG> BC-AUTO-POLLUTE-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONDA AND FORD TO PAY FINES FOR POLLUTION VIOLATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Japan)  (lb) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Honda will pay a record environmental fine, federal
prosecutors announced Monday, for programming the pollution-control
computers in 1.6 million of its cars to ignore spark-plug failures,
allowing the cars to emit twice as much smog-causing hydrocarbons
without warning their drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. will also pay a fine, the officials said, for
selling 60,000 Econoline vans with a secret feature that makes them
emit more nitrogen oxides at highway speeds than they do on
treadmill tests, a design that was intended to improve fuel economy
but means more smog.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making very clear that cars are a major source of air
pollution in this country and it is important for auto
manufacturers to assure they are carefully complying with the Clean
Air Act,'' said Lois Schiffer, an assistant attorney general and
head of the Justice Department's environment and natural resources
division. ``If they don't do it, we will take strong action against
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Honda agreed to pay a civil penalty of $12.6 million, which the
Justice Department said was a record under the Clean Air Act. The
company will perform free tune-ups on the cars, which are from the
1995, 1996 and 1997 model years.
</P>
<P>
   Honda will also extend the warranty on the pollution-control
systems to 14 years or 150,000 miles. Depending on which part was
involved and where the car was sold, the existing warranties ranged
from three years or 36,000 miles to eight years or 80,000 miles.
The Justice Department said that the remedial actions would cost
Honda $250 million, but the company said it did not know the cost,
because no one had ever guaranteed car parts for so long.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement is a stunning blow to Honda, which in
advertising and public statements has portrayed itself as an
environmental leader and has voluntarily put extra equipment on
hundreds of thousands of vehicles to make sure that they meet
California's strict emission standards, even if they are sold in
states around the country that enforce the more lax federal
standard.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a blow to Ford, which voluntarily exceeds emissions
rules on many of its models.
</P>
<P>
   The software in the Hondas is burned into the computer chips,
and to reprogram them they would have to be replaced, at a price
the government put at $500 million. The package that Honda agreed
to _ including free oil changes, to lure drivers in for their free
tune-ups _ was more effective, the EPA said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the largest previous case was the $45 million in
fines and remedial actions that General Motors agreed to in 1995
for producing Cadillacs that passed emissions tests but violated
pollution standards on the road. That case was one of a very small
number of pollution-compliance cases brought against automakers by
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar case that is still under way, the EPA has
discovered that hundreds of thousands of heavy-duty diesel trucks
give off much more pollution in normal highway use than they do in
the tests they must pass to be certified for sale.
</P>
<P>
   In the Honda case, EPA estimated that uncorrected, the cars _
Civics, Accords, Del Sols, Integras, Preludes, NSXs and CR-Vs,
Odysseys and their Isuzu-brand twin, the Oasis _ would emit 8
million extra tons of hydrocarbons in their lifetimes. Total
emission of hydrocarbons from all transportation sources was about
10 million tons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also said that the cars can grow sluggish without
warning the driver that something is wrong, and that if a driver
takes one to a garage, the mechanic will have a harder time
diagnosing the problem.
</P>
<P>
   In the other case announced Monday, Ford has begun a recall of
the Econolines. It will pay $2.5 million in civil penalties,
purchase pollution credits from other sources for another $2.5
million, and spend $1.3 million on fixing the Econolines, with a
goal of completing the work on at least 70 percent of them.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ford and Honda, notified of the problems early last year,
have corrected them for vehicles now in production.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Honda problem was discovered by officials of the California
Air Resources Board, which serves as the federal EPA's surrogate
for certifying that Hondas meet federal standards. The California
board tested one vehicle that had been on the road for several
months, and found that it did not diagnose engine misfires, in
which the fuel-air mixture fails to explode and is shoved out the
exhaust system, sometimes damaging the catalytic converter on the
way.
</P>
<P>
   On closer examination, California engineers found the system was
designed not to work.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement covers all of the Honda and Accura vehicles built
in the 1996 and '97 model years, with the exception of Passport and
SLX, and 1997 Integra R. For 1995 models, it covers the Accord V-6
and the Accura NSX, 2.5 TL.
</P>
<P>
   The computer software does not increase emissions; it simply
fails to light up the ``check engine'' light when parts fail and
emissions rise. It also allows the cars to perform sluggishly
without the ``check engine'' light coming on.
</P>
<P>
   David Alexander, an attorney with the EPA's enforcement
division, said that suppressing the dashboard warning light made
life harder for all drivers, even those who are relatively
knowledgeable about cars. ``The idiot lights are for all of us,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Honda said, though, that the problem was simply one
of interpretation of the rules, and that the vehicles' diagnostic
systems would function if the problem was serious. The lawyer,
William Willen, said the problem was that his company's engineers
had gone too far in their attempts to minimize the number of times
the light came on.
</P>
<P>
   Willen said in a telephone interview that the only time the
dashboard light would fail to illuminate was in times of
intermittent failure.
</P>
<P>
   Honda said owners with questions could call its Consumer Affairs
Department at (800) 999-1009.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
