<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-WOMAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS FAIL TO DETER TEXAS CHURCH FROM HIRING WOMAN AS PASTOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: San Francisco) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Sunday sidewalk protest by dozens of followers of the
ultra-conservative Rev. W.N. Otwell will not keep a Baptist church
in Waco, Texas, from hiring its first female senior pastor, church
leaders said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The protest at Calvary Baptist Church came just one week after
church members voted to become the first Southern Baptist
congregation in Texas with a woman pastor. The 300-member church
has several women in other, secondary ministerial positions.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Julie Pennington-Russell, now senior pastor at the 19th
Avenue Baptist Church in San Francisco, will assume her Waco duties
in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are excited about our new pastor,'' said search committee
chairman Tom Purdy. ``We believe we have acted in the holy
spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of the Calvary congregation, he said,
``believes that men and women share equally the gifts of God.'' He
said he was not aware of any members who were quitting in protest.
</P>
<P>
   At least 30 members of Otwell's fundamentalist God Said
Ministries of Mount Enterprise positioned themselves outside the
church, bearing placards reading, ``Women have no authority,''
``Working women equal moral corruption; working mothers equal child
abuse,'' and ``The spirit of Jezebel; today's `liberated woman' is
under her control.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2 1/2-hour protest, led by Otwell's construction worker son,
Rocky Otwell, was peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   Although the group was not invited, the younger Otwell said a
number of church members confided to protesters that the
congregation is divided over the new pastor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were older members,'' he said. ``They've been there all
their lives. Where are they to go? What are they supposed to do?
Maybe we encouraged them, showed them that if they don't agree
maybe things can be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Church education minister Howard Williams said all the
protesters seemed to be with Otwell's organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes as no surprise that this departure from scriptural
authority has happened in Waco, since Waco's Baylor University, a
Baptist school, has, for years, been one of the main leaders
promoting liberalism of the scriptures and worldliness,'' W.N.
Otwell said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the problems in our nation's homes, schools,
political system and economy have been brought on by the feminist
movement, which has promoted women's liberation and has pressured
most of American women out of the home where God ordained them to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church and this people have sinned and must be held
responsible for their crime against God, the home, the husband, the
children and society as a whole. Women need to go home and leave
preaching, ruling, leading, providing and protecting to the men.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvary Baptist, which received advance notification of the
protest, ``understands and prizes freedom of speech,'' Purdy said.
``We respect the autonomy of local churches.''
</P>
<P>
   Otwell, who has espoused white supremacist and anti-gay views,
is pastor of Heritage Baptist Church near Mount Enterprise, north
of Nacogdoches. He previously clashed with the city of Fort Worth,
which tried to keep him from distributing food to the poor that was
prepared in uninspected kitchens. He also picketed Nacogdoches City
Hall after that community replaced the Confederate battle flag with
the Confederate ``Stars and Bars'' on the police department logo.
</P>
<P>
   Pennington-Russell, 37, senior pastor at the San Francisco
church since 1993, came with high recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot imagine a wiser choice knowing your church,'' the
Rev. George Mason, pastor of Dallas' Wilshire Baptist Church, told
the Waco congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is thoroughly Baptist,'' added Daniel Vestal, coordinator
of the Cooperative Baptist Fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   Pennington-Russell could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
