<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9802 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OIL-REFINERY-ART-2TAK     06-08 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-REFINERY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICK OIL REFINER IS POISED TO STRIKE IT RICH
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo and graphic are being being sent to NYT photo
and graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORCO, La. _ Rivals have tried to buy him off, creditors have
gotten high-powered lawyers to try to cow him, investors have
needled him about going through bankruptcy twice, his own son has
accused him of being a polluter and many in the energy industry
here shake their heads at the mention of his name.
</P>
<P>
   But John R. Stanley, known as Jack in the oil patch, is a hard
man to keep down.
</P>
<P>
   When the elevator was temporarily out of order at his sprawling
oil refinery here recently, Stanley, 59, bounded up nearly 300
stairs to show a visitor the view from the top of the new coking
unit. ``There's $2 billion worth of equipment here,'' Stanley
exulted as his guest fought to catch his breath.
</P>
<P>
   To hear Stanley tell it, that $2 billion worth of equipment is
his ticket to the heights of the U.S. energy market for his
privately held TransAmerican Energy Corp. By the end of the summer,
the towering coking and cracking units are expected to be going
full blast, converting 230,000 barrels of crude oil a day into
kerosene, diesel fuel, heating oil _ and 5.5 million gallons of
gasoline. It will be the largest single addition of new capacity in
domestic refining in two decades.
</P>
<P>
   This could become the jewel in Stanley's corporate crown. But
watching the 6-foot-2 man from Massachusetts stomping around the
1,000-acre complex on the banks of the Mississippi, you'd never
guess how close he came to losing it in bankruptcy proceedings that
began in 1983 and dragged on for four years.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout that battle, the refinery sat idle _ even as Stanley
deflected his creditors' demands to sell it and talked the court
into letting him spend $100 million to keep it in operating
condition.
</P>
<P>
   And that was not his first brush with financial disaster. Ten
years earlier, he had also filed for protection from creditors when
the price of ammonia plunged _ shortly after he built an ammonia
plant.
</P>
<P>
   But far from turning Stanley into the soul of prudence,
judiciously building up a cash reserve for the next rainy day,
those setbacks only spurred him to take even bigger gambles. Almost
immediately after his first bankruptcy, he poured $800 million into
an initial modernization of his refinery here. After the second, he
spent six years paying off $1.37 billion in debt and then put
together $900 million financing _ mostly in junk bonds _ to upgrade
the plant to its current state.
</P>
<P>
   But why should he show caution? For all his faults _ and critics
say he has plenty _ Stanley is that most American of characters,
the entrepreneur. And he has doggedly pursued his vision even when
others predicted disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack has more perseverance than anyone else I know,'' said Ed
Donohue, the chief financial officer for TransAmerican who has
worked for Stanley since 1977. ``He knew the value of the assets.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now: Will he strike out yet a third time, seriously
damaging the fortune he has reamassed, or will his latest gamble
provide him with even greater riches?
</P>
<P>
   One thing going for him is that the refinery will be one of just
a handful in the country that can efficiently process the thick,
low-grade oil that is produced in abundance in Mexico and Venezuela
and sells for as little as half the price of lighter crudes. That
could give Stanley a big competitive advantage regardless of what
happens to oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley has always been quick to spot a money-making
opportunity. In college in 1958, he took a job pumping gas in a
tough neighborhood of Springfield, Mass., and, after seeing how
much cash poured in, leased the station and managed it himself. To
save money, he did almost everything _ repairing cars, haggling
with suppliers and even delivering the fuel in a rented tanker
truck. On weekends, he used the rig to take his girlfriend Eileen,
now his wife of 39 years, to the movies.
</P>
<P>
   The business did so well that Stanley leased another gas
station, and then another, until by the late 1970s he had built up
one of the largest independent networks in the country, the
230-unit Gasland chain. And he continued driving his own delivery
truck.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he reacted to adversity with a decisiveness that
bordered on impulsiveness. When a gasoline supplier refused to
renew a contract in 1971, he bought the old refinery here, 1,300
miles from home, for $2.1 million because owning it gave him a
sense of security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know anything about refining, except that I wanted to
have gasoline for my stations,'' Stanley said.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, he commuted between Massachusetts and
Louisiana before moving here in 1978. With his new acquisition, 15
miles northwest of New Orleans in the middle of alligator-infested
swampland, Stanley displayed another entrepreneurial skill:
improvisation. Whenever there was a crisis, he said, he would round
up his workers _ sometimes summoning them from a local bar _ and
keep them holed up in a conference room until they figured out a
solution.
</P>
<P>
   Having bought a refinery to supply his gas stations, he decided
to go one step further and drill for oil to supply the refinery.
And he again displayed the drive that keeps some entrepreneurs
going when others would more likely throw in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   After his drillers reached the depth recommended by the experts
and announced they had hit a dry hole, Stanley told them ``to drill
the maximum that the rig could handle,'' he recalled. ``That's how
we hit that first well,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   What they hit was not oil, but natural gas. He quickly acquired
more rights in what turned out to be one of the richest gas fields
in the state, Lobo Trend.
</P>
<P>
   The revenue from that find _ though it would ultimately bail him
out of financial tight spots _ inspired yet another investment idea
that went awry, the construction of an ammonia plant. It seemed
like a smart idea, because the plant could use natural gas supplied
by Stanley, but it became a huge money loser after the price of
ammonia plunged.
</P>
<P>
   That led to the initial bankruptcy filing for his company, then
called Good Hope Refineries.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley recovered quickly from that reversal. But he was not so
fortunate in 1983, when the American energy industry was hammered
by a slide in oil and natural gas prices. After a major customer,
El Paso Natural Gas, stopped buying his natural gas, Stanley again
filed for protection from creditors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had $23,000 in the bank and a blue Jaguar,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   His banks tried to sell off his assets and hired a high-powered
law firm to persuade him to step aside. But he refused, even
spurning an offer worth up to $50 million to accept their plan for
reorganization, according to his lawyer. Some creditors accused him
of hiding assets and using the bankruptcy process to shut them out.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he won court approval to spend $100 million to maintain
the refinery. Meantime, he found idle drilling companies willing to
work for a share of the revenue from wells they struck. And they
struck enough to more than triple his gas output and allow him to
emerge from bankruptcy in 1987. By 1993 he had paid $1.37 billion
back to creditors.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of all the legal turmoil, Stanley went through a
wrenching personal ordeal, a dispute with his son, William, that
led to a permanent rupture. After the son disclosed that he had
taken a part interest in companies that were doing business with
his father's company, the elder Stanley dismissed him and later
disowned him.
</P>
<P>
   The son subsequently publicly accused his father of illegally
dumping toxic waste and of bribing Louisiana state officials. The
state investigated the charges but found no evidence of wrongdoing.
In 1996, the Florida Department of Law Enforcement indicted
Stanley's son on charges of defrauding wholesalers out of at least
$175,000, and it is currently seeking his extradition from Spain, a
department spokesman said. His lawyer could not be reached for
comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the story of his life,'' said Stanley, who has three
other children and 13 grandchildren. ``He doesn't share our
family's values.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after Stanley got back on his feet, with money pouring in
from his gas operations and oil wells, the refinery remained
shuttered. After his bankruptcy reorganization was completed, he
won an out-of-court settlement of $300 million from El Paso Gas.
After putting his company on even firmer financial footing by
selling off $1.1 billion in oil and gas operations, he was able to
borrow more money to complete the refinery project, which is
scheduled to reopen this month.
</P>
<P>
   His timing could not be better. Profits in refining are
rebounding, capacity is tight and demand for gasoline is growing at
close to 3 percent a year. ``The manufacturing capacity to make
gasoline is not keeping up with demand,'' said Frederick Leuffer,
an oil analyst for Bear, Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the industry falls on hard times again, Stanley believes
his refinery will flourish because it is so efficient. Mark
Kellstrom, who follows the refining industry for Jefferies &AMP; Co. in
Houston, agrees, saying Stanley is years ahead of some of his major
competitors in his ability to handle low-grade crude.
</P>
<P>
   But others are not so sanguine. They point out that most of the
survivors of the carnage of the late 1980s and early 1990s, when
more than 100 mostly smaller and older refineries went under, are
battle scarred and battle hardened. Moreover, he is working against
two disadvantages _ his junk-bond debt interest payments and the
lack of a guaranteed market for his gasoline. (He sold his
gas-station chain in 1981.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to understand how they're going to get a good
return on capital,'' said Kirby Hedrick, an executive vice
president at the Phillips Petroleum Co.
</P>
<P>
   But Stanley has reason to be upbeat. His net worth is estimated
at $700 million. And, he says, he has the chance to make a huge
profit if he is able to take TransAmerican Refining public early
next year. (His gas operation, the TransTexas Gas Corp., is already
publicly traded. Both companies are units of American Energy.)
</P>
<P>
   For all his wealth, Stanley sticks to the austere business style
that dates back to the days when he ran his gas station empire from
a cinder-block building in Springfield's inner city. In Houston,
while everybody else was moving into glass towers, he worked out of
cheap leased space until 1995, when he moved into an old, partly
vandalized building.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley paid $600,000 for the building, or about $10 a square
foot _ a fraction of what prime commercial real estate was selling
for. ``We only did it,'' he said, ``because it was on the way to
the airport and it had the right price.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
