<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9813 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      06-08 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW RISES 31.89 POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Major stock market indexes rose modestly on Monday,
extending their gains for a third day. Among the leaders were
financial services companies, propelled by merger news, and
pharmaceutical stocks, lifted by a positive outlook for new drug
products.
</P>
<P>
   After soaring more than 167 points on Friday, the Dow Jones
industrial average rose 31.89 points on Monday, to 9,069.60.
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index added 1.86 points, to close at
1,115.72. The technology-laden Nasdaq composite index rose 4.85
points, to 1,787.77. Each of the measures advanced more than 1
percent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Although investors' current bias seems to be to move prices
higher, analysts say, stocks are not expected to gain much ground
in the coming weeks as the second-quarter earning season nears,
said Richard Cripps, chief market strategist at Legg Mason Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the three days of gains, broad market indexes are lower
than they were at the beginning of May, with the Dow more than 142
points away from its May 13 closing high of 9,211.84.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, corporations offered investors mixed signals about
the outlook for the market. On the one hand, merger activity
continued at a brisk pace, improving the outlook for corporate
profits in several sectors. The Norwest Corp. and Wells Fargo &AMP; Co.
announced plans for a $34 billion merger that would produce the
nation's seventh largest bank. The news helped lift other financial
shares like First Union, BankAmerica and Chase Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance Energy, a Canadian oil producer, said it planned to
purchase Pinnacle Resources for more than $720 million, and Just
For Feet, a sneaker retailer, announced plans to buy rival Sneaker
Stadium for $43 million in assumed debt.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, earnings warnings from several companies and
other negative news tempered investors' enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Galey &AMP; Lord, a denim manufacturer whose customers include Levi
Strauss, the Gap retailer, designers Calvin Klein, Liz Claiborne
and Polo Ralph Lauren warned that fiscal third-quarter earnings
would not meet forecasts because of lower sales in the United
States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Harmon, the company's chief financial officer, said that
earnings were hurt because denim sales did not pick up as much as
expected. In addition, the company also has excess corduroy
inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the weakness in the semiconductor industry, Galileo
Technology, an Israeli maker of digital semiconductors, warned that
second-quarter revenue could fall 20 to 25 percent because of
slowing demand, price declines and product delays.
</P>
<P>
   And shares of Premiere Technologies fell more than 26 percent
after a BankAmerica Robertson Stephens research analyst reduced
second-quarter earnings estimates and questioned whether the
telecommunications concern would realize savings this quarter from
a recent acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco Holdings announced a sweeping revamping plan on Monday,
aimed at saving $100 million a year. But the company warned that
the measures could significantly reduce earnings this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What maintains the trading range is that you have earnings
estimates that are still too high and are coming down,'' Cripps
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Profits are being squeezed at the margin because of higher
costs,'' he said. However, stocks will continue to move higher
because ``I don't know where else you put your money.''
</P>
<P>
   Near-term, however, investors are unlikely to place big bets on
stocks, said Andrew Brooks, vice president in charge of equity
trading at T. Rowe Price Associates in Baltimore. Instead, stocks
prices are likely to tread water this week as investors await the
Federal Reserve chairman, Alan Greenspan's testimony before
Congress on Wednesday, as well as May retail sales and producer
price reports due later this week, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
