u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-FTC-675&AMP;ADD-NYT     06-08 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-FTC-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FTC FILES ANTITRUST SUIT AGAINST INTEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Trade Commission filed antitrust
charges Monday against Intel Corp., accusing the company of
threatening and actually injuring three computer manufacturers,
including Compaq Computer Corp., in an attempt to coerce them into
turning over rights to patented technologies.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, Intel is accused of withholding information about
its chips that the computer makers _ Digital Equipment Corp.,
Intergraph Corp. and Compaq _ considered crucial to developing
their own products based on Intel microprocessors. At the same
time, Intel was sharing that information with the three companies'
competitors who were not involved in patent disputes with Intel.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the government's charges is the assertion that
Intel's pattern of withholding technical data as a weapon in patent
disputes stifles innovation in the microprocessor industry, thereby
enhancing Intel's dominant position.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, approved by a 3-1 vote of the commission Monday
afternoon, serves as a civil indictment of sorts that begins a
complex administrative and legal proceeding that could last several
years.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Monday afternoon, Intel said the suit was
``based upon a mistaken interpretation of the law and the facts,''
adding, ``The commission apparently questions whether Intel has the
legal right to assert its intellectual property rights as a defense
to an attack on its core microprocessor business.''
</P>
<P>
   While the general outline of the suit has been known for several
days, the addition of Compaq to the list of aggrieved companies
adds a new dimension to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Intel executives and lawyers, in meetings with FTC commissioners
last week, argued that the two other companies mentioned in the
suit, Intergraph Corp. and Digital Equipment Corp., were not
currently major manufacturers of personal computers. As a result,
they said, Intel's withholding of proprietary information could not
have significantly harmed competition in that industry.
</P>
<P>
   But Compaq is the world's largest manufacturer of personal
computers. The government's suit asserts that Compaq sued Packard
Bell Electronics Corp. in 1994, charging that the company was using
patented Compaq technologies in its computers when, in fact, the
components in question had been supplied by Intel.
</P>
<P>
   ``In response to Compaq's assertion of its intellectual property
rights,'' the suit says, ``Intel cut off technical information''
about Intel microprocessors ``that Compaq needed to design systems
based on Intel's newest chips, even though that technical
information was widely available'' to other manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq executives declined to comment Monday, but according to
the suit, Compaq quickly agreed to license the technology to Intel
to end the cut-off of information. As a result, Intel began
supplying the technical information once again, the suit says.
</P>
<P>
   It is that kind of arm-twisting that the government is
particularly intent on stopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Intel can use its monopoly position in the market for
microprocessors to prevent other firms from enforcing their own
patents, other firms will have little incentive to invent new
features to challenge Intel's dominance,'' said William J. Baer,
director of the commission's Bureau of Competition, the office that
prepared the suit.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement Monday, Intel did not directly respond to that
allegation, but it has long asserted its right to give or withhold
information about its microprocessors, the brains of a computer, as
it sees fit.
</P>
<P>
   F. Thomas Dunlap, Intel's vice president and general counsel,
said Monday: ``For years Intel has shared its intellectual property
and early samples of its products with a number of key customers.
These customers work with Intel to develop products for the market
on a mutually beneficial basis. At the same time, for more than 10
years, Intel has taken unprecedented steps to ensure that all of
our activities and policies are in full compliance with existing
law.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Intel executives, in interviews, conceded every factual element
of the case. They differ with the government, however, in asserting
that they had every right to take the actions they took against
Compaq, Digital and Intergraph, and they say that Intel would take
similar actions again if the need arose.
</P>
<P>
   The company says it will argue the case based on the premise
that the government is trying to enforce a new legal theory, that
``because you are successful, the legal rights you had to control
your intellectual property no longer apply,'' said Chuck Mulloy, a
company spokesman. ``What's at work here is a fundamental
disagreement about what the law says. And we think we have 100
years of case law on our side.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap added, ``The commission's decision today signals that
they want to change the very laws upon which we've based our
policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Baer, on the other hand, said that the commission was pursuing a
traditional antitrust action. Intel, he said, ``remains free to
bargain with other companies over patent rights and to protect
those rights in court.'' But he added, ``Under the law, Intel is a
monopoly, and it's illegal under antitrust law for a monopolist to
wield its monopolistic power to prevent others from challenging its
dominance.''
</P>
<P>
   In meetings last week, Baer said, Intel executives told the
commissioners: ``All we did was put speed bumps in the way of some
of our competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   In those meetings last week, Intel executives also argued that
their actions had not actually harmed Intergraph or the other
affected companies in any significant way. But in an interview
Monday, Intergraph's chairman, Jim Meadlock, called that idea
``absolutely wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't be on the front end of the marketplace in this
business, then you can't compete,'' Meadlock said. And, he added,
when Intel withheld technical information about upcoming versions
of the Pentium II microprocessors, Intergraph could not design
updated computers as quickly as the company's competitors.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he said, ``we went from first in the work-station
marketplace in 1996 to forth or fifth. For us, this is a very
serious business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1951EDT &QL; 
