<HEADER>
A9819 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-08 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: LET'S PLAY  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since everyone is giving President Clinton travel advice, I'll
chime in too: On your way home from China, stop in Iran. Yes, Iran.
Invite yourself. Don't make this upcoming trip to China just about
the last crisis. Make it about the next one. Looked at a map of
South Asia lately? China's got the bomb. India's got the bomb.
Pakistan's got the bomb. Let's see, who's next to Pakistan ...
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably only a matter of time, a decade or less, before
Iran, for its own geostrategic reasons, develops or acquires a
nuclear device. Who knows, maybe Pakistan, reeling from sanctions,
will sell Iran one. The only question is what regime will be in
power in Tehran with its finger on the trigger. There is a struggle
now under way in Iran over exactly that question. The outcome of
that struggle is a vital U.S. strategic interest. It must be
defined as such, and it must be acted upon as such.
</P>
<P>
   If Iran obtains a nuclear bomb and the most radical ayatollahs
are in charge there, it will further undermine stability in the
Middle East. If Iran obtains nuclear technology and the moderate
forces now on the rise there can consolidate their hold on Iranian
politics, it is possible that Iran can once again be a bulwark for
stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
   It is time the United States stopped debating whether to try to
bolster the moderate _ yes, moderate _ new Iranian President,
Mohammed Khatami, and started thinking about far-reaching ways to
strengthen him and the popular forces behind him. Washington should
be doing everything it can to encourage U.S.-Iran contacts _ from
soccer to diplomatic dialogues to cultural exchanges _ and to lay
out a specific road map of what it wants from Iran now, and what
Iran could expect in return. It's time for a Nixon-to-China-like,
bold U.S.-Iran initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping, or at least slowing down, Iran's acquisition of
nuclear technology must remain a top U.S. objective, even if it
means sanctioning Russian nuclear-export companies. It is necessary
for the stability of the Middle East, but it is not sufficient. If
we focus only on preventing Iran from going nuclear by isolating
it, without also focusing on who in Iran has his finger on the
trigger, we will be making a strategic blunder.
</P>
<P>
   Wake up! Smell the Turkish coffee! The Iranian people stunned
Tehran's hard-line leadership last year by rejecting the
conservative candidates and electing Khatami in a landslide,
embracing his platform of permitting greater cultural, personal and
political freedoms. Ever since then, a low-grade civil war has been
under way in Iran between the pro- and anti-Khatami forces.
</P>
<P>
   Last month two senior clergymen on Iran's watchdog Council of
Guardians attacked Khatami for his policies of opening Iran to the
world. Two weeks ago Iran's supreme religious guide and chief
hard-liner, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, suddenly showed up at Tehran
University to address the students in an effort to puncture the
huge outpourings of support there for President Khatami. After the
commander of the Revolutionary Guards told a closed meeting of his
officers that he would ``cut the necks and tongues'' of Iran's new
liberal press, he was denounced and had to back off his remarks,
saying he had been misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important forces in Iran today are the students, the
women and the middle classes broadly defined,'' said Shaul Bakhash,
an Iran expert at George Mason University. ``Those forces, all of
which are militating for a more open society and the rule of law,
are strengthened today, not weakened, by Iran's economic
development and its interaction with the West. The way to
strengthen these forces further is by helping Khatami further open
Iran internationally and to develop it rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing would advance U.S. interests in the Middle East more
than if this struggle is won by those who want to see Iran become a
law-abiding member of the world community. The United States cannot
bring about an end to Saddam Hussein, or produce a radical
Arab-Israeli breakthrough, or really prevent the spread of nuclear
technology in the Middle East, without a different Iran. Whether
Iran is actually capable of being a pivot of stability is unclear.
It needs to be tested. But the potential is there. Unlike elsewhere
in the Middle East, Iran is the only country where the people
themselves are now leading a genuine movement for change.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 20 years, Iran is in play. So let's play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
