u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT &LR;      06-08 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE WATCH: OIL SPILLS? ASK A HAIRDRESSER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Ohio, Mass.)  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By CLAUDIA DREIFUS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cleaning up oil spills could turn out to be easy, if people just
use their heads. Or at least their hair.
</P>
<P>
   It is an idea the space agency has field-tested _ or
ditch-tested, to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   The idea came from Phillip McCrory, an Alabama hairdresser who,
as he puts it, ``walks around in the stuff all day'' in his
Huntsville salon. In 1989, McCrory saw television footage of an
otter soaked in oil from the Exxon Valdez spill. ``That's when the
light went off,'' he said. If the otter's fur soaked up oil, would
human hair do the same?
</P>
<P>
   McCrory went straight to the experimental stage. He built a test
otter by stuffing four pounds of human hair into a pair of tights,
filled his son's wading pool with water, dumped a gallon of used
motor oil on top and heaved in the hair. ``In two minutes the water
was crystal clear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tinkering gave way to figuring. How much hair is thrown out
every day? If there are more than 200,000 salons in America, he
figured, 200,000 pounds a day would be an extremely conservative
figure.
</P>
<P>
   Then, some of McCrory's customers from NASA's Marshall Space
Flight Center in Huntsville put him in touch with Maurice Hale, a
technology transfer expert. When some diesel oil spilled in a ditch
at the center, McCrory made a rough filter _ 16 pounds of hair in a
barrel. When the tainted water was pumped through, it came out
containing 17 parts per million of oil _ clean enough to dump in a
sewer.
</P>
<P>
   The secret is that every hair shaft is covered with tiny
cuticles _ ``like fish scales,'' McCrory said _ that give the
surface tension of oil, which cannot bind with water, something to
cling to.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent lab tests with Hale yielded the estimate that 1.4
million pounds of hair in re-usable mesh pillows could have soaked
up the 11 million gallons spilled by the Exxon Valdez in about a
week. By contrast, Exxon spent $2 billion on a lengthy cleanup that
captured only about 12 percent of the spill.
</P>
<P>
   Zapping Dust Mites
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are exploring a new way to get rid of hazardous dust
mites: by attacking their chemical communication system, as an
alternative to the standard labor-intensive bedroom-cleaning
protocol.
</P>
<P>
   To survive, the mites get as snug as bugs in a rug, most likely
the one by your bed. They pack into clusters to store water between
their tiny bodies. And in order to cluster, they recognize their
fellow mites by a chemical, as yet unknown.
</P>
<P>
   If scientists can interrupt that chemical message system, the
bugs would stay apart, dry out and die, said Emmett Glass, a
researcher in internal medicine in the College of Medicine and
Public Health at Ohio State University.
</P>
<P>
   Dust mites frequently cause asthma, which affects 15 percent of
humans. Most asthma sufferers are allergic to dust mites, making
them the most common indoor allergen, even ahead of mold. Mites
devour the skin cells shed at night by humans and excrete proteins
that can touch off asthma and allergy attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The research team is studying how the mites' message system
works and how they might interrupt it, said Glass. The team's work
appeared in a recent issue of the journal Experimental and Applied
Acarology.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting Collapsed Lungs
</P>
<P>
   A collapsed lung has a random way of reopening as air presses in
from a life-support system, and tissue damage is more likely if the
air pressure is not varied in a random pattern, scientists suggest.
</P>
<P>
   A team at Boston University said that mechanical ventilators
should supply air with randomized pressure that shifts between a
little more and a little less of the normal breath. Such shifts,
they said, will best reopen the closed regions without damage to
the tiny cells that take in the oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have long known that the air forced in by ventilators
can cause harm to lungs. A new computer model of lung injury by the
Boston University scientists, described in May in the journal
Nature, shows how the lung pops open in sudden bursts that expose
large surface areas available for gas exchange, or breathing.
</P>
<P>
   They say that randomly varying the amount of air coming in, from
breath to breath, can decrease possible damage to tissues and
maximize oxygen intake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 1959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
