<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9825 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CISNEROS-CASE-HNS &LR;      06-08 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-CASE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS AGREE TO SEPARATE TRIAL FOR CISNEROS, EX-LOVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros
and a special prosecutor agreed Monday to separate conspiracy
trials for the one-time Cabinet member and his former lover.
</P>
<P>
   The move by independent counsel David Barrett signals possible
cooperation by the woman, Linda Jones, in the case and makes
approval of the separate trials a formality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say it's in the government's best interest,''
Mathew Rosengart, the associate independent counsel, told reporters
following a 2-1/2-hour hearing before U.S. District Judge Stanley
Sporkin.
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin also is expected to rule on other motions to sever the
trials of John Rosales and Sylvia Arce-Garcia, who were assistants
to the former housing official, from the government's case against
Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   The four defendants are accused in a 21-count indictment of
lying to the FBI and Internal Revenue Service about $250,000
Cisneros allegedly paid Jones in exchange for her silence about the
highly publicized affair in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros has acknowledged having had an extramarital affair with
Jones _ then known as Linda Medlar _ while he was mayor of San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Rosales' lawyer, Reid Weingarten, argued that publicity and
evidence in the government's case against Cisneros would be unfair
to his client, who is accused of playing a minor role in the
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not even a fly on an elephant's backside,'' Weingarten
said.
</P>
<P>
   Arce-Garcia's lawyer, Abbe Lowell, said his client ``was even
smaller'' than an insect on the pachyderm.
</P>
<P>
   Rosengart countered that the independent counsel would produce
circumstantial and direct evidence to prove its case against
Rosales and Garcia-Arce.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing Monday was marked by verbal outbursts by government
and defense lawyers to the point that Sporkin had to admonish them
to ``put the swords down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned that life is too short,'' the judge said
following a flurry of shouts.
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin is expected to file written rulings on the motions
argued Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he set a July 20 hearing for arguments on the defense
motions attacking the validity of 88 tapes of telephone
conversations and boxes of documents from Jones' home in Lubbock,
Texas. The government wants to use the tapes as evidence in the
trials.
</P>
<P>
   The recordings are the heart of the government's case against
Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, who headed the Department of Housing and Urban
Development from 1993 through 1996, is scheduled to go to trial on
Nov. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a former San Antonio political fund-raiser, waived her
right to appear in court Monday.
</P>
<P>
   She is serving a three-year, six-month sentence in a federal
prison in Texas after pleading guilty to a 28-count indictment for
money laundering, bank fraud and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Those charges were brought against Jones in Texas and grew out
of the independent counsel's initial investigation into allegations
against Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   The $4 million probe was launched in 1995 after Jones told the
tabloid television show ``Inside Edition'' during a paid interview
that Cisneros lied to the FBI about money he paid her after their
1988 affair.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros told FBI agents he had paid Jones about $60,000 before
his nomination to be housing.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel said the payments actually reached
$250,000, including roughly $73,000 that was paid after Cisneros
took office at HUD. Those payments included two $8,000 deposits
Cisneros made to Jones' relatives to help her buy a home.
</P>
<P>
   Although the extramarital affair was public, the indictment
stated Cisneros paid Jones ``in order to ensure her public silence
regarding, among other things, their relationship and the nature,
purpose and extent of his payments to her and to another woman, so
that he could be nominated, confirmed and serve as secretary to
HUD.''
</P>
<P>
   The name of a second woman referred to in the indictment has not
been made public.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros currently is president of the Spanish-language
television network Univision. Arce-Garcia is an aide to Cisneros at
the network. Rosales is still employed by HUD.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
