<SLUG> BC-NRA-HESTON-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NRA ELECTS CHARLTON HESTON PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN.: Iowa) (ja) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ With a courtly bow, Charlton Heston acknowledged
a loud, standing ovation Monday by the National Rifle Association
board of directors, which voted overwhelmingly to make the actor
the NRA's 56th president.
</P>
<P>
   While Heston ran unopposed to succeed Marion Hammer, and only
one of 76 board members voted against him, the election was a
highlight of the association's annual convention. The gathering
drew about 40,000 of the NRA's 2.8 million members to a city where
almost one person a day dies by a handgun.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Edward Rendell met elsewhere Monday with gun makers to
discuss possible lawsuits by the city to recoup from them the
health-care costs of the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Heston, 73, a veteran of almost 100 motion pictures, said one of
his first priorities would be to restore the image of the NRA,
which many members contend has been tarnished by opponents who
characterize it as extremist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to reverse the trends of the last 10 or 15 years, to a
large extent driven by the media, to demonize the NRA,'' Heston
said in an interview after the vote, which elevated him from first
vice president. ``It's not fair; you're not supposed to play that
way. But I am a reasonably good communicator, and I think I can be
useful, and sometimes successful, in shifting people.''
</P>
<P>
   The election was held shortly after the meeting was interrupted
by an incident that some members said would reinforce the group's
harsh image.
</P>
<P>
   A member from Iowa, Ken Brodbeck, had been videotaping his wife,
Sally, a director, as she addressed the NRA officers.
</P>
<P>
   After Brodbeck ignored two security guards who quietly told him
that taping inside board meetings violated NRA rules, one guard
grabbed him by the throat and threw him to the ground, according to
Brodbeck and several witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Brodbeck's wife ran over and screamed, ``What did you do to my
husband?'' An emergency team was summoned, but Brodbeck said he did
not need treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the accounts of several witnesses, the NRA's security
manager, Tris Barry, who was one of the guards, said Brodbeck
simply fell out of his chair.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Russell, the guard who witnesses said grabbed Brodbeck,
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Heston brushed off the incident, saying it had
been staged by opponents of the leadership ``to stir up trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As an actor and director, I can tell you it was very bad
acting,'' he said, without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
   Internal squabbles aside, Heston considered the larger
challenges ahead and said that he would be happy just to reach the
large numbers of Americans who have ambiguous feelings about the
country's largest gun group. Vocal opponents of the NRA, he
conceded, are probably beyond the persuasive powers of his mellow
voice and movie-star looks that made him a convincing Moses in
``The Ten Commandments.''
</P>
<P>
   One such opponent, Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., who favors
tighter restrictions on gun ownership, wasted no time in attacking
Heston as the wrong choice for an organization seeking mainstream
approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Charlton Heston wants to lead the NRA out of the
wilderness, into the promised land, then they have to abandon their
extremist positions,'' Schumer said in a telephone interview. ``The
idea that he is a moderate is wrong. He is as extreme as the NRA.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., who has appealed to Heston to
support safety locks on guns, a position the NRA opposes, said:
``Even a good messenger can't make something out of a bad
message.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wherever Heston falls on the ideological spectrum, he gives the
NRA an imposing force for its message that gun ownership by
law-abiding people has less to do with crime than do broken
families and a broken criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike those who traditionally carry the NRA banner into
Congress and state legislatures, including Wayne LaPierre, the
executive vice president, and Tanya Metaksa, the chief lobbyist,
Heston said he would devote most of his energy to speaking to
average Americans, calling it ``the most useful thing I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his goals, he said, is to expand NRA membership among
women and minorities. The association is composed overwhelmingly of
white males, and officials estimated that only 10 to 15 percent of
the members are women. They said they have no idea how many people
in the organization are members of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women,'' Heston said, ``make up the fastest-growing group of
handgun owners, especially single women. They are also very good
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Heston also said he would try recruiting people who consider gun
ownership a private matter. ``In Hollywood, a community I know
better,'' he said, reprising a line he used often over the last few
days, ``there are more gun owners in the closet than homosexuals.''
</P>
<P>
   While statements like that invariably outrage opponents of the
NRA, they are wildly appreciated by association members, who are
convinced that Heston's views represent those of the majority of
Americans and that by the strength of his charismatic personality
and passion for gun-owners' rights, he can win over converts to
their cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be a great leader for the NRA and a great spokesman,''
said Oliver North, the former Iran-contra figure who was elected to
the board Monday. ``After all, when you hear the voice of Moses
speak, you know people are going to pay attention.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
