<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9840 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STANLEYCUP-HNS &LR;      06-08 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEYCUP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
DETROIT _ While it may only seem as if the Ice Age lasted longer
than the 1997-98 National Hockey League season, the end to the
longest year in hockey history is in sight.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the greater good of the NHL, however, the league is hoping
the playoffs can last a bit longer _ in terms of games _ than they
have the last three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   When the Detroit Red Wings and Washington Capitals open the
Stanley Cup finals tonight at Joe Louis Arena, a nagging streak of
sweeps will be in place.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Detroit beat Philadelphia in four games. The year
before, Colorado swept Florida. In 1995, New Jersey swept Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   With TV ratings for this year's playoffs down substantially on
both Fox and ESPN, a compelling, dramatic, seven-game finals would
help the NHL regain some fading glory.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, it is not shaping up that way. The Red Wings are
heavily favored to become the first NHL team to win consecutive
championships since Pittsburgh in 1991-92. The Capitals are making
their first appearance in the finals, and even their coach raised
the possibility of a sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have our hands full,'' said Washington coach
Ron Wilson. ``Not too many people are going to give us a chance.
Everyone probably thinks that we'll go out in four straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, of course, has been known to use the media to try to
manipulate things, so his observation must be taken with several
grains of salt.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Red Wings have shown throughout this year's
playoffs that they are capable of sweeping away Washington, a team
that finished in the middle of the pack in the Eastern Conference
during the regular season and has scant playoff experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won last year,'' said Washington center Joe Juneau.
``Obviously, they have all these big names on their team, and I
think that any team facing the Red Wings in the finals would be the
underdog. I'm not surprised. I'm not thinking about it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings know what it's like to be the new kids on the
block. In 1995, they were caught up in the distractions of the
final series and swept away by New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the ultimate disappointment in the series against New
Jersey,'' said Detroit center Kris Draper. ``We were cocky. We had
a lot of young kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we knew it, the series was over. Last year, we took a
100-percent businesslike approach to playing the Philadelphia
Flyers. That's exactly what we have to do. Washington is obviously
excited to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Only five Capitals have been this far. Esa Tikkanen (five) and
Brian Bellows (one) are the only Caps with Stanley Cup rings. That
disadvantage is of little concern to Washington goaltender Olaf
Kolzig, who has provided the impetus for the Caps to reach the
finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the defending Stanley Cup champions, and they are
playing well,'' said Kolzig. ``You guys (media) can write all you
want about how it's going to be a sweep, but we don't believe that.
And I'm sure they don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our job to go out and prove everybody wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings may not be able to sweep the Capitals, who have a
hot goaltender in Kolzig, two high-powered scoring lines and a
capable defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Caps, however, will be taking a huge step up in class when
they face Detroit. Washington got out of the East by beating Boston
(the No. 5 seed), Ottawa (No. 8) and Buffalo (No. 6).
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a lot like us,'' said Red Wings coach Scotty Bowman.
``They've got two lines that have scored in the playoffs and two
lines that can shut down other lines. One thing you wonder about in
these situations is how your team will do against a team you
haven't played that much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington might be a team that some people are taking
lightly, but we aren't. We know that they've done very well on the
road in the playoffs (7-1), and that's been their big secret.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that for the Caps to have any chance, Kolzig will
have to continue his sizzling goaltending. He has been nicknamed
``Godzilla'' because of his 6-3, 225-pound stature, which limits
opposing players' openings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really come into his own,'' said Detroit left wing
Brendan Shanahan. ``When you face a great goaltender, you really
can't change your habits. I think the worst thing you can do when
you are playing against a great goaltender is think about him too
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute you start trying to pick corners and change your
mind on shots, that's when the goaltender already has the advantage
on you. The idea is to shoot the puck on net and try to get traffic
in front.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit goaltender Chris Osgood has been solid, posting two
shutouts against Dallas in the Western Conference finals, but he
also has allowed several soft goals that caused some people to
wonder how he will react under the pressure of the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Osgood was the backup to Mike Vernon when the Red Wings won the
Cup last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every player makes mistakes,'' said Osgood.
``Forwards, defense, goalies. That's why it's a team game.
Everybody covers for everybody. That's what makes our team such a
good team. We play as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be honest. Our team thinks not about the mistakes we've made;
we think what we're going to do about it. We don't dwell on things.
It's over the minute it happens, really.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Red Wings ride their high-powered offense of Sergei
Fedorov, Steve Yzerman and defensemen Nicklas Lidstrom to another
title, they will give Bowman two back-to-back titles in the 1990s.
He was the coach of the 1992 Pittsburgh Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be difficult to keep a team intact,'' said Bowman,
trying to explain why five teams have won the Stanley Cup in the
last five years. ``We have a lot of teams that are pretty close,
and with a good offseason you can make a lot of strides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say the biggest difficulty is complacency. You have a
bit of success, and you sit back, and then all of a sudden there
are new teams that come right by you. We've done a good job this
year in that regard. We feel comfortable with each other. We're
still hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining that appetite for winning has been a never-ending
war of attrition in a season interrupted for 16 days in February to
allow NHL players to take part in the Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, having the defending champs matched against an
upstart newcomer could provide some compelling hockey.
</P>
<P>
   But only if the Capitals cooperate and win a game or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going into this series with a lot of respect for the Red
Wings, but we are not intimidated,'' said Wilson. ``We've got some
guys like (Brian) Bellows and (Esa) Tikkanen who have been here
before. We're not a young team, so intimidation shouldn't be a
factor. I don't think I even have to talk to our players about the
word intimidation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
