<SLUG> BC-WHEAT-SANCTIONS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS WANT TO EXEMPT WHEAT FROM SANCTIONS AGAINST PAKISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fearful that the economic and political fallout
from last month's nuclear tests will devastate the Northwest wheat
industry, regional lawmakers are pushing the Clinton aministration
to find a way to prevent sanctions against Pakistan from affecting
Washington state's most valuable agricultural export.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash, will be joined by at
least 32 other House members in introducing legislation barring
President Clinton from including agricultural products as part of
the sanctions used to punish nations that test nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., has suggested he might try to amend
the defense budget to accomplish the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days Sens. Gorton, Patty Murray, D-Wash., Max Baucus,
D-Mont., and Washington Gov. Gary Locke have pleaded the case of
Northwest wheat growers to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Locke predicted that 20 percent of the state's wheat growers
could be driven out of business if Pakistan is prevented from
buying U.S. wheat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unilateral sanctions don't work, they're ineffective, and they
hurt the American farmer,'' said Nethercutt, whose district
includes southeast Washington, where the wheat industry is
concentrated. ``If we can't sell to Pakistan, some other country
will, and we will lose that market. That's an unacceptable
consequence of bad American foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislative activity comes because of an unusual feature of
the wheat market in the Pacific Northwest. Unlike much of the grain
grown in the United States, which is red, the vast majority of
grain grown in the Northwest is white and resembles indigenous
Pakistani wheat. As a result, Pakistan over the past five years has
become a huge importer of Northwest wheat. Any interruption would
be devastating for Washington's wheat farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan imports about $500 million worth of wheat each year, of
which about half comes from the Pacific Northwest, according to the
State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Washington state's 13,000 wheat farmers already are suffering
from depressed prices and oversupply, and the problem is expected
to be exacerbated by a bumper crop this year. Wheat, which costs
about $4 a bushel to produce, is now selling for less than $3,
according to the state Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Pakistan was the largest single buyer of Pacific
Northwest white year, purchasing 37 percent of the crop, according
to the Washington State Wheat Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sanctions would have a devastating effect on the price of
wheat and the ability to move it at all,'' said Jim Jesernig, the
director of the state Department of Agriculture. ``Once you have a
market taken off limits for political reasons, the usual drill is
for our competitors to come in and take that market over, and
that's a market you're not going to get back.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, as required under the U.S. Arms Export Control Act, has
imposed broad sanctions against India and Pakistan because those
countries conducted underground nuclear tests last month. The
sanctions, designed to deter testing, affect development
assistance, military sales and exchanges, trade in specified
technology, U.S. financial assistance, guarantees and credits,
loans and credits by U.S. banks to those two governments, and
denial of support within international financial institutions for
loans.
</P>
<P>
   Although food products are generally exempted from sanctions,
the wheat industry may be affected because Pakistan uses
U.S.-backed credits to buy the wheat. Clinton administration
officials are debating whether the law allows them to exempt those
credits from sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``No decision has been made, and our legal experts are currently
analyzing the construction and intent'' of the law, said State
Department spokesman Jim Desler.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Clinton administration finds an exemption from
sanctions for the credits Pakistan uses to buy wheat, wheat growers
worry that the other sanctions will make Pakistan ineligible for
credits or unwilling to continue buying from the United States. A
similar concern faces the Washington state pea and lentil industry,
which sells 5 to 7 percent of its product to India.
</P>
<P>
   Locke suggested that if Clinton can't find an exemption for
wheat, he should take other steps to protect the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (an exemption) is not possible, it is essential that our
country have agreements with the major food exporting nations that
they will not supply Pakistan with wheat,'' Locke wrote to Clinton.
``Otherwise, the penalty for the nuclear testing will not be levied
against Pakistan or India, but rather against the Pacific Northwest
wheat growers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
