<SLUG> BC-SCI-HEART-DRUG-705&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA WITHDRAWS A HEART DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Texas)  (lb) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Less than one year after it was approved by the
Food and Drug Administration, the prescription heart drug Posicor
was pulled off pharmacy shelves in 38 countries Monday, amid
mounting evidence that it is dangerous, and possibly lethal, when
used in combination with other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, made by Roche Laboratories of Nutley, N.J., is used to
treat high blood pressure and the chest pains known as angina,
particularly in the elderly. It is used by 400,000 people
worldwide, including 200,000 in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials have long known that it did not mix well with
certain other medications. Over the last few months, however, the
list of drugs that cause toxic interactions with Posicor has grown
so long _ 26 in all, from antihistamines to antibiotics to
cholesterol-lowering medications and the cancer drug tamoxifen _
that the agency asked Roche last week to withdraw it from the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Roche, which spent a decade and several hundred million dollars
developing the drug, complied, describing the decision as
voluntary. Both the FDA and the company urged patients who are
taking Posicor not to stop taking the drug, but rather to consult
their doctors as quickly as possible to find an alternative
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too complicated to try to use a drug in the elderly
population when you have more than 25 different drugs that you
can't use it with,'' said Dr. Murray Lumpkin, deputy director of
the FDA's Center for Drug Evaluation and Research. ``We were going
to the company and saying, `Let's take it off the market now before
we get into a bad situation.'''
</P>
<P>
   It is extremely rare for the FDA, which is widely regarded as
being extremely safety-conscious, to have to withdraw a drug once
it has been approved. Lumpkin said that the only such withdrawals
in the past decade were Posicor and the popular diet drug
combination known as fen-phen, which was taken off the market last
September.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, the agency has been been under intense
pressure from congressional Republicans to speed up its
drug-approval process; it has given its imprimatur to a record
number of new drugs, 92, over the past two years. After Monday's
announcement, agency critics complained that the FDA is relaxing
its standards, particularly for ``me-too drugs'' like Posicor,
which imitate medicines that are already on the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be one thing if this drug were a significant
breakthrough for treatment of this disease, and there were some
safety problems,'' said Dr. Sidney Wolfe, director of Public
Citizen's Health Research Group, a monitoring organization in
Washington. ``But when you've got a drug that no one remotely
thinks is any better than any of the other eight or nine already on
the market, why for the purpose of public health or public safety
do you approve it?''
</P>
<P>
   But Lumpkin defended the FDA, saying that patients and doctors
benefit from having a wide variety of drugs, and that there was no
way to know when Posicor was approved that it would be dangerous in
combination with so many other medications.
</P>
<P>
   Posicor, which is part of a class of medications known as
calcium channel-blockers, inhibits certain liver enzymes that
enable the body to eliminate other drugs. When the enzymes are not
working, those other drugs can build to toxic levels. ``The drug
itself is a pretty clean drug,'' Lumpkin said. ``The problem is its
interference with other drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Posicor went on the market last July, Lumpkin said, the
FDA has been monitoring it closely and has received dozens of
reports of adverse side effects _ including dangerously low heart
rate, irregular heartbeat and a breakdown of muscle that can cause
permanent damage to the kidneys _ in patients taking it in
combination with other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Those reports included 24 deaths, although how many were
actually caused by the medications is unclear, in part because the
patients taking them were so sick to begin with. Valerie Suga, a
spokeswoman for Roche, said that ``no causal link'' had been
established between Posicor and any deaths. But Lumpkin said agency
officials believed two or three of the fatalities could be directly
attributed to the drug combinations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Concerns about Posicor, which is also known by the generic name
mibefradil, first emerged in February 1997, when an independent
panel of expert scientists voted by a relatively slim margin, 5-3,
to advise the FDA to approve it.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who voted against approval was Dr. Lemuel Moye, a
biostatistician at the University of Texas Health Sciences Center
in Houston. Moye said he was troubled by preliminary data from an
ongoing study of 2,600 patients that suggested Posicor might cause
unusual electrical activity in the heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just could not justify voting for this drug in the presence
of a finding which may be a harbinger of danger,'' he said. ``I
wanted us to wait and see what this large clinical trial showed,
before voting for approval.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite that concern, and despite concerns about drug
interactions, the FDA approved Posicor on June 20. The approval
instructed Roche to warn doctors about the drug's effect on the
liver enzymes; the label specifically mentioned three drugs that
can lower the heart rate and should not be prescribed with Posicor.
</P>
<P>
   The drug went on the market in the United States and elsewhere a
month later; by last December, the FDA stepped up its warnings,
asking Roche to add two cholesterol-lowering drugs to the list of
medications that patients taking Posicor should avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the 2,600-patient clinical trial continued; Roche
officials were hoping it would prove that Posicor could be used to
treat not only high blood pressure and angina, but also congestive
heart failure. That might have given the company a reason to press
ahead with the drug in the face of all the warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ms. Suga said, the study found that Posicor was no more
effective than a placebo for congestive heart failure. At the same
time, Ms. Suga said, it yielded additional reports of adverse drug
interactions, which the company shared with the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in full compliance and worked closely with them,'' Ms.
Suga said. As part of Monday's action, the company has written to
doctors telling them to stop prescribing Posicor immediately, and
has also set up a 24-hour telephone line for consumers and health
professionals: 1 (800) 205-4611.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue now is that the patients' well-being is of the
highest priority,'' Ms. Suga said. ``We are doing the most
responsible approach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
