u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NABISCO-CUTBACK-425&AMP;A     06-08 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NABISCO-CUTBACK-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NABISCO TO LAY OFF 3,000, OR 6 PERCENT OF ITS WORK FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nabisco announced a $524 million reorganization plan
Monday that will include factory closings and the layoffs of more
than 3,000 of its 53,000 employees in an effort to pump new energy
into Cheese Nips, Fig Newtons and the rest of its languishing
cookie and cracker business. But Wall Street, caught off guard,
knocked the price of Nabisco stock down by more than 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Nabisco revealed in a midmorning conference
call with analysts that cookie-and-cracker sales _ the lineup
includes such icons as Oreo, Mallomar, Saltines and Ritz _ are down
3 to 4 percent, worse than the flat sales that had been expected
this year. In addition, several businesses are expected to be sold
off, further diluting earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization will cost an estimated $406 million, or $1.01
a share, in the current quarter, with another $118 million in
related expenses spread over the next 12 months, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The changes will mean layoffs for an estimated 6 percent of the
company's work force worldwide. While savings this year of $35
million are expected as a result of the restructuring, marketing
spending will rise by $50 million, and another $70 million will be
spent to reconfigure the basic sales force, which, after being
reorganized in early 1997, has been blamed for a 4 percent drop in
sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco carried out a reorganization almost exactly two years
ago that shed 8 percent of the work force, and there had long been
expectations that a similar move was in the works. But the extent
of the latest overhaul seemed to take several analysts by surprise.
``We didn't think the numbers would be this high, and the near-term
hits this big,'' said John McMillin, an analyst with Prudential
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Following the conference call, Nomi Ghez, an analyst with
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., downgraded the stock from ``buy'' to ``market
perform,'' based on uncertainty about what earnings will be. ``Not
only is the reduction in estimates bigger than I thought,'' she
said, ``but there is still earnings uncertainty because they
indicated they will be reduced further by dilutive asset sales. We
really are faced with not knowing what earnings will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco Holdings stock did a day-long swan dive, falling $6.625,
or 13.2 percent, to close at $39.875, in the biggest percentage
decline since it went public in January 1995. RJR Nabisco, which
owns 80.5 percent of the shares, fell $1.625, or 5.8 percent, to
close at $26.50.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   James Kilts, who became president and chief executive of Nabisco
in January, said the restructuring and marketing were necessary, in
tandem, to move the company forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you'd like to do is be in a situation where you can take
the cost out before you need to make the stepped-up investment,''
he said in a telephone interview. ``But where I see the competitive
situation today, we need to move quickly to invest against the
consumer and at the same time, attack our cost structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilts added that he expected the company to show improvement in
sales and earnings by next year. But that growth will be coming off
a diminished base, McMillin noted, estimating that earnings per
share will fall to $1.30 this year from the $1.60 forecast earlier
this year. Some analysts expect the earnings estimate to fall
further, once the effects of the asset sales become known. No
details were given Monday about what might be sold, though many
people said Nabisco's margarine business, which the company bought
from Kraft when Kilts was in charge there, was a likely candidate.
Kilts said there would be announcements by the third quarter, if
not during the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kilts is in the difficult position of having to grow earnings
at the same time there is pressure on volume and prices as well,''
said Martin Feldman, a director at Salomon Smith Barney. ``The
category is a very competitive one.'' During the conference call,
Feldman noted, the Nabisco chairman ``used the expression, `Biscuit
is struggling.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for Nabisco's doldrums range from changes in eating
habits _ more salsa and taco chips at America's get-togethers in
place of cheese and crackers _ to fierce rivalry from Keebler,
which has long spent more on advertising than Nabisco. ``You can
have the greatest brands in the world,'' said Emanuel Goldman, who
follows RJR Nabisco for PaineWebber, ``but if you don't manage them
right, there's someone out there to take your share.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Ghez said the problems were homegrown, stemming from a
decision made 18 months ago in which seasoned salespeople _ the
ones who go into supermarkets and other retail outlets and persuade
owners to stock their shelves with Nabisco products _ were let go
and replaced with younger, cheaper and less experienced people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Previous management was trying very hard to deliver numbers
they had promised that were unrealistic,'' she said. ``They looked
for places to cut costs, and they did it by damaging the most
important asset that they had. It's a case study of what you should
not do. In this business, your infrastructure, your nitty-gritty,
is so important. If you don't have the right people out there
selling to people they have a relationship with, forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilts, who turned around similar disarray at Kraft, a unit of
Philip Morris, plans to change the sales force so that a single
customer-sales representative is assigned to specific stores and
oversees all sales activity in those stores. New compensation and
training programs will begin, as well as consumer promotions, using
the $70 million announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The $50 million for marketing will be used to increase
advertising of brands like Snackwell's, once a star performer for
the company, as well as Fig Newtons and Ritz crackers. ``There are
a number of brands that merit our attention and support,'' Kilts
said. ``Oreos and Chips Ahoy are examples of where we have done a
good job with the marketing, and those brands are doing well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
