r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEXADDICT-AZR &LR;      06-08 1534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXADDICT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEXUAL OVERDRIVE: THERAPIST SEEKS OUT ADDICTION'S CAUSES,
TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICKENBURG, Ariz. _ If Bill Clinton calls, Dr. Patrick Carnes
will serve.
</P>
<P>
   If the president decides his sex drive is out of control, Carnes
is willing to head for the White House with his little black bag of
psychological remedies.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not waiting for the hotline to ring.
</P>
<P>
   Carnes, clinical director of sexual disorder services at The
Meadows addiction treatment facility, is a renowned expert on
urge-curbing.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years, he has been at the vanguard of treatment for
sexual addiction, a disorder as real and troubling, he says, as
alcoholism, drug abuse or compulsive gambling.
</P>
<P>
   It's a disease that breaks up marriages, destroys careers, and
saps money, health and reputations. It can result in bodily injury
and death.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual addiction is not a sign of poor moral instincts, Carnes
insists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a matter of choice or goodwill. It's not a matter of
character,'' he says. ``Sexual addicts have a very intact
conscience. . . . They make promises to stop, and they make an
effort to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Attention surrounding President Clinton's sexcapades has
heightened awareness of the issue, Carnes says. Therapists are
rejoicing that more addicts are seeking the help they need.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all very grateful, profoundly grateful . . . It's been
a gift.``
</P>
<P>
   Carnes, who holds a doctorate in counseling psychology, was
asked to give expert testimony in the Paula Jones lawsuit against
the president. He will not, however, judge whether Clinton actually
has a disorderly libido.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never met the man,'' he says simply.
</P>
<P>
   But in the one-page affidavit he provided an Arkansas court
after interviewing Jones for half a day, he determined that she
was, indeed, emotionally damaged in 1991 by Clinton's alleged
request for oral sex in a Little Rock hotel room. He believes that
although no further harassment occurred and Jones' job as a state
employee never was threatened, she lived with continued fears of
reprisal.
</P>
<P>
   Carnes will share no further information from his examination of
Jones, keeping his findings confidential until her case goes to
trial. Then he will take the stand and render a more comprehensive
diagnosis. The judge in the case threw out Jones' suit, but that
decision is being appealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt protective of Paula,'' he says, adding that he
personally likes the president and voted for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The politics of the case have been fascinating to watch. It's
certainly not about justice. It's about the most powerful man in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   He offers three theories for the beleaguered president's
reputation as a sexual aggressor:
</P>
<P>
   ``Either he doesn't have a problem and there have been unfair
and false accusations, or he has a problem and he will get help, or
he has a problem and he's getting advice ``not'' to get help.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnes despairs at the thought of the latter. Since entering the
field of addiction in the early 1970s and publishing his first
paper on sexual addiction in 1973 _ one of the first published
anywhere _ he has seen the devastation caused by a condition rooted
in childhood, the result of a repressive household or an
emotionally impoverished family.
</P>
<P>
   Most sex addicts, he says, were sexually, physically or
psychologically abused. Research has found that when they perform
an inappropriate act, they are repeating the abuse, ``re-creating
the neurochemical experience they had as a child, the erotic
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Addicts are not necessarily seeking a turn-on, he says: ``It's
not about orgasm.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, sexual addiction can be about pain.
</P>
<P>
   Some sufferers engage in ``pain exchange,'' commonly known as
sadomasochism, in which they seek out physical abuse. Mistakenly
considered a victimless crime, the practice can result in severe
injury or death.
</P>
<P>
   Some men injure themselves masturbating so vigorously that they
bruise or lacerate their genitals, requiring a trip to the doctor
or emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   Other manifestations of sexual addiction include rape, child
molestation, voyeurism, peeping, procuring prostitutes (or
practicing prostitution), frequenting topless bars (or performing
in them), exhibitionism and ``intrusive sex'' _ making obscene
phone calls, touching or brushing against people inappropriately,
repeatedly telling dirty jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors might find themselves betraying their patients with
erotic touches. A clergy member might pursue parishioners sexually.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a minirape,'' he says of professionals who betray.
``They know it's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnes treated a Florida clergyman acclaimed for his
anti-pornography crusades who shocked his flock when he was
arrested for a pornography trade of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Several recent news reports have spotlighted such risky sexual
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   British singer George Michael was arrested for performing a lewd
act in a park restroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hustler'' publisher Larry Flynt was arrested for allegedly
peddling obscene videos, including to a 14-year-old boy. The
pornography industry is rife with sexual addicts, Carnes says.
</P>
<P>
   And in Seattle, a respected female teacher was jailed for having
an affair with a student who was 13 when the relationship began.
She has borne one child by the boy and is pregnant with a second.
</P>
<P>
   For Carnes, such cases are all too familiar. He says he sees
clients like the Seattle teacher ``all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't help themselves,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Though sexual aggression most often is perpetrated by men and
directed at women, ``we see it can happen the other way around.
Women can be victimizers.''
</P>
<P>
   The incidence of sexual addiction in the general population is
about 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Addicts usually do not seek help until a crisis arises _ the
breakup of a marriage, an arrest, one more visit to the emergency
room.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is providing the newest outlet for sexual
appetites, Carnes says, offering as many as 50,000 pornographic Web
sites. Anonymity has made cybersex a popular clandestine activity _
but no less dangerous when users risk being introduced to deviants.
</P>
<P>
   Internet use can be costly in other ways. Carnes recalls one
patient who rang up $7,000 in weekly fees exploring pornographic
Web sites before being stopped. He'd been charging his bills to his
employer.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to such compulsions, cybersex has become big business.
Two women working out of their garage in Seattle, Carnes says, are
making $60,000 a month helping clients find carnal Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Although technology has expanded the opportunity for pursuing
sexual activity, such behavior is not new. Sexual aberration has
been practiced since the beginning of time, Carnes says.
</P>
<P>
   In the Middle Ages, ``if you were a woman, your chances of
getting through life without being raped were zip. . . . Those were
violent times.''
</P>
<P>
   Research on sexual addiction began in the 1970s, when similar
disorders such as compulsive gambling and compulsive shopping also
were identified.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, progress has been made in the understanding and
treatment of sexual addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much happening,'' Carnes says. ``So much research
is coming out that's interesting. . . We're starting to talk about
it. There is an openness.''
</P>
<P>
   Although frisky Europeans sometimes accuse America of
prudishness, Carnes argues that intolerance for promiscuity signals
a maturing of the culture and indicates that we are moving out of
our collective adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers have found that sexual violence is almost
nonexistent in societies that have achieved equality between men
and women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about evolution . . . how men and women treat
each other and how we raise our children,'' Carnes says. ``That
changes the core of the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Sexual addiction usually is accompanied by other addictions _
alcoholism, drug abuse. Only 13 percent of sex addicts are free of
other compulsions, Carnes says. ``It's a package deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other addicts, sex addicts alternate between bingeing and
purging, first engaging in voracious sex and then falling into what
Carnes calls ``sexual anorexia,'' or celibacy.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment for sexual addiction works, he says. Addicts can
return to a nearly normal sex life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is not to be asexual,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Although medications such as Prozac can help curb cravings,
behavioral modification has proved the best remedy.
</P>
<P>
   The most effective treatment includes 10 components:
</P>
<P>
   _Participation in a 12-step program.
</P>
<P>
   _Treatment for concurrent addictions.
</P>
<P>
   _Doing the homework required for recovery.
</P>
<P>
   _Group therapy _ at least 175 hours.
</P>
<P>
   _Private therapy _ three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   _Family involvement.
</P>
<P>
   _Counseling for co-dependents.
</P>
<P>
   _Couples' therapy.
</P>
<P>
   _Finding a spiritual life, regardless of denomination or
religion.
</P>
<P>
   _A lifestyle of good nutrition and exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Carnes says addicts need not remain slaves to their sex drives,
whether they are ordinary citizens or world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have the patient's cooperation,'' he says, ``the
prognosis is good.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
