<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-UN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, ZEDILLO VOW TO IMPROVE LAW ENFORCEMENT OPERATIONS BETWEEN
U.S., MEXICO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ President Clinton and President Ernesto Zedillo
pledged Monday to avoid a repeat of the secret sting operation in
which U.S. agents arrested more than two dozen Mexican bankers
without informing the Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
   The money laundering probe, dubbed ``Operation Casablanca,''
strained relations between the United States and Mexico, a tension
that was underscored dramatically as both leaders appeared at a
special United Nations summit on drug trafficking with differing
messages.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton appealed for international cooperation, Zedillo
countered with demands that national sovereignty must be respected.
The two later met privately at the presidential suite of the
Waldorf Astoria to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The two issued a joint communique in which they ordered their
attorneys general to ``develop a process for improved consultation
and collaboration on law enforcement operations of mutual interest
and avoid actions that could have undesirable effects on the
bilateral relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement appeared to signal that the United States would
not act on its own again.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, U.S. federal agents arrested 160 people, more than
two dozen of them Mexican bankers, on charges of operating a large
scale scheme to launder drug money. U.S. officials seized $87
million, two tons of cocaine and four tons of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest of Mexican nationals without informing the Mexican
government of the pending action prompted an outcry as some in
Zedillo's government called for the extradition of the federal
agents who carried out the arrests for violation of Mexican law.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Casablanca was just the latest episode to create
friction between the United States and Mexico over the issues of
drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to the U.N. General Assembly, Clinton called for
an end to the bickering between nations and for a united effort to
curtail both production and consumption.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate between drug-supplying and drug-consuming nations
about whose responsibility the drug problem is has gone on too
long,'' Clinton told the Assembly. ``Pointing fingers is
distracting. It does not dismantle a single cartel, help a single
addict, prevent a single child from trying and perhaps dying from
heroin.''
</P>
<P>
   But Zedillo, frustrated by the U.S. actions, pointedly chastised
the United States, though not by name, for violating Mexico's
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all must respect the sovereignty of each nation so that no
one becomes a judge of others, so that no one feels entitled to
violate other country's laws for the sake of enforcing its own,''
Zedillo retorted in his remarks to the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Zedillo were among 30 heads of state who spoke at
the opening session of the U.N.'s special forum.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing a campaign to cut U.S. drug demand and consumption in
half by 2007, Clinton announced the United States would begin a
five-year, $2 billion media campaign, funded from private and
public sources, to persuade children to stay away from drugs.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the United States would create a ``virtual
university'' that would use modern technology to share drug
prevention and treatment news. He also announced the creation of an
international drug fellowship to enable foreign law officers to
train in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was the first leader to address the assembly, followed
immediately by Zedillo. Clinton sat at the United States desk and
listened intently as the Mexican president spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, who has often blamed drug consumption in the United
States for Mexico's rising crime and social problems, maintained it
is the drug-producing and drug-transit nations that suffer the most
while the drug-consuming nations often are wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our men and women who die first combating drug
trafficking. It is our communities that are the first to suffer
from violence. Our institutions that are first to be undermined by
corruption. It is our governments that are the first to have to
shift valuable resources needed to fight poverty to serve as the
first bulwark in this war,'' Zedillo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that is why we have the right to demand that this strategy
be a balanced one. Balanced so that each country recognizes that in
the fight against drug trafficking we are all co-responsible. We
have the same rights and obligations,'' Zedillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the sting operation, Mexico also bristled in recent
years over a U.S. process that requires the State Department to
certify that the Mexican government is cooperating in combating
drugs. Corruption of Mexican government officials and police, as
the nation has emerged as a major transit point for cocaine, has
been a critical problem.
</P>
<P>
   Forest fires in southern Mexico have added to the strain as
smoke has blanketed Texas and other states.
</P>
<P>
   The joint communique issued by Clinton and Zedillo, who met
formally for 40 minutes and then privately afterward, ``underscored
the importance of combating all drug trafficking, in conformity
with the laws in each country.'' It pledged to ``improve
cooperation, communication and information exchange between both
governments.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials refused to interpret the communique, saying it
spoke for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Senior administration officials also downplayed any tensions
between the two nations. ``Clearly, the mutual problem that both
nations face is what do we do about drugs and money laundering. And
we will continue to focus every effort on that. We will also
continue to work with the government of Mexico in every way
possible,'' said Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Barry McCaffrey, Clinton's drug czar, praised the U.S. Treasury
Department and Justice Department for ``aggressively pursuing
international crime.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I'm also persuaded, as are the rest of the
president's team, that we have to do this in partnership with our
neighbors and with absolute respect and deference for their own
sovereign institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   In his address, Clinton noted progress was being made in
curtailing drug abuse. He said drug use is down 49 percent in the
United States since 1979 and drug use by youths is stabilizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we come here to say no nation is so large and powerful
that it can conquer drugs alone; none is too small to make a
difference. All share a responsibility to take up this battle.
Therefore, we will stand as one against this threat to our security
and our future,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
