<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BIODEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS MORE MONEY TO COUNTER GERM WARFARE
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JUDITH MILLER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Monday asked Congress to add
some $300 million to next year's federal budget to better protect
Americans from germ and chemical attacks, a 30 percent rise in
financing, the White House announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said that the increase is the
largest single supplement to the federal budget ever requested
specifically to bolster civilian and military defenses against
chemical and biological terrorism. The government is spending an
estimated $1 billion a year on such efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The budget amendment for fiscal 1999, which begins this October,
includes $51 million to begin creating a civilian stockpile for
antibiotics and other medicines to be administered in the event of
a biological or chemical emergency. But surprisingly, the White
House did not request money for stockpiling vaccines to immunize
civilians against anthrax or other lethal biological agents.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said that the administration
had ruled out buying such vaccines this year in the hope of
developing improved ones that could immunize the nation's
population more cheaply and effectively two or three years from
now.
</P>
<P>
   But some scientists faulted the government's go-slow approach on
vaccines as unwise given the emerging germ threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am extremely disappointed that they have not gone forward
vigorously on a procurement program,'' Dr. Donald Henderson, the
scientist who led the global campaign that eradicated smallpox,
said in an interview. ``We need a Manhattan project to put
everything possible behind this. Two diseases, anthrax and
smallpox, represent the biggest problem. We have them to fear the
most.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has begun vaccinating every member of the armed
services against anthrax, one of the deadliest known biological
agents. Administering the six-shot series and yearly boosters to
the entire military _ which now has 1.4 million troops on active
duty and another 1 million reservists _ is expected to take six
years and cost an estimated $130 million.
</P>
<P>
   That vaccination program will continue, administration officials
said. ``But vaccinating civilians is another thing entirely and
we're don't think we want to do that to do that with the vaccines
currently available,'' one official explained.
</P>
<P>
   The official added that a high-level interagency committee would
consider the vaccine issue again later this year. He also said that
the new budget amendment requests $10 million for the National
Institutes of Health to help conduct vaccine research, a two-thirds
increase in the $15 million a year now allocated for such research.
Clinton has also asked Congress to give the Centers for Disease
Control an extra $43 million to help public health centers and
laboratories better detect outbreaks of suspicious diseases and
share information among them.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the administration is seeking a $16 million increase in
next year's budget for metropolitan medical strike teams, which
would increase the office's current budget from $4 to $20 million,
an almost five-fold increase.
</P>
<P>
   But the lion's share of the supplement, some $190 million, would
go to the Department of Health and Human Services, the Department
of Justice, and the Federal Emergency Management Agency for
equipping and training state and local officials to deal with a
biological or chemical weapons attack. There is no new money for
the Pentagon, which is currently spending about $50 million a year
training and equipping such officials. The Pentagon, said one
official, told the White House that it did not need additional
funds at this time. So far, it has trained so-called ``first
responders'' in 28 of the 120 cities chosen to receive such
training.
</P>
<P>
   The supplement reflects Clinton's growing alarm about the
germ-wielding terrorists who might cripple the nation by sowing
deadly epidemics. Clinton's personal interest, officials said, has
become a powerful force behind a series of secret federal meetings
and directives meant to bolster the nation's anti-terrorism work.
Clinton recently appointed a ``national coordinator'' to attacks
using weapons of mass destruction and to better prepare the country
for such an emergency. Richard Clarke, the coordinator, had pressed
hard for the extra money, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A White House statement issued Monday quoted Clinton as saying
it was ``vital that we take measures to safeguard the health and
safety of our civilian population.''
</P>
<P>
   The supplement is to be offset by budget reductions in other
agencies, especially the Justice Department, which is planning to
take $168 million out of its budget, most of its from its prison
administration budget.
</P>
<P>
   Reached late Monday evening, several aides to members of the
House and Senate appropriations committees said that Congress would
probably support most items of the Clinton's request. ``Chemical
and biological terrorism has become an equally grave concern here
on Capitol Hill,'' said one aide to a senior Republican Senate
appropriations committee member. In 1996, Congress approved a $1.2
billion supplement over five years to boost the nation's effort to
fight terrorism, some of which has been used to help foil chemical
and biological weapons attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
