<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL OF AMERICAN BALLET: STUDENTS STRUT THEIR STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The ambition and execution of the 34th Annual
Workshop Performance on Saturday afternoon at the Juilliard Theater
would have been impressive even if it had been the work of adult
professionals. But the performers were students at the New York
City Ballet-affiliated School of American Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra Danilova, a popular faculty member who died last year,
was remembered in well-danced excerpts from ``Coppelia,''
choreographed by Danilova and George Balanchine and staged by Susan
Pilarre and Garielle Whittle. The cast was led by a polished Davena
Gross and an exalted Nicole Epstein.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe Ostergren stepped in for the injured Megan Pepin in a
staging by Suki Schorer of Balanchine's ``Donizetti Variations,''
partnered by Adam Hendrickson in a performance of awesome aplomb.
Subsidiary roles were danced with endearing verve by Christina Hall
and Elizabeth Ford in a cast completed by a corps of soloist-level
dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Wheeldon's sophisticated new ``Soiree Musicale''
confirmed the choreographic gifts of this City Ballet dancer.
Wheeldon makes his performers look good in the suite of dances, set
to music by Samuel Barber and rooted in social-dance forms. An
ingeniously plotted, suggestive duet, which received a nicely
nuanced performance from Janie Taylor and Jared Angle, is at the
heart of the ballet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gounod Symphony,'' one of the great beauties of the Balanchine
repertory, is a difficult ballet, and Rebecca Krohn, partnered by a
suave Jonathan Stafford, did not make the choreography look easy.
But despite her dizzyingly busy arms, quirky attack and apparent
nerves, Ms. Krohn stood out as a dancer of rare individuality. The
ballet was staged by Ms. Pilarre.
</P>
<P>
   The winners of the school's 1998 Mae L. Wien Awards were Ms.
Pilarre, for distinguished service, and Ms. Taylor and Hendrickson,
graduating dancers, for outstanding promise.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Williams, another popular faculty member who died last
year, was remembered in a tribute on Sunday night at the Juilliard
Theater. Williams was known for his training of male dancers. A
crystalline performance of an excerpt from Peter Martins'
``Gentilhommes,'' danced by the City Ballet principal Peter Boal
and eight advanced male students, did him proud.
</P>
<P>
   Another highlight was the witty, accomplished dancing of Damian
Woetzel and Ethan Stiefel in August Bournonville's ``Jockey
Dance,'' staged by Williams. The program also included
Bournonville's ``Flower Festival'' pas de deux, danced by Miranda
Weese and Nilas Martins, and the Rose Adagio, featuring Darci
Kistler.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' teaching in classes that were meditations on form and
execution was explored on film in excerpts from a PBS Dance in
America program and from Anne Belles' ``Reaching for Perfection.''
A rather dark but amusing side of Williams was reflected in
comments by Martins and Edward Villella. Anne Hoyrup talked
charmingly of Williams as a doting uncle. Other speakers included
Albert Bellas, chairman of the school board, and Robert Weiss, a
former pupil who now directs the Carolina Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   The program ended poignantly with a poem, written and read by
Carlton Smith, director of security at the school. ``Goodbye, my
teacher, mentor and friend,'' Smith said. ``May your journey be
peaceful and bright.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
