<SLUG> BC-TAG-HEUER-AD-COLUMN-548&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: SWAPPING CUTTING-EDGE FOR CONVENTIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Switzerland)   (mk) 
 By COURTNEY KANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Swiss company TAG Heuer AG is abandoning an unusually
striking style of advertising in favor of a more traditional
campaign that uses top athletes to sell its premium-priced sports
watches.
</P>
<P>
   The cutting-edge ads for TAG Heuer proved in the end to be a bit
too sharp for the company. The print ads had featured anonymous
athletes competing against seemingly insurmountable odds: a runner
jumping over hurdles made of razor blades or a swimmer racing
against sharks.
</P>
<P>
   Now the replacement print campaign features much more
conventional images: photographs of the star athletes accompanied
by beauty shots of the watches.
</P>
<P>
   The previous campaign was ``a bit distant and a bit cold,'' said
Philippe Champion, executive vice president at the TAG Heuer
headquarters in Marin, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to add humanity to the campaign,'' he added, ``more
human presence, more emotion,'' so that consumers could ``relate
more closely to the ads.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian Viros, chief executive at TAG Heuer, said: ``Consumers
responded very positively to our old campaign. It captured the
intensity of sports and the notion of mental toughness. But looking
toward the future, our most important objective is enhancing the
prestige of the brand. We have an impressive pedigree and want to
be seen as an institution.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, which is indeed institutional in its routine
familiarity, is the first from Bartle Bogle Hegarty in London since
that agency was awarded the worldwide creative duties for TAG Heuer
in December. The ads arrive amid a fierce battle in the crowded
watch category as brands like Timex, Swatch and Swiss Army all
promote themselves as amazingly strong and reliable.
</P>
<P>
   The TAG Heuer campaign, which carries the theme ``Inner
strength,'' draws comparisons between the endurance and power
needed to succeed at the highest level in sports and the qualities
of the watches.
</P>
<P>
   An international team of athletes was assembled to appear in the
campaign. Some are well known, like the basketball player Grant
Hill and the tennis champion Boris Becker. Others are more ``Who's
that?'' like the runners Marion Jones and Colin Jackson and the
Brazilian soccer player Leonardo.
</P>
<P>
   Each ad includes text in which the athlete describes the role
that ``Inner strength'' plays in his or her competitive psyche and
overall formula for success.
</P>
<P>
   The edgier ads of the previous campaign, which carried the theme
``Success. It's a mind game,'' were created by offices of the
Paris-based agency network BDDP, now a unit of Omnicom Group; they
included Wells BDDP in New York, which closed last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've maintained the sports association which is so important
to the positioning of the brand,'' said Susan Nicholas, president
at TAG Heuer USA in Springfield, N.J. ``But in a way that relates
not only to professional athletes and sports enthusiasts but to
those who have succeeded in other disciplines.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad featuring Becker quotes him as saying: ``I drew my
strength from fear. Fear of losing. I don't remember the games I've
won, only the games I've lost.'' The ad featuring Jones, the
100-meter sprint world champion, has her stating: ``Winning is a
refusal to accept second place. It has happened to me a couple of
times, and to be honest I hated that feeling.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Each ad also explores the ``Inner strength'' of the watches. The
Becker ad describes how they are ``subjected to a program of over
60 different chemical, mechanical and atmospheric tests which
exceed industry standards,'' and the Jones ad discusses how TAG
Heuer chronographs ``are placed in a thermal tank and subjected to
extreme temperatures for 12 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads were shot by Anton Corbijn, who is known for his work
photographing musicians including Pearl Jam, U2 and REM. They are
all tinted grayish-green and white except for the green and red TAG
Heuer logo and the color of each watch face.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Hirst, an account director for TAG Heuer at Bartle Bogle,
defended the use of athletes as endorsers against criticism that it
is a hoary, overused device.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all how you present them,'' he said. ``It can be cliche,
but if you use sport in a way that is absolutely relevant to the
brand, than it's not a cliche _ and that is what we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   The American part of the worldwide campaign has begun appearing
in the June issues of 30 publications including Conde Nast
Traveler, Fortune, GQ, Golf Digest, Saveur, Skiing, Vanity Fair and
Vogue. Spending for the first year in this country was estimated at
more than $10 million. Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi in New York, part of
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC, handles the media duties for the American
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will run in more than 50 countries, with spending
internationally estimated at more than $45 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
