<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WUORINEN-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WUORINEN TRIBUTE: A COMPOSER'S 60TH, QUIRKS AND ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Tuesday, Charles Wuorinen celebrates his 60th
birthday. Two days ago, the Works and Process series at the
Guggenheim Museum was helping him get in the mood by presenting a
short concert of his music, given by longstanding friends and other
virtuosos. Many characteristic Wuorinenian qualities were
prominently on display: the rhythmic dynamism, the playfulness, the
solid and thoroughly traditional handling of instruments, the odd
combination of the studied and the quirky.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Sherry, who had given a warmly engaged performance of the
recent ``Cello Variations III'' at the start of the program, spoke
of Wuorinen with equal warmth and aptness in the middle, and told
of how, on a concert tour of Greece, the composer preferred to stay
in his hotel room composing rather than visit the Parthenon.
</P>
<P>
   This was revealing. There is probably nothing Wuorinen would
rather do than compose; that could well be what he is doing now.
But his reasons for doing so are not obvious. His works tell us
very little about him. They have their own lives to lead.
</P>
<P>
   Being so ready for life, they can be the occasions of great
performances, as they were here. Sherry was followed on the
platform by Ursula Oppens, exuberant in the piano piece ``Blue
Bamboula,'' and then by Susan Narucki and Christopher Oldfather in
three songs for soprano and piano, including a new diversion on
``Christes Crosse Be My Speede'' by Thomas Morley.
</P>
<P>
   Here the two contrapuntal lines of the accompaniment are
progressively entangled and speeded up until they start to sound
like Conlon Nancarrow's player-piano studies. Meanwhile the voice
serenely repeats its melody, except that near the end it jumps up
an octave in alarm. Ms. Narucki was beautifully steadfast,
Oldfather conscientiously deranged.
</P>
<P>
   Finally the New Jersey Percussion Ensemble gave a hugely
exciting performance of the Percussion Quartet, where music slops
and splashes between keyed instruments (vibraphones and marimbas)
and drums in both movements, the second a vigorous and learned
gigue based on something like a children's tune.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
