A9867 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MATTHEWS-MUSIC-REVIEW     06-08 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATTHEWS-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DAVE MATTHEWS BAND: CLAMOR AND HARMONY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We live in easy times, according to the prevailing mood. Stocks
are ascendant; crime has plummeted. If the late 1990s were a
rock-and-roll show, they'd be a long, mellifluous jam by the Dave
Matthews Band. Yet this pleasant haze is regularly punctuated by
hard reality: teen-agers killing teen-agers, terrorists blowing up
fairgrounds. If the late 1990s had a rock singer's voice, it would
be the cracked, capricious wail of Dave Matthews.
</P>
<P>
   The Dave Matthews Band, which played a sold-out Giants Stadium
on Sunday night, are an unassuming bunch of skilled, unassuming
musicians. Critics puzzled by the band's success have declared its
tastefully funky pop a dull soundtrack to an apathetic era. Yet the
DMB's live act clarified its appeal in ways its hits do not.
</P>
<P>
   The energy begins in its rhythms, inspired by world-music
sources including the township jive of Matthews' birthplace, South
Africa, salsa and reggae. Sunday's guest stars, the bluegrass
auteur Bela Fleck and the Johannesburg-based penny whistler
Ikgopoleng Aaron Lerole, emphasized this eclecticism. If the
remarkably agile drummer Carter Beauford and the supple bassist
Stefan Lessard simply steered the band through these wide-ranging
grooves, the Grateful Dead would have a rightful heir.
</P>
<P>
   But the DMB also found direction in forceful rock beats. Just as
a song sagged into incessant noodling, Beauford would deliver a
straightforward note on his kick drum, met by aggressive guitar
strumming from Matthews and bowing by the violinist Boyd Tinsley.
These breaks refocused the band. And while Matthews' singing, which
floated from a soul man's growl to a childlike falsetto, was as
vagrant as his coffeehouse musings, most lyrics included a hearty
sing-along chorus.
</P>
<P>
   Confidently moving between drift and drama, the DMB made its
uncanny musical blend accessible. But the music's disjunctions also
served a deeper purpose. Rock and roll's power originated in its
determination to disrupt. Now this rebelliousness seems arcane, and
young bands must find ways to renew it. The DMB does so by
incorporating clamor into a harmonious whole. Matthews' persona
further plays out this resolution. Emotionally intense but able to
roll with the punches, focused on momentary pleasures like sex and
intoxication, he is an innocent rather than a rebel, sometimes
seeking change but mostly hoping to survive it. His flexibility
makes him a hero at a time when uncertainty is a compelling force
in many people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews and his band are not the only artists adjusting rock's
disruptions to new times. Beck and Ben Folds Five, who both
delivered dynamic opening sets, approached the same conundrum in
different ways. Beck created a virtual museum of bold rock star
moves; like his music, which rearranges the jigsaw history of pop
in surprising patterns, his stage show contorted and refreshed pop
cliches, from the usual stadium patter to choreographed soul
dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Folds Five, a piano-based trio, applies rock frenzy to
whimsical lyrical subjects, like being dropped by a girlfriend
after paying for her dinner; delivered by the sweetly nerdy Ben
Folds in his reedy tenor, the band's rants illuminate and amuse.
Rumor has it that Matthews personally selected these innovative
opening acts. Perhaps he realizes that they are all allies in
keeping rock alive despite the diminishment of its chaotic spark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
