<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WHOM THE BELLS RING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Radio host, trombonist and jazz man  &UR; Mal Sharpe &LR;  called last
week to say that he probably wouldn't be there this December, &LR;  for
the Salvation Army's annual celebrity bell-ringing day in Union
Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't in good conscience do it,'' he said, because he can't
go along with the army's overt opposition to same-sex couples
living together. Like most people in the Bay Area, he has gay
relatives and friends; furthermore, he notes, a large proportion of
Union Square pedestrians he'd be panhandling that day are probably
gay.
</P>
<P>
   At least one other bell-ringer agreed, but many probably won't.
Said author  &UR; Merla Zellerbach &LR; , ``Whether you agree or not, the
Salvation Army shows a lot of guts. Bell-ringing's great and
everyone has a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Terry Lowry &LR; , a Salvation Army board member, has been ringing
bells for at least 18 years, and serves as a kind of director and
hostess for the event. She said she hadn't received any calls from
unhappy participants. ``My feeling is that the Salvation Army
doesn't ring bells for political reasons,'' she said. ``They ring
bells to help people in need.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BODILY FUNCTIONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; _ MTV UK reported that  &UR; John Travolta &LR; , trying to show his
small son a magic trick, wound up in the hospital having a marble
removed from his nose.
</P>
<P>
   _ The BBC has received a reprimand from the British Broadcasting
Standards Commission for a program in the series ``TV Dinners''
that showed the mother of a newborn preparing and eating the
placenta (sauted with shallots and garlic, flambeed, pureed and
spread on focaccia). Labour MP  &UR; Kevin McNamara  &LR; said the program
reached ``a new low in sheer grossness,'' and the BSC said it
``breached convention in a way which would have been disagreeable
to many.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Steve Finacom &LR;  found ``Daughters of the Rich,'' a one-act
play written in 1915 by  &UR; Jack London &LR;  at the Friends of the
Berkeley Public Library book sale. The dialogue includes a father
saying to his daughter, who has taken out a cigarette: ``I wish you
wouldn't smoke those things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Old-fashioned Daddy,'' she replies. ``Everybody smokes. I have
smoked ever since I was 12 years old, learned it in school, in
fact.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Jonathan Handel &LR;  saw an ``only in L.A.'' ad in the Los
Angeles Recycler classifieds: ``Wanted: StarTAC digital cell
telephone, reasonable or trade for designer eye wear.'' And
elsewhere in the South,  &UR; Jimmy Jarrett &LR;  saw a bus-stop sign for
``Alterna-Hemp shampoo'' and knew instantly it would help women
with big hair have high hair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Among the 20 best things to eat in America, according to Men's
Journal magazine: No. 5, Oysters and Pearls, as served in the
French Laundry in Yountville, in which ``Chef  &UR; Thomas &LR;   &UR; Keller &LR; 
captures the texture of sex: poached oysters nestled in a sauce of
zabaglione cream and pearl tapioca, topped with Sevruga caviar'';
and No. 8, seasonal vegetables at Chez Panisse in Berkeley.
``Whatever  &UR; Alice Waters  &LR; and her staff determine is good for you,
eat it,'' says the Journal.
</P>
<P>
   _ The precision tappers of the ``Riverdance'' troupe get a
little audio help from prerecorded taps playing during the show.
Executive producer  &UR; Julian Erskine &LR;  confirmed this augmentation to
the New York Post, explaining that audiences expect perfection
every night.
</P>
<P>
   _ Culture vultures are roaming San Francisco's Castro District
looking for Showtime subscribers, says  &UR; Strange de Jim &LR; , so they
can invite themselves in to see ``More Tales of the City.''
</P>
<P>
   _ An out-of-town pal staying at the downtown Marriott told
 &UR; Stephen Vincent  &LR; that the welcoming literature in his room
described the building as ``a work of art in itself.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A bulletin from the Association for Dressings and Sauces in
Atlanta advises food preparers to ``Practice Cleanliness,'' and it
couldn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   _ Panicking over last week's news that  &UR; Ginger &LR;  is leaving the
Spice Girls,  &UR; Bob Wieder  &LR; says he hasn't been so upset since Snap
walked out on Crackle and Pop, and the Rice Crispie Boys broke up.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Jim Hoffman  &LR; reports that his pal, a medical resident at the
University of California at Davis Med Center, was treated recently
by a pharmaceutical company to a ``Residents' Appreciation
Dinner,'' in which the promotional giveaways included an official
Prozac Beanie Baby.
</P>
