<HEADER>
A9876 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-LAWYERS-ART-9     06-08 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-LAWYERS-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS FIGHT TO COLLECT FEES FROM STATES IN TOBACCO SUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV.: a map and a photo are being sent to NYT photo and
graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
(JT)  
 By BARRY MEIER and JILL ABRAMSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lawyers who fought the tobacco industry have found a new focus
for their energies: fighting for their share of the spoils from
lawsuits against the industry.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the issue of the lawyers' fees has been the
focus of intense controversy in states that have settled lawsuits
against cigarette makers. But now the debate has also erupted in
Washington, where Congress is considering federal legislation that
will resolve many tobacco lawsuits and allow the government to
regulate nicotine.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is the richest pot of legal fees ever to be awarded _
billions of dollars scheduled to be paid to a small group of trial
lawyers who were either hired by state attorneys general to sue
cigarette makers on the states' behalf, or who brought class-action
claims on behalf of smokers.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas and Florida, which have already settled with the
industry, a battle has broken out over fees to lawyers that could
exceed $3.4 billion in those two states. And if lawyers, whose
cases were to have been paid as part of last June's proposed $368.5
billion settlement between the industry and 41 other states, were
awarded fees of just 5 percent, the earnings of some 160 law firms
nationwide could reach $18 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of such huge awards has triggered outcries,
particularly from conservative Republicans who have long sought to
rein in the fees of trial lawyers, traditionally big donors to
Democrats. Even some moderates like Sen. John McCain, the Arizona
Republican who is the sponsor of a new $516-billion tobacco bill
before Congress, have begun to argue for controls on fees.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of tobacco cases that would have been settled
under the 1997 accord are still in the courts. But some of them, in
particular a number of class-action cases, risk being pre-empted by
federal tobacco legislation or are given little chance for success
at trial. Fears that the fees will be scaled back has inspired
intense lobbying by trial lawyers from more than 65 firms
nationwide, who are spending millions of dollars in an effort to
insure that the fees are paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a large body of opinion that the present scenario is
skewed too much in favor of the trial lawyers,'' said McCain. He
added that he had recently asked Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., to
propose limits on lawyer fees resulting from federal legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who led cases against cigarette makers say they deserve
to be richly rewarded. They point out that they took big risks b
taking cases on contingency, spending millions of dollars of their
own money suing the tobacco industry at a time when many experts
believed it was invulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers, including Richard Scruggs, the brother-in-law of
Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader, are already
multi-millionaires as the result of lawsuits brought against
asbestos producers. Others, like John Coale, a class-action lawyer
from Washington, built their reputations on more controversial
ventures. Coale, for example, raced to Bhopal, India, in the
mid-1980s to sign up clients who were victims of the explosion of a
Union Carbide chemical plant there.
</P>
<P>
   Those class-action cases, which were filed in some 25 states, do
not seek monetary damages for smokers but rather demand that the
industry pay for programs like smoking-cessation courses. However,
many tobacco proposals now before Congress would finance such
programs and so effectively pre-empt the lawsuits and the lawyers'
chance to collect fees.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette makers had agreed to settle the class-action lawsuits,
a step that would qualify them to collect fees as part of their
tobacco bills. Herman said that he believed that he and his
colleagues deserved to be paid because they had invested millions
of dollars in the lawsuits and convinced the industry last June to
finance programs like the smoking-cessation courses.
</P>
<P>
   But since the June plan, some of the class-action lawsuits have
faced setbacks in the courts and some lawmakers, like Rep. Martin
Meehan, D-Mass., have declined to include the cases in their bills,
saying that any special consideration for trial lawyers could
damage a bill's bipartisan appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even if the class-action lawsuits are not covered,
federal tobacco legislation, if passed, could generate billions in
fees because such a law would settle the remaining state lawsuits
against the tobacco companies that seek to recover the cost of
treating smoking-related illnesses. To handle those cases, state
attorneys general, beginning in 1994, hired outside law firms and
signed contracts which, depending on the state, guaranteed the
lawyers 3 percent to 33 percent of any recovery.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical contingency fee case, it is not unusual for lawyers
to receive 33 percent of an award. However, the settlement amount
in the tobacco cases are so large that many legal experts believe
that the fees generated y such contracts are excessive.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, about 100 law firms were retained, although just a
handful of lawyers dominated the cases. For example, the law firm
headed by Scruggs represented Mississippi, the first state to sue,
and was later hired by 29 other states. Ness, Motley, Loadholt &AMP;
Richardson, a law firm in Charleston, S.C., was retained by many of
the same states.
</P>
<P>
   But as Congress debates a tobacco bill, lawyers in some states
that have already settled their cases are battling each other over
fees with the same fervor they once reserved for cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a battle has been under way in Texas for months
over the $2.3 billion in fees sought by a group of prominent trial
lawyers who negotiated the state's $15.3 billion settlement with
the tobacco industry in January. The lawyers say they were promised
15 percent of the Texas award when they agreed in 1996 to represent
state Attorney General Dan Morales.
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. George Bush of Texas, a Republican, opposes the award,
calling it outrageous and unjustified. A legal expert hired by Bush
has estimated that the fees sought by the lawyers equal an hourly
billing rate of $92,000.
</P>
<P>
   The fight recently took a bizarre turn when Joe Jamail, one of
the country's richest trial lawyers, said that Morales had demanded
a $1 million payment from him in a 1996 meeting to discuss the
possibility of Morales hiring Jamail to head the state's legal
team. Jamail was not hired.
</P>
<P>
   Morales has denied the claim calling it a ``sideshow'' concocted
by his political enemies to divert attention from the ``improper
conduct'' of state officials like Bush, who are trying to change
the settlement terms. He has also asked a federal judge for
millions of dollars in sanctions Bush and others.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers fear that the Texas spectacle and a similar fight
over legal fees in Florida are only feeding the anti-lawyer
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these tobacco lawyers are becoming the poster children
for tort reform,'' said Scruggs, who is from Pascagoula, Miss.
``The biggest problem is that some of these lawyers don't give a
damn about their colleagues. They just want their money.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the fee issue has split lawmakers on both the
state and federal levels along partisan lines. Many of the lawyers
involved in lawsuits against the tobacco industry are well-known in
Washington because of their large contributions to the Democratic
Party. Since 1995, lawyers from 13 firms with tobacco cases have
made nearly $3 million in political contributions, with the vast
majority going to Democratic Party committees or candidates, public
records show.
</P>
<P>
   Trial lawyers have been battling tort reform legislation
championed by business interests and Republicans in the Congress.
They have been among the Democratic Party's most generous and
stalwart contributors over the last decade. The tobacco settlement
reached last year has deeply divided the Association of Trial
Lawyers of America, because it curbs the future ability of lawyers
to sue the tobacco industry. However, some of ATLA's most prominent
members are the very lawyers who have sued the tobacco industry and
stand to gain from national tobacco legislation.
</P>
<P>
   And since last June, many of those lawyers have also spent
heavily on lobbying on behalf of tobacco legislation. Scruggs, for
example, estimated that his firm paid some $2 million over the past
year to three lobbying firms. He said that virtually all of that
lobbying has been in support of tobacco legislation, rather than on
the issue of fees.
</P>
<P>
   Under most pending federal tobacco bills, an arbitration panel
would be established to weigh lawyers' claims for fees and to award
up to $500 million annually. That method is also being backed by
tobacco companies and by many trial lawyers like Scruggs, who under
his contracts with Mississippi, Texas and Florida already stands to
share in more than $4.5 billion in fees.
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts also say that resolving fee disputes through
arbitration may defuse partisan bickering. ``We need to get one
step removed from the politics of attorneys' fees awards,'' said
Robert Rabin, a professor at Stanford University Law School, who
has followed tobacco litigation.
</P>
<P>
   But other experts argue that because Congress is being asked to
settle lawsuits, lawmakers should set the fees. And some
politicians fear that even arbitration will result in too much
money going to lawyers. As a result, some lawmakers that fees in
tobacco cases should be limited to an hourly rate.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Senate narrowly defeated a proposal to cap the
hourly rate for plaintiffs' lawyers in tobacco cases at $250 an
hour. And there are even more stringent bills to cap fees in the
House, with one proposal calling for a $150-an-hour rate.
Separately, a tobacco bill introduced by two Republican senators,
Phil Gramm of Texas and Pete Domenici of New Mexico, would take a
different approach by imposing a tax on lawyers' windfall profits.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
