u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKS-MARKETPLACE-ART     06-08 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-MARKETPLACE-ART-548&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: WHERE'S THE SHAREHOLDERS' PREMIUM? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Word Monday that Norwest and Wells Fargo plan to merge in a
stock-for-stock transaction may have set bank stock investors'
pulses racing. But for those who had hoped the most recent
mega-merger would breathe a little life into bank stocks, the
sector was a letdown.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Philadelphia Stock Exchange's bank stock index could
not even eke out a 1 percent gain Monday. The index, which closed
on Friday at 850, traded as high as 858 during the day. But by the
close of trading, it had settled back to 857, an eight-tenths of a
percent rise.
</P>
<P>
   Bank stocks, in general, are down between 9 percent and 12
percent from their highs achieved in April of this year. Money
center banks, like Citicorp and J.P. Morgan, are down slightly more
than regional banks like Fleet Financial or First Chicago NBD. This
likely reflects two views: one, that problem loans in Asia will
affect money center banks more than regionals. And two,
notwithstanding occasional rumors about J.P. Morgan as a possible
takeover candidate, regional banks are the only buyouts likely to
take place the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Even if more bank takeovers happen, they will not be done at
enormous premiums to prevailing market prices. In fact, the
Norwest-Wells Fargo deal confirms the recent trend toward so-called
mergers of equals in which little in the way of a premium is paid
by the acquirer to shareholders of the company that's being bought
out.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a bank might pay 30 percent above the prevailing
market price for another in a buyout, but managements are now
dispensing 10 percent or less to shareholders in the acquired
concern.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say this shift to considerably lower premiums has
not been fully digested by investors. ``Many investors still
believe that today's mergers will push their stocks up on big
takeover premiums,'' said Thomas Theurkauf, senior vice president
at Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods, a bank research concern. Investors may
feel justified in clinging to this belief as bank stocks'
price/earnings multiples are between 25 percent and 30 percent
below the multiple on the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500.
</P>
<P>
   But this old way of thinking can buy investors trouble. Those
who bought shares in Wells Fargo in early May, when the rumors of
its imminent takeover were rife, are facing losses today of around
6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Where did all those juicy takeover premiums go?
</P>
<P>
   There are several forces at work in the shift. For starters,
bank stocks have had a monumental run in recent years. Though they
have come off their highs this year, the bank stock index is still
24 percent above its January lows. Investors cannot expect rich
premiums over these already high prices in a takeover.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the currency used to make these acquisitions _
shares of the acquirer's stock _ is down from April. As bank stocks
have fallen in value the last two months, so, too, has the currency
used by acquirers to do their deals.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind, bank mergers are not struck because they are a
cheap way to amass assets. They are done because industry growth is
slowing. ``If everybody was growing their revenues by 20 percent,
you wouldn't see these deals,'' said Diane Glossman, bank analyst
at Lehman Brothers. ``Deals are happening because top-line growth
is relatively limited.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Also cutting into the premiums paid in these takeovers may be
the realization among bank managements that they will be forced to
make enormous investments in technology. And, the jury is still
decidedly out on how well these recent mergers will be integrated.
If the integration is not smooth, the entire bank could be at risk.
It was essentially Wells Fargo's difficulties in meshing its
two-year-old acquisition of First Interstate that forced it into
the arms of Norwest.
</P>
<P>
   Lower merger premiums are not the only part of the bank merger
scene that's beginning to look different. Charles Peabody, analyst
at Mitchell Securities in New York, said the pace of big-bank
mergers will slow in coming months. ``We're starting to see who the
survivors are going to be _ BankAmerica-Nationsbank,
Travelers-Citicorp, First Chicago NBD and Norwest-Wells Fargo,'' he
said. `Those guys may want to make another acquisition, but they
can't do the next big deal because they need to integrate what
they've got.'' It can take up to three years to digest one of these
huge acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   And, while smaller banks may continue to benefit from takeovers,
the prices at which these deals are struck might be disappointing.
Like Wells Fargo's stock price in May, many of these banks' shares
have been bid up to unsustainable levels in deal mania. Theurkauf
at Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods said, ``Small to midsize regional
banking companies that carry a big premium to the group are
especially vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Any stock trading well above 18 times earnings may
be too rich. As Wells Fargo shareholders found, premiums can
evaporate fast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
