<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9881 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONRAIL-COX     06-08 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONRAIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Watershed day' for CSX, Norfolk Southern
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The federal Surface Transportation Board voted Monday
to approve in principle the $10 billion purchase of Conrail by
rivals CSX Corp. and Norfolk Southern Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The board decision, which will be published formally July 23,
becomes effective Aug. 22, freeing CSX and Norfolk Southern to
begin changing routes to absorb the Conrail lines and facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Implementation of the new competing rail systems promises to
speed shipments between Southern states to and from the Northeast
and Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   The railroads have hailed this new service as a means to make
them more competitive with traditional truck traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a nation that depends on safe, efficient, reliable rail
transportation service, June 8 will be remembered as a watershed
day,'' said David R. Good, chairman and chief executive of Norfolk
Southern.
</P>
<P>
   Equally pleased by the board approval, John W. Snow, chairman of
CSX, said, ``This marks the dawn of a new era of transportation
growth, in jobs and business development ...''
</P>
<P>
   To gain approval, the two competing Eastern railroads modified
the application to address concerns of some communities, including
the area around Cleveland, Ohio, where citizens worried about the
noise and congestion from increased traffic.
</P>
<P>
   CSX said the new service will open the way for faster
single-line service from Montreal to Miami, from Boston to Atlanta,
and from the farms factories of the Midwest to East Coast ports.
</P>
<P>
   Norfolk Southern has been particularly enthusiastic about
potential improved service between Atlanta and the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Both railroads say the improved service will mean more jobs and
and a bigger presence in Georgia and the Atlanta area.
</P>
<P>
   Some parties, including New York City and several labor unions,
have indicated they may challenge the final merger approval with
court litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Some New York officials insist the plans need to be changed to
assure competition in the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
