<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORUM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Experts: Big future in online commerce, but overhaul neededBy
Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ From groceries to factory parts to European vacations,
online commerce is forecast to top $600 billion in sales within
five years _ but only if corporate America drastically overhauls
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   That's the assessment of technology experts at this week's
SuperComm, the world's largest communications conference, which is
expected to draw 45,000 people to Atlanta's Georgia World Congress
Center this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make the Internet business-class,'' Bay Networks
Executive Vice President Stephen Pearse told Monday's luncheon
panel. ``It is not safe to go into the water yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The buying and selling of goods and services over the Internet
is estimated at $100 billion, and it is rising fast. It will more
than double to $208 billion in 2000 and reach $633 billion in 2003,
according to the Yankee Group, a Boston consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   In an increasingly typical example, Yankee Group Senior Vice
President Robert Rich said, he and his wife, Barbara, relied on
electronic mail to plan a vacation next week in Austria and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet ``is becoming more a part of the everyday market
for ... the technologically advanced family,'' said Rich, adding
that the trend is accelerating with the steady decline in personal
computer prices.
</P>
<P>
   The growth in commerce, however, is headed for a collision
course with what Pearse calls ``Web mania,'' the public's exploding
interest in sending electronic mail, playing games and searching
for information on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Just as people sometimes run into snags cruising the Internet, a
growing number of the companies that move massive volumes of
information online face similar obstacles, but on a much broader
scale, Rich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most companies, the Internet is not mission-critical right
now,'' Rich said. ``But if we want this to become a
business-to-business market, we have to invest in the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The word is spreading. According to Pearse, technology suppliers
to the Internet are doubling their investment in routers, cables
and other equipment to $20 billion over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
