<HEADER>
A9884 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-COX     06-08 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strike in Michigan may have far-reaching consequences
 &HT;    By Mike Drummond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A strike at a General Motors Corp. plant in
Flint, Mich., triggered parts shortages Monday that shut down the
company's truck assembly plant in Moraine, Ohio and two other
assembly plants in Michigan and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Two shifts of employees represented by the International Union
of Electronics Workers Local 801 in Moraine were sent home Monday
after putting in five hours' work. About 4,200 hourly employees
work at the Moraine plant, which will remain idle until the United
Auto Workers Local 659 and GM settle the five-day strike at the
Flint Metal Center north of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The center stamps hoods, fenders, doors and other body parts
that supply the Moraine plant, which has capacity to roll out about
1,200 GMC Jimmy, Chevrolet Blazer and Oldsmobile Bravada sport
utility vehicles a day, according to employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Moraine shutdown highlights one of the pitfalls of
just-in-time-delivery of parts, a relatively recent business
practice that reduces inventory and other costs, but leaves
parts-dependent plants vulnerable to labor disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW strike also idled an assembly plants in Orion Twp.,
Michigan and Fairfax, Kan., GM said. The two plants employ about
4,300 workers.
</P>
<P>
   The company declined to reveal how many other plants could shut
down if the strike lingers. But David Cole, director of the Office
for the Study of Automotive Transportation at the University of
Michigan, said the woes in Flint could affect more than a dozen
facilities nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Idled Moraine plant workers may be eligible for unemployment
benefits equal to 95 percent of their take-home pay, said Local 801
Vice President Blake Griffin. The state pays up to 50 percent of a
workers' take-home pay, with the company or the union footing most
of the balance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, before the state issues any checks, the Ohio Bureau of
Employment Services must determine if the layoffs are due to a
labor dispute or a lack of work as the result of a parts shortage,
a decision that could be reached by Wednesday, said OBES spokesman
David Garick.
</P>
<P>
   If the state finds a parts shortage triggered layoffs, Moraine
plant workers could be eligible for checks in about two weeks, at
the earliest, Garick said. But if the state determines the UAW
labor dispute caused the IUE layoffs, the state would call a public
hearing, which could lead to a denial of employment benefits. A
public hearing would delay any payments at least 30 days, Garick
said.
</P>
<P>
   Because two unions are involved, ``These things get very
complicated,'' Garick said.
</P>
<P>
   A company memo issued to employees Monday said if the plant is
still quiet by Thursday, regular paychecks for ``A'' and ``B''
shift workers will be available. Swing or ``C'' shift workers will
be able to collect their checks ``in the normal manner,'' the memo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Local 801 members said they support the UAW, despite the fact
the UAW has been critical of the IUE over the years because it has
compromised more with GM and agreed to different pay for workers
doing the same jobs. The fact Local 801 members may be eligible for
unemployment compensation buoyed the solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   By 11 a.m., the first wave of idled Moraine plant workers
crowded into the Upper Deck Tavern across the street from the
Moraine plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to accept the time off when you're getting paid,''
said Jeff Smith, 30, of West Carrollton, Ohio, while enjoying his
third Miller Lite of the morning. ``The job is boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Gosney, 28, of Carlisle, sipped a bottle of Stroh's in
solidarity with the UAW.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about supporting people,'' Gosney said. ``If not, why
even have unions.''
</P>
<P>
   Down time is nothing new at the Moraine plant. GM halted
production for a week in May, citing an overload of inventory due
to slumping sales of its sport utility vehicles and stiff
competition from Chrysler's new Dodge Durango. The company also
will expand a scheduled shutdown in August by two days starting
Aug. 10 to help control inventory at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 3,400 workers are employed at GM's Flint center, which
analysts say is not as competitive as others in the industry. The
strike is the seventh at a domestic GM plant since early 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Flint union leaders said GM reneged on some of the $300 million
investment planned for the their plant. They also object to what
they say are GM's plans to cut 191 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   GM maintains the union has not cooperated with changes to make
the plant more competitive. The company insists it has made a
significant portion of the planned investment, though officials
will not say how much.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute in Flint escalated in late May, when the automaker
removed equipment at its key stamping plant and moved it to an
undisclosed site. Although employees speculated the company hauled
the die-stamp equipment to Mexico, GM refused to disclose where it
shipped the machinery.
</P>
<P>
   One Wall Street on Monday, GM stock (NYSE: GM) closed at 73 7/8,
down 1 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
