<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERCOMM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich encourages funding of research agencies By Michael E.
Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The champion of sleeked-down government has called for
doubling the federal budget for basic research.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich, speaking Monday at the Supercomm
trade show, said he supports a potent injection of cash into
agencies that do that research and development work including the
National Institutes of Health, the National Science Foundation and
the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA). Those
agencies fund science that would not be likely be done by the
private sector, since it would not prove profitable quickly.
</P>
<P>
   However, that research can lead to dramatic breakthroughs _ such
as the Internet, which is often credited to DARPA funding. ``Basic
research has enriched this country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But accompanying Gingrich's support for bigger budgets is a
demand for greater openness and efficiency. All agencies _
especially those doing high-tech research _ should have top-notch
Internet sites that are accessible to researchers and interested
citizens, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said he thinks society and government should be updated
to combine the best elements of technology and democracy. ``The
public sector is operating at a rate that is inappropriate to the
world around it.''
</P>
<P>
   Businesses succeed or fail based on a ``performance-based,
achievement-based standard,'' while the government faces no such
tests, he said. ``That is exactly wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about Gingrich's presidential ambitions has been
spurred in recent months by his increasingly feisty posture toward
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Long a technology buff, Gingrich has also warned of trouble with
the government's preparations for handling ``the millenium bug,''
the problem many computers will have in telling the difference
between Jan. 1, 2000, and the same date a century earlier. Gingrich
said every large government department is behind schedule in
dealing with the issue _ something with implications for at leat
one potential rival for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine anything more destructive for Vice President
Gore's political careers than to talk about the information highway
and then have the largest wreck in history on Jan. 1, 2000,''
Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   A futurist friend of Gingrich, George Gilder, will deliver
Supercomm's closing address Thursday morning. Preceding Gingrich on
the stage Monday was Nobel Prize Winner Arno Penzias of Lucent
Technologies subsidiary Bell Labs.
</P>
<P>
   Penzias predicted that the cost of building a computer will soon
be comparable to a postage stamp, ``although what Intel will charge
for it, I do not know.''
</P>
<P>
   With computing that cheap, various new networks will spring up
in addition to those that now carry phone calls and computer
messages, he said. For instance, appliances from toaster to freezer
will soon be computer controlled, he said. Penzias said he expects
increased links between all those networks. ``To me, that's really
the local telephone business of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Penzias said the best opportunity might be for technology to
help solve the nation's transportation problems. ``You could be the
Microsoft of transportation.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
