<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9888 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BULLS-COX0609     06-08 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0609 &HT;    Kukoc-Rodman switch thriving
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ It was a curious move by coach Phil Jackson. Whether
he turned Toni Kukoc into a starter and Dennis Rodman into a
reserve because of matchups, as Jackson said, or punishment for
Rodman's perpetual tardiness, as many believe, it's worked out
nicely for the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc _ dubbed the Croatian Sensation _ has been a viable
offensive weapon at the start of games, and Rodman finally has
stopped sulking and delivered the kind of energy, defense and
rebounding Chicago needs to fulfill its championship ambition.
Those two are major reasons the Bulls are within two victories of
their sixth NBA title in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of Toni and Dennis has given us great play,''
Chicago guard Steve Kerr said. ``They changed when they'll play,
but they didn't change roles. And it's given us what we needed at
different times in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc has wanted to be a starter for a long time, but there was
no place for him to crack the lineup with Rodman at power forward
and Scottie Pippen at the other forward. So he became one of the
best sixth men in the league, with guard's skills in a flexible
6-foot-10 body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toni can cause problems for any defense,'' Michael Jordan
said. ``His skills make it tough to defend him.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Indiana in the Eastern Conference finals, Jackson said
he elevated Kukoc to starter because he wanted Rodman to match up
with Antonio Davis, the Indiana Pacers' top substitute. Jackson's
decision came after Rodman missed a practice and showed up late for
the first two games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc did not question why he suddenly became a starter; he just
flourished. Matched against any of the Pacers' big men, Kukoc took
them outside, where they were uncomfortable. When defended by
smaller players, he moved inside.
</P>
<P>
   In the deciding Game 7 of the conference finals, Kukoc scored 21
points and helped lead Chicago to victory. He has been a major
factor in two victories against Utah.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2, he attacked the basket off the dribble early,
establishing a mindset that carried the Bulls to a critical
victory. And in Sunday night's historic 96-54 crushing of the Jazz,
Kukoc had 16 points, four rebounds, four assists and two steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need Toni's offense, and he's been giving it to us,''
Pippen said. ``He takes pressure off me and Michael to carry all
the load. That's what Phil was looking for in starting Toni.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all worked out _ so far, at least _ because Rodman, in his
own words, has ``decided to just shut up and play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Toni's in there, and that's it,'' Rodman said. ``I just know I
have to do my thing when I get in. It's tough, because I've started
all year. But we're trying to win a championship, so you just play
when you're told.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
