<HEADER>
A9889 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAZZ-COX0609     06-08 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0609 &HT;    Intense Sloan mellows
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ It was the morning after Utah's Game 1 victory in the
Finals, and Jerry Sloan was listening to reports of discord among
the Chicago Bulls. He was openly skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've never been inside my huddle,'' he said, recounting
strong disagreements among his players. ``When it happens I tell
'em, `Look, you guys want to fight, wait until after the game.
We'll get the ice picks and go out in the parking lot.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan grins under the John Deere tractor hat he wears, the one
with ``Coach Sloan'' written on the back. He's not a very patient
man, and he doesn't suffer fools very well.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter asks a question, and Sloan says he already has dealt
with that issue earlier. ``Where were you?'' he asks. Sloan decides
to answer the question anyway, and when the reporter begins to walk
away, Sloan grabs his shoulder and says, ``Hey, I didn't hurt your
feelings, did I?''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, he wouldn't have worried about the reporter's
feelings. Wouldn't have answered the question, either.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Jerry Sloan is a tough guy. Always was. He came
from tiny Evansville College in the 1960s and earned a reputation
as the toughest player in the NBA. Although he couldn't shoot a
lick, he still made the All-NBA team twice on the strength of his
defense. He was named to the All-NBA defensive team six times.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Loughery, who played against Sloan, compared his
relentlessness on the court to Michael Jordan's and Bill Russell's.
``Only thing is, Jerry wasn't the most talented guy in the world,''
Loughery said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why what happened here Sunday _ Chicago's 96-54 victory
in Game 3 of the NBA finals _ is so difficult for Sloan to stomach.
His teams are supposed to compete. Period. But his Utah team was
manhandled.
</P>
<P>
   So Sloan was faced with the task of picking up the pieces on
Monday. A year ago, it would have been a fire-and-brimstone
proposition. But Sloan has been calm this week, mellowed by what he
calls, ``the toughest year of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, after the Jazz lost to the Bulls in the finals, his
wife, Bobbye, was diagnosed with breast cancer. The chemotherapy,
then the surgery in January, the wrenching emotional turns of
despair, hope and recovery have softened Jerry Sloan, a little
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Miller, who owns the Jazz, says he saw a new side of Sloan
in February, when the Rony Seikaly trade broke down and Greg Foster
and Chris Morris were returned to the team.
</P>
<P>
   Foster and Morris were angry, and Miller asked them in front of
the team if they were going to accept what happened and get on with
the season.
</P>
<P>
   He asked Sloan if he had anything to say. ``He said, `Yeah,
there is,' and he started talking about Bobbye. Blew my mind. I
mean, I think it blew everybody's mind, because he's never done
that. He said, `I've learned what's important. We all like to win
basketball games, but winning games isn't as important as your wife
and your family and stuff like that.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He did it in about two minutes,'' Miller said. ``It was so out
of character for him. But it really showed all of us a side of him
that he had never been willing to disclose to us before, especially
as a group. It simply boils down to him learning what really is
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why Sloan did not wreak havoc after Sunday's
debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm somewhat embarrassed for NBA basketball,'' he said after
the loss. ``I can accept losing, but it's always a disappointment
not playing hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Their lackadaisical effort landed the Jazz in the record book
for futility. Utah's 54 points are the fewest scored in an NBA game
since the inception of the 24-second shot clock in 1954-55, one
point less than Indiana's output against the San Antonio Spurs in
March.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the 42-point victory is the largest margin of victory
in NBA Finals history, eclipsing a 35-point Washington victory over
Seattle in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an embarrassment to all of us,'' Sloan said.
</P>
<P>
   And that was enough.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
