<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-NERVE-GAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON TO INVESTIGATE CHARGES IT USED NERVE GAS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JAMES RISEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defense Secretary William Cohen has ordered an
inquiry into new charges that U.S. forces used nerve gas against
U.S. defectors during the Vietnam War, the Pentagon said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen stressed that the Pentagon had not found evidence to
substantiate the allegations, which were raised by Cable News
Network and Time magazine. But he said he had asked the Air Force
and the Army to search their records from the Vietnam War era to
determine whether the accusations have merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a serious allegation, obviously,'' Cohen said Monday.
``And it's something that I have asked the service secretaries and
those acting in their place to conduct an investigation and to find
out whatever information that could validate these charges. At this
point, I see no such information that would support that. But you
know, it is always possible. So we will continue to look at it, and
I will follow up with the information that comes from the service
secretaries.''
</P>
<P>
   The CNN report on Sunday asserted that sarin, a lethal nerve
gas, was used by U.S. Special Forces in a covert operation in Laos
in September 1970 aimed at a village believed to be harboring U.S.
soldiers who had defected. The Time article on the subject was
published concurrently; Time and CNN are both owned by Time-Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Code-named Operation Tailwind, the mission was to attack the
village and kill the defectors, according to the CNN-Time account.
Quoting several soldiers who said they had been involved, CNN and
Time reported that the unit found a number of white men in the
village whom they believed to be U.S. defectors. In the report one
officer described chasing two white men into a tunnel system, and
then dropping in a grenade, presumably killing them.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief attack on the village, the report alleges,
Montagnard tribesmen fighting with the special forces said they
found several Americans dead in the village huts, but no bodies
were identified or recovered.
</P>
<P>
   As the special forces unit was withdrawing, it came under
increased fire and called for air support, according to the report.
Air Force planes then dropped gas canisters on North Vietnamese and
Pathet Lao soldiers, and the U.S. soldiers say they saw the enemy
troops vomiting and convulsing from exposure to the gas. CNN and
Time added that ``veteran special forces officers'' said sarin was
also used the night before the raid to ``prepare'' the village for
the upcoming attack, indicating that civilians as well as soldiers
were exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Time reported that Thomas Moorer, a retired Navy admiral who
served as chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff in 1970, confirmed
the use of sarin during the Laotian mission and on a number of
search-and-rescue missions for downed U.S. pilots during the war
</P>
<P>
   But Moorer said Monday that he had no firsthand knowledge of the
Laotian mission, or of the use of sarin in Vietnam. ``The
authorization for the use of gas would have had to come from higher
than me,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
