<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAIL-ABUSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS GUARD ARRESTED FOR ALLEGEDLY ABUSING MISSOURI INMATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Mo.) 
 
(Eds.: A tilde goes over N in ZUNIGA) 
 
By JO ANN ZUNIGA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A former Houston-area jail guard was arrested Monday
for allegedly slamming a Missouri inmate's face into a wall, an
incident that was uncovered in an investigation of videotaped abuse
of prisoners by guards.
</P>
<P>
   Wilton David Wallace, 50, was arrested on federal civil rights
charges at 6:30 a.m. Monday at his home in Angleton and taken
before a federal magistrate, said Don K. Clark, special agent in
charge of the Houston FBI office.
</P>
<P>
   Angleton is about 35 miles south of downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In the Nov. 7, 1996, incident, inmate Clarence Fisher lost a
tooth and suffered facial injuries at the Brazoria County jail.
Fisher was one of hundreds of Missouri inmates housed at the East
Texas jail through a contract with Capital Correctional Resources
Inc., a private Texas company.
</P>
<P>
   Although the November incident was not videotaped, the charge
did stem from an investigation into the tape of the Sept. 18, 1996,
incident, Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   On that videotape, which was released in August 1997 and
televised nationally, prisoners from the state of Missouri can be
seen being prodded with stun guns, kicked by guards and bitten by
police dogs as they are forced to crawl on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our investigation into Brazoria County is still ongoing,''
said Clark, who declined to specify whether any subsequent
indictments would involve guards hired by CCRI as Wallace was, or
sheriff's deputies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we're looking into a wide spectrum,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Brazoria County authorities had brought the
problem and the videotape to the federal agency's attention.
</P>
<P>
   James H. DeAtley, U.S. attorney for the Southern District of
Texas, said Wallace could get 10 years in prison and fined $250,000
if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This indictment represents a commitment by this office to
ensure that all citizens, even those who are serving terms of
imprisonment, have their civil rights protected,'' DeAtley said.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Nixon, attorney general of Missouri, said, ``What we saw in
the videotape was not acceptable conduct. We do not allow and do
not condone abusive conduct toward our inmates. In Missouri we
believe in hard time, not abusive time.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the investigation had shown ``CCRI had not done a
good enough job to ensure the guards were controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace told U.S. Magistrate John Froeschner that he understood
his rights and that he could not afford an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Froeschner released him on a $25,000 personal recognizance bond
and ordered the U.S. Public Defender's office in Houston to
represent him. After signing bond papers, Wallace left the
courthouse with his wife. He will be formally arraigned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who CCRI employed as a lieutenant, pleaded guilty to
brutalizing an inmate with a riot stick in 1983, when he was a
major in a Texas state prison, the Darrington unit. He was
sentenced to five months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   On the Brazoria County videotape, Wallace is shown pushing an
inmate on the floor with his foot.
</P>
<P>
   Private guards and sheriff's emergency response team officers
clad in riot gear were involved in the incident, which sheriff's
officials have said was sparked when some prisoners tossed food
trays and guards smelled marijuana smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The handling of the disturbance, which was taped for later use
as a training video, led to the FBI investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri has since canceled contracts totaling $12 million with
Brazoria, Limestone and Gregg counties, where jails are managed by
Capital Correctional Resources Inc.
</P>
<P>
   More than 400 inmates were withdrawn and bused back to Missouri.
CCRI laid off most of the 82 full-time employees and 33 part-time
employees who had been hired to guard them.
</P>
<P>
   Officials for CCRI, which was previously headquartered in
Groesbeck, Texas, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Brazoria County District Attorney Jerome Aldrich, who gave the
FBI and the state Commission on Jail Standards copies of the
videotape, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Brazoria County Sheriff Joe King's office also declined comment,
saying Wallace was not his employee.
</P>
<P>
   The videotape and alleged assaults have spawned at least two
lawsuits _ one from inmates and another from Missouri seeking
additional information for a possible breach of contract lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, who is now serving his 10-year robbery sentence in
Sikeston, Mo., is one of about 500 inmates who have filed federal
civil rights lawsuits against CCRI.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
