<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9894 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-PRIVILEGE-BOS &LR;      06-08 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-PRIVILEGE-BOS </SLUG>
  
 JUSTICES HEAR STARR'S CASE THAT DEATH ENDS LAWYER-CLIENT PRIVILEGE
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prosecutors for the independent counsel, Kenneth W.
Starr, argued before the Supreme Court Monday that notes from a
conversation between the late White House aide Vincent Foster and
his lawyer should be turned over to the Whitewater grand jury. If
the court agrees, the relationship between attorneys and their
clients could be forever changed.
</P>
<P>
   The case marks the the first time the court has addressed this
bedrock aspect of legal practice. Foster's lawyer, James Hamilton,
argued Monday that the attorney-client privilege should extend
beyond a client's death in order to protect reputations and promote
candor between lawyers and those they represent. As Hamilton argued
before the justices, President Clinton's personal lawyer, David
Kendall, watched intently from the middle of the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do care about reputations and the faith of family and
friends after their death,'' said Hamilton. He added that if the
attorney-client privilege ends with death, it would have a
``significant chilling effect on client candor.''
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Starr told the nine justices that the notes between
Hamilton and Foster were crucial to the investigation and should be
turned over to the grand jury in the pursuit of truth. Starr is
investigating whether White House aides lied about the extent of
Hillary Rodham Clinton's involvement in the mass firing of White
House travel office employees in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first position is that death ends it,'' said Brett
Kavanaugh, a prosecutor in Starr's office. As Kavanaugh spoke,
Starr, who argued many cases before the Supreme Court when he was
the US solicitor general, sat next to the lectern.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1993, nine days before he put a gun to his head and
killed himself in a Virginia park, Foster, a White House deputy
counsel, arrived in Hamilton's living room and talked for two hours
about the travel office firings and the controversy that ensued.
Hamilton took three pages of notes and marked them confidential, he
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Before the two began talking, Foster asked if the conversation
was confidential, Hamilton said. ``Without hesitation, I said that
it was.''
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court in Washington had ruled in the Foster
case that once a client dies, the disclosure of information is
permissible if it is of substantial importance to a criminal
investigation. Such a loophole prompted Justice Antonin Scalia to
comment that the exception ``pretty much swallows up the rule.''
</P>
<P>
   The justices blitzed the two attorneys with questions and
comments during the hourlong oral arguments, leaving the lawyers
often unable to complete a sentence before being interrupted from
the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia and Justice Anthony Kennedy appeared particularly
skeptical of Hamilton's argument that the privilege is extended
into eternity. At one point, Kennedy questioned what might happen
if a client confessed to a crime another suspect was accused of.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg said if Foster
had lived, the grand jury probably would not be entitled to the
attorney's notes. Because of Foster's death, she said, the
prosecution might get more information than it otherwise would be
entitled.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen Breyer said to Kavanaugh, ``People all over the
country go to a lawyer and think they're safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Kavanaugh argued that clients may want information given to a
grand jury after their death to ``fulfill their basic obligation as
a citizen and provide information to the grand jury.'' Justice
David Souter said there may be some people who do not want any such
obligation fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   The court accepted the case on an unusually expedited schedule.
A decision is expected by the end of the month, before the justices
leave for their extended summer recess.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers around the country have already marked the decision as
crucial to the way clients will relate to their attorneys for years
to come. For generations, the attorney-client privilege, which
forbids a lawyer to divulge the contents of any conversation with
his client without the client's permission, was considered
absolute.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's sweeping is the chilling effect of this,'' said Larry
Fox, a Philadelphia trial lawyer and the former chairman of the
American Bar Association ethics committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``You create what looks like a relatively narrow exception, but
in advance, you never know when it might apply,'' Fox said. ``So it
has the effect of a lawyer having to say that you can't promise the
confidentiality you ordinarily could.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox and other lawyers said they can envision scenarios where
attorneys would have to explain to clients in criminal cases that
when the client dies, some of the information might have to be
divulged. Such a warning, the lawyers said, would likely cause
clients to hold back crucial information.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William Rehnquist, noting this fear, said in court
that a client must ``feel free to tell a lawyer the truth and the
whole truth.'' Still, Rehnquist questioned both sides closely.
</P>
<P>
   The case of the White House travel office firings has lingered
for five years, as have the questions over the first lady's role.
Initially, White House aides denied that Mrs. Clinton played any
part in the firings, but a memorandum from former Clinton adviser
David Watkins was turned over to Starr's office in 1996 saying she
``desired action _ the action desired was the firing of the travel
office.''
</P>
<P>
   After Monday's court session, Starr spokesman Charles Bakaly
said his office was not trying to diminish attorney-client
privileges except in criminal cases involving significant
revelations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important is we are trying to seek every means to get
information to the grand jury,'' Bakaly said. ``The point is, we're
looking to get the information, the facts, as many ways as we
can.''
</P>
<P>
   In preparing the case, Starr's office sent aides to Boston to
comb the records of the Charles Stuart case, in which Stuart killed
his pregnant wife, made up a black assailant, and later killed
himself after meeting with a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court ruled
that the attorney-client privilege is not altered by the client's
death, and that Stuart's words to lawyer John Dawley were ordered
protected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
