<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9895 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-FRENCH-COLUMN-LAD     06-08 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-FRENCH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO EXPECT FROM WORLD CUP '98
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYON, France _ Brazil? Germany? England? Inquiring minds want to
know what to expect from the 16th World Cup, which kicks off
Wednesday with games in Saint-Denis and Montpellier.
</P>
<P>
   Will Ronaldo fulfill all the hype in his first real test since
being crowned ``the new Pele''? Might Roberto Baggio get the
opportunity to redeem himself for that penalty-kick disaster in the
Rose Bowl four years ago? Can the United States provide the biggest
surprise in an event that promises many?
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? That's what they play the games for there are other
issues, far more vital if you happen to be in France for the
festivities.
</P>
<P>
   Who, for instance, will go on strike next? And where will we be
stranded when they do? Are the threats of terrorism and hooliganism
serious? Anyone know where a decent meal can be found for a
reasonable price?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the primary concerns of those fortunate enough or damned,
depending on one's outlook to spend the next month in France will
be peripheral to the soccer that goes on around them. The game is
there, everywhere, from Toulouse to Lens to Bordeaux to Lyon, sort
of like air and bottled water. If you love the sport, this is
Mecca; if you don't, this is hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had enough of the Coupe de Monde, and it hasn't even
started yet,'' one railway worker here noted the other night as he
stepped over one of the dozens of young fans who had taken
residence in Lyon's Gare de Perrache.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, when play finally begins, he figured to be off the
job. What better way, the rail workers figure, to get your point
across than with a strike on the day the entire world's attention
is on France. Of course, the French's attitude might be there's no
day that's too good for a strike. Air France pilots have been off
the job for about a week now, and before the champion is crowned
July 12 at the new Stade de France in Saint-Denis, they are
expected to be joined by just about everyone in the transportation
industry. Work stoppages, it appears, are the true national sport
here.
</P>
<P>
   It's not soccer. France, unlike Italy or Germany or England (or
a major part of the civilized world) isn't gaga over booting a ball
around, but that might change in the next few weeks. It all depends
on Zinedine Zidane remember the name and what he can prod from the
home team. The French are one of the favorites for the title, which
has never been so wide-open before. Brazil, Argentina, France,
Germany, England, Holland, Yugoslavia, Spain all appear capable of
capturing the title ... or of failure. Of that group, only
Argentina, Holland, Yugoslavia and Spain are playing like champions
at the moment; so is Norway, which nobody seriously considers a
contender.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody has to win. Here's my best guess who it will be:
</P>
<P>
   (8 point) Group play (top 2 each group advance)
</P>
<P>
   Group A:
</P>
<P>
   1. Norway; 2. Brazil; 3. Morocco; 4. Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Norway, my ``surprise'' team of the tournament, edges the
favored Brazilians for first, stunning everyone except Norway coach
Egil Olsen, who has spent most of '98 insisting his is the better
team. A fine performance isn't enough for Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   Group B:
</P>
<P>
   1. Italy; 2. Chile; 3. Cameroon; 4. Austria.
</P>
<P>
   The Azzurri are the class of the group, shutting down Chilean
strikers Marcelo Salas and Ivan Zamorano, who score at will against
overmatched Cameroonians and Austrians.
</P>
<P>
   Group C:
</P>
<P>
   1. France; 2. South Africa; 3. Denmark; 4. Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   The host has it easy, and Bafana Bafana's artistry outweighs the
Danes' toughness.
</P>
<P>
   Group D:
</P>
<P>
   1. Spain; 2. Nigeria; 3. Bulgaria; 4. Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   Group of Death? Not for the Spaniards, who have far too much for
any of their D comrades. Nigeria somehow gets its act together to
edge the aging Bulgars.
</P>
<P>
   Group E:
</P>
<P>
   1. Netherlands; 2. Belgium; 3. South Korea; 4. Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   No problem for the Dutch, and none really for the Belgians,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Group F:
</P>
<P>
   1. Yugoslavia; 2. Germany; 3. United States; 4. Iran
</P>
<P>
   The Germans might be in for a surprise when they meet the
Americans, but Yugoslavia will be the class of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Group G:
</P>
<P>
   1. Romania; 2. England; 3. Colombia; 4. Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
   Romania takes charge and England hangs on.
</P>
<P>
   Group H:
</P>
<P>
   1. Argentina; 2. Croatia; 3. Jamaica; 4. Japan.
</P>
<P>
   No contest here:
</P>
<P>
   Argentina romps to the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Knockout phase
</P>
<P>
   Second round:
</P>
<P>
   Norway over Chile, Italy over Brazil, France over Bulgaria,
Spain over South Africa, Netherlands over Germany, Yugoslavia over
Belgium, Romania over Croatia, Argentina over England.
</P>
<P>
   Intense matchups await Brazil, Germany and England, who pay for
their inadequate first-round performances; the Italians gain
revenge for 1994, on penalty kicks, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterfinals:
</P>
<P>
   France over Italy, Norway over Spain, Argentina over
Netherlands, Yugoslavia over Romania.
</P>
<P>
   Norway's stunning run continues, and Yugoslavia is looking
unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   Semifinals:
</P>
<P>
   Argentina over Norway, Yugoslavia over France.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina has too much and France not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Third place:
</P>
<P>
   France over Norway.
</P>
<P>
   The hosts treat this as a real game and school the Norwegians,
who are still celebrating their drive to the semis.
</P>
<P>
   Championship:
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia over Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   A classic encounter, with skill winning out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
