<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO BILL FACES DEATH IN SENATE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The architects of a landmark plan to combat youth
smoking faced a new reality Monday: All the momentum that propelled
the proposal to the front lines of Congress has dissolved into an
aura of doom.
</P>
<P>
   After defying a series of death notices in recent months, the
$516 billion effort to overhaul the tobacco industry is gasping in
the Senate in what partisans on both sides said could be its last
breath.
</P>
<P>
   With the Senate poised for a key confrontation today over the
controversial antitobacco measure, the Republican majority leader,
Trent Lott told reporters Monday the bill is close to ``not being
able to be resurrected.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott, echoing several conservative colleagues, said the bill's
sponsors have ``lost control,'' allowing the measure to mushroom
from an effort to reduce youth smoking into ``a budget-busting
spending bill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has lost its focus,'' Lott said, ``and it should be
pulled'' from consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, a senior aide to a senator who helped craft the
bill said closed-door negotiations were under way ``to see whether
there is any life still in it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the general mood is not very optimistic,'' the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's demise, which supporters vowed to try to prevent,
would immediately transform the tobacco showdown from a legislative
debate to a major issue in the 1998 congressional campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the defining issue this year,'' said Senator
Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the minority leader.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is scheduled to vote today on Daschle's motion to end
debate and force a final vote on the bill. But even though a
majority of senators are considered likely to support the measure's
final passage if a vote is held, Lott said the GOP majority was
united against cutting short the debate because it would prevent
senators from presenting and voting on numerous amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle's motion to end debate requires 60 votes to pass, more
than Daschle said he can muster. The motion's failure could
ultimately prevent a final vote on the bill unless negotiators
reach an agreement for considering amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Daschle, who has filed a second motion to end debate that is
scheduled for a vote tomorrow, vowed to press on, despite the
serious obstacles. He said that if his motions fail, he will offer
the antitobacco measure as an amendment ``to every bill coming down
the pike.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to the Republicans to come to the realization that
we're going to do this one like we've done others _ the easy way or
the hard way,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   He asserted that the measure is not dead. ``We'll see to it that
it's not dead,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would require tobacco companies to pay the government
$516 billion over 25 years to help pay for smoking-related
illnesses. The measure also would increase the price of cigarettes
by $1.10 over three years. And it would cap the amount of civil
damages the industry would have to pay each year at $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of highly contentious issues are pending, including
attempts to use revenues from the bill to reduce the so-called
marriage tax penalty and to combat drug crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, disputes loom over how to deal with tobacco farmers
who would be affected by the legislation and whether limits should
be placed on the fees lawyers receive for suing the tobacco
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill is being slammed from the left and the right,'' said
the Senate aide.
</P>
<P>
   The question, the aide said, is whether the legislation can be
saved by a coalition described by the prime sponsor, Arizona
Republican Senator John McCain, as ``the great center.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
