<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLINT STRIKE IDLES OTHER GM PLANTS, AND WORKERS ARE SENT HOME  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Kan., Ohio)   By NICHOLE M. CHRISTIAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ With two of its factories running out of essential
components, General Motors sent 4,500 workers home Monday as a
four-day strike at a metal stamping plant in Flint, Mich.,
threatened to halt vehicle production for the world's largest
automaker.
</P>
<P>
   While negotiators for the United Auto Workers and General Motors
Corp. began their fourth straight day of bargaining, assembly
factories in Orion Township, Mich., and Kansas City, Kan., were
closed because of a shortage of engine cradles, according to the
company and union officials. Salaried employees remained at the
plants.
</P>
<P>
   The auto maker said an additional 8,500 workers could be idled
on Tuesday with the scheduled closing of a light truck factory in
Moraine, Ohio, a car assembly factory in Flint and a second shift
at the Kansas factory.
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday is the strike deadline at a second Flint
parts-making factory, where 5,000 workers are demanding more job
security.
</P>
<P>
   The chain of plant closings was set in motion by the strike of
3,400 hourly workers at GM's sprawling metal plant in Flint, where
the workers contend that the automaker has reneged on a promise of
$300 million in new investments that would essentially guarantee
future employment. At least 17 of GM's 29 North American assembly
plants use fenders, hoods and engine cradles built in Flint.
</P>
<P>
   ``GM says the plant is not competitive, but that's their answer
to everything,'' said Dick Shoemaker, the union's vice president
for negotiations with the company. GM's response is that it will
not back down until the UAW lives up to its promise to abolish work
practices that give workers a full day's pay for a half-day's work.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts estimate that the strike could cost the
company $300 million a week in profits. Strikers receive $150 a
week from the UAW and risk losing two weeks of paid vacation that
other employees will get this month during the company's annual
two-week summer shut down.
</P>
<P>
   In most states, workers who are laid off are eligible for state
unemployment benefits, but GM typically fights against issuing
benefits to UAW workers laid off during a strike. A company
spokesman said GM was still deciding whether it would challenge the
benefits, a tactic it tried during a strike at two Dayton, Ohio,
plants in 1996. ``Nobody can afford to be laid off,'' said Dan
Fairbanks of UAW Local 31, which represents GM's 3,400 workers in
Kansas City. ``But somebody has to make GM keep its promises to
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
