<SLUG> BC-SOC-SOCWATCH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
11 PLAYES TO WATCH IN FRANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYON, France _ Keep your eye on these players who can have an
impact at the World Cup:
</P>
<P>
   Goalkeeper
</P>
<P>
   Kasey Keller/United States
</P>
<P>
   The only American who can be called ``world-class'' --- he stops
the unstoppable --- and the one man who can carry the Yanks to the
second round or better. If he plays as in the 1-0 win over Brazil,
the U.S. might stun the field.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders
</P>
<P>
   Paolo Maldini/Italy
</P>
<P>
   The Azzurri coach's son got no favors from dad: He's been the
game's premier defender for nearly a decade. He's slowed down a
bit, but his positioning is so good that it hardly matters.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Carlos/Brazil
</P>
<P>
   Forget the Ronaldo hype --- OK, don't forget it. But remember
this wing-defender, only 5-foot-6, is the planet's premier
footballer. Works hard, crosses well and the goals he scores belong
in the Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   Jaap Stam/Netherlands
</P>
<P>
   No one questions Holland's flair, but its defending ... well,
that's another tale. With Stam, the best Dutch player of the past
year or so, that could change: He's speedy man-marker, solid but
not spectacular --- exactly what is needed from a top-flight
defender.
</P>
<P>
   Midfielders
</P>
<P>
   Didier Deschamps/France
</P>
<P>
   Eric Cantona, the great, arrogant forward, dismissed Deschamps
as a ``water carrier'' --- wine is more like it. The best defensive
midfielder in the world and the key figure in France's transition
game. He can tackle, he can distribute, and --- unlike Cantona ---
isn't about to brag about his skills. They're quite apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Nwankwo Kanu/Nigeria
</P>
<P>
   He led the Super Eagles to the Olympic gold medal two years ago,
then was told to quit when diagnosed with a hole in his heart. The
gentle giant --- he's 6-foot-6 --- refused, returned to America for
surgery and rehabbed at UCLA under an assumed name. He's back,
better than ever, and could guide Nigeria to the heights so many
expect.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel Ortega/Argentina
</P>
<P>
   The successor to Diego Maradona, with a good deal of the skill
and none of the trouble. He can score goals --- had five to lead
Argentina in qualifying --- and has built a strong relationship
with striker Gabriel Batistuta, who has never scored as often for
his national team as for his club sides. Ortega could change that.
</P>
<P>
   Zinedine Zidane/France
</P>
<P>
   The second coming of Michel Platini? Maybe. The son of Algerian
immigrants, Zidane is the most dangerous playmaker in the
tournament, able to score, create goals --- do anything, really. If
he can connect with France's inconsistent forwards, the hosts could
go far.
</P>
<P>
   Forwards
</P>
<P>
   Tore Andre Flo/Norway
</P>
<P>
   Hulking striker at the center of Norway's ugly but effective
attack, nicknamed ``Flonaldo'' for his scoring ability. One of
three Flos on a squad that, if everything does flow, could be the
surprise of the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Predrag Mijatovic/Yugoslavia
</P>
<P>
   Loves to take chances, and they could pay off sweetly for this
rising star. He's got speed, superb reactions and technique, and it
led to 14 goals during qualifying --- and another to give Real
Madrid the European Champions Cup crown.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo/Brazil
</P>
<P>
   Acclaimed as the ``next Pele,'' there's certainly no better
finisher in the game. He's the world's answer to Michael Jordan,
making $15 million a year on the field and far, far more from
endorsements. How he deals with the attention of rival defenders
may determine whether the Brazilians repeat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
