<HEADLINE>
PENTIUM CHIP PRICES SLICED 12 PERCENT TO 20 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(sw) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Intel Corp. said on Monday that it had lowered
prices on its Pentium II microprocessors for desktop computers by
12 percent to 20 percent. Intel also introduced a faster version of
its low-end Celeron processor and dropped the price of the older,
slower model by 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Intel officials said the price cuts reflected increased
efficiencies in manufacturing processes.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said the cuts, the first that Intel has made in the
final month of a quarter, more likely reflected an attempt to
revive a sluggish market.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also dismissed the faster Celeron, noting that it still
lacked the memory called cache, which improves performance on
Pentium and equivalent chips from competing companies such as
Advanced Micro Devices Inc. and the Cyrix unit of the National
Semiconductor Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think revenues are coming in below plan to date, and the
company is hoping these price cuts really provide a kick start for
the quarter's end,'' said Jonathan Joseph, an analyst with
Nationsbanc Montgomery Securities. ``Revenues are going to have to
pick up pretty smartly for margins not to be impacted. It's a tough
quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Intel slipped 50 cents on Monday, to $69.3125.
Analysts said the price cuts had been long expected, as was the
antitrust suit filed against Intel on Monday by the Federal Trade
Commission. Intel shares are down 32 percent from their 52-week
high of $102 reached in August.
</P>
<P>
   On another front, the company and Fujitsu Ltd., Japan's largest
computer maker, said that they planned to strengthen their
relationship. People close to the companies said Fujitsu would
announce that it planned to make work stations and servers using
Intel's forthcoming Pentium II Xeon and Merced microprocessors.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In announcing the price cuts, Intel said it had shifted desktop
production exclusively to the Pentium II product line, which is
made using an advanced manufacturing process called .25 micron. But
it said that the older Pentium with MMX Technology chips would
remain in production for notebook computers.
</P>
<P>
   Intel cut the price of its 400-megahertz Pentium II processor
from $824 to $722, or about 12 percent; the 350-megahertz from $621
to $519, or 16 percent; the 333-megahertz from $492 to $412, or 16
percent; the 300-megahertz from $375 to $305, or 19 percent; the
266-megahertz from $246 to $198, or 20 percent, and the
233-megahertz from $198 to $161, or 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The new Celeron 300-megahertz chip is priced at $159; the price
of the 266-megahertz Celeron was lowered to $106, from $155.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
