</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERCURY-ACCORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCORD ON MERCURY EMISSIONS COULD PROD OTHERS INTO ACTION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New England governors and eastern Canadian premiers agreed
Monday to cut in half emissions of mercury from power plants,
incinerators, and other sources by 2003, in a dramatic move aimed
at reducing elevated levels of the toxic metal found in freshwater
fish across the region.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, aimed in part at pressuring the US and Canadian
governments to take stronger action, probably will lead to tougher
regulation of the burning of coal, trash, and medical waste as well
as a regional effort to get mercury out of consumer products from
batteries to children's sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the prospect of mounting state and federal regulations
on mercury and other pollutants prompted permanent closure of a
waste incinerator in Massachusetts last week. The owners of a
second incinerator, a medical waste burner in Lawrence, also were
reportedly considering closure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of agreement that almost two decades ago set
in motion the national legislation in the US and Canada that has
(reduced) acid rain,'' said Ned Sullivan, Maine's commissioner of
environmental protection. ``We think we lit a fuse today that will
ultimately have implications well beyond the Northeast.''
</P>
<P>
   The governors of Massachusetts, Maine, and Vermont led the
charge in passing the resolution, at one point advocating the
``virtual elimination'' of mercury emissions in 10 years. However,
Canadian officials concerned about the impact on Nova Scotia's coal
industry succeeded in removing the phase-out deadline from the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the softer language, Governor Howard Dean of Vermont was
jubilant that the premiers and governors had endorsed a call to
action. He said the resolution would put pressure to follow suit on
the Midwest, where coal-burning plants account for nearly a third
of the mercury that falls on New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really put the problem on the screen for the leadership
of the eastern provinces and the Northeast states, and, because of
this, it will put it on the national screen,'' said Dean in a
telephone interview from the regional premiers and governors
meeting in Fredericton, New Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists also praised the resolution, but warned that
the real test will be laws and regulations passed by each state and
province. ``These plans are an important first step in reducing
mercury pollution and acid deposition in our region,'' said Cindy
Luppi of Clean Water Action in Boston. ``But the real work lies
ahead'' in implementation.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury pollution has emerged as a growing issue in New England
as samples of freshwater fish increasingly show high levels of
mercury, especially in larger sport fish prized by fishermen.
Massachusetts has issued a statewide advisory that women of
childbearing age and children should limit consumption of
freshwater fish, while other states have gone further.
</P>
<P>
   The human body has no use for mercury, which attacks the central
nervous system and, in high doses, can cause insanity or even
death. In the 1950s, mercury poisoning killed hundreds of people in
Minimata, Japan, who ate seafood caught near an offshore industrial
dumping ground.
</P>
<P>
   However, much less is known about long-term, low-level exposure
to mercury such as that from eating bass or trout caught in New
England. Public health officials say they are most concerned about
people who eat large amounts of freshwater fish.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury also harms fish-eating wildlife, such as bald eagles,
many of which have elevated mercury levels in their blood, studies
have shown.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the mercury falling on the Northeast comes from sources
within the region, according to a study by the Northeast States for
Coordinated Air Use Management in Boston. Trash and medical waste
incinerators, in turn, account for about half of the 15,000 pounds
of mercury coming from New England sources.
</P>
<P>
   To address the mercury problem, Maine, Vermont, and
Massachusetts have adopted new laws and regulations. For example,
Vermont and Maine will require mercury-containing products to be
labeled in hopes of keeping them out of incinerators. Vermont
officials also plan to require mercury-containing waste to be
handled as hazardous waste.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts, meanwhile, has proposed tight limits on mercury
coming out of incinerator stacks that will force plant owners to
install new antipollution equipment and prevent lamps, batteries,
and other mercury-containing waste from being burned.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Ogden Corp. announced it would close down its
waste-to-energy incinerator in Lawrence rather than invest in new
pollution controls that would reduce emissions of mercury and other
contaminants.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, environmentalist Bill Ravanasi of Health Care
Without Harm said that Browning-Ferris Industries has filed an
application with the state to close its medical waste incinerator
in Lawrence and replace it with sterilization equipment. Company
officials could not be reached to confirm the report.
</P>
<P>
   But New England officials said no single state can solve a
problem that is carried on the wind. Maine official Sullivan called
on the US government to limit mercury from all coal-burning plants,
while Dean said the government should lead the effort to get
mercury out of consumer products.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Massachusetts Department of Environmental Protection
Commissioner David Struhs said the resolution adopted Monday should
give the Northeast and eastern Canada a powerful voice in the
mercury debate. ``This is a big win for us,'' said Struhs. ``For
the first time ever, it says that our goal should be the virtual
elimination of manmade mercury.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
