<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9902 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORWEST-WELLSFARGO-AR     06-08 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORWEST-WELLSFARGO-ART-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELLS FARGO AND NORWEST PLAN A MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Minn.)   (ART ADV: Two graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Norwest Corp. and Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. agreed on Monday to merge in
a $34 billion deal, the latest in a string of blockbuster unions
that have created a cadre of giants and a few dozen also-rans in
the once sleepy banking industry.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by stalled revenue growth and heightened competition from
mutual funds, brokerage firms and credit-card companies, banks have
been rushing into one another's arms in record numbers over the
last few years.
</P>
<P>
   But bank mergers like the expected deal Monday have proceeded at
a particularly blistering pace so far this year and only a handful
of outsized deals remain to be completed.
</P>
<P>
   Banks that have already linked up now have to prove to the
public and shareholders that mammoth banking franchises with
national or international aspirations can be managed effectively,
and are more than merely the unwieldy creations of chief
executives' egos.
</P>
<P>
   If all bank mergers announced so far this year are completed,
the ranks of the elite titans will include Citigroup, BankAmerica
Corp., Chase Manhattan Corp., J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co., Banc One Corp.,
First Union Corp. and Wells Fargo, which will be based in San
Francisco and retain its name but will be run by Norwest's chief
executive, Richard Kovacevich.
</P>
<P>
   Norwest and Wells expect the deal to be completed in three to
four months.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction will pressure smaller banks to jump into the
merger game, especially Fleet Financial Group, National City Corp.,
Keycorp, PNC Bank Corp., BankBoston Corp., U.S. Bancorp, Mellon
Bank Corp., Wachovia Corp. and Sun Trust Banks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the merger, the new Wells, with about $186 billion in
assets, still would be quite a bit smaller than the top three banks
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, a combination of Citicorp and Travelers Group Inc.,
would have $697 billion in assets; BankAmerica, a combination of
BankAmerica and Nationsbank Corp., would have assets of $571
billion, while Chase has assets of about $366 billion. The new
Wells, and even Banc One, could become part of larger empires in
another year or two.
</P>
<P>
   Yet size does not really matter if a bank cannot make a buck.
And profitability, as Wells learned when it botched its takeover of
First Interstate Corp. over the last few years, can be derailed
when a merger goes awry.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, Norwest and Wells would create a potential powerhouse
west of the Mississippi River. Norwest, the biggest mortgage lender
in the country, is one of the few banks that have successfully sold
products like insurance, credit cards, and annuities to their
customers. It styles itself as a financial Wal-Mart, and tapping
into Wells' customer base in Western states would provide it with
more shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said that layoffs associated with the merger are
expected to be ``minimal,'' but they declined to quantify job
losses.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have embraced different operating philosophies
over the years. Norwest, based in Minneapolis, likes to keep its
operations decentralized, while Wells has traditionally been very
centralized. Norwest favors bank branches, while Wells has
emphasized electronic banking via telephone, online services and
automated teller machines. All of this could have an impact on some
of the banks' smaller customers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I think you will see a very significant culture clash that
will result in the loss of smaller companies and individuals,''
said Evie Fass, a banking analyst with Stern Marketing Group, a
consulting firm in Berkeley, Calif. ``Ultimately you have two very
smart banks that know how to make money. But smaller community
banks will be able to target individual customers left in the dust
by big mergers like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Others see the merger as working despite inevitable culture
clashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's attractive because of the complementary nature of their
markets and the fact that they're both retail banks,'' said Keith
Stock, a consultant with A.T. Kearney Inc. in New York. ``This
merger is based on the potential for top-line revenue growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The two banks have talked informally over the last few years
about a merger, but the talks became more serious a few months ago
when Kovacevich invited Wells' chief executive, Paul Hazen, to talk
about the merits of a deal. Investment bankers and lawyers were
then retained, and the real outlines of a merger began to take
shape about 11 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Norwest was advised by Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. and by the law firms
of Fried, Frank, Harris, Shriver &AMP; Jacobson and Wachtell, Lipton,
Rosen &AMP; Katz. Wells was advised by Goldman, Credit Suisse First
Boston and the New York law firms of Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell and
Wachtell, Lipton.
</P>
<P>
   It is rare for an investment bank to straddle both sides of a
deal, and Credit Suisse was invited in to render its opinion of the
transaction because Goldman was advising both banks.
</P>
<P>
   The combined banks' board of directors will be evenly
represented by both companies, but Wells shareholders, who will
receive 10 Norwest shares for each Wells share they own, will own
about 52.5 percent of the combined company with Norwest
shareholders holding the balance. Based on Norwest's share price
Friday, the merger with Wells is worth $396.875 a share or nearly
$34 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In trading Monday on the New York Stock Exchange, Norwest's
shares dropped $2.875 to $36.8125 while Wells' shares rose $2.50 to
$365.75.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hazen will be chairman, Kovacevich will be chief
executive and president and is expected to exert more managerial
influence.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best-regarded executives in banking, the 53-year-old
Kovacevich began his banking career at Citicorp in 1975. He stayed
there for 10 years and left in 1986 after he was passed over for
the presidency. He became Norwest's president in 1989 and was named
chief executive in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   He is credited with helping turn around Norwest, which was mired
in bad loans when he arrived, and for building the bank's business
through small but profitable acquisitions in the Midwest. But none
remotely resemble the megamerger with Wells, and Kovacevich is
ignoring his aversion to doing a deal in what he has repeatedly
called an overheated merger environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We complement each other,'' Kovacevich said Monday. ``Where
one has a strength, the other has a weakness. That is the essence
and excitement of this great new franchise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
