<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9903 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAELI-SETTLERS-HNS &LR;      06-08 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAELI-SETTLERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSIONS ESCALATE AS JEWISH SETTLERS MOVE INTO ARAB NEIGHBORHOOD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Jewish settlers took over two old stone houses in an
Arab neighborhood of east Jerusalem before dawn Monday, raising
Israeli flags over the structures, putting up barbed wire and
scuffling with Palestinian residents.
</P>
<P>
   About two dozen settlers from Elad, a hard-line Jewish
organization dedicated to buying property in the Palestinian
neighborhood of Silwan, took over the homes, Palestinians said.
Silwan is built over the ancient City of David.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 2:30 a.m., my neighbor called me and told me the settlers
had opened my house and thrown my things outside,'' said Fatima
Karaeen, one of the owners, who has been living at her
mother-in-law's house since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-morning, Palestinian leaders and Israeli peace activists
had descended upon the houses.
</P>
<P>
   Scuffles broke out when the settlers tried to prevent the
Palestinians living next door to one of the houses from climbing to
the roof, according to Faisal Husseini, the Palestinian Authority's
representative in Jerusalem. Police also fought with about 20
Israeli Peace Now members, who refused to leave and were dragged
away by the officers.
</P>
<P>
   The settlers' takeover was the latest in a series of incidents
that have raised tensions in the disputed city. Two weeks ago,
settlers from a different organization called Ateret Cohanim
provoked scuffles with Palestinians after they erected seven tin
shacks in the Muslim Quarter of the Old City. Two days earlier,
Ateret Cohanim members took over a Palestinian home a few streets
away and threw the owner's belongings into the street.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents occurred as U.S. efforts to pull peace
negotiations out of a 15-month freeze continue to be frustrated. On
Monday, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu dashed
expectations that an agreement was imminent on the long-awaited
Israeli troop withdrawal from the West Bank by telling Israel Radio
that negotiators would not rush toward an agreement that would
compromise Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's incident also took place while Israeli Cabinet
ministers debated whether to allow Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, the
spiritual leader of the militant Hamas organization, to return to
Gaza after the 61-year-old cleric completes a tour of Muslim
countries. Yassin, who opposes the Israeli-Palestinian peace
accords, has been rallying support abroad, prompting some ministers
to argue that Israel should not allow him to return.
</P>
<P>
   In Silwan, settlers and Palestinians gave different accounts of
the takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Elad activists said the group had purchased one of the houses,
which is divided into three separate apartments, from the
Palestinian owners.
</P>
<P>
   They said the other one was purchased from the Israeli
government, which had expropriated it after the property's owner,
Fatima Karaeen's father, was declared an ``absentee'' in 1991
because he lives in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, Israel's courts ruled in favor of the settlers
after lengthy court cases, settler activists said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Netanyahu government appeared to side with the
settlers. ``This is an absolutely legal transaction,'' David
Bar-Illan, the prime minister's adviser, said.
</P>
<P>
   Another adviser to Netanyahu, Danny Naveh, told Israel's Army
Radio: ``We believe Jews should be able to live in Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians accuse the settlers of using unscrupulous means to
acquire the homes and of maneuvering to influence the outcome of
negotiations over the city by changing the demographic makeup of
the eastern half. Jerusalem is one of the issues that has yet to be
resolved in a final peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians hope to make eastern sectors that are majority Arab
part of the capital of an independent state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The settlers say that the Palestinians are selling their
houses _ they are not,'' said Husseini, the the Palestinian
Authority's Jerusalem representative. ``There are a lot of illegal
things happening here, and the problem is that the Israeli
government does not always act in a legal way. They use the law to
serve one side.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Authority echoed Husseini's statements, calling
the settlers' moves part of an ``unholy war against Palestinian
property.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the authority condemned an archaeological dig at the
site where the seven shacks had been put up in the Muslim Quarter,
calling it a search for ``fake Jewish antiquities.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Ateret Cohanim agreed to a compromise by
which the group would tear down the shacks and instead help finance
the dig for Jewish artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Elad spokesman Dully Basok said the group would
continue to purchase homes in Silwan, where they believe King David
built his palace 3,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This area is the center of the ancient Jerusalem,'' said
Basok, who lives in one of 17 homes in Silwan owned by Elad. Unlike
the Ateret Cohanim, which buys property in all Arab areas of the
city, Elad concentrates only on Silwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very natural that Jews hope to live in this area,'' he
said. ``Our national song is about Zion and Jerusalem. All our
hopes are about Zion and Jerusalem, so it's very simply why we want
to live exactly here on this hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Basok said Elad now owns 54 percent of the City of David, which
covers a small part of Silwan closest to the Old City, much of it
empty houses and open fields. He said the group was trying to
acquire several other properties through the courts. He would not
disclose the number.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Deborah Horan is a free-lance journalist who wrote this for the
Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
