<HEADER>
A9904 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CAPSULES-LADN     06-08 4567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CAPSULES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM CAPSULES OF THE WORLD CUP FIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEAM CAPSULES
</P>
<P>
   GROUP A
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Mario Zagallo
</P>
<P>
   Cup note: Champions in '58, '62, '70, '94, runners-up in '50.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   D Roberto Carlos, MF Dunga, MF Leonardo, MF Denilson, F Ronaldo.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Alberto Parreira drew the wrath of his countryman when he
forfeited beauty for organization four years ago, but it paid off
with the championship. Zagallo, his successor, has brought back the
beautiful game, but his team has looked uninspired and disjointed.
Injuries to Romario and Juninho haven't helped, and Edmundo's
fistfight with Leonardo can't have aided a fragile team chemistry,
but there's enough talent here particularly Ronaldo and Roberto
Carlos to overcome anything.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's team to beat. It wouldn't be a surprise if someone
did beat them. Can go all the way or get knocked out in the second
round.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Craig Brown
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Never reached second round.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   GK Jim Leighton, D Colin Hendry, MF John Collins, MF Jackie
McNamara, F Kevin Gallacher.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   The pragmatic Brown has assembled a gritty, tenacious team that
will play strong defense, but Scottish hopes of grandeur
disappeared when captain and midfield general Gary McAllister went
down with injury. Collins provides class in midfield and Gallacher
is a scoring threat, but it isn't likely that will be enough
against the likes of Brazil and Norway.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   First-round exit, again.
</P>
<P>
   MOROCCO
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Henri Michel
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Fourth appearance (1970-86-94); reached the second round in '86.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   D Noureddine Naybet, MF Youssef Chippo, MF Moustafa Hadji, F
Salaheddine Bassir.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Possibly the most organized of Africa's entrants, with strength
in attack and defense. Bassir, Hadji and the veteran Naybet,
teammates with Spanish power Deportivo de La Coruna, are the
anchors. Frenchman Michel has the team playing well heading into
the tournament, drawing with England and falling by one goal to
France at its King Hassan II Cup last month in Casablanca.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Draw is too tough; Three and out.
</P>
<P>
   NORWAY
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Egil Olsen
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Third appearance (1938-94); never reached the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   D Henning Berg, MF Erik Myklsnd, MF Vidar Riseth, F Tore Andre
Flo, F Ole Gunnar Solskjaer.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Unbeaten in 19 matches since January 1997 including a telling
4-2 win over Brazil last year in Oslo the Norwegians have never
been better. Not the most talented side, but Mykland adds a bit of
skill to a long-ball game that benefits from target man Flo's size
and the team's increased international exposure. Olsen's confidence
has spread to his players, who believe they are capable of beating
any team in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Could be the
</P>
<P>
   surprise; Quarterfinals likely, semis possibly.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP B
</P>
<P>
   ITALY
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Cesare Maldini
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Champions in '34, '38 and '82, runners-up in '70 and '94.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   GK Gianluca Pagliuca, D Paolo Maldini, MF Demetrio Albertini, F
Alessandro Del Piero, F Fabrizio Ravanelli, F Roberto Baggio.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Always contenders for the crown, the Italians disappointments
two years ago during the European Championship and strugglers in
qualifying appear to be peaking at the best possible time. The
defense, led by Maldini, the coach's son, is among the world's
best, and a fine group of forwards should make the Azzurri's fine
counterattack pay off. Del Piero is the best of the bunch, but he's
been slowed by a groin injury, and '94 star Baggio, out of the
lineup for 3{ years, has returned following a superb campaign for
Bologna.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Italy has a tough draw once it's out of the first round, so the
tournament could end sooner than it would like. If things go well,
it could hoist the trophy on July 12.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Acosta
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   First appearance since '82; semifinalists in '62, best showing
in six Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   GK Nelson Tapia, MF Clarence Acuna, MF Marcelo Vega, F Ivan
Zamorano, F Marcelo Salas.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Salas and Zamorano are terrific forwards, as good a 1-2 punch as
exists in this Cup, but what else can Chile offer? The defense is
weak, the midfield offers nothing special, and the Chileans figure
to struggle with life on the road and their opponents' quicker
tempos. They'll be tough to stop, particularly Salas, but will be
susceptible to counterattacks.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Salas and Zamorano may be enough to offset defensive troubles in
group play, but the Chileans can't hope for much more.
</P>
<P>
   CAMEROON
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Claude Le Roy
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Quarterfinalist in '90.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   GK Jacques Songo'o, D Rigobert Song, MF Patrick Mboma, MF
Salomon Olembe, F Francois Omam-Biyik, F Alphonse Tchami.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Marc-Vivien Foe to a broken leg may prove a crushing
blow he was the Indomitable Lions' midfield workhorse and won't be
easily replaced. Frenchman Le Roy was brought in following a
disastrous African Nations Cup earlier this year and made wholesale
changes, but there's only so much he can do. Omam-Biyik, Mboma and
Tchami give Cameroon power up front, but the defense, aside from
Songo'o and Song, is iffy.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the Lions upset Argentina and Brazil; in 1994, they
tanked.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Prohaska
</P>
<P>
   Cup notes:
</P>
<P>
   Third in '54 best showing in six Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   D Wolfgang Feiersinger, MF Andreas Herzog, MF Heimo
Pfeifenberger, F Toni Polster.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Defense is supposed to be the Austrians' strength, but the
United States had little trouble picking it apart in April. Coupled
with a loss to non-finalist Hungary, confidence hit bottom, and
there's been little to suggest things will get better.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Second round a reach.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP C
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Aime Jacquet
</P>
<P>
   Cup notes:
</P>
<P>
   Third in '58 and '86 best showings in 10 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   D Laurent Blanc, D Lilian Thuram, D Marcel Desailly, MF Didier
Deschamps, MF Christian Karembeu, MF Zinedine Zidane, F Youri
Djorkaeff.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Seem to have all they need, aside from a top-notch goalscorer,
to win the title: the world's most talented defense and midfield, a
playmaker without peer and an adoring audience. Zidane is the
playmaker, and he may be a household name by the time the Cup is
done, but he needs someone to finish what he creates. Djorkaeff is
the top forward, but he's not a goalscorer in the classic sense,
and Jacquet has found it difficult to find him a suitable partner.
France may not surrender a goal: Laurent and Desailly are
world-class defenders, and there is no better defensive midfielder
than Deschamps.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   France hasn't played like a champion during its preparation, and
it must overcome the pressure of playing at home. The title is
within reach, but an early exit is more likely.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Philippe Troussier
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   First appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   GK Hans Vonk, D David Nyathi, D Mark Fish, MF Lucas Radebe, F
Phil Masinga, F Benedict McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Troussier is known as the ``White Witchdoctor'' in Africa for
his accomplishments on the continent, but his brief reign with
Bafana Bafana has been contentious. He's got plenty of talent to
work with particularly McCarthy, who shared the scoring title at
the African Nations Cup earlier this year but was nearly left off
the squad and a solid defense led by Nyathi. Only 13 players from
the runners-up in Burkina Faso have been invited to France, and
among those added to the team were former MLS players Doctor
Khumalo and Shaun Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   In the past six years have emerged as a force in Africa after 28
years of isolation because of Apartheid. Troussier is a proven
commodity, and Group C isn't all that tough. The second round is
certainly within reach.
</P>
<P>
   SAUDI ARABIA
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Alberto Parreira
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Second appearance (1994); reached second round.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   MF Khalid Al-Muwalid, F Saeed Al-Owairan, F Sami Al-Jaber.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Parreira, who guided Brazil to the title in '94, will have the
Saudis organized, and forwards Al-Jaber and Al-Owairan, who scored
the goal of the tournament four years ago, provide some firepower.
The defense is poor and none of the side play outside Saudi Arabia,
leaving it little international know-how.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Parreira's presence makes the second round possible, but
inexperience makes that unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   DENMARK
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Bo Johansson
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Second appearance (1986); reached second round.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   GK Peter Schmeichel, D Marc Reiper, MF Michael Laudrup, F Brian
Laudrup.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   If Schmeichel has fully recovered from a hamstring injury that
bothered him late this past season, the Danes could go far. He's
one of the world's great netminders and the defining personality of
a squad long on physical presence but short on skill. The
exceptions to that are the Brothers Laudrup, the two finest field
players Denmark has produced, extraordinary talents that could mean
the difference between an early exit and being the surprise of the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   The second round is in reach, with the game against South Africa
on June 18 crucial.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP D
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Javier Clemente
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   10th appearance; quarterfinalists in '34, '86 and '94.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   GK Andoni Zubizarreta, D Fernando Hierro, MF Luis Enrique, F
Raul Gonzalez, F Fernando Morientes.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   The classic underachievers might be ready, finally, to excel.
The Spaniards are in great form, with talent everywhere on the
field, especially up front with Raul (doesn't use his last name)
and Morientes, who has four goals in two national team appearances.
Luis Enrique does everything in midfield, and Hierro offers
experience in the back.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Clemente built his team around the 1992 Olympic gold medalists,
which could be an omen. It's as good as any team here with could
cart off the top prize at the end.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Bora Milutinovic
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Second appearance (1994); reached the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   D Taribo West, MF-F Nwankwo Kanu, MF Austin Okocha, MF Sunday
Oliseh, F Finidi George, F Rashidi Yekini, F Daniel Amokachi, F
Victor Ikpeba.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   The reigning Olympic champions have more attacking talent than
any other team in France, and ex-U.S. coach Milutinovic's emphasis
on defense should, theoretically, shore up the Super Eagles' great
weakness. But the lead-up to the Cup has been abysmal, with Nigeria
demonstrating neither a cohesive attack nor the ability to shut
down the opposition. Kanu's return from heart surgery and the form
of African player of the year Ikpeba are huge pluses, but players'
squabbles with the Nigerian federation over money has damaged the
team's focus.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Whether Nigeria survives the Group of Death likely depends more
on its attitude than its capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   PARAGUAY
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Paulo Cesar Carpeggiani
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Fifth appearance (1930-50-58-86); reached second round in '86.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   GK Jose Luis Chilavert, D Francisco Arce, D Celso Ayala, MF
Roberto Acuna, F Miguel Benitez.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   The enigmatic Chilavert is one of the game's great goalkeepers,
and a scoring threat, too he takes all free kicks within goal
range. He won't be nearly enough to save Paraguay, which has been
beset by internal strife, a good deal of it Chilavert's doing. The
defense isn't bad, but so what? Inconsistency and inadequacy define
the Paraguayans.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   The Paraguayans peaked during qualifying, but got no favors from
the draw. Even one win would be stunning.
</P>
<P>
   BULGARIA
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Hristo Bonev
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Semifinalists in '94 best showing in six Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   D Trifon Ivanov, D Ivailo Petkov, MF Krassimir Balakov, F Hristo
Stoichkov, F Emil Kostadinov.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Stoichkov led a miracle run to the semifinals four years ago,
but he's 32 now and there's only so much magic left in his aging
legs. Most of his support is older, too, and team chemistry is a
problem. Bonev has already withstood one Stoichkov-led mutiny, and
the mood within camp has been tense. Add inconsistent defense and
the ancient midfield, and there's only so much that can be
accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   There's little optimism that occurred in '94 can be duplicated.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP E
</P>
<P>
   NETHERLANDS
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Guus Hiddink
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Runners-up in '74, '78, slipped in '90, '94.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   GK Edwin van der Sar, D Jaap Stam, MF Edgar Davids, MF Clarence
Seedorf, F Dennis Bergkamp, F Marc Overmars.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   One of the world's most richly talented sides, capable of truly
beautiful work, and are playing well as the Cup begins. The return
of Davids, who was dumped after a row with Hiddink during the
European Championships two years ago, could be crucial, and there's
enough depth that the potential loss of Bergkamp one of the world's
great strikers with a hamstring injury isn't as worrisome as it
might be. They're strong in the back (especially Van der Sar and
Stam), have one of the world's best midfields, and in Overmars have
an incomparable winger. And the selection of leader Pierre van
Hooijdonk is supposed to erase the the usual racial tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Enough talent to win the whole thing as long as they don't
self-destruct. Quarterfinals at the very least.
</P>
<P>
   BELGIUM
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Georges Leekens
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Semifinalists in '86 best showing in nine Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   D Lorenzo Staelens, MF Danny Boffin, MF Franky Van der Elst, MF
Enzo Scifo, F Marc Wilmots, F Luis Oliveira, F Luc Nilis.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Belgium's success has been built on defensive organization, but
this time out its attack is far superior to its back line. The
Brazilian-born Oliveira is key, as is Scifo, who rejoined the squad
last month after quitting in anger when he was left out of a
``friendly'' with the United States in February. He and Van der
Elst are in their fourth World Cups, and that experience could be
crucial, especially against South Korea and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   The Belgians' organization should be sufficient to get them to
the second round. Defensive liabilities a concern.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH KOREA
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Cha Bum-kun
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Never reached second round in four Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   D Hong Myung-bo, MF Seo Jung-won, MF Noh Jung-yoon, F
Hwang-Sun-hong, F Choi Yong-soo.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Asia's reigning power still is seeking to prove it can be a
force in the international game, and while some performances the
near-upset of Germany in '94 suggest the Koreans are closing in on
their goal, others hint otherwise. Cha, who played in the '86 Cup,
hasn't done well in preparation matches, but he's got a solid
defense led by Hong, South Korea's most versatile player. The
attack is limited, which could be troublesome in this group,
although none of their opponents can match the Koreans' energy
level.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Pace and persistence causes havoc for opponents; if they can
score a few goals, second round is in reach.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Lapuente
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Quarterfinalists in '70, '86 best showing in 11 Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   GK Jorge Campos, D Duilio Davino, MF Claudio Suarez, MF Ramon
Ramirez, MF Alberto Garcia Aspe, F Luis Hernandez, F Cuauhtemoc
Blanco.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Mexico will likely pay for dumping Coach Bora Milutinovic after
qualifying for the Cup; Lapuente's tenure has been marked by
indecision, inane personnel decisions and a string of horrendous
results. There's plenty of talent here Ramirez, Suarez and Garcia
Aspe are fine players but unless Hernandez takes charge is a fine
and player decisions that
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   The Tricolor is in dire straits. The second round is
conceivable, but last place in the group is more likely.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP F
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Berti Vogts
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Champions in '54, '74 and '90, runners-up in '66, '82 and '86 in
12 Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   D Olaf Thon, MF Thomas Haessler, MF Andreas Moeller, MF Dieter
Hamann, F Oliver Bierhoff, F Ulf Kirsten, F Juergen Klinsmann.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Always among the best prepared teams and always a favorite, but
a lack of creative talent could take its toll. Moeller and Haessler
are key, and they have several proven goalscorers Bierhoff in
particular to work with. The Germans will carry a psychological
edge into every match, and should they get hot, they could join
Brazil as a four-time champion.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Although they are notorious slow starters, the Germans have
never failed to reach the second round, and there's no reason to
think they won't this time.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED STATES
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sampson
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Semifinalists in '30 best showing in five Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   GK Kasey Keller, D Thomas Dooley, D Eddie Pope, D David Regis,
MF Claudio Reyna, MF Chad Deering, F Eric Wynalda.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Sampson's decision to drop captain John Harkes and switch to a
3-6-1 alignment appears to have invigorated the Americans,
providing Claudio Reyna the tools he needs to run things on the
field and erasing the troubles that plagued a slow-footed defense.
At issue is whether the U.S. can score goals, which may not be a
problem if Wynalda is fully healed from a knee injury suffered two
months ago. There's speed on the wings, with Cobi Jones and Frankie
Hejduk, a creative defensive midfield tandem in Deering and Brian
Maisonneuve, veteran leadership from Dooley, a solid bench (with
Preki Radosavljevic, Tab Ramos and Joe-Max Moore all capable of
changing games) and superb goalkeeping with Keller and backup Brad
Friedel.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Brutal draw will make it difficult to reach the second round,
but if the wings do their job and Keller comes up big, this team
could stick around awhile.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan Santrac
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Semifinalists in '30 and '62 best showing in eight Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   D Sinisa Mihajlovic, MF Dragan Stojkovic, MF Vladimir Jugovic,
MF Dejan Stankovic, MF Slavisa Jokanovic, F Predrag Mijatovic, F
Dejan Savicevic, F Savo Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   No team not Brazil nor France nor Nigeria has as much pure
talent as the Yugoslavs, who emerged from their civil war ready to
impress and haven't disappointed. Mijatovic is Europe's top striker
at the moment, Mihajlovic a superb sweeper, Jugovic a top-notch
midfielder, and the supporting talent particularly veteran
Savicevic is nearly as good. Capable of scoring plenty of goals,
but how they deal with the Germans' and Americans' fighting spirit
will be crucial.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Enough talent to win it all. The dissolution of Yugoslavia might
help here: This is a much more homogenous squad, without the usual
competing races, religions and languages that too often were
detrimental to the cause.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Jalal Talebi
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Second appearance, first since '78.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   MF Mehdi Mahdavikia, MF Karim Bagheri, F Ali Daei, F Khodadad
Azizi.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   The Iranians enjoyed a record-setting qualifying run, scoring 17
goals in one match and luring 130,000 fans to another. They've got
a superb German-based trio with Bagheri, Daei and Azizi but little
else, and they might be the least experienced team in the
tournament. Talebi took charge just last month after a string of
poor results under Croat Tomislav Ivic. The change has helped team
morale, but it won't erase on-field defeciencies.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Bagheri, Daei and Azizi might impress, but not enough. Three and
out.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP G
</P>
<P>
   ROMANIA
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Anghel Iordanescu
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Quarterfinalist in '94 best showing in six Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   D Dan Petrescu, D Gheorghe Popescu, MF Gheorghe Hagi, MF Ilie
Dumitrescu, F Adrian Ilie.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   This is the last chance for an outstanding generation of
Romanian players to shine. Essentially the same team that played in
the 1990 and '94 Cups, Iordanescu's side has great talent but is a
bit old to do anything of real significance. Turmoil has hurt the
team, with several players quitting because of disagreements with
Iordanescu, who has battled Romania's federation and plans to take
charge of Greece's national team once the Cup is over. Hagi, the
star in '94, remains the creative force, but goalscorer Ilie may
determine how far the Romanians progress.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   The quarterfinals are possible if it can beat England for the
group title.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Hernan Dario Gomez
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Fourth appearance (1962-90-94); reached second round in '90.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   D Jorge Bermudez, D Wilmer Cabrera, MF Harold Lozano, MF Carlos
Valderrama, F Faustino Asprilla.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   The Colombians aren't as strong as in '94, but that might be a
plus. The expectations that accompanied them to America proved
paralyzing, and their disastrous performance turned tragic when
Andres Escobar was killed after the team returned home.
Bushy-haired playmaker Valderrama remains the key figure, but at 36
he's slowed down a good step or so and won't deal well with
physical marking. Asprilla, so disappointing in '94, is on top of
his game and that could be the difference in a tough group.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Needs everything to go right to reach the knockout phase, and
things tend not to go right for Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ENGLAND
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Hoddle
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   10th appearance; champions in '66.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   GK David Seaman, MF Steve McManaman, MF Paul Ince, MF Paul
Scholes, F Alan Shearer.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   England looked like the real deal during qualifying, and there's
no denying the talent available to Hoddle. But injuries, troubled
form and all sorts of side issues from Paul Gascoigne's failed
attempt to get into shape to all the talk about faith healing and
Uri Gellar's crystals have played havoc with the team's focus. The
English still play hard, but their skills are now more continental,
and McManaman and Scholes could be standouts in France. Seaman is a
superb goalkeeper, Ince a fine defensive midfielder and Shearer one
of the best strikers in the game, but expectations on the Isles are
far beyond what this team's capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty here, but not enough to win a title. The second
round is within their grasp and maybe the quarterfinals, but
anything beyond that is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   TUNISIA
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Henryk Kasperczak
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   Second appearance (1978).
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   D Jose Clayton, MF Zubeir Beya, F Mehdi Ben Slimane.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Tunisia had a superb run its first time in the World Cup,
beating Mexico for Africa's first Cup victory and holding West
Germany to a 0-0 draw. It's been a long, slow climb back, and
nobody expects similar success this time. Former Poland dtandout
Kasperczak has a disciplined side, but its talent level isn't good.
There's Beya and Slimane, who play in Germany, and the
Brazilian-born Clayton, who received Tunisian citizenship in April.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Not a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP H
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Passarella
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   12th appearance; champions in '78 and '86, runners-up in '30 and
'90.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   D Roberto Ayala, D Jose Chamot, MF Diego Simone, MF Marcelo
Gallardo, MF Ariel Ortega, F Gabriel Batistura.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   The Argentines are without Diego Maradona for the first time in
five World Cups, and his absence will allow some of the other stars
to make an imprint on the team's character. Chief among them will
be playmaker Ortega, who is strong on the ball, in setting up
teammates and shooting but has struggled most of this year. The
chief target player is Batistuta, known as ``Batigol'' for his
exploits. The team really is defined by Passarella, a star defender
on Argentina's 1978 championship squad and a disciplinarian as
coach. He's put together a nice blend of youth and experience, of
attack and defense, and turned a team that wasn't expected to
contend until 2002 into a favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Argentina is on top of its game as the Cup begins and the
championship is not out or reach. Anything less than the
quarterfinals would be a major disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Takeshi Okada
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   First appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   MF Hidetoshi Nakata, MF Hirohi Nanama, MF Teruyoshi Ito, F Shoji
Jo, F Masashi Nakayama.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Japan's triumph was getting to this point, and they don't expect
to go further. Already out is Kazu Miura, Japan's greatest player,
whom Okada had described as indispensable. The stars are Nakayama,
who recently scored 16 goals in four J-League games, and superb
playmaker Nakata, better known for his orange hair and outrageous
remarks than for all the good he does on field.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Three games worth of entertaining soccer, then a long flight
home.
</P>
<P>
   JAMAICA
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Rene Simoes
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   First appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   GK Warren Barrett, D Frank Sinclair, MF Walter Boyd, MF Robbie
Earle, MF Fitzroy Simpson, F Paul Hall, F Deon Burton, F Marcus
Gayle.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian Simoes has turned a team of nobodies into an
international cause celebre the Reggae Boyz, essentially an English
B side, may be the most popular team in France, but that will count
for only so much once the whistle blows. The Boyz have speed and
quite a bit of skill, and the addition of a half-dozen English-born
players of Jamaican origin has improved the team's organization
immeasurably. Key is Burton, one of the Brits, who scored six times
during qualifying, and veteran goalkeeper Warren Barrett, one of
the best in CONCACAF.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   Second round possible but not expected.
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA
</P>
<P>
   Coach:
</P>
<P>
   Miroslav Blazevic
</P>
<P>
   Cup note:
</P>
<P>
   First appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Key players:
</P>
<P>
   D Robert Jarni, D Igor Tudor, MF Zvonimir Boban, MF Robert
Prosinecki, F Davor Suker, F Goran Vlaovic.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook:
</P>
<P>
   Don't think of this team as a first-time qualifier. Blessed with
experience and superb talent, the Croats are one of two excellent
teams to emerge from the rubble of Yugoslavia's civil war. Their
chances to do much here were hurt by the loss last month of forward
Alen Boksic, their most important player, to a knee injury; Suker,
the No. 2 striker, has been out of form, but the midfield is
outstanding especially half-Serb, half-Croat playmaker Prosinecki,
a standout with Yugoslavia in the 1990 Cup, and captain Boban.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction:
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Boksic likely will prevent the Croats from doing
anything special, but they should expect to reach the second round.
</P>
