<SLUG> BC-STUDENTS-STRANDED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE BOSTON HIGH SCHOOL STUDENTS ARE STRANDED IN NIGER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charlestown High School sophomore Darnell Crump knew a field
trip to Western Africa was going to be an adventure. After all, he
had never been on a plane before; the farthest he can remember
being from Boston was to Vermont last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the 16-year-old is getting more than he ever bargained for
in Niger. After an action-packed two-week trip, an airline strike
has stranded him and four classmates in the African country since
Friday, and rumors of a possible coup are rampant.
</P>
<P>
   Lessons about the country's camel trade and millet production
have been traded for studies in how to get out of a country where
most flights leave once a week. Instead of sharing stories with
African youth, as they did their first two weeks in Niger, the
students and their teacher are trying to persuade Moroccan
authorities to ease strict visa requirements so they can catch a
New York-bound plane from Casablanca later this week.
</P>
<P>
   While the students are not in any danger, they can't wait to get
home and, they admit, back to school. They are crossing their
fingers that the latest of four escape plans will land them in
Boston by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``More than anything, what I really want is to go home ... and
then I want a pizza,'' said Crump from the hotel Gaweye in the
Niger capital of Niamey Monday. ``But it's been a great time, I'm
learning so much more than reading any book.''
</P>
<P>
   The visit is the first field trip abroad in Charlestown High
School's history. Jonathan Silverman, who studied in
French-speaking Niger while at Harvard, obtained enough funding
from private foundation grants to pay for five students to study
the country's culture and report back to classmates.
</P>
<P>
   The five were chosen from among 120 students who wrote papers
and made presentations about Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, &UR;  &LR; the trip was everything they had planned. The
students were attending local schools every day, meeting with
villagers, and studying Niger's political structure, history, and
culture. They visited the village of Balleyra, where students rode
camels and learned how villagers build their homes out of mud.
</P>
<P>
   True, they were cautioned by their guide not to talk too loudly
about the president, who overthrew a democratic government in a
1996 military coup. Then again, they knew there was some civil
unrest in the country before they arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us got scared by what the guide said,'' said Jennifer
Camacho, 18. ``But we're fine.''
</P>
<P>
   During their trip, they've exchanged addresses with about ``a
hundred people'' and feel a bit like movie stars because so many
Africans stare and follow them out of curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   The students, who raised $485 from staff and peers at
Charlestown High, bought red pens for the village teachers to mark
papers and notebooks for their students. The rest of the money was
used to buy giant sacks of corn and rice that were carried into the
village on a cart pulled by a donkey, Silverman said.
</P>
<P>
   The students stayed in various areas of the parched country,
expecting to go home last week. But then Air France went on strike
_ and remained on strike as of last night.
</P>
<P>
   The airline, which subsidized the students' trip, has put them
up in the fanciest hotel in Niamey at $140 a night. For Niger
``it's the best,'' said Camacho Monday, lowering her voice to
finish the sentence, ``but for America it's like a Days Inn.''
</P>
<P>
   Students are given a food allowance from the airline to eat in
one of the hotel's two restaurants. They've spent the last three
days chatting with guests, swimming in the pool, and sleeping.
Local residents have invited them to parties and a city newspaper
has interviewed them.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Silverman and student Santo Perez are spending their
days at the Moroccan embassy to ensure that Perez, who was born in
the Dominican Republic, can get a visa to stay in Casablanca for
one night. Americans do not need a visa. The flight will arrive in
New York, where Silverman's parents will pick up the students in a
rented van and drive them home.
</P>
<P>
   The students appear to be taking their unintended vacation well.
They have gotten used to the torrential rain and sandstorms, and
have learned how to cool down in the 105-plus degree heat by
brushing their teeth with toothpaste refrigerated overnight putting
toothpaste and washing their hair with chilled shampoo. When the
water only comes out hot, they say, you have to cool down other
items.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the wind blows, it's hotter than the sun,'' said student
Xaymara Saez, who is somewhat upset she is missing her father's
birthday today.
</P>
<P>
   But her family and other parents are at ease, saying
communication has been good from the landlocked nation and they
trust their children will be home soon.
</P>
<P>
   All the students _ Camacho, Janniver Castro, Perez, Saez and
Crump _ dream of McDonald's and Silverman plans to treat them at
the Golden Arches if and when they arrive in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   Crump, who prays every night for a safe journey home, is
concerned more about getting on a plane again. But after the first
few hours, he says, he'll look forward to giving his mother, Lisa,
a big hug and telling his classmates all he's learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been so much,'' Crump said. ``I know I'll go back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
