<HEADLINE>
BOSTON FORUM CONTRIBUTES TO CLINTON'S DIALOGUE ON RACE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS C. PALMER JR.  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton got a lot of advice Monday on how to deal with
the nation's race problems, but if he is looking for a consensus in
the debate, he will have to keep the dialogue going.
</P>
<P>
   Forty people _ black, white, and Asian _ from the Boston area
sat for two hours at the John F. Kennedy Library and contributed to
Clinton's ongoing ``One America'' conversation. There were many and
often conflicting views, which were videotaped and will be
considered for inclusion in a final report in several months.
</P>
<P>
   With dark clouds and the South Boston horizon in view through
the Stephen Smith Center's wall of windows at the library,
participants talked of Boston and its rocky racial history as a
source of conflict and possible lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Amstead, a black Vietnam veteran, said he returned from the
war to street violence sparked by the court-ordered busing of
students, and an attack he witnessed on Ted Landsmark, a black man
who was struck by a white man wielding an American flag in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Boston people pointed to the South and said, `We're
not like that,''' said Amstead, who noted that events in Boston in
the 1970s changed that belief.
</P>
<P>
   But Amstead and almost all of the other participants were
pessimistic that quick solutions could be found to racial problems.
Community exchanges like Monday's _ the first one in Massachusetts,
among 150 or so that have been held in 42 cities around the nation
_ will wrap up in September.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those who spoke Monday embraced affirmative action,
though Boston City Council President James Kelly did not. The only
question that should be asked of student applicants or prospective
employees is, ``Are they fit and willing and qualified?'' Kelly
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a trust fund either,'' he said, responding to a
previous speaker's view that one legacy of slavery is relative
poverty in the black community. Said Kelly, ``I never wanted to
have a slave, never had a slave, so don't blame me.''
</P>
<P>
   The inclusion of Kelly and of the blunt-spoken Jack Osgood, who
said whites and ``many sophisticated blacks'' do not want
integration, was a bold response to the early criticism from
conservatives that Clinton's race conversation was one-sided.
</P>
<P>
   However, even those who embrace more government-fostered
solutions and proactive remedies for lingering racial inequalities
differ on where the focus of discussion should be. Some favored
less formal, neighbor-to-neighbor talks.
</P>
<P>
   But Glendora Putnam said, ``Institutional racism is what we
should be looking at.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always struck as to how quickly we get into
victimization,'' she said. ``We can never solve our problems if we
continue to say, `I'm more oppressed than you are.'''
</P>
<P>
   Said Peter Kiang: ``I don't like to count, but I always do
count. And I think I'm the only Asian-American in the room.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany Blackwell, who works for the Greater Boston Convention
and Visitors Bureau, said honest talk about what works is
necessary. ``The current threats against affirmative action
threaten everything we've done to get to this point,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be able to live and work in Boston were it not for
affirmative action,'' added Blackwell, who said she went to a
predominantly black college where her race's contributions were
understood.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Parks, who was the first black president of the Boston
School Committee, went so far as to say that slavery should not be
viewed only for its ``absolute negative'' aspects. Blacks have
suffered the aftermath, but they played a vital part in making the
United States the rich country it is today, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three hundred years of free labor built a nation,'' Parks
said. ``All you have to do is look at the cities we have built. ...
We don't have to take a back seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Hayward of Allston said a formal apology is in order, and,
``Clinton, being the voice of America, should offer that apology to
black folks.'' Others disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in an apology for anything,'' said Brenda
Cherry, a 10-year Boston resident. ``It must be articulated in a
language that people understand, and that's money. I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherry said she had in mind grants and research that would prove
to an unconvinced public that racial diversity is critical to any
successful institution.
</P>
<P>
   Having lived in the Midwest and the South, she also said she had
observed an unwillingness to admit a problem in the Boston area.
``There's a lot of pretense here,'' she said. ``Because you're
`enlightened,' you're `New Englanders.'''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's discussion was led by William E. Leftwich III, deputy
assistant secretary of defense for equal opportunity. Like other
Clinton administration officials, he has been on the road over the
last year, explaining the process and listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leadership is important,'' he said of Clinton and other
politicians. ``But I don't think we can look to them to carry the
water. It's really up to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyra Sidberry said Mondayshe hopes some of the views expressed
make their way into a Clinton advisory board's report on race,
along with strategies to reach a solution. But she added, ``I don't
think we'll get there in my lifetime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
