<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA BORDER CITIES CHALLENGED BY MEXICAN  ENTREPRENEURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NOGALES, Sonora _ Businessman Mario de la Fuente sees a lot more
dollar signs these days on the Arizona-Sonora border.
</P>
<P>
   Just south of the border, to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, for Arizona cities like Nogales and Douglas, the
increasing economic activity celebrated by de la Fuente and others
is happening on the Mexican side.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. border towns like Nogales and Douglas, used to benefiting
from the complexity of Mexican trade regulations and the unmet
needs of Mexican shoppers, are now facing stiff challenges from
ambitious Mexican entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   And given the weak peso, the additional restrictions on Mexicans
crossing the border and the flow of business south to cheap labor,
the situation is expected to worsen.
</P>
<P>
   The North American Free Trade Agreement, advertised as a boon
for border areas, has been a cruel joke on cities like Douglas,
Mayor Ray Borane said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been one job created here by NAFTA,'' Borane
said. ``The truth of the matter is it doesn't work on our side of
the border.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, de la Fuente's bulldozers here, three miles south of
the border, begin work this week on a 5,000-seat domed amphitheater
for bullfighting, concerts and other tourist attractions.
</P>
<P>
   A Mexican department store chain recently bought by Wal-Mart, a
bowling alley and the first U.S. fast-food franchises in this city
of 250,000 will come within a year, de la Fuente said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just starting to catch up to the demand here,'' he said.
``I went to Ciudad Juarez recently and visited 14 shopping centers,
and that was only about half of what's there.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the American side, El Paso is experiencing its
roughest times economically since the Great Depression in the
aftermath of Mexico's peso devaluation in late 1994.
</P>
<P>
   De la Fuente doesn't see anything better ahead for Nogales.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long term, I don't see it as anything but a tourist
stop on the way to Mexico,'' he said, ``with some hotels and gas
stations.''
</P>
<P>
   Nogales officials are quick to differ.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that Nogales is in dire need of an economic
plan, Assistant City Administrator Ignacio Barraza said that
doesn't mean it will become ``anyone's damn parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're revitalizing downtown with a Main Street program, and we
are investigating a lot of other avenues to help us progress,''
said Barraza, noting that the city doesn't have a property tax.
</P>
<P>
   But Dan Coogan, a Nogales attorney who is a member of a
tri-national NAFTA dispute resolution board, said great concern
about the future of the state's border cities is justified,
especially in Nogales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nogales' niche has been the physical transfer of goods,
primarily produce in warehouses on this side, going north,'' Coogan
said. ``But what is to stop a supermarket chain in the Midwest from
ordering something directly from Mexico?
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in Nogales have got to be thinking about what they
can do to stay in the loop.''
</P>
<P>
   Middlemen in the produce industry already have raised red flags,
Coogan said. Land speculators have bought land along both sides of
the border for use of the direct off-load of Mexican products into
U.S. trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could spell big trouble for the produce warehouse
industry in this area because it could lead to direct transfer from
the grower to the market,'' Coogan said.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Ley, a customs broker in Douglas, sees other troubles
ahead for U.S. border cities whose economies in part rely on
business with Mexican ``maquilas,'' or twin plant, industries.
</P>
<P>
   About 34,000 Mexicans work in those plants in Nogales and in
Agua Prieta, across the border from Douglas. Traditionally,
unfinished products are shipped to the U.S. side of the border and
stored in warehouses while awaiting export to Mexico. After the
products are assembled by cheaper Mexican labor, they are exported
back to this country.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are seeing less and less of companies having both a U.S.
and Mexican presence,'' Ley said. ``The Mexicans have really
streamlined their import-permit process, and there isn't the need
like there once was for warehouses on this side. As a result, more
companies are locating their entire operations in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   But the largest concern in Nogales and Douglas is the negative
impact of federal immigration policy.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the Immigration and Naturalization Service announced
that all Mexicans would have to obtain new border-crossing cards at
a cost of $45 a person by Oct. 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican shoppers account for about 70 percent of retail sales in
Nogales and about 50 percent in Douglas, city officials said.
Officials predict dire consequences for the two towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The large majority of the people who walk across to shop here
can't afford the $45,'' said Borane, the Douglas mayor. ``Those who
can already bypass us and go to Tucson for their shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the city still pushes a plan to allow Mexicans with
legal crossing documents to receive a free ``shopper card'' for
eight hours to come into the U.S. border communities. But thus far,
Borane said, the idea has fallen on deaf ears.
</P>
<P>
   That means U.S. border-city retailers now face the burden of
high-priced cards, a $50 limit on U.S. purchases allowed back in
Mexico without paying a 23 percent tax, and the development of
competing retail outlets south of the border, Borane said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
