<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ PLAYERS TRY TO EXPLAIN EMBARRASSING LOSS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESY 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Utah Jazz spent Monday trying to explain the most
embarrassing defeat in the history of the NBA Finals. Answering
questions about Sunday night's 96-54 massacre wasn't much fun for
Karl Malone and Co., but they didn't argue with the postgame
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The Mailman and Co. delivered a stink bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's two days we got to swallow it, but I'm looking forward to
Wednesday,'' said Malone, who is quickly becoming the Roger Clemens
of the NBA postseason.
</P>
<P>
   If the Jazz want some inspiration, they can look back to the
golden days of the Celtic-Laker, Bird-Magic rivalry of the
mid-'80s.
</P>
<P>
   The 1984 Celtics opened the Finals on the Garden parquet and
suffered a 137-104 defeat at the hands of the Lakers. It was a
butt-kicking of the highest order and left little doubt that the
Lakers were the superior team. LA managed to humiliate Boston on
its home court and it looked as if James Worthy and Magic Johnson
could run the Celtics off the floor at will.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2, the Celtics played better, but still faced a 2-point
deficit in the closing seconds while the Lakers had enough time to
dribble out the clock. It was then that Celtic guard Gerald
Henderson stole a lazy cross-court pass from Worthy and made a
layup to send the game into overtime, and Boston went on to
victory. When the Celtics were routed again in Game 3, we all
counted them out because they could easily have been down, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston rallied in Los Angeles. Kevin McHale performed his
WWF takedown of Kurt Rambis in Game 4, and Cedric Maxwell said,
``It's different now. Before, the Lakers were just running across
the street without stopping to look. Now, they stop, they hit the
button, they look both ways, then they wait for the signal to
cross.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics won it in seven.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the butt-kicking shoe was on the other foot. The
Lakers came to Boston for another Game 1 and were routed, 148-114,
in the famous Memorial Day Massacre. Kareem Abdul-Jabbar was
compared with Willie Mays, stumbling toward retirement in the 1973
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened? Kareem and the Lakers rallied to take the
second game, then won the series in six, winning the championship
on the parquet floor. To this day, Pat Riley and Kareem will tell
you that winning the championship in Boston was the highlight of
their professional lives.
</P>
<P>
   So you see, it can be done.
</P>
<P>
   Bulls assistant coach Jimmy Rodgers, who was on the bench as an
assistant with the Celtics in both '84 and '85, said, ``I can't
believe our team is going to be fooled by anything. We know we're
up against a fine basketball team. I sense from the reaction of our
players that they know. You can't live on what you did two nights
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1984 when I was with the Celtics, we were embarrassed. When
a good team with pride gets embarrassed, they usually respond.''
</P>
<P>
   At this hour, the Jazz look more hopeless than the Celtics did
in 1984. Despite nine days of rest and a home-court crowd, the Jazz
struggled to beat the Bulls in overtime in the first game, they
dropped Game 2 at home. Bloody Sunday no doubt drove some Mormons
to drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to the next game,'' Jazz coach Jerry Sloan said
bravely Monday. ``I always want to see whose got fight left in
'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan, perhaps two games from retirement, downplayed
the blowout, saying, ``We're gonna look at it as just one game. I'm
pretty sure they want to redeem themselves. They're going to be
wounded, but I think that's going to make them come back harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's late-game onslaught might give the Jazz extra
incentive. Leading, 72-45, after three quarters, the Bulls went to
the bench and the Chicago scrubs demolished the Jazz reserves,
24-9, in the fourth period. Some of the Jazz took exception to the
fact that the Bulls bench hoisted five 3-pointers in the
fourth-period garbage time, connecting on four of the treys (two
apiece by Steve Kerr and Jud Buechler).
</P>
<P>
   Malone said, ``What they did to us definitely has to be
motivation. They was having a good time, still taking those threes
in the last quarter. If that can't get you motivated nothing can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
