<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-DISTANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC PLANS TO BUILD $500 MILLION LONG DISTANCE DATA
NETWORK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moving to stave off competitors offering a new generation of
digital networks, &UR;  &LR; Bell Atlantic Corp. Monday said it will begin
building a $500 million high-speed long distance data network to
carry Internet traffic &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; cl10.5 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Sprint announced plans to offer a new data and
voice network using its existing fiber optic cable network. And
other upstart companies increasingly are challenging big carriers
like Bell Atlantic by offering voice and data services directly to
business customers.
</P>
<P>
   Both Sprint &UR;  &LR; and Bell Atlantic are the latest carriers to
develop the next generation of long distance phone networks. Both
are designed mostley for businesses that depend on the Internet _
although, for Bell Atlantic, the new data capability is independent
of its current voice network.
</P>
<P>
   Several other carriers, most notably Level 3 Communications Inc.
of Omaha and Qwest Communications International Inc. of Denver, are
also developing very high speed networks to transmit data, voice
and video over fiber optic wires at a fraction of the cost of
today's much slower voice phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic said it expects to offer its service initially in
Boston, New York, Philadelphia and Washington, D.C. as early as
Jan. 1. Within five years, the company expects revenues to reach $4
billion to $6 billion in the 13-state region it serves between
Maine and Virgina, said Joseph Farina, chief executive of Bell
Atlantic's data solutions group.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bell Atlantic expects to spend up to $500 million over
the next five years to create the network, of &UR;  &LR; which $225 million
will go to Lucent Technologies Inc., which will provide equipment
and software.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that for the Boston market, this data network will
offer businesses in the Route 128 corridor tremendous potential for
high speed Internet,'' said Stewart Verge, president of Bell
Atlantic Global Networks Inc., a new unregulated subsidiary created
to build and manage the long distance data network.
</P>
<P>
   But Bell Atlantic could face regulatory roadblocks in building
the new network. The company is awaiting federal regulatory
approval to offer long distance phone services. Bell Atlantic must
still prove to the Federal Communications Commission that it has
opened its local phone market _ a requirement that company
officials say they will meet in the next 18 months in New York and
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Already, MCI Communications Corp. and AT&AMP;T Corp. have voiced
objections to plans by Bell Atlantic and two other regional Bell
operating companies to start high speed data networks. MCI and ATT
claim the networks are a way to circumvent the 1996
Telecommunications Act, which requires that the regional phone
companies open up competition in local service before offering long
distance telephone services.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, technology improvements will soon enable users to
send data and make voice calls over the Internet, creating a
possible loophole to the Telecommunications Act that worries MCI
and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a clear attempt to circumvent the law, which we think
will be unsuccessful,'' said Jonathan Sallet, MCI chief policy
counsel. ``The law applies to communications generally, not just to
voice. Bell Atlantic wants to have a monopoly on Internet traffic _
voice and data _ and that is not good for the consumer because it
takes away choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic shares closed Monday at 94 3/4, down 2 1/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 2119EDT &QL; 
