<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9920 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SANCTIONS-NYT &LR;      06-08 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SANCTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SAYS IT WILL SUPPORT NATO STRIKE IN KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., see also KOSOVO-REBELS)  
(ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo and graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(ja) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States said Monday that it would support
a British resolution in the United Nations to authorize a NATO
military intervention in the southern Serbian province of Kosovo,
and that Washington would press NATO to speed up planning for such
an action.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said that military action is not imminent,
and that Washington would act only through NATO. But they said that
a credible threat of military action is an important part of NATO
strategy to convince President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia to
end his armed forces' attacks on civilians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The national security adviser, Samuel Berger, said early Monday
that American military intervention ``is not something that is on
the table.'' But American officials said later that he meant that
unilateral American action is not being considered, and that
military planning would be left to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Monday the United States also joined the European Union in
imposing a ban on new investment in Serbia and to freeze Yugoslav
and Serbian government assets abroad. Washington and the European
Union, pressed by Britain, acted after a continuing crackdown by
Serbian special police and Yugoslav Army units in Kosovo that has
caused at least 250 deaths, driven at least 10,000 ethnic Albanians
into Albania and displaced another 50,000 people from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions were approved last month but were suspended at
Washington's request when Milosevic agreed to open talks with
Ibrahim Rugova, leader of Kosovo's ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   After a first round of talks, however, Milosevic began his
crackdown, aimed at defeating guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation
Army and creating a cordon sanitaire near the Albanian border to
prevent infiltration of arms and recruits into Kosovo. Rugova and
his team said they could not continue the talks while the violence
continued because it would undermine their credibility and their
search for a nonviolent, negotiated solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the light of the indiscriminate use of violence over the
last two weeks, and the way such violence has undermined the basis
for talks, we are proceeding to implement these bans while calling
on both sides to continue the talks,'' said James Rubin, the State
Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The investment ban will hurt Milosevic because he depends on the
sale of state industries to finance his government, Western
officials said. Government credit for private companies to invest
in Serbia was already banned. The asset freeze is largely symbolic,
since Belgrade has few assets abroad. But it will also serve as a
disincentive for future investments, because it will mean that
Belgrade cannot open bank accounts overseas. Both the European
Union and American officials said they were ready to consider other
sanctions and measures.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 nations of the European Union acted first Monday, when
foreign ministers agreed to put the sanctions in place and called
on the United Nations and NATO to consider authorizing military
action to force Milosevic and Serbia to stop its attacks on ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, where they represent 90 percent of a
population of about 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Given that Kosovo is internationally recognized as a part of
Serbia _ unlike Bosnia, which was internationally recognized as
independent _ Western officials believe that a Security Council
resolution authorizing the use of force would be necessary. The
resolution would come under Chapter 7 of the U.N. Charter, which
allows intervention to deal with a threat to international peace
and security, the same authority used in the gulf war with Iraq.
The British are consulting key countries but have not yet
circulated a draft resolution, American officials said. All key
Western countries are working to persuade Russia, which has a veto
and is a traditional Serb ally, to go along.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, fearing the precedent that an independent Kosovo could
set for Chechnya, Ingushetia, Tatarstan and other restless parts of
the Russian Federation, is extremely sensitive to any suggestion of
Western backing for Kosovo's independence.
</P>
<P>
   In Bonn on Monday night, Chancellor Helmut Kohl was expected to
try to persuade the visiting Russian president, Boris Yeltsin, to
agree to the resolution, which would serve as a strong deterrent to
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   That effort will continue when senior officials of the so-called
contact group _ the United States, Britain, Germany, France, Italy
and Russia _ meet in Paris on Wednesday. The foreign ministers of
those countries, plus Japan and Canada, will meet in London on
Friday, while NATO defense ministers will meet in Brussels on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The defense ministers could authorize planning for allied air
strikes against targets inside Serbia, a NATO diplomat said, in
addition to working on plans for ``preventive deployments'' around
Kosovo to try to prevent the fighting there from spreading through
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's crackdown has served to accelerate the recruiting
efforts of the Kosovo Liberation Army, which draws many of its
members from among ethnic Albanians from Germany and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``With every day he makes the mistake of using force rather than
finding the wisdom to negotiate, Milosevic becomes the membership
chairman'' of the KLA, Rubin said Monday, ``because he continues to
push the people of Kosovo into a more extremist posture than they
would otherwise be.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the pressure of the KLA's popularity, even Rugova
advocates independence for Kosovo, while Washington and the West
favor only more political autonomy for the province within a
federal Yugoslavia. But the federal Yugoslavia is already breaking
apart, with Milosevic having driven Montenegro into virtual
independence and Kosovo rising in rebellion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 2119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
