<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9921 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PIPPENSDEFENSE-HN     06-08 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PIPPENSDEFENSE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
CHICAGO _ Scottie Pippen will go down in basketball history as
Michael Jordan's sidekick.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Except, maybe, if you're a member of the Utah Jazz. In that
case, he will be forever known as the biggest nuisance of the 1998
NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, perhaps even more than Jordan, has put his imprint on
the Finals with his quick, rangy and _ if you believe the Jazz _
soon-to-be-illegal defense. After the Bulls held Utah to the lowest
point total in any game since the advent of the shot clock in their
96-54 win in Game 3 on Sunday, Pippen's defensive reputation has
grown to mountainous proportions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our most memorable defensive performance for a full
game,'' Bulls center Luc Longley said. ``We corralled them better
than we have since I've been with the team.''
</P>
<P>
   And Pippen is the ringleader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, is he ever,'' Longley said. ``The great thing about
Scottie is he can do so many things. You can put him on the ball
and have him guard a specific guy. Or in this case, you can put him
on (Greg) Foster or (Greg) Ostertag and have him roam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he's like the boy and the dike. He just sticks his thumb
in wherever it's needed. He did a great job. I don't know how many
charges he took. But he seemed to be everywhere we needed him.''
</P>
<P>
   The essence of Chicago's defensive strategy has been to put
Pippen on Utah's offensively challenged centers. Without having to
worry about them doing a lot of damage, Pippen can brush them off
and leave quickly to double-team John Stockton or step into the
lane when Karl Malone begins driving to the basket. Pippen drew a
pair of charges against Malone on Sunday, the second of which
started the Bulls on the blitz that broke open the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there's a better defensive player in terms of
understanding visualization and concepts,'' Bulls coach Phil
Jackson said. ``He's a one-man wrecking crew.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen's defense has been terrific throughout the playoffs but
especially so in the past two series.
</P>
<P>
   Against Indiana, he sacrificed his offense to put all his energy
into guarding Pacers point guard Mark Jackson. He effectively
neutralized the NBA's regular-season assist king.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Pippen is playing the NBA equivalent of center field,
helping out where necessary when the opportunity presents itself.
At 6-8 and with his long arms, he has been a pest to the Jazz's
offensive attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just playing a roaming defense,'' Pippen said. ``A lot of
times, Phil wants me to be a help defender, and that's how I'm
trying to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been trying to force Karl to make jump shots, but Karl
is going to try to get to the basket. You have to be man enough to
take the charge, because he comes to the basket pretty hard.''
</P>
<P>
   What is it that makes Pippen so good at his job? It's a number
of things, Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's both natural ability and desire, as well as
knowing that he has four other players in the lineup who play the
same style of defense,'' said Jordan. ``So he can gamble a little
bit, and we can cover his back. I can gamble a little bit, and they
can cover my back. There's a certain understanding there, a certain
connection with all five guys on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sets the tempo defensively. The more active Scottie Pippen
is, the better we are because we read off of his situations. He can
disrupt anybody's offense because of his ability to play so many
different players, from the point guard to, on some teams, the
(center) spot. That type (of) versatility on the defensive end
really gives us some chances to gamble quite a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Basically, what Pippen is doing against the Jazz is clogging up
the works because he's not respecting the man he's charged with
guarding. When Stockton and Malone begin to work the pick-and-roll,
Pippen goes to work.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz blames itself for letting this happen. Coach Jerry
Sloan's players know they can combat Pippen's roaming. But it takes
execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could be the best defensive player playing,'' Malone said.
``But you can have a great defensive player, and there are things
that you can do to offset that. But you have to do it as a team. We
talk about spacing and all that. And if you don't do those things,
you're playing right into their hands because he recovers really
quick and he gets into the position he wants to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockton, meanwhile, said the Jazz is at fault for not making
Pippen pay for his roaming tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were tremendous defensively,'' Stockton said of Game 3.
``I'm not going to take that away from them. The help side, the
recovery for when guys did help, was just terrific. We counter that
by being more patient when they come to help so we can expose the
illegal defense. By not doing that, it's not illegal. So it makes
it kind of simple in that regard. That's something they did from
day one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy comes right across the lane, and you go right to him,
it's not illegal. He's come to help. If you somehow maintain your
patience and don't charge right at him, trying to get something out
of it, then he's across the line. It's very visible. So there's no
finger-pointing, except at ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen countered by saying he in no way considers his defensive
tactics to be illegal under the NBA's complicated no-zone rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never. I'm never illegal,'' he said. ``When I'm leaving my
offensive player, I'm trying to go to the ball and be aggressive.
And that's what the rules say _ that any time you come double-team,
you have to be aggressive. If they turn back away, I have the right
to turn and go back to my man. That's the way I'm playing defense.
And until the officials see differently, that's the way I'm going
to continue to play it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan added that the way Pippen plays defense helps the rest of
the Bulls play better at that end of the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``That rhythm starts with Scottie and myself and then (filters
down),'' Jordan said. ``It becomes infectious. We know our
defensive strategies, and we go out and execute that. (Sunday)
night was a great execution of our defensive strategy. And we're
going to have to continue that to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The task they have to deal with is how they break down our
defensive intensity. We seem to have a good plan to try to contain
them and their set offense. What they have to do is find a way to
break open the game with their offense and get more people involved
than Karl and John. But I think we have a good feel for them. We've
played pretty solid defensively in the first three games. Sure, we
made mental mistakes in the first game, or it could be a 3-0
series. We have to keep the pressure on them defensively.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
