<SLUG> BC-RACIAL-ATTACK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI ASKED TO INVESTIGATE MAN'S MURDER IN TEXAS TOWN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Federal investigators have been called to this
East Texas town to probe the murder of a 49-year-old black man
early Sunday and the three white suspects in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jasper County Sheriff Billy Rowles said he does not
believe the crime was racially motivated, he said he contacted FBI
officials in Beaumont to see if federal charges of conspiracy to
deprive constitutional rights could be filed against the
defendants. Such charges often are filed in racially motivated
cases.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff refused to comment on allegations the victim had
been dragged behind a vehicle. He denied rumors that James Byrd Jr.
had been cut, lynched or set on fire, and said only that no firearm
was used in the crime and death was caused by ``blunt trauma.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowles also refused to identify the three men, two of them from
Jasper, who have been arrested but not yet charged in the case. The
trio could be formally charged Tuesday morning, and the sheriff
planned to address the news media afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd was found dead Sunday morning about 10 miles from his
northeast Jasper home. As investigators continued searching the
heavily wooded area late Monday afternoon, an FBI agent met with
the man's family. FBI lab personnel were processing evidence,
Rowles said.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators would not elaborate on how Byrd died. Family
members gathered at his parents' home also would not discuss it,
citing a request by authorities. An official at Robinson's
Community Funeral Home, which was expecting to receive the body
Tuesday morning, said the condition of the remains was not known.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives did say they doubt the people who killed Byrd knew the
man.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was totally at random,'' said his sister, Clara Taylor of
Houston. ``Nobody who knew him would have done anything like this.
He was in the right place at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she admitted that her brother had his faults and had
spent time in a Texas prison, she said he was well-liked within the
community. Family called him ``Son'' and friends knew him as
``Toe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a real gift of gab,'' Taylor said of her brother.
``Everybody liked him. The sheriff cried when he told us about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Department of Criminal Justice records show that Byrd was
given a seven-year sentence for theft in 1990. He was paroled twice
and returned to prison for violating parole. He was last released
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   One of eight children, Byrd spent most of his time with family
and friends, Taylor said. He was the divorced father of three and
had been gleefully holding a year-old granddaughter in his lap and
playing with her on Saturday at a gathering at his parents' home
for a niece who is getting married.
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, he went to an anniversary party for a
sister-in-law and then to visit friends, Taylor said. He was last
seen alive about 1 a.m. Sunday, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said she thinks her brother, who had no car, was walking
home to his apartment when he was induced to get into a passing
vehicle. She said she doesn't know what happened to him after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had his faults like anyone else,'' she said, ``but nothing
to make anyone want to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Callers told the sheriff's department about seeing his body in
the Huff Creek area east of Jasper at 8:20 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It couldn't have been a robbery,'' Taylor said. ``He didn't
have any money. He was always asking us for a few cents here or
there so he could buy something.''
</P>
<P>
   A former vacuum cleaner salesman, Byrd lived alone in an
apartment and supported himself on a small disability check.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Rowles said he doubted Byrd's murder was related to the
beating death a week earlier of Jerry Lynn McQueen, who was white.
Donald Louis Kenebrew, who is black, has been charged in that
crime.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Staff writer T.J. Milling in Houston contributed to this report. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
