<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. SUES INTEL, CITING HARM TO COMPUTER MAKERS
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission filed antitrust charges against
Intel, accusing it of threatening and injuring three computer
makers, including Compaq, the leading maker of personal computers.
The government contended that the company withheld information
about its microprocessors that are at the heart of a personal
computer in an effort to coerce the three companies to turn over
rights to patented technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Intel contended that the suit was ``based upon a mistaken
interpretation of the law and the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel lowered prices on its Pentium II microprocessors for
desktop computers by 12 percent to 20 percent and introduced a
faster version of its low-end Celeron processor. It cut the price
of its older, slower model by 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   WEAK YEN IMPERILS ASIA RECOVERY
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese yen weakened to 140 to the dollar for the first
time in seven years. Its yearlong decline is now threatening the
economic recovery of the emerging Asian markets that were battered
by their currency devaluations last year.
</P>
<P>
   DOW INDUSTRIALS UP 31.89 POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Stocks extended last week's gains, rising modestly, led by
financial-service and pharmaceutical stocks. The Dow industrials
gained 31.89 points, to 9,069.60.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury securities were little changed. Investors were cautious
ahead of Wednesday's scheduled congressional testimony by Alan
Greenspan, the Federal Reserve Board chairman.
</P>
<P>
   STRIKE IDLES TWO GM PLANTS
</P>
<P>
   General Motors sent 4,500 workers home at two plants as a
four-day strike by the United Auto Workers at a metal-stamping
plant in Flint, Mich., threatened to halt the company's vehicle
production.
</P>
<P>
   HONDA AND FORD FINED ON POLLUTION
</P>
<P>
   Honda will pay a record $12.6 million environmental fine,
federal prosecutors announced, because of bad programming on the
pollution-control computers in 1.6 million Honda and Accura models.
Ford will pay a $2.5 million fine for selling 60,000 Econoline vans
that emit more nitrogen oxides at highway speeds than they do on
treadmill tests.
</P>
<P>
   ROCHE RECALLS POSICOR HEART DRUG
</P>
<P>
   The prescription heart drug Posicor was pulled off pharmacy
shelves in 38 countries by its maker, Roche Laboratories. The Food
and Drug Administration cited mounting evidence of dangerous,
possibly even lethal, drug interactions.
</P>
<P>
   AOL TO BUY CHAT SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   America Online will pay at least $287 million for Mirabilis, a
small Israeli company known for its highly regarded online chat
service that enables users to detect when fellow users are online
and to communicate instantly with them. AOL's stock rose 2 percent
on the news, which was viewed by analysts as a shrewd move.
</P>
<P>
   STATE FARM TO ISSUE REBATE
</P>
<P>
   State Farm, the United States' largest auto insurer, said it
would return $891.6 million to its policyholders in 35 states and
the District of Columbia. Accident claims have fallen.
</P>
<P>
   BELL ATLANTIC PLANS DATA NETWORK
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic plans to begin building a $500 million network to
carry Internet and data traffic as it awaits regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   KOREAN ECONOMIC PAIN MOUNTS
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's economic pain is mounting, with few signs of a
turnaround. Economic output fell 3.8 percent in the first quarter,
and unemployment reached 6.7 percent in April. Both numbers
exceeded forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   President Kim Dae-jung of South Korea, who assumed office in
February, told New York business leaders that his country's
once-prized economic miracle was nothing but a ``house of cards''
and that his people now needed U.S. help to rebuild the economy.
</P>
<P>
   LAWYERS GRAPPLE FOR TOBACCO FEES
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who fought the tobacco industry have found a new battle:
fighting for their share of the richest pot of legal fees ever to
be awarded. Some in Congress are arguing for controls on the
multibillion-dollar fees.
</P>
</TEXT>
