<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: DREAD REPLACES MOURNING IN NIGERIA
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NIGERIA-ABACHA, ABACHA-OBIT, NIGERIA-OPPOSITION)  
(ja) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ Few Nigerians are in a state of
mourning over the death of Gen. Sani Abacha, a deeply unpopular
leader. But while Nigeria awaits clearer signs of its political
future, nearly all of the nation is in a state of dread.
</P>
<P>
   Abacha's legacy is a divided and demoralized army with no clear
lines of succession, a political class whose leaders have been
jailed or driven into exile and a national economy that has been
looted into penury.
</P>
<P>
   The booby traps he left in the nation's path could not only
violently rend Africa's most populous country, but also send
shudders through the West African countries that gravitate around
this region's demographic giant like so many small moons.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the very first hints of potential trouble came from
within the Nigerian army itself, when journalists summoned without
explanation to the presidential compound in the capital, Abuja,
early Monday afternoon were just as suddenly chased away.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later the military government officially announced the
death of the president which had taken place early in the day. The
lapse reflected deep divisions at the highest level of command over
the army's role both immediately and into the future, according to
retired senior officers in the Nigerian military.
</P>
<P>
   Abacha, governing in a style bordering on heightened paranoia,
left a military that is both Africa's largest and perhaps least
unified. Wave after wave of purges of senior officers, show trials
of suspected opponents and long-sustained ethnic favoritism in the
officer corps have left many commanders deeply demoralized and
dangerously suspicious of each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many of us who have made our lives in the army
because we were trained to believe that the military had something
vital to offer to the nation,'' said one senior Nigerian general in
a recent interview. ``This, however, does not include politics, and
we have a bunch of officers who come to think of themselves as
permanent politicians. In behaving this way they are dragging us
all down.''
</P>
<P>
   With feelings this raw and opinions so divergent, between those
who wish to get back to a classic republican army and those who
have for years cherished military power as a means of access to the
country's trough of abundant petroleum wealth, many now fear an
open and potentially violent split.
</P>
<P>
   ``How divided is this military? It is seriously divided,'' said
Bolaji Akinyemi, a former Nigerian foreign minister. ``What is the
strength of each faction? Nobody knows. What is certain is that
this is a very dangerous moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Abacha's unexpected death came less than four months before a
transition toward democratically-elected civilian rule he had long
promised. But by the time he died early Monday, reportedly of a
heart attack, even those who had been temporarily willing to
believe in the improbable gift of democratic rule from a stern and
secretive military man had long ago concluded that he would destroy
the country in his attempt to maintain tight personal control.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Nigerian high command is able to maintain a
reasonably united front and put forth yet another officer-designed
plan for a ``transition to democracy,'' just as seven other
military dictatorships that have dominated the country's history
since independence from Britain have before, there is no sign that
the country's political class will meekly sit back and await the
results.
</P>
<P>
   Already, in the hours following Abacha's death there have been
impassioned renewed calls for the restoration of the presidential
mandate of Moshood K.O. Abiola, the millionaire businessman who is
widely believed to have won the country's militarily annulled
elections in 1993, which international human rights groups have
called the most democratic ever held in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abiola should be invited to head a government of national
unity to organize a sovereign national conference and lead Nigeria
to genuine democracy,'' the Nigerian human rights lawyer, Gani
Fawehinmi told Reuters. ``The Nigerian people will not allow the
military to take over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, already suspecting the military has little intention of
relinquishing power, have begun to warn of the possibility of
spreading unrest. In the weeks leading up to his death street
protests against the military have erupted into small-scale riots,
and opposition leaders had already announced plans for a series of
strikes and other demonstrations against the army.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't relinquish power quickly there will be factional
struggles and great social disorder,'' said the leader of one
Nigerian human rights group who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerians, still haunted by the 30-year-old memories of the
Biafran conflict, one of Africa's bloodiest civil wars, have little
difficulty imagining a continuation, indeed acceleration of their
national tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   And throughout West Africa, where Nigeria looms huge, whether by
virtue of its 105 million people, its large army or sophisticated
economy, these kinds of scenarios are already causing serious
worry.
</P>
<P>
   In Sierra Leone, where Nigerian soldiers intervened recently to
restore the overthrown elected president, Ahmad Tejan Kabbah and
rout a rural guerrilla force that has been terrorizing much of the
countryside, people from street vendors to government officials
expressed fear Monday that disorder in Nigeria would cause that
country to lessen its commitment in Sierra Leone, perhaps allowing
the rebels to make a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abacha may have been hated in Nigeria, but he saved us here,''
said one Sierra Leonean journalist. ``If things go badly in
Nigeria, we will surely suffer again.''
</P>
<P>
   In other West African countries mounting concerns about
stability in Nigeria have less to do with Nigerian military
involvements than with fears of a huge refugee outflow.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is trouble in Nigeria, there is trouble for all of
West Africa,'' said one senior official from Ivory Coast. ``A
sinking Nigeria is big enough to swamp us all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
