<HEADER>
A9926 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-JOBS-2takes-LA     06-08 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-JOBS-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE WORLD ADDS NEW PERIL TO JOB HUNTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After the march, the diploma and the champagne,
area graduates have to face this sober fact: Landing a job.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they face one of the best job markets in recent
history, job seekers should not be complacent, recruiters say.
Indeed, pitfalls await the unprepared grad from beginning to end.
</P>
<P>
   And with cyberspace getting a big share of job applications, new
protocols have emerged for job seekers as well: Should applicants
send a hard copy resume after e-mailing it? Is it appropriate to
provide a personal Web site address on an online resume? How does
an applicant follow up on an application _ call or e-mail?
</P>
<P>
   ``Graduates have degrees in certain industries. They don't have
a degree in interviewing and how to get hired,'' said Lynn Taylor,
research director for OfficeTeam, a unit of employment services
firm Robert Half International.
</P>
<P>
   Consider these blunders by actual candidates in an OfficeTeam
survey:
</P>
<P>
   _ An employer walked into the lobby to meet a nervous candidate,
whose mouth displayed a ring of antacid from the bottle he was
holding.
</P>
<P>
   _ An applicant was asked why she wanted the job. ``I'm here for
a paycheck, isn't everybody?''
</P>
<P>
   _ An entry-level candidate became so animated during an
interview that his clip-on tie fell off.
</P>
<P>
   _ A job seeker fell asleep during a job interview.
</P>
<P>
   _ A candidate pulled his pet iguana from his briefcase, saying,
``I didn't want to bring him here, but he hates to be alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the examples are as extreme as they are funny. But
there are more subtle mistakes that can kill an applicant's chances
_ and that's no laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   When sending resumes online, it's a good idea to send one in
ASCII or plain text format with a file attachment of a Microsoft
Word or WordPerfect document, said Ken Ramberg, founder of JobTrak,
a Los Angeles-based online job search company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any computer can open ASCII,'' he said. The Word or
WordPerfect files provide a refined version of one's resume to
employers who can access it.
</P>
<P>
   Since recruiters want to see resumes that fit on one printed
page, it's OK to provide a link to a personal Web page for the
employer to look through, as long as it will help _ not hurt _ the
candidate, Ramberg added.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a silly or humorous Web page will probably hamper
the chances of an applicant seeking a job at a bank or investment
house.
</P>
<P>
   Before e-mailing the resume to the company, send a copy to
yourself first to make sure the format and font show up fine, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't use fancy graphics, unless the job calls it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers want the resume to pull up quickly. Be
straightforward with the data,'' said Marc Goldman, corporate
marketing vice president at AppleOne Employment Services, a
staffing firm in Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   Send both a cover letter and resume with the online application,
Taylor said. The cover letter reinforces the candidate's interest
in the job.
</P>
<P>
   It's advisable, but not necessary, to send a hard copy cover
letter and resume after e-mailing them to the employer, Goldman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Call or e-mail the company within a week to make sure they have
received the application, but don't make a pest of yourself, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   To get your resume noticed, plug in buzzwords for the job
opening, whether or not you're applying online. Because employers
receive thousands of resumes, many Fortune 1000 companies'
computers scan them for certain key words to narrow their search.
</P>
<P>
   Resumes containing the words sought _ such as C++ for a computer
programming job _ will be retained and gradually narrowed down to a
pool of candidates that the company can handle.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Amgen, based in Ventura County's Thousand Oaks,
does.
</P>
<P>
   The biotech firm, for instance, may scan for the word ``DNA
sequencing'' in resumes of candidates applying for a research
associate or scientist position, said Thomas Hutton, senior manager
of staffing and staffing operations.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the company will fine-tune the search to include
words like ``biology degree'' and ``chemistry degree'' or ``master
of science.''
</P>
<P>
   When the pool is sufficiently narrowed, Amgen recruiters then
look at the individual resumes for work experience, skills and
other factors.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get carried away and list all possible skills, Taylor
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be careful not to say proficiency if you only have some
exposure to it. It could get you in trouble later on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's critical to make a good first impression with one's resume
and cover letter, since they usually form the candidate's first
contact with the company, recruiters say.
</P>
<P>
   Misspellings, grammatical errors, smudges and a poor print job
will hurt an applicant's chances. Using brightly colored paper also
isn't recommended for most positions, recruiters said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go to Kinko's. It's money well-spent,'' Goldman said. ``The
first impression is sometimes the only impression you get to make.
Make it perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Let someone else proofread them before they're mailed out, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   As for content, the most relevant work and academic experience
should be highlighted. A college graduate without years of
experience in the field would do well to emphasize any academic
achievements, internships or part-time jobs. A high grade-point
average should be listed as well.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   But tell the truth. Listing false degrees or job experiences can
be grounds for termination later on, recruiters say.
</P>
<P>
   Once an interview is granted, the candidate should research the
company's business, culture and goals to prepare for the one-on-one
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   With the Internet making research easy, candidates have no
excuse for not finding out about their prospective employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how many college graduates don't do it,'' said
Anthony Mulkern, founder of Mulkern Associates, a Glendale
management consulting firm that helps recruiters assess job
candidates. ``There's no excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the interview, dress conservatively. That means
dark-colored suits for men and women, preferably navy blue. Even if
the company has a casual dress policy, the recruiter wants to see
the candidate at his or her best.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take a risk when you go outside that set,'' Hutton said.
</P>
<P>
   Look neat. Men should trim beards and chuck any earrings,
Goldman said. Women shouldn't wear overpowering perfume or big
jewelry, but panty hose are a must.
</P>
<P>
   Show up a little early for the interview. In Southern
California, that means allowing enough time for traffic.
</P>
<P>
   When meeting recruiters, have a firm handshake and look them in
the eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to like somebody who won't look you in the eyes,''
Goldman said. ``(Recruiters) will hire someone they feel
comfortable with.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, be prepared but stay away from canned answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost as bad as coming in too slick,'' Mulkern said.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiters don't like candidates who oversell themselves without
having anything specific to back their claims, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, before claiming to be a team player, candidates
must come up with specific examples where they exhibited this
quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to talk about what they have done specifically
rather than (spout) vague generalities,'' Mulkern said.
</P>
<P>
   After the interview, send a thank-you note within a day or two
of the meeting reiterating your interest in and appropriateness for
the job.
</P>
<P>
   Having recommended all that, job recruiters say there's one
exception to all those rules: computer programmers.
</P>
<P>
   With more jobs than graduates, competition for candidates is
stiff.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're good, you can get away with almost anything,''
Ramberg said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 2127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAIRY-PRICES-ART-1     06-08 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIRY-PRICES-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 FIGHT ON MILK PRICES MAKING ITS WAY TO CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLISLE, Mass. _ Do not be fooled by the virtuous grins on all
those celebrities with the white mustaches. The question ``Got
Milk?'' and its corollaries ``How much?'' and ``At what price?''
are fueling what economists call the most contentious, most
political battle over agricultural policy in the East, if not the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   The fight affecting cows named Oprah and Cher involves Mark
Duffy's dairy farm here, 20 miles northwest of Boston. It has
already burst through a score of other statehouses and is expected
to flare in the New York legislature this week. And it will soon
play itself out in Washington, pitting East against Midwest,
farmers against dairy processors, those who want to preserve
farmland against those who want to preserve lower milk prices.
</P>
<P>
   The formal name for the focus of these milk wars is the
Northeast Interstate Dairy Compact, a treaty-like agreement among
the six New England states. It guarantees their dairy farmers a
higher price for drinking milk than the one dictated under the
system the federal government has been using to set farmers' milk
prices since the depression. Created by federal law, the agreement
acts something like a regional minimum wage for farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The compact, which went into effect last July, is meant to shore
up the region's remaining dairy farms, whose numbers have dropped
by nearly half over the last decade to about 4,600. By April, the
compact had paid New England farmers a total of $33 million more
for their milk than what federal pricing would have paid them, the
commission that runs the compact says.
</P>
<P>
   The price of milk in New England stores, meanwhile, has jumped
about a dime or 15 cents a gallon to an average of $2.88, the
commission's executive director, Ken Becker, said. He figures the
compact has cost New England's 13 million residents about $2.50
each since it went into effect.
</P>
<P>
   That seems acceptable to some, but not to opponents of the
compact, who include advocates for consumers and the poor, groups
of dairy processors who must pay the higher prices, and Midwestern
farmers, who are worried that if New England's milk production
rises and increases the national supply, then the prices for milk
outside New England will drop.
</P>
<P>
   These opponents say the agreement has fulfilled several of their
Economics 101 projections that when price rises, so does the
incentive to produce, thus swelling supplies, while demand drops.
New England's production this spring was up 2.4 percent over 1997,
Becker said, while the national average was up less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That is another problem because the compact specifies that if
New England milk supplies jump disproportionately and the compact
is determined to be the cause, the New England states must
reimburse the U.S. Department of Agriculture for buying up the
extra supply to keep it from affecting the national market.
Already, the compact commission has held back a total of $1 million
from farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing has backfired,'' said John Schnittker, an economist
with Public Voice for Food and Health Policy, a consumer advocacy
group in Washington. ``We've got consumers paying more; we've got
surplus production; we've got government cost, and the extra
revenues the consumers are paying are being directed back into the
federal Treasury. This is a lose-lose-lose policy right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The compact's backers, however, say that other factors besides
price are at work: El Nino brought bad weather to the West and
warmer weather to the East, they say, and the mild winter combined
with better feed harvests has increased cows' milk production here.
</P>
<P>
   Duffy, whose farm in Carlisle is about average for New England
in its milking herd size _ 60 cows _ said that the compact has
brought him $5,570 extra so far, raising his milk receipts by about
3 percent. But he said his production is up because of the mild
winter and a good harvest of corn for feed last fall, not because
of the price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't go out and buy a single cow,'' Duffy said. Rather,
his family decided to use the extra money to invest in modernizing
some stalls and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the compact commission is working on altering its rules
in order to discourage big increases in production, and is
discussing ways to direct the payments more to small farmers and
less to big farms, which already enjoy economies of scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a work in progress,'' said Jay Healy, Massachusetts
commissioner of food and agriculture and a backer of the compact
for its potential to save disappearing farmland. The compact has
already altered its rules in response to criticism that higher milk
prices hurt those who can least afford it. Participants in the
Women, Infants and Children nutrition program were compensated for
higher milk costs from the start; school lunch programs will be as
well, beginning this August.
</P>
<P>
   But the compact will be hard-put to compensate for another
predictable result: New Englanders are drinking about 2 percent
less milk than a year ago, compared with a slight rise in the rest
of the country, said E. Linwood Tipton, president of the Milk
Industry Foundation, a Washington organization of milk processors,
manufacturers and marketers that is leading the charge against the
compact.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a word,'' he said. ``It's spelled M-A-R-K-E-T. It
actually works and that's what the rest of the dairy industry is
living with, and they seem to be surviving and thriving.''
</P>
<P>
   The conflict also touches on the question of whether, at a time
when the federal government is moving away from supporting prices
for commodities like corn, wheat and milk, consumers should be
asked to help provide American farmers with a new economic safety
net. Many see the compact as insurance for farmers as the federal
government fiddles with its own complex system for pricing milk
across the nation. But the dairy compact itself is facing an
imminent deadline. Under federal law, the compact expires next
April. Unless it is re-authorized, it dies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But while the federal fate of the agreement may be up in the
air, other states are jumping on the compact bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen Southern states, from Tennessee to Texas, have
expressed interest in forming a Southern dairy compact, and several
of their legislatures have passed laws to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, New Jersey, Maryland and Virginia have passed laws
recently seeking to join the existing dairy compact. The federal
law creating the Northeast compact left it open to future
participation by New York, New Jersey, Maryland, Pennsylvania and
Delaware but only as contiguous states. The focus of the political
fight over the compact has thus shifted to Albany, because if New
York does not join, neither can New Jersey and the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The New York state Senate passed a bill calling for the state,
with its 9,000 dairy farms, to join this winter, and Gov. George
Pataki endorsed the idea despite complaints that it helped upstate
farmers at the expense of downstate consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Assembly, where the bill's fate is expected to be
decided this week, the compact suffered a major blow last month
when William Parment, the chairman of the Agriculture Committee,
withdrew his sponsorship of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that I want to jump into something that's not
well-tested and has the potential for negative impact for both
consumers and farmers,'' Parment said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Novakovic, director of Cornell University's Program on
Dairy Markets and Policy and a leading expert on the dairy
industry, said he believed the compact could be made to work.
</P>
<P>
   In his assessment, retail prices have risen only slightly thus
far to a level not unusual in other parts of the country, while
farmers have gotten a definite lift; but it is worrisome that there
are reports of a surplus that can drive prices down elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   He was gloomy about the compact's prospects for a federal
extension, but then immediately hedged his bet, noting that he had
bet his house the compact would never pass in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing nobody took me up on it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
