<HEADER>
A9930 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RODMANFINED-HNS &LR;      06-08 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RODMANFINED-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
CHICAGO _ In case anybody had forgotten, Dennis Rodman is still
Dennis Rodman.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The unpredictable Chicago forward was fined $10,000 by the NBA
and an undisclosed amount by the Bulls for missing practice and a
mandatory media session Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bulls coach Phil Jackson said he talked to Rodman by telephone
as the team's practice was winding down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke with Dennis,'' Jackson said. ``He didn't speak back.
But this is not a practice day. This is a day when you have to be
here to meet the press. Dennis obviously is susceptible to the fine
from the NBA for not being here and also from us. But he's willing
to go through that. Physically, we didn't go through a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way, Dennis, practice is at 10:30 tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman's unexcused absence is another in a long line of problems
the hair-dye king has had with respecting the Bulls' coaching staff
and authority figures in general. Last season, he kicked a
cameraman, suffered a lengthy suspension, missed countless Bulls
workouts, showed up late for games and had a plethora of other
controversies envelop him.
</P>
<P>
   This season, with a contract based mostly on incentives for
remaining on good behavior and playing in at least 75 of the 82
regular-season games, Rodman improved his work habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody understands that this is a guy concentrating
at times on the mundane parts of this game,'' Jackson said. ``He's
not particularly comfortable in these (interview) situations. He's
willing to take whatever deviant action happens and take
responsibility for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He rarely offers an excuse for this. He never tells me he had
a flat tire, or something happened, or his dog ate his keys. He
just says, `I was late.' I asked him, `What do you think I should
say to the press?' And he hung up on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, he hung up because he was on his way out to lunch, a
place some of his superiors believe describes where Rodman often
is.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour after the other Bulls filtered out of the
United Center, Rodman was seen arriving for lunch with his
entourage at a Hooters restaurant in downtown Chicago. He was in a
jovial mood, although he did not want to talk about what activities
kept him from the morning practice.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Bulls know Rodman wasn't in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dennis Distraction Factor cannot be dismissed,
especially in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis is not here, and I'm pretty sure Phil is going to fine
him,'' Michael Jordan said. ``That's something we have to address.
With Dennis comes a lot of baggage. And unfortunately, this is one
of the baggage areas we have to accept. How long will the
organization accept it? It depends. But we know when he steps on
the basketball court, he's going to give us 110 percent. In some
ways, we have to put up with some of the baggage.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Scottie Pippen: ``It's very frustrating at this time, but
you don't want to carry that into the next game or the next
practice. You want the team chemistry to stay as strong as
possible. The situation we're in right now, we don't want Dennis
taking the focus away from the team. He's going to come to practice
tomorrow, hopefully, and have some lame excuse. But we're going to
overlook it and look forward to the next game. We want him to come
to play but also come to practice, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The one bit of solace Jackson can take is that he at least
doesn't have a whole team of Rodmans _ or young players who might
be overly distracted by him.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was asked what it would be like if there were more
Rodmans in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be in chaos,'' Jackson said. ``We couldn't have a
society. Dennis is not a normal person.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if managing Rodman is a little like being a kindergarten
teacher, Jackson said: ``It's a little bit more like being in
special ed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
