<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-TRAINING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COHEN UPHOLDS MIXED MILITARY TRAINING FOR MEN AND WOMEN  
 (JT )
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID STOUT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defense Secretary William Cohen said on Monday that
the Army, Navy, and Air Force would continue to train male and
female recruits together but would provide stricter privacy and
security in the barracks areas.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary's announcement was expected and, in a sense,
anticlimactic. On March 16, when he rejected a special panel's
recommendation that the services segregate men and women for much
of basic training, he nevertheless told military leaders to do more
to separate them in their living quarters. Cohen said Monday he had
approved plans that the services submitted to him for carrying out
those goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot run a military without women, and our goal is to
find a way to train men and women together,'' the secretary said,
noting that 14 percent of the people in the military are women.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue of the treatment of women in the military remains
contentious. Although he stressed Monday that he had accepted most
of the recommendations of a special panel that investigated the
issue, Cohen nonetheless rejected in March the panel's main
recommendation, for segregation in basic training.
</P>
<P>
   That panel, headed by former Sen. Nancy Kassebaum Baker, was
appointed by Cohen in the aftermath of several highly publicized
sex scandals, some involving male instructors who had relations
with female trainees.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of segregating men and women in the services is sure to
be hotly debated in Congress. The House, as part of the
defense-authorization bill, voted last month to separate basic
training of men and women, and the Senate is expected to take up
the matter soon.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary said he did not plan a ``massive lobbying
campaign'' but was confident that Congress would listen to the
recommendations of military leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen sought to give the impression that stricter security and
privacy, as opposed to outright segregation, would require no major
changes. He said the Army would need to spend relatively little to
provide ``totally separate and secure sleeping areas and latrines''
for men and women, but would not necessarily house men and women on
different floors. The Navy and Air Force, on the other hand, will
continue to house male and female recruits on separate floors, with
some additional security ``enhancements.'' The Marine Corps will
continue to house men and women in separate barracks and run
separate boot camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``With their different missions, traditions and conditions of
service, some differences in the ways the services conduct their
basic training are appropriate and desirable,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary said the services would also intensify physical
training, make the job of training instructor more attractive, and
re-emphasize ``core military values,'' like courage, honesty and
loyalty, over materialistic values, like joining the service to get
money for college.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
