u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-ABACHA-ART-55     06-08 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-ABACHA-ART-550(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIAN DICTATOR DEAD; SUCCESSION UNCERTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also, ABACHA-OBIT, NIGERIA-ASSESS and NIGERIA-OPPOSITION)  
(ART ADV: Map and graphic are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 By ROBERT McFADDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gen. Sani Abacha, the dictator of Nigeria, whose ruthless
suppression of opponents, human rights and democracy led to
condemnation around the world and seething discontent at home, died
suddenly early Monday, leaving Africa's most populous nation
rudderless, and also at a crucial political crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   As Nigeria's top military and government leaders convened, it
was unclear who would succeed the general and lead the oil-rich
nation of 115 million, a country wracked by decades of harsh,
corrupt military regimes and the effects of Western sanctions
imposed in a futile effort to hasten democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   But from Washington, London, Paris and other capitals, world
leaders and exiled Nigerians said that the death of the general
offered an opportunity for Nigeria to release hundreds of political
prisoners, cancel impending executions set by kangaroo courts and
restore civilian government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abacha's death is not going to bring my father back,'' said
Ken Wiwa, the son of playwright and environmental activist Ken
Saro-Wiwa, who, with eight other opponents of the general, was
publicly hanged for ``treason'' in 1995 while a worldwide
outpouring of appeals for mercy was icily ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Wole Soyinka, the Nigerian playwright who won the 1986 Nobel
Prize for literature, fled to exile in Paris in 1994 and was
recently charged in absentia with treason, said from Jerusalem that
the general's death was an ``incredible opportunity'' for Nigeria
to resurrect democracy.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the White House offered no comment, but a State
Department spokesman, James Rubin, offered sympathy to Abacha's
family, reaffirmed the U.S. commitment to promoting democracy in
Nigeria, and urged a ``peaceful transition to civilian, democratic
rule.''
</P>
<P>
   After a morning of rumors and confusion in which heavily armed
soldiers sealed off the general's compound in the capital of Abuja,
a brief communique by the defense chief of staff, Gen. Abdulsalam
Abubakar, confirmed that the 54-year-old Nigerian leader, who
seized power in 1993, was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The head of state and commander in chief of the Nigerian armed
forces, Gen. San Abacha, died at dawn,'' the statement read on
national radio said. ``He was to be buried today in Kano, his
native town, in accordance with Muslim rites and tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   The communique did not specify the cause of death, but news
reports quoted family friends and western diplomats as saying he
had suffered a heart attack. U.S. officials said they had no
evidence of foul play. Reports that Abacha's health was failing
circulated after he canceled a highly publicized trip to Lagos,
Nigeria's principal city and former capital, last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the death drew no outpouring of sorrow in Nigeria, where
the general had tamed political parties, trade unions and the
press, and had an enemies list that read like a Who's Who of
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   In Lagos, where opposition to Abacha had been strongest, there
were no signs of mourning. Small crowds gathered on corners, and
there was cautious talk about the passing of a widely despised
leader. ``God is capable of wonderful things,'' an opposition
political figure in Lagos said from behind a screen of anonymity.
``Perhaps Nigerians will be free at last.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
