<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-BILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTT WANTS TOBACCO BILL WITHDRAWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., S.D.)  (lb) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Turning up the heat in a partisan debate, Sen.
Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Republican leader, said Monday that
the tobacco bill now before the Senate was such poor legislation
that it should be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott was careful not to say at his news conference how or
when that could happen or who would do it.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third week the bill has been before the Senate, and
little progress has been made in bringing it to a vote. The Senate
is scheduled to vote on Tuesday and Wednesday on Democratic moves
to cut off debate, efforts that are bound to fail as long as nearly
all Republicans follow Lott and oppose them.
</P>
<P>
   At a separate news conference, Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota,
the Democratic leader, threatened that Democrats would tie up the
Senate so that no other issue could be voted on until a definitive
vote was cast on the tobacco bill. He also said that if the
Republicans blocked the anti-smoking measure, they would have to
answer for it in the election campaigns this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, meant to discourage teen-agers from starting to smoke,
would raise the price of cigarettes by at least $1.10 a pack over
five years, strengthen federal regulation of tobacco products and
force the cigarette manufacturers to pay stiff penalties if youth
smoking did not fall to specified levels.
</P>
<P>
   Ten weeks ago, the bill was approved by the Senate Commerce
Committee by a bipartisan 19-1 vote. But since then, a deep
partisan divide has developed, as the statements Monday by Lott and
Daschle suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans argue that the legislation is a tax-and-spend,
big-government approach to the problem of teen-age smoking. ``The
bill has grown and grown and grown, and what has happened is that
greed has just taken over,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a spending bill,'' he added, ``and it should be pulled.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority leader has the authority to pull, or withdraw, a
bill from consideration, and Lott, like all leaders, has sometimes
done so despite the wishes of a bill's supporters. But on Monday,
when asked when and whether he would do that, he replied, ``Well,
you know, in the Senate, you don't just walk up and pull it on your
own.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
