<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9941 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WELLS-SFCHRON &LR;      06-08 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELLS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Wells merger makes bank 7th largest  
   
 By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
In yet another megabanking deal, Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. confirmed
yesterday that it has agreed to merge with Norwest Corp. of
Minneapolis to create the country's seventh-largest bank.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The combined bank will retain the Wells Fargo name, which has
been around since the Gold Rush era, and its headquarters will
remain in San Francisco. It will have $191 billion in assets,
branches in 21 states, about 20 million customers and more than
90,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo shareholders will own approximately 52.5 percent of
the combined company, and both banks will have equal representation
on the board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   The major concession by Wells is that Chairman Paul Hazen will
relinquish his chief executive title at the new Wells Fargo to
Richard Kovacevich, his counterpart at Norwest who initiated merger
discussions about a month ago. Both Kovacevich and Norwest
President Leslie Biller will move to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in New York yesterday, both Hazen and
Kovacevich characterized the deal as ``a merger of equals.'' The
same term was used by the CEOs of Bankamerica and NationsBank to
describe their merger plans two months ago. In that case, though,
BofA ceded not only the CEO slot, but the headquarters of the
combined bank and equal representation on the board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   BofA's concessions _ especially its agreement to move the
headquarters of the new bank to Charlotte, N.C. _ ignited a storm
of protest in the Bay Area. By contrast, Wells Fargo's deal with
Norwest was greeted with general approval.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco city officials even suggested that Wells Fargo
should get preference in obtaining city business. ``I will look
with much greater fondness on a company based here,'' said
Supervisor Michael Yaki, a leading critic of the BofA deal. ``The
city should look at ways to reward them, maybe by moving their
checking accounts there.''
</P>
<P>
   City Treasurer Susan Leal added, ``The news of the Wells Fargo
merger is as good as can be expected. It sounds as though Wells
Fargo will become bigger and stronger, and that's good news for San
Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   BofA currently handles most of the city's checks, but Leal
indicated that Wells Fargo could break into the business. ``Someone
who is based here would mean something to us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kovacevich, who earned his MBA degree at Stanford while Hazen
received his from the University of California at Berkeley, said
that basing the bank in San Francisco and adopting the Wells Fargo
name made obvious sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combined bank will have $54billion of deposits in
California, compared to $13 billion in Minnesota,'' he said. In
addition, he noted that the Wells Fargo name and stagecoach logo
are known throughout the West, while ``there were problems with the
Norwest name (short for Northwest) in states like California, Texas
and Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides their geographic differences, the product lines are
different at both banks. Wells Fargo is a leader in alternative
financial delivery channels such as ATMs, supermarket branches and
online banking. It also is big in commercial real estate and small
business lending.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Norwest is strong in a broader range of consumer
financial products, including home mortgages, insurance and loans
to consumers with less than sterling credit records.
</P>
<P>
   The Wells Fargo-Norwest merger is taking place as banks have
been merging at a frenzied pace to gain economies of scale and
compete more forcefully with nonbank competitors like brokerages,
mutual funds and credit card companies.
</P>
<P>
   Both Wells and Norwest could have grown by themselves, but
merging achieved the goal more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, which needs shareholder and regulator
approval, Wells Fargo shareholders would get 10 shares of common
stock of Norwest for each share of Wells Fargo common stock.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is valued at about $31.4 billion, based on the price of
Norwest stock, which lost $2.87 yesterday and closed at $36.81.
Wells stock closed at $365.75, up $2.50.
</P>
<P>
   Upon completion of the deal, the combined bank will rank as the
top U.S. bank in originating mortgage loans and servicing them, as
well as No. 1 in agricultural lending and online banking. It will
rank No. 2 in small business loans and automated teller machines,
with a network of 6,152 ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no surprise that Wells was looking for a merger
partner,'' said analyst Campbell Chaney of Sandler O'Neill &AMP;
Partners. ``Its earnings were not living up to expectations since
its merger with First Interstate, and shareholders were very
restless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With the massive consolidation of the financial services
industry,'' he added, ``if you don't keep investors happy, you
don't earn the right to remain independent.''
</P>
<P>
   At a teleconference from New York, Hazen did not say Wells Fargo
had to merge. But he conceded that he learned important lessons
from the First Interstate acquisition _ namely, that it doesn't pay
to embark on unfriendly takeovers and try to rush the results.
</P>
<P>
   Hazen said that because of lucrative severance packages, about
500 of First Interstate's top executives had more financial
incentive to leave than see the merger through and help with the
transition. In addition, Hazen said, ``We tried to integrate the
company too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   In that merger there was extensive overlap, and Wells axed more
than 7,000 jobs as well as hundreds of branches. As a result of
faltering service and computer glitches, there were serious
customer defections, too.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than complete all systems conversions in nine months, as
it did with First Interstate, Wells is looking for a much longer
gestation period this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Integration of the two banks will not be completed for three
years. In part, that results from the need to focus attention on
upgrading the banks' computer systems to handle the year 2000
conversion problem.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to achieve $650 million in annual cost savings
within three years. About 2,300 positions out of 90,000 will be
eliminated, mostly at the headquarters of the two banks. But citing
the ``train and retain'' theme, both Kovacevich and Hazen said that
the plan is to lay off few workers.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for this kinder, gentler approach is that there is
hardly any overlap between Norwest and Wells Fargo. The two banks
operate in five of the same states, but they only expect to have to
sell or close a few branches in Arizona and Nevada to meet the
concerns of regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers said another reason for the more deliberative
approach to the bank merger is Norwest's very different corporate
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norwest is more in rural markets and has high-touch
relationships with its customers,'' said Van Kasper analyst Joe
Morford. ``Wells Fargo deals more in densely populated metropolitan
markets and has a cost-conscious streamlined approach to banking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
