r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORWEST-SFCHRON &LR;      06-08 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORWEST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Banks Come From Different Perspectives  
   
 By Arthur M. Louis  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
It was strictly lovey-dovey yesterday as the chief executives of
Wells Fargo and Norwest took turns ballyhooing the proposed merger
of their companies. But experts say the two banking giants have
``wildly dissimilar'' corporate cultures.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minneapolis-based Norwest, which was founded in 1929, ranks 10th
in the nation in assets _ just ahead of 11th-place Wells. But it is
about as old-fashioned as a big bank can be, with an abundance of
branches and a strong emphasis on personalized customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Most other banks _ Wells foremost among them _ impose tight,
centralized control over their operations and try to squeeze out
profits largely by cutting personnel and other costs and shutting
down supposedly superfluous branches.
</P>
<P>
   Norwest has bucked the trend by expanding aggressively, mainly
through &UR;  &LR; acquisitions of much-smaller banks. It boasts more than
4,000 bank branches, consumer-finance offices and mortgage-lending
outlets spread across all 50 states and offering a vast array of
financial products.
</P>
<P>
   Norwest grants considerable autonomy to its 60,000 employees _
whom it dubs ``team members'' _ at the branch level, on the premise
that it will help build solid relationships with customers.
</P>
<P>
   It follows what the banking industry calls the ``high-touch''
approach, as distinguished from the ``high-tech'' approach, in
which customers are encouraged to interact with automated teller
machines rather than bank employees. Wells Fargo is a leading
proponent of ``high-tech.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Norwest's theory is if we sell more products, we will grow,''
says Ben Crabtree, an analyst with the Dain Rauscher brokerage firm
in Minneapolis. ``They are far more revenue-oriented than
cost-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy clearly has paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Norwest's profits have grown by more than 20 percent annually
over the past decade, and its stock price has shot up tenfold. It
ranks among the top five banks nationwide in return on assets and
in keeping bad loans off its books.
</P>
<P>
   Norwest is the nation's largest originator and servicer of home
mortgages, operates the largest bank-owned insurance agency and is
the fourth-largest issuer of student loans.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kovacevich, who has served as chief executive of Norwest
for five years and will continue in that role with the merged
company, is a fervent advocate of the growth-and-service culture
and a principal architect of the company's great success. Crabtree,
who has observed him up close, calls him ``a very strong leader.''
</P>
<P>
   His opposite number, Wells CEO Paul Hazen, who will hold the
largely ceremonial title of chairman in the merged operation, has
faced a slew of troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them stem from his company's hostile takeover of First
Interstate in 1996, which was followed by a wave of branch
closings, asset sales and layoffs totaling 20 percent of the
workforce. That drove away many former First Interstate customers
who were accustomed to a greater measure of ``high touch'' service.
</P>
<P>
   Although the merged bank will be based in San Francisco and take
the Wells Fargo name, experts say the presence of Kovacevich in the
CEO's chair should make for a kinder, gentler operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 2136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
