<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLLAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEN CONTINUES ITS SLIDE, THREATENING OTHER ASIAN MARKETS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Japanese yen weakened to 140 to the dollar for the first
time in seven years Monday, extending a yearlong decline that is
now threatening the economic recovery of the emerging markets in
Asia that were battered by their currency devaluations last year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fallout from the weakening yen, many currency
traders and strategists expect its value to decline further because
the Japanese government has not come up with a convincing program
to stimulate the economy. Many economists have already said Japan
is in a recession, which could be confirmed Friday when Tokyo is
expected to report its second consecutive quarterly decline in
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Economists and analysts said the falling yen was hurting Asia's
recovery in two ways: One, the decline is a reflection of a
weakening Japanese economy that means Japan will not be a big buyer
of products from the troubled countries of South Korea, Thailand
and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   The weakening yen also means South Korean, Thai and other Asian
manufacturers will have a harder time competing against Japanese
goods sold elsewhere, especially in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A weakening currency makes that country's products less
expensive abroad. But the advantage that South Korea and other
Asian countries gained with their devaluations has been reduced by
the 18 percent fall in the yen since last July, when the Asian
crisis began.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competitive edge that South Korea has obtained is
minimal,'' said Desmond Lachman, the head of emerging-markets
research at Salomon Smith Barney. And, he said, ``If the yen slides
toward 150 we can be sure we are going to have real regional
currency turmoil.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that one important unknown was how the Chinese would
react to the yen's weakness. The Chinese said they would not
devalue in the wake of the Asian devaluations. But Lachman said
that he believed China's restraint was based on the assumption that
the yen would remain relatively stable and not damage China's
competitiveness. A Chinese devaluation now could set off another
round of devaluations.
</P>
<P>
   The yen's latest decline came after Koji Tanami, Japan's vice
finance minister, indicated that finance ministers in the Group of
Seven industrialized nations were not going to discuss the yen's
problems in Paris today and tomorrow. In addition, Tanami said it
was unlikely that the United States, Japan, Germany, France,
Britain, Italy and Canada would take action to support the yen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main topic of the meeting will be Russia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In late trading in New York, the dollar cost 140.71 yen, up from
139.75 Friday. The dollar also rallied against the German mark,
rising to 1.7794 marks from 1.7745.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to its strength against the yen, the dollar had been
falling in value against the mark since April.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a whole lot the G-7 can do for the yen without
the Japanese government providing the policy for support,'' Lachman
said. Even a surprising round of central bank intervention to
support the yen after these comments would only have a temporary
impact if Japan's policies are not changed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a succession of fiscal stimulus programs, the Japanese
government has not yet done enough to stimulate the economy or to
deal with the mountain of bad loans that is undermining its banking
system, said Jeremy Fand, senior foreign exchange strategist at
BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamentally, there is no reason why the yen should
strengthen,'' said Fand, who is forecasting that the dollar could
strengthen to 180 yen in the next 12 months. But he also said that
the yen had fallen so much recently that it might be in line for a
sharp rebound in the near term before resuming its decline.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the dollar's strength was also highlighted
yesterday in a report by the Bank for International Settlements,
which coordinates the activities of the world's central banks. The
bank said the dollar was overvalued by 33 percent against the yen
and 21 percent against the mark, which makes American exports less
competitive and increases the likelihood that the American trade
deficit will keep growing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9944 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-ABACHA-ART-2N     06-08 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-ABACHA-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: at last.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reports from Kano, the northern city where Abacha was born in
1943, said that thousands of people lined the streets, awaiting the
arrival of the general's body and an escort of senior government
and military officials who were to attend the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't know what to think,'' a Kano businessman who had
closed his shop for the day told the Reuters news service. ``It's
true some people are sad, but some will not be so sad either. We
just worry over what comes next.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the question on many minds.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of Abacha _ who wielded absolute power and was so
haunted by the specter of a coup that he surrounded himself with a
2,000-member personal security force, rarely appeared in public and
jailed or executed many leading Nigerians _ there was a political
vacuum Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The general left no clear successor. His former
second-in-command, Lt. Gen. Donaldson Oladipo Diya, who had been
seen as a possible successor, was sentenced to death by a military
tribunal in April for allegedly plotting a coup. His fate is still
in the hands of the military junta.
</P>
<P>
   As Nigeria's leaders gathered in Abuja in a body called the
Provisional Ruling Council, a behind-the-scenes power struggle over
the next few days seemed likely. Political analysts said the likely
contenders to succeed the general included Abubakar, the defense
chief; Lt. Gen. Jeremiah Useni, Nigeria's most senior officer, and
Maj. Gen. Ishiaya Bamaiyi, the army chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   But a coalition of 45 Nigerian groups that had clandestinely
opposed Abacha called Monday for the installation of a civilian
government headed by Moshood K.O. Abiola, who was imprisoned by
Abacha after his election as president in 1993 in what was widely
seen as the country's most democratic vote since it gained
independence from Britain in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   While Abiola remains in prison, his wife, Kudirat, an outspoken
critic of the regime, was shot down in Lagos in an execution style
killing in 1996 that has gone unsolved. Abiola's daughter, Hafsat,
23, a Harvard-educated resident of Maryland who works with the
Special Olympics, called Monday for her father's release. ``It's
the end of an era, and I hope the end of military rule,'' she said
in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Abacha has been the seventh and by most accounts most brutal of
the military dictators who have ruled Nigeria for 27 of its 38
years of nationhood. independence. Tucked into the elbow of
Africa's west coast, Nigeria was under British control for more
than a century before gaining independence in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   It is a nation of 250 tribal groups. The Hausa and Fulani in the
north, the Yoruba in the southwest and the Ibos in the southeast
make up 65 percent of the population. The 1960s were marked by a
struggle for political dominance among the major ethnic groups, and
a devastating civil war almost broke the country apart in the late
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1970s oil exports helped Nigeria recover
economically, and in the early 1980s, with a civilian government in
Lagos, Nigeria became known as a model of African democracy and
prosperity. Nigerian arts were the envy of the continent. Its press
was one of the freest anywhere. Nigerian diplomacy forcefully
challenged the United States and Britain over issues like
apartheid. The nation's currency was worth twice as much as the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   But democracy in Nigeria died in 1983, and Abacha, a career
soldier who became an infantryman at 18 and attended military
colleges in England, the United States and Nigeria, had a role in
three military coups.
</P>
<P>
   When generals ousted Nigeria's last civilian government in 1983,
it was Abacha who announced it on national television. In 1985, he
again went on television, this time to announce that Gen. Mohammed
Buhari was being replaced by Gen. Ibrahim Babangida. Later,
Babangida named Abacha as his defense minister.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for a return to democracy were high in June 1993, when
Abiola, a millionaire businessman, won an election with pledges to
return Nigeria to civilian government. But Babangida annulled the
election, and three months later Abacha overthrew Babangida.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola, frustrated over his stolen victory, declared himself
president in defiance of Abacha and was jailed on treason charges.
Abacha promised democratic reforms and an election in 1996 to bring
back civilian government, but the promises proved hollow.
</P>
<P>
   While announcing that he was stretching his rule to 1998, Abacha
began a virtual reign of terror. He cracked down on all political
opposition, subdued trade unions, took control of the press, jailed
hundreds of people and began a series of trials that sent opponents
to prison or the gallows.
</P>
<P>
   Saro-Wiwa was executed on charges stemming from his campaign to
have Nigeria's huge oil revenues shared with the communities where
the petroleum was produced. The general's purges also reached out
to prominent Nigerians and into his inner circle, many fled into
exile.
</P>
<P>
   His iron rule drew wide condemnation in the West. While an
international oil embargo did not materialize, but limited economic
sanctions against Nigerian oil, which accounts for 80 percent of
its foreign currency earnings, were invoked. There were reports
that he and other military leaders were siphoning off billions from
oil.
</P>
<P>
   As the general became a virtual pariah in Western countries, he
was said to have turned increasingly for support to the Middle East
and to Asia, particularly China. At the same time, he became
increasingly isolated personally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
