<SLUG> BC-WIRE-SCHOOLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE COMPANIES' TACTICS MAY KILL PLAN TO WIRE SCHOOLS FOR
INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- A plan by President Clinton and Congress to help
wire all classrooms to the Internet has prompted a revolt by phone
companies, lawmakers and consumer groups, now that the cost is
about to show up on long-distance phone bills.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission expects to vote on the
future of the program this week amid growing pressure to kill it or
scale it back. Key lawmakers who supervise telephone legislation
are calling the program ``fundamentally flawed and legally
suspect,'' and House Speaker Newt Gingrich yesterday threatened to
pass a bill to block what he and others have called the ``Gore
tax,'' a reference to Vice President Al Gore's pledge to wire all
schools to the Internet by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The losers could be 30,000 schools and libraries that have
applied for federal grants and subsidies for equipment and
telecommunications services to link to the Internet. They include
more than 350 schools or school districts and 135 libraries in
Massachusetts. About half of the 180 schools in the Archdiocese of
Boston system have applied for money under the program.
</P>
<P>
   Without the federal money, ``our project is dead, and we will
have to find some way to resurrect it from oblivion,'' said Peter
J. Sullivan, a parent who has led efforts by the East Boston
Central Catholic School to set up an e-mail account for each grade
level at the elementary school. About 40 volunteers have already
begun wiring the classrooms for Internet access. The school is
hoping the federal government will cover about $8,000 of the
$40,000 pricetag.
</P>
<P>
   But even some groups that support the subsidies say the FCC
should not issue the first checks to schools, which were expected
to go out in July. ``We like the program, but it's a little funny
the way it is being funded right now,'' said Kathy McShea of the
Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether the subsidy program, which could cost as
much as $2 billion annually, is raising the nation's phone bills.
</P>
<P>
   The subsidy program, which goes by the shorthand of ``E-Rate,''
was created by Congress in the 1996 Telecommunications Act, the
bill that set broad new rules for the long-distance, local
telephone and cable TV markets.
</P>
<P>
   By law, phone companies have always subsidized phone rates for
low-income users and for people in rural communities, where the low
population density can make phone service expensive. But under a
plan championed by Senator Olympia Snowe, Republican of Maine, the
1996 bill broadened the subsidy program to include schools,
libraries and rural health centers. They were invited to apply for
grants to buy computer equipment, as well as for discounted rates
on Internet access charges.
</P>
<P>
   Long-distance and local phone companies were to pay the bulk of
the cost, but cellular phone, paging and other telecommunications
companies would also pay in.
</P>
<P>
   According to congressional aides, lawmakers believed that
telephone costs would fall significantly because of new rules
designed to bring more competition to the long-distance and local
phone markets. As competition forced the phone companies to operate
more efficiently, money could be diverted to the subsidy program
without raising the nation's phone bills.
</P>
<P>
   Residential long-distance phone bills have in fact fallen 5
percent or more since early 1996, at least partly because of
government-ordered changes in the way phone companies bill each
other and their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, however, AT&AMP;T announced that it would not absorb the
cost of the new subsidies and instead would pass it to residential
customers. Starting July 1, a new line will appear on residential
phone bills showing a 5 percent surcharge on long-distance calls to
pay for the subsidy program. MCI followed suit with plans for a 5.9
percent surcharge.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than raise rates, the phone companies could have absorbed
the cost of the program ``in your ample profit margins,'' comlained
Senator Robert Kerrey, Democrat of Nebraska, in letters to AT&AMP;T and
MCI last week. ``Even more disturbing, you are now mounting a
public relations campaign to convince consumers that your price
increase is the equivalent of a tax. ... I am gravely disappoined
in the long distance companies' behavior,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But Gingrich yesterday said the FCC had in fact turned the
subsidy program into a new form of taxation. ``It is wrong for five
unelected, appointed commissiners to be able to establish a tax on
every telephone line in the United States,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican chairmen and senior Democrats on both the House
and Senate Commerce Committees have also called on the FCC to stop
collecting any money for the subsidy program, saying Congress never
intended to raise phone rates.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and FCC Chairman William Kennard have
issued statements supporting the subsidy plan, and President
Clinton hailed it during his commencement address at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But in his speech, Clinton cited a $1 billion pricetag for the
program, less money than many people anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC intially envisioned a $2.25 billion program, which
Kerrey said comes to less than 3 percent of the 1996 revenues of
the long-distance industry alone. The FCC later scaled the plan
back to about $2 billion, and it approved a plan to collect money
only for the first six months of the year, saying it would revisit
the issue this month.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC has collected about $625 million so far. It will collect
$1.4 billion more this year unless it changes the size of the
program this week. Some long-distance companies have raised their
share of the $625 million raised so far by adding a surcharge to
business customer bills.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC may also vote on the mechanism by which phone companies
collect money for the program, such as the surcharge on business
and residential long-distance bills. In addition, the commissioners
may consider a complaint that local phone companies, taking
advantage of rules that force phone companies to pay each other
fees, have found a way to pass their share of the Internet program
to long-distance firms instead of to their own customers.
</P>
<P>
   The program's supporters say there should be no cutbacks in the
size of the Internet subsidies. ``If we lose this vote at the FCC
this week, we're down the tubes,'' said Lynne Bradley of the
American Library Association. ``It will show that the forces of
darkness are prevailing, that it's profits over kids and corporate
interests over our kids' education.''
</P>
<P>
   And in East Boston, any cutbacks could force parents and local
churches to make up the difference, or lose the Internet program
altogether. The school's primary source of money is tuition, and
after that it relies on local parishes for its budget, said Sister
Mary Jude Waters, director of school planning at the Archdiocese's
Catholic School Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every school across the nation is going to be a loser if this
doesn't come through,'' Waters said. ``With 30,000 applications,
there will be a lot of disappointed folks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
