<HEADER>
A9946 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-SFCHRON &LR;      06-08 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   FTC Suing Intel Over Tactics  
   
 By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The Federal Trade Commission filed suit against Intel Corp.
yesterday, accusing the chipmaker of using its monopoly power to
bully computer companies.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The FTC, in a 3-to-1 vote, accused Santa Clara-based Intel of
punishing three computer companies by withholding vital information
about its Pentium microprocessors _ the brains that power more than
90 percent of computers sold today.
</P>
<P>
   Intel wielded its monopoly like a ``nuclear bomb,'' said William
Baer, head of the FTC's Bureau of Competition, which investigated
Intel. ``They can pull it out of their weapons arsenal, and they
win,'' Baer said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the suit is narrower in scope than the action the
Justice Department brought against software-maker Microsoft Corp.
last month, Intel said the case threatens the core of the company's
business: its intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the Federal Trade Commission is mistaken in
its interpretation of the law,'' said Intel spokesman Chuck Mulloy.
</P>
<P>
   The basic facts of the case are not in dispute. Intel admits it
canceled agreements to share advanced information about its
next-generation chips with certain computer-makers when those
companies engaged in patent disputes with Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has settled its lawsuits with Compaq Computer Corp., the
world's largest personal computer maker, and with
Massachusetts-based Digital Equipment Corp., a large workstation
and PC-maker. It remains a defendant in a suit brought in Alabama
by Intergraph Corp., a maker of computer workstations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central issue here is the law,'' Mulloy said. ``Is Intel
within its rights to withhold its intellectual property from
companies that are suing it over intellectual property?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  When Intel attained its dominant market share, it anticipated
heightened government scrutiny. ``We put 12 years into an antitrust
compliance program based on existing law,'' Mulloy said. ``Now it
appears the FTC is beginning to assert a new legal theory.''
</P>
<P>
   The FTC may face an uphill battle in proving its claim, some
observers said, and even if the government wins, Intel may not be
hurt too badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``No judge is going to say Intel has to give out its
intellectual property willy-nilly,'' said Joe Sims, an antitrust
attorney with Jones Day Reavis and Pogue in Washington, D.C.
``Assuming the government won _ which is a big assumption _ you're
talking about some kind of injunctive relief, some limits on the
circumstances in which Intel can withhold its intellectual
property.''
</P>
<P>
   Many observers said the FTC may decide to file more charges
later. ``This is the narrow case,'' Sims said, noting that other
allegations against Intel may be more difficult to prove.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have said that Intel faces a greater threat from a
changing marketplace than it does from government prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a company you could argue is not doing well,'' said
Ken Pearlman, an analyst with CIBC Oppenheimer in San Francisco.
``It has not been able to grow its revenues last year or this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel's stock price dropped 50 cents yesterday, closing at
$69.31. But, Pearlman said, that doesn't mean the FTC suit presents
a big threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anyone on Wall Street who thinks this
will have any impact on Intel anytime soon,'' he said. ``Intel is
very well equipped to deal with it. It has a huge organization and
a lot of experience with the FTC, and it's going to make sure
(this) doesn't have any effect on its business.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Intel needs to watch competitors like Advanced Micro
Devices of Sunnyvale and National Semiconductor of Santa Clara.
Those companies have stolen market share from Intel in the past
year by selling chips for computers that cost less than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Intel is expected to argue that such competition weakens the
FTC's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FTC is stepping into the middle of disputes between Intel
and its customers, which have had no effect on competition,'' said
Carl Shapiro, a professor of economics at the University of
California at Berkeley, who is working on Intel's behalf in this
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel certainly faces competition from AMD and National
Semiconductor,'' Shapiro said. ``What the FTC did (Monday) is
really unrelated to competition in the marketplace. I fail to see
how they're protecting consumers in doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the suit was widely expected, the FTC had remained mum
until yesterday, not even confirming its investigation. Intel had
disclosed in September that the FTC was probing its business
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the FTC's Baer said Intel used its clout in the
marketplace to create winners and losers in the workstation market.
Baer said the three cases show a pattern of Intel demanding that
its business partners sign over their patent rights _ and when they
don't, retaliating against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel used its monopoly power as a club to obtain licenses to
other firms' intellectual property,'' Baer said. ``Intel illegally
used its monopoly power to lock others out of the market. If firms
cannot protect their patented information from Intel, there is no
incentive for them to innovate.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel argues that the FTC won't be able to show that competition
was harmed by its actions or that Intel leveraged its monopoly to
grab a new market _ both key components of antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   With companies like Silicon Graphics, Hewlett-Packard, Digital,
IBM, Compaq, Dell and others all making workstations _ large
corporate computers _ ``there are more choices in workstations
today than there ever have been in the history of that market,''
Mulloy said. ``There are 1,000 PC choices. Consumers have never had
more choices ... from the low end to the high end.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial will likely begin in three to four months. The matter
will be heard before an FTC administrative law judge, who must
issue an opinion within the next 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   Intel will now interview witnesses and review documents. If it
loses at trial, it can appeal, first to the FTC and then to a U.S.
Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   With sales last year of $25 billion, profits of nearly $7
billion, and a market value of more than $116 billion, Intel is the
largest company in the Bay Area. It employs 6,000 people in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   At lunchtime yesterday, dozens of Intel workers were outside
jogging or walking on the path that runs along the edge of the chip
giant's Santa Clara headquarters. None of those questioned would
discuss the FTC's suit. Some knew little about it, and others
simply declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has long been hailed as an innovative leader in the chip
industry, but some observers say that it is now a victim of its
success. ``The thing people love you for when you're small, they
hate you for when you get to a certain market share and size,''
said Dan Hutcheson, president of VLSI, a San Jose market research
firm. ``There are certain characteristics that we love in toddlers,
but we don't want to see them in adults.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
