<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FTC FILES SUIT AGAINST GIANT CHIP MAKER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chipmaking giant Intel Corp. has joined software titan Microsoft
Corp. squarely in the crosshairs of federal antitrust regulators,
though the government's case againt Intel differs significantly
from the charges lodged against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the Federal Trade Commission filed suit against Santa
Clara, Calif.-based Intel, accusing the company of using its
near-monopoly on desktop computer processor chips to undermine some
of its own customers.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC charged that Intel withheld vital technical information
about its chips in an effort to punish companies that refused to
provide information on their own products. And in the case of
Maynard-based Digital Equipment Corp., the FTC says that Intel
wielded this weapon after Digital had sued Intel for alleged patent
violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only issue here is Intel's use of that club that it had as
a monopolist, to force other companies to turn over their
intellectual property,'' said Willard Tom, deputy director of the
FTC's Bureau of Competition. ``They're attacking companies that
have competing intellectual property.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel has vowed a vigorous defense.
</P>
<P>
   The company says it has an absolute right to control information
about its products. In addition, an Intel spokesman said that the
company only cut off companies that had filed intellectual property
suits against Intel, or were threatening to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prudent legal strategy is not to provide our intellectual
property to a company that is suing us over our intellectual
property,'' said Intel spokesman Chuck Molloy.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC complaint is Phase 2 of an aggressive federal campaign
to rein in the power of two computer industry titans, Intel and
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   In the computer industry, the two companies collectively
constitute a duopoloy dubbed ``Wintel.'' Intel processor chips are
found inside over 80 percent of the world's desktop computers,
while Redmond, Wash.-based Microsoft's Windows operating system is
found on about 90 percent of all computers sold.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials say that merely becoming a monopoly is no
crime. But they say that both companies have unfairly used their
power to crush rivals and force other industry players to do their
bidding.
</P>
<P>
   The antitrust case filed against Microsoft last month by the
Justice Department _ the FTC and Justice share federal antitrust
oversight _ claims that Microsoft has incorporated Internet
features in its Windows operating system in order to destroy rival
company Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But the case against Intel is different. The FTC cites three
companies that have been harmed by Intel's actions: Digital,
Intergraph Corp. of Huntsville, Ala., and Houston-based Compaq
Computer Corp., which will soon acquire Digital.
</P>
<P>
   Of these, only Digital competes directly against Intel in the
chip business, with its powerful Alpha processor. And even there,
Intel isn't accused of trying to drive the Alpha off the market.
Instead, the FTC complaint alleges that Intel used vital
information about the functioning of its computer chips as a weapon
after Digital sued Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every computer maker must use Intel chips to manufacture
its machines. In order to bring new products to market quickly,
companies sign agreements with Intel that entitle them to detailed
specifications for present and future Intel chips. This information
is essential in order to design new computers that use the chips.
</P>
<P>
   If a company is cut off from this data, it could take it months
longer to design a machine using a new Intel chip. Meanwhile, rival
computer makers will already have brought their products to market.
Such a lag would be devastating to a company at the high end of the
computer market, where users insist on obtaining the newest
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Digital sued Intel for patent infringement, claiming
that certain features of Intel's Pentium chips were unfairly
derived from Digital's Alpha microprocessors. Intel responded by
cutting off Digital's information about future Pentium designs, and
by threatening to withhold Pentium chips from Digital. The threat
carried a lot of weight with Digital, a major producer of
Intel-based computers.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Digital and Intel settled their patent dispute out
of court. Yesterday, a Digital spokeswoman said the matter had been
resolved to the company's satisfaction. She refused to comment on
the FTC complaint, except to say that Digital is providing
information to the FTC under subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   In another example of alleged wrongdoing, Intel stopped
providing technical information to Intergraph Corp., an Alabama
firm that makes high-powered engineering computers using Intel
chips. Intel took its action after Intergraph CEO Jim Meadlock
refused to hand over patented information about Intergraph chip
designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They began to try to say if you want to participate in future
programs, you have to sign away your patent rights,'' said
Meadlock.
</P>
<P>
   Intergraph took Intel to court. In a dramatic early victory for
Intergraph, a federal judge ruled in April that Intel's chips are
an ``essential facility,'' similar to an electrical utility,
because computer companies can hardly do business without them. The
judge ordered Intel to resume providing technical information to
Intergraph. Intel has appealed the ruling. But the FTC sees the
Intergraph affair as one more example of Intel's abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, however, says that it only took action after Intergraph
claimed that Intel products had violated some Intergraph patents.
Mulloy said that Intergraph officials had approached some firms
that used Intel chips and threatened to sue them. These companies,
in turn, contacted Intel asking for protection against Intergraph
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were on the verge of taking the customers to court,''
Mulloy said. ``We had every reason to believe at the very least
that we'd be brought into litigation along with our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust experts said that the FTC case has merit. ``I think
that Intel...was being extraordinarily aggressive,'' said Rich
Gray, an antitrust attorney with Bergeson, Eliopoulos, Grady &AMP; Gray
in San Jose, Calif. ``That wouldn't be a problem with a company
that didn't have market power, but it is a problem for a company
with market power.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Gray also believes that Intel has a right to refuse to
share its intellectual property with some firms. He said that the
FTC should forbid Intel from cutting off a company suddenly.
Instead, Intel might be ordered to give a couple of years' notice
before taking such an action.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Neil Motenko of Nutter, McClennen &AMP; Fish in Boston
raised a more fundamental question: Is Intel really a monopoly? He
noted that a variety of chipmakers, including National Semicondutor
and Advanced Micro Devices, have begun winning market share in the
desktop computer business. Indeed, Intel has had to slash its
prices and roll out a new line of cut-rate chips to compete with
the upstarts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real question as to whether Intel has monopoly power
when they have to cut their prices,'' Motenko said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's stock closed yesterday at 69 5/16, down 1/2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
