<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 AOL Buys Net Chat Company   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
America Online said yesterday it has acquired Israeli startup
Mirabilis Ltd. and its popular Internet chat technology for $287
million in cash.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The deal is expected to extend the reach of the world's largest
online company and could pave the way for it to provide
telephone-like service over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Mirabilis, a closely held Tel Aviv company, provides software
that lets people privately exchange instant messages over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   With 12 million registered users, its ICQ (short for ``I Seek
You'') real-time chat technology is second only to AOL's Instant
Messenger Service. AIM is available to AOL's 12 million subscribers
plus 70 million users of Netscape's Navigator Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   Both services are free. But ICQ is considered the better
technology and is especially popular with overseas Web surfers, who
account for 60 percent of Mirabilis' subscribers. More than 50,000
copies of ICQ are downloaded from the Internet each day.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that provide free instant messaging _ which also
include Excite, Inc., E-Share and OnLive Technologies _ hope to
make money by selling advertising. But so far advertisers aren't
enthused, in part because the window where the messages appear is
very small _ less than 10 percent of the overall screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice, attractive feature for AOL to retain happy
subscribers,'' said analyst Jim Balderston, of Zona Research in
Redwood City. ``It's not necessarily about jamming in more ads, but
about strengthening the bond between AOL subscribers and the AOL
brand name.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger of the two biggest instant messaging services worries
some industry observers because it will draw even more users to
AOL's site. To use instant messaging, both parties must be logged
onto the same service.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``AOL is cornering the market on eyeballs,'' said David
Cassel, editor of AOL Watch, a Berkeley newsletter. ``With this
acquisition, they have established the dialtone of cyberspace and
they already are the world's largest online service with 12 million
subscribers. It's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   But AOL critics doubt that federal regulators will move to stop
the merger, since they made barely a peep when AOL took over its
largest competitor, CompuServe, last year.
</P>
<P>
   AOL Chairman Steve Case told The Chronicle he expects the deal
to accelerate AOL's international expansion.
</P>
<P>
   And he said it is ``conceivable'' AOL will meld voice technology
into its instant-messaging services, creating a cyber equivalent to
the phone system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a blurring between different forms of
communications,'' he said. ``We are as much a communications
company as we are a media company.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he declined to say when audio will be incorporated into
ICQ or AIM.
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that AOL doesn't have enough network capacity to
provide voice communication. The Dulles, Va., company will have to
partner with a telecommunications giant to handle a glut of traffic
if it decides to add audio to its instant-messaging system.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the purchase price, AOL will pay the owners of
the Mirabilis as much as $120 million a year over three years
starting in 2001, depending on Mirabilis' performance.
</P>
<P>
   AOL shares rose $1.50, to $84.75, in trading yesterday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
