<SLUG> BC-FLASH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Netscape Puts Some Flash Into Web Browser  
   
 By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Angling for an edge in its war with Microsoft, Netscape
Communications said yesterday it will incorporate animation
technology into an upgrade of its popular Web browser.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Starting this summer, Netscape Communicator will include the
Flash player, which lets users view animated content designed with
Macromedia's Flash software.
</P>
<P>
   Flash _ the latest incarnation of Macromedia's popular Shockwave
software _ is widely used to add animation to Web sites for movies,
television shows and consumer products.
</P>
<P>
   The Flash player is currently available as a ``plug-in'' for
both the Netscape and Microsoft browsers. Web surfers must download
the player from the Internet and install it in their browsers.
Macromedia officials claim that 40 million copies of the Flash
player have been downloaded in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Netscape's move eliminates the need to download and plug in
the Flash player.
</P>
<P>
   ``This creates a big advantage for the Netscape user, who wants
to enjoy a really rich Web experience without having to go get a
plug-in,'' said Bob Lisbonne, senior vice president of Client
Products at Mountain View-based Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage might not last long. Microsoft plans to include
the Flash player (along with the Internet Explorer browser) in
versions of Windows 98 that come with new computers. Macromedia
officials said Microsoft also may decide to put the Flash player
into the upgrade version of Windows 98 sold in stores.
</P>
<P>
   The real winner in yesterday's deal could be Macromedia, which
has been trying to regain the heights it attained during the first
wave of Internet mania two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Macromedia was originally known for its programs that let
developers working on Macintosh computers design multimedia
software and games. The San Francisco company became a Wall Street
darling when Shockwave caught on as a tool for animating Web sites.
Macromedia's stock soared as high as $62.50 in the winter of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But a series of ill-advised acquisitions and softness in the
Apple Macintosh market led to four losses in the five quarters
prior to its last one. That, coupled with a deflation in the value
of Internet stocks, sent Macromedia's shares plunging to a low of
$7 in April of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Former Silicon Graphics executive Bob Burgess was brought in to
turn the situation around. He cleaned up the product line and
focused the company on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The prescription may be working. In its latest quarter,
Macromedia showed a profit of 5 cents a share on revenue of $30
million. And its stock has doubled since late January, closing
yesterday at $16.13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are improving for them,'' said analyst Greg Vogel of
NationsBanc Montgomery Securities. ``The new management is pretty
solid, they're doing the right thing in focusing on the Internet
and they have some products that are doing pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Netscape may not give Macromedia's bottom line a
big boost, said Vogel, ``but it's a significant endorsement for
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
