<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Breaking the Sound Barrier  
   
 By Jonathan Marshall  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
How do you say ``love'' to a deaf person at the other end of a
phone? With a videophone _ and your arms crossed over your chest.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As video-conferencing technology improves, the deaf and
hard-of-hearing are enjoying new levels of communication with
distant friends and loved ones. Inexpensive videophones are
becoming good enough to permit signing, the most comfortable
language for many deaf people, as well as some lip reading.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the only way the deaf could communicate in real
time over long distances was typing into a teletype (TTY) machine,
which sends text messages over ordinary phone lines to a similar
machine at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Dirk Visser of Fremont has found videophones a great tool
for letting his deaf daughter, Zoe, communicate with her hearing
grandmother and deaf great-grandmother in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been real fun because our 4-year-old is now a participant
(in phone conversations), whereas before she was left out almost
completely,'' he said. ``Now, she's one of the players.''
</P>
<P>
   The videophone also has had a big impact on the other end of the
conversation, Visser said. ``It's been real good for the older
folks. Her great-grandmother started crying when she saw how big
Zoe was and how well she was signing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Visser family uses a new videophone tailored especially for
the deaf and hard-of-hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced this spring by Santa Clara-based 8x8 Inc., the $399
VideoTTY Videophone connects to a standard camcorder camera, TV set
and touch-tone telephone to offer full audio and video over a
standard phone line.
</P>
<P>
   With a wireless keyboard (included), it also lets parties at
either end type messages, in addition to talking, signing and
gesturing.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgetta Bourne-Firl, a Newark resident and co-leader of the
famous student revolt in 1988 at Gallaudet University, the national
college for the deaf, said she was awed the first time she used the
8x8 videophone. She and her family called up her father, mother,
sister and sister's fiance in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of picture was not on the top of the world, but it
was amazing,'' she recalled. ``My sister, who is hearing, could
speak to my son, who is also hearing. My husband typed with my
father. My mother and I were signing to each other. All of us were
talking simultaneously _ wow! Also, I could show off my baby who
was growing fast.''
</P>
<P>
   When 8x8 introduced its original videophone in early 1997, it
had no thought of serving deaf customers. But then it hired Richard
Medugno to write copy for its Web page. Medugno had moved from
Toronto, Canada, to Fremont to enroll his deaf, 6-year-old daughter
in the renowned California School for the Deaf.
</P>
<P>
   Medugno worked on persuading company officials to produce the
VideoTTY version, so deaf users could do text chat as well as sign.
He now manages the product line, propelled by his personal mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deafness is so isolating,'' he said. ``If we can get (the
deaf) videophones, suddenly the world is open to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Medugno noted that his in-laws in Canada and his sister in San
Diego weren't about to buy a TTY machine, which costs from $200 to
$800, just to communicate with his daughter, who can hardly type.
But they were quick to buy videophones so that they could converse
with each other as well.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, his daughter now is part of the conversation. ``She
can sign `I love you,' show a missing tooth, show a picture she's
drawn or wish her grandfather happy birthday,'' Medugno said.
</P>
<P>
   Videophones put direct emotion back into conversations between
the deaf, said Ray Willingham, manager of the telecommunications
program for the Oklahoma Department of Rehabilitation Services.
Until now, they've had to simulate emotion over TTY machines with
phrases like ``LOL,'' for ``laughing out loud.''
</P>
<P>
   Josh Gendel, director of technical services for the New
York-based League for the Hard of Hearing, said many of the
agency's clients can't hear well enough to understand phone calls
but can follow a conversation over 8x8's videophone. They pick up
on visual clues, including lip movements, and can use text chat to
clarify any misunderstood words.
</P>
<P>
   The 8x8 videophone doesn't yet support fast enough video to
permit rapid signing. But with practice, deaf users can slow down
their signing and get their message across, said Susan McGee, a
researcher at the University of Arkansas. ``I prefer it to plain
TTY,'' she said. ``It's nice to be able to have the face to go with
the words.''
</P>
<P>
   Deaf people have several other videophone options if they don't
mind doing without text chat. 3Com sells the BigPicture TV phone,
based on 8x8's technology. C-Phone Corp. in North Carolina sells a
higher-quality videophone, but it costs $1,000 and requires a
digital ISDN line. And Fremont-based Advis has just introduced a
videophone called the AD-20, promising higher performance for
customers with two phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Many video-conferencing kits also exist for use with high-end
PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Other new technologies, including two-way pagers and wireless
e-mail devices, also are helping the deaf communicate at a distance
and deal with emergencies without the benefit of voice.
</P>
<P>
   Many new digital phones permit short text messaging. Lucia
Erwin-Stowbunenko of San Jose uses her Pacific Bell PCS phone to
keep in touch with her deaf, 12-year-old stepson, Vincent. If
Vincent wants to stay over at a friend's house or forgets his lunch
at school, he need only tap out a short message on the phone's
keypad. And if any family members send him a message, a vibrator on
the phone will alert him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are amazed when you give a 12-year-old a cell phone,''
Erwin-Stowbunenko said. ``But for mom and dad, it's good knowing
he's OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 2143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
