<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-world </SLUG>
 cup-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Future may be now for `new' Argentina
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ortega takes over Maradona role
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ Call it Argentina, The Next Generation.
</P>
<P>
   Diego Maradona, the star-crossed superstar who remarkably has
been a part of every Argentine World Cup team since 1978, finally
has faded away. It was a difficult and often painful separation for
the superstar and the once-super team.
</P>
<P>
   Now 37, Maradona spent much of the past four years trying in
vain to return to form in time to make one more run at the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Argentine national team often tried in vain to
find the right mix of players that could continue the tradition of
greatness. Just in time for the grandest event of the quadrennium,
the Argentines finally think they've got it.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Daniel Pasarella, who took over the national team four
months after the 1994 World Cup, which Maradona left in shame after
testing positive for drugs, has his team on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   It took four years and numerous experiments. More than 70
players have seen service with Argentina's national team since
1994.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some humiliating defeats along the way, notably
a series of losses in 1995 to the likes of Israel and Morocco. The
United States drubbed Argentina 3-0 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The team seemed to lack direction.
</P>
<P>
   And the free-spirited Argentine players were not exactly
thrilled with Pasarella's banning of earrings and long hair, to say
nothing of his public scoldings of players he believed were living
promiscuous lives.
</P>
<P>
   But after settling on a roster and imparting much more
discipline to the team, the transition seems nearly complete.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks before today's World Cup opener, Argentina hit its
stride with victories over such powers as Chile, Ireland and Italy
and an impressive 1-0 victory over Brazil in Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Argentina was drawn into what is essentially a
two-team group also could help build confidence.
</P>
<P>
   A strong Croatian team appears to be the only threat to
Argentina in Group H; Japan and Jamaica seem to be here only for
the ride.
</P>
<P>
   The World Cup definitely seems like a good time for the
emergence of previously overshadowed Argentine players such as
Gabriel Batistuta and young Ariel ``El Burrito'' Ortega, who was
given Maradona's No. 10 jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Batistuta is well known in many parts of the world but always
has been a secondary thought to Maradona. What many fans might not
know: Batistuta actually has scored more career international goals
(39) than Maradona.
</P>
<P>
   And Ortega _ whose nicknamed means ``the little donkey'' _ is a
blur of energy who has grown into a leadership role. Throw in the
tough Juan ``The Witch'' Veron, and the Argentines again seem
capable of making a big World Cup run, with or without Maradona.
</P>
<P>
   The key match in the group should be the June 26 showdown with
Croatia in Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   The winner likely will win the group; the loser gets a tougher
road but likely still advances.
</P>
<P>
   And even in the head-to-head matchup with Croatia, Argentina
seems to have caught a break.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful Croatian team was tabbed by many as a favorite for
the group but lost a pair of big goal-scorers only days before Cup
rosters were due.
</P>
<P>
   Alen Boksic, a veteran of more than 100 international matches,
including some in the former Soviet Union, injured his right knee
during training and will have to miss the Cup. Forward Davor Suker
was cut from the team by coach Miroslav Blazevic after the player
refused to do drills ordered by the coach.
</P>
<P>
   The Croats probably still will give fits to every opponent,
since they are one of the deeper teams in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Japan hopes to gain experience before it hosts the tournament in
2002, and the ``Reggae Boyz'' of Jamaica are only beginning to play
soccer at this level.
</P>
<P>
   But this grouping seems destined to be the start of something
big for Argentina.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
