<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Changing Your E-Mail `Reply To' Address  
   
 By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 Q:   Apparently my e-mail arrives at its destination with a 
 ``reply to'' address that is not my e-mail address. Instead it 
 is the address of my e-mail server. How can I get rid of it? I 
 use Outlook Express. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  Outlook Express, Netscape Communicator and other e-mail
programs let you designate two return addresses in messages you
send: your regular e-mail address and a reply address. Ordinarily,
the two addresses will be the same. But a separate reply address
can come in handy if, for instance, you send someone a message from
work but you want the response sent to your personal e-mail account
at home (or vice versa).
</P>
<P>
   Use the following steps to change the reply address in Outlook
Express: Choose Accounts from the Tools menu, select your account
and click Properties. Tab to General, where you'll see a space in
which to enter a reply address. That's the place to enter a
separate address other than your regular e-mail address. If you
want both your addresses to be the same, leave the Reply space
blank.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;   &LR; When I am on my home PC, how can I access my office PC &LR; 
 &LR; via modem? I have a Pentium with Win95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  There are several software programs that should do the job
for you, including pcANYWHERE from Symantec ($149) and LapLink from
Traveling Software ($124.95). Both programs can connect via modem,
local-area network or the Internet. Using a modem is the easiest
way to go, because all you have to do is load the software on your
PCs at home and at work. If you only plan to connect to your office
PC occasionally, consider Traveling Software's Remote DeskLink
($49.99). It offers many of the features of LapLink, although you
can't transfer files with it.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to go through your corporate network, make sure: A)
it's OK with the company; and B) they're able to configure the
network or intranet server so you can &LR;   &LR; access your office PC.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Q: &LR;  In one of your columns you gave directions for blocking &LR; 
 &LR; the download of cookies for Microsoft Internet Explorer and &LR; 
 &LR; Netscape Navigator, but not for America Online and its browser. &LR; 
 &LR; Could you provide this, please? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  Sure. Actually, the procedure is similar to the one for
Microsoft's browser, because AOL uses a version of Internet
Explorer. With the main AOL window open, choose Preferences from
the Members menu, then click the WWW button. Tab over to Advanced,
then scroll down until you get to the cookie options. There are
three: Always accept cookies; Prompt before accepting cookies; and
Disable all cookie use.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, for readers who don't know, cookies are tiny files
that Web sites download to your computer to keep track of
information about you, such as marketing preferences and passwords
for secure sites.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;   &LR; When I point my mouse at the little monitor icon on the &LR; 
 &LR; Taskbar, a bubble pops up giving numbers like (640x480) 256 &LR; 
 &LR; color. What does this mean? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  The message you're getting indicates that your display
resolution is 640 by 480 pixels, with 256 possible colors. You
might try increasing your resolution, which should improve the
quality of graphics. To do that, right-click an empty space on the
Windows desktop, choose Properties and tab over to Settings, where
you'll find the options for resolution and color. Try 800x600,
which is supported by all newer monitors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  Since I installed Netscape Navigator, there is an AOL &LR; 
 &LR; Instant Messenger screen that pops up every so often. It's most &LR; 
 &LR; annoying and I would love to get rid of it but I can't figure &LR; 
 &LR; out how. I'm tempted to just uninstall all of Netscape and go &LR; 
 &LR; back to Internet Explorer (horrors!). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  The folks at Netscape suggest this cure: Go to the Netscape
Communicator folder in the Windows Programs menu and choose AOL
Instant Messenger. In the Sign On box that appears, click Setup,
then tab over to Misc. You should see a checked box labeled ``Start
AIM when Windows starts.'' Click the box to remove the check mark,
then click OK. Let me know how it works.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   You can use the keyboard rather than the mouse to quickly move
to another open program or toggle to a different open document in
Windows 95. Suppose you're running Word and Excel at the same time.
Hold down the Control key (Ctrl) and press Tab to move from one to
the other. Similarly, if you have more than one document open in
Word or Excel, the combination of Ctrl + F6 lets you shift between
them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
