<HEADER>
A9964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCCER-ELECT-NYT &LR;      06-08 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ALLY ELECTED TO HEAD WORLD SOCCER BODY  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ After a quarter-century of one-man rule, soccer's world
governing body got a new president on Monday. If this had been a
soccer match instead of an election, the two candidates would have
received at least a yellow card warning for foul play during their
bitter campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph (Sepp) Blatter, 62, a gregarious Swiss backed by the
United States, scored what many saw as an upset in defeating
Lennart Johansson, 68, of Sweden. Blatter prevailed by the
surprising margin of 111 to 80 in voting by the federation's
worldwide members.
</P>
<P>
   Blatter succeeds Joao Havelange, 82, of Brazil, who ran FIFA, as
the world soccer federation is known, with a combination of
autocratic rigidity and progressive reform. In 24 years as FIFA's
president, Havelange was credited with building the Zurich-based
organization from a fledgling operation in a private residence to a
worldwide force that oversees a $250 billion-a-year international
industry.
</P>
<P>
   With Blatter working by his side for 17 years and implementing
his programs as FIFA's general secretary, Havelange increased the
size of the World Cup, which begins on Wednesday, from 16 to 32
teams, introduced a World Cup for women, gained a place for women's
soccer in the Summer Olympics and built up marketing and television
rights fees to the point that each of FIFA's 204 national
federations will receive $1 million from the 1998 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Blatter, who jumped into the campaign only several months ago,
said he would not deviate much from the path that Havelange created
in making the World Cup the world's most widely viewed sporting
event, one that remains independent from and dwarfs the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am for continuity,'' Blatter said.
</P>
<P>
   To Johansson, that was the problem. For all his undeniable
success, Havelange has been accused by critics of running FIFA in
an iron-fisted, dictatorial manner and of gaining re-election five
times in part through favoritism and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Johansson, the president of UEFA, the association of European
soccer federations, called Blatter a puppet of Havelange's and
campaigned for a more open, democratic and ``clean'' federation,
where many voices would be welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be president of a system where one man decides
who gets what,'' Johansson said.
</P>
<P>
   His distrust of the voting process, and his fear that it would
be manipulated, was on full view Monday. Some 191 national soccer
federations had one vote apiece. Johansson wanted three members of
each federation to enter the voting booth together, so that the
delegate entrusted with the predetermined vote could not change his
mind secretly. He was overruled.
</P>
<P>
   He did succeed, however, in getting the votes counted in full
view of the FIFA congress, apparently concerned that ballots might
not be fairly counted in a backroom tally.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he lost by a considerable margin. A two-thirds majority,
or 128 votes, was necessary to win on the first ballot, but when
Johansson saw how badly he trailed, he conceded, saying, ``The
game's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Johansson had the backing of Pele, the great Brazilian star who
had a falling-out with Havelange, and Johansson believed he had
sufficient backing in Europe and Africa to win. But he apparently
made two critical mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   One, he gave the impression to the United States and other
federations in the North American, Central American and Caribbean
region, as well to the South Americans, that he was too
Eurocentric.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us are former colonies of European countries, and we
don't want to return to that status,'' Alan I. Rothenberg,
president of the United States Soccer Federation, had said in
comments to Mexico, Jamaica, Canada, Trinidad and Tobago, El
Salvador, Costa Rica and other regional partners.
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg and Blatter worked closely when the United States put
on the hugely successful World Cup in 1994. Blatter insisted on
having Giants Stadium as a site and approved the use of instant
replay on scoreboards, as well as the experiment to grow natural
grass for use in the Silverdome in Pontiac, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe that his victory will increase the United States'
chances of obtaining the World Cup again in the near future,
perhaps as early as 2010.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
