</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-MORMANS-1STLEDEWRITETHRU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN BAPTISTS DEEMED MORE INCLUSIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Subs for earlier story with today's developments) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Southern Baptists who apologized for racism
three years ago have made major breakthroughs in hiring
African-Americans to key positions and are giving strong support to
the 2,700 predominantly black churches in the denomination, black
Southern Baptists said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   That was the word during a meeting of the Southern Baptist
African American Fellowship held before Tuesday's opening of the
national Southern Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving into a new day, I believe,'' said the Rev.
Phillip Davis, one of several black leaders at the convention.
Davis recently was named director of a major thrust of Southern
Baptists _ creating new churches.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptists apparently are serious about their
much-publicized 1995 statement in which they apologized for past
racism and pledged to be more inclusive in denominational
leadership, the black leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sincere effort to be more inclusive,'' said the Rev.
Joseph Lyles of Fort Washington, Md., president of the
African-American fellowship. ``The new thing is that they are
recognizing that we bring some contributions to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   African-American churches are among the fastest-growing segments
of the denomination. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Sid Smith, director of the African American Ministries
Division for the Florida Baptist Convention, said eight state
conventions of Southern Baptists have elected black presidents in
the past. The national denomination has elected three
African-Americans as vice presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people haven't kept up with where Southern Baptists are
today, they might think they are still holding to (racist) policies
of the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. E.W. McCall of La Puente, Calif., immediate past
president of the African American Fellowhip, agreed. He said the
denomination, founded in 1845 because of a dispute with northern
Baptists over slavery, is moving forward in racial justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made a lot of progress just in this last year,'' McCall
said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted Davis' appointment and the naming of another
African-American, Franklin ``Jerry'' Burkett, as a vice president
of the North American Mission Board. Burkett supervises computer
technology with the mission board.
</P>
<P>
   Although no exact numbers are available, Davis said more and
more blacks are being hired in Southern Baptist state and national
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-Americans are now getting positions besides those just
centering on work in black churches,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Lyles said not all blacks are open to the new inclusiveness of
Southern Baptists. When Southern Baptists offered their apology in
1995, some African-American church leaders said it was an attempt
to lure black churches away from their predominantly black Baptist
denominations.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-Americans know how to be racist just as much as those
who are Euro-racist,'' Lyles said. ``We can't hold grudges. We need
to work together.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Tom Elliff, pastor of the First Southern Baptist Church
in Del City, Okla., and outgoing president of the denomination,
said Anglos and people of all ethnic backgrounds are slowly
learning how to work together in his denomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together we have a great deal to offer the world,'' he said.
``Separated we don't have much to offer at all.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 2153EDT &QL; 
