<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NEWS AND NOTES: 
SAINT LAURENT PASSES A REIN  
 FASHION AT PIER 94 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Certainly, several of the recent designer hires at
French fashion houses have been more sensational than the
appointment this week of Alber Elbaz as the designer and creative
director for Yves Saint Laurent Rive Gauche. But none have been as
ripe with sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Saint Laurent is, after all, a legend, a living one, and a
monument of French culture. Pierre Berge, Saint Laurent's business
partner of almost 40 years, has continually suggested that no one
would ever replace the groundbreaking designer in his own house
while he was still alive. Amid the swirl of designer dust-ups, the
house of Saint Laurent seemed stubbornly determined to survive on
its memories.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Berge acknowledged that time had caught up with the
house. Saint Laurent, who is 62 and has become increasingly
reclusive, was relieved to be giving up the reins to Rive Gauche,
the house's ready-to-wear line, Berge said in a telephone interview
from Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ready-to-wear in France has completely changed, and it was
difficult for him,'' Berge said. Saint Laurent, who Berge said was
unavailable for comment, will continue to design the haute couture
collection. Elbaz will direct the ready-to-wear, diffusion lines
like Encore and Variation and the licensed accessory lines.
</P>
<P>
   In his new position, to begin in November, Elbaz will report to
Berge. There was no thought, Berge said, that Elbaz would work with
the man whose name was on the door. ``I think he could be
paralyzed,'' Berge said of Elbaz, 37. ``I'm ready to accept what he
will create. He has wonderful technique, and he likes women. It's
not a question of replacing Saint Laurent; it's a question of
bringing something new.''
</P>
<P>
   Berge's head was turned by Elbaz's work at Guy Laroche. Elbaz
was at the Laroche studio in Paris Monday overseeing the production
of his last collection for the house, which hired him two years ago
from Geoffrey Beene, where he was the assistant designer.
</P>
<P>
   Elbaz immediately stamped his imprint on the French line with a
fresh, light interpretation of a style that had become cloying and
out of date. His floor-sweeping, jewel-toned mohair skirts and
sweet embroidered tulle dresses buoyed up the beached house of
Laroche.
</P>
<P>
   The approach is consistent with the Saint Laurent esthetic. ``I
love that he makes women beautiful,'' Elbaz said, adding that he
had not yet met Saint Laurent.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Morocco, a favorite inspiration of the older designer,
Elbaz grew up in Israel and moved to the United States when he was
25. His appointment to the house of Saint Laurent, with a
three-year contract, is not a dream come true, he said. ``It's my
only dream,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fashion at Pier 94  &LR;  Fashion will have another home in Manhattan
when renovations are completed on Pier 94, a 175,00-square-foot
space at 755 12th Ave. (at 55th Street). Formerly a parking garage,
the site, to be called the Unconvention Center, is to open on July
26 with the Collective, a men's-wear trade show produced by ENK
International. ENK presents some of fashion's premier trade shows.
</P>
<P>
   Elyse Kroll, the president of ENK, who has a financial interest
in the development of Pier 94, is overseeing the transformation
from garage to fashion center. The Unconvention Center is being
developed at a cost of about $3 million, Ms. Kroll said.
</P>
<P>
   The new space is a result of a two-year search that Ms. Kroll
undertook after presenting her shows primarily in hotels, like the
Omni and the Plaza. Accommodations for mid-size trade shows have
become scarce, she said. With the tourist boom, several city hotels
are now turning trade groups away, she said. Last year, ENK shows
were spread out over Piers 88, 90 and 92. ```Titanic' came out, and
all of a sudden the piers are fully booked with cruise ships,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In her search, Ms. Kroll turned for help to the city's Economic
Development Corp. The piers are owned by the city and leased to
private businesses like Port Parties and the International Terminal
Operating Co., which together will operate Pier 94 for a fee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
