<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9972 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-PRESIDENT-VISIT     06-08 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-PRESIDENT-VISIT-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH KOREAN CHIEF URGES U.S. HELP FOR ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ President Kim Dae-jung of South Korea told New York
business leaders Monday that his country's once-prized economic
miracle was nothing but a ``house of cards'' and that his people
now needed U.S. help to rebuild the economy in a more Western
image.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, a former dissident who assumed the country's highest office
in February, lashed out at his predecessors for creating an economy
characterized by collusion and corruption. Now, he said, South
Korea has turned decisively to democracy and it has opened its
borders to foreign investment and trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``My greatest purpose in coming here,'' he said, ``is to plead
with the American government and businessmen to invest in South
Korea, to tell you that we are doing everything we can to open''
the economy. He joked with an audience of executives, diplomats and
scholars at the Council on Foreign Relations in Manhattan, saying,
``If each of you today could invest just $100 million, that would
be a great help.''
</P>
<P>
   Once one of Asia's most successful growth machines, South Korea
has been a major victim of the economic turmoil that has swept the
region. Last year, the International Monetary Fund arranged a $58
billion rescue package. Since then, the country's foreign-currency
reserves have rebounded sharply and interest rates have stabilized.
</P>
<P>
   But Seoul is scrambling to find a solution to its huge
private-industry debt problems, which have crippled financial
institutions and bankrupted several leading conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, who is in his 70s, looked haggard during back-to-back
appearances Monday, beginning with breakfast at the New York Stock
Exchange. He walked stiffly and stayed seated during a question
period after cutting short his lunchtime speech. Later, he left for
Washington, where he will meet with President Clinton and top
economic advisers.
</P>
<P>
   But Kim was energetic in promoting his government's friendly new
attitude toward foreign business. He stressed that he had committed
South Korea to open capital markets and relaxed investment rules as
the cornerstone of economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Many of New York's top business leaders turned out to hear the
president's remarks, including Sanford Weill, chairman of Travelers
Group; Jon Corzine, chairman of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., and Maurice
Greenberg, chairman of American International Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said all the right things _ very direct, very positive,''
said Robert Hormats, vice chairman of Goldman Sachs International.
``It will take some time for businesses to respond, but the
direction is right on.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim outlined new rules that permit hostile takeovers of Korean
companies. Foreign executives can now run South Korean companies
and foreign investors can own land on the same terms as Koreans, a
first for a country that long maintained one of capitalist Asia's
most protectionist economies.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics have contended that Kim has stalled on a basic
economic overhaul and allowed old practices _ including bailouts
for the some of the country's biggest companies instead of allowing
them to fail. But the president insisted that he was going forward
with a ``full-scale restructuring.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He recited a list of measures straight out of the International
Monetary Fund's guidebook: abolish cross-guarantees of debt among
related companies; require better disclosure and accounting
standards; give shareholders more power; force companies to focus
on core businesses rather than peripheral investments.
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize his welcoming attitude toward foreign investment,
Kim said he considered Dow Chemical Co.'s decision to build a $1
billion plant in Malaysia instead of South Korea a ``serious
mistake,'' adding that his government would not allow bureaucratic
resistance to derail important foreign investments in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
