<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 6/08/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- June 8, 1998 -- TOBACCO-LAWYERS, 6-08 --
Sen. John McCain, left, with Attorney General Mike Moore of
Mississippi, W. Steve Bozeman, Richard Scruggs and Steve Mitchell.
The issue of lawyers' fees has been the focus of intense
controversy in states that have settled lawsuits against cigarette
makers. But now the debate has also erupted in Washington, where
Congress is considering federal legislation that will resolve many
tobacco lawsuits and allow the government to regulate nicotine.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- June 8, 1998 -- INTEL-PRICE, 6-08 --
William Baer of the Federal Trade Commission displays the insides
of a computer at a news conference held Monday to discuss the
agency's decision to file an antitrust suit against Intel. At the
core of the government's charges is the assertion that Intel's
pattern of withholding technical data as a weapon in patent
disputes stifles innovation in the microprocessor industry, thereby
enhancing Intel's dominant position. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CARLISLE, Mass. -- June 8, 1998 -- DAIRY-PRICES, 6-08 --
Mark Duffy's dairy farm in Carlisle is part of a dairy price
agreement that could spread beyond the six New England states. The
agreement guarantees dairy farmers a higher price for drinking milk
than the one dictated under the system the federal government has
been using to set farmers' milk prices since the depression. (Keith
Meyers/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNITED NATIONS -- June 8, 1998 -- CLINTON-DRUGS, 6-08 --
Addressing a special summit-level session of the General Assembly
convened Monday to discuss ways to counter drug trafficking and
use, President Clinton says that pointing fingers has not advanced
the fight against drugs. ``It does not dismantle a single cartel,
help a single addict, prevent a single child from trying and
perhaps dying from heroin,'' he says. (Ruby Washington/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NORCO, La. -- June 8, 1998 -- OIL-REFINERY, 6-08 -- Jack
Stanley, owner of TransAmerican Energy Corp., is converting this
1,000-acre refinery on the banks of the Mississippi into a fully
functional facility. ``There's $2 billion worth of equipment
here,'' he says. By the end of the summer, the towering coking and
cracking units are expected to be going full blast, converting
230,000 barrels of crude oil a day into kerosene, diesel fuel,
heating oil Q and 5.5 million gallons of gasoline. (Lee Celano/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- June 8, 1998 -- WATER-THEATER-REVIEW, 6-08 --
Marty Pottenger, carpenter and writer, in ``City Water Tunnel No.
3.'' Ms. Pottenger, who spent 20 years in the building trades,
gives new meaning to ``underground theater.'' Embroidered by video
scenes of the tunnel in progress and the actress's compassionate
impressions of laborers, engineers and bureaucrats, the performance
piece consists of vignettes illuminating aspects of the vast
project, begun more than 20 years ago. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 8, 1998 -- TONYS, 6-08 -- Robert
Foxworth as an unfaithful husband and Jane Alexander as his wife in
``Honour,'' which closes Sunday at the Belasco Theater, becoming
the first casualty of the Tony Awards ceremony. The play had 57
regular performances and 28 previews. Producers for several other
shows that had hoped in vain for a Tony to bolster sagging ticket
sales met Monday to crunch numbers and decide whether to close as
well. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) HOLLYWOOD -- June 8, 1998 -- CALIF-EGYPTIAN-THEATER, 6-08
-- A Pharaonic icon oversees the work of painters on the exterior
of Grauman's Egyptian Theater recently. Like Times Square,
Hollywood Boulevard is staggering toward a comeback. And the
Egyptian, with the phoenix motifs sprinkled throughout its still
grand skeleton, is rising from the ashes as well. The theater will
be the new home of the American Cinematheque, a local film
preservation group that plans to use it for screenings of classic
movies. (Marissa Roth/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 8, 1998 -- AGENT-PROFILE, 6-08 -- Flora
Roberts has guided the careers of some of the theater's top
writers. She is one of the last of the red-hot play agents, a
fiercely independent woman who has gone her own way in a world
dominated by corporate agencies. In a career of almost 50 years,
she has been a formidable talent spotter, artful in her choice of
clients Q such as Stephen Sondheim, Tina Howe and Alfred Uhry.
``I'm very rough on clients,'' says Ms. Roberts.(Jack Manning/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- June 7, 1998 -- FALN-PRISONERS-2-HNS, 6-7 --
Rafael Cancel Miranda gestures towards some of the mementos that
hang in his home. Cancel Miranda and his three nationalist
compatriots who in 1954 etched their names in infamy by storming
the U.S. House of Representatives, unfurling national flags and
opening fire with pistols. Five lawmakers were wounded as they
dived under their desks. He served 25 years in jail before he and
the others were pardoned by President Carter. (Steve
Ueckert/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MARION, Ill. -- June 7, 1998 -- FALN-PRISONERS-1-HNS, 6-7
-- Oscar Lopez Rivera was among 15 Puerto Ricans sentenced in the
early 1980s for a campaign of bombings and robberies and conspired
to use force to bring to an end the U.S. stewardship of Puerto
Rico. ``I have no regrets for serving a noble cause, but ... there
has been a lot of pain and a lot of suffering,'' Lopez Rivera says
from prison where he is doing 70 years. (Steve Ueckert/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BETHESDA, Md. -- June 7, 1998 -- SCI-IMMUNE-THEORY, 6-7
-- Outside the National Institue for Health, Polly Matzinger, a
tenured medical researcher at the Institue, sits with her dogs,
Annie, left, and Roy. Dr. Matzinger is turning the world of
immunology upside down with her radical theory suggesting that the
human immune system is activated by dangerous substances in the
body. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) RICHMOND, Va. -- June 7, 1998 -- SURVIVAL-ODDS-HEALTH,
6-7 -- Thomas Smith, a hematologist and oncologist at the Massey
Cancer Center at Virginia Commonwealth University in Richmond,
studies the x-rays of a 25-year-old patient with an advanced, and
likely fatal form of cancer. ``Ninety-nine percent of patients will
say, 'Tell me everything,''' says Smith who works to improve
communication between doctors and dying patients. (Timothy
Wright/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
