<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9987 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     06-08 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trading Hakeem &QL; 
would be senseless
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ As the NBA Finals take a merciful two-day break to allow
the Jazz to try to pick up the pieces, two questions dominate the
buzz around the league:
</P>
<P>
   Could Utah possibly play worse if blindfolded?
</P>
<P>
   Would the Rockets even consider trading Hakeem Olajuwon?
</P>
<P>
   The answer to both is, well, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Let Jerry Sloan worry about the Great Salt Fakes. Of immediate
concern is whether I'll be able to take more than two steps in the
next couple of days without hearing another Olajuwon trade rumor.
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem for Penny Hardaway and Bo Outlaw. Hakeem for Juwan Howard
and Calbert Cheaney. Hakeem for Stephon Marbury. Hakeem for Shareef
Abdur-Rahim. Hakeem for two Cubs tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's out there,'' said one NBA general manager in town for the
pre-draft camp for rookies. ``But I don't know how serious they
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Serious enough for us to address the notion, which can be done
in this very simple fashion:
</P>
<P>
   Dumb.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate.
</P>
<P>
   Stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Panicky.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention disloyal.
</P>
<P>
   Misguided rationale
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the Clinton administration's shipping off satellite
secrets to the Chinese. This is real treason. And it needs to be
nipped in the bud, even if we do get the usual raft of denials.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of this magnitude don't spring out of nowhere. Somebody
in the Rockets organization has, at the very least, decided to toss
Olajuwon's name out into the marketplace like high-priced chum,
then watch the hungry sharks come swimming. First, they make him
wear that clown-suit uniform. Now, they want to peddle him like a
corn dog at the fair.
</P>
<P>
   Your candidates: executive vice president of basketball Carroll
Dawson; senior executive vice president of basketball affairs
Robert Barr; head coach Rudy Tomjanovich; and owner Leslie
Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody here has decided that one subpar season that began with
surgery on his left knee and ended with a first-round playoff loss
to the Jazz means that Olajuwon, at 35, no longer has the stuff to
take the Rockets back to the level of championship contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody wants us to believe that because Olajuwon decided to
take off for a vacation in the Caribbean, delaying a heart
examination and possible surgery on his right knee, he is no longer
committed to returning to his previous level as one of the top
centers in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a news flash: Even after scoring a career-low 16.7 points
a game in 1997-98, Olajuwon still is one of the best centers in the
NBA. Who would you rank ahead of him right now? Shaquille O'Neal.
Maybe David Robinson. It's a short list.
</P>
<P>
   Those who would trade Olajuwon also believe the $44 million in
salary the Rockets will owe him over the next three years is a yoke
around the neck of the franchise and that it is time to move on and
rebuild completely.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets are said to be looking very hard at Alief High
prospect Rashard Lewis in the draft. Put him alongside Abdur-Rahim,
and you could argue the Rockets might be hitting their championship
stride again in a few years, just when a new arena might be on the
horizon in downtown Houston. If Abdur-Rahim can carry a franchise.
If a high school kid can make the leap to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   A legend deserves better
</P>
<P>
   This is where you might suspect Alexander to be behind the
rumors. I have two names for Les: Nolan Ryan and John McMullen.
Don't mess with our legends.
</P>
<P>
   If it is the coaching staff behind the rumors, it would be a
disappointing case of blame-shifting and finger-pointing at the
player who took them all on two wild, heady championship rides. If
Hakeem is to be held responsible for one bad year, what about the
staff that assembled this underachieving team?
</P>
<P>
   Work him, prod him, goad him into a strenuous offseason rehab
program. Don't just give up on him. Not now. Not after what he has
been _ a splendid athlete and an honorable man.
</P>
<P>
   If anybody knows about loyalty and representing one franchise
for an entire career, it would be Rudy T. And if anybody could ever
share Rudy's title as Mr. Rocket, it should be Olajuwon. For 14
years, he has been the heart of this franchise, the sports pulse of
the city. Those championships were his, then theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Forget that tripe about avoiding the trap of the fallen Celtics.
They had two great young talents _ Len Bias and Reggie Lewis _ die
on them and also hired a fool in M.L. Carr to be their coach.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers won five titles in the '80s, never hit bottom, and
all of those Hollywood heroes _ Kareem, Magic, Worthy _ retired in
LA uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon deserves the same. Anything less would be a bad ending
to a Dream.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Fran Blinebury on the Sports Page radio show on KPRC
(950 AM) from 5-7 p.m. weekdays. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
