<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
END OF THE BRAWLEY CASE MAY BE IN SIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ After nearly seven months of bitter
confrontation, legal wrangling and bizarre courtroom behavior, the
Tawana Brawley defamation case appears to be stampeding toward a
close.
</P>
<P>
   Alton Maddox Jr., the one of the three defendants who is
representing himself, rested his case Monday. Another defendant, C.
Vernon Mason, plans to present his case with only two witnesses on
Friday. Jurors could hear closing arguments by late next week.
</P>
<P>
   Maddox, who had vowed ``a long hot summer in Dutchess County''
and promised to call about 20 witnesses, finished his examination
after putting only four people on the stand to counter the
plaintiff, Steven Pagones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we did a wonderful job,'' Maddox said to reporters
outside the courthouse Monday. ``That's why we rested today. We
have not only shattered his case, we have given the jury some
insight as to some of the things that happened to Tawana Brawley.''
</P>
<P>
   Pagones, a former assistant district attorney, is suing Maddox,
Mason and the Rev. Al Sharpton, advisers to Ms. Brawley, for
publicly accusing him of kidnapping and raping her, a black
teen-ager, over the course of four days in 1987. A grand jury later
found that there was no evidence to show that Ms. Brawley had been
attacked, and it specifically exonerated Pagones. He sued the three
men for defamation and is seeking about $400 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Since the trial began on Nov. 18, the case has staggered through
29 witnesses and three seasons. In contrast, the state's second
death penalty trial, unfolding in the same building two flights up,
whipped through 13 witnesses in its first week. Prosecutors in the
Dalkeith McIntosh trial joke that they will be finished before
Pagones hears a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Although the trial has been lengthy, the judge, Supreme Court
Justice S. Barrett Hickman, has kept it from being even longer. He
pared Maddox's original list of witnesses _ precluding testimony
from two former talk show hosts, Geraldo Rivera and Phil Donahue,
for example _ and limited the subjects about which Maddox could
question his witnesses. He also curtailed the case proposed by
Mason's lawyer, Stephen Jackson, who said he now planned to call an
FBI agent to the stand on Friday, as well as a woman who appeared
in silhouette in a videotape documentary about the case.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of other loose ends. Michael Hardy, who is
representing Sharpton, has already called two witnesses, but may
call one more. And for the next few days, Hickman will be ruling on
motions made by the lawyers, as well as deciding how to instruct to
the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Pagones, however, appeared giddy with relief that the case might
be over soon. ''I'm anxious to get this to the jury,'' he told
reporters outside court Monday. ``I think they will find in my
favor and put this case to rest once and for all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
