<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-RADIO-TELESCOPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY RADIO ASTRONOMER IS HONORED  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLMDEL, N.J. _ His assignment from his bosses at Bell
Laboratories in 1931 was simple: build a 100-foot-long rotating
antenna to find out what was causing the static that interfered
with trans-Atlantic telephone calls. His discovery was anything but
simple: the static was the first evidence that stars and galaxies
were emitting radio waves.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Jansky's serendipitous discovery of what he called ``star
noise'' led to work in the field of radio astronomy in 1950, and
the rest is history _ or, more properly, cosmology. For it is
through radio astronomy that scientists have confirmed much of what
they theorized about black holes, pulsars, and the lingering
microwave signature of the Big Bang.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, armed with new details from recently discovered
notes, a group of scientists, including two Nobel Prize winners
whose own discoveries were made possible by Jansky's, gathered here
on the grounds of Bell Laboratories to dedicate a sculpture of the
original device _ stylized and miniaturized _ on what is believed
to be its original site.
</P>
<P>
   Jansky died in 1950, and until his notes were found, the only
trace of his discovery was a sign that pointed vaguely toward a
grassy area of the company's research complex. No one knew exactly
where the rotating array of brass piping and receivers mounted on
four wheels from a Model T _ Jansky called it his merry-go-round _
had been situated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't seem right to just go out there and pick a spot,''
said Robert Wilson, the Nobel Prize-winning astronomer whose own
radio telescope in 1964 detected the microwave radiation left over
from the Big Bang itself, and who helped uncover the lost notes.
``Because Jansky's antenna was the start of our science, we wanted
to mark it appropriately'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jansky's son, David, noted on Monday that Jansky had died
without ever hearing the term radio astronomy.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Tyson, an astrophysicist who helped find the lost notes,
said of Jansky's discovery: ``The astronomers were mystified and
the electrical engineers were clueless. So no one beat a path to
his door, but he was 20 years ahead of his time.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only after World War II that the Jansky discovery
attracted widespread attention. Jesse Greenstein, 89, an astronomer
who was one of the few to recognize its importance at first, said
on Monday that analysis of radio waves emanating from space
provided researchers with ``10,000 times the information'' that
they could get from optical astronomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It led to information that overturned the idea of a rationally
developing universe,'' he said, ``and replaced it with a
relativistic, ultra-high energy cosmos of scary, violent,
uncontrollable forces like black holes and quasars. It was a
revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Grote Reber, 95, who in the 1930s and '40s duplicated Jansky's
work, recalled Jansky as ``a competent, energetic and mild-mannered
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Jansky's sister, Helen Sanford, who came to the ceremony from
her home in Ojai, Calif., attributed her brother's perseverance in
pursuing the source of the static despite the lack of interest by
others to his training as a physicist and their father's admonition
to them as children to ``question everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Taylor, a 1993 Nobel Prize winner and the discoverer of
pulsars, agreed. ``When you have a prepared mind ready to receive
some signal from nature, then you have real progress,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of Jansky's discovery the front page of The New York
Times of May 5, 1933, carried an account of a scientific paper
detailing the discovery of the star noise, under the headline ``New
Radio Waves Traced to Centre of the Milky Way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten days later, between a Lowell Thomas news broadcast and a
Marx Brothers show, radio's Blue Network broadcast an interview
with Jansky, complete with three 10-second-long live segments of
actual static hiss emanating ``from the depths of the universe.''
At one point, the announcer told the listeners that they were tuned
in to Sagittarius, the constellation at the center of the galaxy
from which the waves emanated.
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker magazine, with a wry, world-weary tone in its
Talk of the Town section, said at the time of the discovery that it
was ``believed to be the longest distance anybody ever went to look
for trouble.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
