<SLUG> BC-NY-BLOOD-SHORTAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URGENT NEED FOR BLOOD DONORS IN NEW YORK REGION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With less than a day's supply of blood on hand for
hospitals in the New York region, health officials are urging
people to donate to curb the severe shortage.
</P>
<P>
   Blood supplies usually dwindle twice a year: around the December
holidays and near the end of the summer, both times when many
people are traveling and take off from work, where blood donations
are often collected. This year, however, the summer shortage
appears to have come early.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's scary to us now is we are reaching that point in
June,'' said Dr. Robert Jones, president of the New York Blood
Center. ``If that curve continues, we're going to be in real
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones described the need for blood as urgent, especially for
Type O, which can be used without negative reactions in patients
with any type of blood. The region's blood supply is typically
about 13,000 pints, Jones said. As of Monday, he said, there were
7,000 pints, an amount that would run out in one day if the stores
were not replenished.
</P>
<P>
   Around the nation, blood supplies are also down, though the need
varies by region. While some areas in the Middle West have small
surpluses, both coasts report severe shortages, particularly of
Type O blood.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and other health officials speculated that the early
shortage of blood was caused not by any single reason but an
accumulation of several trends. Since the start of the AIDS
epidemic more than a decade ago, the number of blood donors has
steadily declined. The reasons, Jones said, include an unfounded
fear of infection, fewer blood drives at businesses because of
corporate downsizing and a general belief that there is less need
to donate blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to get people to come in and give blood,'' said
Angela Buscemi, manager of the National Blood Exchange in Bethesda,
Md. ``I don't think there is as much of a connection today _ that I
need to donate blood because I'm going to help people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said this year has also been more difficult than others
because there is less blood to borrow from other regions. ``It's
tight everywhere,'' he said. The New York region includes New York
City, Long Island, the Hudson Valley and northern New Jersey.
People interested in donating can call (800) 933-2566 for the
location of the nearest blood donation center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 2221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
