</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BRAWLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELIG WANTS TO TOUGHEN RULES TO LIMIT FIGHTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Acting in the wake of nasty-looking on-field brawls two weeks
apart, baseball's acting commissioner, Bud Selig, called Monday for
more severe penalties for players who leave their locations to
``incite or further inflame violence of any sort.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig, saying the fights have distressed him, called on three
high-ranking major-league baseball officials to meet with players
association representatives to discuss the issue and to take action
designed to deter the kind of brawls that broke out at Yankee
Stadium on May 19 and in Kansas City last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Current fines and suspensions _ which do not include loss of
pay _should be revised or reformed to deter behavior which is not
in keeping with the integrity of the game,'' Selig said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   He instructed Paul Beeston, president and chief operating
officer of major-league baseball, and the league presidents, Gene
Budig of the American League and Leonard Coleman of the National
League, to meet with union officials to ``immediately devise new
and more effective penalties for those players and managers who
leave the dugout or their on-field positions to incite or further
inflame violence of any sort.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig did not include bullpens in his statement, but players in
those areas presumably would also be covered.
</P>
<P>
   New rules and penalties, Selig said, should be made effective as
soon as they can be agreed to.
</P>
<P>
   Because such changes would affect working conditions, the
players must agree to them. Managers are not covered by the union,
but the leagues would not implement rules regarding their behavior
without new rules also applying to players.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Fehr, head of the players association, said he was
prepared to listen to any proposals the baseball officials might
make. ``We'll wait and see what they have to say,'' he said. ``Most
people, I think, thought the penalties most recently imposed were
severe, especially on the managers. But we'll have to wait sand
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Fehr referred to Budig's disciplinary action against two
managers, three coaches and nine players for their roles in two
fights during the Angels-Royals game. Managers Terry Collins of
Anaheim and Tony Muser of Kansas City were suspended for eight
games each, the players were suspended for one to five games and
the coaches were fined.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the fight between the Yankees and the
Orioles after Armando Benitez hit Tino Martinez with a pitch
following a Bernie Williams home run, Budig suspended Benitez for
eight games and four other players for two or three games.
</P>
<P>
   The players suspended from both games were also fined amounts
ranging from $500 to $2,000. There has been a call from various
quarters for fines to be increased so that they would be more in
line with today's salaries. Asked about that idea, Fehr said, ``If
they want to make us proposals on fines, we'll listen to what they
have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is the only one of the four major professional sports
that does not impose automatic penalties on players for joining
fights in progress.
</P>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association warns its players that if
they leave the bench to join an on-court fight, they will be
suspended and fined. National Hockey League players incur automatic
suspensions for leaving the bench for an on-ice altercation. The
National Football League tells its players to ``stay away'' if a
fight breaks out among other players or face being fined.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials have said a similar rule would not make sense
for baseball because players whose team is at bat would be at a
disadvantage in a fight with the team in the field because it has
nine players not in the dugout or the bullpen. If a new rule
included penalties for players leaving their positions, however, a
fight would be fairer from the standpoint of numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Selig said fights bother him because they jeopardize players'
safety and ``reflect poorly on that large majority of players who
respect and maintain the tradition of sportsmanship long associated
with the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Players rarely emerge from baseball brawls with serious
injuries. The fights, for the most part, involve a lot of pushing
and shoving and grabbing and holding.
</P>
<P>
   As vicious as some viewers thought the Yankees-Orioles brawl
looked, the only punches that landed were thrown by Darryl
Strawberry at Benitez and Alan Mills at Strawberry. Graeme Lloyd, a
Yankees reliever, threw a series of punches at Benitez after he
raced to the mound from the bullpen, but he appeared to miss on
every one. Even so, he was suspended for three games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
