<HEADLINE>
COREY MILLER DOESN'T SHOW, BUT FASSEL'S ANGER DOES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ When Giants linebacker Corey Miller
agreed to take a pay cut last week to stay with the team, he talked
with Coach Jim Fassel, and according to the coach, promised to be
at Giants Stadium this week for the passing-camp workouts.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller did not make an appearance at Giants Stadium on
Monday, an absence that clearly left Fassel miffed, although
Raymond Anderson, Miller's agent, told the team that Miller left
his South Carolina home early Monday morning, apparently heading
for New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``He usually flies up here, but maybe he's driving this time,''
Giants General Manager Ernie Accorsi said of Miller, whose
$1.5-million salary was slashed by $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he'd be here, and he's not,'' Fassel said. Asked
whether he was angered by Miller's absence, Fassel said to
reporters, ``You guys can draw your own conclusions.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel then recited the names of a few players who had been
given excused absences from Monday's workout. ``They all talked to
me about why they wouldn't be here,'' Fassel said.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' workouts this month are technically optional, but
players customarily tell teams of any absence, anyway. Fassel gave
Miller last week off from the workouts. ``He said he had some
things to take care of, and I said that was OK,'' Fassel said.
``I'll visit with him about that. I always give the guy the benefit
of the doubt until I talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller may be on the verge of losing his starting job at
strongside linebacker. Some Giants coaches are leaning toward
giving that starting assignment to Marcus Buckley, whom the team
signed to a three-year free agent contract this winter.
</P>
<P>
   If Miller is upset over his pay cut, it will surprise Accorsi.
The Giants' general manager said that Miller signed his new
contract and mailed it to the team last week. ``There were no
problems,'' Accorsi said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
