<SLUG> BC-AUTO-POLLUTE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONDA AND FORD TO PAY FINES FOR POLLUTION VIOLATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Story rewritten throughout.)  
 (ATTN: Calif., Japan)  (lb) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Honda and Ford have agreed to pay millions of
dollars in civil fines for selling cars that were designed to pass
emissions tests but were certain to run substantially dirtier on
the road, federal prosecutors announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and the Environmental Protection Agency
fined Honda Motor Co. $12.6 million for violations of the Clean Air
Act. The EPA said the automaker would also face costs of about $250
million for remedial efforts, including extending warranties and
providing free tune-ups for the 1.6 million cars that are affected.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. will pay a $2.5 million fine for a
pollution-control problem on 60,000 of its 1997 Econoline vans, the
officials said, and $3.8 million in other costs and compensatory
measures. Ford began a recall of the vans Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement is an embarrassment to Honda, which in
advertising and public statements has portrayed itself as an
environmental leader. The automaker has voluntarily put extra
equipment on hundreds of thousands of vehicles to make sure that
they meet California's strict emission standards, even if they are
sold in states that enforce the looser federal standard. Ford also
voluntarily exceeds emission rules on many of its models.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making very clear that cars are a major source of air
pollution in this country and it is important for auto
manufacturers to assure they are carefully complying with the Clean
Air Act,'' said Lois Schiffer, an assistant attorney general and
head of the environment and natural-resources division at the
Justice Department. ``If they don't do it, we will take strong
action against them.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with Honda covers all of the Honda and Acura
vehicles built in the 1996 and '97 model years, with the exception
of Passport and SLX, and the 1997 Integra R. For 1995 models, the
agreement covers the Accord V-6 and the Acura NSX, 2.5 TL. Acura is
a division of Honda.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors say Honda was fined for programming the
pollution-control computers to ignore spark-plug failures. The
computer software would not illuminate the ``check engine'' light
when parts fail and emissions rise, thus allowing the cars to emit
twice as much smog-causing hydrocarbons without warning their
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Honda, William Willen, said that the problem was
one of interpretation of the rules, and that the vehicles'
diagnostic systems would function if the problem were serious. The
``check engine'' light would fail to come on, Willen said in a
telephone interview, only in times of intermittent failure.
</P>
<P>
   Willen said the company's engineers had simply gone too far in
their efforts to minimize the number of times the light came on.
</P>
<P>
   But the environmental agency estimated that uncorrected, the
cars _ Civics, Accords, Del Sols, Integras, Preludes, NSXs and
CR-Vs, Odysseys and their Isuzu-brand twin, the Oasis _ would emit
8 million extra tons of hydrocarbons in their lifetimes. Total
emission of hydrocarbons from all transportation sources was about
10 million tons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also said that the cars could grow sluggish without
warning the driver that something was wrong, and that if a driver
took one to a garage, the mechanic would have a harder time
diagnosing the problem.
</P>
<P>
   David Alexander, a lawyer with the EPA enforcement division,
said suppressing the dashboard warning light made life harder for
all drivers, even those who were relatively knowledgeable about
cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idiot lights are for all of us,'' Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   In Ford's case, the 60,000 Econoline vans are equipped with a
feature that makes them emit more nitrogen oxides at highway speeds
than they do on treadmill tests.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to paying $2.5 million in civil penalties, the
company will buy pollution credits from other sources for $2.5
million, and will spend $1.3 million on fixing the Econolines, with
a goal of completing the work on at least 70 percent of them.
</P>
<P>
   A Ford spokeswoman, Sara Tatchio, said the company had changed
the pollution systems on Econolines on its assembly line and in
dealer lots as soon as the government raised its objections early
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation also called into question the
pollution-control systems on 1.7 million Ford Escorts sold between
1991 and 1995, but the agreement did not require any corrective
action to those cars. Ford sold 6.9 million vehicles worldwide last
year and had earnings of $6.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Honda was also notified of the problems last year and has also
corrected them for vehicles now in production.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The software in the affected Hondas is burned into the computer
chips, and correcting the problem would mean replacing the chips,
at a price the government put at $500 million. The package that
Honda agreed to _ including free oil changes, to lure drivers in
for their free tune-ups _ was more effective, the EPA said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to tuneups and engine checks, Honda will extend the
warranty on the pollution-control systems to 14 years or 150,000
miles. Depending on which part was involved and where the car was
sold, the existing warranties ranged from three years or 36,000
miles to eight years or 80,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the Justice Department estimate, Honda said it did
not know the cost for the remedial actions, because no one had ever
guaranteed car parts for so long. Honda's payment will be spread
over 14 years, which will significantly reduce the financial impact
on the company. Honda sold 2 million vehicles worldwide in 1997,
and for the fiscal year that ended March 31 had a profit of $1.96
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The largest previous case was the $45 million in fines and
remedial actions that General Motors Corp. agreed to in 1995 for
producing Cadillacs that passed emissions tests but violated
pollution standards on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Honda problem was discovered by officials of the California
Air Resources Board, which serves as the Environmental Protection
Agency's surrogate for certifying that Honda vehicles meet federal
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The California board tested one vehicle that had been on the
road for several months, and found that it did not diagnose engine
misfires, in which the fuel-air mixture fails to explode and is
shoved out the exhaust system, sometimes damaging the catalytic
converter on the way.
</P>
<P>
   On closer examination, California engineers found that the
system was designed not to work.
</P>
<P>
   Honda said owners with questions could call its Consumer Affairs
Department at (800) 999-1009.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
