<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-MARTIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN WILL RIDE HIS CART IN THE OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ In dramatic fashion, Casey Martin qualified for the
U.S. Open Monday, fulfilling another dream and returning his
remarkable story to the national stage.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who successfully sued the PGA Tour earlier this year for
the right to use a cart in competition, prevailed on the second
hole of a sudden-death playoff at the U.S. Open sectional qualifier
at Clovernook Country Club. By making a 25-foot birdie putt on the
38th hole of competition, Martin won a five-man playoff for the
last available spot and earned a berth in next week's U.S. Open at
the Olympic Club in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who suffers from Klippel-Trenaunay-Weber syndrome, a
painful circulatory ailment, will become the first golfer ever to
ride a cart in the Open.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the odds were against Martin at Clovernook, with 67
golfers vying for just five qualifying spots. And during Martin's
third hole, his specially designed one-seat cart stalled, forcing
him to walk for two holes. But Martin shot a 2-under-par 138 over
36 holes of regulation before winning the playoff. When it was
over, Martin was relieved, drained, and somewhat stunned. On his
fourth attempt at making the Open, and at age 26, Martin had
finally reached a lifelong goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a growing up, hitting shots around my yard and
thinking I was in the Open, I never thought it would become a
reality,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin will become a focal point of attention next week,
especially since PGA Tour players were divided on whether he should
be allowed to use a cart. Martin has used a cart on the Nike Tour
this year, but the Open will be his first taste of competing
against the world's best players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard from a respected player that I'll be welcome,''
Martin said when asked what kind of reception he expected to
receive from players next week.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's scene was full of bizarre moments, the most unusual of
which was when Martin's cart stalled. The vehicle was approved by
the U.S. Golf Association and designed by Pride Health Care, a
manufacturer of lift chairs and scooters based in Exeter, Pa.
Martin played down the incident, saying he must have accidentally
kicked the ignition key, which caused it to malfunction. But
Martin, who uses a regular cart on the Nike Tour, had trouble
steering the new cart at times, and when he could not get it to
move on the third fairway, he got up and limped to his ball,
leaving the vehicle behind.
</P>
<P>
   After one of Pride Health's representatives restarted the cart,
it was returned to Martin after his tee shot at No. 5, and he used
it the rest of the day. But more distractions followed. The gallery
was smaller than expected, reaching a maximum of only about 200
people, but a television station helicopter followed Martin's
threesome for the three holes during the afternoon. ``It annoyed
everyone on the golf course,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin pressed on. He almost squandered his dream, making a
double-bogey six on the final hole that threatened to cost him a
playoff spot. Martin nervously waited in his car after he finished
for the remaining golfers to complete their rounds.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin regained his composure in the playoff to make a putt
he will not forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't sunk in, but I'm sure it will,'' Martin said. ``Next
week should be something I can really savor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
