<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL WALTON URGES MALONE TO STEP UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What I wouldn't have given for a few renditions of
``That's terrible!'' from Bill Walton to describe Utah's
ignominious 96-54 collapse Sunday night to Chicago in Game 3 of the
National Basketball Association &QC; finals.
</P>
<P>
   But Walton is not the third member of NBC's game crew for the
finals as he had been for several years. Now, his tart, contrarian,
sometimes odd views are confined to NBC's pre-game and halftime
studio programs and to CNBC's post-game show.
</P>
<P>
   For every lousy clanged shot, dumb turnover or missed rebound by
Utah, NBC should play taped Waltonisms: ``That's awful!'' or
``Deliver me from this dreadful display of horrible passing that is
turning John Wooden's stomach!''
</P>
<P>
   If Walton is irked by his slim role, you must read between his
lines. ``You do whatever you can,'' he said Monday from Chicago.
``You do your best.''
</P>
<P>
   At least before Sunday's game, Walton used the pre-game show to
launch into a typically emotive challenge, this to Karl Malone, the
slumping Jazz forward: ``How about playing? How about 35 points on
a minimum of 25 shots? At least go down fighting. Let us see your
soul, your passion, Karl. This isn't another day at work. This is
about competitive greatness, about leadership, the ability to
respond to the greatest challenge and opportunity in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Walton said, Malone responded ``for about five
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone's and Utah's failures, he said, are reminders of how far
Chicago towers over its rivals and how much greater Michael Jordan
is than anyone else. ``I always get the sense that Chicago is
toying with us,'' the former Trail Blazer, Clipper and Celtic said.
``They're just so good. In a close game, I'm thinking, `You're
teasing us.'''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding Jordan, he said: ``We haven't seen the best of Michael
Jordan because we haven't gotten to the point where Michael has had
to come up with something new. Just imagine if someone were in
their pushing him further?''
</P>
<P>
   Utah, he said, has failed to figure out how to attack Chicago's
defense, or create anything offensively once its pick-and-rolls
broke down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great offensive players should be able to break down a great
defense,'' Walton said. ``If Chicago's defense is such a big factor
in this series, then it's an indication of the separation between
these teams. They talk about defense winning championships _ well,
everybody plays defense _ but you need a guy who can come down and
when the defense is so good, can still get a good shot.''
</P>
<P>
   So even if Utah lays down for Games 4 and 5, Walton insists he
can gaze admiringly upon the Bulls and not cry on Wooden's fatherly
shoulder. ``I'm lucky to have played on teams that have been
brilliant at times,'' he said. ``You hope the other team matches
that level, but as long as one team gets there, where everything
you dream of comes true, you get so high.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps watching the Bulls unleash devastation is not a turnoff.
Game 3's Nielsen 16.8 overnight rating rose from a 15.9 last year.
Despite the runaway, the rating rose from a 16.8 from 8:30-9 p.m.
to an 18.2 from 9-9:30 and fell only slightly to an 18.1 in the
final 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Loving the World Cup  &LR;  Preston Padden, the president of the ABC
Television Network, is hopeful about the success of the network's
14 World Cup telecasts, which begin Saturday at 3 p.m. with the
Netherlands playing Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not suggesting it will overtake `Monday Night Football'
but it is a building phenomenon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``You've got all this built-in marketing, with kids,
coaches and parents. We're glad to have the franchise. We think
it'll grow. It's our Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC is seeking World Cup synergy: Sunday's ``Wonderful World of
Disney'' is a soccer movie called ``The Big Green.'' ``The View,''
a daytime talk show, is giving away a van. The Saturday morning
cartoon shows are being used for a soccer contest, and Friday's
prime-time shows will present brief soccer features between the
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Padden said the network tried to weave soccer story lines into
the afternoon soap operas, but the U.S. team was chosen too late.
He hopes ``Ted Koppel is a big soccer fan,'' so ``Nightline'' will
book a soccer program. Maybe with the soccer aficionado Henry
Kissinger expounding on the Ronaldo Realpolitik?
</P>
<P>
   Looking to the United States-Iran game on June 21, Padden said,
``We're thinking about asking former President Jimmy Carter back
for commentary.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Backstretch Thoughts  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ABC's Belmont Stakes coverage on Saturday excelled for showing
the finish photo being examined before stewards declared Victory
Gallop the winner and for quickly reporting the stewards' inquiry
of Real Quiet. But the running graphic showing the horses'
positions failed again, showing horses out of the slots that the
race caller Dave Johnson said they were in. Nielsen's overnight
ratings for the race were 6.6, up from 6.2 last year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
