<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-NEWARK-POLITICS-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSIONS RISE OVER COUNCIL RUNOFF IN NEW JERSEY
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS.: DeTwayne Holmes is cq) 
 (ja) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Runoff elections rarely set pulses racing. But
the one being played out Tuesday in Newark's Central Ward may prove
the exception.
</P>
<P>
   The race for the City Council seat from the neighborhood that
was ground zero in Newark's 1967 riots and the setting for
rebuilding in the last 15 years, is between a veteran politician
and a 29-year-old newcomer with Ivy League and Oxford credentials.
As New Jersey's largest city continues its steady struggle back
from the turmoil of the late 1960s, the Central Ward contest is not
just about young versus old and outsider versus insider, but about
the glitter of things hoped for against the solidity of things
known.
</P>
<P>
   The passion excited by the election was evident after a
candidates' forum June 3, when Darlene Parker argued with a
neighbor about the merits of one candidate, George Branch, a
69-year-old, four-term incumbent. Branch had, by virtue of his
experience and his quiet but constant presence in the ward, earned
re-election, she said. He had paid his dues, she went on, and this
country ought to respect such people.
</P>
<P>
   But her debating partner, DeTwayne Holmes, retorted that
Branch's 29-year-old opponent, Cory Booker, had impressive
educational credentials: Stanford University, Oxford University,
Yale Law School. Holmes said he saw Booker as just the kind of
``young, innovative, educated'' candidate that the now resurgent
ward and city needed. ``We need new blood,'' he stressed.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's runoff was forced by the May 12 municipal election, in
which no candidate in a three-way race attained a majority in the
Central Ward voting. Branch finished 340 votes ahead of Booker, out
of 7,700 votes cast.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of its energy level alone, the runoff shows a new
fervor about politics and the city's future among the ward's 27,000
registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to Newark's credit that there is this runoff,'' said
Raymond Codey, director of development for the New Community Corp.,
a nonprofit housing and economic development group in the Central
Ward. ``Residents didn't just vote for the older guy, but are
intelligently evaluating the candidates. It speaks well for Newark
that we can attract a candidate like Cory Booker and give residents
this kind of choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's ballot also features a runoff in the West Ward and a
runoff among eight candidates for four at-large seats on the City
Council.
</P>
<P>
   But Booker's presence in the Central Ward race has generated the
most interest. He could have been sent by central casting to typify
a product of the black middle class who grew up in an era of
integration and civil rights gains. A cum laude graduate of
Stanford University, a Rhodes scholar and 1996 graduate of Yale Law
School, he was raised in Bergen County's affluent Harrington Park,
where his family had to invoke anti-discrimination laws to buy
their home. His only early connection to Newark was through an
uncle who lived and practiced dentistry here.
</P>
<P>
   Then, two years ago, he moved to Newark with a fellowship to do
legal work for the Legal Action Center for the Homeless, a
nonprofit group. He says he soon saw politics as a surer route to
change. Through school contacts, he had entree to city corporate
and business leaders. Soon his name was on all their lips as
someone who bore watching, and that buzz, as much as anything else,
placed him as a new star in the city's political firmament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked a community which was in incredible distress and
which at the same time had amazing human beings,'' Booker said, in
explaining why he chose to come to Newark and to run in the city's
Central Ward. ``I'm in the top 1 percent educationally of this
nation _ black or white _ and I have been taught that to he who
much is given, much is expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Booker has raised and spent more than $140,000 so far, an
extraordinary amount for a council race in Newark, which rarely
sees more than $50,000 spent. Much of it was raised from a network
of friends and associates from Stanford, Oxford and Yale.
</P>
<P>
   Newark's mayor, Sharpe James, who is supporting Branch, has
styled the Central Ward contest as a race between the Rhodes
scholar and the ``road scholar'' in an effort to burnish Branch's
street smarts and long service in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Branch, a former youth coordinator with the Newark Housing and
Redevelopment Authority, is also a former lightweight boxer who
amassed a professional record of 28-8. They were mostly decisions,
he said in a recent interview, noting that he patterned himself
after Sugar Ray Robinson, and was not a flashy knockout artist.
</P>
<P>
   This style has characterized his political career as well, say
supporters like the Rev. Jason Guice, pastor of Hopewell Baptist
Church. Branch played a role in making sure that the privately
financed, middle-income town houses of Society Hill/University
Heights got built and was one of the first buyers, Guice noted. He
also helped bring about the construction of apartments by
church-sponsored nonprofit groups and town houses by the city's
housing authority, Guice said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition, he has performed the traditional constituent
service in solving problems for the elderly, helping start youth
programs and getting homeowner tax abatements. ``He has been there,
and that is why the ministers of the Central Ward are supporting
him,'' Guice said.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, Branch and his supporters were lackadaisical
before the vote on May 12. But by the end of last week, Branch had
raised and spent more than $100,000 himself in an effort to beat
back the challenge in the runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Branch and his supporters are pressing hard to stick the
``outsider'' label on Booker, as well as tie him to downtown and
business interests whom they deride for having moved many of their
operations, and in some cases their residences, from Newark to the
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jonah Nixon, vice chairman of the Newark North Jersey
Committee of Black Churchmen, said that these unnamed interests now
want to return and reclaim a prominent place in the city, as it
seems to be rebounding with such amenities as the New Jersey
Performing Arts Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who have deserted the city would like to come back, and
these are the people who are supporting Cory Booker and giving him
most of his money,'' Nixon said.
</P>
<P>
   While Booker and his backers do claim the support of business
leaders who have holdings in Newark but live elsewhere, they brand
as ridiculous suggestions that they are his only supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Booker's claim of broader support is borne out in part by the
results of the May 12 election. Branch won most of the
middle-income, homeowner areas and precincts with large numbers of
elderly people, if only by slim margins. But it was Booker who won
the poorer areas dominated by the city's last remaining high-rise
public housing complexes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parker and Holmes never resolved their own debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newark is not moving as fast as it could,'' Holmes said. ``We
need young people, educated people with vibrant new ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parker shot back, ``Education is not enough by itself. You
can be an educated fool, you know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
