<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-BOMB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY BOMB IS ACTUALLY JUST A DUD  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is every director's nightmare _ bombing on
Broadway. For Judy Cohen, it came true on Monday, in a manner of
speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Clutching a white plastic bag, she stopped at a Citibank branch
on Broadway and 111th Street to use an automated teller machine.
Then she rushed to the Village Copier on 115th Street to make
photocopies of a script for a play she is about to direct.
</P>
<P>
   Then she had a chilling realization. The bag was still at the
Citibank branch. Inside the bag was a prop for the play. The prop
resembled a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she scampered back to the bank, a security guard had
called the police, who cordoned off the area. Ms. Cohen was left to
frantically explain that an episode of frightening confusion was
the result of a moment of absent-mindedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so horribly embarrassed,'' said Ms. Cohen, 27, a graduate
student at Columbia University. ``I don't want this to be my 15
minutes of fame. I want the play to be my 15 minutes of fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the incident lasted 77 minutes, said Sgt. Cory Cuneo,
a police spokesman. After a customer told the security guard about
the bag, who called the police at 6:39 p.m., the bomb squad closed
Broadway between 110th and 112th Streets.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the prop resembled the genuine article. There
were six cardboard tubes, painted fire-engine red and bundled with
gray electrical tape to resemble dynamite. Black wires snaked from
the end of each tube and were connected to a wristwatch atop the
bundle. After the police found that the bomb was make-believe, the
emergency was called off at 7:56 p.m., Cuneo said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cohen's play, called ``Baggage,'' opens on Friday at the
Theater for the New City, on First Avenue near 10th Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
