<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0455 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONRAIL-DIVIDE-725&AMP;AD     06-08 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONRAIL-DIVIDE-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. BACKS DIVIDING CONRAIL TO SPUR COMPETITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Va., Conn., Mass., Pa., Canada)  (lb) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government approved a sweeping plan
Monday to restructure the United States' rail freight system east
of the Mississippi River, a move officials said would take trucks
off the road, reduce air pollution and lower the cost of goods for
the New York City metropolitan region and much of the rest of the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's vote by the Surface Transportation Board gave final
approval to a proposal by CSX Corp. and Norfolk Southern Corp. to
divide Conrail's nearly 12,000 miles of track, stretching from
Boston to St. Louis. CSX and Norfolk Southern jointly bought
Conrail, which operated mainly in the Northeast, for $10.2 billion
last year in one of the largest rail mergers in the nation's
history.
</P>
<P>
   The plan approved Monday creates two railroad giants that will
dominate rail freight shipping throughout the nation's eastern
half, allowing direct competition between the two companies in
several places, including much of New Jersey and parts of western
New York state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This carefully crafted, privately negotiated deal injects
competition in the entire East like no merger before has ever
done,'' said Linda Morgan, the chairwoman of the board. ``It will
bring competition back to many areas that had lost options through
the creation of Conrail.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and New York Gov.
George Pataki hailed the decision, saying it would allow more than
one major railroad company to ship goods in and out of New York
City for the first time in decades and potentially provide new
transportation routes for Long Island businesses that are solely
dependent on trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in a long time, businesses on the east side
of the Hudson will have access to competitive freight rail
services,'' said Bradford Race, Pataki's chief of staff. ``It's a
significant step forward for Long Island, Manhattan and communities
all along the river.''
</P>
<P>
   But some members of New York's congressional delegation said the
plan fell well short of what was needed to revitalize the region's
rail freight industry, charging that the transportation board had
squandered an opportunity to force much more competition for New
York City's huge market. Less than 3 percent of all the goods
shipped in and out of the city is carried by trains, compared with
about 40 percent in other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they agreed to was grossly inadequate,'' said Rep.
Jerrold Nadler, D-New York City, who said he might file suit to
block the plan. ``This doesn't give us any real competition at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also not clear whether the new plan would have a
significant impact on rail shipping in Connecticut, where CSX will
take over Conrail's lines. But in New Jersey, where CSX and Norfolk
Southern will jointly operate hundreds of miles of former Conrail
track while directly competing with each other, shipping costs are
expected to decline and rail traffic to increase.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental advocates and New York officials said they were
concerned that added rail traffic in New Jersey would lead to an
increase in trucks carrying goods from New Jersey rail yards into
New York City over the George Washington Bridge even as New Jersey
benefits from less trucking over all. The transportation board said
Monday that it would conduct a study to see if that happened.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's vote clears one of the last major hurdles for CSX and
Norfolk Southern to complete their takeover of Conrail, a monopoly
system created by Congress 22 years ago out of the remnants of the
failed Penn Central system.
</P>
<P>
   The board's decision _ which includes dozens of conditions
dealing with labor, environmental and administrative issues _ still
has to be set down on paper. After that report is released on July
23, the two companies will have to wait 30 days before the takeover
becomes effective. Officials with the two companies have said they
may take several months more to put the plan in place.
</P>
<P>
   CSX and Norfolk Southern have said that their plan will cut
truck travel on the nation's roads by a million trips a year,
sharply reducing air pollution in congested regions like New York
City. And while the elimination of Conrail's freight lines will
lead to the loss of more than 2,500 union and management jobs, the
two companies contend the nation's economy will benefit from lower
shipping costs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This is going to be good for every consumer and every producer
in the East,'' said David Goode, chairman of Norfolk Southern.
</P>
<P>
   Norfolk Southern, based in Norfolk, Va., will grow from 14,400
track miles to 21,400 miles in 22 states. CSX, which is based in
Richmond, Va., will grow from 18,300 track miles to more than
23,000 miles in 23 states.
</P>
<P>
   Some unions representing workers who may lose their jobs were
expected to protest the plan. And some manufacturing trade
associations said that they were concerned that shipping rates
might actually rise in regions where Conrail had once been in
competition with CSX or Norfolk Southern.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for CSX to take over Conrail's lines in
Connecticut, Massachusetts, along the Hudson from New York City to
Albany, N.Y., and running west from there to Buffalo, as well as
from Syracuse to Montreal. Norfolk Southern will take control of
lines along the New York-Pennsylvania border and throughout
Pennsylvania. The two companies will jointly operate much of
Conrail's former lines in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Among the provisions the transportation board approved Monday is
a requirement that CSX allow Canadian Pacific Ltd. to ship goods
from Canada and parts west along the Hudson to New York City. City
officials said that requirement would greatly increase rail
competition in the metropolitan region, opening it up more to
western markets.
</P>
<P>
   But Nadler and other members of New York's and Connecticut's
congressional delegations had wanted the transportation board to
require CSX to allow Norfolk Southern to operate on the east side
of the Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Doing that would not only reduce shipping rates, they said, but
also encourage the two companies to expand the use of barges to
carry rail cars across New York Harbor from New Jersey to Brooklyn
in New York City. Because there is no rail bridge connecting New
Jersey to New York City, rail freight coming from the south has to
be unloaded in New Jersey and then trucked across bridges or
through tunnels to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morgan said the board was not willing to make such a radical
change to the CSX-Norfolk Southern deal. But the board did require
the two companies to join in a city and state study into improving
cross-Hudson shipping.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is also expected to reduce shipping costs in Buffalo,
N.Y., and Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
