<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DRUG-RING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SAY NEW YORK COUPLE RAN DRUG RING USING 2 SONS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal prosecutors said Monday that they had charged
a Bronx man and his wife with running a large-scale drug operation,
and accused the husband of using their two sons, ages 6 and 10, to
carry narcotics and cash in the drug deals.
</P>
<P>
   The husband, Manuel Grullon, 38, and his wife, Maria Polanco,
37, were charged along with 26 other people for their roles in the
operation, which sold thousands of dollars in cocaine, crack
cocaine and heroin each week to customers in the High Bridge
section of the Bronx and elsewhere in the city, law enforcement
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But there were questions Monday night about the fate of the
couple's two sons. City and police officials said the sons were
left in the custody of a neighbor after the police and Drug
Enforcement Administration agents arrested Grullon on Friday and
Ms. Polanco on Saturday, but the children may have been taken to
the same apartment building where Grullon is accused of basing his
narcotics operation.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the city's Administration for Children's
Services said that the placement with the neighbor was temporary,
pending an investigation by the child welfare agency.
</P>
<P>
   But the wife of the superintendent of the building in which the
Grullon family had lived, at 162 W. 165th St., said that the two
boys, as well as the couple's two teen-age daughters, were then
taken by Ms. Polanco's sister, who lives at 1055 University Ave.
</P>
<P>
   According to papers unsealed in Federal District Court in
Manhattan Monday, Grullon and his associates based their drug
dealing in that building, in a group of apartments they controlled,
as well as from its lobby and from a bodega on its ground floor.
</P>
<P>
   A young man who answered the door Monday night in the
fifth-floor apartment at 1055 University Ave. where Ms. Polanco's
sister, Carina, lives, refused to say whether the children were
there. He would only give his first name, Eric, and said: ``They
are safe. They are with family.''
</P>
<P>
   The spokeswoman for Children's Services, Leonora Wiener, said
that she did not have further details on the status of the agency's
investigation, or whether a caseworker had yet visited the
children's temporary new home to determine its suitability or
safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children are with a neighbor and we are investigating,''
Ms. Wiener said.
</P>
<P>
   It was also unclear how the decision was made to leave the
children with the neighbor after Grullon and Ms. Polanco were taken
into custody. Their arrests followed an eight-month joint
DEA-Police Department investigation of drug trafficking in and
around 1055 University Ave, ``a building that has long been
infested with pervasive drug dealing,'' prosecutors said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the DEA, Special Agent Diane Ingalls, said
that the drug agents and police officers who arrested Ms. Polanco
had left the children in the custody of the neighbor after Ms.
Polanco identified them ``as people that she trusted the children
to be left with.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, a Police Department spokeswoman, said that the
police, as part of the continuing investigation in the case, had
alerted Children's Services in advance of taking the parents into
custody. ``There was a prior referral. This has been discussed with
ACS even before the arrests.''
</P>
<P>
   The court papers describe the boys' father, Grullon as leader of
the drug dealing organization, and Ms. Polanco as her husband's
chief deputy, who ``shares responsibility for the daily operation
and management.''
</P>
<P>
   One law enforcement source, who asked not to be identified, said
that it is believed that the organization has been selling as much
as $50,000 worth of narcotics in New York City, as well as
Delaware, for almost 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The federal complaint filed in the court cites two instances
earlier this year of Grullon's using his sons to carry bags of
cocaine and crack in their jackets, and in one case, to carry a
$2,400 payment from a customer back to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Although minors are often used by drug dealers to carry out
transactions, it is rare to see children so young be used by their
parents, said law enforcement officials who have followed such
prosecutions over the years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
