<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0038 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-NIGERIA-ABACHA-1STL     06-08 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NIGERIA-ABACHA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIAN DICTATOR DIES; SUCCESSOR QUICKLY NAMED 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Subs to update, repeating for all needing)  
 (See also, ABACHA-OBIT, NIGERIA-ASSESS and NIGERIA-OPPOSITION)  
(lh) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gen. Sani Abacha, the dictator of Nigeria, whose ruthless
suppression of opponents, human rights and democracy led to
condemnation around the world and seething discontent at home, died
early Monday, and his defense chief was quickly sworn in to lead
Africa's most populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of the death were sketchy, but U.S. officials said they
had no evidence of foul play.
</P>
<P>
   Abacha had not left a clear successor, but Nigeria's top
military leaders convened and selected Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar,
apparently averting a protracted power struggle for leadership in
the oil-rich nation of 115 million, a country wracked by decades of
harsh, corrupt military regimes and the effects of Western
sanctions imposed in a futile effort to hasten democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The swift selection of another military leader came in the face
of appeals by exiled Nigerians and world leaders in Washington,
London, Paris and other capitals, who said the the general's death
heralded an opportunity for Nigeria to release hundreds of
political prisoners, cancel executions set by kangaroo courts and
restore civilian government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abacha's death is not going to bring my father back,'' said
Ken Wiwa, the son of the playwright and environmental activist Ken
Saro-Wiwa, who, with eight other opponents of the general, was
publicly hanged for ``treason'' in 1995 while a worldwide
outpouring of appeals for mercy was icily ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Wole Soyinka, the Nigerian playwright who won the 1986 Nobel
Prize for Literature, fled to exile in Paris in 1994 and was
recently charged in absentia with treason, said from Jerusalem that
the general's death was an ``incredible opportunity'' for Nigeria
to resurrect democracy.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the White House offered no comment, but the State
Department spokesman, James Rubin, offered sympathy to Abacha's
family, reaffirmed the U.S. commitment to promoting democracy in
Nigeria, and urged a ``peaceful transition to civilian, democratic
rule.''
</P>
<P>
   After a morning of rumors and confusion in which heavily armed
soldiers sealed off the general's compound in the capital, Abuja, a
brief communique by Abubakar, announced that the 54-year-old
Nigerian leader, who seized power in 1993, was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The head of state and commander in chief of the Nigerian armed
forces, Gen. Sani Abacha, died at dawn,'' the statement read on
national radio said. ``He was to be buried today in Kano, his
native town, in accordance with Muslim rites and tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   The communique did not specify the cause of death, but news
reports quoted family friends and Western diplomats as saying he
had suffered a heart attack. Reports that Abacha's health was
failing circulated after he canceled a trip to Lagos, Nigeria's
principal city and former capital, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the death drew no outpouring of sorrow in Nigeria, where
the general had tamed political parties, trade unions and the
press, and had an enemies' list that read like a Who's Who of
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   In Lagos, where opposition to Abacha had been strongest, there
were no signs of mourning. ``God is, capable of wonderful things,''
an opposition political figure in Lagos said from behind a screen
of anonymity. ``Perhaps Nigerians will be free at last.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 2256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0458 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0039 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-NIGERIA-ABACHA-1STL     06-08 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NIGERIA-ABACHA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: at last.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reports from Kano, the northern city where Abacha was born in
1943, said thousands of people had lined the streets, awaiting the
arrival of the general's body and an escort of senior government
and military officials who were to attend the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't know what to think,'' a Kano businessman who had
closed his shop for the day told Reuters. ``It's true some people
are sad, but some will not be so sad either. We just worry over
what comes next.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the question on many minds.
</P>
<P>
   There was a political vacuum Monday in the absence of Abacha _
who wielded absolute power for five and a half years and was so
haunted by the specter of a coup that he surrounded himself with a
2,000-member personal security force, rarely appeared in public and
jailed or executed many leading Nigerians who could form a credible
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The general's former second-in-command, Lt. Gen. Donaldson
Oladipo Diya, who had been seen as a possible successor, was
sentenced to death by a military tribunal in April for allegedly
plotting a coup. His fate is still in the hands of the military
junta.
</P>
<P>
   As Nigeria's leaders gathered in Abuja in a body called the
Provisional Ruling Council, the prospects appeared at first to be
for a behind-the-scenes struggle over the next few days to see who
would lead the government. Political experts said the likely
contenders to succeed the general included Abubakar; Lieut. Gen.
Jeremiah Useni, Nigeria's senior officer, and Maj. Gen. Ishiaya
Bamaiyi, the army Chief of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   Abubakar, after his selection, was promoted from major general
to full general and was sworn in by Nigeria's chief justice,
Mohammed Uwais.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of 45 Nigerian groups that had clandestinely opposed
Abacha called Monday for the installation of a civilian government
headed by Moshood K.O. Abiola, who was imprisoned by Abacha after
his election as president in 1993 in what was widely seen as the
country's most democratic vote since it gained independence from
Britain in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola remains in prison.
</P>
<P>
   It is a country of 250 tribal groups. The Hausa and Fulani in
the north, the Yoruba in the southwest and the Ibo in the southeast
make up 65 percent of the population. The 1960s were marked by a
struggle for political dominance among the main ethnic groups, and
a devastating civil war almost broke the country apart in the late
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1970s, oil exports helped Nigeria recover
economically, and in the early 1980s, with a civilian government in
Lagos, Nigeria became known as a model of African democracy and
prosperity. Nigerian arts were the envy of the continent. Its press
was one of the freest anywhere. Nigerian diplomacy challenged the
United States and Britain over issues like apartheid. The nation's
currency was worth twice as much as the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   But democracy in Nigeria died in 1983, and Abacha, a career
soldier who became an infantryman at 18 and attended military
colleges in England, the United States and Nigeria, had a role in
three military coups.
</P>
<P>
   The generals ousted Nigeria's last civilian government in 1983.
Hopes for a return to democracy were high in June 1993, when
Abiola, a millionaire businessman, won an election with pledges to
return Nigeria to civilian government. But the government annulled
the election, and three months later Abacha overthrew President
Ibrahim Babangida.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola, frustrated over the victory that was stolen from him,
declared himself president in defiance of Abacha and was jailed on
treason charges. Abacha promised democratic reforms and an election
in 1996 to bring back civilian government, but the promises proved
hollow.
</P>
<P>
   While announcing that he was stretching his rule to 1998, Abacha
began a virtual reign of terror. He cracked down on all political
opposition, subdued trade unions, took control of the press, jailed
hundreds of people and began a series of trials that sent opponents
to prison or the gallows.
</P>
<P>
   Saro-Wiwa was executed on charges stemming from his campaign to
have Nigeria's huge oil revenues shared with the communities where
the petroleum was produced. The general's purges also extended to
prominent Nigerians and into his inner circle, and many fled into
exile.
</P>
<P>
   His iron rule drew wide condemnation in the West. While an
international oil embargo did not materialize, limited economic
sanctions against Nigerian oil were invoked. There were reports
that the general and other military leaders were siphoning off
billions of dollars from oil.
</P>
<P>
   As the general became a pariah in Western countries, he was said
to have turned increasingly for support to the Middle East and to
Asia, particularly China. At the same time, he became isolated
personally.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria has fallen into steep decline. In most cities,
electricity and water supplies are unreliable at best. Unemployment
soared in recent months, and inflation cut the purchasing power of
most Nigerians to subsistence levels. And for all the general's
repression, criticism could still be heard in Lagos, the
bursting-at-the-seams former capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
