<SLUG> BC-NY-SHOOTING-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMAN FATALLY SHOOTS MAN IN NEW YORK PARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roy Fidel was talking to a few friends late Sunday
night in Carroll Park, a small patch of trees and lawns in a
brownstone-lined section of Brooklyn, when a green car pulled up
and a man with a gun got out.
</P>
<P>
   The man pointed his pistol at Fidel's friends, who were sitting
on a park bench, and ordered them to ``scatter like cockroaches,''
said Lenore Calicchio, 21, Fidel's girlfriend. The gunman then
ordered Fidel, 22, to kneel in front of a park maintenance
building, just a few feet from a playground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was asking Roy, `Do you know this guy? Do you know who he
is?''' Ms. Calicchio said Monday. ``And that's when he shot Roy in
the back of the head.''
</P>
<P>
   The gunman got into the car and the driver sped off. Fidel, who
was recently convicted on a charge of selling drugs and was
awaiting sentencing in federal court, died at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The police described the gunman as a Hispanic male in his late
teens, said Gerry Falcon, a police spokeswoman, but the authorities
had few leads in the execution-style murder Monday. And as
detectives sought clues in Carroll Park Monday afternoon, their
presence stirred both fear and resentment among residents of
Carroll Gardens and nearby Cobble Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is terrible, but it's such an aberration,'' said a
Carroll Gardens resident, Patti Jones, 44, as her 4-year-old son,
Hart, climbed a jungle gym. ``We come here every day. Most of the
time, the older kids aren't here when the younger ones are playing.
The only thing I'm a little worried about is that someone might
strike back in revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   As parents and young children packed the benches and playground
on one side of the park, gathering on the other side were about a
dozen of Fidel's friends, teen-agers whose anger at his murder
quickly turned to disdain for the police officers trying to solve
it. At about 3:30 p.m., as officers posted signs offering a $1,000
reward for information leading to the arrest of Fidel's killer, the
teen-agers heckled the officers, cursing and screaming, ``Don't put
that poster up!''
</P>
<P>
   After a tense exchange between the teen-agers and the police,
Ms. Calicchio convinced her friends to let the officers continue
their work. She quickly added that she had not seen the killer's
face and would not cooperate with the detectives investigating the
homicide.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Calicchio, who said she had dated Fidel for six years, wept
as she discussed the prospect of raising their 8-month-old
daughter, Angelique, without him. She acknowledged that Fidel had a
minor criminal record, but she said he was trying to find steady
work as a mover, that he had recently earned his general
equivalency degree and was trying to turn his life around.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't deserve to die this way,'' Ms. Calicchio said.
``This kind of thing doesn't happen here very often.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidel's grandmother Leatrice Foti said her grandson had run into
some trouble with the law, but was a good-natured person.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't a thief,'' said Ms. Foti, 63. ``His favorite thing
to do was eat. Anything. As long as it was food. He was a big guy
with a soft heart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
