<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABBY WHO FLED INDIA FINDS NEW STRUGGLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Day after day, the view of Balvinder Singh that
people get is the back of his head. So why would anyone think he
has a story to tell? But he does, like everyone else. His life has
excellent, if heartbreaking, plot lines, from his flight from the
1984 pogrom of Sikhs in India to what Singh sees as the strange
persecution of taxi drivers by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani today.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows what's in the mayor's mind, and who gives him
ideas, and why he's acting like this,'' Singh said last week, in an
interview in his immaculate taxicab. ``He was not like this.
Everyone liked this mayor. And everyone voted for him. Even the
taxi drivers, they liked him before.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh, 35, is one of the top elected leaders of the United
Yellow Cab Drivers Association, one of the few cabby groups in a
disorganized industry. He is also one of the only taxi leaders to
drive a cab. He owns his own taxi medallion and represents the
largest group of cabbies _ people from India, Pakistan and
Bangladesh _ although nobody knows for certain the number of
immigrants from the subcontinent among the city's 42,000 licensed
drivers. (City estimates range from 40 to 60 percent. Singh says
the number is 75 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter. In the last decade, the turban has become the
symbol of the New York City taxicab driver, just as a Brooklyn
accent was four decades ago. Until now, the industry has been as
fragmented as its ethnic mix, but strict new taxi rules pushed
through by Giuliani are forcing drivers to try to work together _
and creating a new immigrant interest group in New York. A fresh
skirmish in the battle of strikes and protests will probably occur
next week, at another hearing of the Taxi and Limousine Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Taxi organizers describe Singh as a quiet and thoughtful man who
is the opposite of a self-promoter. No one, at least, would accuse
him of seeking press attention. ``Actually, we all are working the
same,'' he said, dismissing his leadership role. ``I'm not even
doing anything that other people aren't doing. They are working
more than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to reach Singh in New York in recent weeks sometimes
felt, in fact, like trying to locate him in Patel Nagar, the
housing colony in New Delhi where he used to live. Calls to the
United Yellow Cab Drivers Association were met with a busy signal
or a recording; callers to Singh's cell phone were informed that he
was outside its range. Singh finally responded to a message left
for him at the office of the mayor's nemesis, Norman Siegel, the
executive director of the New York Civil Liberties Union, who is
representing the cabbies.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Singh turned up in his taxi to drive his
interviewer in circles around midtown for a while. Then he stopped
at a diner, and drove around some more.
</P>
<P>
   Does he like driving a cab?
</P>
<P>
   ``Really not,'' Singh said. ``It's not a respectable job.''
</P>
<P>
   What would he prefer? ``Actually,'' Singh said, ``I really want
to be a doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh left New Delhi in 1984 when he was 21, after hiding for
four days in a Hindu neighbor's home as thousands of his fellow
Sikhs _ and five of his cousins _ were murdered by Hindu mobs in
revenge for the assassination of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi. Mrs.
Gandhi had been shot to death by two of her Sikh bodyguards, who
were themselves seeking vengeance for Mrs. Gandhi's military
crackdown on secessionist Sikhs in Punjab, where 1,200 died. There
are 18 million Sikhs in India, many of them business people,
members of the military _ and taxi drivers. Their religion emerged
in an 18th-century schism from Hinduism.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the riots, I really did not want to live in Delhi,''
Singh said. Like other Sikhs at the time, he got rid of his
identifying Sikh characteristics _ his turban and long beard _ to
survive. He left his job as an apprentice technician at a company
that made water meters and other measuring instruments, and by
early 1985, he was picking sweet potatoes in California. Then he
installed windows in New York. ``That business goes very slow,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Singh started driving a taxi in 1990 and got his medallion three
years ago. He is now married, with three children, living in a
one-bedroom apartment in Flushing, Queens. His wife is a window
clerk at a post office in New Jersey; together they make about
$40,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Singh said that if taxi owners like himself had to post a
$100,000 bond for accident victims, a proposed rule the commission
has not yet voted on, he would be out of business. ``From where I
bring in the $100,000?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Singh acknowledges the existence of reckless taxi drivers, but
says that the mayor has become too harsh on groups he once
championed. ``In the beginning, he spoke for the immigrant
people,'' Singh said. ``I don't know what happened. His thinking is
good, but his way is not good.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh is now looking for other jobs _ and dreaming through his
6-year-old son. ``The first generation that comes over here, they
have no choice but to do hard work,'' he said. ``Some people get
lucky, but their businesses depend on hard work _ restaurants,
construction. And after that, the next generation, they go with the
American system. Their thinking gets changed.''
</P>
<P>
   What would he like his son to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to be a doctor,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
