A0195 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JAZZ-HNS &LR;      06-08 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Jazz tries to get over embarrassment
<TEXT>
<P>
   Silver lining: Team has made habit of responding successfully in
Game 4
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ There have been several times when trying to beat the
Bulls was almost a joke.
</P>
<P>
   But there has never been anything like Sunday's 42-point laugher
at the United Center in Game 3 of the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one microscopic bit of hope the Utah Jazz can take
from that game, it's that things can't get any worse.
</P>
<P>
   Can they?
</P>
<P>
   Utah coach Jerry Sloan certainly hopes not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a couple of tables back there in the training room so
guys could lay back and rest while we watched the films _ in case
anybody gets sick,'' said Sloan of that 96-54 loss to the Bulls
that put Chicago up 2-1 in the best-of-seven series that resumes at
the United Center on Wednesday. ``So we'll take a look at that.
Hopefully, that (the films) will help them a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz set a slew of NBA Finals records in Sunday's loss,
including fewest points in a game, fewest points in a second half
(23), fewest points in a fourth quarter (nine), fewest players in
double-figure scoring (one, Karl Malone with 22) and fewest field
goals in a game (21).
</P>
<P>
   Monday's questions prior to Jazz practice centered on whether
the Bulls were running up the score. The Bulls scored just 96
points, but it certainly seemed like a lot more, especially to
Sloan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that all they scored _ 96 points?'' he asked. ``Is that
really all? I thought they had 196 points.''
</P>
<P>
   Understandably.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning behind the run-up-the-score questions was that Jud
Buechler and Steve Kerr were jacking up 3-pointers in the fourth
quarter with the Bulls up by more than 30 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``There definitely has to be some motivation, because they were
having a good time, and they were obviously still taking 3s when
the game was well out of hand,'' Malone said. ``Over here on our
side, our coach would have a fit if we did that. But it's the
championship, so you can't feel sorry about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is going to feel sorry about it. We got it handed to
us, without a doubt, so you give them credit for that. If this
can't get you motivated, nothing else can. So we're looking forward
to the game on Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   File those questions, and the answer, in the ``searching for
motivation'' file.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point was whether Utah was running down the score.
The Jazz shot just 30 percent Sunday (21-of-70), and that's with
Malone hitting eight of his 11 shots. Nobody else on the team hit
more than three field goals. Other than Malone, the other four Jazz
starters combined to hit just six of 26 attempts from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   And if you tack on the fourth quarter from Friday's Game 2, in
which the Jazz scored 15 points, Utah has eked out just 69 points
in five quarters of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an embarrassment for all of us,'' Sloan said. ``I take
responsibility for that. That's what I've always done.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does Sloan do now? Nothing, if you listen to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't motivate players,'' he said. ``They have to motivate
themselves. I've always had that philosophy, and I think that
(motivation) is the most overused word in sports. I'll say that
again. A player has to motivate himself. He has to want to play
hard and want to succeed, and if he doesn't and that's not very
important to him, then he is probably not going to perform well.
That comes from within yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   While certainly not on the level of Sunday's humiliation, the
Jazz has had a history of Game 3 pratfalls in the past few years,
only to respond with terrific fourth games. Last year, the Los
Angeles Lakers pounded the Jazz by 20 points in Game 3 of the
Western Conference semifinals, but Utah came back with a 110-95
victory in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Who in Houston can forget Utah losing Game 3 to the Rockets in
the Western Conference quarterfinals, only to have the Jazz bounce
back and take Game 4 by 22 points?
</P>
<P>
   And in Game 3 of the Western Conference finals this year, San
Antonio routed the Jazz 86-64, but Utah responded in Game 4,
hammering out an 82-73 victory in the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (Sunday's loss) was nothing to lose sleep over,'' said Greg
Ostertag, who started Game 3 in place of Greg Foster, who has
started every other playoff game for the Jazz this season. ``We had
a bad game and got our butts kicked. So far this year, we've been
really strong in Game 4s, and now it's just a matter of coming out
strong for Game 4. We're not letting this affect the way we play.
We're putting this behind us now, and we're coming to play the way
we're capable of playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's embarrassing to get beat like that. It's over. All we can
do is watch film and see where we went wrong, come out and make
what changes we have to. If those changes are to play harder and
more aggressively, then maybe that's what we need to do. I think
Wednesday's game will be a much better game.''
</P>
<P>
   One would hope so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be in your heart and mentally,'' Bryon Russell
said. ``All the little adjustments in the world won't help if we
don't come out and play. If you don't have any heart, you shouldn't
even be out there. I'm sure we'll be all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, when it rains, it pours, and this one had thunder and
lightning, too. That's what happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
