<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MARTINEZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0609 &HT;    Martinez comeback is for record and nation
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dennis Martinez goes for history tonight. He will try
to become the winningest Latin American pitcher of all time when he
pitches for the Braves against the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   He does not care if he receives congratulations from Juan
Marichal, the man with whom he shares the record with 243 wins.
</P>
<P>
   It will be enough for him to have taught the baseball world a
geography lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came from a country that nobody knew where it was at the
beginning (of my career),'' Martinez said. ``I lived with this. I
lived for somebody to say, `that man is from Nicaragua. Now we know
where it's at. Central America, a tiny country. Basically, that's
why I think the Nicaraguan people are proud about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has already been celebrated by his country. Last week,
Nicaraguan Ambassador Francisco Aguirre-Sacasa honored him when the
Braves were in Baltimore to play the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has turned around his season since moving into the
starting rotation in place of the injured John Smoltz. In his first
six games, he was 1-2 with a 10.05 ERA. In his last 12 games, since
April 24, Martinez is 1-0 with a 1.11 ERA, striking out 21 in 32
1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason is perseverance,'' he said. ``I've been trying to
show that I'm healthy, that I can still win at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is 43, and he's been pitching professionally for 24
years. But he said he only became aware of the Latin American
record in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I first heard about it when I got to the '95 World
Series with the Indians.'' he said. ``That's when I start passing
Luis Tiant. And the stats in the media guide told me I was the
second winning pitcher among Latin pitchers and there were numbers
that were reachable. Before that, I never had thought about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he is friends with Marichal, but he seems a bit
annoyed that the former San Francisco Giants pitcher hasn't
acknowledged his tying the record. Marichal has been quoted as
saying he was offended that Martinez would try a comeback (after an
elbow injury) just to get the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good friend of mine,'' Martinez said. ``But I heard
some comments that he made when I first decided to come back, which
I never expected anything like that from him. We all have different
personalities. He may try to (inspire) me by saying that or maybe
he was trying to make me quit. I don't know which way it was. I
took it the positive way, it motivated me more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record was basically why I did come back. I do remember
when I left this game, it was because of the injury that I had in
my elbow. Before I got hurt, I was successful. Now finally I feel
better, the injuries disappear, I recover real well, I've worked
hard for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
