<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NOMO-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: A SUPPORT GROUP OF NOMO'S VERY OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLAIRE SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is much about Hideo Nomo that gets lost in translation,
and not just because of the language barrier that has separated the
Japanese pitcher from almost every element surrounding him in his
major-league career. Even if Nomo woke up today with the ability to
speak perfect English, that would not assure that the right-hander
would suddenly be any less unfathomable.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo has been reserved from the day he arrived on the
major-league scene and single-handedly opened up the market to
adventurous and able Asian athletes. Nomomania may have had its
manic aspects. The pitcher never has.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he has fallen to a 2-7 record this season, one the
Dodgers were willing to trade, and Nomo succinctly said, ``I'm
getting hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? ``If I knew that, I'd be shutting out everybody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A David Cone, a Randy Johnson, even a sometimes taciturn Roger
Clemens would most likely spend more than nine words on such
questions. For Nomo, though, such discourses are tantamount to a
flood. This impenetrable and private aspect of Nomo existed during
his halcyon days with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   By all appearances it will not change during the next phase of
his career, which kicks off Tuesday night when Nomo makes his
pitching debut for the Mets against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays at
Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo's inner sanctum, his island of peace, remains all but
untouchable. Fortunately for the Mets, they are probably the only
major-league team, including the Dodgers, that has the small
handful of people Nomo ever allowed inside.
</P>
<P>
   First, there is Mike Piazza, the recently acquired All-Star
catcher, who was a teammate of Nomo's on the Dodgers. There is also
Dave Wallace, who was the pitching coach when Nomo joined the
Dodgers and won them over thanks to a sensational rookie season.
And finally there is Masato Yoshii, the pitcher who is a fellow
graduate of the Japanese major leagues, a former teammate and, of
no small importance, Nomo's very good friend.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher. Pitching guru. Kindred spirit. The Mets have engineered
this multitiered reunion, counting on it to make a difference not
only in the life of a pitcher hoping to reverse a slide, but also
for a rotation that has only one glaring hole to fill.
</P>
<P>
   Al Leiter, Bobby Jones and Yoshii are fine. So to is Rick Reed,
who Monday night retired the first 20 Devil Rays he faced in coming
within seven outs of a perfect game before Wade Boggs doubled. Nomo
need not be perfect. He is being asked to do only better than Dave
Mlicki, who was 1-4 before being traded in the Nomo deal June 5.
</P>
<P>
   The team did not bring Nomo, Wallace, Piazza and Yoshii together
after long, mapped-out planning. These multitiered reunions are the
result of many an intriguing coincidence. If they work, the Mets
will have every right to call them wondrous.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever unfolds Tuesday night and beyond for Nomo, the Mets
have to be comforted by the presence of so many who will at least
be able to read the signs. Wallace started that Monday when he
interpreted one of Nomo's more cryptic responses at his first news
conference in New York. The pitcher turned more than one head with
his response when asked if he could be a winner again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to tell,'' Nomo said with the help of an
interpreter. ``There are so many things I can't control.''
</P>
<P>
   Was that false modesty? Or was it shattered confidence because
of a 2-7 record and a 5.05 earned run average. Neither, assured
Wallace, now the special assistant to the Mets' general manager,
Steve Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the reserved Hideo Nomo,'' he said. ``You'll come to
know that he's pretty quiet in his thoughts, and he doesn't reveal
a lot of stuff. It takes a while to really get to know him.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wallace insists that it will be worth the wait, though. ``My
thoughts are very strong that to shake him mentally takes quite a
bit,'' he said. ``So I think he's fine from that standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   So Wallace; the Mets' pitching coach, Bob Apodaca, and Manager
Bobby Valentine will concentrate on the mechanics, the A-B-C's of
pitching. Yet they will not underestimate the more esoteric aspects
of this deal, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Yoshii-Nomo friendship, Valentine said, is important if only
to give Nomo a person to talk baseball with without a translator.
``I can only imagine, but I've got to think that is a real bonus,
to experience things together,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Piazza, Wallace praised the catcher for understanding
early not only Nomo's standing in the baseball community _
well-established in Japan _ but also the pitcher's personality and
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship is very good,'' Wallace said. ``One based on
mutual respect. Mike communicated with him. And Hideo, as people
will get to know, is a guy that if you respect where he comes from
and what he does, and his privacy, he will open up a little bit.
And Mike did that. Mike got the best out of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Wallace, whose mere mention causes Nomo do to the
unusual and reveal some of his feelings. ``Dave Wallace has been
very important in my development,'' the pitcher said with obvious
gratitude. ``When I first came to the Dodgers, I didn't speak a
word of English, yet he understood me very well.''
</P>
<P>
   With Nomo that may be half the battle, one already won by three
other Mets who can only hope to help the pitcher get back to
winning the only way he knew how.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
