<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'DONNELL SHOOTS FROM THE LIP  
 MUSICAL PRINCE  
 MUSCLES WON'T WAIT  
 SEEN AND HEARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON WITH GLENN COLLINS AND STEWART KAMPEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The people in the audience for the Tony Awards at
Radio City Music Hall must have wondered if they had wandered onto
``The Jerry Springer Show.'' Rosie O'Donnell, the talk show diva
and Springer competitor who was the MC for the awards show,
ad-libbed shoot-from-the-lip patter that the folks in television
land did not see because she delivered it only during the
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   First Ms. O'Donnell referred to Fran and Barry Weissler,
producers of the hit musical ``Chicago'' and the 1994 Broadway
revival of ``Grease'' (in which Ms. O'Donnell starred as the
salty-mouthed Betty Rizzo), as ``the cheapest people in the free
world.'' She also mimicked Mrs. Weissler's distinctive
pronunciation of ``darling.''
</P>
<P>
   Weissler leapt from his seat, but not to object. He took a bow.
He waved. Then the commercial ended, the cameras came back on and
Ms. O'Donnell returned to the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't take ourselves seriously,'' Mrs. Weissler said
Monday. ``We thought it was hilarious. Everyone is talking about
the Tonys and about us, so what's the problem?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. O'Donnell said she had intended her comments to be
affectionate. Of Mrs. Weissler, she said, ``She's like a mother
figure to me, and I will tease her forever about the fact that
they're cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   During later commercials, Ms. O'Donnell sometimes lapsed into
language not printable in a newspaper. She had unkind words for
everyone from Charlton Heston, the new president of the National
Rifle Association (she suggested that he star in a musical called
``Everybody Get Your Gun''), to Nancy Reagan (``looks like a human
Pez dispenser'').
</P>
<P>
   Royal Overture
</P>
<P>
   Crown Prince Naruhito of Japan so liked what he heard at a New
York Philharmonic concert (which opened the Minato Mirai 21 hall in
Yokohama, Japan) that he made overtures about playing with the
orchestra. Apparently, the crown prince, who attended the concert
with Crown Princess Masako, is serious about his viola.
</P>
<P>
   In a backstage huddle after the performance, he and the
Philharmonic's music director, Kurt Masur, talked repertoire. They
zeroed in on the Brandenburg Concerto No. 6 by Bach and the Octet
in E flat (Op. 20) by Mendelssohn.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a catch. ``Your Highness must still audition,''
Masur said.
</P>
<P>
   Put it this way: The crown prince has not given up his day job.
</P>
<P>
   No-Wait Workout
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Billy Crystal wanted barbells. In his hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   He got them, but not from room service. Crystal, the actor and
comedian who is in New York to appear in the film ``Analyze This''
with Robert DeNiro, went shopping with a trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typical New York, everything right immediately,'' said Richard
Miller, an owner of the Gym Source, a workout equipment store on
East 52nd Street where Crystal rented not only barbells but also a
bench. ``Took the stuff right off the floor. We said, `We'll
deliver it tomorrow.' They said, `No, no, we're working out in five
minutes.' They put it in the back of a big Suburban he was in, and
went over to the hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   Seen and Heard In the Hamptons
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gelman, executive producer of the midmorning talk show
``Live With Regis and Kathie Lee,'' was seen surveying the ocean at
Atlantica, a restaurant in Westhampton Beach, N.Y. ``We had heard
that `Good Morning America' was interested in doing some shows from
there,'' said a man who works for the restaurant, ``and now, all of
a sudden, Gelman is here.'' ... Bryan Bantry, the fashion agent and
producer, had a showing of the new George Clooney-Jennifer Lopez
film ``Out of Control'' in the thick-carpeted screening room in his
home in Wainscott, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who settled into Bantry's comfortable seats (and
then went to supper at Alison by the Beach, a nearby restaurant)
were Steve Kroft of the CBS newsmagazine ``60 Minutes''; Nina
Griscom, a former host on the Food Network who has summered in the
Hamptons since she was a child, and Bill Beutel, an anchor on
WABC-TV who has a home in Westhampton.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he had liked the film, Beutel was diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice party, isn't it?'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
