<HEADER>
A0203 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK-COX     06-08 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves Notebook
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Finally, some good news for Pedro Borbon.
</P>
<P>
   The once heavily relied-on reliever who hasn't pitched in a
major-league game in almost 22 months took a big step in his rehab
Monday as he was moved from the Class A Macon, Ga. team to the club
in Class AA Greenville, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Still recovering from reconstructive elbow surgery, Borbon's
numbers have not been terribly impressive, with a 9.00 ERA in three
games at Macon, though all the runs (three) came in one appearance.
But there isn't any pain and his control has been good, walking
just one of the 14 batters he has faced.
</P>
<P>
   Borbon still does not have the velocity he had before the
injury, now throwing his fastball at around 84 mph. However, his
control has been good and he said, ``I still have to build the
velocity, but it will come.''
</P>
<P>
   If Borbon can get healthy by the end of the summer it would be a
huge bonus for a club whose bullpen is still its shakiest part.
Fortunately, so far the starting pitching has been so good and the
offense has scored so many runs that on most evenings the Braves
haven't had to rely on their group of relievers.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Mark Wohlers continues to be befuddled with control
problems, and while Kerry Ligtenberg has been effective, he has
been miserable on some nights, an inconsistency that can quickly
shoot down a good team in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Also headed to Greenville
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander John Smoltz will begin his rehab assignment
Wednesday at Greenville, then going to Macon for another start
Sunday. If all goes well, Smoltz is expected to throw three innings
in each game, then the club may pencil him back in the Atlanta
rotation for a start on June 19 in Montreal. Smoltz, who has been
bothered by pain in his right elbow after undergoing surgery last
December, said, ``It's my goal to pitch without pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Not wanted here
</P>
<P>
   One opposing player who always likes returning to Atlanta is Red
Sox catcher Jim Leyritz, who in the 1996 World Series broke this
city's heart when he hit a Game 4 homer that sparked the Yankees to
a world championship. ``It was my greatest personal moment,''
Leyritz said. ``But winning it all back in New York was my greatest
moment in sports.'' Leyritz, who played his college baseball at
Middle Georgia, still has the ball he hit off Wohlers for the
homer, along with the bat and jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Honors for Mad Dog
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Greg Maddux was named co-National League player of
the week along with Sammy Sosa of the Cubs. Maddux was 2-0 last
week, allowing two runs on nine hits and striking out 14 in 18
innings. This is the sixth time in his career that Maddux has won
the award. Sosa hit six homers last week.
</P>
<P>
   Around the park
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox and Braves had faced each other just three times
before Monday night but that was hard to tell before the game as
players and management from each team spent time together. Of
course, the Red Sox clubhouse has more Georgia flavor than any
other club in baseball, including three former Georgia Tech players
(Nomar Garciaparra, Darren Bragg and Jason Varitek) and also five
who have ties to the Braves _ manager Jimy Williams, coach Grady
Little, pitcher Steve Avery and second baseman Mark Lemke. Avery
even went on the field during Atlanta's batting practice, spending
time with his former rotation mates. ... So much for the myth that
Turner Field is a pitchers' park: Andres Galarraga has hit 10 of
his 23 home runs at home and is hitting .333 here compared with
.301 on the road. ... Courtesy of Reebok, Galarraga was wearing a
jersey in batting practice with the words ``Big Cat'' written
across the chest. ... On Friday Tom Glavine will hold his annual
sports memorabilia auction for the Georgia Counsel on Child Abuse.
The auction will be held on the Steve &AMP; Vicki morning show on Star
94 with bids taken over the telephone. A few of the items will
include a Mark McGwire bat and a Titanic poster signed by many of
the movie's stars, including Leonardo DiCaprio. ... Infielder
Rafael Belliard, who has been out since April 9 with torn
quadriceps, may go on a rehab assignment next week. ... Braves
manager Bobby Cox on Avery's seven innings of shutout ball Sunday
night against the Mets: ``I was tickled pink, especially not to
have to come in here and answer questions about what is wrong with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia pitcher signs
</P>
<P>
   Zack Frachiseur signed a minor-league contract with the Braves
and will be assigned to the organization's Class A team in Eugene,
Ore. Frachiseur, who recently completed his junior season at the
University of Georgia, was selected by the Braves in the 19th round
of last week's baseball draft.
</P>
<P>
   The former Rockdale County, Ga. standout was the ace of
Georgia's staff, leading the team in strikeouts and innings pitched
each of the past two seasons. He posted a 6-7 record and 5.38 ERA
this spring for a team that finished 24-30.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
