<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-TAMPA-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REED GETS WITHIN SEVEN OUTS OF PERFECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rick Reed keeps making the art of pitching look so
simple. But Monday night was a little numbing even for him. Just
about every pitch had a purpose or slithered into the strike zone.
Just about every Tampa Bay batter wondered how the Mets'
right-hander, so coolly efficient, was so dominating with pitches
that looked so hittable.
</P>
<P>
   Reed unleashed two-seam and four-seam fastballs to start off,
fooled batters with his sinker or his slider and mixed in his
curveball. But regardless of what pitches Reed threw, they almost
always managed to brush the corner of the strike zone or come so
achingly close that they were impossible for the batters to let go.
</P>
<P>
   Inning after crisp inning, Reed tamed the Devil Rays in pitching
the Mets to a three-hit 3-0 victory at Shea Stadium. He retired
three in a row, then six, nine, 15, 18 and 20 straight. There were
two outs in the seventh, and Reed was seven outs from completing
his pursuit of perfection.
</P>
<P>
   To finish the seventh inning and carry his masterpiece into the
eighth, though, Reed needed to retire Wade Boggs, the five-time
former American League batting champion with the keen eye. At 2-2,
Reed fired a pitch just below Boggs' knees. It was so close that
Boggs flinched, and he hesitated to peek at Larry Vanover. The
plate umpire did not raise his arm for strike three.
</P>
<P>
   Boggs plastered the next pitch over Brian McRae and off the
center-field warning track for a ground rule double.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have never had a no-hitter in their 36-year history,
and Reed's terrific 20-batter sequence before Boggs' hit was five
short of Tom Seaver's team record of 25 straight retired from the
start of a game, which Seaver did against the Chicago Cubs on July
9, 1969.
</P>
<P>
   It was a night when Mike Piazza returned to the lineup after
missing three games against Boston with a bruised left hand and
bashed a mammoth homer off the hapless and luckless Dennis
Springer. But Piazza was a footnote. The big news was that Reed
(7-3) settled for the shutout spiced with 10 strikeouts. He is 6-1
with a 1.21 earned run average in his last eight starts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After Boggs' double, Reed walked Fred McGriff before pumping a
1-2 pitch past Paul Sorrento to end the seventh. Reed surrendered
singles to Dave Martinez and Mike DiFelice to start the eighth, but
his 10th strikeout and gorgeous plays by Rey Ordonez at shortstop
and Bernard Gilkey in left helped preserve the shutout.
</P>
<P>
   Reed had faced one of his toughest challenges in the fifth
inning after McGriff checked his swing on a low 2-2 pitch. McGriff
fouled off a pitch before lining a fastball back at Reed. The
pitcher, who was just completing his delivery, stuck out his glove
while still crouching and grabbed the ball for the first out. It
was the sort of play that makes everyone in the dugout look at each
other with raised eyebrows, thinking, maybe, just maybe.
</P>
<P>
   The fans must have sensed that something special was transpiring
in the fourth inning, because they howled as if it were October
when Boggs dribbled a grounder to Carlos Baerga for the third out.
It was as routine a play as a second baseman will ever make, but
the fans realized that it ended another inning and kept the pursuit
of perfection percolating.
</P>
<P>
   Reed did not waste time on the mound _ the game took only 2
hours 18 minutes. He rarely moved off the pitching rubber and was
waiting for the signal from Piazza the moment the ball returned to
his glove. He started the game by getting Quinton McCracken to
stare at a 1-2 fastball for strike three. Four pitches, one out and
the first of many baffled hitters who thought that Greg Maddux was
suddenly wearing a Mets uniform.
</P>
<P>
   The trend continued as Reed worked fast and achieved quick
results. If the Devil Rays had a plan of attack against Reed, it
never showed. He barely had to sweat in the third, tossing nine
pitches to register a pair of three-pitch strikeouts sandwiched
around Kevin Stocker's unsuccessful bunt attempt. It was only the
third inning, and Stocker was desperate enough to try to steal a
hit with a bunt. Maybe he knew something. Maybe he knew Reed would
make it look simple.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   By losing Monday night, Dennis Springer (2-10) of the Devil Rays
gained an unwanted and dubious distinction: The knuckleballer has
lost more games (10) in the last two months than the entire Yankee
team has (nine). ... The Mets had an unexpected visitor as
outfielder-designated hitter Ruben Sierra arrived unannounced at
Shea Stadium in search of a job. Sierra, who was released by the
Chicago White Sox on May 25 after hitting .216 with four homers and
11 runs batted in, said, ``I can help this team if they give me a
chance.'' But the former Yankee, who played for Bobby Valentine in
Texas, failed in his attempt to meet with General Manager Steve
Phillips. ``We have no interest,'' Phillips said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
