<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FATAL-FIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1 DEAD, 9 HURT IN QUEENS FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A fire that engulfed a home in Queens early Monday
killed one person and left at least nine others injured, and city
officials said that the home _ meant to house only two families _
had been illegally subdivided into six apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Monday night that the fire had been
intentionally set from the first floor. ``Some sort of flammable
liquid appeared to be used,'' Frank Gribbon, a spokesman for the
Fire Department, said.
</P>
<P>
   One neighbor, Tarshena Simmons, said she was awakened by screams
at the fire. ``We saw people running, flames coming from the attic
and people jumping out of the windows,'' said Ms. Simmons, 20, who
lives across the street and watched the blaze from her living room
window. ``No one really seemed to make it out the front door, they
got trapped inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the people seriously injured were in stable condition at
local hospitals following the 4:24 a.m. fire at 163-14 109th Ave.
in South Jamaica, fire officials said. Another resident, a woman
eight months pregnant, survived the fire by jumping two stories to
the sidewalk, and was treated for minor injuries, the officials
said. Three firefighters were treated for smoke inhalation, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   The identities of the victims were not released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The flames were extinguished in about 40 minutes, according to
Amanda Schmidt, another Fire Department spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials said they were investigating whether the illegal
subdivisions of the house were contributing factors in the death of
a man who was found on the third floor. Gribbon said 15 people from
10 different families were living in the house. He said the Fire
Department had declared the house off limits because of the illegal
subdivisions and the inadequate escape routes for the number of
people living there.
</P>
<P>
   Buildings Department officials, who placed an ``unsafe building
notice'' on the residence, said they would visit what remained of
the structure to determine how many people were living there. Ted
Birkhahn, a spokesman for the Buildings Department, said he could
find no past complaints about code violations at the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sending an inspector out tonight,'' Birkhahn said.
``You can't have nonfamily members living in the building, but a
family is allowed to have as many people as they want, unless it
poses an imminent danger.''
</P>
<P>
   But neighbors said they had complained to city officials about
the conditions at the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 25 more people living there,'' she Ms. Simmons'
mother, Florence. ``We couldn't sleep. They were showering with a
water hose in the back yard all night. There were gun shots. It was
horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she had heard a woman who lived in the house threaten
to burn it down last week, but the authorities said they had no
information on suspects or a motive at this time.
</P>
<P>
   The problem of illegal subdivisions has been a source of
friction in many Queens communities, as landlords find they can
profit by dividing up homes for rental by immigrants and others
eager for low-cost housing. But subdividing a house often can
overwhelm a home's electrical system or create other potential
safety problems, like inadequate fire exits.
</P>
<P>
   Birkhahn said that first-time violators of Building Department
regulations on occupancy and illegal subdivisions can face fines
from between $800 and $2,500 per violation. If the illegal
occupancy contributed to the death, city officials said that those
responsible could also face criminal charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
