<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MAYOR-COUNCIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI USES VETO POWER AGAINST COUNCIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Taking direct aim at his adversaries in the city
budget battle, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani used his line-item veto power
for the first time Monday to eliminate nearly $5 million that the
City Council had allocated for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani vetoed the expenditure only hours after the Council
voted to use money from a property tax reserve fund to cover a $251
million gap in the budget the Council approved last week, in
defiance of the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani denounced the vote as an effort to usurp his authority,
and then announced that he was vetoing 13 percent, $4.6 million, of
the Council's $35.2 million operating budget.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Vallone, the Council speaker, described the mayor's
actions as mind-boggling and accused him of intentionally
underestimating the city's revenue for next year when its coffers
hold a record $2 billion surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's actions by the Council and mayor were the latest
volleys in a battle that could heighten Tuesday or Wednesday when
the mayor is expected to veto up to $200 million more from the
Council's budget. The Council is expected to then override all the
vetoes.
 &UR;  &LR;  It is the first time that the mayor, a Republican, and the
Democratic-dominated Council have been unable to agree on an annual
budget since the city charter was revised in 1989. Almost everyone
agrees, though, that the disputes are destined for the courts, and
that they will drag on beyond the beginning of the new fiscal year
on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   The $251 million shortfall, which represents less than 1 percent
of the Council's $34.08 billion city budget, would have been easily
resolved in previous years by Giuliani and Vallone, who had
friendly relations until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's deluge of tax and fiscal information nearly obscured
the political reasons behind the impasse: Giuliani's insistence
that Vallone drop his call for a referendum asking voters whether
city money should be used to help build a new stadium for the
Yankees, and Vallone's refusal to do so. Vallone is running for
governor, and his chances of defeating Gov. George Pataki in the
general election would be enhanced by a referendum on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone is expected to introduce a bill establishing the
referendum at a Council meeting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Bender, the speaker's chief of staff, said the mayor was
retaliating for the Council's show of independence by cutting $4.6
million from its operating expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he realized that the Council couldn't be abolished,
and he can't take over the body with martial law,'' Bender said.
``So now he's trying to cut our budget.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, after the Council passed its own budget, Giuliani
promptly said 1998-99 revenues would fall short of previous
estimates by $251 million. To balance the books, the Council would
have had to agree to the mayor's vetoes or raise the property tax,
the only tax it controls.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, the Council voted to use $251 million of a reserve
fund that exists to cover property tax shortfalls. The mayor's
office had set the fund total at more than $700 million.
</P>
<P>
   Outside fiscal experts said it was extremely difficult to
determine the level needed to offset delinquent taxes of the
reserve fund, because budget officials have arrived at different
figures, depending on the criteria they use.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Criscitello, director of the city's Independent Budget
Office, said his agency's calculations showed that the level would
be around $600 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
