A0225 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-PRIVILEGE-NYT &LR;      06-08 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PRIVILEGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A CRUCIAL PRIVILEGE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 9:
</P>
<P>
   Though the presidential inquiry by Kenneth Starr has yet to
produce many answers, his hunt for evidence has raised thorny legal
issues, among them the fight over attorney-client privilege heard
on Monday by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Starr wants to see the notes taken by the personal lawyer for
Vincent Foster, the White House counsel who committed suicide,
during a meeting the two men had just nine days before Foster's
death. Starr is seeking to determine whether presidential aides
lied about any role Hillary Rodham Clinton might have had in the
dismissal of seven employees of the White House travel office. The
question confronting the justices is whether attorney-client
privilege survives a client's death.
</P>
<P>
   A 2-to-1 decision by a federal appeals court last summer carved
out an exception to lawyer-client privilege in criminal
investigations involving a dead witness. Taking a tack supported by
a number of legal scholars, the ruling said the privilege is not
absolute, and must be balanced against the needs of investigators
and the availability of the information in other places.
</P>
<P>
   That outcome failed to satisfy Starr, who takes the more extreme
view that the privilege should always die with the client. It also
provoked strong opposition from the organized bar as well as
hospice and psychiatric groups, which argued that watering down the
permanency of the attorney-client privilege beyond existing
exceptions, say for contested wills, would destroy the basic trust
the privilege is meant to foster.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's questioning by the justices indicated concern about
chilling relations between lawyers and their clients. But several
justices were also properly skeptical about the idea that death
should rob investigators of evidence that they might have obtained
had the client been alive and able to testify.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney-client privilege should not be set aside lightly.
But in a narrow category of cases, especially where the information
is needed to establish guilt or innocence and prevent injustice,
there are more important values than protecting a dead person's
secrets. Carving a new rule that recognizes this without unduly
tampering with the lawyer-client relationship is now the court's
challenge. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-98 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980608.0482 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0227 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAINELEVATOR-BLAST-K     06-08 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAINELEVATOR-BLAST-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Grain elevator explosion kills two, injures others  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN PETTERSON  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAYSVILLE, Kan. _ An explosion tore through a south-central
Kansas grain elevator Monday, killing two persons and leaving four
others trapped in tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   Eight persons were hospitalized after the blast at the DeBruce
Grain elevator, one of the largest in the world. The explosion
apparently occurred when a spark ignited grain dust suspended in
the air.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers worked cautiously to find a way to reach the four
workers trapped beneath tons of rubble that blocked entrances to
the tunnels. The four tunnels are 20-25 feet below ground level and
run from the center to the ends of the half-mile-long elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Structural engineers finally gave the OK late in the afternoon,
and rescue teams from Wichita, Sedgwick County and Oklahoma City
entered the tunnel with dogs to look for the victims.
</P>
<P>
   They found none of the missing, and parts of the tunnel were
blocked by debris and grain, they reported.
</P>
<P>
   Searchers were concentrating on an 800-foot section at the south
end of the elevator, said Curtis Wilson, Sedgwick County deputy
fire chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a rescue mode,'' Wilson said. ``Crews will be working
around the clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday about 25 persons at a time were working in the
tunnel and grain bins, said Ken Cox, division chief for the
Sedgwick County Fire Department. Lights and generators were set up
inside. They were using Bobcats to remove debris. Some men were
using shovels.
</P>
<P>
   About 300 people were working at the site, including 150
volunteers who joined rescue workers and firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's labor intensive,'' said Cox. ``It's hand-to-hand work.''
</P>
<P>
   The elevator's headhouse, a central structure that contains
machinery used to move grain from bin to bin, was badly damaged by
the blast and in danger of collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``That headhouse is moving six to eight feet in the wind,'' Cox
said. ``It has huge holes blown through its upper portion.''
</P>
<P>
   The ends of the elevator were blown out, and slabs of concrete
dangled from reinforcing bars. Chunks of the bin deck, which runs
along the top of the elevator and connects the separate bins, were
blown away.
</P>
<P>
   A helicopter from Fort Riley plucked David Pickens from the top
of the south end of the elevator. A 150-foot crane was used to
remove several persons from the top of the elevator early in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse was the threat of severe weather in the
area around Haysville, just south of Wichita. Rain fell Monday
afternoon, and the area was under a tornado watch for a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the weather turns bad enough, we'll have to pull (rescue)
people out of the structure. This is going to be a long, drawn-out
operation,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   There were unconfirmed reports that rescuers had heard a sound
like someone banging on pipes, a sign that someone could still be
alive in the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is always critical,'' Cox said. ``We're hoping they are
in a space where they can breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   The elevator, which is in Sedgwick County between Wichita and
Haysville, is owned by DeBruce Grain, of North Kansas City. The
structure is 120 feet tall to the top of the bin deck and 214 feet
to the top of the headhouse. The grain elevator has a capacity of
24 million bushels.
</P>
<P>
   DeBruce had no comment on the explosion Monday afternoon. Paul
DeBruce, the company's chief executive officer, was at the scene, a
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Black, a grain merchandiser for the company, said Monday
night that he had no knowledge of complaints against the company
concerning excessive grain dust.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four persons were at the elevator when the explosion
occurred about 9:20 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had one individual who said he saw a red ball of fire come
out of the north end of the bin deck,'' said Tom Marple, area
director for Kansas for the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grain dust suspended in proper proportions in the air can be
as explosive as dynamite,'' Marple said.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Yorgensen, principal of Oatville Elementary School, about a
mile from the elevator, was at the school at the time. ``It really
rattled the windows and shook the whole building,'' Yorgensen said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said it appeared that the explosion started at the north
end of the structure and that explosions traveled along the bin
deck.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said that was typical of grain dust explosions, as one
blast kicks up dust, which in turn ignites.
</P>
<P>
   One of the dead was found outside the elevator, and the other
was found in the headhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen survivors were removed after the blast, including eight
sent to area hospitals. Five of the hospitalized workers were in
serious condition with burns.
</P>
<P>
   The victims' families gathered at the Oatville school, where
they received hourly briefings.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are distraught. These people are in shock,'' said
Mark Schroeder, chairman of the Sedgwick County Commission. ``The
families were very quiet _ some of them visibly shaken, crying.''
</P>
<P>
   A helicopter from Fort Riley circled the structure Monday,
seeking survivors with the help of infrared sensing equipment
borrowed from the Vulcan Chemical Co. plant nearby.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen agencies were on hand, including firefighters;
police officers; agents of the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms; and the state fire marshal's office. The Oklahoma City
Fire Department and the Federal Emergency Management Agency office
in Lincoln, Neb., sent rescue teams.
</P>
<P>
   Marple said the explosion was the worst he had seen in his three
years in Kansas. He said there were 16 explosions blamed on grain
dust in the United States last year.
</P>
<P>
   He said the most significant damage was at the ends of the
elevator. ``That's typical of a grain-dust type of explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   Once inspectors get inside, they will look for potential sources
of ignition, such as improper electrical equipment, sparks caused
by metal striking metal, welding, static electricity, and even heat
from a slipping conveyor built.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
