<SLUG> BC-GRAINELEVATOR-OWNER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAIN ELEVATOR THAT EXPLODED HAD BEEN CITED FOR DUST PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The grain elevator near Wichita that exploded
Monday had been cited at least twice in the last 19 months by
federal warehouse inspectors for excessive grain-dust conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said the company in both cases pledged to take
satisfactory action to clean up the dust, which can be a flammable
and deadly hazard.
</P>
<P>
   DeBruce Grain Inc. officials in Kansas City referred all
questions to company executives who traveled Monday to Wichita.
Company phones in Wichita were not answered late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from another federal agency said Monday that since
1977 at least three other persons had died in industrial accidents
inside the huge grain-storage facility _ one the nation's largest.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey Grain Inc. sold the 24-million-bushel-capacity elevator
complex to North Kansas City-based DeBruce in late 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Around the time of that sale, Ned Bergman, chief of the
examination branch of the U.S. Agriculture Department's Kansas City
Commodity Office, said his inspectors cited the elevator for
excessive dust problems.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman said a follow-up inspection and the company's responses
resulted in a satisfactory finding.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was improvement in housekeeping and operational items,''
he said, and indications ``that management was paying closer
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   In August of last year, however, agency inspectors again cited
the Wichita elevator for excessive dust, Bergman said.
</P>
<P>
   He said DeBruce officials responded in September that they were
taking added steps, including daily inspections by management
representatives, to control the problem, Bergman said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no follow-up inspections since then, Bergman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Grain dust, Bergman said, is an unavoidable problem throughout
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have the resources and the manpower on hand to
clean (dust) up on a regular basis,'' Bergman said. ``Explosions in
grain elevators are typically caused by excessive grain dust.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Commodity Office licenses and regulates about
2,600 U.S. grain elevators under the federal Public Warehouse Act.
</P>
<P>
   The agency does not issue fines for violations, Bergman said.
Persistent cases of negligence or abuse can lead to suspension of
an elevator's federal warehouse license.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, officials in the Kansas City regional office of the
Occupational Safety and Health Administration said it investigated
a fatal asphyxiation at the Wichita grain elevator in 1983 and a
double fatality there in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Details of those earlier accidents, and whether any fines were
levied, were unavailable Monday, said Pat Hand, agency spokesman.
Garvey Grain owned the elevators at the time of those two cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
